A4216 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-PIMENTEL-COL-AZR &LR;      08-17 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIMENTEL-COL-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-PIMENTEL-COL-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION NOT VERY DEMOCRATIC(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By RICARDO PIMENTEL(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (LOS ANGELES) - You had to be here. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   If you ever want to find out what it's like to live in a police
state, attend a national party convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your papers, please,'' the police and security folks are
constantly demanding at the Democratic National Convention. OK,
mostly they ask nicely, but the effect is the same.
</P>
<P>
   Your ``papers'' define you here. Where you can sit and stand.
Who you can talk to and when. Even which party - as in fiesta - you
can attend.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, delegates to journalists, is prodded and herded.
</P>
<P>
   Police and security are everywhere. They are everywhere on the
drive from the hotel to the convention center. They flank every
demonstration. Inside the convention center, they are standing and
gazing at everyone seemingly every few paces.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular item of personal adornment here is that thing
plugged into the ear that connects to Fearless Leader at security
central someplace.
</P>
<P>
   Your bags are inspected, your person detected for metal. My
laptop has been X-rayed so often it is developing a tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Inside and outside, concrete barriers, wire fence and burly
muscle separate the privileged - those with credentials - from the
unwashed.
</P>
<P>
   Security, security, insecurity. And, of course, it is all too
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But, there really is nothing less democratic, small d, than a
party convention these days. Sadly, all the democracy has occurred
long before the delegates get here.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about those demonstrators, who have alternated between
being merely noisy to downright nasty.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague told me here that she doesn't ``get it.'' Times are
good. The economy is growing. Why are they beefing?
</P>
<P>
   I gave her an inadequate answer.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, much of it is simply rage-against-the-machine kind of
stuff, people with far too much time on their hands and not enough
gray matter between the ears.
</P>
<P>
   But, really, many are making a statement about the deification
of economics in our culture and in our political system and the
fact that it seems to have all gone global.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the placards rail against things seemingly distant and
arcane.
</P>
<P>
   But allow me to say it in a manner, I hope, that is far more
persuasive than a thrown rock. They are here to demonstrate their
disgust at how crass materialism and politics too often trump
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   They are saying people first. They are saying too many, even
under the Clinton administration, have been left behind.
</P>
<P>
   That they say it badly does not mean it doesn't need saying.
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Paul Rodriguez said it more comically at a convention
gala: ``You better make friends with the people who touch your food
first.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Jesse Jackson said it best Tuesday night:
``Politics ask, `Can I win?' - Morality and conscience ask, `Is it
right?'''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Clinton's swan song here Monday night:
</P>
<P>
   It was perhaps the best of his lifetime. It highlighted all that
the Democrats say makes them different from the GOP. No surprise:
It described his own administration in glowing terms.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest accomplishment, however, has very little to do with
what he listed. Simply, history should remember him as the
extremely effective counterweight to a GOP Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be known, the GOP hates him more obsessively for that than
for any peccadillo.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us should merely thank him.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Ricardo Pimentel at ricardo.pimentel(a)arizona
</P>
<P>
   republic.com or (602) 444-8210.
</P>
</TEXT>
