<SLUG> BC-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BULLPEN CAN'T SAVE THEM THIS TIME AGAINST ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAFAEL HERMOSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bobby Valentine was talking before Wednesday night's
game about the importance of bullpens. The New York Mets' manager,
meeting with reporters, argued that an effective bullpen can
unburden a starting pitcher from the need to continually pitch deep
into games and can help an offense rally by holding an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to gush about the Mets and their bullpen after they
had swept a doubleheader from the Colorado Rockies on Tuesday. But
Wednesday night, pitchers Glendon Rusch and Rick White created a
gap too wide to close with a rally.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' 7-5 loss to the Rockies cost them ground in both
playoff races.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having won 18 of their previous 22 games, the Mets are
struggling to dent Atlanta's first-place lead in the National
League East. Since the Braves had won earlier in the day, the
deficit grew to three games. And the Mets' grip on the NL wild-card
berth loosened just a bit, shrinking to four games over Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets trailed by 7-1 entering the bottom of the eighth
inning. But Kurt Abbott led off with a home run and Edgardo Alfonzo
added a two-run homer with two outs to bring the Mets within three
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bohanon, the Colorado starter, left for reliever Mike
DeJean, and Mike Piazza hit a sharp grounder through the left side.
Todd Zeile, whose eighth-inning homer Tuesday helped complete a
doubleheader sweep of the Rockies, then lined DeJean's 2-2 outside
pitch to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, Piazza was running on the pitch and when center
fielder Juan Pierre's dive fell short, Piazza was going home. But
the ball died on the outfield grass and right fielder Larry Walker
threw to the cut-off man Jeff Frye. Piazza's feet-first slide broke
through catcher Ben Petrick's block to draw the Mets within two
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe White replaced DeJean and struck out Robin Ventura looking
at an 0-2 pitch to end the inning and quiet the crowd. Ventura
slowly left the plate after speaking with Umpire Brian Runge.
Ventura wasn't alone in his displeasure. Eight batters struck out
looking Wednesday night, including six Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch was charged with six runs in seven-plus innings, the most
runs he has allowed since he gave up seven on July 2 against the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Rick White had allowed only one run in his previous six outings
as a Met. Wednesday night, he had the misfortune of allowing a
run-scoring single to Bohanon with two outs in the eighth inning.
Bohanon had four hits this season before Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
