<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-ASSESS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: LIEBERMAN MUST DOWNPLAY PAST POLICY DIFFERENCES WITH
GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs 4th graf to correct spelling of `shtick')  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was a new-model Joseph Lieberman, hurriedly
retooled to the specifications of a national campaign, who took the
stage here Wednesday night as the presumptive Democratic vice
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   No advocacy of school vouchers or the partial privatization of
Social Security, no criticism of affirmative action. No untrimmed
edges that might keep the party's core voters from supporting Al
Gore. Nothing that might dramatize the candidates' differences
rather than their agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Al Gore for 15 years,'' Lieberman assured the
convention delegates in his speech. ``I know his record and his
heart. I know him as a public servant and I know what it is like to
sit with him around the dining room table. We have discussed _
sometimes even debated _ policy issues. And we have shared private
moments of prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   There was talk about his family, about his immigrant
grandmother, his father's bakery route, his wife's family's
survival of the Holocaust. There was a helping of Jewish shtick.
There was a bow to bipartisanship _ ``our opponents are decent and
likable men'' and ``I am proud to call many in their party my
friends'' _ but also a careful enumeration of policy differences
between the rival tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But any new proposals will have to come from Gore himself on
Thursday night. For his part, Lieberman delved even less into the
nitty-gritty than Dick Cheney, his Republican opponent, did at the
Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of the vice presidential candidate (and the
vice president, for that matter), where the rules are simple:
Praise your master and mute your own views.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of his record, some people might have expected
something a bit more unconventional, from Lieberman, the
Connecticut senator, though probably unrealistically.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton was a master at reconciling differences among
Democrats of varying stripes. But as William Daley, the chairman of
the Gore campaign, noted the other day, wearing his best Buster
Keaton deadpan, ``Clinton is not on the ticket this year.'' And
Gore has trouble enough with the party's base without getting into
more because of Lieberman's views.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of Democratic skittishness on this point that
Lieberman has backtracked on several points of importance to the
constituencies that the ticket needs to re-energize. But the
rejiggering could be costly.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has a bit of a reputation for flip-flopping and
corner-cutting on issues like abortion and trade. Former Sen. Bill
Bradley, Gore's opponent during the primaries, accused him in
January of ``using words in a very tricky manner.'' Gov. George W.
Bush, the Republican nominee, mocked Gore for having voted one way
on guns in the 1980s and another in the 1990s, adding, ``When it's
convenient politically, he changes his tune.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists hoped that Lieberman, who refused to
buckle when colleagues tried to dissuade him from criticizing
Clinton's sexual misconduct, would lend the ticket some
stand-by-your-guns luster. Much of that could be lost if Lieberman
seems to be bending to political expediency at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman began attacking that problem when they
visited the vice president's home town, Carthage, Tenn., almost a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me,'' said Lieberman, ``when President Gore decides,
Vice President Lieberman will support him wholeheartedly.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president responded: ``I think it's a strength and not
a weakness, an asset, not a liability, to be able to have a
different point of view represented in the room at the time that
decisions are being made.''
</P>
<P>
   But that, they seem to have concluded since, was not quite
enough.
</P>
<P>
   There was a day when presidential nominees chose running-mates
who provided ideological balance. In 1952, Adlai Stevenson, a
Northern liberal, chose John Sparkman, an Alabama conservative, and
in 1976, Jimmy Carter, a Southern conservative, chose Walter F.
Mondale, a Minnesota liberal. But like so many old norms in U.S.
politics, that has gone by the board.
</P>
<P>
   This year, ideological identity is the real goal for the
Democratic ticket, much as the party may have flaunted its
ideological diversity in ``Liberals' corner'' Tuesday night. Vice
President Al Gore not only selected someone from roughly the same
segment of the party as he _ both have been stalwarts of the
centrist Democratic Leadership Conference _ but he and his aides
have sought to make sure Lieberman fell into line on all the major
issues.
</P>
<P>
   That took some doing, because on some issues, his position was a
bit to the right of Gore's. Not that Lieberman is a right-winger,
or anything resembling one. He may have had doubts about
affirmative action, for example, but he will be the first person
ever chosen for a national ticket who went to Mississippi to show
racial solidarity in the dark days of 1963.
</P>
<P>
   But take the matter of vouchers issued to parents by the federal
government, to be used to pay their children's tuition. In his time
as Connecticut's junior senator, Lieberman sponsored legislation
establishing experimental programs for vouchers. He voted for such
programs on at least four occasions. But vouchers are anathema to
the American Federation of Teachers and the 2.5 million-member
National Education Association, a pair of powerhouses that are
expected to pour money and manpower into the Gore campaign this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? After he was named by Gore, according to a report in
The Wall Street Journal, Lieberman called Sandra Feldman, the
leader of the teachers' federation, and promised that a
Gore-Lieberman administration would be resolutely anti-voucher.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Lieberman voiced support for Proposition 209 in
California, a ballot initiative that ended racial and gender
preferences in state university admissions. The same year, in a
Senate floor speech, he said ``affirmative action is dividing us in
ways its creators could not have intended,'' and added: ``If you
discriminate in favor of one group on the basis of race, you
thereby discriminate against another group on the basis of race.''
</P>
<P>
   Statements like that helped to win Lieberman a reputation as one
of the least partisan, most civil and most thoughtful members of
Congress. But not among African-Americans, one of the groups Gore
must count upon.
</P>
<P>
   So this week Lieberman visited the Congressional Black Caucus to
assuage its members' concerns. ``I have supported affirmative
action,'' he told them. ``I do support affirmative action. And I
will support affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he has retreated from the idea of allocating some
percentage of Social Security funds for investment by individuals _
a proposal, known as partial privatization, at the heart of the
Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in 1998 with the Copley News Service, Lieberman
said, ``I think in the end that individual control of part of the
retirement-Social Security funds has to happen.'' Gore stoutly
opposes that.
</P>
<P>
   But almost immediately after he was chosen by Gore, the senator
released an unpublished op-ed article entitled, ``My Private
Journey Away from Privatization,'' written at the behest of the
Gore campaign. In it, he said that the promises and the numbers
supporting the proposal ``don't add up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
