<SLUG> BC-DNC-HUGGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSEMBLY LEADER KNOWN FOR HIS HUGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You could call him the Compassionate Californian.
</P>
<P>
   State Assembly Speaker Robert M. Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys, loves to
hug. And after addressing the Democratic National Convention on
Wednesday, he waded into the California delegation to do the thing
that has become his trademark: hug. And hug and hug and hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's famous for hugging but, you know, he's very genuine,''
gushed Assemblyman Darrell Steinberg, D-Sacramento, the first to
receive a lingering bear hug from the jovial lawmaker after he
spoke to the DNC about health care and presidential nominee Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-hour on the convention floor, Hertzberg clutched at
least a dozen people, some of them twice. That's one hug every
two-and-a-half minutes; barely enough time to clutch, release, take
a step and repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's who I've always been all of my life,'' Hertzberg said
between embraces. ``It's just how I relate to people. It gives a
warmth and a connectedness.''
</P>
<P>
   He has it down to a science: the bear hug, the shoulder-pat hug,
the cheek hug. And every once in a while, he even squeezes two
people at once.
</P>
<P>
   He mostly sticks to hugging people he knows, he said. ``If
they're Democrats, I'll hug them twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Tony Cardenas, D-Panorama City, was treated to a hug
and even a quick back rub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though he's one of the three most powerful people in the
state of California, he's still the same guy,'' Cardenas said.
``The hugs we get from him today are the same we got from him two
years ago and 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobbie Jean Anderson, a Los Angeles delegate, also received an
embrace by Hertzberg. And she doesn't let just anybody do that.
``Some people I don't, but he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Hertzberg, a Sherman Oaks lawyer who was elected to the Assembly
in 1996 and quickly became one of the Legislature's most
influential members, tailored his remarks Wednesday to health care
issues.
</P>
<P>
   He said Gore will, if elected, work to expand coverage for
treatment of mental illness, prescription drugs for older Americans
and health insurance for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to improving the health of all Americans, Al
Gore is just what the doctor ordered,'' he said. ``I know that when
the votes are counted, California is Gore country.''
</P>
<P>
   He shared the podium with his wife, Dr. Cynthia Tellis of the
UCLA School of Medicine. Tellis' father was the first Latino
ambassador for the United States, appointed by former President
John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hispanics all across the country are looking forward to once
again electing a great American who understands that in an era of
tremendous growth and prosperity, our greatest challenge is to
ensure that no community is excluded and that no American is left
behind,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
