u p BC-NY-LAZIO-420&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      08-17 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDE CONFRONTS LAZIO ON TAX DISCLOSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTON, N.Y. _ Among the demonstrators greeting Rep. Rick Lazio,
the Republican Senate nominee, on a Harlem sidewalk on Wednesday
was a tall, bearish man dressed casually in khaki pants and a dark
golf shirt and clutching a couple of slips of paper.
</P>
<P>
   It was none other than Howard Wolfson, the communications
director and a top adviser for Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate
campaign, who came for one of the more unusual recent stunts
intended to tarnish Lazio's appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson, responding to Lazio's quip Tuesday that he would
release his state income tax return in 15 minutes if Clinton did
the same (as a resident for six months, she would have no such
return), sought to thrust on him copies of Mrs. Clinton's property
tax bills from her home in Chappaqua. Disclosure of the $17,368.64
in payments on those bills, Wolfson reasoned, complied with the
spirit of Lazio's challenge, which followed repeated demands by
Democrats that he release his federal income tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he says he can release them in 15 minutes, why doesn't
he?'' Wolfson asked reporters as he stood near a Democratic Party
operative dressed as Uncle Sam and shouted for Lazio to release his
tax return. Lazio has said repeatedly he will do so this month.
President and Mrs. Clinton released their return in April.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, told of Wolfson's presence after a speech at the National
Black Theater, did not acknowledge the visitor as he left behind a
curtain of police officers, who blocked Wolfson's way.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson declined to hand the papers to Patrick McCarthy, a Lazio
spokesman, as Lazio boarded his campaign bus to continue a tour
across the state that began Wednesday and concludes Monday.
Wednesday evening, he was at the Delaware County Fair here in
Walton.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign, seeking to rebut Lazio's questioning of
Clinton's character and integrity, has taken up the issue of his
not releasing his tax returns _ a ritual expected of candidates
these days _ as a way to question Lazio's own character.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, the episode highlighted the effort by
the Clinton campaign and its supporters to rain on Lazio's
campaign. Lazio's staff, in turn, has grown irritated at the
intrusions that they say only reinforce what they consider the
negative tenor of the first lady's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a cheap political stunt,'' McCarthy said afterward,
asserting it only reaffirmed that Clinton could not produce state
income tax returns because ``she is not really from New York.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWs)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wolfson is not the only assistant to Clinton making his presence
known on the opponent's trail. Employing a common campaign tactic,
a young man from the Clinton campaign trails Lazio with a small
video camera at nearly all of the congressman's appearances,
without disrupting them. ( Lazio, who says he does not employ such
a tracker, has come to know ``Eric'' and even gave him a slice of
pizza and a transit fare card at a recent event.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is ``Uncle Sam,'' who has become a fixture at
Lazio's events this past week, with a Lazio spokesman wrestling him
away from the podium before Lazio began a news conference Monday.
And demonstrators from abortion rights groups have waved placards
questioning his commitment to abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Clinton is often greeted at her appearances by
protesters from anti-abortion groups.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio received a mixed reaction in Harlem, one of the
traditionally Democratic areas he says his campaign will seek to
reach.
</P>
<P>
   As his bus approached the theater, the Rev. Calvin O. Butts III,
pastor of the Abyssinian Baptist Church, one of the most
influential in the city, tapped on the door and greeted Lazio, who
stepped off momentarily. Butts said he had made no endorsement in
the race and might not do so, but he had kind words for the
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have found the Republican administration in the state of New
York has been extremely helpful for the things we have done here in
Harlem, as well as for the things we hope to do in the future,''
Butts said after embracing Lazio and inviting him to the church. He
said he had discussed Lazio's candidacy favorably with Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in his largely autobiographical speech, Lazio sprinkled
references to Langston Hughes in his talk before 200 mostly elderly
residents gathered for lunch at a Harlem Week 2000 celebration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
