</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-LIEBERMAN-HUMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO HERE'S THIS JEWISH GUY WHO GETS NOMINATED ... 
</HEADLINE>
  By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No doubt about it, Joseph Lieberman is a
trailblazer. Wednesday night he surely became the first
vice-presidential nominee in American history to begin his
acceptance speech with a mother-in-law joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old saying that behind every successful man, there
is a surprised mother-in-law,'' Lieberman, lifting his eyebrows for
emphasis, told a national television audience after being
introduced by his wife, Hadassah. ``I am here to tell you, It's
true.''
</P>
<P>
   That was just one of a string of borscht belt lines that
Lieberman has delivered in recent days. At a meeting of 200
Hispanic Democrats on Wednesday, he said he was thrilled when Vice
President Al Gore made that special phone call last week. But he
added, ``I'll be honest with you: I'd be excited if just about
anybody else called.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk of this convention has been comparisons between John F.
Kennedy's religion breakthrough 40 years ago and Lieberman's now.
But it may have been Henny Youngman, Rodney Dangerfield, Jack Benny
or any of the legions of other Jewish comedians, whose distinctive
humor has permeated the popular culture so thoroughly, who also
paved the way for Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Joe,'' said the comedian Al Franken, who picked
Lieberman as his own running mate in his recent faux presidential
campaign book, ``Why Not Me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe read the book,'' Franken said, ``and made up some bumper
stickers for an all-Jewish ticket. `Franken-Lieberman: No Pork, No
Bull,' and one for the angry white male voters, `Lox and Load.'
He's a happy fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point Wednesday, Lieberman welcomed Al and Tipper
Gore to the convention, meeting them at Burbank Airport with a
twist on Ronald Reagan's old standby line. ``I've been waiting for
a week to say this,'' Lieberman began, ``and I can't control myself
anymore. In this election, will you help me win one for the
Tipper?''
</P>
<P>
   Talking to gay and lesbian Democrats at a caucus meeting, he
quoted his parents in an accent of pure shtick: ``When I went into
politics, my parents said, `You can make a living from this?'''
</P>
<P>
   And at the convention Wednesday night he brought down the house
by lambasting the Republicans with this line: ``Not since Tom Hanks
won an Oscar has there been that much acting in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean Daniel, a veteran movie producer here, said he was sure his
Jewish friends in the entertainment industry would appreciate
Lieberman's efforts despite his sometimes caustic critiques of the
moral content of their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood might take issue with some of his pronouncements,
and at the same time see its own roots in Lieberman's material,''
said Daniel, who said other Jewish friends in the business had told
him they would be going home early to catch Lieberman's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not being facetious. That will surface quickly in the
brain of any Hollywood viewer. It's turning into quite a matter of
pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say,'' Daniel added in a line of his own. ``We're
funny.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 0011EDT &QL; 
