<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE ENDS RANGERS' SKID AND ADDS TO HERNANDEZ'S 
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ He sprinted off the mound after each inning
and jumped over the foul line. He buried his face in a towel once
he got to the first-base dugout and he tried to remain calm in a
tense setting. Brian Sikorski was throttling the Yankees in his
major league debut, stopping a team that has won three of the last
four World Series and a team that regularly antagonizes the Texas
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas right-hander could not think about the past
because he was worried about the present and whether he could
continue slipping and sliding past the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   While Sikorski was resilient in leading the Rangers to a 5-0
victory on Wednesday night, Orlando Hernandez had another subpar
performance and lost his third straight start since being activated
from the disabled list on Aug. 6. He has lost four in a row
overall. The last time El Duque won was on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Sikorski held the Yankees scoreless into the eighth. Hernandez
allowed four earned runs in seven innings and was hurt by left
fielder Luis Polonia, who made one error and should have been
charged with another in plays that helped lead to three Texas runs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 96-degree temperature and humid conditions,
Hernandez (8-10) wore a long-sleeved shirt under his uniform.
Hernandez loves the warm weather and seemed comfortable while
retiring the first six Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Lamb led off the Rangers' third and battled the Yankee
right-hander in a nine-pitch at-bat. After Hernandez jumped ahead
with a 1-2 count, Lamb fouled off four pitches before lacing a 2-2
pitch for a single. The ball soared a few inches past Hernandez's
glove and into center field.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez stalked around the mound and then threw a quick pitch
to Bill Haselman, which Haselman smacked for a single. Royce
Clayton's sacrifice bunt moved the runners to second and third, and
Luis Alicea punched a single to center that knocked in Texas' first
run.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro had been one for 19 against Hernandez before he
faced him in the fourth. Hernandez tossed a hanging slider to
Palmeiro and Palmeiro hammered it deep to right field.The only
question was whether Palmeiro's drive would remain fair, and when
it did, it made the score 2-0. It was Palmeiro's 391st career
homer, 35th on the career list.
</P>
<P>
   The game got messier in the fifth as Manager Joe Torre's
revolving door in left field hurt the Yankees. With two out,
Hernandez walked Alicea and gave up a single to Frank Catalanotto.
Rusty Greer hit a sinking line drive to left and Polonia, who
started his fourth game in left since joining the Yankees on Aug.
3, charged in and then stopped when he realized he would not be
able to catch the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But Polonia turned his head while the ball bounced and it
deflected off his leg and rolled to the warning track. Both runs
scored on a play that was generously scored a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Sikorski, who was 10-9 with a 4.04 earned run average for Class
AAA Oklahoma, was recalled after Ryan Glynn was put on the disabled
list. Glynn fainted in the dugout during his start last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sikorski walked Derek Jeter in the first, but the Yankees
stranded him. David Justice singled and Tino Martinez doubled in
the second, but Sikorski struck out Jorge Posada and Scott Brosius
on 0-2 fastballs. Jose Vizcaino walked, but Polonia grounded out to
leave the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   After Jeter opened the third with a double, Sikorski retired 13
straight. The Yankees were 0 for 8 with runners in scoring position
against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
