u p BC-DEM-LIEBERMAN-CONN-NY     08-17 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-LIEBERMAN-CONN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A FAVORITE SON, ALLEGIANCE ON DISPLAY IN NEW HAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ As this city's most famous resident, Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, appeared Wednesday night before Democratic Party
delegates and a national television audience, many of his
supporters back in Connecticut gathered to watch and cheer him and
share what they all said was a visceral sense of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special feeling,'' said state Rep. Michael P. Lawlor,
one of about 80 Democrats gathered at Tycoons, a corner bar here,
to eat chicken wings and watch Wednesday's night's speech on a
rented large-screen television. ``Especially because two weeks ago,
you're trying to figure out which baseball game to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lieberman strode on stage in Los Angeles and the applause
there and in the New Haven bar reached a crescendo, Lawlor added
derisively, ``Did this happen with Dick Cheney?'' Wednesday night's
bar party was thrown by state Sen. Martin M. Looney, a Democrat
from New Haven, who invited every party member he could find to
come and watch Lieberman address the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sense of celebration,'' Looney said inside the bar,
between backslaps and handshakes. ``This is the first time we've
had anyone from Connecticut on the presidential ticket.'' Wednesday
night's gathering, he went on, was to acknowledge ``a sense of
community and a sense of shared pride and getting ready for the
hard work ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lieberman spoke of his family background and hammered away at
the policies of his Republican opponents, the partisan crowd here
cheered, sometimes longer and seemingly louder than the delegates
in Los Angeles. On the walls of the bar were several hand-drawn
posters announcing ``Liebermania'' and ``Mazel Tov Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   During the speech, Norma Rodriguez-Reyes, another New Haven
Democrat, beamed with pride. ``It was really intense, I felt like
we were part of the convention,'' she said afterward. ``I felt as
if we were all part of one big family here. This was a time when no
one recognizes any difference between us.'' Her favorite line, she
said, came when Lieberman acknowledged that ``behind every
successful man, there's a surprised mother-in-law.''
</P>
<P>
   James D. Newton, a former New Haven mayoral candidate, clapped
enthusiastically for Lieberman as he strode off the stage. ``Joe
Lieberman made a powerful speech tonight,'' he said. ``I think he
made it very clear that there is a racial divide that separates
people in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many others here, Philip Voigt, a New Haven alderman, said
he came because of a mixture of personal and political allegiance
to Lieberman. ``We've seen Joe move from being attorney general to
United States senator,'' he said. ``One of our own being selected
for vice president, it's real personal pride.'' And besides, he
said, ``Joe's son is in my wife's synogogue.''
</P>
<P>
   A few miles down Interstate 95, in the Stamford living room of
Alex and Vita Lionetti, 10 of the senator's former Stamford High
School classmates were holding their own Joe Lieberman party.
Everyone in the Lionettis' living room had known Lieberman since he
won the ninth-grade class presidency, a year before he was voted
king of the sophomore sock hop, which he did not attend because of
measles (leaving the queen, Lionetti, to sit by an empty chair all
night).
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for Wednesday evening's speech, the Lionettis laid
out an array of cheeses and crackers on red, white and blue napkins
and paper plates and posted a few American flags and old
photographs of Lieberman on the walls. ``We got a little
patriotic,'' Lionetti admitted. As 10 p.m. drew closer, everyone
paged through high school yearbooks and settled in for a large,
nationally televised dose of Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great speech for Joe Lieberman, to try to let people
understand who he is,'' Lionetti said after Lieberman walked off
the podium in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family items were probably the most telling,'' he went on.
``Sometimes you don't really hear him say a lot about himself. I
think a lot of people like to know the guts of a person, and I
think they really got to know Joe Lieberman as a caring person.''
</P>
<P>
   Lionetti, now an accountant in Stamford, heads the Class of
1960's annual reunion, which Lieberman makes a habit of attending.
Wednesday night was the 40th reunion planning committee's second
meeting (its first meeting was on the same day Lieberman and Gore
appeared together in Stamford last week.) ''Anytime we have a
meeting, something big is happening with Joe,'' Lionetti said.
</P>
</TEXT>
