<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4234 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-DEMS-HNS &LR;      08-17 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-DEMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ARRIVES TO GET DEMOCRATIC NOMINATION &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democrats nominated Vice President Al Gore for
president Wednesday night, after a parade of admirers _ including
his running mate and his daughter _ promised new opportunities for
prosperity for all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   While praising Gore in an address to the Democratic National
Convention, vice-presidential candidate Joseph Lieberman also went
on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Republican nominee George W. Bush, a self-styled
``compassionate conservative,'' of merely giving lip service to
people's needs and of neglecting environmental and health care
problems in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of appealing to a broad range of American voters,
Lieberman underscored the importance of family, hard work, hope and
prayer in his own life.
</P>
<P>
   He was interrupted several times by chants of ``Go, Joe, Go!''
from the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's eldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, 27, seconded her
father's nomination after Gore was nominated by actor Tommy Lee
Jones, a college roommate.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff recounted several childhood experiences, including how
her father helped with late-night homework assignments and taught
his children how to build an igloo after a big snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Dad is a man of faith in the most gutsy, practical sense,''
she said. ``He wants to see goodness prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff said her father wants to provide affordable health care,
give struggling single mothers a ``fair paycheck,'' protect the
environment and defend abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in every woman's right to choose _ and I know my
father will always, always defend it,'' she said, pointing out one
of the most emotional issues that separate Gore and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; After Schiff spoke, Gore made a brief appearance, his first in
the convention hall. He walked onto the podium to embrace his
daughter, wave to the crowd and shake hands with a few people
sitting nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The roll call of states followed, with Florida providing the
votes necessary to put Gore's nomination over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who roomed with Gore for four years at Harvard, discussed
the men's friendship, rather than politics, in his nominating
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said his big issues concerning Gore were these: ``Are they
feeding him well? And will the stress of the job hurt him?''
</P>
<P>
   He answered his own questions: ``He has sense enough to eat well
_ and the stress is no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he was glad that Republicans had ``changed their
rhetoric, but I wish they would also change their policies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good thing that our opponent talks about
education. Schools need to be held to the highest standards of
performance and accountability,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   But, he contended, Bush's education plan doesn't provide enough
resources for schools to meet high standards.
</P>
<P>
   He also ripped into Bush for poor air and water quality in
Texas, for being governor of a state that ``ranks next to last for
health insurance for both women and children'' and for proposing
tax cuts for the wealthy at the expense of the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their (Republican) tax plan operates under the old theory that
the best way to feed the birds is to give more oats to the horse,''
Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see America's hard-earned surplus through a very different
set of eyes, the eyes of working middle-class families.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released from Austin soon after Lieberman spoke,
Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett said, ``Tonight, Senator
Lieberman took a page from Al Gore's playbook by misrepresenting
the facts about Governor Bush's record in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Lieberman, the first Jewish candidate to run for vice
president under a major party banner, vowed to work to ``overcome
the differences that are still between us, to break down the
barriers that remain, and to help every American claim the
limitless possibilities of our own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he knew Gore's record and ``his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have discussed _ often debated _ policy issues. And we also
shared private moments of prayer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a senator from Connecticut, drew on his own family's
experience to paint a picture of hope for Americans from
disadvantaged or modest backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   His father, he said, lived in an orphanage as a child and later
drove a bakery truck and owned a package store.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught us the importance of work and responsibility. With
my mother by his side, he saw me become the first person in my
family to graduate from college,'' Lieberman continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that somewhere in America right now, there is another
father loading another bakery truck, or a young woman programming a
computer, or a parent dreaming of a better future for their
daughter or their son.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep the faith, then 40 years from now one of their
children will stand before a gathering like this, with a chance
like I have to serve and lead this great country that we love so
dearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also reaffirmed his support for affirmative action, an
issue that raised concern this week among black Democrats.
Lieberman told black congressional leaders on Tuesday that his
position was misrepresented in a 1995 news report saying he
supported an anti-affirmative action proposition in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to affirmative action, mend it, but please don't
end it,'' he said, adopting a phrase President Clinton has used on
the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his wife, Tipper, arrived earlier Wednesday at the
Burbank Airport, where they were greeted by a mariachi band and
enthusiastic supporters in an airport hangar. Lieberman and his
wife, Hadassah, also were at the airport to join the Gores.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic ticket was greeted by Los Angeles Mayor Richard
Riordan, a Republican, and California Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced by Tipper Gore, Lieberman quipped, ``In this election
will you help me win this one for the Tipper?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the airport crowd that his campaign is about bringing
``positive change to America.'' He said he was looking forward to
delivering an acceptance speech that will talk about ``hard choices
that I believe we have to make in order to ensure that we have a
bright future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You deserve to know exactly what the candidates are proposing
to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore noted that he supported managed care reform, gun control,
raising the minimum wage and laws against hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   On a day that portrayed Gore as a ``principled fighter'' for
such issues as education, health care and human rights and against
gun violence, House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., told
the convention that Gore ``could be the best president this country
will ever have.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Mayor Lee Brown, who once was drug czar in the
Clinton-Gore administration, addressed the convention Wednesday
afternoon, telling delegates that Gore was ready for the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked day in and day out with Al Gore, and I was impressed
with his intelligence, integrity and sense of fair play,'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Martin Frost of Dallas and state Rep. Al Edwards of
Houston, also joined a steady stream of Democratic pre-prime time
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Frost, chairman of the House Democratic caucus, said that
Democrats were responsible for most of the ``compassionate''
government programs in Texas that Republican nominee Bush ``tries
to claim credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 0016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
