<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4236 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETH     08-17 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN SETS STAGE FOR GORE AS DEMOCRATS NOMINATE TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS lede with Gore nomination)  
(ART ADV: Photos _ CVN1,10,12,13,14,15,16,17,18,20 _ are being sent
to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds.: Complete text of the speeches by Joseph Lieberman, Dick
Gephardt and Karenna Gore Schiff is available on The New York Times
Website: www.nytimes.com) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Albert Arnold Gore Jr., who steadfastly served as
vice president through an often tumultuous eight years, was
nominated for president Wednesday night after his running mate,
Sen. Joseph Lieberman, introduced himself to America with a
forceful appeal on behalf of Gore and a muted rebuke of Gov. George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, whose selection as Gore's running mate made him the
first Orthodox Jew on a major party ticket, offered a personal
testament to the vice president by saying they were so close that
they prayed together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Al Gore for 15 years,'' Lieberman said in his
prepared text. ``I know his record and I know his heart. I know him
as a public servant and I know what it is like to sit with him
around the dining room table. We have discussed, sometimes even
debated, policy issues. And we have shared private moments of
prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Making his case for the Democratic ticket _ and one against the
Republicans _ on the night he and Gore were to be formally
nominated, Lieberman said flatly, ``It's this simple: We Democrats
will expand the prosperity. They will squander it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's address was one of the most anticipated, and
consequential, moments of the four-night convention. The Gore
campaign has counted on the Connecticut senator to electrify the
ticket of a standard bearer who has struggled to galvanize even
loyal Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for all the interest in Lieberman is that he is
virtually unknown beyond his home state. Though he has been a
senator for 12 years, Lieberman, who is 58, is not nearly as tested
on the national stage as Gov. George W. Bush's running mate, Dick
Cheney, who had served as a congressman, White House chief of staff
and secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also took a shot a the Republicans who gathered in
Philadelphia two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Republican friends tried to walk and talk a lot like us,''
he said. ``But let's be honest. We may be near Hollywood. But not
since Tom Hanks won an Oscar has there been that much acting in
Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the largely glowing reception Lieberman has drawn, his
selection has unsettled some liberal Democrats because of his
centrist stands. On Tuesday, he met with black delegates to
reassure them that he supported affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Wednesday night, he sought to establish his
credentials as champion for minorities. ``In the early 1960s, when
I was a college student, I walked with Martin Luther King in the
march on Washington,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who had not been widely viewed by most Democrats as a
likely choice for Gore _ and was plucked out of obscurity only
eight days ago _ still seems a bit fazed by his newfound celebrity
and, perhaps, that Gore dared to pick a Jew. As he put it in his
opening line, ``Is America a great country or what?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Before the program opened, Gore arrived here triumphantly,
stepping off Air Force Two for a rally at the Burbank airport with
Lieberman and their families. Only one day after President Clinton
embraced Gore in Monroe, Mich., as the inheritor of his political
legacy, the vice president moved to strike out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every generation, we have to make the hard choices between
one direction or another, between going back to the past or forward
to the future,'' Gore declared. ``Let others argue the case for the
old guard. We're the new guard, and we're going to bring positive
change to the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if manufactured, the suspense Wednesday was inside the
Staples Center, where more than 4,000 delegates converged for the
ritualistic, but joyous, roll call of states to officially award
Gore his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore claimed enough delegates to put him over the top five
months ago, this remained a night of triumph _ and, at long last,
emergence _ for Gore. He represented Tennessee in the House for
nine years and the Senate for eight years, but has been best known
for his eight years of faithful service to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As did Cheney in Philadelphia two weeks ago, Lieberman used his
night in the spotlight to critique the opposition. He scolded
Republicans for putting forth what he portrayed as a misleading
festival of inclusion at its convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the GOP has changed their rhetoric,'' he said, ``but
I wish they would also change their policies. As my friend John
McCain might say, let me do some straight talking about their
record.''
</P>
<P>
   In the excerpts of his speech, Lieberman's taunts at the
Republicans were far more subtle than Cheney's had been against the
Democrats, signaling that Lieberman may not be as willing to play
the traditional running-mate role of attack dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing that our opponent talks about education,''
Lieberman said. ``Schools need to be held to the highest standards
of performance and accountability. But I'm sad to say their plan
does not provide the resources our schools need to meet those high
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I've read their plan. To me, it seems like their
idea of school modernization means buying a new calendar for every
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gore's often grueling primary race against Bill Bradley
and his high-profile assignments from Clinton, like running a
program to streamline the federal government, the vice president
remains something of a mystery to the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   It has become almost a cliche for people to describe Gore as
remote and hard to warm to. But Karenna Gore Schiff, Gore's eldest
daughter and one of his closest political advisers, sought to alter
that perception by describing a warm-hearted, conscientious Al Gore
that the public does not know.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my dad was a congressman, he listed our number in the
phone book in Carthage so the people he worked for could always
reach him,'' Schiff said in the prepared text of her speech
seconding Gore's nomination. ``During my summers on the farm, I
would answer the phone, and it would often be a constituent who
needed help getting his veterans' benefits, or finding the right
health care. I was taught to run _ not walk _ to get my dad so that
people wouldn't be kept waiting for a moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, who is 27, also spoke lovingly of her father. ``One time
he came home after a long day of hearings and meetings and votes
and found me struggling to begin that all-important elementary
school assignment: the dinosaur diorama,'' she recalled. ``He was
tired, but while my mom was getting the others to brush their teeth
and get in bed, my dad was the one who took me down to the store to
get the emergency Q-Tips, colored Play-Doh, and construction paper
because he was simply being a dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House Democratic leader whom Gore had
considered as his running mate, also spoke to the personal side of
Gore. ``Al Gore is a good man,'' he said. ``He is a decent, caring
man. He listens to his heart and his head. He loves his family. He
loves this country. He could be the best president this country
will ever have.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rubin, who was a treasury secretary under Clinton,
saluted Gore for his help in ensuring a vibrant economy. ``I worked
with Al Gore for six and a half years,'' he said. ``And he was a
powerful and effective force in all of the major economic policy
decisions that contributed so critically to this record. I was
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also took some time to tell his personal story to the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I try to see this world as my dad saw it from his
bakery truck,'' he said. ``About this time, he'd be getting ready
for the all-night run. I know that somewhere in America right now,
there is another father loading a bakery truck, or a young woman
programming a computer, or a parent dreaming of a better future for
their daughter or son.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep the faith,'' he went on, ``then 40 years from
now one of their children will stand before a gathering like this
with a chance to serve and lead this country that we love.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, at least, Lieberman brought the Democrats a
wave of favorable publicity in the days leading to the convention.
By turning to Lieberman, the first Democratic senator to
aggressively repudiate Clinton for his affair with a White House
intern, Gore underscored his determination to shed the president's
shadow.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in the convention hall Wednesday, more than 20
delegates, one after another, said they had not known much about
Lieberman until last week. But many said they were impressed, even
thrilled, as they learned more about him.
</P>
<P>
   Eufaula Frazier, a delegate from Florida who is black, said she
also could relate to the historic nature of the Lieberman
selection. ``Forty years ago I was a beautician and we were all in
the shop watching the TV, so excited we were about Kennedy being
nominated,'' she said. ``The supply man came in and said it was
incredible, a Catholic in such a position. He said maybe one day it
will be a Jew. It is coming true tonight, and I get to be a part of
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
