r s BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COL-SWIM     08-17 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COL-SWIM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FLAGS MAY NOT FLY HIGH IN SYDNEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ They set a lot of records. They wore a lot of
bodysuits. They cried a lot of tears.
</P>
<P>
   In the warm, chlorine-filtrated cocoon of the Indiana University
Natatorium, the fastest swimmers that the country has to offer
entranced audiences at the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials for eight
days and nights.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven American records fell, plus 23 Olympic trials marks.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the nightly standing-room-only crowd of swim
coaches, swim moms and swim dads, the Olympians-to-be could do no
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But tell me, mate _ can they take this act on the road?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about improvement,'' observed Mark Schubert, who will
coach the U.S. men's team in Sydney. ``Whatever happened here
really won't be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   Schubert wasn't trying to rain on the patriotic parade. As a
celebration of American swimming, these trials pushed all the right
buttons and drained all the right tear ducts. Each evening session
began with a stirring sermon by a designated luminary from U.S.
swimming's golden Olympic past.
</P>
<P>
   (The trials' low-water mark: the introduction of the unfortunate
1976 women's team. The team manager, whose name I have mercifully
purged from memory, took the microphone and exhorted the crowd to
cheer ``these girls, who were cheated by the East Germans.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Schubert is right. For all of the water that got churned
here, will any of it mean anything when the Americans swim again,
one month from now, halfway around the world?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to improve,'' U.S. women's coach Richard Quick said,
soberly. ``I'm not exactly sure, but I think we're ranked No. 1 in
the world in one women's event \Ractually two\S going into the
Olympics _ the 800 free.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the rest of the events, we've got to improve and swim
better than we ever have in our lives to have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   After failing to ruffle the record book at the '96 trials, yes,
there were American records broken here, nearly one or two every
day. But note that no world records fell during the NBC-elongated
eight days of competition. And Quick's math isn't far from wrong:
Only four of the times posted here rank as the fastest in their
events heading into Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Since most of the swimmers wore some style of bodysuit, you
could argue that the new suits influenced the number of American
records that were set.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, the bodysuit was a very good thing,''
Schubert said. ``But the jury is still out on that. Basically, this
meet was an experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, though, some people were swimming very, very fast
in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick tried to quell the concerns about the lack of world
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any world records in '96, and that women's team
still seemed to scramble away with seven gold medals,'' he sniffed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but Quick's first words rang the loudest. To reap
anywhere near the golden haul of the Atlanta Games, which came in
front of a home audience, times need to be lowered _ in one month's
time _ nearly across the board.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming has changed. While our U.S. college coaches were giving
out scholarships to German, Dutch and Canadian kids, all in the
name of winning a conference championship, the rest of the world
was reeling us in like a stuffed tuna.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest freestyle sprinter in the world is a Russian,
Alexander Popov. The fastest woman is a Dutch girl, Inge de Bruijn.
The favorite in the Olympic women's breaststroke will be a
Japanese, Masami Tanaka. And the odds-on, undisputed, most gifted
swimmer on the planet is Australian teen-ager Ian Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming has changed.
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans lay an egg in Sydney, USA Swimming officials,
including Schubert and Quick, will be sternly second-guessed for
their decision to hold the trials only four weeks before the start
of the Games. The last time anything like that was tried, 1988 (in
Austin), only Janet Evans and Matt Biondi brought home individual
gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   The two coaches addressed that yesterday, but they gave only
vague reasons about taking advantage of ``the natural summer'' and
how it's nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   Quick and Schubert apparently wanted their best athletes peaking
for Sydney, not for Indianapolis. They know that the Australians,
competing in their most passionate sport, in front of 17,000 every
night, will be more than ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to say,'' Schubert said, when asked to assess
what lies ahead for Jenny Thompson, Dara Torres, Gary Hall Jr. and
company. ``It's easy to race fast when you don't have the best in
the world, or the second- or third-best, swimming next to you.''
</P>
<P>
   In four weeks, we'll all find out.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0022 </DOCNO>
