<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-RAMPART-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
38 ARRESTED IN MARCH ON RAMPART STATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Updating arrest figure from 37 to 38 in headline,
2ndgraf) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dozens of demonstrators were arrested in acts of
civil disobedience Wednesday after a march from MacArthur Park to
the Los Angeles Police Department's Rampart Division to protest
police brutality and the Rampart scandal.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 took part in the rally and march. Police said 37 were
arrested at the police station for blocking the building.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles, spoke at MacArthur Park, a
day after he accused police of mishandling Monday night's protest.
He said he was working with police to maintain peace during the
march.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, protesters, including a large number of
Catholic workers, are being nonviolently arrested to symbolize what
they consider the injustices of police behavior,'' Hayden told the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   At the Rampart Division, hundreds of police surrounded the area
and lined the rooftops as protesters banged a drum and called out
the names of those they said were victims of the police.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters also demanded that the LAPD, not taxpayers, pay for
any restitution to unjustly accused Rampart defendants. They also
want an independent Rampart review and the release of Alex Sanchez,
whom they call a political prisoner, threatened with deportation in
the wake of a Rampart arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Steven Jacobs of Temple Kol Tikvah in Woodland Hills
participated in the protest and said the police show of power was
very intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Yugoslavia to rescue soldiers with Rev. Jesse
Jackson,'' Jacobs said. ``I feel more threatened here than I did in
downtown Belgrade when the bombs were going off.''
</P>
<P>
   Many think the protesters are ``just unruly kids who are
angry,'' he said. ``They are not. They have a very powerful message
about the incarceration of people, the future of our children and
police fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   American Civil Liberties Union officials said they intend to
file a federal lawsuit against the LAPD for deliberately attacking
members of the media during the melee outside Staples Center on
Monday night. The suit was not filed Wednesday because federal
court was closed. An ACLU representative said the group would
attempt to file it Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference at the nearby ACLU office, Chief Counsel
Michael Small said police who shut down a protest concert Monday
night went after the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LAPD deliberately targeted members of the media, clubbing
and shooting them,'' Small claimed, saying he has received six
calls from reporters interested in joining in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD Cmdr. David Kalish said he had not been briefed on the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be ludicrous to imagine the LAPD would target members
of the media,'' Kalish said. ``However, during the incident
following the rock concert, it may be possible that media who were
in the group were inconvenienced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0023 </DOCNO>
