<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENDT SETS U.S. RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Erik Vendt dropped his time 20 seconds in the
1,500-meter freestyle and almost drowned in the backwash. When the
USC sophomore won the metric mile at the 1998 outdoor senior
nationals, U.S. Swimming officials immediately branded him ``The
Next Great American Distance Swimmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Vendt wore the label like an albatross. He didn't come anywhere
near his personal best in the event last summer. When he failed to
make the finals at the Pan Pacific Championships in Sydney last
August, Vendt felt like he had hit rock bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Having sunk to such depths is what made his swim one year later
at the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials all the more satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Vendt, 19, became the first American to break the 15-minute
milestone in the event. He was timed in 14 minutes, 59.11 on
Wednesday in the final race of the 2000 U.S. Olympic Trials to
break the U.S. mark that George DiCarlo set at the 1984 Olympic
selection meet.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about ending with a bang; the subsequent fireworks display
inside IUPUI Natatorium that sent the 48-member Olympic team off to
Sydney seemed colorless by comparison. With his swim, Vendt
achieved the inconceivable on two fronts: He broke a barrier no
U.S. miler had come within four seconds of since 1984 and he stole
the spotlight from sometime model Dara Torres.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, 33, who returned to the sport last year after retiring
in 1992, set an Olympic Trials record in the 50-meter freestyle to
edge Amy Van Dyken, 24.90 to 24.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know most of the fans came here tonight to see Dara swim the
50,'' Vendt said, ``but I think we put on a good show.''
</P>
<P>
   Vendt was 3 years old when DiCarlo lowered the American record
to 15:01.51 (at which point Russia's Vladimir Salnikov already had
gone under 15 minutes). In the ensuing 16 years, Vendt, who clocked
a 15:10.50 in 1998, was one of only four Americans to advance to
within 10 seconds of the U.S. record.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Australia's Kieren Perkins was busy lowering the
global standard to 14:41.66.
</P>
<P>
   You can't approach 14:41 until you can conquer 15 minutes, which
is why swimming insiders were so quick to pin a nation's hopes on
Vendt when he entered DiCarlo's neighborhood in 1998. Little did
anybody - least of all, Vendt - suspect it would take another two
summers to break down the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I put a lot of pressure on myself,'' Vendt said. ``I
felt I had to do incredible stuff in practice every day. If I
didn't, I was really hard on myself. Swimming turned into a huge
burden. It wasn't fun at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Said USC coach Mark Schubert, ``Erik was so intense, he would
beat himself up emotionally if he didn't accomplish in practice
what he wanted to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Schubert, the head men's coach for the Sydney-bound U.S. team,
forced Vendt to swim behind one or two teammates on certain
freestyle sets at practice so his intensity couldn't lead him
astray.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy led Vendt right to where everybody thought he
belonged in the first place. ``It feels great to win and also to
break the American record,'' Vendt said. ``It's been my goal since
I started swimming the mile at 12 years old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 0059EDT &QL; 
