<SLUG> BC-SOC-BURN-FIRE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNGSTERS SPARK BURN'S WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A main reason for the Burn's inactivity Tuesday before
the Major League Soccer trading deadline was the faith Burn
higher-ups said they have in the future of their young players.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, at least three of those players made a strong case
for their status in the present.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Aleksey Korol scored two goals and first-year midfielder
Antonio Martinez, a second-half substitution, assisted on the
third, sealing a 3-0 victory against the Chicago Fire at the Cotton
Bowl. Second-year midfielder Lazo Alavanja also notched a secondary
assist on the second goal.
</P>
<P>
   The game represented a return to form for the Burn (12-12-4),
which had a less-than-inspired performance in its previous game and
had taken a 5-1 thrashing from the Fire in the teams' previous
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It also gave the Burn an additional push into the playoff
picture, boosting its overall points to 40, one behind the
fifth-place Fire (12-9-5) heading into a 10-day break for the Burn.
Eight of 12 teams make the playoffs, and the Burn has four games
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our young guys have been playing well lately,'' Burn
coach Dave Dir said. ``It's made a big difference for us.
Obviously, Martinez played well off the bench, and Korol played
extremely well tonight. And Alavanja did a great job of hanging on
and doing what he had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Korol, who scored his fourth and fifth goals of the season, was
able to work himself into the lineup because leading scorer Ariel
Graziani (13 goals) is playing for the Ecuador national team.
Another key player, sweeper Jorge Rodriguez, was with El Salvador's
national team, but the Burn defense managed to hold up without him.
</P>
<P>
   That Chicago was without seven regular starters _ including
leading scorer Ante Razov (13 goals) and playmaker Diego Gutierrez
(13 assists) _ didn't help the Fire. The Burn went up 1-0 in the
25th minute, when Korol collected a long cross from midfielder
Oscar Pareja and streaked across the middle of the field. Korol
fired a blast from 25 yards out to the left corner, catching
goalkeeper Zach Thornton off guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire missed two prime opportunities to equalize, both coming
early in the second half. Bulgarian midfielder Hristo Stoitchov
knocked an easy finish wide, and forward Josh Wolff had a
one-on-one breakaway play stifled by Burn goalkeeper Matt Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the most significant two plays of the game were the
two chances we had to make the game 1-1,'' Fire coach Bob Bradley
said. ``That probably took more out of us than the first goal.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
