<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEAGUE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SAFETY GEORGE TEAGUE WORRIES ABOUT JOB SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ With the pedigree of a high draft pick
and the resume of a journeyman, Cowboys free safety George Teague
admits his career has been somewhat of a conundrum.
</P>
<P>
   Selected 29th overall in the 1993 draft by the Green Bay
Packers, Teague has been with four teams in eight years, including
the Miami Dolphins (1997) and Atlanta Falcons (1996). He is in the
third year of a second stint with the Cowboys. He also was with the
team in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now the former Alabama star, who signed a four-year contract
extension with the Cowboys in the off-season, appears to finally
have a home.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys see Teague, 29, as a defensive anchor and are
counting on his leadership to help tutor the young cornerbacks this
season.
</P>
<P>
   However, Teague, whose paradoxical experiences have taught him
that things aren't always as they seem, says his main focus is
taking care of George Teague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of like have a selfish attitude,'' Teague said. ``In
the past I might be going out of my way to help a young buck out. I
got to worry about me, about George Teague. I'm not going to play
out of scheme, and I will do what I need to do to help out. But my
mind-set is what does George Teague got to do to keep his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking calmly and firmly while in his golf cart in front of
the cafeteria at Midwestern State, Teague's words were not guided
by emotions but by history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Cowboys gave the starting free-safety job to
second-year player Omar Stoutmire in training camp. Teague won back
the job in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Cowboys came to camp looking to insert Izell
Reese at free safety. Teague, however, won the job and started all
16 games.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed the best season of his career in 1999, posting a
career-high 102 tackles and intercepting three passes.
</P>
<P>
   His performance warranted a contract extension after the season.
And with Reese's future in question because of neck surgery, common
sense said the Cowboys would sign him to a deal without any
consternation.
</P>
<P>
   Teague got his contract, though the four-year, $3 million deal
is cheap compared with what other top safeties earn. He also hasn't
forgotten that the Cowboys hinted at his tenuous job security
during negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Teague is not mad. He just says he's not naive. He said he
played well last year because he trained hard and took care of
himself. He plans to do the same in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm carrying that over,'' Teague said. ``I have to have the
same mind-set. Just because I have a new deal, I still know how the
negotiating went. I don't feel set. I know Izell can play. I'm not
going in thinking I'm comfortable, because I don't know. I really
don't know how much confidence the team has in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo, who was the defensive coordinator the
past five years, does not apologize for trying to get ``the best
player on field.'' He says the way Teague has battled for his job
has made him and the Cowboys better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think George has ever gotten the respect he totally
deserves,'' Campo said. ``The guy has been in the league a number
of years. He's been a big playmaker. But we are always looking to
improve in an area. George just keeps turning that thing back,
saying `I am a football player, and I can do this.' I'm happy about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Secondary coach Bill Bates, citing Teague's hard-hitting play
against the Oakland Raiders on Sunday when he made a couple of
bone-jarring hits, including one that caused a fumble, calls the
braids-wearing safety a big part of the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Teague has heard the compliments before, but he dismisses most
of it as coach-speak. He knows that some guys have security and
some don't. He also knows that at one time he was part of the
``in'' crowd. Now he knows he's not.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't blame the Cowboys for his attitude or the
situation. Teague said he hasn't been comfortable since Green Bay
traded him to Atlanta before the 1996 season. The most embarrassing
moment of his career came when the Falcons cut him in training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   He then signed with the Cowboys and had a good enough season
that the Miami Dolphins signed him to a lucrative free-agent deal
in 1997. One year later, however, he was looking for a job again
and landed back with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain people you know they are going to be there ... Troy
\RAikman\S, Emmitt \R Smith\S, \RDarren\S Woodson,'' Teague said.
``But with George Teague and the Dallas Cowboys, you don't know. I
take it day by day. I signed a three-year deal in Miami and played
one year. I signed a contract with Atlanta and didn't play there at
all. Just because I signed a four-year deal here doesn't mean
anything. It's four one-year deals. This is the first trying to
make four.''
</P>
<P>
   To Teague, that is no mystery. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0031 </DOCNO>
