<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-TRADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS OWNER FINISHES TRADE, BUT ISN'T READY TO RELAX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Sleep has been hard to come by for Mark Cuban lately.
Brokering a nine-player, four-team trade that landed point guards
Howard Eisley and Dana Barros and forward//center Bill Curley has
kept the Mavericks owner up into the wee hours most nights the past
couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did get to sleep early Tuesday night after putting
his first major trade to bed, but with 21/2 months to go before the
start of the season, Cuban is settling in for many late nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be done dealing until the day they turn out the
lights,'' Cuban said yesterday at a news conference announcing the
completion of the mega-trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks, who traded Robert Pack and John ``Hot Rod''
Williams to Boston and Bruno Sundov to Utah, have 17 players under
contract. The NBA allows 12 on the active roster and up to three on
injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs are still searching for a backup center with their
$2.25 million salary-cap exception, which was not compromised by
the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban has often said that he's borrowing much of his ownership
strategy from fellow billionaire and Portland Trail Blazers owner
Paul Allen. Much like the Microsoft co-founder, Cuban is making
sure money _ and more specifically salary-cap issues _ don't stand
in the way of putting together the best team possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is not \Rto build\S the team with the fewest players
or the team with the optimal salary construction,'' he said. ``It's
the team with the best players that wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban plans many more moves before the season starts. He has
already talked to Barros' agent about trading the 11-year veteran,
who has two bulging disks in his back, to another team of Barros'
choosing.
</P>
<P>
   And though Cuban is hoping to package several players and their
salaries for more established players with bigger contracts, much
like Portland, he's not worried about possibly bringing 17 players
to training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to have them compete and pick the best 12-15 guys.
If it means someone ends up getting cut that we have a guaranteed
contract with, that's OK,'' Cuban said. ``I'd rather face the risk
of having to pay a guy that we have to release, than not having
enough guys.''
</P>
<P>
   One training-camp battle Cuban eagerly awaits is that of Eisley
and Steve Nash, last year's starting point guard. After backing up
future Hall of Famer John Stockton for the past five years in Utah,
Eisley said he's ready to start but isn't taking anything for
granted in his competition with Nash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both going to push each other, and it's going to help
make both of us better players,'' said Eisley, who averaged 8.6
points and 4.2 assists last season. ``No one has guaranteed me
anything. I come here to help this team. If I start, great. If not,
that's great, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said regardless of which player wins the starting job, the
Mavs settled one of their off-season goals _ depth at point guard.
Eisley received a seven-year contract for $41 million, with six
years and $35 million guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard brings playoff experience, Finals experience,'' Cuban
said, referring to the two trips the Jazz made to the NBA Finals.
``We saw what he did in the playoffs last year, single-handedly
trying to take over games. He's the type of player that we want.
He's the type of player the franchise hasn't had in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban put together the four-team trade, which involved
sign-and-trade deals for four of the players, with a tool
compliments of Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I built a little \RMicrosoft\S Excel spreadsheet,'' Cuban
said, ``and I starting plugging in players and calling different
teams saying, `This fits and that fits, this works and this works.
I heard that you were looking for this guy and you were looking for
this guy.'' And all the pieces fell into place.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the talk of how Portland conducts business, Cuban sent
a friendly jab at a team that he hopes can become a true Western
Conference rival one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference is I want a team that can hit a couple
shots up by 10 with eight minutes to go,'' he joked.
\Nsubheds:Nelson's goodwill mission Mavs coach//general manager Don
Nelson is in China working with Wang Zhi Zhi and the Chinese
national team. The Mavs are hoping to bring Wang, their 7-foot-1
second-round pick in 1999, to the NBA in the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When in the future, I'm not sure,'' Nelson said on the phone
from China yesterday. ``What I need to do is get him focused to
become the best player he can before coming over. We haven't seen a
lot of growth in him the last year. When you don't play against the
best competition, it's hard to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson would like to see Wang gain 15-20 pounds and improve his
conditioning. The Chinese team has been scrimmaging against a squad
of former NBA players, including former Mavericks star Rolando
Blackman. \NtagtopArthur Garcia, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:agarcia\Nstar-telegram.com
