<SLUG> BC-BBA-KAPLER-STREAK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAPLER'S STREAK RUNS OUT OF GAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers' Gabe Kapler spent the past two
days running on fumes, and on this night there would be nothing
left in reserve.
</P>
<P>
   That as much as anything spelled the demise of the longest
hitting streak in Rangers history.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler's eighth-inning at-bat last night against Yankees
left-hander Randy Choate revealed an overaggressive, overanxious
hitter exhausted mentally by the toll of a 28-game hitting streak.
Kapler chased and swung through an 0-2 fastball out of the strike
zone that completed an evening of four hitless at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried my best to enjoy it, but the last couple of days were
tough,'' Kapler said. ``I felt like I was just kind of hanging
on.''
</P>
<P>
   His body language and recent at-bats suggested as much to
manager Johnny Oates and hitting instructor Rudy Jaramillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see it,''' Jaramillo said.
</P>
<P>
   One can only wonder what former Yankees great Joe DiMaggio went
through during his streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even imagine 56,'' Oates said. ``We got halfway there.
We? I like the way I use the word ``we.'' It's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler sensed his streak in jeopardy before last night's game at
The Ballpark in Arlington. A headache annoyed him, and the
outfielder sensed mental exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took its toll,'' Kapler said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler drew a tough assignment to begin with Yankees
right-hander Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, who entered last
night's game limiting right-handed hitters to a .228 batting
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough on right-handed hitters,'' Kapler said. ``The funny
thing is I felt really comfortable against him. I felt like I got
some good pitches tonight as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez induced a routine fly ball from Kapler during their
second-inning encounter and a ground ball during his fourth-inning
at-bat. Kapler's best swing resulted in a sixth-inning smash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit that ball hard,'' Kapler said, ``but I hit it to the
wrong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter fielded the wicked short hop
cleanly and retired Kapler easily at first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a good play,'' Kapler said. ``This is a game of
inches. We all know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler admitted afterward that his patience at the plate
dwindled recently as the mental fatigue began to mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's to be expected,'' Oates said. ``You only get so
many chances, and you want to make the most of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates likely will reward Kapler with a break from tonight's game
against the Red Sox at Fenway Park. The streak is over after 28
games, the major leagues' best since Montreal's Vladimir Guerrero
hit safely in 31 games during the summer of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really proud of him,'' said Jaramillo, who worked
extensively with Kapler this season to rebuild his swing. ``There
was never a doubt that he was going to hit.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
