<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-KARENNA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTER PAINTS A LOVING PORTRAIT OF DAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore, months after clinching the
job, was formally chosen on Wednesday night as the Democratic
nominee for president after his eldest daughter described him in a
loving tribute as a man who ``wants to see goodness prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the applause for her speech died down, Gore came on
the stage to hug daughter Karenna Gore Schiff, waving to the
roaring, sign-waving, foot-stomping crowd that chanted, ``Let's go
Gore. Let's go Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   The more than 20,000 delegates and Democratic activists meeting
in Staples Center erupted again when Gore went over the top to win
the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration concludes tonight when Gore makes his acceptance
speech and prepares to face Republican nominee Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas in November.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was officially nominated for the presidency by his former
college roommate, actor Tommy Lee Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of people at this convention who will talk
about policy,'' the Academy Award-winning actor said, focusing
instead on anecdotes of their college years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can speak to this man's character. He is a good, decent,
loving man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a person with Al Gore's commitment. We need a
president with your heart, Al.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Schiff, however, who shined brightest for Gore on
Wednesday night with her warm recollections of a father who went
out of his way for his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always there for us ... and told us we could do
anything we worked for,'' Schiff said.
</P>
<P>
   And, she also pushed his belief in policy issues of health care,
equal pay, pollution and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope for the sake of our country and our future that my
father is elected president,'' Schiff said. ``I'm not asking you to
support Al Gore because he's my father or a great dad to his kids.
What really matters is what he will do for all our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In seconding the nomination and seeing her father selected as
the Democratic Party's presidential candidate, Schiff took a bold
public step in the political life to which she was born and,
seemingly, to which she is destined.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, 27, is seen as the Gore campaign link to Generation X
and as a counterpoint to George P. Bush, the half-Latino nephew of
Republican nominee George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, described as an energetic and candid campaigner for her
father, first became actively involved in political campaigning
during her father's second run for vice president after her
graduation from Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   She helped him prepare for his 1996 debates against Republican
vice presidential candidate Jack Kemp and remained as an unofficial
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Born to a political family, Schiff _ named after author Leo
Tolstoy's character Anna Karenina _ was 3 years old when her father
was first elected to Congress from Tennessee, following in his own
father's footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years she would campaign with him, take telephone
messages from constituents and sit in on strategic meetings _
where, the stories go, she would sometimes correct her father or
his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   During those years, she said, she saw the impact of being an
elected official and became motivated to get involved _ but at the
backroom, strategic level of planning, developing and cultivating
voters.
</P>
<P>
   After the successful 1996 election, Schiff moved to Spain and,
like her father, went to work as a newspaper reporter for El Pais.
In 1997, she returned to the United States and worked briefly for
the electronic magazine Slate and then was married the following
year to a New York physician, Drew Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, on July 4, she gave birth to a son and while taking
time off decided she wanted to play an active role in her father's
presidential campaign. She began by meeting with young people to
convince them of the need to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the trust her father places in her, that he agreed to
her suggestion to move the campaign from Washington, D.C., to
Tennessee. And, she advised him on his decision to select
Connecticut Sen. Joe Lieberman as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   During this convention, she has been actively involved in the
planning and staging of the events on Wednesday _ including the
list of speakers _ as well as in tonight's session where her father
is to deliver his acceptance speech, which she also is said to have
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff is part of a one-two punch of her generation in the Gore
family. Her sister Kristin, 23, is to speak tonight. The two long
have been in the public spotlight, thanks mostly to an NBC-TV
``Saturday Night Live'' skit about the ``babelicious Gore girls.''
</P>
<P>
   The two have been actively courting the MTV generation,
stressing how issues such as Social Security and Medicare are as
important to the young as they are to the elderly, since the young
will have to pay to keep the system alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
