r s BC-OUT-INTERNS-LADN     08-17 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-INTERNS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNS GET EDUCATION IN WILDERNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gustavo Gonzalez always has been receptive to new
experiences. The 17-year-old encountered his share in the Santa
Monica Mountains National Recreation Area outreach program this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was among five Wilson High students in the six-week
program designed to expose underrepresented groups to careers with
the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   The students were selected to the inaugural program on
scholarship and aptitude. They assisted staff ecologists with
removing exotic plants and replacing dead plants and the
restoration of the Potrero Creek at Ranch Sierra Vista/Satwiwa.
</P>
<P>
   The activities also ranged from soil sampling to water-quality
monitoring to tracking bobcats, coyotes, reptiles and insects to
maintenance of the backbone trail and office work. They were easy
to spot wearing baseball caps and T-shirts with the National Park
Service insignia.
</P>
<P>
   For Gonzalez, a member of the Wilson Environmental Academy and
Environmental Club who will be a senior in the fall, the job in the
Santa Monica Mountains National Recreation Area was a welcome
change from his internship at Cal Poly Pomona the previous summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made us be like farmers, which was not very fun for me,''
Gonzalez said. ``I was hoping the job would be better than Cal
Poly. I am willing to try everything once. So once I try everything
here, I'll tell you what I like doing best.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Villalaba, 18, Kelly Trainor, 17, and Phillip Rodriguez
and Joe Rene Jimenez, both 16, were other program participants.
Like Gonzalez, all had an interest in the environment and applied
to the program to aid in choosing a college major.
</P>
<P>
   Through a grant of nearly $15,000 from the Public Lands Corp.
and matching funds from the National Park Service, the students
were paid an hourly salary of about $8. For most, it was their
first paying job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides this being a job, I have always been into the
environment, nature and mostly animals,'' Trainor said. ``I was
always curious what a ranger does and the different opportunities
there were. I hoped to understand more what this field of work
would be as well as having fun and getting out of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's main interests are music and art but a career in the
National Park Service has become a strong candidate. He is
particularly interested in using his art skills to map parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like checking out all the stuff that is around and the
different places,'' Rodriguez said. ``Being able to meet new people
and make some friends out here is pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   The students worked Monday through Friday from 8:30 a.m. to 4:30
p.m., rising before sunrise to car pool for the 50-mile trip from
Los Angeles to report to duty at the visitors center in Thousand
Oaks. The round trip during rush-hour traffic averaged three hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked a little sleepy in the morning, but I was
impressed about how hard they worked,'' said coordinator John
Tiszler, a plant ecologist at the Santa Monica Mountains National
Recreation Area. ``There were preconceived thoughts about
teen-agers, but I was surprised with their enthusiasm to be ready
to go after a long ride.''
</P>
<P>
   The program was designed to complement Wilson's Environmental
Science Academy, a cooperative program with the L.A. Unified School
District and the National Resources Conservation Service in which
the students learn plant, insect, fish and animal biology.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the summer, the students worked on group
projects. Each day, they elected a leader, who was in charge of
safety and breaks. But in the final weeks of the program, the
students were frequently separated to fill demands for their
service.
</P>
<P>
   On their final day on Aug. 11, the students were honored at a
luncheon and presented appreciation certificates by Santa Monica
Mountains National Recreation Area Superintendent Art Eck.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were first planning this thing, there was concern
about them doing the same thing over and over again, but there was
a huge demand for their labor,'' Tiszler said. ``It got to the
point where people throughout the park were calling the day before
and asking if they were available.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiszler welcomes the students' return and would not hesitate to
hire them as seasonal employees. Funds permitting, he hopes to
expand the number of students next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a trial and in our eyes it was a great success,''
Tiszler said. ``We tend to call them interns, but they are much
more than volunteers. They are our official employees. They really
did a job for us, and the work they did was needed, which was good
for us and good for them to see the range of activities they might
be exposed to with the National Park Service.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
