<SLUG> BC-FBN-CUNNINGHAM-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUNNINGHAM LATEST COWBOYS QUARTERBACK WHO'S HURTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Cowboys yesterday re-signed former
Arena Fooball League quarterback Charlie Puleri to help them
through the preseason because of a mounting attrition at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Cunningham, Troy Aikman's backup, has been found to have
bursitis in his throwing shoulder. Paul Justin, who is in a battle
with Clint Stoerner for the No. 3 job, suffered a right elbow
contusion in Sunday night's loss to Oakland. Both Cunningham and
Justin are getting limited work.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, 37, doesn't consider the bursitis to be ``a
problem,'' while the Cowboys are ``just being precautionary about
it,'' coach Dave Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this juncture, I'm not too concerned. I think Randall will
work \Rthe bursitis\S out,'' said owner Jerry Jones, who is
comfortable in knowing that the 15-year veteran has had bursitis in
the same shoulder before.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham has demonstrated that he can throw the ball further
than any quarterback in camp. But the arm has made more than 4,400
throws in NFL games, and that doesn't count preseason games and
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Puleri, 30, went through the team's off-season workout programs
before being cut June 8]. Puleri was brought back because he knows
offensive coordinator Jack Reilly's system. Puleri will be on the
practice field this morning.
Enough for Ogden Frustrated by two separate foot sprains that have
held him out of training camp, wide receiver Jeff Ogden put on his
uniform yesterday afternoon and tried to practice. His bid was
denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our \Rmedical\S decision,'' Dave Campo said. ``He's not
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach can empathize with the third-year player who starred
for the Rhein Fire in NFL Europe before suffering the first of his
two foot sprains late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough sitting there, I know,'' said Campo, who earlier in
the day said at his daily news conference: ``Jeff obviously has
fallen farther and farther behind just because he's not out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo added, ``But he has a track record in NFL Europe and with
us, so we'll be a little bit more lenient in hoping he shows us
something relatively quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo is hoping to see Ogden in the final preseason game Aug. 24
against St. Louis.
Briefly ... Tight end Chris Smith lasted five days with the
Cowboys. He was waived yesterday after driving in from Washington,
where he earlier had been cut by the Redskins. Three free-agent
tight ends remain in the Cowboys' search for a third tight end who
can play behind either Jackie Harris or David LaFleur. The audition
became necessary when Mike Lucky suffered a season-ending knee
injury July 30 against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Erik Williams participated in both team
practices yesterday, after just observing his first day back in
camp.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
