<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4276 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-RDP-3RDLD-WRITETH     08-17 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-RDP-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN SETS STAGE FOR GORE AS DEMOCRATS NOMINATE TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for updating, rewriting throughout)  
(ART ADV: Photos _ CVN1,10,12,13,14,15,16,17,18,20 _ are being sent
to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds.: Complete texts of the speeches by Joseph Lieberman, Dick
Gephardt and Karenna Gore Schiff are available on The New York
Times Website: www.nytimes.com) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Albert Arnold Gore Jr., who steadfastly served as
vice president through an often tumultuous eight years, was
nominated for president on Wednesday night after his running mate,
Sen. Joseph Lieberman, introduced himself to America with a
forceful appeal on behalf of Gore and a muted rebuke of Gov. George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, whose selection as Gore's running mate made him the
first Jew on a major party ticket, delivered a personal testament
to the vice president, saying they were so close that they prayed
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is a man of courage and conviction,'' Lieberman said.
``He believes in service to America. He volunteered for Vietnam.
Together, we crossed party lines to support the Gulf war. I was
there in the room when I heard him forcefully argue that America's
principles and interests were at stake in Bosnia and Kosovo. That
wasn't easy. He had the guts to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ceremonial, but joyous, roll-call of states to ratify
Gore's nomination, Florida put him over the top just before
midnight ET, surpassing the 2,170 votes needed for the nomination.
The Democrats were signaling their intention to make Florida a
battleground in November.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the actual vote, the hall exploded in chants of
``We want Gore!'' when the vice president, unannounced, stepped
briskly on stage from a submerged stairway to embrace his eldest
daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, after she seconded his nomination
with a personal testament to her father. After waving to the roars
of the more than 4,000 delegates, the vice president strolled off
stage with his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The address by Lieberman, who will formally be nominated on
Thursday, was one of the most anticipated, and consequential,
moments of the four-night convention. The Gore campaign has counted
on the senator to electrify the ticket of a standard bearer who has
struggled to galvanize even loyal Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for all the interest in Lieberman _ who was
introduced by his wife, Hadassah, on Wednesday night as ``just a
regular Joe'' _ is that when he was plucked by Gore eight days ago
he was virtually unknown beyond his home state of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has been a senator for 12 years, Lieberman, who is 58,
is not nearly as tested on the national stage as Bush's running
mate, Dick Cheney, who had served as a congressman, White House
chief of staff and secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman dutifully took on Bush and the Republicans, but
without the hard edge of Cheney, who in his own acceptance speech
two weeks ago at the Republican convention in Philadelphia bitterly
ridiculed Gore and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's this simple,'' Lieberman said flatly. ``We Democrats will
expand the prosperity. They will squander it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's half-hour address was less a traditional attack on
the opposition and more an American tale of the senator's life
story. As Lieberman stepped to the rostrum, the hall swelled with
music from the film ``Chariots of Fire'' _ the story of two track
stars, a Jew who fought anti-Semitism to win an Olympic medal and a
Christian who refused the importunings of the King of England to
run on the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   While he said he was embarking on ``a miraculous journey,''
Lieberman first reached back to his own family's odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Lieberman remembered his grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was raised in Central Europe,'' he said, ``in a village
where she was often harassed because of the way she worshiped God.
And then she immigrated to America.''
</P>
<P>
   He moved on to his parents, Henry and Marcia Lieberman. ``My
father lived in an orphanage when he was a child,'' Lieberman said.
``He went on to work in a bakery truck and then owned a package
store in Stamford, Conn. He taught my sisters and me the importance
of work and responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to his mother in the audience, he said, ``Mom is 85
years old, but I'll tell you, she never felt younger than she feels
today.''
</P>
<P>
   He progressed to the 1960s, describing himself as an early
champion of civil rights. He was seeking to establish his
credentials as a champion of minorities because of concerns among
some black delegates that he did not adequately support affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early 1960s, when I was a college student,'' he said,
``I walked with Martin Luther King in the March on Washington for
jobs and freedom. That was my honor. That was my opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   As attorney general of Connecticut, he said, ``I worked to be
the people's lawyer. I went after polluters who were spoiling our
water and our air.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he spoke of Hadassah, his wife, whose family, he said, was
``literally saved by the greatest generation of American G.I.'s who
liberated the concentration camps.''
</P>
<P>
   While his delivery was earnest yet unadorned, it drew
enthusiastic applause from the delegates. And his effort to
reassure African Americans _ he was proceeded on stage by Rep. John
Lewis of Georgia, a civil rights hero _ seemed to meet with some
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked about his civil rights record,'' said Virginia
Rollins, a black delegate from Virginia. ``If anyone had doubts
about where he stood, he took care of that tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond telling his story, Lieberman drew contrasts between his
party and the Republicans. And he skipped over the fact that he is
viewed as hewing to more moderate positions on a range of issues
than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a shot at the Republicans who gathered in Philadelphia
two weeks ago, Lieberman said, ``Our Republican friends tried to
walk and talk a lot like us. But let's be honest. We may be near
Hollywood. But not since Tom Hanks won an Oscar has there been that
much acting in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who had not been widely viewed by most Democrats as a
likely choice for Gore still seemed a bit fazed by his newfound
celebrity and, perhaps, that Gore dared to pick a Jew. As he put it
in his opening line, ``Is America a great country or what?''
</P>
<P>
   Before the program opened, Gore arrived here triumphantly,
stepping off Air Force Two for a rally at the Burbank airport with
Lieberman and their families. Only a day after President Clinton
embraced Gore in Monroe, Mich., as the inheritor of his political
legacy, the vice president moved to strike out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``In every generation, we have to make the hard choices between
one direction or another, between going back to the past or forward
to the future,'' Gore declared. ``Let others argue the case for the
old guard. We're the new guard, and we're going to bring positive
change to the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if manufactured, the suspense on Wednesday was inside the
Staples Center. While Gore claimed enough delegates to put him over
the top five months ago, this remained a night of triumph _ and, at
long last, emergence _ for him. He represented Tennessee in the
House for nine years and the Senate for eight years, but has been
best known for his eight years of service to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While his speech was not devoted to critiquing the opposition,
as was Cheney's, Lieberman did scold Republicans for putting forth
what he portrayed as a misleading festival of inclusion at its
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that the GOP has changed their rhetoric,'' he said,
``but I wish they would also change their policies. As my friend
John McCain might say, let me do a little straight talking'' about
their record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing that our opponent talks about education,''
Lieberman said. ``Schools need to be held to the highest standards
of performance and accountability. But I'm sad to say their plan
just doesn't provide the resources our schools need to meet those
high standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gore's often grueling primary race against Bill Bradley
and his high-profile assignments from Clinton, like running a
program to streamline the federal government, the vice president
remains a bit of a mystery to the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   It has become almost a cliche for people to describe Gore as
remote and hard to warm to. But Schiff, one of Gore's closest
political advisers, sought to alter that perception by describing a
sweet and conscientious Al Gore that the public does not know.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my dad was a Congressman, he listed our number in the
phone book in Carthage so the people he worked for could always
reach him,'' Schiff said, seconding Gore's nomination. ``During my
summers on the farm, I would answer the phone, and it would often
be a constituent who needed help getting his veterans' benefits, or
finding the right health care. I was taught to run _ not walk _ to
get my dad so that people wouldn't be kept waiting for a moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's name was put in nomination by Tommy Lee Jones, the actor
who was one of his roommates at Harvard. Jones also tried to warm
up Gore's image by attesting to the Gores' relationship, ``To this
day,'' he said, ``when they come to our house, they sit in each
other's laps. They hold hands. They even smooch occasionally _ like
the kids they have always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rubin, a Treasury secretary under Clinton, saluted Gore
for his help in ensuring a vibrant economy. ``I worked with Al Gore
for six and a half years,'' he said. ``And he was a powerful and
effective force in all of the major economic policy decisions that
contributed so critically to this record. I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, at least, Lieberman brought the Democrats a
wave of favorable publicity in the days leading to the convention.
By turning to Lieberman, the first Democratic senator to
aggressively repudiate Clinton for his affair with a White House
intern, Gore underscored his determination to shed the shadow of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in the convention hall on Wednesday, dozens of
delegates, one after another, said they had not known much about
Lieberman until last week. But many said they were impressed, even
thrilled, as they learned more about him.
</P>
<P>
   Eufaula Frazier, a delegate from Florida who is black, said she
could relate to the historic nature of the Lieberman selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty years ago I was a beautician and we were all in the shop
watching the TV, so excited we were about Kennedy being
nominated,'' she said. ``The supply man came in and said it was
incredible, a Catholic in such a position. He said maybe one day it
will be a Jew. It is coming true tonight, and I get to be a part of
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
