<HEADLINE>
BOEING TO ANNOUNCE EMPLOYMENT SHIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. will announce an emerging plan tomorrow
to close some Puget Sound area operations and retrain and transfer
hundreds of workers within the region but not cut jobs, a source
familiar with the plan said last night.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Boeing would close a 300-worker small-parts
assembly facility on Harbor Pointe Boulevard near the company's
huge Everett, Wash. manufacturing plant and shut down its
300-employee machine shop in Kent, Wash. Workers in both plants
would be moved to new jobs in the area, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
   While no employees are expected to lose their jobs under the
plan, other more dramatic steps are possible in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In the plan, which a company spokesman warned still might
change, Boeing would name its plant in Wichita,Kan. a ``center of
excellence'' for tooling, a move that would preserve 2,000 tooling
support jobs in the Seattle area and require the retraining of an
additional 350 tooling workers in the region, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to comment,'' John Kvasnosky, Boeing
spokesman, said last night. ``These things change literally up to
the last minute. When we are ready, we are going to communicate to
our employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials in Wichita told a reporter there last night they
expected to be briefed today. The union officials said they did not
know about the plan last night.
</P>
<P>
   The plan arrives after months of rumors that the world's leading
airplane manufacturer was preparing to close a major facility in
the Puget Sound area. For example, one rumor suggested the company
would sell its Auburn, Wash., parts facility.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has been reviewing its operations with an eye toward
boosting efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The plan isn't as dramatic as some workers feared. However, the
International Association of Machinists is concerned about the idea
of moving and retraining union workers, according to Bill Johnson,
president of the International Association of Machinists District
Lodge 751.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have been sitting on the edge of their
seats,'' Johnson said. ``We are going to continue to fight for each
and every job in the company.''
</P>
<P>
   They could have a future fight. Peter Jacobs, an analyst at the
Seattle-based investment firm of Ragen MacKenzie Inc., said the
plan represents a good first step in the Puget Sound area toward
greater efficiency, but the company could easily take other steps
in the region in the coming two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``These steps don't sound dramatic enough to represent the only
(moves) we should expect in the Puget Sound region,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These steps demonstrate Boeing is committed to making
incremental improvements in its operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two months ago, Boeing put a St. Louis manufacturing unit
on the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   The move was the latest and one of the strongest signs in recent
years that Boeing was serious about shedding underused plants and
assets as it strives to become a leader competitor in the aerospace
business.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed sale also left 1,665 Missouri-based employees in
limbo, although Boeing said any buyer would be expected to hire
most of the workers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few months, Boeing executives have stressed that
they must re-evaluate what the company sells. These statements and
the St. Louis sale, as well as steps to consolidate operations in
Boeing's Delta rocket program have fueled the fears of Boeing
workers in the Puget Sound region.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Boeing, and at other manufacturers nationwide are
examining operations because they believe it could be cheaper to
buy certain parts than produce them, Frederick Zimmerman, a
professor of manufacturing systems engineering at the University of
St. Thomas, said earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Academics have highlighted Ford Motor Co., PepsiCo Inc. and
Coca-Cola Co. as high-profile firms companies that which have shed
less- profitable enterprises. For example, Ford spun off its
parts-making arm, Visteon Corp., in June.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging Boeing plan comes after the Machinists the largest
union at Boeing, launched a public and private lobbying campaign
designed to press Boeing to discuss their plans and keep jobs in
the Seattle area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
