<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIG-CLONE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PIG CLONING BRINGS PAYOFF, BUT RAISES CONCERNS  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pigs have been cloned for the first time using methods that may
lead to an important new source of human-like organs for
transplant, scientists said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The birth announcement of genetically identical piglets came
from two independent research teams, each using different
techniques refined from past cloning experiments in sheep, cattle,
mice and goats.
</P>
<P>
   But the announcements were tempered by another scientific report
highlighting the risks of ``xenotransplantation.'' The report
warned that hidden diseases may be transferred from pigs to people
along with life-saving organs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some potential risks here,'' said Dr. Daniel Salomon
of the Scripps Research Institute in La Jolla, senior author of the
report.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the significance of the research, Salomon's study
and one of the other cloning-experiment reports were released by
the British journal Nature Wednesday in advance of regular print
publication.
</P>
<P>
   The second report on cloning research was originally slated to
appear Friday in Science, but editors of that journal also agreed
to release the report early so that all three studies would come
out at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Authors of the Nature cloning study include scientists
affiliated with the Scotland-based company PPL Therapeutics, which
was formed to commercialize the technology that gave birth to
Dolly, the famous cloned sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Advance word about Salomon's study led to speculation in the
financial markets earlier this week that PPL and researchers
affiliated with Geron Corp. of Menlo Park, Calif., were backing
away from xenotransplantation research. PPL issued a statement
Wednesday that ``reaffirmed'' its commitment to the field, although
the company said it will be at least four years before clinical
trials can commence.
</P>
<P>
   Geron, meanwhile, said it is ``refocusing'' its investments in
cloning-related research but denied it was backing off due to
medical risks.
</P>
<P>
   Safety concerns already have led U.S. regulators to impose tight
restrictions on xenotransplant experiments, while some experts are
advocating a blanket moratorium on clinical trials. Research also
has been complicated by ethical considerations involving the use of
animals as organ donors.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts insisted that while such concerns must be taken
seriously, cloning offers one of the few practical solutions to the
critical problem of organ shortages.
</P>
<P>
   About 72,000 people are awaiting organ transplants of various
kinds, including nearly 16,000 awaiting livers and 46,000 in need
of kidneys. Only a small fraction of those on the waiting lists
find a donor match.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of cloning, combined with genetic engineering
techniques, suggests that ordinary barnyard animals might someday
be transformed into walking organ factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the moon shot of liver transplantation,'' said Alan
Brownstein, president of the American Liver Foundation. ``The need
is staggering, and pursuing this type of research is critically
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Pigs are considered an ideal species because they can be grown
quickly to roughly human size and are relatively free of pathogens
capable of causing disease in humans.
</P>
<P>
   However, pig reproductive biology presented some daunted
technical problems for cloning pioneers. Only a single success in
pig-cloning experiments had been reported until Wednesday,
involving laborious methods considered impractically difficult to
duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the results reported Wednesday, no one suggested it
will be easy to make pig cloning anything more than a laboratory
novelty any time soon. Dr. Ryutaro Hirose, a transplant surgeon at
the University of California at San Francisco, said the cloning
experiments amounted to ``a small step forward'' in light of other
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Most pressing, he said, is the need to find ways of manipulating
the pig's genetic machinery in a much more subtle fashion than can
be done now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can introduce new genes into a pig, but we can't yet knock
out specific genes,'' he said. ``Pigs make all kinds of proteins
that essentially are pig versions of our own proteins. The trouble
is those are not the kind of proteins you really want in your
body.''
</P>
<P>
   In the cautionary Nature study, Salomon, the Scripps researcher,
and his colleagues showed for the first time that an infectious
agent called porcine endogenous retrovirus, or PERV, can infect
mice genetically engineered with a condition similar to
immune-suppressed human transplant patients.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was found to move around in the mouse bloodstream and
infect other organs as well beyond the transplant site. However,
the infection induced in the mice did not lead to any disease
symptoms, and the same could be true in humans, Salomon said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the research may help speed progress in the
xenotransplant field by giving scientists a way to study
cross-species infections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's every reason to believe the mouse is a good model,''
he noted. ``We need to keep the field moving forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
