 BEYOND THE ISLAND, A LINE IS DRAWN  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's not often I get to break a major news
story, but here it is:
</P>
<P>
   Alameda is creeping into San Francisco. Could be devastating to
property values.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Weixel says he was listening to radio KFOG and the morning
crew asked a listener this question: What is the eastern-most point
of land in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The person answered ``Treasure Island.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Correct!'' said the radio guys.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. Weixel says he has heard that a tiny corner of
the Old Alameda Air Station creeps over the S.F.-Alameda boundary
line that runs north-to-south through the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   I checked with the San Francisco office of Thomas Bros., the map
people. They put Michael Delano _ ``our map expert'' _ on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Delano says a tip of the air station, ``ever so
tiny, maybe two square blocks,'' spills over into San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   So in Alameda, there is a here there.
</P>
<P>
   THANK YOU, Rat Boys:
</P>
<P>
   Those laboratory scientists who continually find new ways that
good things are bad for you (``Cancer linked to breathing'') have
found a new way that a good thing is good for you.
</P>
<P>
   For un-young guys, the researchers found, sleeping more helps
reduce love handles and double chins.
</P>
<P>
   Deep sleep produces growth hormones that in a lot of ways make
you younger and more athletic.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, gym; hello, hammock.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can develop rock-hard abs to go with your rock-hard
arteries.
</P>
<P>
   But they say you may need help to achieve that deeper sleep.
Maybe a six-pack of beer? I'm starting my deep-sleep program
tonight by watching Al Gore's acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDLY SKIES keep their distance:
</P>
<P>
   Steve Cannata is in L.A. and says that if you spend time
wondering about the intangible qualities that make United Airlines
the company it is, you might ponder the sign he saw on the door of
the United ticket office at 6th and Grand, about a half mile from
the big convention:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are enthusiastic supporters of the Democratic National
Convention and wish to do everything we can to help L.A. serve as a
good host. This office will be closed Monday, Aug. 14 through
Thursday, Aug. 17.''
</P>
<P>
   TIGER WOODS tees off Thursday in the PGA Championship, and you
have to wonder if the kid is over the hill. At last week's Buick
Open, Tiger won a measly $57,240.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Bristol wonders, ``Does Tiger's bank assess him a surcharge
when he makes a deposit that small?''
</P>
<P>
   What deposit? Tiger probably used that check to floss his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   CONCRETE GOD: The folks at Cody's bookstore in Berkeley were
worried that nobody would show for Tony Hawk's book-signing
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hawk is the king of skateboarding, in town for the X Games, but
the signing had been rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Word got out. Kids were lined up around the block, and superstar
Tony couldn't have been cooler, signing boards and books (``Hawk _
Occupation: Skateboarder'') and posing for pics.
</P>
<P>
   Some guys get all the luck. With a name like Tony Hawk, what
could he have been but a skateboard god? If you're a Tony Hawk, you
don't drive a bread truck.
</P>
<P>
   THEY'RE N0. 1: The broad-brushers will tell you that Palo Alto
is all wine-sipping dot-commers with golden retrievers that drive
Porsches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to point out,'' points out Bill Bucy, ``that
Rudy's Pub on University St. in downtown P.A. is No. 1 in Santa
Clara County in smoking citations.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucy also notes that the Rudy's attitude is well-expressed in
its newspaper ads: ``Buy 10 beers ... get 10 beers.''
</P>
<P>
   FRONTIER JUSTICE: The Police Log of the Half Moon Bay Review
(thanks, Dick Alexander) reports that a young man was 86'd from the
Half Moon Bay Inn for intoxication, after punching a bartender.
</P>
<P>
   ``When police attempted to contact the man, he ran and was
sprayed by a skunk.''
</P>
<P>
   CARMEL DRAGGED into the 20th century:
</P>
<P>
   Carmel's postal folks, under pressure from a group of citizens,
has agreed to deliver mail.
</P>
<P>
   This is in Carmel-by-the-Sea, the city's charming inner city.
</P>
<P>
   The way it has always worked is that Carmel-by-Sea homes have no
addresses and no mail delivery. You pick up your mail at the post
office.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of addresses, many homes have names, like ``My Reward,''
``Living Right'' and ``Xanadu.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, if the City Council approves, you will have the option of
home-delivery or the old pick-up system.
</P>
<P>
   This means war. The anti-delivery forces could ramrod (that word
is illegal in Carmel, by the way) into law a prohibition on any
kind of box being placed in front of a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That probably will happen,'' says Daryl Glen. ``At Carmel
construction sites, people cover their porta-potties with tasteful
wooden lattices.''
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if the porta-potties have names? ``Think Tank.''
``Xanadoo.'' ``My Reward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
