<HEADER>
A4283 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-COLLEGE-GRANTS-SFCHRO     08-17 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-GRANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEEDIEST GET GUARANTEE OF COLLEGE FUNDS  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Under a landmark deal cut by lawmakers and Gov.
Gray Davis, the state is committing at least $1.2 billion in grant
money to guarantee that low-income high school graduates can go to
college.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next year, the state's neediest students who meet grade
requirements have the right to receive a grant from the state for
community colleges, campuses in the California State University and
University of California systems or private four-year colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most significant increase in access to higher
education since the GI bill,'' said John Mockler, Davis' cabinet
secretary for education. ``There is no state in the country doing
anything comparable to this.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Davis described the agreement as
``historic.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a major modification of the so-called Cal Grant program. In
the past, an established amount of money was set aside for grants,
and when it ran out, otherwise eligible students got no aid.
</P>
<P>
   Now if a student meets the eligibility criteria, the state will
give him or her a grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can walk into any high school in this state and say to a
poor kid that just because you're poor doesn't mean you don't have
a chance. If they have the grades, they get money for college,''
Mockler said.
</P>
<P>
   The new program is expected to reach 30 percent of the students
attending California high schools. When Davis took office last
year, there was enough Cal Grant money to reach 17 percent of those
students.
</P>
<P>
   The grants are available to students whose families have no more
than $45,400 in assets. The income ceiling varies, based on the
size of students' families.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a student with five family members and an income of
$68,700 would qualify. As family size drops, so does the income
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Students earning up to $23,500 on their own are also eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Students fitting income and asset requirements who earn a 3.0
grade point average or better would be eligible for grants that
range from a maximum of $1,428 for CSU, $3,249 for UC and $9,703
for a private university such as Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Students earning a 2.0 average would get a grant of up to
$1,551, which they could use to pay for textbooks and other
incidental costs at community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Part-time students enrolled at least half-time _ six credit
units a semester _ would also qualify for grants.
</P>
<P>
   Students have within a year of high school graduation to apply.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is students who complete community college within
five years of high school graduation and who have the grades to
move on to four-year colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was championed in the Legislature by Senate President
Pro Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will make a real difference in a lot of lives,'' Burton
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also embraced the idea, even though they rarely
support entitlement programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What distinguishes this from other entitlements is that the
receipt of the benefit is based on merit, and it requires the
recipient to fulfill their potential,'' said Sen. Chuck Poochigian,
R-Fresno. ``It's not a crutch or a giveaway.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans backed the plan for more personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about hope. My parents were dirt poor. They used to
tell me growing up how they wanted to go to college but didn't have
the money,'' said Assemblyman Rod Pacheco, R-Riverside. ``That's
not going to happen anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governor initially opposed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   He backed a $71 million increase in money for the Cal Grant
program in his budget proposal _ which did not include the
educational guarantee _ far less than lawmakers had proposed.
</P>
<P>
   To win Davis' support, Burton linked the Cal Grant to another
Davis-backed bill giving $1,000 merit scholarships to students who
score in the top 10 percent of their school on aptitude tests or in
the top 5 percent statewide.
</P>
<P>
   If Davis had vetoed one of the bills, the other would have died
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Burton also told Davis that because of unanimous GOP support,
the governor might risk an override if he vetoed the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Burton and Davis negotiated during the past month and finally
reached an agreement earlier this week that narrows the scope _ and
cost _ of the program, but maintains the guarantee of an education
to needy students.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, a new category of grants also is created.
</P>
<P>
   Burton calls them ``redemption'' grants. They are intended for
students who did not go to college within a year of high school
graduation but later enrolled in community college and those who
have been working and want now to attend college.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
