r a BC-DEMOCRATIC-CONVENTION     08-17 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATIC-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LIEBERMAN EXHORTS AMERICANS TO `OVERCOME DIFFERENCES'  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marveling that ``only in America'' could a Jewish
baker's son aspire to help lead his nation, an awed Joseph
Lieberman called on Americans Wednesday night ``to overcome the
differences that are still between us ... and to help every
American claim the possibilities of their own God-given lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As every faith teaches us ... we must, as Americans, try to
see our nation, not just through our eyes, but through the eyes of
others,'' said Lieberman, accepting his party's vice presidential
nomination before a panorama of cheering delegates in the Staples
Center last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my eyes, I've seen the goodness of this great country
through many sets of eyes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the third night of the Democratic National Convention,
delegates formally selected their presidential ticket, Al Gore and
Lieberman. Gore made an unexpected visit to the hall, delivering an
exuberant bear hug to his daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, after she
formally nominated her father for president.
</P>
<P>
   But the evening's spotlight clearly belonged to Lieberman, the
first Jewish candidate on a presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty years ago we came to this city and crossed a new
frontier,'' said the Connecticut senator, in a reference to the
nomination of John F. Kennedy in Los Angeles the last time
Democrats met here. ``I believe the next frontier isn't just in
front of us, but inside of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman entered the hall to a deafening ovation and set the
tone with his opening line: ``Is America a great country, or
what?''`
</P>
<P>
   The remarks were a clear departure from those of his GOP
counterpart, Dick Cheney, who acted as a partisan attack dog for
his party two weeks ago in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Lieberman opted for an often reverent,
conciliatory, and sometimes humorous tone aimed at outlining the
divide between Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Calling his GOP opponents ``decent and likable men,'' Lieberman
said there are ``very real differences'' between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be near Hollywood tonight, but not since Tom Hanks won
an Oscar has there been that much acting in Philadelphia,'' he
said, as the hall erupted in cheers.
</P>
<P>
   He chided the GOP for what he said were failures in policies
affecting education, health care, environment and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore and I are the only candidates in this race who will
extend health care coverage to every single child in America,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their idea of school modernization means buying a new calender
for every school building,'' he said. ``We are committed to making
America's public schools the very best in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the more emotional moments of his speech, Lieberman
talked of his family's immigrant roots and his own opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will we dream for our country ... and how will we make it
come true?,'' he asked. ``It's not just the size of our national
feast that's important ... but the number of people we can fit
around the table. There must be room for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for barriers to be torn down ``on race, and gender and
sexual orientation,'' saying, ``In America, every time a barrier is
broken, the doors of open opportunity grow wider for every single
one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``when it comes to affirmative action, mend it, but please
don't end it,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman reached out to undecided and independent voters who
are crucial to his ticket's election. ``For those of you at home
who haven't made up your mind how you're going to vote in this
election, if you want to build on prosperity, if you want progress,
not partisanship in Washington, if you want to reform the system
and not retreat from the problems, then ... your choice is clear:
Al Gore and I are the guys who are ready to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   And addressing his own political differences with Gore,
Lieberman said, ``We have discussed, often debated, policy issues
... and we've often shared private moments of prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates appeared transfixed as Lieberman humbly thanked the
country for his latest opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I try to see this world as my dad saw it from his
bakery truck,'' he said. ``I know that somewhere in America right
now, there is another father loading a bakery truck, or a young
woman programming a computer, or a parent dreaming of a better
future for their daughter or their son.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep the faith, then 40 years from now one of their
children will stand before a gathering like this, with a chance to
serve and lead this country that we love,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's acceptance address came on a day Gore made a
triumphant entry into Los Angeles, met by hundreds of roaring
supporters as Air Force Two touched down at Burbank Airport. Gore
was greeted by Gov. Gray Davis, Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan
and Lieberman as he concluded a campaign trek across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic vice president gave a hint of themes for his own
acceptance speech tonight, saying he would talk about ``specific,
hard choices that I believe we have to make in order to ensure that
we have a bright future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said teacher pay, minimum wage, health care, hate crimes,
gun control and the environment would be part of the issue-packed
address.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future starts in California, the victory starts in
California,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, too, roused the supporters with his own cheer, a
takeoff on a popular GOP chant: ``Let's win this one for the
Tipper!''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was nominated by his former Harvard roommate, actor Tommy
Lee Jones, and Gore's daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   Poised and personal, Schiff tried to give Americans a more
intimate side of her father, saying, ``I would be supporting my dad
for President even if he hadn't raised, fed, clothed, taught and
loved me _ and even if he hadn't accepted more late-night collect
calls from me that I'd ever like to admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asking you to support Al Gore because he is my father,
or even because he's been a great dad for his kids,'' she said.
``What really matters is what he will do for all our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's wife, Hadassah, entered the hall to a huge ovation
and thousands of blue and white ``Hadassah'' signs. And in an
emotional speech, she introduced Americans to the man she
affectionately called ``my Joey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For Joe, family, faith, neighborhood, congregation and
community are the guideposts of his life,'' she said. ``It reminds
him of the republic he serves: one nation, under God, indivisible,
with liberty and justice for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Al Gore chose my husband as a running mate, this country
got a man whose mission in life is inspired by the people he
serves,'' she said to cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman himself engaged in a busy day of campaigning
Wednesday, appearing before delegations of Hispanic, Asian-Pacific
and gay and lesbian Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And he confirmed in an interview with the Associated Press that
_ as the race moves into its crucial post-Labor Day period _ he
will withdraw from the campaign for several days in the coming
weeks for religious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   It is a period in which Jews observe some of the holiest days of
their religious year, which include Rosh Hashanah, the Jewish New
Year that falls on September 30, and Yom Kippur, the day of
atonement, which this year is Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to do what I've always done and work extra hard
on the days that I'm campaigning,'' Lieberman said. ``Al Gore is a
man of faith, and he respects my faith and my observance and he's
been very clear that he doesn't want me to vary from my traditional
practices and I won't,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
