<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r p BC-DNC-GORE-2TAKES-LADN     08-17 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-GORE-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ARRIVES WITH CALL FOR `THE BEST AMERICA'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif _ On the eve of the most important speech in his
political career, Vice President Al Gore arrived in town Wednesday
to a cheering hero's welcome, greeted by hundreds of party faithful
who are counting on him to keep the White House in Democratic hands
for four more years.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring the Democratic ticket ``the new guard,'' Gore spoke
briefly at Burbank Airport, where he was joined by his running
mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, and local dignitaries including Gov.
Gray Davis and Mayor Richard Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's time for all of us to come together and lift up
the ideal of the best America that we can move toward,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every generation, we have to make the hard choices between
one direction or another, between going back to the past or forward
to the future. Let others argue the case for the old guard. We're
the new guard, and we're going to bring positive change to the
United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Perspiring profusely as he spoke inside a hot airport hangar on
another sizzling day, Gore relished the reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with the Liebermans, we are looking forward to being
here in Los Angeles. The future starts in California,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Gore steps into the limelight as he accepts
the presidential nomination at the Democratic National Convention.
The speech, which he has been thinking about for the past three
months, is particularly critical because he is behind in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast with the Republicans, he said, his speech would
contain specific policy details. He gave a taste to the airport
crowd, setting out his agenda in sound bite-size declarations.
</P>
<P>
   Among his goals, he said, are raising the minimum wage; giving
doctors, rather than HMOs, more medical decision-making authority;
giving senior citizens a prescription drug benefit under Medicare;
passing a hate crimes law; getting guns out of the hands of
children and criminals; and cleaning up the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who have dubbed this week's events the Gore
``reinvention convention,'' scoffed at Gore's speech. They said his
liberal policies are a shift from the more conservative positions
he held as a senator, designed to win votes rather than express his
true beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has had more upgrades than Microsoft Windows,'' said
Terry Holt, spokesman for Victory 2000, a Republican National
Committee campaign organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``After eight years in office, he has left the American people
confused about him, whether he has convictions, what his positions
on issues are. And over the last couple of weeks, the picture of Al
Gore has become even more complicated. He walks a razor edge
between holding on to the charm of Bill Clinton even while he knows
he needs to separate himself from Bill Clinton's liabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   As for declaring himself the ``new guard,'' Holt said, ``His
opening a new chapter begs the question: What were you doing in the
last chapter? According to Bill Clinton, he's the most influential
vice president in history. Where have you been for the last eight
years, Mr. Gore?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore arrived with his wife, Tipper, and daughters, Karenna Gore
Schiff and Kristin. As he got off the plane, he embraced a line of
local officials who included Davis, Riordan, actor Sean Penn, Los
Angeles County Supervisor Yvonne Brathwaite Burke; state Sens.
Richard Alarcon and Jack O'Connell; and Los Angeles Councilmen
Michael Feuer and Alex Padilla.
</P>
<P>
   As he strode up to the podium, the South Gate Middle School
mariachi band struck up a Mexican folk tune called ``Relampago'' or
``lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Gore worked the crowd for a half-hour, shaking
hundreds of hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go, Hey, can I get a high-five? and he said `Yeah,' and we
just smacked hands,'' said a smiling Tina Jasiukonis, a preschool
director from Sherman Oaks. ``I thought it was great. I'm in the
best mood right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Her uncle, Romas Jasiukonis, similarly got a chance to shake the
veep's hand, but he later revealed a secret.
</P>
<P>
   Leaning close to a reporter, he confessed in a low voice, ``I'm
a Republican. She dragged me in here.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he plans to vote for Bush, to which his niece replied:
``You just think you are. I'm gonna take you around on voting day,
too. Come on _ today was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was,'' he agreed. ``It was.''
</P>
<P>
   After the rally, Gore, Lieberman and their families traveled by
motorcade down the street to Warner Bros. Studios, where they were
greeted by their home state delegations from Tennessee and
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Hart's band played at the party, as actor Martin Sheen
and other cast members of NBC's ``The West Wing,'' which is
produced on that lot, signed autographs for delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, normally a critic of Hollywood, referred to the show
when speaking of the Republican nominee: ``The closest George Bush
will get to the West Wing is a remote control!''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman had been scheduled to speak later that afternoon at a
panel discussion at the Los Angeles Central Library on the issue of
media violence and its impact on children, but he backed out in
order to work on the convention speech he delivered Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was a Republican, former Education Secretary
William Bennett, who spoke on his behalf to rail against what
Lieberman has in the past called the ``revolt of the revolted'' _
or those upset by increasingly violent and obscene content in the
entertainment media.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Lieberman met with a series of minority
caucus groups _ Latinos, Asians, gays and lesbians _ to convince
them he is on their side, despite his reputation as a centrist
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   To the gay and lesbian group, the senator said he supports
hate-crimes legislation. He received a standing ovation when he
said he opposed the Clinton's administration's ``don't ask, don't
tell'' gays in the military policy.
</P>
<P>
   And he told the Latino delegates that, as opposed to the
Republicans, ``we're not faking anything'' when it comes to the
party's racial and ethnic diversity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
