<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4295 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LASER-COVERUP-SFCHRON     08-17 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASER-COVERUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CONGRESS MISLED ABOUT COST OF SUPERLASER, REPORT SAYS  &HT;     By BERNADETTE TANSEY 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Officials in charge of a superlaser under
construction at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory misled
Congress in 1995 by intentionally lowballing the project budget to
win initial funding, investigators said in a report to be released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Energy and lab officials then knowingly downplayed
the National Ignition Facility's mounting technical problems and
altered an outside contractor's evaluation to give the project
glowing reviews last year, the General Accounting Office report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Energy Department and lab officials vigorously denied
wrongdoing in representing the superlaser's costs _ now set at
nearly $4 billion _ to Congress. A Lawrence Livermore Lab watchdog
group, meanwhile, called on Congress to start a criminal
investigation of what it called ``a clear pattern of deceit, fraud
and abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be clear evidence of a coverup, of knowingly
lying to Congress,'' said Marylia Kelley of Tri-Valley CARES.
</P>
<P>
   Madelyn Creedon, Energy Department deputy administrator for
defense programs, said the agency made a straightforward case for
the project in 1995 based on its merits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was anything nefarious about the (Energy)
Department's original presentation,'' Creedon said.
</P>
<P>
   The report raises doubts about the value of the experimental
superlaser project to the Energy Department's nuclear weapons
program as Congress decides whether to continue or reduce the
project's funding.
</P>
<P>
   Costs for the stadium-size laser now stand at more than $3.9
billion, according to the report's estimates, which include funds
for related research and programs that investigators believe should
be counted as part of the ignition facility's budget.
</P>
<P>
   That estimate is more than $600 million higher than the Energy
Department's latest projection of $3.3 billion, which excludes
costs that the department insists do not belong on NIF's balance
sheet.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how the numbers are added, federal investigators say,
the price could rise again by an unknown amount because substantial
technical problems still have not been solved. The final report,
submitted at the request of two congressional committees
investigating the superlaser's cost overruns and project delays,
will be made public Thursday by the House Science Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The superlaser, designed to test the reliability of nuclear
weapons through experiments rather than bomb blasts, was originally
scheduled to begin operating in 2002. But those deadlines kept
slipping as technical snags came to light. The project, if funded
as the Energy Department requests, will not reach full power until
2010.
</P>
<P>
   The full extent of the project's troubles began to surface
publicly in the fall of 1999, when Energy Secretary Bill Richardson
accused Lawrence Livermore of belatedly informing him that the
laser project was behind schedule and as much as $350 million over
budget.
</P>
<P>
   But the General Accounting Office report says that both lab
managers and high-level officials at Energy Department headquarters
covered up the project's true costs beginning with an initial
budget request of $1.2 billion in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Based on interviews with the Energy Department and lab
personnel, investigators said officials admitted that they
``accepted this unrealistic budget in the belief that Congress
would not fund the (ignition facility) at a higher cost and that
the value of the (facility)  &LR; to the future of the laboratory
overshadowed potential cost concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Creedon said, ``I don't buy that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the Energy Department has always reported the known
expenditures of the ignition facility, though some costs were
considered part of the larger Inertial Confinement Fusion program,
which tries to use experiments instead of underground bomb tests to
test the condition of the nation's nuclear stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the apparent multimillion dollar cost increases
reflected in the report come down to differences in accounting
methods that attribute larger program costs to the ignition
facility, Creedon said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Wells, the General Accounting Office's director of
Energy, Resources and Science Issues, said Congress should be given
all related costs as it decides whether to continue funding for the
ignition facility.
</P>
<P>
   The burgeoning costs of the superlaser are likely to drain the
budgets of other elements of the nuclear stockpile program, the
Accounting Office reported. Officials at Los Alamos and Sandia
national laboratories, the Energy Department's other nuclear
weapons labs, have advocated cutting back the number of ignition
facility's laser beam lines from 192 to as few as 48 until the
budget impacts become clearer, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The Accounting Office recommended a freeze on shifts in funding
to the ignition facility from the other labs until an outside team
independent of the Energy Department has evaluated the program.
Reacting to the report, House Science Committee Chairman F. James
Sensenbrenner Jr. called the ignition facility's cost and schedule
overruns ``alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that (the Energy Department's) own independent
reviews masked the cost overruns is even more disturbing,'' said
the Wisconsin Republican. ``(The Energy Department) and Lawrence
Livermore National Lab should have come clean about the engineering
difficulties and cost overruns for this project years ago. (Energy
Department) mismanagement has left the American taxpayers holding
the bag once again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner's fellow Republican Duncan Hunter, however, said
the report does nothing to change his opinion that the ignition
facility should be fully funded as an essential resource to
maintain the nation's nuclear deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, R-El Cajon, a member of the House Armed Services
Committee, said the Accounting Office has made no allegation that
Lawrence Livermore wasted any of the money spent on the superlaser,
even if officials underestimated the cost of the cutting-edge
scientific project.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Livermore lab spokeswoman Susan Houghton said lab
scientists have already established a track record of solving some
of the thorny technical challenges presented by the laser project.
They expect to overcome remaining obstacles in the development of
optical lenses for the superlaser.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
