what looks like a boost for stocks right now may not seem so
favorable by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Worries that Greenspan's Fed may have done its job too well _
that the economy might be slowing too much _ could derail the
fourth-quarter rally that many investors are banking on to rescue
their portfolios in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Once the market gets the proof it needs that the Fed has decided
to cease its anti-inflation campaign it, too, will probably begin
asking these questions.
</P>
<P>
   How quickly the collective attention of investors shifts from
the good news about the Fed to the bad news about a slowing economy
may be the single most important unknown facing equity investors in
the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   With this in mind, let's go back and review the underlying
economic news that first prompted the market rally.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, the Department of Commerce reported that spending on
construction projects had fallen by 0.6 percent in April. It was
the first decline in this important economic indicator since
September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The latest figure also represented a sharp change from the 0.8
percent gain Commerce had reported for the month of March.
Additionally, the April figure was well below the consensus
projection of Wall Street economists, who had anticipated a number
closer to zero.
</P>
