<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GORE SPEECH MUST TRANSLATE POLICY INTO PASSION  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Al Gore tells people he spent his youth
shoveling pig manure on his family's Tennessee farm, many laugh in
disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   A congressman at age 28, a senator at 36 and a presidential
candidate before he turned 40, the vice president is better known
today as a sober understudy whose idea of lightening up is to
change from blue pinstripes to earth tones.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, as he formally accepts his party's nomination
for the highest office in the land, Gore faces a challenge that
goes beyond stepping out from President Clinton's shadow. He must
somehow win over voters who can no more picture him in the No. 1
position than as a simple farmhand.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, still buzzing over Clinton's address to the
convention on Monday night, wait with nervous anticipation. They
know that while Clinton can pass the torch of party leadership to
his vice president, he cannot transfer his gift for political
charm.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's address, scheduled for 7 p.m. tonight, must find a way to
stir an electorate that tends to fall for oversized political
personalities like Gov. Jesse Ventura, Sen. John McCain and
President Clinton. He must rise above his stiff speaking style long
enough to explain why his policy positions are the right ones. And
he must convince the nation that a cerebral policy wonk who knows
more about biodiversity than baseball is the man they want for
their president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that those who watch and listen will feel afterward
that they have a clearer idea of exactly what I'm proposing to
do,'' Gore said as he arrived in this convention city. ``They'll
also know how the ideas and proposals I'm making are rooted in the
experiences that I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's task is very similar to that faced by then-Vice President
George Bush in 1988, who had an impressive resume that included
eight years of service to a very popular president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in what was regarded by many to be the finest speech of
his career, touched on his loyalty to President Reagan and then
detailed his vision for the nation's future and what sort of leader
it would take to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends,'' Bush declared to the GOP faithful in New
Orleans, ``I am that man!''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bush trailed Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis by
17 points in public opinion polls. He came back to win the
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of his effort to communicate to voters
who he is,'' said House minority leader Dick Gephardt, D-Missouri,
speaking about a man who has been in the public eye since his birth
made the front page of the Nashville Tennessean.
</P>
<P>
   ``As vice president, he is famous,'' Gore's daughter Karenna
Gore Schiff said. ``But he is not well-known.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has presented the public with a life of contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, he spent the school year living in a hotel suite on
Washington's Embassy Row and his summers on the family farm in
Carthage, Tenn. He opposed the war in Vietnam, but enlisted to
serve because he thought it would be wrong for someone else to go
in his place. He was a conservative Democrat in the House of
Representatives, voting against abortion and gun control. He
emerged as a more liberal, centrist member of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He is a faithful Christian and a devoted family man. Yet his
political ambition is so fierce he earned the nickname
``solicitor-in-chief'' for his aggressive efforts to raise money
for the party, which included questionable telephone solicitations
from the White House and an event at a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent his entire life in the public eye but still looks
uncomfortable before television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore begins a new chapter in his long political career,
strategists say he has a unique opportunity to shape his public
image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters are just beginning to pay attention,'' said Democratic
pollster Celinda Lake. ``This is his chance to powerfully introduce
himself to those voters.''
</P>
<P>
   One way for Gore to distinguish himself is to focus on issues.
With Not only do  &LR; polls showing that the public supports most of
his positions, but  &LR; this would allow him a chance to display his
mastery of policy.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kennedy Jr., whose family knows something about political
oratory, said the most important advice he could offer Gore is to
draw a policy distinction between himself and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic Party has to win this election on issues,''
said Kennedy, the third son of the man who was headed to the
Democratic Party's nomination in 1968 before his assassination only
a few miles from the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   So Gore will detail his plan for education, health care,
targeted tax cuts, Social Security and Medicare, his aides say. He
will leave no doubt that voters have a choice in November.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom is that Gore must somehow convince the
nation that he is likable. Not necessarily. The nation has a long
history of electing less than likable characters, most recently
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   His task is actually much broader. He has to convince the
country that he ought to be president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
