<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4301 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-FLORA-LEWIS-AUGUST17-     08-17 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORA-LEWIS-AUGUST17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DULL POLITICAL EXTRAVAGANZAS IN THE U.S.  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 825-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of the FLORA LEWIS column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Flora Lewis  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   PARIS _ The American political conventions have performed their
formal task of naming presidential and vice-presidential candidates
for November elections, and their informal function of rallying
party cadres and, the leaders hope, energizing potential voters.
Fine. These traditional duties still must be done, and be seen to
be done.
</P>
<P>
   But the conventions also served to show how much American
democracy is frittering its vigor, even as the familiar old
procedures are observed. A remark by the chairman of the Democratic
National Convention Committee, Terry McAuliffe, just before the
meetings in Los Angeles reflected the essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to peacefully coexist with the demonstrators,'' he
said as the plans were made for dealing with street confrontations.
``They have every right to be heard, and we have every right to be
heard.'' In a word, that means nowadays to be on television.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to do it. One is to provoke the cameras'
attention by being important, outrageous or entertaining, and
better, all three. The other is by paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money involved, to be spent to a very large extent
on TV, continues to rise with every campaign. It has reached levels
so absurd that the figures have somehow lost their shock value.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of 1999 to the middle of this year, the
Democrats elicited $118.6 million and the Republicans $137 million
in ``soft money'' contributions, the unlimited gifts which can be
accepted in addition to the straightforward ``hard money'' maximum
of $1,000 per person to candidates. It is clear that the totals
this time around will be well over a quarter of a billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance reform has been a recurrent issue for
generations and every time new restrictions are imposed on
donations, new ways are found to avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   The one effective way to take the politicians back from the
moneybags would be to reduce the need for spending-free TV time as
in practically all other democracies and strict limits or even an
outright ban on TV political advertising.
</P>
<P>
   A good European idea to get rid of the sneaky and misleading
attack ads that pollute American airwaves would require that the
candidate appear personally in the spots and that they last a
minimum of three minutes. That is a long time on TV; you have to
have something to say or reveal your emptiness.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Supreme Court, wrongly I think, has ruled that to
limit political advertising on the public airwaves would violate
freedom of speech. So the people who can't raise that kind of money
but still want to assert their right to be heard are learning to
use a kind of TV theatricality to get their share of camera time.
</P>
<P>
   After their surprise success at disruption at the World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle late last year, and their
undeniable presence at the World Bank meeting in Washington this
spring, demonstration organizers have become remarkably
professional at planning, training, and outfitting their troops for
maximum effect.
</P>
<P>
   They use a catch-all multiplying approach. One of their Web
sites listed some of the issues they were inviting protesters to
join them in opposing as ``corporate globalization, militarism,
poverty, starvation, campaign finance corruption, sexism, racism,
homo/transphobia, criminalization of youth, environmental
destruction, prison industrial complex, genocide.'' Why not traffic
jams and junk mail?
</P>
<P>
   It was nothing like the passionate demonstrations at the 1968
Democratic National Convention in Chicago, where opposition to the
Vietnam War had already driven President Lyndon Johnson to renounce
a bid for reelection. There were people of various background, but
with a real cohesion of opinion that merged their many voices into
a clear message.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a bit of bashing _ and after all, a good dollop of
bashing is supposed to be a TV specialty _ the demonstrations this
time seemed to be as much a part of the show as the balloons.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats weren't so carefully scripted and scheduled as the
Republicans, but they have both understood that TV focuses on
glitches so they must make sure that nothing disturbs the smooth
surface.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves it to the demonstrators, and the
``counter-convention,'' to provide some tumult and spontaneity to
keep viewers from dozing. But it is far from any political reality.
It only adds to the ordinary citizen's sense of having no part in
the procedure, indeed to not being really represented.
</P>
<P>
   The low turnout of voters in the United States, a country so
proud of its democracy that is always ready to lecture others on
how to go about it, has been a perplexing scandal for years.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the official launch of Campaign 2000 foreshadows an
improvement this November. On the contrary, there may be even a
further drop below 50 percent. But it doesn't seem so perplexing,
given the show. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist
for The New York Times. She is the author of five books, including
``Europe: Road To Unity'' and ``Europe: A Tapestry of Nations.''
Her articles have appeared in the International Herald Tribune, The
New York Times Magazine, The Atlantic, The Economist, France-Soir,
Life, The London Observer, The New Yorker and many other
periodicals. Last year she won the Overseas Press Club's Award for
Lifetime Achievement.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the FLORA
LEWIS column and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
