<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-MARLINS-CORRECTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES EXCELS DESPITE LACK OF REST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Fixes headline) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A guy walked up to Ismael Valdes in the Los Angeles
Dodgers clubhouse and told him he's starting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go. Bring it on,'' Valdes said.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? At least Valdes would have a day to rest, unlike
Wednesday when he was pressed into starting when Chan Ho Park
became ill.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, went out and pitched five strong innings and the
Dodgers, powered by a group who call themselves the ``scraps,''
salvaged the finale of their three-game series against the Florida
Marlins with a 10-4 win at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes had started Saturday in Atlanta and pitched a mop-up
ninth inning in Tuesday's loss to the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty awesome,'' Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw said. ``That's
exactly what you look for when a guy goes down. He took that ball
and stepped up. He might not have said that last year. He's matured
a little bit and he understands you're not always going to start,
you're not always going to relieve.''
</P>
<P>
   With a starting lineup that was missing Eric Karros, Mark
Grudzielanek and Adrian Beltre, the ``scraps'' brought energy to a
stale lineup. Eventually, the Dodgers broke it open with seven runs
in the eighth inning - more runs than they've scored in 21 of their
past 25 games - as Beltre came off the bench to deliver a three-run
homer.
</P>
<P>
   F.P. Santangelo had his second three-hit game of the season and
drove in a run and Dave Hansen tripled in two runs in the eighth
inning. Chad Kreuter, an honorary ``scrapper'' because he starts
much more frequently than Hansen, Santangelo or Jim Leyritz, added
two hits and drove in a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go out to have fun, bring some energy,'' Hansen said.
``It's nothing personal, but guys needed some time off. I think it
was a good win all around for camaraderie.''
</P>
<P>
   The win, indeed, was something the Dodgers, losers of eight of
10 entering the night, needed. They end their road trip 2-4, but
they remain 6 games behind San Francisco in the National League
West.
</P>
<P>
   And while it was the big eighth inning that catapulted the
Dodgers (61-58) past Florida, it was the five innings Valdes
provided that set the stage. He was called upon again when he
learned Park was sent back to Los Angeles with flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Claude Osteen approached Valdes about starting,
and for the second time since being reacquired from the Chicago
Cubs less than a month ago, Valdes started a day after pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Claude, `I'm ready if you need me, either starting or
relieving,' `' said Valdes, who left with a 3-1 lead but wasn't
involved in the decision. ``I'm here to help the ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   While Park flew back to Los Angeles earlier in the day to get
rest and possibly get ready for a start Saturday against the Mets,
provided he's healthy, Valdes took to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   He did a similar thing when he rejoined the Dodgers, facing two
batters in the first inning against Pittsburgh before rain
postponed the game. Valdes came back the next day and pitched four
solid innings, allowing two runs in a game the Dodgers went on to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awful tough to be out there, pitch an inning, and come
back and pitch the next day,'' said Dodgers manager Davey Johnson,
who added reliever Antonio Osuna wasn't available because of a sore
shoulder, putting a further burden on the bullpen. ``He impressed
me.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's something the Dodgers, clinging to playoff hopes,
need. In three weeks with the Dodgers, Valdes has done more to
shatter his reputation as not being tough enough and not putting
the team first than he did in his previous five seasons with the
team.
</P>
<P>
   The only run Valdes allowed came in the second inning when Kevin
Millar doubled with one out and scored on David Berg's two-out
single. But Valdes, who allowed seven hits, got out of possible
danger in the third inning with a double play and was aided in the
fifth when left fielder Gary Sheffield threw Ramon Castro out at
second trying to stretch a base hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not used to (consecutive days), the mental aspect
is probably the toughest,'' Osteen said. ``But he's been very
positive since getting here. I think his stuff is getting better
each time out. I thought he did an outstanding job. I thought he
got better as the game went on. He started throwing a lot better
curveball. It's been breaking but missing power lately, and it got
a lot better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
