<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-PROTESTS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. POLICE MOVE FAST TO BREAK RESISTANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO, DAVID GREENBERG, DONNA HUFFAKER, JASON KANDEL
and JORDAN SMITH 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles police moved swiftly and decisively
against a few bottle-throwing demonstrators Wednesday and quickly
dispersed what organizers billed as the biggest protest of the
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 activists flooded Olympic Boulevard and Figueroa
Street outside Staples Center in the late afternoon after a day of
angry but nonviolent protests targeting Los Angeles Police
Department tactics.
</P>
<P>
   They were met head-on by hundreds of officers in riot gear who
split the group in two, shoving their batons at challenging
protesters as bottles and sticks were hurled at them.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the front lines of the skirmishing, Chief Bernard C.
Parks directed the operation personally. Police broke up the crowd
with pepper spray and rubber bullets but backed off after talking
with organizers and watching dozens of protesters who had been at
the front of the confrontation walk away.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the phrase repeatedly used by LAPD officials all week,
Mayor Richard Riordan called the police response ``measured,
strategic, appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   He said officers had been disciplined and effective at
maintaining the peace throughout the week while respecting the free
speech rights of protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of what the LAPD has done,'' Riordan said.
``They've been calm. But when they've had to be tough ... they've
been appropriately aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Police made 38 arrests Wednesday, nearly all at a Rampart
Division protest at which demonstrators submitted voluntarily and
peacefully to officers to dramatize criticism over anti-gang
officers accused of framing hundreds of people in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   During the series of convention protests, police have made 192
arrests, 59 of those felonies. Most of the arrests included failure
to disperse. A group of 51 bicyclists was arrested Tuesday for
reckless driving.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, protesters took to downtown chanting, ``LAPD go
away _ racist, sexist, anti-gay,'' and, ``Two, four, six eight.
Smash the police state.'' Signs at the Pershing Square rally
included: ``LAPD: License to Attack Peaceful Demonstrators'' and
``Does this look like Berlin 1930s?''
</P>
<P>
   There were a few incidents where protesters threw bottles at
police. Police, citing intelligence reports, said the bottles were
filled with urine, gasoline or an acid, similar to incidents in
Philadelphia at the Republican convention. A California Highway
Patrol officer was taken to the hospital after being hit with a
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Police warned delegates and media that some protesters had
stolen, or tried to steal, convention passes off their necks.
</P>
<P>
   But other than the mass arrests at Rampart Division, the day
went with few arrests and incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at Staples Center in the afternoon, District Attorney
Gil Garcetti said the police response has been ``a tempered, proper
response, up to what I have seen right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are out there, they are keeping things in order,''
Garcetti said. ``For the most part, we have demonstrators and
protesters who are enjoying their First Amendment rights. And I
cheer them.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere protesters went, they were met with an overwhelming
police presence.
</P>
<P>
   Too overwhelming, according to City Councilwoman Jackie
Goldberg, who watched a protest outside Parker Center, where
hundreds of officers ringed the police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in protecting property and keeping the peace, but
this is ridiculous,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an exaggeration of police presence, and one that's
going to cost of millions of dollars in taxpayers' money. The
protesters are saying they want to change the world, and the police
are saying they won't let them because they're the ones that have
the guns.''
</P>
<P>
   The only serious confrontation of the day happened as protesters
tried to filter into the designated protest center outside Staples
Center. An overflow crowd on the street refused to move, according
to police. Officers moved in, and after about an hour discussing it
with protest leaders, police called it an ``unlawful assembly'' and
broke up the group.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Fithian, a D2KLA organizer who negotiated with officers at
the scene, said ``the cops completely instigated this.''
</P>
<P>
   Police, though, had turned back the hard-core protesters and
from there, much of the crowd dispersed, with several heading back
to Pershing Square. Two people were arrested in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're violating our rights,'' said 31-year-old Eric Magnuson
of Atwater Village. ``They stopped a peaceful protest. We have
permits to be here for another two hours. They broke up a legal
rally.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Goldberg of Direct Action Network, a protest group at the
convention, decried the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do not suspend the First Amendment rights of the masses
because of the actions of a small sum,'' she said. ``This is
continued harassment that started weeks ago. We will continue to be
in the streets, we will continue to be peaceful. If the LAPD needs
to deal with some then they should deal with some. It is not their
job to suspend the rights of the masses.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights attorney Osha Neumann of the Midnight Special Law
Collective said police made a big deal out of a small incidents
``and used them as excuses to violate First Amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawsuits have been filed and there will be more coming this
town is paying for the misconduct of the police,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Garcetti, who has tangled with the Parks and the LAPD over
the Rampart corruption scandal, called police action professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demonstrators and protesters are having their rights
protected by the police,'' Garcetti said. ``There is nothing going
on to tarnish (the image of L.A.). We should all stand tall.''
</P>
<P>
   Most businesses downtown were closed, but the protests did upset
the convention, said George Van Til, a delegate from Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, he and half the Indiana delegation were trying
to get to the convention for the roll call on Joe Lieberman's
nomination for vice president, but they were stuck inside the
Holiday Inn across the street from Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   He said it didn't look safe to go out, and after spending nearly
$2,000 on the trip, he was frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this? To stand here?'' he said. ``I was looking forward to
coming here, to being renewed in the Democratic spirit. It really
hasn't turned out to be that way. I want to be in there tonight and
I can't be.''
</P>
