<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-RAPIDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANNEY'S GOAL LIFTS GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ With the Los Angeles Galaxy's Western
Division title shot fading, Greg Vanney followed in a loose ball
with two minutes left in sudden death overtime, scoring from 18
yards to give the Galaxy a much-needed 1-0 victory over Colorado on
Wednesday before 5,187 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy played poorly to that point, except for Luis
Hernandez, who flew in from Mexico City earlier in the afternoon
after playing a World Cup qualifier the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez started the second half, creating two chances for
himself and another for Simon Elliott in the final 10 minutes of
regulation, but both couldn't find the net.
</P>
<P>
   Vanney, a defender who had been left off the U.S. national team
for Wednesday's game against Barbados, scored his sixth goal of the
season, but his first from the field after five penalty kick goals.
</P>
<P>
   The win enabled the Galaxy (12-7-8, 44 points) to stay within
striking distance of the division-leading Kansas City Wizards
(14-6-6, 48 points), a 3-0 winner over San Jose earlier in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just stood at the top of the box and there were two or three
shots deflected in front of me,'' said Vanney. ``It bounced out and
I knew the goalie had gone to the near post to make a save. I got a
good first touch and hit it home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good for us and a huge relief to get that win in
overtime because it was a hard-fought battle all night.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, the victory strengthens the Galaxy's hold on the
fourth playoff seed after Chicago (12-9-5, 41 points) lost earlier
to Dallas. The fourth seed earns home-field advantage in the first
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Regular starters Mauricio Cienfuegos (El Salvador), Ezra
Hendrickson (St. Vincent and the Grenadines) and Cobi Jones (U.S.)
were absent due to World Cup qualifying commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy midfielder Sasha Victorine had a rough night, missing two
good opportunities in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   On a breakaway in the ninth minute, Victorine could do nothing
against Colorado goalkeeper David Kramer, sending a weak shot
straight at the former Galaxy keeper, which Kramer knocked out of
bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Victorine had an easier opportunity in the 30th minute from
20-yards out with Kramer off his line, but his chip shot was far
left of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's Junior Agogo broke loose near the end of the first
half, but goalkeeper Matt Reis, who has filled in nicely for
injured starter Kevin Hartman, deflected his shot away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 0156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
