<P>
   &UR; DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEM-GORE-BIO-TRANSFORM (Undated) _ After Al Gore ran for
president in 1988 and lost, he organized a series of dinners where
he went around the room and asked each person to tell him where he
had gone wrong. It was excruciating, his friends said, but he
insisted on hearing the bad news. Gore responded, as he always has,
by going back to school. He put together a graduate seminar for
one, complete with a syllabus and a heavy-duty reading list, and
applied himself. Politicians often learn from and are even
transformed by a good drubbing at the polls, but few have pursued
their lessons as aggressively as Gore. By Melinda Henneberger and
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-ASSESS (Los Angeles) _ It was a new-model Joseph Lieberman,
hurriedly retooled to the specifications of a national campaign,
who took the stage here Wednesday night as the presumptive
Democratic vice presidential nominee. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-NETWORK-STRATEGY-NYT (Los Angeles) _ Of the many contrasts
that persist between the Democratic convention and the GOP
gathering, the party's network strategy is one of the biggest. As
far as the DNC is concerned, there really are only two important
moments here: Clinton's speech and Al Gore's. Everything else is
superfluous. By Peter Marks.
