<P>
   DEM-SCRIPTED-NYT _ The made-for-cuddly-TV conventions of 2000
don't merely shelve controversy, they abandon political traditions
that had a purpose, like using major speeches to show breadth of
support for the candidate. Instead we get Karenna, Tipper, Tommy
Lee Jones, Hadassah, rolling roll calls and other apolitical
innovations. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-DOCUMENTARY (Los Angeles) _ A political interlocutor learns
on the job: Philip Seymour Hoffman is acting as a kind of guerrilla
guide to the presidential campaign in ``Last Party 2000,'' a
documentary being directed by Donovan Leitch that has been shooting
on and off since March. By Rick Lyman. 1,400 words. (Will move in
``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SKYBOX (Los Angeles) _ If the role of the contemporary
political convention has undergone a radical transformation, so has
the role of the modern network skybox. Once little more than a
spartan cave from which the likes of Chet Huntley or Walter
Cronkite could look out over the convention floor, the booth has
become a statement unto itself. Even the most cursory look up from
the floor of the Staples Center provides a sense of how many
different statements a sky booth can make. By Peter Marks.
</P>
