</P>
<P>
   LAWYERS-PRO-BONO (Undated) _ Inundated by a hyperactive economy
that generates more business than they can often handle, many law
firms have cut back on pro bono work so sharply that they fall far
below professional guidelines for representing people who can not
afford to pay. The decline is troubling for many in the legal
profession, especially because the American Bar Association urges
lawyers to do at least of 50 hours of pro bono work each year, and
the roughly 50,000 lawyers at the nation's 100 highest-grossing
firms are averaging only 36 hours a year. By Greg Winter.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-OVERHAUL (Undated) _ With its stock price down, AT&AMP;T will
probably decide on a significant restructuring in September,
possibly including a leveraged buyout, led by John C. Malone, of
the company's consumer long-distance telephone business, people
close to AT&AMP;T said Wednesday. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
