<P>
   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DECORATOR-COSTS (Undated) _ Unlike other business relationships,
services a decorator renders to a client are often impossible to
pin down. There is no right way or wrong way to decorate a room.
Nor can a price tag be put on taste, or a so-called ``good eye.''
Add to the psychological imbalance the mind-boggling complexity and
ever-shifting methods by which designers seek reimbursement for
their often elusive, time-consuming services. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   PARISH-DESIGN (Dark Harbor, Maine) _ On ``Sister: the Life of
Legendary American Interior Decorator Mrs. Henry Parish II'' (St.
Martin's Press), by Apple Parish Bartlett and her daughter, Susan
Bartlett Crater. The book is a loving oral biography of Ms.
Bartlett's mother, who shaped the domestic aesthetic of various
Kennedys, Astors, Paleys and Whitneys, until her death in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TIBOR-DESIGN (New York) _ Since Tibor Kalman was a friend of
mine, I'm not able to write an objective review of ``Tiborocity:
Design and Undesign by Tibor Kalman'' the New Museum of
Contemporary Art's lively retrospective of the late graphic
designer's work. But I'd feel idiotic if I didn't write a personal
story before the show comes down this weekend. ``Tiborocity'' had
me shadowboxing with my friend over some of the issues we used to
argue about. What is sensibility? What was Visual Culture? How do
you maintain, or even measure integrity in the consumer society?
Those are a few of the issues we didn't exhaust in Tibor's
lifetime. Continuing the conversation is my way of remembering him.
By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
