<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOEMURRAY-COLUMN
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: It's still anybody's election
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gore-Lieberman? Heck of a ticket the Democrats have ended up
with.
</P>
<P>
   A Southerner from Tennessee needed a Jew from the Northeast to
bring moderation to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the political times we live in. Moderates are where you
find them, in places you never would have thought to look. That
goes for both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a Republican can be for zero income tax, zero inheritance
tax, reintroducing segregation and mandatory gun ownership ...
</P>
<P>
   But, if you are pro-choice, you are a moderate.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, you can be for a 100 percent estate tax, a
punishing progressive income tax, reintroducting busing and
abortion on demand whether you want one or not ...
</P>
<P>
   But, if you are pro-defense, you are a moderate.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that Sen. Joe Lieberman somehow comes across as Tail
Gunner Joe, having stood up and voted for the Gulf War when most
every other Democrat was running for cover.
</P>
<P>
   Good, too, that he was the first of his party to publicly
denounce President Clinton for immoral perpetration, if that's the
word.
</P>
<P>
   The code words, incidentally, in the Republican campaign are
``restore honor and dignity to the White House,'' a political
anagram for ``Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Lieberman, a moral man by anyone's standards,
may well have canceled out that part of the GOP game plan.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it could still be anybody's ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the big lead the polls have been giving Texas Gov. George
W. Bush. In 1968, former President Richard Nixon came out of the
conventions _ his a coronation, the Democrats' a conflagration _ as
much as 25 points ahead.
</P>
<P>
   By election day, it was a split-hair finish.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's chances, if you figure the betting
odds, are maybe one in three. But that's still a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore-Lieberman can pull it out. Here are some ideas on how:
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's saying that Gore needs to define himself. Better he
should define the Republicans, and Bush-(Dick) Cheney are perfect
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Paint them up as a couple of reactionary Texas oilmen who are
anti-environment, pro-guns and anti-choice, and the Democrats will
be able to wrest away a large portion of the women's vote Bush has
attracted.
</P>
<P>
   Tag the Republicans as the party of tobacco and insurance, the
forces of evil that, on the one hand, have made us sick unto death
and on the other are denying us proper medical care.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget big oil, especially for voters north of the
Mason-Dixon line. If they liked the price of home heating oil last
winter, they're going to love Bush-Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   If anybody tries to argue it, just show them the money. The bulk
of Republican soft money comes from oil, tobacco and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Vote-wise, Democrats can pretty much write off the South with
the exception of Tennessee and, maybe, Georgia. Anybody who knows
anything about Georgia politics will tell you that you never can
tell about Georgia politics.
</P>
<P>
   So, with New York and California ceded to Democrats, here's the
three-pronged key they'll need to unlock a winning ballot box:
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania, New Jersey and Illinois _ each of which contains a
significant Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   Gore-Lieberman? It reads better as Go Lieberman!
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4398 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0818-COX     08-17 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earth calling Texas
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Texans like to brag about big. Everything is
braggable here, and size certainly qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   But one area of big in which we'd just as soon not brag is crud.
</P>
<P>
   Crud is a by-product of crude. Oil, that is. Texas tea. We're
pretty big in that, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the airborne crud category, the kind pumped into our skies by
cars, factories and refineries, if Texas were a country it would
rank seventh largest.
</P>
<P>
   So what the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission will
consider Wednesday is big, even by our standards.
</P>
<P>
   The commission will consider an appeal by environmental
organizations to begin formal rulemaking toward a state plan to
curb greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
   This is 10 years removed from the Texas Legislature authorizing
the state's environmental enforcer to come up with such a plan.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, 1990, sufficient lawmakers were moved by a
state-authorized study showing that the planet was warming and that
made-in-Texas pollution shared the blame.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, absolutely nothing climatologically has happened
that would undermine the thesis.
</P>
<P>
   Science magazine recently published a study by Texas A&AMP;M
geologist Thomas J. Crowley citing man's role in making the 1990s
the hottest decade in recorded history. Sure, recorded history is
just a fly speck on Earth's lifeline. Much remains theoretical. But
to worldwide participants in the United Nations Intergovernmental
Panel on Climate Change, any question about man's role in these
trends has vanished.
</P>
<P>
   'W' WARMS TO IT
</P>
<P>
   If you want a revelation sure to melt the ice caps, consider
Gov. George W. Bush going on the record recently saying that the
planet is warming. According to climatologists, that's no leap of
faith. That's math. But any acknowledgement helps, particularly
from a Republican standard-bearer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not ready, apparently, to blame man-made pollution for
these matters. This is convenient, particularly in Texas, and
particularly with a party leadership in Washington which has
blunted efforts to make good on the Kyoto Accords aimed at curbing
greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION TO OUR AIR
</P>
<P>
   Texas air has gotten a lot of attention lately with Bush's
candidacy and with Houston's supplanting Los Angeles as the
nation's smog capital. Good things have happened with all this
attention, including cleaner-air provisions built into electric
deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   The TNRCC, under the gun from federal regulators, recently came
out with tough proposals that could mean major lifestyle changes in
Houston _ slower speed limits, bans on heavy machinery in the
morning and more.
</P>
<P>
   The TNRCC is just now getting a handle on pollution as a
statewide syndrome rather than a metro or regional one. From Big
Bend to North Texas, our river of air is rancid and getting more
rank.
</P>
<P>
   Is Texas a major culprit in global warming? So say most
climatologists. But in some ways the argument about the earth's
warming _ the ``is not'' vs. the ``is so'' _ reminds one of the
tobacco companies trying to say ``prove it'' on the accusation that
ambient smoke causes cancer. Cancer is just one of many concerns.
Try allergies, asthma and heart disease if you want others.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to prove man-caused global warming to know that
the pollutants we are spewing into the air do us no good.
</P>
<P>
   The world really is watching Texas when it comes to pollution.
And we shouldn't flatter ourselves into believing that it's just
because of a Texan running for president. It's because Texas, as a
polluter, is just that big.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
