<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-COLUMN0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now Harley, Bugs Bunny help sell cars
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cross marketing seems to be the way of this
millennium. Or has it been around for a while?
</P>
<P>
   Cross marketing is the practice of one product hitching a ride
on the star of another product's success. How many of you have
purchased just one more Kid's Meal to get a dinosaur from the
latest Disney movie?
</P>
<P>
   But fast-food restaurants and movie studios are not the only
ones playing that game. Automakers today are using cross marketing
to target a segment of potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   One is Ford's hot, limited-production Harley Davidson F-150
pickup truck. In the mid-'80s, you couldn't have paid an automaker
to put out a vehicle emblazoned with Harley badges. Back then,
bikers were bad dudes. But no more. Today, a Harley Soft-Tail may
be the ultimate baby boomer status symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it makes good business sense for Ford and Harley-Davidson
to capitalize on each other's success. If a Harley is the ultimate
status symbol, the ultimate accessory for your bike could be a
black-on-black truck complete with bike tie-downs in the bed,
chrome Harley badges here and there, and even wheels that evoke the
spirit of the motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   You don't find P275/45R20 Goodyear Eagle GT1s on just any pickup
truck. Stand back and look closely and you will notice that the
exceptionally low profile tires mounted on wide-spoked alloy wheels
actually are pretty close to what an actual Harley has.
</P>
<P>
   With an asking price of $33,205, the Harley F-150 is one
tricked-out version of America's best-selling truck.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet is capitalizing on a much younger market with its
Warner Bros. Edition Venture minivan. Anybody can put a video
screen in a minivan but can they say that it has had Bugs Bunny or
Wiley Coyote or the Tasmanian Devil? General Motors already has
hooked Taz up with its NASCAR and Monte Carlo teams.
</P>
<P>
   In the Doraville-built Warner Bros. Venture minivan, Chevy has a
package that appeals to the whole family. For the 2001 model year,
Chevy is enhancing the Warner Bros. Venture with the addition of an
extra video screen. Now the smaller ones can sit in the middle row
of seats and watch Bugs and company, while third row passengers can
play with their Sony PlayStations on the second screen.
</P>
<P>
   y? There's another tie-in.
</P>
<P>
   But is this concept really new?
</P>
<P>
   In the late '60s, one of the popular buzz phrases was: ``Here
comes the judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac capitalized on the craze by offering its hot-selling GTO
in the Judge edition. Across town, Chrysler Corp. marketers were
wrapping the tails of Plymouths with a big wide stripe that carried
a Roadrunner cartoon character decal.
</P>
<P>
   I guess history does have a way of repeating itself.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp's column is written exclusively for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
