<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4408 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WET-BASEMENT0818-COX     08-17 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WET-BASEMENT0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Easy steps can keep basement dry
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Though rainfall has been at or below normal this
summer, there was at least one July storm that left many, including
me, with wet basements.
</P>
<P>
   It's natural that basements are more damp than other parts of
our houses, but if you regularly get a puddle, a stream or even a
lake during a heavy rain, there are things you can do to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Inspect your gutters. If you didn't have gutters along the edge
of your roof or downspouts to carry rainwater into the yard, almost
all the rain that hit your roof would fall on the drip area right
under the eaves.
</P>
<P>
   This area quickly would become saturated, and water pressure
would build up outside your basement walls and under the floor. Any
cracks or air pockets in the concrete or the seams between concrete
blocks would allow a path for the water to seep into the basement.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest key to a dry basement is keeping rainwater away from
the foundation. If you've had problems with basement moisture after
a rain, go outside and see what's happening on your roof and in the
yard around the house the next time a downpour occurs.
</P>
<P>
   I did that this spring and found a pool forming between my west
wall and the slope alongside my neighbor's driveway. It's going to
take some excavation to give the water a path away from the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, though, working with the gutters and downspouts
will be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Look for leaks in gutters and downspouts and pay particular
attention to seams and connections. Look for sagging spots or areas
where so much water hits the gutters that they overflow. Sagging
spots in gutters are often the sites of overflows.
</P>
<P>
   You usually can fix minor leaks around seams with caulk designed
for gutters. Adding a strategic support strap or nail will correct
a minor sag.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of each downspout, attach some kind of extension
or splash guard that directs water leaving the downspout at least
three feet away from the house. If your basement is chronically
damp, releasing the water even farther away might help.
</P>
<P>
   If the gutter and downspout system is sound, periodically clean
the gutters to keep leaves and other debris from interfering with
efficient water flow.
</P>
<P>
   Check that water that enters the gutters flows smoothly through
the downspouts. Clogged downspouts often can be cleared by
directing a powerful stream from a garden hose through the top
opening.
</P>
<P>
   The soil adjacent to your foundation should slope away from the
house at a rate of at least an inch of drop per foot. Concrete
patios, porches, walks and other solid surfaces also should slope
away from the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   If you do any landscaping or gardening, make sure you don't
create raised areas that cause water to flow back toward the house.
Grass or ground covers with thick root systems planted next to the
foundation also help control water.
</P>
<P>
   Check for more serious problems. Once you've dealt with surface
rainwater runoff, dampness problems should be greatly reduced. But
they might not be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   To correct persistent seepage problems, start by sealing all
visible cracks with concrete patching compound or hydraulic cement.
Hydraulic cement is a putty-like material that can be used to plug
a leak.
</P>
<P>
   After following manufacturers' directions for patching compound
or hydraulic cement to seal cracks, cover walls and floors with a
waterproofing paint. Make sure the paint you select is a
waterproofer, not just a sealer, and that it is rated for use below
grade _ that is, below the ground level. And follow all application
instructions, especially wall-preparation instructions.
</P>
<P>
   If all these steps fail, you might have a problem that needs a
professional.
</P>
<P>
   Waterproofing contractors can install a sump pump to pump
underground water away from the foundation. Or they can excavate
around the foundation to add water barriers to the outside of the
basement wall or add underground pipes called drainage tiles to
help direct water away from the house.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
