<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-VALHALLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PGA PUT VALHALLA ON A FAST TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Augusta National. Pebble Beach. St. Andrews.
Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   Play a game of ``What's Wrong With This Picture'' and folks who
follow professional golf will tell you quicker than you can pick up
a gimme putt that Valhalla doesn't fit. There's just no tradition,
which, of course, it couldn't possibly have, given the fact it is
only 14 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Valhalla is the venue for the 82d PGA Championship, the
season's fourth major that annually gets trashed as the weak link
in the chain of golf's four majors. Too bad, said Curtis Strange,
``because it's a big deal to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Players generally have been generous in their praise of this
Jack Nicklaus-designed course, but skeptics are everywhere. The
problem, as some observers see it, is that the PGA of America
co-owns the place and will own it outright by the end of this year.
Having an event the size of the PGA Championship or Ryder Cup
(2007) on your own property ensures higher profits, which smacks of
money being the bottom line in selecting a layout.
</P>
<P>
   When Valhalla was granted the PGA Championship in 1996, eyebrows
were raised because rarely do young courses get awarded such
jewels. The return to Valhalla for this season's fourth major has
given more ammunition to the skeptics because it's the soonest a
major championship has returned to a venue since the Myopia Hunt
Club in South Hamilton, Mass., was host for the US Open in 1905 and
1908.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares? say the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell you it's my favorite golf course,'' said
Justin Leonard, ``but we're all here playing on the same one.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of his colleagues, Leonard knows that criticizing the
course would serve no purpose. Many of them are connected to the
PGA of America, and no Tour player wants to be accused of taking a
slap at Nicklaus. While Valhalla lacks the aura of Augusta, the
breath-taking views of Pebble Beach, and the unmatched history of
St. Andrews, it's not exactly a cow pasture (though it was a horse
pasture before Dwight Gahm bought this 430-acre site in 1981).
</P>
<P>
   Quite the contrary, it's a marvelous layout if you can forgive
the eyesore created by a number of electrical towers and cable
lines. The front side, around which Nicklaus had to deal with
low-lying land that floods easily, is wide open, almost to the
point of radiating a links-like feeling. The backside cuts through
woods and transforms the course into a more traditional American
layout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great course,'' said Sergio Garcia, voicing a
popular opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But as there always is with these players, some criticisms
surfaced, much of it surrounding the par-5 seventh hole. On a tract
that provides some quirky features (an island green at the par-4
13th, thick bluegrass rough, greens with severe humps), it is the
seventh hole that elicits the most noise.
</P>
<P>
   Goofy, said Ken Venturi. ``I think they ruined it. Get rid of
the (fairway) on the left. Play it on the right.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the fact that players have an option off the
tee: Driving it right to the fat part of the fairway where it
becomes a three-shot hole, or going left, cutting the distance by
nearly 60 yards, and turning it into ``nothing but a long par 4,''
said Venturi.
</P>
<P>
   Like Venturi, Leonard has his doubts about the hole. ``I think
everybody should have to play the same fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would probably go right because there is added danger
left. Still, he knows that bigger hitters who take it left will
have a huge edge by being within mid-iron distance to the green.
</P>
<P>
   John Daly, the longest of long hitters, is looking the right way
for once. ``I hit it down the left side today, but I'll probably go
down the right unless the wind is blowing right in our faces. If
you miss the fairway (going left), you don't have a second shot to
get back to the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   The right side? ``I don't know why (a player would),'' said
Venturi, although if it were up to him, the players would be forced
to go that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get rid of the left side and now you have one hellacious par
5,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
