<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4417 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-HOGAN-BOS &LR;      08-17 1621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-HOGAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS'S FOCUS HOGAN-LIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The teacher was trying to explain his point,
searching for the perfect tool to do so. Words just didn't do it,
no matter how he used them. So Claude ``Butch'' Harmon Jr. did what
anyone from his era would do _ he turned to Ben Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   Not the legend himself, but a picture of him. It had been taken
years earlier, but because the photo was clear, so, too, was the
teacher's point. ``Look,'' said Harmon. ``Look at the picture. This
is where I need to get you, but you've got to get stronger to get
to there.''
</P>
<P>
   Get stronger to get better? The student, Tiger Woods, salivated.
Though he had taken the golf world by storm months earlier,
shattering the scoring record at the 1997 Masters, Woods didn't
like the way his golf swing was holding up under pressure. He was
flying greens with wedges, coming up short with 9-irons, pushing
drives right.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, there was something in the swing that only the most
astute gurus could have picked up. Woods wasn't strong with his
left wrist at impact. Bowing. Pronation. Whatever the term, Woods
needed to work on it and to remind him, Harmon gave him a large
blowup of the photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't get there,'' said Harmon, explaining the position
Hogan was in in the photo. ``He (Woods) would always rub his arms
right here (pointing to an area above the left wrist where the
right hand would flip over the left at impact). He actually had a
spot on his arm because he rolled it so much when he was younger.''
</P>
<P>
   That Woods trusted Harmon is no surprise, for they had been a
team since August 1993, a collaboration that had produced three
straight US Amateur championships and five victories in his first
16 PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   That Harmon trusted a decades-old photo of Hogan was no
surprise, either, for in the industry, no one's work ethic,
attention to detail, and determination was admired more.
</P>
<P>
   In God we trust? That's currency. In golf, they trust Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   He sees things his competitors can't, sets goals mere mortals
can't even fathom, and pushes himself harder than most of his
colleagues would dare consider. Which is why Tiger Woods is where
he is today, even at age 24.
</P>
<P>
   He's in the field for the 82d PGA Championship at Valhalla Golf
Club, but more than that, Woods is in a league by himself. His
colleagues can pursue their craft in hopes of one glorious week;
Woods will continue his assault on the history books.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, Woods already has established scoring records in the US
Open (12 under) and British Open (19 under) to complete his victory
trip around the four majors in just 15 attempts, quicker than any
of the four other players who can claim such a feat. In cementing
his domination of a game that observers had always said could not
be dominated, Woods has become not only the most feared golfer, but
the most recognized sports figure in the world. And each week,
stories are written and words are spoken as to why all of this has
happened so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Examine any number of reasons, but again experts will point to
the picture of Hogan. This time, not for the swing, but for an
essential quality that no one possessed quite like him. Focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hogan was a breed apart,'' said Ben Crenshaw. ``He was
unbelievable. He would not say hello to his mother if she were out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan. The mere mention makes Crenshaw pause out of respect. It
is arguably the most revered name in golf history, not so much
because he was a warm, beloved person as much as he was the most
diligent worker in a game that demands supreme diligence.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are legendary: Hogan's struggle for years with a
brutal hook that he eventually cured or his unmatched ability to
shape a shot to whichever way was required. The answer ``was in the
dirt,'' he used to say, which meant you had to practice for hours,
then practice some more. On his way to tournaments, it is said that
Hogan would drive well below the speed limit, going just slow
enough to get himself into a frame of mind that would fit the
meticulous pace he would play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had tremendous focus,'' said Harmon, who is one of the few
people who can relate to Hogan on a personal level and not through
the pages of history books.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and my dad (Claude, the 1948 Masters champ and one of the
best pros of his era) were friends. I knew Hogan my whole life. I
grew up watching him practice at Seminole.''
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic, agreed Harmon, that he is helping to guide Woods
toward a Hogan mark that many people felt would never be matched.
That is, three major victories in a season, a feat Hogan
accomplished in 1953 and one which Woods could match with a victory
at Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   There are huge differences between these men, said Harmon. While
Woods was told to study Hogan at impact, he did not try to sell him
the entire package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say you should try to copy Hogan's swing, because I
think it's ruined more people than it's helped,'' said Harmon.
``He'd try to bend that right elbow in, the shaft would lay down,
but he had tremendous speed in his body and his hands and he would
get the club squared, the left wrist in a more tucked position and
the clubface open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the average player doesn't have that sort of
speed and would hit it right every time.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there was one thing Harmon would transplant from Hogan to
Woods, it would be the legendary steel-eyed focus. He won't take
credit for it, but it appears to be taking place, said Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hogan) had tremendous focus, and I think you're seeing Tiger
Woods is now getting to that. If you watch Tiger play, especially
in the major championships, he is totally in command of not only
his physical being, but mentally, too. And that's where I think
Hogan and (Jack) Nicklaus had it over everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they were great players, but they also were so smart and
they had to focus with what was at hand. I think you're seeing
Tiger Woods is now able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The story has been told many times in many versions and is
considered the quintessential tale to demonstrate just how focused
Hogan was. ``Dad swore it was true, so it's all I can go by,''
Harmon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 12th hole at Augusta and my dad made a hole-in-one. Mr.
Hogan made a 2, and as they walked to the 13th tee, Mr. Hogan said
to my dad, `Claude, that's the first time I've ever made a 2 on
that hole. What did you get?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon laughs pleasantly, for the story hasn't lost an ounce of
its appeal over the span of 50 years. And he is well aware that his
star pupil is compiling his own legendary tales that perhaps now
don't measure up to Hogan's, but someday will.
</P>
<P>
   The US Open at Pebble Beach a few months ago provided just such
a moment. In the final round, Woods's walk down the third fairway
brought him close to a jam-packed gallery. Two attention-seeking
spectators grabbed prime spots to stand there, both of them donned
in Tiger costumes head to toe, complete with makeup and whiskers.
</P>
<P>
   People laughed, hooted, and waited for Woods's reaction. There
wasn't any. He locked his eyes straight ahead, walked briskly, and
never strayed one step from his intended destination. The men in
their Tiger costumes walked away.
</P>
<P>
   A different example, for sure, but these ``are different eras,''
said Ken Venturi, the CBS analyst and former US Open champion who
counted Hogan among his friends. No one, in Venturi's mind, matches
Hogan for pure determination, and if Woods drew inspiration from a
large photo of the four-time US Open champion, it only proves he's
like many others.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Woods is respectful of what Hogan did and not in
any rush to look past the business at hand. ``I am not here trying
to duplicate what Hogan did in '53,'' he said. ``That strictly is a
by-product of winning the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan loyalists are quick to point out that the '53 feat should
rank ahead of what Woods could do _ and their rationale is sound.
After winning the Masters and US Open that year, Hogan had to
choose between the PGA Championship (July 1-7) and the British Open
(July 8-10). There was no way he could travel from one to the
other, not with the British Open in those days requiring
pretournament qualifying, so there would not be any chance at the
Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   There was also no outcry for it, either. Like Venturi said, ``a
different era.''
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward 47 years and Woods is at the center of every
interview, the focal point of every practice round, seemingly the
only player in a field of 150 who matters. It is, said Woods,
sometimes stifling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Hogan played in a time when the media atmosphere
wasn't what it is now, so that's different.''
</P>
<P>
   He was addressing a room filled with reporters, most of whom
will be jammed inside the ropes for this morning's round, played in
front of galleries packed 10-15 people deep. Indeed, more hectic
than in Hogan's prime, but Woods concedes that the man whose mark
he is chasing had to deal with it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played golf in a way, both mentally and emotionally, where
he liked to just kind of be on his own and block everything out.
And that is what I try and do.''
</P>
<P>
   Can he do it? Are you kidding, ask his colleagues. Have you been
watching?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be very surprised if he actually knew there was a big
gallery there,'' said Lee Westwood. ``I think mentally he is that
strong. I don't think he sees anything but the ball and the hole,
or the ball and the flag. I don't think he'd know whether there
were 5 or 5,000 people watching him.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, you know Hogan would approve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
