<P>
   HOW TO AVOID E-MAIL LAWSUITS
</P>
<P>
   AVOIDING-E-MAIL-LAWSUITS-HARVARD-BUSINESS-PUBLISHING _ Instant
gratification always comes at a price. E-mail makes it easier to
communicate with colleagues, but inappropriate messages can make
you and your company vulnerable to lawsuits for harassment, libel
and copyright violations. How should one navigate these treacherous
communication waters? By taking heed of these tips. 700 words.
Excerpted from the Harvard Management Communication Letter.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING WITH INDEPENDENT CONTRACTORS
</P>
<P>
   CONSULTANT-BOOM-HARVARD-BUSINESS-PUBLISHING _ The terms are used
loosely: independent contractor, contract employee, consultant. But
the phenomenon they refer to _ people who put in a substantial
number of hours at a company but are not legally employees of the
business _ has exploded in recent years. Some independent
contractors, or ICs, are brought in for specific short-term
projects. Others have a long-term gig with a company, moving from
one task to another. This article lists 20 ways to tell who's truly
a consultant and who's not. 800 words. Excerpted from the Harvard
Management Update newsletter.
</P>
