<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4471 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-CONSULTANT-BOOM-HARVA     08-17 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSULTANT-BOOM-HARVARD-BUSINESS-PUBLISHING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING WITH INDEPENDENT CONTRACTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release: Tue., Aug. 15, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 &HT;    
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 &HT;    
 FROM: HARVARD MANAGEMENT UPDATE  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The terms are used loosely: independent contractor, contract
employee, consultant. But the phenomenon they refer to _ people who
put in a substantial number of hours at a company but are not
legally employees _ has exploded in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Some independent contractors, or ICs, are brought in for
specific short-term projects. Others work what amounts to a
long-term gig with the company, moving from one task to another.
</P>
<P>
   From a manager's perspective, it seems like an easy solution:
Freeze or reduce the permanent staff and instead contract with
skilled professionals.
</P>
<P>
   A company isn't responsible for income-tax withholding, Social
Security and Medicare, unemployment, workers' compensation and all
the other benefits that generally amount to more than one-third of
total payroll costs.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does anyone have to worry about terminating the ICs in a
downturn: When their contracts end, they're gone.
</P>
<P>
   The contractors, for their part, can pick and choose clients,
work where and when they determine and typically earn significantly
more per hour than they'd make as regular employees.
</P>
<P>
   But complications can arise. For instance, imagine a situation
in which employers suddenly decide to treat whole groups of
employees as independent contractors, thereby saving bundles on
benefits. A relationship that looks like a win/win from society's
perspective when the IC is, say, a skilled software engineer could
look more like exploitation when the newly declared IC is an
unskilled factory worker who is asked to work without benefits.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, tax-collecting authorities have a big interest in
how employees are classified. Employees' taxes are withheld and
paid to the government on a regular basis. ICs, by contrast, are
responsible for paying their own taxes. That makes the tax
collector's monitoring-and-collection job harder.
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, there are a host of governmental regulations
concerning the circumstances under which workers may legitimately
be classified and treated as ICs.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR OR EMPLOYEE? THE 20 TESTS
</P>
<P>
   Here are 20 common factors that the IRS and federal courts use
in combination to determine whether workers are properly
classified. Measure against this list to see if your classification
is appropriate:
</P>
<P>
   1. INSTRUCTIONS. Employees must comply with instructions of
when, where and how work is to be performed. ICs can be held
responsible only for the final product.
</P>
<P>
   2. TRAINING. Employees often receive training from their
employers; ICs do not.
</P>
<P>
   3. INTEGRATION. Employees provide services that are an integral
part of a company's day-to-day operations; ICs should not do work
that determines the success or continuation of the hiring firm.
</P>
<P>
   4. SERVICES RENDERED PERSONALLY. Employees must do their own
work; ICs generally can hire other people to do their work.
</P>
<P>
   5. HIRING, SUPERVISING AND PAYING ASSISTANTS. Employees hire,
supervise and pay assistants only at the discretion of the
employer; ICs can hire whomever they want.
</P>
<P>
   6. RELATIONSHIP TO EMPLOYER. Employees have a continuing
relationship with their employer; ICs generally move on after
finishing a project.
</P>
<P>
   7. WORK HOURS. Employees normally have set hours of work; ICs
set their own hours.
</P>
<P>
   8. WORKING FULL TIME. An employee may be required to work full
time for an employer; ICs can work when and for whom they choose.
</P>
<P>
   9. LOCATION OF WORK. Employees must work where their employer
specifies; ICs can usually choose where to work.
</P>
<P>
   10. SEQUENCE OF WORK. Employees may have the sequence of work
established for them by their employers; ICs decide the sequence
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   11. PROGRESS REPORTS. Employees may be required to prepare
progress reports; ICs are responsible only for the final product.
</P>
<P>
   12. METHOD OF PAYMENT. Employees are paid by amount of time
worked; ICs are often paid a flat rate per project.
</P>
<P>
   13. BUSINESS OR TRAVEL EXPENSES. Employees' expenses are paid by
the employer; ICs are responsible for their own expenses.
</P>
<P>
   14. TOOLS AND MATERIALS. Employees get all necessary supplies
from their employer; ICs must provide their own.
</P>
<P>
   15. INVESTMENT. Employees usually don't have an investment in
equipment or facilities; ICs do.
</P>
<P>
   16. REALIZATION OF PROFIT OR LOSS. Employees are paid for their
labor and have no liability for business expenses; ICs can earn a
profit or suffer a loss as a result of the services they provide.
</P>
<P>
   17. WORKING FOR MORE THAN ONE FIRM. Employees may be restricted
from working for another firm at the same time; ICs have no such
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   18. MAKING SERVICES AVAILABLE TO THE GENERAL PUBLIC. Employees
work primarily for the hiring firm; ICs can make their services
available to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   19. RIGHT TO FIRE. An employee can be fired at any time, for
almost any reason; ICs can be terminated only according to the
terms of their agreement.
</P>
<P>
   20. RIGHT TO QUIT. Employees may quit at any time without
liability; ICs are legally obligated to complete the work they
contracted to do.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``The Contract Employee's Handbook''
(www.cehandbook.com) and ``How to Safely and Legally Hire
Independent Contractors'' by Stephen Fishman.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on HARVARD
BUSINESS PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
