<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVOIDING-E-MAIL-LAWSUITS-HARVARD-BUSINESS-PUBLISHING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO AVOID E-MAIL LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For immediate release.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 &HT;    
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 &HT;    
 FROM: HARVARD MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION LETTER  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Instant gratification always comes at a price. E-mail makes it
easier to communicate with colleagues, but inappropriate messages
can make you and your company vulnerable to lawsuits for
harassment, libel and copyright violations.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, senior management may be watching. An American
Management Association survey released in April found that 38
percent of companies routinely store or review e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   How should one navigate these treacherous communication waters?
By taking heed of these tips.
</P>
<P>
   BE CAREFUL WHAT YOU WRITE
</P>
<P>
   Labor lawyers are kept busier than ever with sexual and racial
harassment claims, and an increasing number of lawsuits feature
damaging e-mails as evidence. Indeed, lawyers say the climate for
harassment in the workplace has dramatically shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last six months, it's been rare to hear about
harassment complaints that don't involve e-mail, the Internet or
both,'' says Carole O'Blenes, a lawyer at Proskauer Rose in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Employees today often claim they are victims of a hostile work
environment that could include persistent e-mail requests for
dates, racy jokes or pornography downloaded from the Internet. What
is one person's notion of fun can be another's humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   O'Blenes says a larger problem is the technology itself. E-mail
is often viewed as an informal medium with few, if any, rules.
``There's an ephemeral quality to e-mail that allows people to be
more offhand than if they were writing a memo on company
letterhead.''
</P>
<P>
   DON'T BE FOOLED BY `DELETED E-MAILS'
</P>
<P>
   The informality of e-mail can lull users into a false sense of
comfort. After all, if they send or receive something questionable,
all they have to do is hit the delete button and no one will be the
wiser, right? Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The stark reality is that deleting an e-mail merely sends the
document into the recesses of a hard drive, and it will sit there
indefinitely unless the drive itself is purged.
</P>
<P>
   SEND CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION VIA ANOTHER MEDIUM
</P>
<P>
   This may seem like a no-brainer, but lawyers say its alarming
how often employees will use e-mail to casually discuss strategy,
trash-talk a competitor or divulge information not meant to be
shared.
</P>
<P>
   This can especially be a problem for personnel issues. E-mail
that speaks negatively of a person and goes beyond the original
sender and recipient could be the basis for a libel claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do employee reviews by e-mail because that's not
something you want someone else to accidentally get,'' says lawyer
Marcelo Halpern of Gordon &AMP; Glickson in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   BE WARY OF COPYRIGHT RESTRICTIONS
</P>
<P>
   It's easy _ too easy _ to download software and other material
and then e-mail it with abandon. Woe to the employee whose company
gets a cease-and-desist letter.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount Pictures reportedly sent out plenty of those when the
trailer for ``Star Wars: Episode I - The Phantom Menace'' became a
download darling.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, these files suck up too much bandwidth and slow
down the normal course of business. An otherwise efficient T I pipe
will behave like a balky 14.4 kb modem if too many of these files
are traveling through the system.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Although you can't stop people from sending you
things, you can ask them to not send them. And never pass them
along.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL IS COMPANY PROPERTY
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to e-mail, employees have no right to privacy. As
long as they are using a company PC and computer network, then any
product generated from that use _ including e-mail _ is considered
company property and is subject to monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of firms are turning to monitoring software
to do the work for them. Employees might find that akin to Big
Brother getting a corner office. But those who make the software
prefer to view their product more as a security blanket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most companies have internal audit departments,'' notes Bob
Friedhoff, whose Falls Church, Va., company xVault makes monitoring
software. ``It's not audited because nobody believes you. It's
audited because you want to have controls and assurance that things
are being done properly.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on HARVARD
BUSINESS PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
