<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4473 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-CELL-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      08-17 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CELL-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOPEZ AT THE CENTER OF ``CELL'' FANTASY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
There's a reason why Jennifer Lopez looks so comfortable in the
wilder, more surreal segments of ``The Cell.'' The movie's director
used to make music videos. Called upon to strike poses in
phantasmagorical settings while wearing outrageous outfits, the
singer-actress seems right at home.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A psychological thriller that takes place largely within the
dreamlike confines of the mind, ``The Cell'' plays like an
audacious cross between ``The Matrix'' and ``The Silence of the
Lambs.'' At times it even starts to resemble ``What Dreams May
Come.'' In that romantic fantasy, Robin Williams, with the help of
groundbreaking computer graphics, journeyed through extravagant
visions of heaven and hell.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Cell's'' first scene, Lopez sits astride a black horse
that gallops through the desert, dwarfed by gigantic pink dunes.
She wears an elaborate white, feathered dress. Accompanied by a
cacophony of Middle Eastern-sounding music, she starts to walk
slowly up the dune, leaving footprints behind in the mountain of
sand.
</P>
<P>
   It's a peculiar opening for a cop movie, but it is only the
first of many peculiarities.
</P>
<P>
   Video directors who graduate to film often have problems with
basic storytelling. Their movies look good, with every shot
suitable for framing, but fundamentals such as narrative
progression, character building and suspense can seem beyond their
grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Tarsem Singh avoids this pitfall. ``The Cell'' has a narrative
thread as strong as steel. A psycho killer is on the loose. After
he's caught, there is a race to unravel his secrets so that his
last victim may be saved.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers use a radical (and largely unexplained) therapy that
uses drugs and futuristic devices to project the consciousness of
Lopez's character into the killer's mind. Once there, she learns
that there is an innocent but wounded boy buried deep inside the
killer's brain. Is it possible to vanquish the monster but save the
child?
</P>
<P>
   With such a strong storyline, the movie can afford to take time
to luxuriate in spectacle. Still, the cost for all of those grand
images is a diminished detective story and characters that are less
developed than they ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   This is a psychological thriller with little concern for
psychology, a detective story with no patience for detection. After
he takes his own journey through the mind of the killer, FBI agent
Peter Novak (Vince Vaughn) springs awake with a head-smacking good
idea: Why not poke around the psycho killer's lair for clues?
</P>
<P>
   As basic as this is, it's treated as such an outlandish notion
that when Novak suggests it, his partner cautions him against
rushing off half-cocked.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow it feels right that when Lopez's character, psychologist
Catherine Deane, journeys into the killer's mind, she encounters
limited memories and no ideas but plenty of bizarre, unhinged
fantasies. In his imagination, the killer (Vincent D'Onofrio) is
alternately a cruel but regal warlock-like being or else a savage
warrior king in a splendiferous hall.
</P>
<P>
   Unfettered by irrelevant notions of realism or physics, director
Singh and his teams of visual effects artists go all out. These
scenes sometimes have the feel of fantastic comic books or of
science fiction _ narrative forms in which the imagination is the
only limit. In such landscapes as this, war is waged against good
and evil.
</P>
<P>
   But that opening scene in the desert takes place inside the mind
of a child. Later scenes inside Deane's own mind are similarly
visual and dreamlike. For example, she imagines herself in a red
nun's habit. She stands in a perfectly symmetrical hall, and when
she speaks, gold filigree and flowers appear along the edges of the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   These images are all great to look at, but are they meant to
suggest that we all think solely in images, as if we have Hollywood
production designers inside our heads with our own teams of visual
artists?
</P>
<P>
   As good as Lopez looks in these costumes (she wears nothing as
showy as that green, open-fronted number she notoriously half-wore
to the Grammys), she comes across less well in the dramatic
portions of the movie. Her character risks her sanity, if not her
life, by projecting her own consciousness into the killer's head.
</P>
<P>
   Deane is part of this important experiment not because of her
scientific acumen but because of her unusual ability to connect
with wounded individuals and draw them out. ``She has a gift,'' one
scientist says of her.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez makes us believe in Deane's vulnerability and gift for
empathy, but, with her little girl's voice, her passive manner and
body-hugging skirts, she's not what you would expect of a
competent, educated professional, much less a partner in such an
important scientific project.
</P>
<P>
   These traits all could've been used to establish character. At
the beginning of the film, a man who questions her abilities almost
withdraws his son from the experiment. But rather than explore his
reasons or even acknowledge that Lopez isn't typical, the movie
makes either her casting or the way she was directed seem like a
lapse in judgment.
</P>
<P>
   It's the only serious lapse. The rest of the movie probably
works pretty much the way the filmmakers wanted it to. You can
question the worthiness of their subject and vision, but you can't
really argue with the way they executed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cell'' &QL; 
Starring: Jennifer Lopez, Vince Vaughn, Vincent D'Onofrio &QL; 
Director: Tarsem Singh &QL; 
Screenwriter: Mark Protosevich &QL; 
Rating: Rated R for bizarre violence and sexual images, nudity and
language. &QL; 
Running time:  &QL; 
Grade: B &QL;
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
