<HEADLINE>
EYE SCOOPS!  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 COMPILED BY THE EDITORS OF WWD, DNR AND W MAGAZINE 
 (Art is available.) 
 From WWD, DNR and W magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CHER'S LATEST VENTURE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    She sings, she acts _ and now she makes jewelry. Cher is hard at
work on a new jewelry line that will be in stores by November.
 &HT;    The collection, called ``Cher for Loree Rodkin,'' includes long
earrings, necklaces and bracelets; platinum, gold and silver, and
lots of beads and stones.
 &HT;    As with the vanity cases that Sharon Stone's designing for Louis
Vuitton, a percentage of the profits will go to charity _ in Cher's
case, the Facial Foundation for Disfigured Children, the cause she
took up during the making of the film ``Mask.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    IMAN'S AIDS STANCE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``AIDS is not over. Our children remain at great risk. Every
hour of every day, two American adolescents are infected with
HIV.''
 &HT;    These words are from the model Iman, who has signed on as
celebrity spokeswoman for Mothers' Voices, a nonprofit group
focused on educating parents and teachers on AIDS issues as they
affect youth.
 &HT;    Sheryl Schwartz, wife of Calvin Klein Inc. vice chairman Barry
Schwartz, serves as chairwoman of the group, which also receives
financial and logistical support from Calvin Klein.
 &HT;    ``As parents, we all want to protect our children and given them
the skills they need to live a sexually healthy life,'' Iman added.
 &HT;    This fall, the organization plans to extend its workshop series,
which aims to teach parents how to seize ``teachable moments'' to
explain to their children the facts about the disease _ from its
New York headquarters to Atlanta, Chicago, Houston, Los Angeles,
Miami and Providence, R.I.
 &HT;    The group also plans to host a full-day workshop titled
``Parenting in the Age of AIDS'' this October in New York for the
parents of children attending public schools.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    BRITNEY'S ONLINE LATHER
 &HT;    
 &HT;    It seems that Clairol is taking its association with new
spokeswoman Britney Spears to a new level. Not only is the company
sponsoring Spears' summer concert tour, it's also garnering new
listeners for the teen queen with a promotional pack available on
CVS.com.
 &HT;    The set includes full-sized bottles of Clairol's Herbal Essences
Shampoo and Conditioner for normal/oily hair and a Spears sampler
CD for $8.99.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    POWER LUNCHERS
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ ``Men already run the world,'' said Susan Estrich,
the first woman to run a presidential campaign _ Michael Dukakis' _
and the author of an upcoming book, ``Sex and Power.'' She said
it's up to women ``to recognize the power they have,'' be proud of
it and use it.
 &HT;    Estrich, who spoke to about 60 women at Harper's Bazaar's recent
``power luncheon'' at the Alain Ducasse restaurant, pointed out
that one of the most powerful women was sitting right in the room _
Barbara Walters. She cited Walters' refusal to have O.J. Simpson on
her show, ``The View,'' which drew applause from the audience.
 &HT;    ``I do not have power,'' Walters called out, to which the crowd
exhibited some disbelief _ especially since Walters is negotiating
a reported $12 million contract with ABC.
 &HT;    Other heavy hitters who came out to celebrate Bazaar's August
``power'' issue included Tina Brown, Maria Bartiromo, Kate Spade,
Diane Von Furstenberg, Lesley Stahl, Carolina Herrera, Aerin
Lauder, Josie Natori and Dana Buchman.
 &HT;    The luncheon was hosted by Kate Betts, Bazaar's editor in chief,
and Cynthia Lewis, vice president and publisher.
 &HT;    Bartiromo, an anchor for CNBC whose staggering schedule left
some in the room breathless, said her idea of power is not having
lots of assistants and delegating.
 &HT;    ``I make my own phone calls and in many cases, I'm a one-woman
show,'' said Bartiromo, who does three live shows a day. ``For me,
power is not delegating. It's getting the story right and getting
it first and putting it on the air before it's disseminated.''
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
