u f BC-STRIKE-0818-COX     08-17 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIKE-0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    STRIKES RARE IN HIGH-TECH ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) Financial categories
 &HT;    See chart information below
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There's a phone strike?
</P>
<P>
   Even though 87,000 operators and technicians at Verizon, the
nation's largest local phone company, walked off their jobs nearly
two weeks ago, dial tones keep droning and folks keep talking into
cell phones even in Verizon's service area throughout the busy
northeast corridor.
</P>
<P>
   A satellited, digitalized, Internetted, high-tech economy has
wrought changes in collective bargaining, labor experts agree.
</P>
<P>
   When miners strike, coal shipments stop. When auto workers
strike, no cars are made. But other than falling behind in repairs
and new installations, highly automated Verizon has continued to
provide service since contract talks stalled on Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Strikes do seem to be less effective in high-tech industries,
said Don Parsons, an economics professor at George Washington
University. ``If you look at it as a game between labor and
management, it gives a tremendous advantage to the employer'' if
basic operations can continue indefinitely during a work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   In these negotiations, striking workers must miss a lot of
paychecks before the impact of their sacrifice is felt, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has existed for some time in telecommunications,
said William Dickens, a senior fellow in economics at the Brookings
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utilities have generally had an easier time maintaining
service. The system pretty well runs itself,'' said Dickens. ``If
you had operators connecting calls, it would be different.''
</P>
<P>
   If production or service continues during a strike, the striking
workers are at a disadvantage, conceded Ron Blackwell, the
AFL-CIO's director of corporate affairs. But even in high-tech
industries, ``if workers were unnecessary to the operation, they
wouldn't have been hired in the first place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Withholding labor is still a viable tactic.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there is no doubt strikes are less a part of the
information age than they were in an industrial economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, there were only 17 work stoppages involving 1,000 or
more workers _ the fewest in six decades, according to the Bureau
of Labor Statistics. That compares to 34 in 1998, 412 in 1969 and
470 in 1952. There have been fewer than 100 such strikes every year
since 1982 while there were more than 200 almost every year between
1947 and 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing scarcity of strikes is partly due to ``the
declining importance of the industrial armies of the past _ the
hordes of blue collar workers'' in a high-tech economy, said Marvin
Kosters, the director of economic policy studies at the American
Enterprise Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The number of union workers in the private sector has declined
dramatically as the economy changed. And many strongly organized
occupations _ such as school teachers _ are more concentrated in
the public sector and have historically been reluctant to strike.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon was formed from the merger of Bell Atlantic and GTE. The
strike affects Washington, D.C., New York, New Jersey, Virginia,
West Virginia, Delaware, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, New
Hampshire, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island and Vermont. A key issue in
the contract talks is mandatory overtime _ which workers want to
cut back and management said is needed in a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Verizon is in a competitive market, Blackwell said
any reductions in service will send customers to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a well-run strike'' by the Communications Workers of
America and International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, unions don't exist to strike. That's just a
tactic'' to achieve broader goals, he said. The fact that there are
fewer strikes reflects that workers ``don't do it unless its
absolutely necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Unions are trying to organize high-tech workers. Blackwell
pointed to a recent strike by Boeing engineers as a successful
example of labor moving into a new sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to build a new constituency,'' said Marcus
Courtney, co-founder of WashTech _ the Washington Alliance of
Technology Workers _ which is seeking to organize technical
writers, web site developers and other high-tech employees in
Washington state. He said the fledgling union has 250 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just at the very beginning so the whole notion of a
strike is not what's on our minds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the sorts of highly skilled workers that his group is
seeking to organize are vital to continued operations of even
automated industries. If large numbers of these workers united,
Courtney said, a work stoppage could shut down a company's
high-tech services.
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.verizon.com
</P>
<P>
   www.cwa-union.org
</P>
<P>
   www.ibew.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
