<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4496 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-GRILLING-PIZZA-HNS &LR;      08-17 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLING-PIZZA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PERFECT FOOD FOR AN OUTDOOR COOKOUT? TRY PIZZA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE WALKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take two very popular eating activities _ grilling and pizza _
put them together and what do you get?
</P>
<P>
   You might get burnt cheese on your grill, but if you follow some
simple directions, that won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, you'll get one of the best-tasting pizzas you ever
sank your teeth into.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled pizza has been around awhile. I read about it years ago,
but was reminded of it recently while reading Patricia Cornwall's
mystery ``Black Notice.'' In the book, medical examiner Kay
Scarpetta throws together several pizzas to cook on the grill. At
the same time, she is entertaining company, doling out advice to
her niece who is tracking a gang of vicious drug dealers, grieving
her boyfriend's violent death and trying to solve a mystery
involving a homicidal French werewolf.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, messing up the grill was the least of her
worries.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled pizza sounded delicious, so I decided to give it a try.
Without directions to follow, friends and I tackled the task using
our own, generally reliable, common sense.
</P>
<P>
   First, we made pizza dough using my favorite recipe from Jack
Bishop's ``The Italian Vegetarian.'' It is a very flavorful dough
that works great in the oven. We stretched the dough, put it on an
oiled cookie sheet and added our toppings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we ran into difficulty _ how to get that pizza, with wet
sauce and loose toppings, off the pan and onto the grill. It took
two of us, using spatulas and fingers, to lift that first pizza off
the cookie sheet and onto the grill.
</P>
<P>
   One person folded the second pizza in half, then moved it to the
grill and rearranged the toppings. This worked better, but we
decided that next time we'd find a cookie sheet that was open at
one end, oil it and slide the pizza off.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the cooked pie off the grill wasn't a problem. The dough
begins to cook the minute it hits the hot rack and soon will move
easily when prodded with a spatula. Only one of our pizzas came out
looking bad (it fell apart for some reason) but it succeeded in the
taste category _ smoky, crusty and delicious.
</P>
<P>
   While we were reasonably pleased with our results, we decided
the next time we made pizzas on the grill we'd put the dough on the
grill, then add toppings.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some expert consultation seemed in order. So, I called
Steven Raichlen, author of ``The Barbecue Bible'' and an
experienced pizza griller.
</P>
<P>
   He, not to my surprise, had a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to remember three basic things,'' Raichlen said.
First, cook the crust over direct heat and flip it, so that both
sides cook over the heat. (Obviously, you don't put toppings on
until after you've flipped it!)
</P>
<P>
   ``Indirect heat,'' said Raichlen, ``is for sissies.''
</P>
<P>
   Have the topping ingredients handy and when you put them on the
crust, ``do it in reverse order,'' Raichlen says. That means you
brush oil and scatter cheese on the hot, crusty top of the pizza,
then arrange the other ingredients and sauce over the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't really need wet sauce, though. ``I really like a
combination of fresh chopped arugula, chopped tomatoes, caramelized
onion and gorgonzola cheese,'' Raichlen said. Ingredients such as
these don't even need to be put on the crust as it bakes on the
grill _ pile it on afterward, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a salad on pizza, but it's good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few more tips for grilling pizza:
</P>
<P>
   _ Do a trial run using frozen (then thawed) ready-made bread
dough. It won't taste as good as homemade, but you won't feel so
bad if it doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have a grill that is adjustable up and down, cook the
dough until it's crisp on the first side, then flip it and raise
the grill for lower heat.
</P>
<P>
   _ The lid can remain open while you're grilling the pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   _ For best luck, keep the pizzas ``personal'' size, 7-to-8
inches.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make your sauce a little thicker than usual, or just use
freshly sliced tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't forget to reverse the order of the ingredients, with
cheese going on the hot crust before the other ingredients and
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Bonnie Walker by e-mail at
bwalker1(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
