<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, Aug. 17, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Eric Rosenberg or Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-WILLIE-BROWN Los Angeles) _ In his first year as San
Francisco mayor, Willie Brown stormed into the 1996 Democratic
National Convention in Chicago with the electricity of a Hollywood
star. In his second-term, Brown is no less a party, but his
presence at this year's convention has been decidedly low-key. By
ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   ETHICAL-DILEMMA (San Francisco) _ When an area 8-year-old kidnap
victim was returned safely to her family in last weekend, it was
cause for relief. Those feelings were shared by reporters and
editors long accustomed to writing stories about missing children.
But the news raised an ethical issue for the media after police
revealed that the child had been sexually assaulted by her alleged
abductor. The child's name had been widely publicized in the two
days she was missing. By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNALIST-SHIELD (San Francisco) _ The California state Supreme
Court has lifted the threat of contempt of court from a reporter
who refused to answer a prosecutor's questions in a Marin County
murder case. But the court's action left news organizations fearful
of a possible new breach in California's shield law for
journalists. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-DESIGN (San Francisco) _ For all its breakthrough
technology and acknowledged superiority in desktop computing, Apple
Computer's lasting legacy will be industrial design. By ALAN T.
SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-SBC-INTERNET (Los Angeles) _ Vice President Al Gore has
conceded he didn't invent the Internet. But Democrats still believe
they are the e-political party and when they decided to hold their
national convention in Los Angeles, they were determined to create
a cutting edge, technological e-convention. San Antonio-based SBC
Communications says its people made that possible. The company is
the official communications provider for the convention. By SHERRY
SYLVESTER.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED-AIRLINES (San Francisco) _ There's an old expression
about winning the battle but losing the war. If you don't
understand it, watch what's happening with United Airlines. The
world's largest airline is in danger of becoming America's most
common swear word. Because of separate labor disputes involving
mechanics and pilots, United has canceled hundreds of flights, and
many others have been delayed for hours. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FASH-LADYLIKE (Undated) _ From pearls to pumps, classic ladylike
fashions persevere for fall and winter. Suits replace separates in
a season that is shaping up as anything but business casual. By
LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   FASH-LADYLIKE-PEPLUM (Undated) _ Fashion's return to ladylike
styles this fall heralds the return of the peplum. Texas first lady
Laura Bush prefers the style for many of the jackets made for her
by designer Michael Faircloth. By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   FASH-TWEED (Undated) _ For decades a fashion standby, tweed is
now the basis for this fall's designer brainstorm _ the sporty side
of dressing up. Native to Scotland, this once lowly fabric that was
the province of workmen, then golfers, has been snapped up for some
of the most glamorous fashions. By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   FASH-ACCESSORIES1 (Undated) _ What to wear with ladylike looks.
By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CELL-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``The Cell,'' a scientist
(Jennifer Lopez) is asked to enter the mind of a serial killer,
while an FBI agent (Vince Vaughn) tries to find the latest victim
in time. By ERIC HARRISON.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DEMENTED-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Cecil B. Demented,''
director John Waters (``Serial Mom,'' ``Pink Flamingos'') mocks his
favorite things in the story of terrorist filmmakers who kidnap a
Hollywood star (Melanie Griffith) to make rebel movies. By LOUIS B.
PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GODZILLA-REVIEW (Undated) _ Hollywood had a chance to
create its own Godzilla monster movie and blew it, so now the real
Japanese critter is back fighting an alien UFO and crushing entire
miniature cities in ``Godzilla 2000.'' By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GRASS-REVIEW (Undated) _ With the help of marijuana
activist Woody Harrelson, director Ron Mann takes a look at all
things marijuana in the pro-weed documentary ``Grass.'' By BRUCE
WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-KINGS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Spike Lee directed ``The Original
Kings of Comedy,'' a documentary about stand-up comics Cederic the
Entertainer, Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley and Bernie Mac. By ERIC
HARRISON.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GRILLING-PIZZA (Undated) _ Take two very popular eating
activities _ grilling and pizza _ put them together and what do you
get? You might get burnt cheese on your grill, but if you follow
some simple tips, that won't happen. Plus, you'll get one of the
best-tasting pizzas you ever sank your teeth into. By BONNIE
WALKER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THAMES-FOOTPATH (Kemble, England) _ The Thames Path, the newest
of Britain's national long-distance footpaths, is a walk through
the green heart of the England, past fields of golden barley and
thatched cottages as homey and precious as a Thomas Kinkade
painting. It ambles alongside the dreaming spires of Oxford,
brooding Windsor Castle, Hampton Court, Big Ben, Shakespeare's
Globe Theatre and the Tower of London. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   With: THAMES-IF-GO
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-JEWISH (San Francisco) _ Al Gore's vice presidential
selection has put a spotlight on what is usually only whispered in
private. It bubbled to the surface when newspaper headlines across
the country announced in bold type that Al Gore had picked ``a
Jew.`` Many political analysts point out that it's only because he
is the first ``Jew`` to be placed on a national ticket that there
is so much brouhaha. Others hint at something less pleasant. By
RUTH SHERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-MORSE-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ What a week. I've been trapped
between phalanxes of cops every day. I've heard too many rap chants
for Mumia. On Wednesday a bomb threat kept me out of my hotel for
hours. One thing has kept me going _ the people I met at the
convention. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
