<P>
   HARLEY'S LEADERSHIP U-TURN
</P>
<P>
   HARLEY-U-TURN-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW _ When Rich Teerlink
became president of Harley-Davidson's motorcycle division in 1987,
the hard work of saving the company was done. After seven years of
crisis, it was growing steadily. In this first-person essay,
Teerlink tells how a new kind of leadership was needed _ one that
encouraged union and salaried employees to break new ground and
care about the company on a personal level _ and how hard it was to
make the shift. By Rich Teerlink.
</P>
<P>
