<HEADER>
A4530 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-SUMMER-MOVIES-AZR &LR;      08-17 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)
</HEADLINE>
  
 BC-SUMMER-MOVIES-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    SUMMER FULL OF SURPRISES FOR HOLLYWOOD(a)  &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Hollywood, the summer of 2000 was a season of surprises.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)The Perfect Storm (enditalic)blew away
(beginitalic)The Patriot (enditalic)at the box office.
(beginitalic)Chicken Run (enditalic)trotted past the fowl Jim
Carrey movie (beginitalic)Me, Myself &AMP; Irene(enditalic). And people
loved hanging out at (beginitalic)Big Momma's House(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest surprise was the runaway hit (beginitalic)Scary
Movie(enditalic), the Wayans brothers' raunchy send-up of teenage
slasher movies that cracked the $140 million mark. In the
wheels-within-wheels department, (beginitalic)Scary Movie
(enditalic)parodied such films as (beginitalic)Scream(enditalic),
which poked fun at such old horror flicks as (beginitalic)Halloween
(enditalic)and (beginitalic)Friday the 13th(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Scary Movie (enditalic)overcame some pretty loud
harrumphing from critics, many of whom felt it scored too high on
the raunch-o-meter.
</P>
<P>
   And it pretty much did. But (beginitalic)Scary Movie
(enditalic)was a far better effort than the disgusting
(beginitalic)Me, Myself &AMP; Irene(enditalic), which got a pass from
some because it had Carrey and the Farrelly brothers behind it. No
matter that the movie stunk.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, people voted with their feet. At last count,
(beginitalic)Scary Movie (enditalic)has made over $50 million more
than (beginitalic)Me, Myself &AMP; Irene(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   The Wayanses led a vanguard of African-American filmmakers and
stars who cashed in this summer.
</P>
<P>
   There was Martin Lawrence in (beginitalic)Big Momma's
House(enditalic), playing an FBI agent who dresses up like an
elderly woman to catch a thief. At last count, the movie was
approaching $115 million in receipts, especially impressive because
it cost only about $30 million to make.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy also climbed back into the fat suit for
(beginitalic)Nutty Professor II: The Klumps(enditalic). Widely
dismissed as inferior to the original, the movie still grossed $43
million on its first weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And director John Singleton scored a solid hit with
(beginitalic)Shaft(enditalic), starring Samuel L. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of stars, we saw a battle for Hollywood hunk supremacy
between Mel Gibson in the Revolutionary War epic (beginitalic)The
Patriot(enditalic) and George Clooney in (beginitalic)The Perfect
Storm(enditalic), which chronicles the exploits of a fishing boat
caught in a horrific gale.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a wave of incredible special effects, Clooney easily
bested Gibson, outearning him by $60 million. To be fair, Gibson
had to carry his long, dull movie, while Clooney's performance
consisted mainly of clinging to something while being battered with
spectacular digitized waves.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)The Perfect Storm (enditalic)didn't rule the summer
season, however. That honor goes to (beginitalic)Mission:
Impossible 2(enditalic), the Tom Cruise spy movie that made more
than $200 million while proving to be critic-proof. Many reviewers
saw it as a step down from the original, but audiences loved it.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Mission: Impossible 2(enditalic) was closely
followed at the box office by another guy movie,
(beginitalic)Gladiator(enditalic), which followed the exploits of a
Roman general who is first double-crossed and then becomes the Rock
of the Colosseum.
</P>
<P>
   With testosterone-laden flicks dominating theaters, the summer
films didn't give women much to choose from. So it was no surprise
that the splendid ghost story (beginitalic)What Lies
Beneath(enditalic) showed some staying power, with receipts
approaching $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The supernatural thriller gets my vote as the summer's best. It
stars Michelle Pfeiffer, whose character is haunted by an
apparition somehow connected to her husband, played by Harrison
Ford. Of the calls I received praising this movie, most were from
women.
</P>
<P>
   Another big summer movie, (beginitalic) X-Men(enditalic),
started strong with a $54 million opening, but it's faded fast in
recent weeks, perhaps because all the comic book collectors have
finally seen it the requisite 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   As the summer winds down, there were three late entries in the
sweepstakes. Last weekend's (08/04-06) (beginitalic)Space Cowboys,
Hollow Man (enditalic)and (beginitalic)Coyote Ugly (enditalic)all
tried to grab pieces of the weekend gate, with (beginitalic)Hollow
Man (enditalic)breaking on top with a $26 million opening.
</P>
<P>
   If the summer lacked anything, it was that one critical success
that had everyone talking about it. But there's no need to worry.
</P>
<P>
   The fall film season is right around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
