<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4537 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CVN-SBC-INTERNET-HNS &LR;      08-17 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-SBC-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SBC LAUNCHES DEMOCRATS INTO CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SHERRY SYLVESTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore did not invent the
Internet. But Democrats believe they are the e-political party and
when they decided to hold their national convention in Los Angeles,
they were determined to create a convention with cutting-edge
technology.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications Inc., the telecommunications giant spanning
the Southwest, West Coast and parts of the Midwest, says its people
made that possible.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio-based company is the official communications
provider for the convention. This week, it has supplied the fiber
optic voice, data, video, broadcast and wireless services for
45,000 media personnel, delegates and political service companies
that have gathered here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest single deployment of digital subscriber
lines ever at one spot on the planet,'' said John Britton, the SBC
communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said SBC also provided data and voice services for the
Republican National Convention that was held in San Diego in 1996,
but technology has advanced so dramatically in four years that the
scope of services needed has exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996 we had almost no Internet service,'' Britton said.
``This year, there are over a hundred dot-coms that are streaming
out information constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Watts, president of the Los Angeles region of Pacific
Bell, a division of SBC, said the Democratic convention has
provided an opportunity for SBC to demonstrate that it is no longer
a regional phone company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an opportunity for us to show nationally and
internationally that we have become a global player in
communications,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Motta, vice president for operations for the Democratic
National Committee, said Democrats are paying retail rates for all
the regulated communications and broadcast services being provided
for the convention. In-kind contributions of telecommunication
services are closely monitored by the Federal Election Commission,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Motta said the company has not forecast how much revenue it
expects to receive from the convention, but said the project would
be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Responsive Politics, SBC contributed
$2.1 million to candidates in a wide range of races in the current
election cycle, with 51 percent of the money going to Democrats.
But Motta said SBC's involvement with the Democratic convention has
nothing to do with politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to evolve into a bigger and better global forum and
this convention is a global stage,'' he said. ``There is nothing
like it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Sherry Sylvester by e-mail at
ssylvester(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
