<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4540 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-UNITED-AIRLINES-HNS &LR;      08-17 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED-AIRLINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     UNITED IS IN FOR A ROUGH LANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There's an old expression about winning the
battle but losing the war. If you don't understand it, watch what
is happening with United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest airline is in danger of becoming America's
most common swear word. Because of separate labor disputes
involving mechanics and pilots, United has canceled hundreds of
flights, and many others have been delayed for hours.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an attempt to side with management or the unions.
It's rare in any dispute that either side is completely right or
wrong. But contract negotiations everywhere are sort of like
playing chicken on the railroad tracks; deep down, you honestly
think the other side will flinch before you do. But sometimes you
forget that the train is perfectly capable of destroying you both.
</P>
<P>
   That might happen with United. Even if management and labor both
eventually end up claiming victory, they might lose something more
important than one contract: a habit.
</P>
<P>
   Companies count on repeat business. They want customers to get
into the habit of using their service without even thinking about
what competitors have to offer. United had that with me, and I'm
sure I'm not alone. I have frequent-flier miles there, so I would
automatically take United whenever it was available. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   I have no horror story; just a change of habit. When my wife and
I flew to Atlanta in May, we chose Delta instead of United because
we didn't want to risk having a vacation fouled up by a labor
dispute. When we flew our nephew out from Boston in July, we chose
American instead of United for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   People who work for United probably think this mess is better
than a strike, which can cause serious scars on both sides. After
all, workers still get paid and the airline still gets revenue from
passengers. But for customers, the experience might be worse
because you never know when the whole thing is going to be over.
</P>
<P>
   Be honest now: If you were booking a flight for January and had
a choice between United and any other decent airline, wouldn't you
choose the competitor? Why risk it? But if the pilots and mechanics
were on strike, you might go ahead and book the flight, figuring
that the strike isn't going to last five months.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take long for habits to change. The Teamsters got
most of what they wanted after a 15-day strike at United Parcel
Service in 1997, but UPS lost business and had to cut jobs. Even a
year later, its business was suffering, and a lot of employees were
still ex-employees. Fifteen days was long enough to change
customers' habits.
</P>
<P>
   In United's case, the labor dispute carries a double whammy
because of competition and timing. Both of our flights on Delta
were on time, as were both of our nephew's flights on American.
Certainly part of the credit for that could go to United.
</P>
<P>
   After all, we were going through three of the busiest airports
in the country, places where you expect delays. But those airports
_ particularly San Francisco's _ weren't as busy as usual, because
the world's largest airline had canceled so many of its flights.
</P>
<P>
   United not only unwittingly sent us to its competitors, it
helped to ensure that our experience with them was more
pleasurable. Now THAT'S customer service.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the whammy is the timing. For logical
reasons, labor unions often act during the busiest time of the
year. That can cause management to suffer more, which is part of
the game of chicken.
</P>
<P>
   When you mess with people's summer vacations, you can build up
hatred in a hurry. Business travelers can get numb to airline
delays, but those whose only airline experience is a week or two of
vacation each year can get awfully testy if you spoil it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy writes for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O. Box
7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address is
murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
