<HEADLINE>
MORE SPEED NEEDED TO MAKE WAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ For eight days here, the theme was ``Send a
Message to Sydney.'' The Aussies are talking about a gold rush in
their home waters. Gotta send 'em a message.
</P>
<P>
   So, now that the US Olympic Swimming Trials are done, what's the
message? Our girls are older than your girls? Our guys are younger
than your guys? The Americans didn't send the only message that
matters _ world records.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they couldn't have. Lenny Krayzelburg, the Ukrainian
emigre-turned-California beach boy, could have taken down his own
global mark in the 100-meter backstroke in the semis, but eased up.
Tom Malchow did the same in the 200 butterfly. And a few others
came within hundredths of a second _ Gary Hall in the 50 freestyle
and Ed Moses and Megan Quann in the 100 breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
   This was still a much better meet than it was four years ago,
when no American records were set for the first time since 1920.
Nine US marks were established here, including Erik Vendt's
historic 14:59.11 in Wednesday's 1,500 freestyle, the first time an
American has broken 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the Yanks will be delighted to do as well in Sydney as
they did in Atlanta, where they won 26 medals, half of them gold.
If the Games were held today, the US men would still be favored for
six gold medals _ Krayzelburg (two), Malchow, Tom Dolan (400 IM),
and the two 4x100 relays. But the women figure to win only three _
Brooke Bennett (800 free) and the two 4x100 relays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ranked No. 1 in the world in one individual event,'' US
women's coach Richard Quick said Wednesday, after perusing the form
sheet. ``The rest, we've got to improve to have a chance. We will
have to swim better than we ever have in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   That's essentially what Quick said here four years ago. The
difference then was that his swimmers had four months to get faster
after the March trials. This time, they have four weeks. Last time,
the Games were on home soil. This time, they're halfway around the
world in a hostile pool.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, when the trials were also held in August and the Games
were also on the other side of the international dateline (Seoul),
the Americans had their worst showing (18 medals) since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Matt Biondi and Janet Evans, everybody peaked at the
trials and was flat by the Games. ``We learned something from
1988,'' Quick says. ``We do need to have that balance of work and
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   So the US team will train hard for the next two weeks at its
Pasadena camp, then taper and hope that its old girls and young
guys can jack up their times to podium range. ``It's all about
improvement,'' says men's coach Mark Schubert. ``Whatever happened
here won't be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Americans easily topped the table in Atlanta, nobody
cared that they'd been slow here. But the question is whether their
old girls (oldest in history, including 33-year-old Dara Torres)
and young guys (eight teenagers) will be able to get up enough
speed to stay in front of a world that's gotten markedly faster
over the last quadrennium.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the hype has surrounded the Yank-Aussie showdown,
the fact is that the two old rivals go head-to-head for gold in
only one individual event _ the men's 100 backstroke with
Krayzelburg and Matt Welsh. ``It's not the Pan Pacifics and it's
not US versus Australia,'' says Quick. ``It's the US versus the
rest of the world. We have to be prepared for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Chinese women are clean and slow, the sprinters
have to worry about the Netherlands' Inge de Bruijn, who holds
three world records. The breaststrokers still will have to deal
with South Africa's Penny Heyns.
</P>
<P>
   The US men have more than just The Thorpedo (Australian phenom
Ian Thorpe) and his mates to handle. Russia's Alexander Popov, who
has tormented them at the last two Games, is still around and still
talking trash.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the American men needed only jump in the
water to win all three relays. This time, they could lose them all.
Odds are that won't happen _ the US has never lost either of the
4x100s at the Olympics and has always set a world record.
</P>
<P>
   But when the clockers and watchers penciled the times from the
last eight days into the world rankings, the message that emerged
was strictly intramural: Gotta get faster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
