<HEADLINE>
F-150 SUPERCAB SHARES FORD, HARLEY ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listen.
</P>
<P>
   That staccato burble you hear might be coming from a
Harley-Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   Look.
</P>
<P>
   You're half right. The tuned exhaust notes are pouring forth
from a 2000 Ford F150 SuperCab pickup truck that has been restyled
and customized in the first year of a five-year joint partnership
between Ford Motor Co. and Harley-Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Limited Edition Harley-Davidson F-150. Black with
distinct Harley-orange pinstriping. Black leather all over the
inside. Chrome glistening in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   And that sound is the perfect purr to announce the joining of
two companies, both founded in 1903 _ same year the Wright Brothers
flew at Kitty Hawk _ and hooked at least through their centennial
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Their recipe for this truck? Drop in Ford's 5.4-liter Triton
V-8, make it sound something like a Harley V-Twin engine, and let
the folks at Harley _ with ol' Willie G. Davidson himself taking a
heavy hand _ give it a distinct look.
</P>
<P>
   What you get is an F-150 SuperCab that is lowered so low it
looks like it is crouching. It's the cruiser look.
</P>
<P>
   You've got a chrome billet grill and remarkable 20-by-9-inch
wheels _ biggest ever on a Ford production vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 20-inch wheels pose a significant problem when you add them
to a rig that can spin them at high speeds. Bigger wheels means
bigger tires. Bigger tires, at high speeds, mean more centrifugal
force, and that could mean tire distortion or failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the thing we worked hardest on,'' George Magor, the
project manager for the Ford-Harley Alliance, said of the
wheel-tire combo.
</P>
<P>
   They built the wheels out of aluminum and coated them with
chrome. For the tires, they turned to Goodyear, which developed
Eagle GT2s that incorporate the company's ``run-flat'' technology
which, in effect, produces very strong sidewalls. They are rated to
130 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The result is some of the most beautiful wheels I have seen on
any vehicle. They give this F-150 a distinct presence.
</P>
<P>
   The other remarkable distinction is the sound, produced, Magor
said, by ``tinkering with the lengths and numbers of tubes inside
the exhaust can.'' Like building a musical instrument. It's a tune
that does it for me.
</P>
<P>
   The Triton V-8 that produces the power that produces the burble
cranks out 260 horsepower and 350 ft.-lb. of torque. It delivered
15.6 miles per gallon in more than a week of driving.
</P>
<P>
   It is a very responsive engine, hurtling the truck forward when
asked to do so and, with that torque rating, I'm sure it would be a
hauling and towing beast.
</P>
<P>
   To smooth the ride _ no easy task on a truck with big wheels _
the suspension has been lowered an inch and the springs and sway
bar suspension have been strengthened. They've done a good job in
tuning the suspension _ coil springs up front, leaf springs in the
rear _ and on most roads and in highway travel, it is a crisp,
smooth charger. Only when the suspension encountered a repetitive
series of bumps _ such as washboard _ did a noticeable shudder
develop, running diagonally from front to opposite rear.
</P>
<P>
   In hard corners, it sat remarkably upright and you quickly
realized the only leaning being done was by the occupants of the
truck.
</P>
<P>
   With four doors, getting in and out of the front and rear seats
was easy _ made easier for adults, at least, by the fact the truck
sits lower than normal.
</P>
<P>
   The front seats _ leather captain's chairs embossed with the
Harley logo were firm and supportive _ like a good saddle on a
Softail Springer.
</P>
<P>
   The back of the rear seat, where three people could sit with
decent legroom, was a bit upright, and as the four-door pickup
evolves increasingly into a popular family transport choice,
manufacturers are going to have to make this rear seat just a bit
more comfortable. Some folks will make their decisions on whether
or not to buy a particular truck with the back seat a key factor.
</P>
<P>
   Leather, as I said, is all over the inside: seats, steering
wheel, armrests.
</P>
<P>
   When it was first introduced, the Harley-Davidson F-150 came
with a tonneau cover and it was a slick-looking cap. But Ford had
quality problems with the supplier _ the covers wouldn't hold the
paint job Ford/Harley wanted on them _ so Harley dropped $550 off
the MSRP and delivered this year's model without the cover. The
problem with that is it leaves the big rubber bedliner _ loose in
the bed and embossed with a huge Harley logo _ in easy reach of
thieves.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bedliner that would make a nice wall hanging or rug in
certain homes. I can see one in, say, a living room in winter with
a Harley parked on it.
</P>
<P>
   But news for the future is good. The tonneau cover will return
and, Magro assured me, Ford/Harley will offer a new model of the
specialized truck for each of the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to sell 8,000 this year, 8,000 next year, and remain
limited in production throughout the run of the joint venture.
Colors will change and mechanics will change.
</P>
<P>
   Is that an F-150 SVT Harley-Davidson Lightning I hear rumbling
just over the hill?
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The arrow just below that fuel gauge that reminds you which
side the gas cap is on. If you're a family that swaps vehicles
around, it's sometimes easy to forget how to pull up to a pump.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --The chrome pseudo-step-up-bars tucked under the rocker panels.
Don't tread on me, they say. Problem is, lots of families with what
some Harley types call ``rug rats'' would probably prefer some
semblance of a usable step those kids could use to get out of the
truck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $32,305 &QL; 
Price as tested: $33,330 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 260/350 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 138.5 inches/225.9 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 78.3 inches/71.7 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 5,600 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
