<SLUG> BC-OLY-US-GYM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS MATH ADDS UP TO BETTER THAN SIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Peter Kormann has the math to prove his hypothesis:
``People who think we have no chance to win a medal in the Olympics
. . .,'' said the head coach the US men's gymnastics squad, ``. . .
they are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   For going on five years now, said Kormann, the US men's squad
has shown an upward spike in its learning curve. With the Olympic
Trials under way at the FleetCenter, shaping the teams that will go
to Sydney next month, Kormann is confident that his Yankee men will
flash the moves that have kept them consistently among the world's
top six competitive nations since the last Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``They,'' said Kormann, ``are approaching the fields of glory.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone for banging the drum of patriotic optimism,
Bela Karolyi, head of the women's squad, soon grabbed the
microphone at Wednesday's news conference and proclaimed the
women's team ``very, very good.'' He said it with the typical
Karolyi body English, punctuating adverbs and adjectives with
twists of his torso and shadow punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a problem,'' said Karolyi. ``We don't have a team
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The sorting-out process, putting names to rosters, begins with
the men's preliminary round, which includes six events. The women,
whose preliminaries are Friday night, compete in four events.
Finals for the men will be held Saturday, followed by the women
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The naming of the squads inevitably raises some controversy. The
men will take the top four finishers, determined by combined scores
here and last month's US championships in St. Louis. The fifth and
six members will be chosen by Kormann and members of USA
Gymnastics. All six members of the women's squad will be picked,
regardless of scores here, although the women who finish 1-2-3 will
receive special consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that is subjective, concedes Bob Colorassi, president of
USA Gymnastics, but like figure skating, judging is subjective. In
the end, the sport's governing body wants to be comfortable that it
is heading to Australia with the best tumblers and jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our responsibility,'' said Colorassi, ``to put the best
on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to figure rosters now, said Karolyi ``is all mental
bingo.'' And in the end, he said, the athletes will determine the
roster by their performances, his attempt to diminish fears of
politics playing a cruel hand come selection time.
</P>
<P>
   The most recognizable athlete to take the floor will be Shannon
Miller, the most accomplished gymnast in US history. Hindered by a
hairline fracture in her shin, Miller Tuesday worked out on all
four events and convinced USA Gymnastics honchos that she was fit
for a third run at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Miller didn't begin thinking seriously about another run at
Olympus until December, when she approached her longtime coach
Steve Nunno, ex- of Burlington, Mass., about reaching for the Rings
once more. ``She came to me and said, `I'd like to get in shape and
see where it brings me,' '' said Nunno. ``Then she said, `Maybe I'd
like to compete again.' To me it was, `Hey, been there, done that.
What do you want to do that for?' I mean, for what? What if (the
US) team doesn't even medal. Isn't that going to be
anticlimactic?''
</P>
<P>
   But within a month, said Nunno, Miller was the best athlete in
his gym once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I would have started all this,'' said Miller,
sounding confident about a third trip to the Games, ``if I didn't
think I could make it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
