<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4548 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-USGYM-WILSON-ART-     08-17 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USGYM-WILSON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 BLAINE WILSON IS NOT AFRAID TO CRASH THE SELECTION PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He's got a ticket to ride, but he don'tcare. Blaine
Wilson was guaranteed a free pass to Olympus months ago, based
solely on his resume. No thanks, he says. He's no charity case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If by some chance I screw up and don't make this team, I'm not
going,'' declared Wilson, who's far and away the top man coming
into Thursday night's US Olympic Gymnastics Trials at the
FleetCenter. ``Because there'd be six other guys out there who've
busted their ass and they should be there. If you didn't earn a
spot on this team, you shouldn't be there.''
</P>
<P>
   USA Gymnastics says Wilson has more than earned a spot with a
record five straight national titles and a fourth-place finish at
last year's World Championships. So if he gets hurt this week or
falls off an apparatus or three, Wilson can petition onto the team
and get an automatic thumbs-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in petitions,'' said Wilson flatly.
</P>
<P>
   Ask and ye shall receive doesn't make it in Wilson's value
system. You might as well ask the Lords of the Rings for a gold
medal if you miss your wakeup call at the Olympics. There are no
handouts in this league. Or there shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dad would be like, `Weak way to get in,' ' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   How weak would it have been if Michael Johnson and Maurice
Greene had been able to petition onto the 200-meter team after
pulling up lame at the track and field trials last month? ``So much
hype for absolutely nothing,'' Wilson snorted. ``We waited all day
to watch that race and then _ nothing. The other three guys won
that race because they didn't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   So Wilson will attack all six events in Thursday night's
preliminaries and attack them again on Saturday. Twelve-for-12 is
the goal and if Wilson misses a routine, he will come off cursing,
as always.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is 26 and coming off shoulder surgery but he's still
dissatisfied with anything less than a 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's way better than he was last year,'' said two-time
Olympian (and four-time US champ) John Roethlisberger. ``He's
meaner and nastier. I'm just glad he's on my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has been The Man all quadrennium, winning his last 110
domestic events by US coach Peter Kormann's count. He missed a
bronze medal at the world meet by .001 points. If Wilson had just
stuck his rings routine, he would have been the first American on
the all-around podium since Kurt Thomas in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   By then, though, Wilson had already served the greater good,
making sure that the Americans stayed among the top six in the team
competition going into the Olympic year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top six is like the Final Four,'' said Kormann. ``You're
not going to win any medals if you're not in that group. Unless
you're on the floor with the top teams, you're not going to get a
break.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Wilson, the Yanks likely would have sunk out of the top
10 and off the radar screen. They've been invisible before. After
the US men won their only Olympic title in 1984 in Los Angeles,
they plunged to 11th in 1988 and were still only sixth in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, there was concern about whether we'd even qualify for
1996,'' said men's team director Ron Galimore.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Americans were in medal contention in Atlanta until
two of them fell off the pommel horse. This time, they're mounting
``Operation Sneak Attack,'' which is aimed at ambushing the
Koreans, Japanese, and Belarussians and getting the United States
back on the podium. And Wilson, his tongue repierced, will be
walking the point.
</P>
<P>
   He had taken out the tongue stud and removed the eyebrow ring
because Kormann thought they conveyed the wrong image in a
clean-cut, clean-shaven sport. But the four tattoos are here for
keeps. And the stud is back. ``I got tired of listening to other
people,'' Wilson said. ``I'm doing my own thing. Anyway, it's not
like I'll be sticking out my tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Sundance Kid, he goes his own way. Wilson was always
getting chucked out of practice for acting up. But his spunk and
spark and his fierce team sense always got him invited back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blaine is a bit misunderstood,'' said Kormann, who coached him
at Ohio State. ``He does have a rebel side to him that he uses to
his advantage. But I've never had anyone who's as strong a team
player as Blaine Wilson.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Wilson might be too much of a team player for his
own good. ``When the team competition is over, Blaine tends to
think his job is done,'' said Kormann, ``and he lets down.''
</P>
<P>
   Operation Sneak Attack aside, the Americans have a decidedly
better chance of getting an individual medal from Wilson than they
do of leapfrogging three countries for a team bronze. And if it's
in the all-around, which only one US male (Peter Vidmar in 1984)
has ever managed at Olympus, Wilson will finally get his moment on
center stage.
</P>
<P>
   If he were female, five US titles would already have put Wilson
on a magazine cover. But the men have always played second banana
in America (Mary Lou Retton overshadowed the golden boys in 1984)
and that won't change this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, they won a gold medal in 1996,'' said Wilson.
``That's legit.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that what the women do isn't demanding, Wilson conceded. The
4-inch balance beam is so nasty that cops should use it for a
sobriety test. But still . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you rather watch somebody crash on the high bar or watch
balance beam?'' Wilson said. ``I would not watch balance beam. I'd
watch the crash. It's just more exciting. The events we do are
powerful. Their events are graceful. I don't know if I could sit
and watch graceful for three hours. But I could watch people crash
all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so the USA Gymnastics people, who've already watched one
Olympics implode because their national champion (Dan Hayden in
1988) crashed twice on high bar and missed the team. That's why
Wilson got his ticket to ride, no matter what he does or doesn't do
here this week. Charity has nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The federation people will tell you it's terrific that Wilson is
so competitive, so hard-core, so honest that he won't take anything
he hasn't earned.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not up to him,'' Kormann said.
</P>
<P>
   Blaine Wilson is going back to Olympus even if his coach has to
handcuff him to the rings and ship him Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Blaine says anything,'' said Kormann, ``here's what I'm
going to tell him: `Ask not what your country can do for you, ask
what you can do for your country.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
