<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK-TO-SCHOOL LOOK IS RETRO, RETOOLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents may find back-to-school shopping this year nostalgic,
confusing, and annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers are stocking the shelves with predictable staples and
retro accessories from several eras, creating the potential for a
jumble of styles, from cute (plaid skirts) to seductive (sparkly
stretch denim).
</P>
<P>
   For girls, there are patent-leather shoes, Peter Pan collars,
and blouses with ruffle trim.
</P>
<P>
   But before you start thinking your darling could head off to
class looking like a kilt-wearing private-school student, be aware
that trendsetters are also offering animal prints, fake leather,
stretch jeans (to go with leg warmers _ no joke), colored corduroys
with studs, and jeans in wider bells or flares, some adorned with
fringe, shiny fabric, or beads.
</P>
<P>
   According to one interpretation, these looks are supposed to be
blended, for example, patent-leather Mary Janes paired with orange
bell-bottom corduroys and a dark denim jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is juxtaposition to mixing and matching,'' said Robert
Rutkauskas, fashion director at Filene's in Boston. ``And plaid is
important. A bold plaid. It's not the traditional schoolgirl plaid.
You'd be wearing it with a pleather (fake-leather) jacket or a
chunky sweater, breaking style with a different attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, it's simpler for boys.
</P>
<P>
   Cargo pants that zip off at the knee or loose-fit
carpenter-style corduroys are hip. So is layering screen T-shirts
under short-sleeve woven ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``For boys, it's the great basics, updated by color and
fabric,'' said Betsy Thompson, spokeswoman for Talbots Kids. ``If
you buy things that are lightweight that can be layered up, they
can wear it right through fall; fleece vests, baseball-inspired
T-shirts. Boys take their inspirations from rugged outdoor sport
themes.''
</P>
<P>
   For both sexes, cowboy and motorcycle boots in wood or lug
soles, and brightly colored suede sneakers, are popular this year.
Girls may also choose from among side-zip booties, platforms, and
Mary Janes.
</P>
<P>
   The season's hot accessories for girls include stacks of
bracelets and gold hoop earrings, right out of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgic yet?
</P>
<P>
   The trend in outerwear is denim jackets, down vests, and
peacoats for kids in every age bracket, while ponchos are one of
the biggest items for girls.
</P>
<P>
   Jeans are always popular, but this year the denim is darker, and
for girls, it sometimes has a sheen or sparkle. (Sparkle falls into
the annoying category.)
</P>
<P>
   One trend is wearing a denim jacket with matching jeans,
hearkening back to a James Dean look. It's retro, but also a more
polished and put-together approach for students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is somewhat of a return to wearing a denim jean jacket
in the same finish as the bottom,'' Rutkauskas added.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, pleather may seem over the top for kids. But
retailers say the look, in pants, jean-style jackets, or skirts, is
not just for grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pleather is the hottest trend out there,'' said Mary Ann
Crenshaw, spokeswoman for the Children's Place.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the kicker: ``It's machine washable,'' Crenshaw
insisted. ``And it's for girls and boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleather comes in solid colors, such as red and black, and
plain, smooth finishes. But there are also snake-print and
imitation-crocodile looks.
</P>
<P>
   As for sweater trends, there are hooded or zip-front cardigans,
chunky knits, and an '80s preppy look with Fair Isles and argyles
in a range of necklines.
</P>
<P>
   The preppiness also extends to plaid skirts, which can be
dressed down with layered novelty T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Rutkauskas calls the cotton tops ``attitudes'' because they have
words on them, such as ``Princess'' or ``Goddess.'' The look is a
continuation of the logo T-shirt trend, which is several years old.
</P>
<P>
   Those T-shirts _ with quite different logos or images _ are also
in for boys, who have grown accustomed to wearing a short-sleeve
version over a long-sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Layering is something kids have done for many years, but the
fabrics these days make it easier than ever,'' said Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   New fabrics extend to pants as well, ``like corduroys that have
that soft, lived-in quality,'' Thompson added. ``It feels good
against the skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Flight pants have a more techno feel, coming in shiny fabrics
with toggle drawstrings and handy pockets for electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Although cargo pants have been popular for a few years, there's
a new formula for wearing them: They are supposed to fit, not hang
low or bunch up at the ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Following the trend in women's wear, kids are expected to look
more pulled together this year _ despite the trend of mixing and
matching.
</P>
<P>
   Confused yet?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more refinement to dress,'' Rutkauskas said. ``It's a
little more cleaned up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
