<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDRO PRONOUNCES HIMSELF READY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM KALEC  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pedro Martinez knew the countdown to an extremely
important game of catch rested on his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   When the portable timer attached to the large bag of ice on
Martinez's arm hit 0:00, the Red Sox ace grabbed his glove and
headed toward the field to try to discover what happened to his arm
Monday night in the Red Sox' 7-3 win against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems in good spirits,'' manager Jimy Williams said before
Martinez took to the field for warmups. ``He has to go out there
and find out something for himself. He has to go throw long catch.
I don't know if he necessarily has to get up there and throw a side
session, but I think by playing catch, he would certainly know.
</P>
<P>
   ``(He needs) to just be honest with himself. We all know he
wants to pitch, loves to pitch. We want him to pitch every fifth
day or whatever it is, but we don't want to jeopardize his career,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams's concern was replaced with the comforting feeling of
knowing when Martinez's turn in the rotation comes up Saturday
against Texas, he will be physically ready to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Cy Young Award winner threw long tosses between the
420-foot mark in center field and the 380-foot mark in right field
to pitching coach Joe Kerrigan for approximately 10 minutes.
Martinez then went into the bullpen to throw briefly before
returning to the clubhouse to give Williams an estimation on how
serious was the pain in his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's verdict pleased Williams so much that the Red Sox
skipper felt the need to answer a question nobody asked when he
emerged from the dugout to start batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ready to go,'' Williams said, referring to Martinez, with
enthusiasm to a couple of reporters sitting in the Red Sox dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is fine, I feel optimistic right now and I think I
am going to be out there on Saturday,'' Martinez said. ``Like I
said, it was probably something that was (just) one day. I know I
was fine in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I feel fine. I just threw my pitches, threw
everything over pretty good, just like a normal game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez will keep taking anti-inflamatory medication and
receive massage therapy. He insisted that further treatment is
nothing more than just precautionary measures, and if he were to
rate his health it would be ``100 perecent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm feeling like before I took this (last) start,''
Martinez said. ``So, I hope I'm just fine. Now, if I feel something
then I am probably going to be concerned or checking about it. But
I don't expect to be the way I was the last time out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Martinez pulled himself out as he pointed to his
shoulder while looking into the Red Sox dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has been on the 15-day disabled list twice in his
Boston career, the first because of soreness in his right shoulder
July 24, 1999. Pain in his oblique muscle suffered in June caused
Martinez to miss another two weeks of action earlier this season _
an injury he compares to his recent setback. ``It was the same
feeling, that is why I decided to shut it down,'' Martinez said.
``The other time took me to the DL and I didn't want to go through
that again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to feel so free (yesterday in warmups),''
Martinez said. ``As soon as I threw the first ball I was ready to
let it go. I didn't feel anything probleming me or holding me.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said if there were pain, he would consider pitching
through it because of the lack of games remaining in the regular
season. But he explained that he would not pitch if he felt he
could cause long-term damage to his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the experience I had back in those days I probably would
have pulled something because I would have tried to pitch because I
didn't know,'' Martinez said. ``It took me seven years to miss a
start. I didn't believe in any pain.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Martinez has nothing to hide. He says he honestly
does feel fine and is ready to face Texas at Fenway this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was free and easy and it looked like his delivery was very
much back to normal,'' Kerrigan said. ``He looked like Pedro.''
</P>
</TEXT>
