<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CRITICISM, BLEDSOE IS GETTING LITTLE HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It was in Canton, Ohio, during Hall of Fame
induction week that the answer to your Drew Bledsoe riddle was
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The hints came from Joe Montana, the greatest quarterback of all
time. He was asked about his greatness, his magical nature, his
elusiveness, his penchant for comebacks and dramatics _ what was
the essential reason why he was so great?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had great receivers, I had a running game, I had a great
offensive line, and I was in a system that was made for me,''
Montana said. ``The rest was up to me. If I've had any success,
it's due to the people who played in front of me and around me.'
</P>
<P>
   Check out Brett Favre, a three-time MVP. As soon as the talent
around him was depleted, his game suffered. John Elway? Always a
great quarterback, but it was only after the Broncos added the best
offensive line in the business to go along with the best tight end
(Shannon Sharpe) and the best running back (Terrell Davis) that
Elway was able to win two consecutive Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe in 1996? Pretty good offensive line and running back
(Curtis Martin), a great tight end (Ben Coates), and excellent
receivers (Terry Glenn and Shawn Jefferson). The result? A Super
Bowl appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Montana tells us a quarterback cannot do it all. But if Bledsoe
were to stand on the podium after Patriots practice and complain
that he has an unsettled offensive line, a shallow receiving corps,
a tight end problem, and no real running game _ so how in the world
can he get the job done? _ he'd be ridiculed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet those are the facts. Sometime between now and the
regular-season opener Sept. 3, the level of play around Bledsoe, as
well as his own play, must improve for the offense to be able to be
in synch with a defense that should be the team's strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect us to be explosive,'' said Bledsoe. ``I expect us to
score points on people. To do that we have to have individuals make
big plays and be consistent in our passing game. We have to start
picking up third downs, and when we have a chance to hit the big
play, we've got to hit it. That's what I expect to happen. If it
doesn't, I'd be dissapointed and surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe certainly has heard his critics. He's gone from
superhero (when he won two games in the final seconds two years ago
with a broken finger) to ostensible league MVP (the first half of
last year) to a quarterback nobody could recognize (by the time the
dust of a 2-6 second half of last season had settled).
</P>
<P>
   His detractors say he should be able to do it on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anyone who could do it all by himself,'' said
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition season, Bledsoe has had one bad half (which is
the only measureable time he's had on the field), in the 30-20 loss
to the Redskins last Friday. But then he came out and completed 9
of 10 in the second half, though he threw an interception that
would have given him a second touchdown in as many drives.
</P>
<P>
   When Bledsoe isn't going right, the entire nation of Patriots
followers begins to panic. You hear that Bledsoe can't do this and
that, that he can't lead the Patriots. Bring on Michael Bishop.
Trade Bledsoe for draft picks. The stream of negativity never ends.
So many Boston superstars have endured it when they haven't lived
up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's my coach and me (saying it), it means something,''
Bledsoe said. ``It's obvious the turnovers are unacceptable. They
are 100 percent my responsibility, but there are some things that
come into play. What I'm disappointed in is third-down conversion.
If you can get into a shorter third-down situation, you can pick
them up. If it's third and 10 or 12, we'll have to make some plays
in the regular season to get the first down. We have to do it to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bledsoe has a running game, he'll often get to face the less
formidable challenge of third and short. If he doesn't, he'll be
backpedaling on third and long, likely running for his life and
being forced to rush his throw. That's been the trend, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he's concerning himself with running backs Kevin
Faulk and Raymont Harris right now. If J.R. Redmond, who is
supposed to play Sunday vs. Tampa Bay, becomes a factor, ``then
I'll concern myself with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Never one to rock the boat, Bledsoe didn't express outrage at
Vincent Brisby's parting, instead saying, ``I'm very comfortable
with Troy (Brown) and Terry (Glenn). I don't know Tony (Simmons) as
well, but he's a guy who's going to be out there a lot and we have
to develop something between us. (Chris) Calloway is also someone
I'm looking forward to throwing the ball to.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe loves the two-minute, no-huddle offense, but he knows it
would be taxing on his offense to do it all game. But in spots,
Bledsoe would love to implement it. Part of it depends on center
Damien Woody being able to make the snap properly, which allows
Bledsoe to set up properly. It's been a problem in the exhibition
season, and coach Bill Belichick has threatened that if Woody
doesn't get more fluid while still being able to make his block,
the team will scrap the shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do it and use the shotgun until it becomes a
problem,'' said Bledsoe, who earlier in his career felt
uncomfortable with it. ``It has been a problem in preseason games,
but if we can get through the next two without any problems with
the shotgun snaps, we'll use it. I prefer to be in the shotgun
because it gives me more separation in the rush. It improves my
field of vision. It's something we need to be able to do, but not
at the expense of creating turnovers out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite looking chaotic at times, Bledsoe said, the offense ``is
getting close.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terminology has come back rather quickly,'' he said.
``That's the No. 1 thing: You have to learn and be accustomed to
the language. As far as what we're trying to do this week, and with
the short week next week, we're moving toward fine-tuning how we're
going to use our personnel. Now we're moving closer to which things
we're going to use. With Vincent gone, that changes things.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bledsoe could, he would tell the fans to relax. It is only
the exhibition season. There are other teams around the league
having miserable times getting their offenses going, too, because
defenses generally are ahead of offenses now.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he cannot take the pounding of 50-something sacks, as he
did a year ago. He can't have Bruce Smith drill him on the first
play of a game, as he did in last week's exhibition in Washington,
setting the tone for the game and putting the thought in Bledsoe's
head that he must rush his throws so he won't eat the ball. On
Sunday he'll be watching Warren Sapp closely.
</P>
<P>
   Those are things Bledsoe will never bring up. He'll never blame
a soul. He will keep it all inside and take the beating from not
only the opposition but his own fans as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to go. I'm excited about it,'' he said. ``At this
point in my career, it's hard to get up for exhibition games, but
this one I am. We open the season against these guys and we have a
chance to get the upper hand going into that game. I'm excited.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
