<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT YOU'LL BE READING AT THE `BEACH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once in a lifetime comes a novel like ``Beach Blanket
Blockbuster,'' which is just as well, because there are so many
books like it already on the shelves, novels rife with triumph and
tragedy, peopled by characters who cope with human experiences,
wrestle with human emotions, and yet, through it all, still manage
to be something less than human.
</P>
<P>
   So brace yourself for ``Beach Blanket Blockbuster,'' the novel
everyone is reading this summer, or trying to read but never
finishing. It's the perfect summer book, because once you put it
down you never want to pick it up again.
</P>
<P>
   (``Lush, soporific.'' Publishers Weekly)
</P>
<P>
   It's a compelling tale of passion and intrigue, a grand and
sprawling account of how one desperate woman defied the odds to
write a novel that will be remembered as the book few people ever
managed to actually read in the summer of 2000, but one that proved
useful in so many surprising, life-enhancing ways _ as an eyeshade,
a cake stand, a pasta press, a 5-pound free weight, a headrest, a
bookmark cosy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beach Blanket Blockbuster'' tells the story of a woman who
ruthlessly seizes her future by the throat and throws together a
novel that will tug at your heartstrings, fire your imagination,
knock you down, pick you up again and leave you asking, ``What was
that all about?''
</P>
<P>
   (``Fatuous in the very best sense of the word,'' Kirkus Reviews)
</P>
<P>
   They said it couldn't be done. Or did they say it shouldn't be
done? It doesn't matter because she went ahead and did it anyway,
in spite of whatever it was they said. And she did it alone,
almost, with only the help of one of her multiple personalities,
Dee Dee, sometime advice columnist and full-time know-it-all.
</P>
<P>
   It's a white-hot story of romance, intrigue, and betrayal set in
the high stakes world of contemporary publishing, where authors'
egos are eviscerated and profit prevails over passion, except on
the dustjackets.
</P>
<P>
   (``Three thumbs up!!!'' The author's mother.)
</P>
<P>
   It's a saga of obsession, sabotage, and superstition in the
scorching tradition of every trashy bestseller you ever imagined
and then some. Teeming with all sorts of stuff, it's something
you'll immediately forget, and be glad you did, especially since
it's soon to be a major made-for-TV movie starring Tea Leoni, Neve
Campbell, Rhys Ifans, Udo Kier, Piper Perabo and a lot of other
actors whose names you have no idea how to pronounce.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the characters:
</P>
<P>
   The Author. Her novel has everything it takes to soar to the top
of bestseller lists including the three big ``S's'': sex, shopping,
and submarines. When she confronts the mysteries of her past lives
she discovers a fourth ``S,'' a secret that may prove her undoing.
</P>
<P>
   The Agent. A basically decent woman possessed by evil spirits
who refuses to settle for anything less than 20 percent. She
wrestles with her conscience daily, and wins.
</P>
<P>
   The Publisher. The company's plans to build an underwater
printing plant off the coast of exclusive Palm Beach hits a snag
when the Bureau of Fisheries and Wildlife Management declares the
area a publishing-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Bookseller. She learned life's lessons the hard way _ she
read about them. Will she be able to unload all those copies of
``Beach Blanket Blockbuster'' by summer's end?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
