r a BC-JOURNALIST-SHIELD-HNS     08-17 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNALIST-SHIELD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REPORTER CLEARED OF CONTEMPT THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The California Supreme Court has lifted the
threat of contempt of court from a reporter who refused to answer a
prosecutor's questions in a Marin County murder case. But the
court's action left news organizations fearful of a possible new
breach in California's shield law for journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The justices unanimously denied review of an appellate decision
in May that overturned a judge's contempt order and $1,000-a-day
fine against Dan Fost, now a San Francisco Chronicle staff writer.
The dispute involved an article Fost wrote about the murder case in
1997, when he worked for the Marin Independent Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Fost's lawyer, joined by an attorney representing several
newspapers and the California Newspaper Publishers Association,
said the ruling could jeopardize other reporters and asked the
state's high court to withdraw it as a precedent for other cases.
The court declined to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The murder case involved Darrell Hunter's trial for the shooting
death of Ronnie Small at a party in Marin City. Prosecution witness
Shayla Davis testified she had seen only one man break into the
apartment, but Fost quoted her as telling him three or four men had
burst in.
</P>
<P>
   Called as a defense witness, Fost said he had quoted Davis
accurately. But when the prosecutor tried to cross-examine him
about the circumstances of the interview, Fost refused to answer,
citing the shield law, which prohibits reporters from being held in
contempt for refusing to disclose confidential sources or
unpublished material.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge John Sutro held Fost in contempt of court
but was overruled by the 1st District Court of Appeal, which said
Sutro had failed to make the findings required to overcome a
reporter's protection under the shield law: that the evidence is
needed to protect the defendant's right to a fair trial and could
not be obtained from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   But the court also said a reporter might be required to answer a
prosecution's questions in a future case.
</P>
<P>
   If a reporter answers defense questions about a published
article and then refuses to answer the prosecutor's questions about
unpublished material, the prosecutor can ask the judge to strike
the earlier testimony from the case and deprive the defense of
evidence, Presiding Justice J. Anthony Kline said in the 3-0
ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4560 &Cx1f; tdt-z
