<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RACHEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPINSTER FICTION' PUTS ON A NEW FACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MONICA L. WILLIAMS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
RACHEL'S HOLIDAY 
By Marian Keyes 
Morrow, 624 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Critics weren't too kind to Marian Keyes the last time around.
Her second novel, ``Lucy Sullivan Is Getting Married,'' a success
with book buyers, was a failure with reviewers. Her eponymous
heroine was quickly labeled a poor clone of Helen Fielding's
irresistible Bridget Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But Keyes knew that Fielding was on to something. Publishers
were scrambling to turn out tales of the badly behaving
30-something single woman. This fashionable ``spinster fiction''
was a roaring success, and Keyes, Melissa Bank, Jane Green, and
others cashed in on the discovery, even if the publishing
industry's answer to Ally McBeal was more fun than substance.
</P>
<P>
   Bits of Bridget resurface in Keyes's latest work, ``Rachel's
Holiday,'' a hilarious but poignant novel that is already a
bestseller in England. While ``Rachel's Holiday'' is not the usual
frantic-single-woman comedy, it is a coming-of-age journey of love
and self-discovery. This first-person narrative gives a
behind-the-scenes glimpse at life in a drug rehabilitation center.
The protagonist, Rachel Walsh, has a penchant for recreational
drugs and recreational sex, especially with men sporting tight
leather pants. Like the predecessors of her genre, Rachel is a hip
single woman who spends inordinate amounts of time obsessing over
men and weight. But for her, life in the fast lane is a bit too
slow. Luckily, New York City is the perfect place for the
transplant from Dublin to indulge _ or overindulge. But 2 1/2 years
after moving to New York, Rachel gets a painful lesson in what it
means to have too much fun.
</P>
<P>
   When she wakes up in a hospital emergency room to find herself
diagnosed as a suicidal drug addict, she is outraged. As if being
dumped by her wonderful boyfriend were not enough, her quirky
family flies in from Dublin to hustle her straight to the
Cloisters, Ireland's equivalent of the Betty Ford Clinic. She is
furious at the idea of being institutionalized with a bunch of
addicts, but admits that her life had a way of veering out of
control. ``I had long stopped believing that the God who had been
assigned to me was a benign old guy with long hair and a beard. He
was more like a celestial stand-up comic, and my life was the
showcase he used to amuse the other gods.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad could the Cloisters be? Hundreds of rock stars had been
admitted to the converted monastery to go tepid turkey. Maybe it
would be OK to leave New York for a life of steam rooms, Jacuzzis,
massage, mud wraps, and fruit salad. And, of course, the Cloisters
would have a gym where she could tone up the abs. Maybe people like
her, the ones without serious substance abuse problems, could
wander down in the evenings to the local pub.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of seaweed and saunas, though, Rachel gets chores at the
crack of dawn, tubby middle-aged men in brown acrylic sweaters,
hours of excruciating group therapy, and quarters more like a
Dickensian orphanage than a luxury spa. She's ready to make her
great escape until she meets sweet, wonderful Chris. Chris has a
complicated past, but his chlorine-blue eyes and earnest manner are
enough to make Rachel believe she may have met her perfect match.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes's third novel is her most serious, and yet her funniest.
She deftly builds on the characters introduced in ``Watermelon,''
her grand first novel. Her touch in ``Rachel's Holiday'' is
sometimes heavier, and the narrative is a bit long, but what easily
could have been a grim shelf-warmer turns out to be a delightful
page turner, propelled by its unforgettable heroine and her
supporting cast of eccentric sidekicks. Readers will grow to love
the exasperating and beguiling heroine as Rachel finds her way
through her bittersweet self-discovery.
</P>
<P>
   After 600 pages and months of drug rehab, readers may expect a
dynamic denouement. This is where Keyes falls short. Instead, the
ending is a bit too convenient and predictable. A marvelous journey
is disappointingly wrapped up in a one-page epilogue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
