<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGING THE ONCOMING BRITNEY BANDWAGON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you have tickets to take your 6- or 7- or 8- or 9-year-old
daughter to see Britney Spears, throw them away and think of it as
money well-spent in the effort to reclaim your daughter's
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Spears's lyrics are so bad; they're suggestive but
not immoral or evil. Her bumps, grinds, and pouts are provocative
but not over the edge. Even her clothes, which often do go over the
edge, can also be schoolgirl All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem: If her peppiness, catchy tunes, and
wholesome clothes tell 7-year-olds, ``I'm just like you!'' what do
her vampy outfits say? If a 6-year-old can see that whatever Spears
does translates to lots of attention and therefore is cool, can she
also understand that sexy is just one of many ways for a female to
be, along with kind or strong or smart?
</P>
<P>
   No way, say psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   Girls under 10 don't have the cognitive equipment to decode the
subtleties of Spears's messages or movements. All that time they
spend watching her videos, singing her songs and dressing like her?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because they're confused. In very basic ways, they can't
make sense of Britney, so they put all this energy into trying to
figure her out,'' says early childhood educator Diane Levin of
Wheelock College.
</P>
<P>
   That leads to perhaps an even more serious problem. In idolizing
Spears, young fans may be skipping an immportant developmental
phase of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus on her takes time away from what girls this age
typically work on: friendship, values, and safe, altruistic,
heartfelt love,'' says psychologist Catherine Steiner-Adair of the
Harvard University Eating Disorders Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Moreno of North Andover, who is a proud 6 3/4, doesn't see
it that way, of course. ``I like Britney because she looks pretty
and she writes down nice music,'' she says. ``I like the clothes
she wears and her style. I like her movements. I'd like to be like
her when I grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes her mother cringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when my daughter is developing her sense of who she
is, I worry she's getting a warped view of what it means to be a
girl,'' says Bridget Moreno. (Conscious of this, she's careful to
set limits around what Emily absorbs of pop culture: There's no
unsupervised TV, for instance, and no cable.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Being a girl
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Learning what it means to be a girl is a process that begins in
the toddler years when a child imitates behaviors of the same-sex
parent. At 4 and 5, cause-and-effect enters her thinking: ``I'm a
girl because I wear a dress.'' At 6 or 7, a girl is still partially
in that place, says developmental psychologist Elizabeth Debold, a
gender development researcher in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's looking for extreme examples of what it means to be a
girl to accentuate the differences between boys and girls,'' she
says. ``That's why Barbie is so popular at this age and why Britney
is, too. In that sense, Britney and Barbie fit the same mold.''
Indeed, there is a Britney Spears Barbie doll.
</P>
<P>
   What also fuels girls' interest is that Spears is marketed
directly at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since `Teenage Ninja Mutant Turtles,' there's been a
steady escalation of marketing teenage issues to young children,''
says Levin, who is the author of ``Remote Control Childhood?''
(NAEYC Press).
</P>
<P>
   In the process, adults have come to accept as normal what once
upset and shocked us, including the marketing of sexuality to young
children. Which can explain why plenty of responsible, caring
parents might buy tickets to a Britney Spears concert.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stamp of approval
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking our daughter to a concert, though, isn't just a matter of
buying into the cultural escalation, says Levin; it's also giving
her a giant, personal ``This-is-for-you-honey'' stamp of approval.
Because we're so important to young children, that can add to the
pressure a girl already feels.
</P>
<P>
   The culture is telling her ``to think that the way to gain
attention is by how you look, not by how you relate to others,''
says psychologist Linda Hartling of the Centers for Women at
Wellesley College. She specializes in risk prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a girl skips the step when she learns she's capable of
having relationships because she's a kind, caring person, she's
more susceptible later on to thinking that a sexy body is what she
needs for a relationship,'' says Hartling.
</P>
<P>
   This also is typically the age when a girl begins to discover
the athletic power in her body.
</P>
<P>
   ``She sees she can run like the wind or jump rope five times
through the alphabet,'' says Steiner-Adair. ``This enables a girl
to see her body as a whole entity, not as body parts.'' It's an
important developmental step, she says, because it gives girls a
broad relationship to their body.
</P>
<P>
   Spears crowds this out, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``She pushes them to tune in to body parts instead of the
whole,'' says Steiner-Adair.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget Moreno sees it happen when Emily looks in the mirror and
says, ``My thighs are fat.'' Steiner-Adair hears it in young girls'
conversations about whether Spears has had a ``boob job,'' a hot
topic among radio DJs. ``That girls this age even have this on
their radar screen is a distortion of childhood,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preoccupation with looks
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The preoccupation with how you look may account for the onset of
eating disorders in 10- and 11-year-old girls, researchers say, as
well as an increase in early onset of other risky behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 10-year-old in a belly-shirt who looks sexy is putting
herself out there in a way that says to men and boys, `I'm ready to
go,' '' says educator Amy P. Vorenberg , a veteran third-grade
teacher and now head of the lower school at the Shady Hill School
in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The younger a girl is when she begins to internalize the
message, the more power it has over her. ``They don't have the
intellectual capacity to argue with themselves, so it's absorbed
more deeply,'' says Debold. She is the author of ``Mother-Daughter
Revolution'' (Bantam).
</P>
<P>
   Steiner-Adair urges parents to shield young girls from exposure
to Spears or anyone like her for as long as possible.
Unfortunately, as Bridget Moreno has seen, exposure often occurs in
spite of our vigilance. ``Britney is part of children's social
currency,'' says Vorenberg. Even if it's not on your TV set, ``it's
on the playground and in the backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, there are ways to blunt the impact:
</P>
<P>
   --Say no. Even if she puts up a fuss, ``A girl 6 to 9 will be
satisfied and deep down inside, relieved, to have you say, `This is
too grown up for you,' '' says Steiner-Adair.
</P>
<P>
   --Find positive things to say about Spears: ``I can see why kids
think she's cool; she's so young and so upbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   --Don't censor her completely _ ``I'm not saying you can't sing
her songs, they're really catchy'' _ but set clear limits. Moreno,
for instance, won't let Emily buy belly-shirts or CDs.
</P>
<P>
   --Watch your tone. ``You don't want to have a lot of heat in
your voice,'' says Steiner-Adair. ``Children will tune out.''
</P>
<P>
   If you decide you aren't going to take your daughter to the
concert, for sure there will be unhappiness to tolerate, and for
sure, it will be hard to take. Steiner-Adair's advice is to tell
her you've made a mistake and you're sorry: `` `I didn't realize I
was taking you to see someone who is so sexy; she's icky. After you
stop being disappointed, let's find something else to do together.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Vorenberg urges parents to have deliberate conversations about
what it means to be a strong and powerful girl.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno had one one night recently as she tucked Emily into bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, I don't think I'm innocent,'' her daughter said.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Moreno recognized that as a line from Spears's song,
``Oops! . . . I Did It Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her being innocent was a good thing,'' she says. ``That
it means you aren't guilty of doing anything bad and that you can
look at nature and appreciate it. And then I told her, `In that
song, she's playing with a person's emotions, pretending to be a
friend when she isn't. That's not a quality I want in my friends.
What about you?''
</P>
<P>
   It was a conversation that was exactly developmentally where her
daughter ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BRITNEY TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --By 10 or 11, interest in Britney Spears tends to wane (or not
ignite) because a girl either sees how unreal Spears is _ ``Nobody
is that perfect'' _ or is frightened by her: ``Is this how I have
to be?''
</P>
<P>
   --Because Britney Spears is young enough, at 18, to be a girl's
father's daughter, fathers who say she's sexy or talk about her
(``I heard she had breast implants'') give young girls a confusing
and scary message.
</P>
<P>
   --Expose your daughters to varied female role models.
</P>
<P>
   --Learn something about Spears so you can help your daughter see
her as a real person. For instance, ``She's been dancing since she
was 3 and spent her life doing talent shows and TV commercials; I
wonder what that's like?''
</P>
<P>
   --Ask your daughter why she likes Britney: ``What attracts you
to her? Is it her energy? Her confidence? Her clothes?''
</P>
<P>
   --Have conversations with a son, even if he doesn't like Spears:
``Our culture makes such a big deal about sexiness and bodies that
I want to make sure you know that I think it's never OK to like a
girl just for the way she looks.''
</P>
<P>
   --Get to know the parents of your daughter's friends so your
girls are all getting similar messages about Spears and the values
she represents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Barbara F. Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
