<HEADLINE>
DON'T DEFEAT POLARIZED PLUG'S PURPOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a small night light that plugs directly into an
outlet, but one of its prongs is a little wider than its neighbor,
so it is difficult to plug it in. Can I file it down to match the
smaller one, so it will fit?
</P>
<P>
   G.S., Jamaica Plain, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. No. The prongs are a different width to make sure the light
is plugged in the correct way to maintain polarity. It is not a
good idea to trim down a prong. Besides, if you find you cannot
push the light into the socket, turn it 180 degrees and try again.
If the outlet is not really, really old, the prongs will fit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wall shingles are 70 years old and not curling. The paint
is thick and cracked, but there is no peeling. I have heard of a
Power Shaver, an electric tool for scraping paint. Or should I
pressure-wash? I want to repaint, but not necessarily get down to
the bare wood.
</P>
<P>
   JOAN KASPRIK, Winchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Power Shaver or a good, coarse power-sanding is your best
bet. Either method will get down to bare wood or just take off some
of the paint. Then you can prime and paint, and hope it lasts
another umpteen years.
</P>
<P>
   Power washing is good for some projects, but not for yours,
because it will not remove paint that is intact, only loose stuff.
And, there is a chance of water saturating the wood; you would have
to wait several days for this water to evaporate. Power washing can
also get water behind the shingles; if that happens, they could
take months to dry out, and in the meantime the shingles could rot
out from that steady moisture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The ceramic tiles on my concrete bathroom floor are 4 by 4
inches, and when I walk I hear a popping sound. They are installed
with thin-set mortar. What is this popping sound, and how can I
stop it? Is it dangerous?
</P>
<P>
   KATHRYN JOHNSON, Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Some of the tiles are loose, and that popping sound is a
double click, the sound of your foot hitting the tile, then the
tile hitting the floor. It is not dangerous, especially since the
tiles are on concrete. If they were on a wood floor, that floor
could leak water.
</P>
<P>
   You can live with them until you are ready to chip out the
grout; lift the tiles; scrape off grout and old thin-set mortar
from the tile and floor; apply new thin-set, a bit thicker than
originally; and relay the tiles.
</P>
<P>
   If some of the loose tiles are around the toilet, you will have
to lift the toilet before lifting the tiles underneath. When you
are ready to have the toilet put back, it will need a new wax ring.
So, call your friendly plumber.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I spilled gasoline on my mother-in-law's asphalt driveway. It
created a circle darker than the asphalt. Soap and water did no
good. Is there anything I can do to disguise the mark?
</P>
<P>
   S.D., Beverly, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There must be a law in heaven that says you always hurt the
ones you love. I know I am not innocent, either, but can't think of
any incidents, except when my daughter ran over her cousin's
motorcycle. That's nothing, except that the car was a BMW.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds as if your mother-in-law is taking it in stride or
doesn't even know about it, so your attitude is admirable. The
gasoline is long gone, but the stain remains. It might weather out
over a few months. Or, put down a driveway sealer _ which the
handyman has often contended is mostly cosmetic. You have to do the
whole driveway, though; just a section will make Ma suspicious.
Regardless, she is going to say, ``Now why is he doing that?''
Trying to spray-paint the spot to lighten it up will end in
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house is 18 years old and the basement is damp. How can I
keep it dry, except with a dehumidifier?
</P>
<P>
   EILEEN ZELLER, Swampscott, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. On damp days, when the humidity is sky high outdoors as well
as in, is the time to use the dehumidifier, usually in July and
August. All the rest of the time, and on dry days, ventilate,
ventilate, ventilate: Open windows, screen and secure them, and
leave them open in May, June, September, and October. Put a fan in
a window to get the moist air out. Air conditioning will also work
because it is a dehumidifier, but is not practical unless the
basement is lived in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
