<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Includes toughest plants text table.)  
 FOREIGN INVADERS THREATEN NATIVE SPECIES IN THE WILD  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all people, gardeners know best how quickly plants can get
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   We've all had plants that took advantage of our hesitant
hospitality. There's that multiflora rosebush that sprouted
unbidden and was such a hit with the mockingbirds that you let it
stay, and now it's big and thorny enough to guard Sleeping Beauty's
castle. Meanwhile, baby rose canes are reaching out to grab you
from every unpatroled niche, spread by those ungrateful
mockingbirds.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you tell an overly aggressive and invasive plant from
a desirable one?
</P>
<P>
   This is not an easy question. You don't have to graduate from
West Point to be able to weed a garden, but you do need to be able
to recognize the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, the most important war on weeds today is being
waged not in our yards but in conservation land and along
shorelines, where invasive species are taking over about 10 million
acres nationally each year. ``An average of 40 percent of the
vegetation in Massachusetts now is invasive species,'' said Sharon
McGregor of the state's Executive Office of Environmental Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible example of this is the miles of purple
loosestrife in bloom in many of our wetlands. Twenty years ago
these were diverse habitats, then almost overnight, they became
solid purple.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like `The Invasion of the Body Snatchers,' '' said Tim
Simmons, a restoration ecologist with the state's Natural Heritage
and Endangered Species Program. ``Overnight you realize you have a
problem. We don't know when a new plant that existed in sparse
amounts will suddenly explode. They seem to reach a critical mass
and go crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking in most woods near a highway today and you'll find
yourself tripping on honeysuckle and bittersweet vines busy
smothering trees, or being stuck by increasingly impenetrable
thickets of thorny multiflora roses, buckthorns, and Japanese
barberries. Bamboo-like Japanese knotweed has been around for 100
years, but in the last 10 it's spread to every major river system
in Massachusetts. Like the worst invasives, it pushes out all other
vegetation, rendering natural areas useless for most wildlife and
recreation.
</P>
<P>
   One irony is that many of these invaders originated in our own
gardens. We usually think of our garden plants as fragile,
cultivated creatures under relentless attack from wild weeds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No enemies here
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the opposite is also true. The wild plants of forest and
field are being overwhelmed by some of the most aggressive
cultivated plants, especially those imported from other parts of
the world that don't have insects and diseases here to keep them in
check.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is this truer than among homes close to conservation
land and waterways. It's a status symbol today to clear a lot and
build a house snug against protected land so you don't have to
worry about other builders impacting your privacy and natural view.
But the plants landscaping these new homes pose a threat to those
very natural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every new home that goes in gets two Norway maples, three
Japanese barberries, and four burning bushes,'' said Chris
Mattrick, an invasive plant specialist with the New England Wild
Flower Society in Framingham, Mass., citing three common nursery
plants he sees as threats to native plant communities because of
their aggressive self-seeding.
</P>
<P>
   But won't nature just find a new balance? After all, most of our
ancestors weren't native to these shores either. Isn't this just
evolution?
</P>
<P>
   These are actually profound questions, because what's happening
to southern New England's wild areas is happening all over the
world as global trade facilitates the spread of species.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Learning from Hawaii
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To put it simply, some ecologists think we may end up with the
same plants, animals, and bugs all over the world, as the toughest
arrivals invade new areas and overwhelm the daintier local flora
and fauna, as has already happened in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, plants from India and Brazil are not going to take
over Boston because the climate is different. Most of the invasive
life-forms we see here are from similar temperate regions such as
Northern Europe, China, and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   What's undesirable about this scenario, of course, is mass
extinctions. The world would become an even more homogenized place,
with a relatively few supersuccessful species circling the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Not only would there be a Gap store at every mall, but Norway
maples in every forest, which, locally speaking, would be a letdown
for people who like the orange fall foliage of our retreating
native sugar maples, not to mention maple syrup on their pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   The most hopeful strategy is to import some natural enemies of
invasives. This is called ``biological control,'' and it's a
growing field, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lythrum-eating beetles
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lythrum, or loosestrife, is native to Europe, and Bernd Blossey
at Cornell University has imported two beetles that eat lythrum
there and have begun eating it here. Should widespread release of
the beetles win USDA approval, they are predicted to bring lythrum
under control _ in several decades.
</P>
<P>
   But in the short term, what can gardeners do to help protect
wild areas in their neighborhoods?
</P>
<P>
   They can remove invasive plants from their properties so they
aren't jumping-off points, said Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   He advises homeowners to get rid of their multiflora rose,
Norway maple, Oriental bittersweet, porcelain berry, Morrow's
honeysuckle, as well as Tatarian, Amur and Japanese honeysuckles,
burning bush, also known as winged euonymus, Japanese knotweed,
autumn olive, black locust, black swallowwort, common and Japanese
barberry (including those colored varieties), common and glossy
buckthorn, garlic mustard, goutweed, also known as bishop's-weed,
purple loosestrife, and yellow water iris (Iris pseudocorus).
</P>
<P>
   Other plants Simmons suggests gardeners avoid, as they may
eventually become problems here, include kiwi vine, rugosa rose,
Japanese and common hedge privet, Japanese hops, creeping
buttercup, chervil (Anthriscus sylvestris), Lysimachia nummularia,
silver lace vine, sycamore maple, tree of heaven, wild thyme, white
mulberry and Western catalpa trees, and Myosotis scorpioides.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vulnerable habitats
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some people telling me they can't even grow some of
these plants, so how can they be a problem? It depends on where you
live and the types of habitats around you. Flood plains, woodlands,
and wetlands are particularly vulnerable,'' said Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, individuals dumping yard wastes in natural areas are a
real problem,'' Simmons added.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these plants also have berries that are spread by birds,
but a recent Illinois study indicates that nesting is less
successful in landscapes dominated by invasives, said Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   Mattrick calls buckthorn berries ``junk food for birds because
they're sweet, but they have little nutritional value. They just go
right through them.''
</P>
<P>
   Invasives are supertough, so just occasional cutting back
usually only encourages their roots to grow larger and the plants
more vigorous, said Mattrick. The root must be killed.
</P>
<P>
   If a plant is too large to pull by hand, the best way to uproot
medium-size shrubs and small trees is with a weed wrench, a large
lever that almost effortlessly pops the entire root systems of
honeysuckles, buckthorns, and barberries out of the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Invasives can come back to life after you think you've killed
them, so don't toss them aside. They will probably just reroot. And
don't add them to usable compost piles. ``Just create a separate
pile for them where you can check them occasionally for rerooting.
Or let them cook in black plastic trash bags for a month in the sun
until they turn to mush,'' advised Mattrick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recommended herbicides
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Herbicides are the easiest way to kill roots, and any homeowner
is free to apply herbicides on his or her property, provided
they're handled responsibly. The two herbicides that Mattrick
recommends are glyphosate and triclopyr. ``These get everything we
need to get done,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Glyphosate, which breaks down into harmless molecules in 40 to
60 days, is the active ingredient in Monsanto's popular Round-Up,
the workhorse of herbicides, and Rodeo, which is safer to use
around wetlands. Triclopyr is the active ingredient in Weed-Be-Gone
and Brush-Be-Gone, which unlike glyphosate is effective on most
woody plants except Oriental bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   But Mattrick always wears hospital gloves inside elbow-length
pesticide gloves, eye protection, and a dust mask when spraying. He
also wears long pants and shirts with long sleeves, which are
washed separately from family laundry. He also carries an eye wash.
</P>
<P>
   Among the better tools are ``weed wands'' that allow you to
touch an herbicide-soaked sponge to herbaceous weeds such as
chervil and garlic mustard while standing.
</P>
<P>
   Chopping a few gashes into tree trunks in late fall when sap is
flowing back into the roots, then painting the wounds with
herbicide, is effective for large, problem trees such as buckthorn,
tree of heaven, black locust, and Norway maple.
</P>
<P>
   For the homeowner with a woodlot or a large problem there are
industrial strength tools such as ``hypohatchets,'' which can chop
gashes into the tree while injecting it with glyphosate, and the
``EZject,'' which drives small pellets of herbicide into tree
trunks.
</P>
<P>
   Ridding even a modest backyard of potentially invasive plants
can take years, warned Simmons. Though he spends his days
patrolling state lands for invasives, he says, ``I'm still in the
process of eradicating all these plants from my own yard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TOUGHEST OF THE TOUGH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to Chris Mattrick and the State Division of Fisheries
and Wildlife's upcoming ``Guide to Invasive Plants in
Massachusetts'' (which, when published, will be available by
writing to the state's Natural Heritage and Endangered Species
Program, Route 135, Westborough, MA 01581), some of the most
difficult plants to kill include:
</P>
<P>
   --Barberry: These prickly plants must be pulled up by the roots.
Use a weed wrench for fully grown shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   --Buckthorn: Cut stems and apply herbicide to the stumps in
winter.
</P>
<P>
   --Garlic mustard: This garlic-smelling biennial with four white
petals outcompetes native wildflowers in shady woodlands. Hand-pull
or apply herbicide to rosettes of basal leaves during the winter,
and repeat for two to five years, as new seeds sprout.
</P>
<P>
   --Honeysuckles: Pull Lornicera morrowii, L. tatarica, L.
maackii, and L. xbella by hand or pull these shallow-rooted shrubs
with a weed wrench.
</P>
<P>
   --Japanese knotweed: A minimum of four cuttings for several
years are required to deplete underground rhizomes. Occasional
sporadic cutting back may be counterproductive. For faster results,
pour herbicide into the hollow canes after cutting.
</P>
<P>
   --Multiflora rose: It blooms once a year with clusters of many
white flowers, and produces tiny red hips. The stems look feathery
at the base of each leaflet. Hand-pull young plants. Use a machete,
not a chain saw, to cut through thorny branches to get to the trunk
in winter, when it can be pulled with a weed wrench, or cut and
paint the cut stem with herbicide.
</P>
<P>
   --Oriental bittersweet: This fast-growing vine can choke young
trees and smother vegetation, interfering with the natural
succession of forest regeneration. Because of its many underground
runners, it often requires the application of glyphosate to freshly
cut stems at the time of the first killing frost, usually in early
October, to destroy established plants. Because the bright-orange
berries are viable, do not use them in holiday decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Purple loosestrife: Uproot when first seen because it is almost
impossible to remove once established. Each plant produces up to 2
million seeds. Nursery hybrids are not necessarily sterile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
