<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4564 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-EYESOFTAMMYFAYE-     08-17 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EYESOFTAMMYFAYE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELLE OF THE BAWL: DOCUMENTARY LOOKS AT TAMMY FAYE WITH APPROVING
EYES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in this documentary, Tammy Faye Bakker Messner ruminates
on one of her many misfortunes, and predictably enough, the tears
flow and mascara runs. What's unexpected is the way filmmakers
Randy Barbato and Fenton Bailey treat the moment: Rather than mock,
they're almost too earnest, letting Messner indulge in her sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   It's just sorrow, though, and not self-pity, and that's the
portrait ``The Eyes of Tammy Faye'' paints of Messner: a courageous
survivor who steadfastly declines to judge anyone who has wronged
her or to mourn the misfires in her past. It's a riches-to-rags
story, with the familiar arc of Tammy Faye and Jim Bakker's rise
with their PTL empire, their fall amid sexual and financial
scandals in the '80s, and Tammy Faye's recovery through her second
marriage to Bakker friend and aide Roe Messner, who would endure a
financial scandal of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Some early reviews have criticized this Sundance hit as too
kitschy, and with Messner, some kitsch was inevitable. But aside
from the sock puppets who, a la Babe, introduce the various
``chapters,'' the movie is a surprisingly respectful and
straightforward _ albeit hardly objective _ look at its subject.
Barbato and Bailey laud Tammy Faye for being among the first
televangelists to open the door to AIDS sufferers and homosexuals,
and portray ex-husband Jim Bakker as humble and penitent. Most
other people in the film are cast as opportunists, whether they be
Jessica Hahn (whose one-night stand with Jim Bakker helped lead to
his decline) or Jerry Falwell (whose takeover of PTL is portrayed
as hostile).
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Messner maintains a sense of humor and a refusal to
be seen as a victim. Barbato and Bailey's film may be lopsided, but
it remains eye-opening; in a climate in which the Bible is too
often quoted as a means to support mean-spiritedness, Messner
proves that there are still people who love not only their
neighbors, but their enemies as well.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
