<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4567 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-ROADSHOW-ART-BOS     08-17 1652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-ROADSHOW-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 IF IT'S `ANTIQUES ROADSHOW,' YOU DON'T WANT TO THINK TUPPERWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Here are a few tips from the experts for the 7,000
lucky ticket holders planning to tote a treasure or two to an
``Antiques Roadshow'' taping.
</P>
<P>
   Leave the Hummels at home.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for the Tupperware.
</P>
<P>
   And the black velvet Elvis makes three.
</P>
<P>
   People actually bring such things to be appraised on the
``Antiques Roadshow''?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they do, says Rudy Franchi, owner of the Nostalgia
Factory, a gallery specializing in movie memorabilia, in Boston's
North End. Franchi, an expert on books, manuscripts, and
collectibles has been an ``Antiques Roadshow'' appraiser for all of
the PBS show's five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Appraisers try to keep a sense of humor,'' he says, ``but it
can be trying when I've been at it all day, and it's 3 o'clock in
the afternoon, and I've just seen my fifth piece of Tupperware, and
somebody has just dumped the contents of their sewing drawer on my
table.''
</P>
<P>
   All that can change in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then somebody will bring in something fantastic,'' Franchi
says, ``and it will all be worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Antiques Roadshow'' is produced by WGBH-TV and underwritten by
the Chubb Group, insurers of collectibles and fine arts. It is
PBS's highest-ranked prime-time show, with 14 million viewers each
week. When the Boston Herald revealed last year that two of the
show's appraisers had perpetrated a fraud on a segment of a 1997
show, the scandal didn't diminish the ``Roadshow'' 's popularity
one whit. The appraisers responsible for the scam were dismissed,
the segment was cut from the tape of the show, and the ``Roadshow''
moved on, virtually unscathed, and seemingly unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has history, mystery, romance,'' appraiser Colleene Fesko
says, attempting to explain the ``Roadshow'' 's appeal. Fesko, a
specialist in paintings at Skinner, the Boston appraisal and
auction firm, says she once described the ``Roadshow'' to a friend
as `` `Baywatch' with Meissen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It also has the appeal of a game show,'' she adds. ``Anyone
can be a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Roadshow'' fans are familiar with the big scores. A Tiffany
lamp bought in the 1960s for $125. Estimated worth:
$80,000-$125,000. A bad painting of the Titanic that was valueless,
apart from a luncheon menu from the doomed ship affixed to the
back. Estimated worth of the menu: $75,000-$100,000. A card table,
bought for $25 at a garage sale. Estimated worth: $200,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   These, and other stories of ``Roadshow'' discoveries, have got
millions of people sorting through their belongings, looking for
hidden treasures. Jamie Mercier, managing editor of New England
Antiques Journal, says the ``Roadshow'' has had a significant
impact on the antiques business in general. ``More people are going
into their attics and cellars and dusting things off and looking at
them with a new set of eyes,'' she said. ``It's probably driving
the prices of antiques up because people have great expectations,
which are sometimes justified and sometimes not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wave of the future''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mercier said that the show has also piqued interest in
appraisals. ``More people are willing to bring things in to be
appraised,'' she said. ``And at antiques shows they have more
appraisers on site. It seems to be the wave of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston is the next-to-last stop on the ``Roadshow's'' nine-city
summer tour, which has taken it to Denver, Charleston, and Las
Vegas, among other places. The free tickets for a Boston event,
distributed by Ticketmaster, were made available July 8 and were
gone the next day.
</P>
<P>
   This season the ``Roadshow'' has a new host, Daniel Elias of
Lincoln, Mass., a contemporary art dealer who has a gallery in
Boston's Allston section. He replaces Chris Jussel, who presented
the show in its first four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Elias says his wife, Karen Keane, an expert in Americana at
Skinner, urged him to try out for the host job. She has been an
appraiser on the ``Roadshow'' since it started. Elias says he
hesitated to audition. ``But then I started thinking about the fact
that there are parallels between what I do in the gallery and what
they do on the `Roadshow,' '' he says. ``One of the challenges for
an art dealer is to get people not only to look, but to listen to
what the artist is saying. `Antiques Roadshow' does that very
effectively. They get people to listen with great interest to the
objects that show up at the events.''
</P>
<P>
   Elias says his first season with the show has been an adventure.
``There's so much out there. People have this tremendous amount of
stuff; it's impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally it's stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in Tulsa and this guy brought in his TV stand,'' Elias
recalls. ``Turns out it's a 1765 John Cogswell cabinet worth
$150,000. And he has his TV on it at the end of his bed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of submissions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was a perfect ``Roadshow'' story, but such stories are rare.
During each taping the appraisers look at thousands of items. Of
these, only about 50 are taped for two shows from each city. And
many of those are never used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antiques Roadshow'' is patterned after the British show of the
same name, one of the highest-rated television programs in Britain
since its debut 22 years ago. The PBS program uses 60-70
appraisers, covering more than 20 specialties. None of them is
paid, and each picks up the cost of his or her own travel and
lodging. The exposure is good for their businesses, and has even
made celebrities of some of the appraisers, perhaps especially the
identical twin furniture experts Leigh and Leslie Keno, who
recently signed a book contract rumored to be in the high six
figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on the show has seen their careers blossom,''
Franchi says. ``I think of us as like the Hawaiian missionaries who
went out to do good and ended up doing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Difficult personalities
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ``Roadshow'' appraisers' task is not easy. They must work
quickly, under a great deal of pressure. And they have to cope with
difficult personalities. ``Some people get really stroppy when they
think they have something of value and you tell them they don't,''
says Franchi. ``They have some family heirloom and stories have
built up about it, how it was handed down from Thomas Jefferson to
FDR, who gave it to their uncle Waldo.''
</P>
<P>
   The appraisers work their way through thousands of items that
have only ``sentimental value'' _ ``Roadshow''-speak for worthless,
or close to it _ to find the good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The recent visit to Las Vegas produced scores of Elvis-related
artifacts. ``Panties, scarves, menus, acres of Elvis stuff,''
Franchi said. ``If he really signed it all he never would have had
time to ingest drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fesko says that one man who brought in an oil painting of Elvis
to the Las Vegas event refused to believe that it had no value.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's old,'' he protested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's from the '60s,'' Fesko told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's really old,'' the man insisted.
</P>
<P>
   This season, tickets for the show are timed at 90-minute
intervals to cut down on the crush. Ticket holders are limited to
two items. And they must bring at least one item. The producers
hope to discourage ``Roadshow'' groupies, who show up empty-handed
and wander around for hours, observing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes sort of an event, and people will grab anything
just to show up,'' says Carol Prisant, author of ``Antiques
Roadshow Primer'' (Workman, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How it works
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Their eagerness is understandable, Prisant says, because the
production of the show is interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first come in there's a sort of triage table with
people who tell you where to go,'' Prisant says. ``Is it Asian?
Metal? Black memorabilia? Books? Whatever. They give you a ticket
and you get in line at the appropriate table.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the appraiser thinks your item is worthy of a segment
taping, the appraiser quickly finds one of the producers and sells
the story. If the producer agrees, you're immediately parted from
the appraiser and taken to the green room. That way, when you're
taped for the show, it's fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Prisant's book should be required reading for anybody who hopes
to attend the ``Roadshow.'' She offers suggestions about what sort
of things to bring for appraisal _ and what not to bring.
</P>
<P>
   Hummels are a ``Roadshow'' joke. ``The appraisers say that the
more carefully the tissue paper is unwrapped the more certain they
are it's a Hummel,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Prisant, too, has seen her share of Tupperware at the
``Roadshow'' while researching the book. ``There is a price guide;
some people collect it,'' she says. ``But some people collect glass
insulators or barbed wire.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Items to avoid
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the frequently seen but valueless items she's observed
people bring to the show lately are samovars, elaborately carved
furniture, and trays with butterflies trapped in plastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems such a shame that people would wait all that time and
stand in line and bring the wrong thing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, Prisant suggests bringing something old,
with signs of wear, preferably something with a mark, a label, a
signature. ``But not the country of origin because that means it's
not old,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope in writing the book was that it would help people
choose the right thing to bring. Also, they could read the book
while standing in line. It would give them something to do, and
help them appraise the things brought by the people around them.
Because that's what everybody does while they're waiting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
