<HEADLINE>
A FUNGUS AMONG US! WAYS TO KILL IT AND KEEP IT AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you read about the biggest living thing in the world, miles
and miles long and thousands of feet deep, enjoying life under
Oregon?
</P>
<P>
   It's not a plant, although some seaweeds are huge, and it
certainly is not a mutated ant or any kind of animal. It is a
fungus, a 'shroom pof sorts, which is probably the only living
thing that can grow so big. It's a scientific curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   That's good, because other fungi are driving us all bananas.
Chief among those is mold, often misidentified as mildew, and it's
eating us out of house and home.
</P>
<P>
   The wet summer has aggravated the problem, providing wet
surfaces for the mold to grow on, on siding, foundations, and
roofs, and in basements. Mold spores, which are microscopic
``seeds,'' are flying around everywhere, waiting to land on a damp
surface and grow. &QL; 
 &QL; 
It'll grow anywhere &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mold will grow on anything _ wood, cloth, paper, plaster, brick,
concrete, vinyl, paint, stain, and sealer _ except glass and metal,
and even metal becomes a victim on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Shiny objects resist mold growth because the spores have
difficulty sticking to a hard, shiny surface. Many mold-resistant
paints are hard and shiny.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of paints, don't be fooled by claims that a paint is
mold-proof. It may be mold-resistant but not mold-proof.
</P>
<P>
   Most exterior paints and stains are mold-resistant, because they
contain a mildewcide, and will keep a surface mold free for perhaps
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Mold comes in all colors, but mostly black. Those black dots on
siding are mold. So is a gray or black haze on the house.
</P>
<P>
   The second most popular color is white. Other colors are
relatively rare.
</P>
<P>
   Most mold grows on the shady side of the house because shady
sides are damp longer than sunny sides, although you can get mold
in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we know what mold is, how do we get rid of it and, keep
it away?
</P>
<P>
   The first part is easy. The second part is impossible,
especially outdoors. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bleach: the primary weapon &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, check to see if it is, indeed, mold. Treat a small area
with liquid chlorine bleach. If the black disappears, it was mold.
Now you can treat the whole area with a mix of one part bleach and
three parts water.
</P>
<P>
   Wear skin and eye protection when working with bleach. It is
caustic and toxic, even diluted. It can burn. In fact it did burn
the handyman, who ignored his own advice and worked barehanded.
Man, that hurt!
</P>
<P>
   Paint the bleach mix with a paint brush. If you don't plan to
paint in the near future, you don't have to rinse. If you plan to
paint, the bleach must be rinsed off.
</P>
<P>
   There are bleach helpers on the market designed to make the
bleach stick longer. Some of these helpers require addition of
bleach, others stand alone.
</P>
<P>
   Why not just leave the black marks, which to some are OK on
weathered cedar shingles? That's not a good idea, because the mold
can actually eat into the wood and cause decay.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies a problem when using bleach, the most effective
mold killer. While it will not affect most paints and some stains,
chlorine bleach can deteriorate weathered wood or any bare wood.
</P>
<P>
   So, to guard against that, you can blast the mold off with
pressure washing. Be careful that you don't get a lot of water
under the shingles. Under the shingles, it will take months to dry.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a milder alternative to bleach that may be
effective. It is Era, a detergent with ``bleach alternative,'' an
oxygen bleach that is relatively benign. It is sold in
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what you do, outdoor mold is likely to come back.
Keeping it away is impossible because there will always be
dampness. In dry years, there may be less. With dampness, more will
appear. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Keeping mold at bay &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All these treatments can be used indoors. Most indoor mold grows
in damp basements. But indoor mold can be kept away, simply by
keeping basements and all interior spaces dry.
</P>
<P>
   To keep a basement dry, ventilate it. Open windows for
cross-ventilation to get that damp air moving out. Put a fan in a
window to help it out. And, because basement windows are usually
high on the wall, they will ventilate only the top third of the
basement. So, put a fan on the floor to get all the air moving. Be
sure to screen and secure windows against invasion by critters and
burglars. If there are no windows, install vents in the foundation
wall or above it.
</P>
<P>
   Ventilation is your best bet. In July and August, when the whole
world is humid, venting won't work. That is the time to use a
dehumidifier.
</P>
<P>
   Mold seldom grows elsewhere indoors, except in bathrooms, where
there is a lot of moisture. Venting will solve that problem, too.
An open window will help, but best is an exhaust fan venting air to
the outdoors, not into the attic or anywhere else in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Attics are another place mold will grow, if it is not well
ventilated.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes mold will grow in peculiar areas, such as on a wall
behind a solid headboard or a large bureau or armoire. That is
because moist air gets caught in those restricted spaces, and
condenses on the cool wall.
</P>
<P>
   The cure there is to pull out the furniture several inches to
prevent the moist air from accumulating.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the information available on mold and bleach and
other mold killers, some homeowners complain that their house is
the only one in the neighborhood affected by so much mold. Why me,
they ask, and there is no answer, only guesses. Perhaps it is
because some houses are damper than others. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Algae and lichen, too &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, we've solved the mold problem, or at least dealt with it.
What about its dirty, rotten cousin, algae, and another seeming
plague, lichen?
</P>
<P>
   Algae is related to seaweed, a bright green growth on damp
surfaces. It does not have a thickness. Moss has a thickness, and
is most easily scraped off.
</P>
<P>
   For algae, the bleach treatment is effective, but it must be
scrubbed lightly with a soft scrub brush, then re-treated with the
bleach solution.
</P>
<P>
   Lichen is another matter. It appears as a light gray-green
color, with some little thickness, on stones and on asphalt roof
shingles. Lichen is a combination of algae and mold, the very
things we have been battling against.
</P>
<P>
   The algae and mold grow symbiotically, to form lichen, relying
on each other for life. Lichen resists chlorine bleach. It also
resists scrapers, which should not be used on asphalt shingles
anyway, because scraping can ruin them.
</P>
<P>
   One lichen killer is a mix of two tablespoons copper sulphate in
a gallon of water. Put this in a spray can and sprinkle it on the
lichen. (Sam Bordelon of Bloomington, Ind., sent us this
information.)
</P>
<P>
   Be extremely careful with copper sulphate. It is a powerful
poison, with a common name of blue vitriol.
</P>
<P>
   And, one positive note. Lichen will grow on roofs, but it may
not be urgent to take it off because it is slow growing and may
cause less damage than mold or algae. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Zinc as a deterrent &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another positive note about things growing on roofs: We
mentioned that these growths are impossible to keep away, but that
is not entirely true, especially on roofs.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy special zinc strips that will deter the growths, but
will not get rid of what is already there.
</P>
<P>
   These zinc strips, in various lengths and 3 to 4 inches wide,
are tucked under the second-highest roof shingle with two inches
exposed. Rainwater will run over this strip, leaching out zinc that
runs down the roof, deterring the growths.
</P>
<P>
   The strips are sold in some lumber and building supply stores.
If you can't find them, call the manufacturer or distributor to
find out where they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Shingle Shield, by Chicago Metallic, 800-638-5192.
</P>
<P>
   PDQ Building Products Sales, Hingham, 781-878-8733.
</P>
<P>
   Z-Stop, by WESPAC of Seattle, Wash., 425-745-5964.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
