<HEADER>
A4581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COSTARICA-INVEST-$ADV     08-17 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTARICA-INVEST-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMERICAN EXPATS, INVESTORS FINDING NIRVANA IN COSTA RICA
 &HT;    (1100&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Jaco Beach is 100 miles
southwest of San Jose along the Pacific coast.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACO BEACH, Costa Rica _ Zach McDuffie had a degree from the
University of Georgia, a promising career at an Atlanta ad agency
and a rush-hour commute he couldn't stand.
</P>
<P>
   He dumped it all for a life in this Central American hideaway,
trading button-downs for baggies, his car for a surfboard, his
climb up the corporate ladder for free-form creativity.
</P>
<P>
   And he's loving every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came down here for a month the first time and fell in love
with Costa Rica,'' said McDuffie, 27. ``I went back to Atlanta and
was doing the I-285 commute, but I just kept dreaming about Costa
Rica. I finally came back to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   McDuffie is one of an estimated 30,000 Americans and Canadians _
some believe the number might run as high as 70,000 _ who have been
lured to a life in this tropical oasis.
</P>
<P>
   Once a little-known swath of mountains, jungle and beaches
sandwiched between the Caribbean and the Pacific, Costa Rica became
something of a '90s nirvana for those seeking escape, simplicity,
natural beauty and cheap living.
</P>
<P>
   Bordered by Nicaragua on the north and Panama on the south, the
country stands out among its neighbors, but mostly for good
reasons. In a region torn by dictatorships, drug trafficking and
political instability, Costa Rica has enjoyed free democratic
elections for decades.
</P>
<P>
   While its neighbors struggle to overcome poverty and illiteracy,
Costa Rica enjoys a 94 percent literacy rate and broad-based
economic prosperity with only 6 percent unemployment in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   While others lack basic sanitation and adequate health-care, 99
percent of Costa Rica's 3.6 million residents are served by piped
water and 90 percent receive public health services recognized as
among the best in the region. More than 90 percent have access to
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most dramatic measure of Costa Rica's
difference: the nation abolished its army in 1949 and plowed the
money into development and social services. That stunning move
earned Costa Rica the nickname, ``The Switzerland of Central
America.''
</P>
<P>
   In another far-reaching move, leaders also set aside huge chunks
of the gorgeous countryside, so that now nearly 25 percent of Costa
Rica's territory is protected as national parks or preserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been everything I dreamed,'' McDuffie said. ``I'm
the happiest guy I know. It's such a different tempo here, a
different pace. All my dad's friends are mad at me, saying I
somehow managed to retire at 24.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as in any paradise, there are a few potholes.
Literally. The roads, while better than in neighboring countries,
suffer washouts and sporadic repairs that make driving an
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of foreigners has driven up real estate values, so
that prices in popular areas compare better to Miami than Managua.
The escalation has driven some would-be expatriates to look for
cheaper homesteads in Nicaragua, Honduras and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rican crime has also shot up, with the high-profile
murders of two American college students in March triggering a bout
of unfavorable international publicity. There has also been a rash
of kidnappings, leading many Costa Ricans to ponder whether some of
the less-appealing aspects of modern life are catching up with
their paradise.
</P>
<P>
   But the foreigners are still coming in droves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boom started about 10 years ago,'' said Ryan Piercy,
manager of the Association of Residents of Costa Rica, a private
group that provides services to incoming foreigners. ``For a while,
our group was growing by 300 percent a year. Now it's evened out to
a steady 10 percent a year. But we're seeing a lot of young people.
A few years ago, it was mostly retirees.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever visionary, Costa Rica's leaders years ago made it easy for
foreigners to move in. The law basically requires that would-be
residents have an income of US$600 per month and that they agree to
stay in Costa Rica at least four months each year.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders can own businesses _ which means they often create
employment for native Costa Ricans, known as ``Ticos.''
</P>
<P>
   McDuffie spent several months traveling the country before
finally settling down in Jaco Beach, a surf town on the Pacific
coast about two-hours drive from the capital, San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   After casting around for opportunities, he decided to open a
school catering to the hordes of young backpacker tourists who have
made Costa Rica a favorite destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to a lot of people who were going to language schools
in San Jose, and they were frustrated because they weren't seeing
the country,'' he said. ``So we designed a program that's hands-on
learning, with language, ecology, art and surfing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a struggle at times, but now in its third year,
McDuffie's ``Escuela del Mundo'' _ ``School of the World'' _ is a
growing enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our students find out about us from the Internet,''
McDuffie said. ``That's been the key. I wouldn't have been able to
do this 10 years ago because nobody would've been able to find
us.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Another ex-pat who has found his place in Jaco Beach is Dave
Klostermann, who once ran a thriving but stressful swimming pool
construction business in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got fed up with high insurance rates, workers'
compensation, crime and traffic,'' he said. ``I was working harder
for less money.''
</P>
<P>
   After investigating Montana and Idaho, Klostermann , 40, came to
Costa Rica on a lark with a minister friend doing outreach work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been told by several friends that this was the place to
come with a grubstake to buy a big farm and just sit back and watch
property values go up,'' he said. ``I wanted a place that was
growing but safe.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the idea that moving to Costa Rica is a
stress-free ticket to easy-street. Cars cost double what they do in
the United States. Most natives speak only Spanish. Petty theft is
a problem. Some natives grow resentful of ``gringos'' who open
businesses that compete with Tico shops.
</P>
<P>
   Klostermann wanted to open a construction business, but found
the market just wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he turned to his lifelong hobby: horses. It's taken
several years to establish his inars on everything from buying
property to obtaining insurance and avoiding scams. The sessions
have grown so crowded _ 35 to 50 people _ that he's considering
adding a second seminar each month.
</P>
<P>
   But he recommends that would-be residents investigate carefully
before making such a big move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some people who have sold everything at home, moved
down here and signed contracts to buy a house in the first week,''
he said. ``Some of them have been burned. It's important to bring
your common sense just as if you were moving to Florida or
Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams may be contacted at: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   Association of Residents of Costa Rica:
arcr(at)casacanada.net/arcr.
</P>
<P>
   General tourism information: www.tourism-costarica.com/ or
www.tourism.co.cr/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
