<SLUG> BC-ECOM-CHINA-E-SECTORS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 THREE ROADS INTO CHINA: B2B, B2C and C2C   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    
 By CRAIG S. SMITH  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BEIJING _ Somewhere in the Turkish highlands this summer, a
camper will bed for the night with a Chinese-made tent and sleeping
bag, courtesy of a Turkish sporting goods wholesaler that bought
hundreds over the Internet from a Chinese company earlier this
year. It is the kind of transaction that many people hope is the
beginning of a revolution for China's formidable economy.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions for revolution are ripe: China is relaxing
central government control over its vast export machine, and the
Internet is linking that machine to buyers worldwide. Furthermore,
e-commerce is cutting through China's archaic distribution system,
a fragmented, multilayered realm that harks back to the nation's
feudal past. The government is also bringing the country's growing
online population new services, from Internet auctions to
electronic matchmaking.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many barriers, both cultural and technical. And
for all the talk of the Internet's rapid spread, only a fraction of
the country is wired. Of those, only a fifth has shopped online.
The chief concern among consumers is the security of online
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that debt has always been scorned in
China, and collection is a challenge in a country that still has
only rudimentary rule of law. The nation's banks recently began
issuing true credit cards, but they are rare. And while many people
have debit cards, few trust using them online.
</P>
<P>
   So it will be a long time before China's e-commerce sector can
support more than a few big companies. The nation's Ministry of
Information Industries predicts that online transactions will reach
$42 million this year, more than six times last year's total. That
is far from enough to go around for the 1,100 consumer-oriented
e-commerce Web sites in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the state of e-commerce in China for
business-to-business, business-to-consumer and consumer-to-consumer
sites:
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TO-BUSINESS trade is the most promising because the
country has never developed a national distribution system, despite
the centralized administration of China's state industrial
conglomerates. Instead, production was localized _ nearly every
province had its own textile industry, tobacco factory, etc.
Selling products from one province to the next often required going
through Beijing. Meanwhile, the state-owned foreign-trade
corporations monopolized foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is not much better now. The right to export is
still controlled, and state-owned corporations continue to dominate
foreign trade. Domestic distribution remains fragmented. But
e-commerce presents a way to cut through the bureaucratic thicket.
</P>
<P>
   Several business-to-business Web sites are providing the conduit
that China's traditional distribution system lacks. Sites like
MeetChina.com and Alibaba.com go further, bringing China to the
world. Even China's state trade companies are exploring the
cybertrade routes.
</P>
<P>
   From a blue cubicle in a white-tiled building in northwestern
Beijing, Rao Qinfu types into the Alibaba site the specifications
for an industrial ice-making machine designed for fisheries. The
mandate from his employer, the China National Technology Import and
Export Corp., is to see whether the Internet is a workable
marketing tool.
</P>
<P>
   Rao, 28, is an eager Alibaba convert. ``It's free, and you get
quick feedback because it's one of the services with lots of people
online,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The site is a sort of industrial clearinghouse that draws
together buyers and sellers from 186 countries and regions
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But there are problems. Because the site is free, few customer
inquiries are serious, Rao says. After six months, he has not sold
anything other than the tents and sleeping bags to the Turkish
wholesaler.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Ma, Alibaba's founder, says his main goal is to be the
premier business-to-business site for China's smaller exporters.
Investors, who include Goldman Sachs, the Softbank Corp. of Japan
and Investor A.B. of Sweden, have pumped $25 million into the site.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TO-CONSUMER companies are the most common type of
e-commerce start-up here. Because of China's byzantine distribution
system, online sales theoretically give anyone with a Web site
national reach. And direct sales cut out the multiple
intermediaries who help inflate prices.
</P>
<P>
   At 8848.net _ whose name, derived from the height of Mount
Everest in meters, reflects the company's lofty goals _ Chinese
customers can buy books, software and computers. But in a country
rife with counterfeit goods and shoddy merchandise, China's
look-and-feel shopping habits are hard to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Tan Zhi, 8848's president, speaks frequently at universities,
hoping to engender online shopping habits among China's plugged-in
generation. ``We have to change people's way of thinking,'' Tan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Helping to bring about that change involves flawless execution,
so the company has built a cavernous ``fulfillment center'' in
northwestern Beijing, where staff members roller-skate down
warehouse aisles loaded with goods. The skaters gather requested
items onto a conveyor belt that delivers them to the packing
department, where delivery trucks wait.
</P>
<P>
   Logistics is the biggest challenge for companies like 8848,
which came under early criticism for unreliable delivery by a
subcontractor. Now the company relies on the national postal
service to deliver goods and collect money for cash-on-delivery
orders, which is how most people pay despite the company's
agreements with several banks to clear their customers'
transactions online.
</P>
<P>
   Still, business is slow. The company's transaction volume in
September was nearly $1.2 million and rose to $1.5 million by
November, but the company stopped providing figures to the public
at the end of last year. It says that growth remains high, but that
the company's new business-to-business service accounts for most of
today's transactions.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-TO-CONSUMER: Dozens of local online auction sites have
cropped up, though few generate enough activity to qualify as real
businesses. Part of the problem is trust; the kind of mutual
confidence that makes the transactions of America's eBay work is
rare in China.
</P>
<P>
   Eachnet.com, China's largest auction site, has solved that
problem by creating local sites that encourage transactions by
people in the same city who can meet before exchanging cash. The
total value of transactions settled on the site averages around
$2.5 million a month.
</P>
<P>
   Eachnet eventually wishes to charge users a ``success'' fee, but
it currently makes nary a penny from those deals. Instead, it would
like to make money by renting space on its site to other
e-businesses.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
