<HEADER>
A4588 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-CVN-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-17 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BEYOND THE BIG CORPOATE BUCKS, THERE'S STILL PASSION IN THIS
PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What a week. I've been trapped between phalanxes
of cops every day.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard too many rap chants for Mumia. On Wednesday a bomb
threat kept me out of my hotel for hours. One thing has kept me
going _ the people I met at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But first I had to get past the signs at the front tables at the
daily California delegation breakfast. The tables have been
sponsored by PG&AMP;E, California Association of Realtors, the
Correctional Peace Officers Association, the Agua Caliente Band of
Cahuilla Indians and Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, California. Let there be expensive light, real estate,
prisons, casinos and Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   But behind those front tables was seated Eliseo Medina, of Los
Angeles, the executive vice president of the Service Employees
International Union.
</P>
<P>
   When Medina got up to speak to the delegates, he said, ``You
know what? We can't always wait for the Republicans to be stupid.
This isn't about pretending to appreciate mariachi or salsa music.
This is about appreciating the people who do the hard work in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not a Republicrat.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't all parties and big money. This convention is filled
with delegates from every background and of modest means and great
dreams. They're the ones who cheer and are treated like extras in
the TV coverage.
</P>
<P>
   TV doesn't show the important stuff at the convention, and the
little people who spend thousands of dollars to come here to make a
difference. They don't get to vote on candidates, but they come to
``rekindle the fire in the belly,'' as Rep. Tammy Baldwin of
Wisconsin put it.
</P>
<P>
   I met Baldwin, the only openly lesbian member of Congress, on
Wednesday after she spoke to the 200 gay and lesbian delegates.
There were no TV cameras in this cramped room at the Wilshire Grand
Hotel, but here were some people who had shaken up the political
system.
</P>
<P>
   After speeches by lesbian candidates for Congress, the meeting
took a small-town Democratic turn. The moderator asked if anybody
wanted to introduce himself or someone else. Someone said he wanted
to introduce Glen Maxey, the only openly gay member of the Texas
state Senate, and a man who knows Gov. George W. Bush very well.
Maxey told a story that tells you all you need to know about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supported a bill that would prevent gays and lesbians in
Texas from adopting children, and even take away their children.
After the bill was signed, according to Maxey, Bush said, ``Glen, I
like you as a person, I respect you as a person, and I want you to
know that what I say publicly about gays does not apply to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxey said he told Bush, ``Governor, when you say publicly that
I am not fit to be a parent, then I take it real personally.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the kind of story you'll hear on TV. Neither will
you hear jokes like the one Maxey told. ``George W. Bush is thin on
policy,'' said Maxey. ``He knows more about baseball than politics
_ and he traded away Sammy Sosa.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Maxey added, ``I didn't know that. A lesbian told me.''
</P>
<P>
   In small places away from the cameras, I kept hearing people say
things that let me know the Democratic Party was still alive.
People are committed. I asked Alyson Abramowitz, a delegate from
Cupertino, Calif., if there was any big money in this convention
for her. ``Zero,'' she said. ``We pay our own way and it's very
expensive. . . . If I want to take a taxi to a party at Sony or
Paramount, it costs about $40. It would be cheaper if I fed
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts stress on our families,'' said Dang Pham, a delegate
from San Francisco. ``Sure, there are parties, but this isn't all
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't know it from the media, but not everybody is going
to parties in limousines. And when most people go to a party, they
don't have what normal people would describe as fun. They talk
politics.
</P>
<P>
   What's in it for the average delegate? ``It's political fantasy
camp,'' said Christine Pelosi, the daughter of Rep. Nancy Pelosi of
San Francisco and a third-generation Democratic delegate. ``There's
a joy in it. It's their big event. Every other group from the AMA
to the AFL-CIO has conventions, but none gets to nominate a
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Dustin Hall seemed like he'd rather be at a
baseball fantasy camp, but he was making the best of his second
Democratic convention by collecting autographs from politicians. He
had a Skip Humphrey and a Paul Wellstone from his home state of
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   His dad, John Hall, is a shop steward for a Minneapolis local of
the electrical workers union. ``I'm a working stiff like anyone
else,'' he said. ``I work the 7 to 3 every day, and I'm here
because America is not for sale. The Republicans are backed by big
business, selling out America to strike-breakers.''
</P>
<P>
   And they say the parties are just the same and there's no
passion in electoral politics anymore? Nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
