<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4589 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-LIEBERMAN-JEWISH-HNS &LR;      08-17 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-JEWISH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HEADLINES ABOUT LIEBERMAN SUGGEST WE HAVE A WAYS TO GO  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;    
 By RUTH SHERMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Al Gore's vice presidential selection has put a
spotlight on what is usually only whispered in private.
</P>
<P>
   It bubbled to the surface when newspaper headlines across the
country announced in bold type that Al Gore had picked ``a Jew.''
Of course, disclaimers quickly followed, pointing out that, even
though he is ``a Jew,'' Joe Lieberman is one terrific, moral,
ethical guy, greatly respected in the Senate by Republicans and
Democrats alike.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts point out that it's only because he is
the first ``Jew''' to be placed on a national ticket that there is
so much brouhaha.
</P>
<P>
   Others hint at something less pleasant. How long have Jews been
American citizens? How many generations are native-born, schooled
and raised right here in the United States?
</P>
<P>
   Jews helped build San Francisco. Starting in 1849, Levi Strauss
made blue jeans for dreamers who panned for gold in search of the
good life. Jews emigrated from Germany and other parts of Europe,
set up businesses, created social service agencies, designed homes
and schools. They raised families. They felt proud to play a part
in building a wonderful city, a meaningful life. They were happy to
be able to make a contribution, to give back something of value to
their society and their country.
</P>
<P>
   In New York and in other major and minor cities and towns
throughout America the story was the same.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for Joseph Lieberman, a man who went to Yale, became
Connecticut's attorney general and served with distinction in the
Senate, the headlines shouted: ``Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Jews make up only 2 to 3 percent of the population of
this country, they have made their presence felt _ in philanthropy,
the arts, education, science and business. Nonetheless, for many
years they were not welcome in many American towns, neighborhoods,
businesses or social clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, who are not Jewish, feel that Jews are
``different.''Others hold Jews responsible for ancient wrongs. Many
have never met any Jewish people but distrust them just the same.
</P>
<P>
   These feelings are expressed in overt and covert ways. It's easy
to decry skinheads who paint swastikas on synagogues and threaten
little children. But it's the more insidious, subtle things that
help perpetuate stereotypes and hatred.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, who is now 11, loves the books of T.A. Barron, a
Colorado writer with a deep reverence for nature. His fantasy
novels have taken her throughout the galaxy, beneath the sea and
into the magic realm of Merlin.
</P>
<P>
   But it was in this fantasy world, in a book on Merlin's
childhood, that boys threw rocks at a rag pile covering a human
being they identify as ``a dirty Jew.'' It's a jarring, discordant
note, totally out of keeping with the rest of the story. In fact,
nowhere else in any of Barron's books is anyone _ ogre, giant,
villain _ labeled in this pejorative way.
</P>
<P>
   The passage was so unexpectedly painful that it was hard to find
the words to try and explain it to my daughter, an American Jewish
girl.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jews are not the only minorities to experience
discrimination. Sadly, it's a story that has repeated itself over
and over again throughout our country's history.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a child, people referred to America as a ``melting
pot,'' the place poet Emma Lazarus described as a welcoming haven:
``Give me your tired, your poor, your huddled masses yearning to
breathe free.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, people from all kinds of diverse cultures have made
important and lasting contributions. In fact, every time a new wave
of immigrants becomes a part of this country, America is
reinvigorated and reborn in unexpected and meaningful ways.
</P>
<P>
   Yet negative labels still continue to be used.
</P>
<P>
   I think that in the year 2000, it's time for us to begin sharing
the things we have in common, that bind us _ celebrating, rather
than denigrating the differences that make us who we are.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lieberman, a decent, caring and highly moral man, is also
a Jew. Being Jewish has helped shape him, and is part of what
guided him to speak his mind on what he believes to be right and
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking out on right and wrong is how this country was founded.
I like to think of Joe Lieberman, Al Gore, George Bush, Dick Cheney
and you and me as part of that great tradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
