<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-17 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTING ON EMOTIONS RATHER THAN FACTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CECIL JOHNSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emotion more often than not trumps knowledge, observed the
former nuclear engineer.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't put it in exactly those words, but that was the gist
of his comments in reaction to a woman's remarks to me and my
daughter about the Firestone tire recall.
</P>
<P>
   We were all seated in the waiting room of one of the branches of
a company whose name suggests that it dispenses top-of-line tires
at marked-down prices.
</P>
<P>
   The woman had asked if we were in the black Ford Explorer. When
I said ``yes,'' she asked if we had heard about the Firestone
recall.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter said: ``Been there, tried to do that.'' Then I went
on to explain how the Firestone dealer had said that all they could
do was put people on a list because they didn't have any
replacement tires yet. And when they get them, which could take
months, the replacements more than likely would be other Firestone
tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides,'' said my daughter, ``they said my tires didn't
qualify because their serial numbers indicated that they were not
made at Firestone's Decatur, Ill., plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone and federal investigators, I pointed out,
have pinpointed that plant as the source of the problem with the
tires whose tread has separated and reportedly caused several major
accidents, some involving fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   The woman turned what African-Americans refer to as ``soulful''
and said: ``I don't care where mine were made _ they are gonna give
me some new tires or some money to get some, or I'm gonna turn the
place out.''
</P>
<P>
   I wished her luck. But I pointed out that I wasn't going to let
my daughter drive on her Wilderness ATs another day, regardless of
where they were made. I'd gamble on being reimbursed someday. I
expressed concern that if we waited, drivers of Ford trucks and
SUVs would buy up all the compatible tires of different brands.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the former nuclear engineer said to me that the
Firestones made at other plants probably were safe because both
Bridgestone/Firestone and federal inspectors had conducted a
thorough investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is going to be hard to convince the public of that
because most people make their judgments on such things based on
emotion rather than facts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His conclusion about the supremacy of emotion in such contexts,
he said, was based on his experience as an engineer involved in the
construction of the Comanche Peak nuclear power plant near Glen
Rose in north Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That plant unquestionably is one of the safest in the world.
It was way overbuilt for safety because we got caught up in an
emotion-driven regulatory environment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed the view that the American people are unnecessarily
anxious about the so-called perils of nuclear energy when it is the
safest and most environmentally friendly energy source now
available.
</P>
<P>
   I mentioned the Three Mile Island meltdown and triggered a
strong reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Mile Island was a success story. We had a meltdown, but
no radiation escaped from the containment area. We had a meltdown,
but we didn't have a Chernobyl disaster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked about the problems of disposing of nuclear waste,
he chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That problem already has been solved,'' he said, but the
public, caught up in uninformed emotion, doesn't want to accept the
solution.
</P>
<P>
   He described that solution as simply converting the waste into
chunks of ceramic material and burying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still radioactive. But the radiation doesn't extend but a
few feet, and because the stuff is ceramic, it won't leach into the
ground water.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm ruled too much by my emotions, but I couldn't quite
buy that. But I didn't try to put up an argument because he knew
much more about what he was expounding upon than I did.
</P>
<P>
   Changing the subject, I asked him what he was having done to his
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm replacing the Wilderness ATs on my Explorer with
Michelins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You may contact him at cecil(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
