<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4594 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-GODZILLA2000-TEX     08-17 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GODZILLA2000-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING SMUG OR SLICK ABOUT `GODZILLA 2000,' AND THAT'S THE WAY WE
LIKE IT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vinyl-record junkies often say that they like LPs because they
have a warmth that CDs don't have; the higher-tech sound is too
sterile and compressed. ``Godzilla 2000'' is sort of like a vinyl
movie; although it contains computer-generated effects, it looks
pleasingly retro, with obvious miniatures, occasional glimpses of
latex, and awkward dubbing. It has a warmth that, say, ``Mission:
Impossible 2'' doesn't have.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make it great, but it is the real deal: a Toho
Pictures spectacular, brought to the United States by TriStar _
possibly as an apology for TriStar's bombastic, smugly winking
Hollywood ``Godzilla'' from 1998. The American version planted its
tongue in its cheek, and was worse for it; ``Godzilla 2000'' plays
it so straight that it's often hard to tell which of the jokes are
intentional and which aren't. It lets moviegoers do the work,
deciding just how ironic they want to be.
</P>
<P>
   And if the preview was any indication, this is a movie that
needs an audience _ which it's unlikely to get as it battles ``The
Cell,'' ``Hollow Man'' and ``Space Cowboys'' for box-office bucks.
But Godzilla fans were out in force at the screening, often
pontificating with touching depth on their hero. The polite ones
even waited till the movie was over to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Godzilla elements are so familiar, you don't have to be a
fanatic to know about them, and many are in this movie: a scientist
(Takehiro Murata) who works for the amusingly named Godzilla
Prediction Network strives to understand the creature. A government
agency led by hilariously stoic Chief Katagiri (Hiroshi Abe) _
who's so stern and macho that only his hair and clothes blow
dramatically during the windy scenes _ wants to kill Godzilla,
who's wreaking havoc on communications systems. The agency also has
its hands full with an island-size rock that turns out to be full
of surprises.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, contemporary anxieties _ about mass media and,
apparently, the most highly developed computer hacking imaginable _
provide the plot with a little meat, and Godzilla gets into a
climactic battle with another huge beast. Yet despite the movie's
earnestness, it never takes itself so seriously that it stops being
fun. Sometimes you laugh at it instead of with it, and it seems to
invite that kind of condescension. You could call it a ready-made
midnight movie, except that it seems better-suited to a Saturday
matinee, preferably with bargain popcorn and a double feature with
a Gamera movie. Too bad nobody does monster-movie marathons
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Godzilla 2000''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 0-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Takao Okawara
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Takehiro Murata, Hiroshi Abe
</P>
<P>
   Length: 97 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ violence, strong language and monster mayhem
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
