<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4604 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-$ADV20     08-17 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHIAPAS ELECTION THAT COULD FORCE NEW CHAPTER IN ZAPATISTA
CONFLICT
 &HT;    (1100&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Yajalon is located about 90
miles north of San Cristobal de las Casas, in Chiapas state.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. Aug. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YAJALON, MEXICO _ Pigs snorted in mud and a chilly rain soaked
the mountains outside as Nicolas Lopez described how armed men
staged a terrifying raid on his hamlet earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Firing weapons into the air, the invaders claimed rights to the
villagers' land, setting fire to five huts, chasing about 30
families into hiding, and looting what little corn and clothes the
peasants had, Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he shivered at the memory, Lopez managed a smile. On
Sunday(8/20) the Mayan Indian will vote in a historic election for
the new governor of Chiapas, one of Mexico's most impoverished and
volatile states. And if pre-election opinion polls are accurate,
Mexico's 71-year-old ruling party is headed for another defeat
after being trounced in July 2's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting for a solution to our problems,'' said Lopez,
who will vote for Pablo Salazar, candidate of an opposition
alliance that could unseat Mexico's Institutional Revolutionary
Party, the PRI, from a state considered a barometer of social
justice in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Chiapas is home to the Zapatista Indian rebels, who launched an
insurrection against the Mexican government here in January 1994
that still hasn't been resolved. Since that time, armed
paramilitary groups loyal to the ruling party have also evolved,
periodically attacking Zapatista sympathizers like Lopez's hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``All government ties to these paramilitary groups will end (if
the PRI loses). One way to dismantle these groups is to simply not
guarantee them impunity any longer,'' said a sweat-soaked Salazar,
pausing for an interview and quick lunch during one of his final
grueling all-day campaign swings along Chiapas' sweltering tropical
coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are fed up and want change. And change is contagious,''
he said, waving at a marimba band in a restaurant that played a
song as a tribute to the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But Chiapas is considered a bulwark state for the PRI, and its
candidate, Sami David, has counted on a sympathetic state media
establishment that, as usual, offered slavishly favorable coverage
to him. A cordial man who is warm one-on-one, David also touched a
traditionally conservative nerve here with a campaign warning that
a Salazar victory could provoke even more instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Chiapas, an era of stability is at stake,'' David told a
recent gathering of PRI youth in the capital city of Tuxtla
Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the northern part of Chiapas is a checkerboard of Mayan
Indian villages divided between Zapatistas and PRI loyalists who
sporadically clash over land rights and political differences. The
collection of huts where Lopez lived _ nestled in rugged hills
above the city of Yajalon (pronounced, ``ya-ha-LONE'') _ was
eventually occupied by Mexican Army troops. But since the villagers
also fear the army, they refused to return.
</P>
<P>
   The election of Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox has sparked
hope for a peaceful resolution to the cycle of violence. Fox
ousted, for the first time in seven decades, the PRI, which the
Zapatistas blame for the squalid conditions the southern state's
Indians live in.
</P>
<P>
   Before the July 2 election, Subcommander Marcos, the primary
Zapatista spokesman, issued a statement reiterating the rebels'
position that they would negotiate again if a peace accord signed
in 1996 is implemented and federal troops are withdrawn from Indian
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is a promoter of free-market economic policies, which the
Zapatistas oppose, but he has pledged to revive negotiations with
the rebels and send Mexico's Congress the stalled 1996 accord that
grants sweeping Indian rights. If elected, Salazar could also set
an example that change can be forced at the ballot box rather than
at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one, not even the most radical person in the country can
dispute the legitimacy of a Fox government,'' Salazar said,
predicting that the Zapatistas can't dismiss electoral change.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent campaign stop in the gritty border town of Hidalgo
on the Guatemala border, supporters were enraptured with Salazar's
pledge to address the demands of the poor _ including the
Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Zapatistas said our fight is against being forgotten. They
said there is a worse death than dying from diarrhea or from
curable diseases,'' the candidate shouted from the stage to wild
cheers. ``There is a worse death, say our Indian brothers, and that
is , you people are about to do something about that painful
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Salazar is a federal senator and former member of the PRI, which
he says used to be the only option available to someone who wanted
to get into political office. But he left the party in May 1999
after a long string of disputes over the government's handling of
the Chiapas conflict.
</P>
<P>
   He is unaffiliated now, but is representing a four-party
alliance that includes Fox's conservative National Action Party, or
PAN, and the leftist Democratic Revolution Party, the PRD. The two
parties clash ideologically, but for the purpose of defeating the
PRI in Chiapas they pooled their funds and worked hand-in-hand for
Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   An exhausted-looking David said he isn't giving up, and he
dismisses polls like one conducted by Reforma newspapers, which
gave Salazar a 9-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Chiapas, the conditions to avoid confrontations or even
social collapse are being constructed with great difficulty,'' he
said an interview with Cox Newspapers. He had a badly bruised and
swollen ear, the result of an injury when someone threw a metal
weight at him in Salazar's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a platform for electoral reform,'' he insisted. ``The
offers for change have to be based on clarity and not on
deception.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's presidential candidate, Francisco Labastida, won in
Chiapas last month. But Salazar is counting on the combined votes
of the PAN and the PRD to carry him to victory. His campaign
posters say, ``the PRI has already lost in Chiapas, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's victory could also inspire PRI desertion.
</P>
<P>
   Among some of Chiapas' poor peasant farmers, Fox is now seen as
Mexico's new ``tlatoani,'' the Aztec word for ``maximum leader,''
Salazar campaign aide Mauricio Gandara said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that the 'Papa PRI' has died now. So they are
wondering who will be managing the money and resources. They are
thinking that now there is a 'Papa Fox,''' Gandara said. ``This is
the product of 71 years of domination by one party.''
</P>
<P>
   Araceli Burguete, a Chiapas sociologist, said the PRI still
controls many Indians in the state. It will probably be business as
usual in Indian towns where the local PRI leader habitually orders
residents how to vote, she said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But even in PRI strongholds, some residents appeared to be
bracing for change.
</P>
<P>
   Chenalho is an Indian town that produced at least one of the
convicted killers implicated in the infamous December 1997 massacre
of 45 people in the pro-Zapatista village of Acteal, just minutes
away.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Jimenez, 82, said he would listen to the advice of
village leaders, but wasn't sure who he'd vote for. He pulled
dismissively at a PRI T-shirt he was wearing and said almost
apologetically, ``This is five years old now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Luis Ortiz, a resident who has joined the movement to
deploy thousands of election observers here, complained that the
PRI had donated a Ford truck to the town ``in exchange for votes.''
</P>
<P>
   In Acteal, the site of the massacre, affiliates of the Zapatista
Army said they didn't plan to vote and declined to speak further.
Rebel leaders have been silent, other than to say they won't call
for a general boycott of the election.
</P>
<P>
   Those in Acteal who sympathize with the rebels but don't belong
to the army will cast ballots for Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Salazar doesn't win, we will think there has been fraud,''
said Spanish-speaking spokesman Agustin Vasquez. ``Acteal is
willing to vote for Salazar. The victims of the massacre are
waiting for justice and for change.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.globalexchange.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
