<P>
   CORPS-BOONDOGGLE _ ATLANTA _ The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
and several political and environmental leaders in Georgia and
Florida agree that it is finally time to end a boondoggle in which
more than $60 million was spent to build massive locks at the big
dams on the lower Chattahoochee to float what was expected to be
flotillas of commercial barges hauling a variety of freight. The
shipping channel is little used and has become one of the Corps
most heavily subsidized projects. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   UNC-WIRED _ CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ Arriving on Wednesday for the
start of his junior year, Mike Trinh said he was feeling the pang
of ``e-mail withdrawals.'' As much as the 19-year-old at the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill wanted to hook up his
computer to the Internet, his dorm room was a mess of disassembled
beds. Aside from start-of-the-school-year housekeeping lapses,
North Carolina's flagship public university is taking major steps
to connect its students with computers. UNC-Chapel Hill is the
latest _ and it says the nation's biggest _ university to require
undergraduates to own laptop computers. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   TRADER-JONS _ Pensacola, Fla._Trader Jon's, the legendary Navy
fliers' bar that has been closed for two years, will re-open Labor
Day weekend according to its new owners Matt and Kerry Heckemeyer.
Last week (August 8) they bought the bar and its memorabilia for
$465,000. Meanwhile, a group of Navy aviators who had hoped to buy
the bar plan to announce soon how they plan to spend the $100,000
they had raised. (David, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ Gore-Lieberman? Heck of a ticket the
Democrats have ended up with. A Southerner from Tennessee needed a
Jew from the Northeast to bring moderation to the party. Such are
the political times we live in. Moderates are where you find them,
in places you'd never would have thought to look. That goes for
both parties. (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin
(Texas) Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I am on the lookout for
lumber. Black walnut is my favorite wood to work, but it's easier
to find someone who's going to vote for Ralph Nader than it is to
find black walnut. I'll buy red oak when I find a decent deal,
trade for ash or cypress on occasion, pick up cedar if the price is
right and am considering a trip to Central Texas to pick up some
mesquite and pecan. (Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the
Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Texans like to brag about big.
Everything is braggable here, and size certainly qualifies. But one
area of big in which we'd just as soon not brag is crud. Crud is a
by-product of crude. Oil, that is. Texas tea. We're pretty big in
that, too. In the airborne crud category, the kind pumped into our
skies by cars, factories and refineries, if Texas were a country it
would rank seventh largest. So what the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission will consider Wednesday is big, even by our
standards. (John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-SUMMIT _ Amid a summer of discontent for airline
passengers, U.S. Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater has called
a summit meeting of airline chiefs in Washington Monday. The idea
is to discuss current problems but also start working on ways to
handle continuing growth before it turns every summer into the
``worst ever.'' (Fonti, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   UPS-TRACKING _ ATLANTA _ Deep in the fine print of all UPS
shipping contracts, there's an item that allows the company to
charge $3 each time a shipper tracks a package on the company Web
site. The charge is only used for companies that track hundreds of
packages a day and place great demands on the UPS information
network. But critics say it's meant to keep freight bill auditors
from collecting refunds on ``guaranteed'' shipments that arrive
late. This is the Information Age, UPS has figured out a way to
keep some information away from those who would use it to cost the
company money. (Hirschman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMOTIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ ATLANTA _ Cross marketing seems to be the way of
this millennium. Or has it been around for a while? Cross marketing
is the practice of one product hitching a ride on the star of
another product's success. How many of you have purchased just one
more Kid's Meal to get a dinosaur from the latest Disney movie? But
fast-food restaurants and movie studios are not the only ones
playing that game. Automakers today are using cross marketing to
target a segment of potential buyers. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLES
</P>
<P>
   ENCORE-MARRIAGES _ A look at remarriage _ or, as the industry
calls it _ ``encore marriages'' Don't think they're that common?
Think again. In half of marriages that take place now, at least one
partner is walking down the aisle again. And in one in seven
marriages, a partner is marrying for the third time or more. (Lore,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   ROTHKO _ HOUSTON _ After undergoing a $1.2 million renovation
and a major restoration to the paintings, the Rothko Chapel in
Houston is recently reopening. We visit this meditative landmark
and talk to the conservator who unraveled the mystery behind why
Rothko's stunning black paintings were slowly turning white. (Van
Ryzin, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WET-BASEMENT _ DAYTON, Ohio - Though rainfall has been at or
below normal this summer, there was at least one July storm that
left many, including me, with wet basements. It's natural that
basements are more damp than other parts of our houses, but if you
regularly get a puddle, a stream or even a lake during a heavy
rain, there are things you can do to fix it. (Cummings, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   WEEKEND-TV _ Weekend TV preview, including a so-so rating for
the remake of High Noon. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   TIM-REID _ Former WKRP in Cincinnati star Tim Reid has directed
a film, Asunder, that is opening on a staggered schedule around the
country. He talks with Dave Larsen. (Larsen, Dayton Daily News).
25.
</P>
