<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4607 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIE-REVIEW-DEMENTED     08-17 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-REVIEW-DEMENTED18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waters wit runs dry in `Demented'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been decades since Divine and dog feces became one of
cinema's signature moments. While the rest of the world was lining
up for stuff like ``The Poseidon Adventure,'' John Waters was
making, well, John Waters movies _ savvy outsider flicks with a
nice sick edge and a gleefully amateurish tone.
</P>
<P>
   The world has wised up (and dumbed down) considerably since
then. Now mainstream audiences groove on the gross-out obviousness
of ``Scary Movie'' or ``Road Trip.'' But John Waters is still
making John Waters movies. Sicker, yes, but the sickness comes off
as almost benign compared with the daily crudeness of tabloid TV.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the trouble with the amusing but ultimately tiresome
``Cecil B. DeMented.'' It's just not demented enough.
</P>
<P>
   A gang of self-described outlaw filmmakers kidnaps a glamorous
Hollywood star named Honey Whitlock (Melanie Griffith), who's come
to Baltimore for the premiere of her newest bit of glossy schlock.
Led by the titular Cecil (Stephen Dorff), whose motto is ``Death to
Mainstream Cinema,'' they force her to star in their no-budget
underground movie. Initially appalled by teen freaks with the
hallowed names of such independent-minded filmmakers as Sam Fuller
or David Lynch tattooed on their bodies, Honey is won over to their
cause. In other words, it's the Patty Hearst story refracted
through a melange of cinema in-jokes (which becomes especially
fitting since Hearst herself, a Waters regular, plays the mom of
one of the guerrilla moviemakers).
</P>
<P>
   You have to like a movie in which the protagonists storm a
theater playing ``Patch Adams: The Director's Cut'' or crash the
set of the ``Forrest Gump'' sequel, ``Gump Again.'' Plus, in
attacking the megaplex mentality, Waters also manages to pinpoint a
central problem in today's independent movie scene. As one
character proclaims, the studios ``have stolen our sex and co-opted
our violence.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, too much of ``Cecil B. DeMented'' is silly
and just plain slapdash. There's a laziness in Waters' work that,
in his outlaw days, seemed simultaneously daring and necessary. But
today, he's a veritable brand name _ a safe choice (relatively
speaking) for those moviegoers who want to be hip but don't really
want to take a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Dorff is appropriately wild-eyed and off-the-wall, but he
actually gave a riskier performance in the same vein in the little
seen ``City of Industry.'' As for Griffith, she's absolutely
convincing as the catered-to star who throws a hissy fit when
forced to ride in a white stretch limo (her contract specifies
black). But she's less effective as the newly minted revolutionary.
Still, it's good to hear her declare, ``It's a free country. People
can make bad movies if they so desire.'' Having inflicted stuff
like ``Milk Money'' and ``A Stranger Among Us'' on moviegoers, she
should know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cecil B. Demented''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Melanie Griffith and Stephen Dorff. Directed by John
Waters. Rated R for profanity, sex, violence and substance abuse.
At metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Not quite demented enough.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
