<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4608 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIE-REVIEW-SAVING18     08-17 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-REVIEW-SAVING18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gentle humor as a saving grace
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Saving Grace'' has everything it takes to be hopelessly twee:
steaming teacups and scenic seascapes, eccentric villagers, a rowdy
pub and some naughty business involving marijuana. But to the
credit of everyone involved, especially Brenda Blethyn in the title
role, the comedy mainly skirts the pitfalls of preciousness. It's a
guiltless, feel-good flick in the ``Waking Ned Devine'' mold.
</P>
<P>
   Recently widowed when her husband chose to step off an airplane
sans parachute, Blethyn's Grace is a middle-aged woman we meet
trying to keep herself together at his funeral. Her customary
gentility threatens to give way to hysteria, and no wonder. Not
only has her husband's mistress, Honey (Diana Quick), shown up at
the graveside, but Grace is soon to learn what everyone else in the
seaside village already knows: The dearly departed has left her
saddled with massive debt.
</P>
<P>
   As creditors turn up at the front door to evaluate her assets
(furniture, antiques, even the lawn mower), Grace meets an unlikely
savior: her gardener, Mathew (Craig Ferguson, also co-writer and
producer of the film). It seems that the kindhearted pothead is
having trouble growing his secret stash of marijuana and wonders if
Grace _ an enthusiastic horticulturist with a state-of-the-art
greenhouse _ might lend her expertise. The profits from selling the
crop, he explains, could save her house from foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Director Nigel Cole aims for the genial charms of the old Ealing
comedies, and often comes close. As Grace and Matthew embark on
their enterprise, the neighbors keep tabs. Their illegal project is
an open secret, thanks to the beacon of light that shoots out of
Grace's greenhouse every night. The whole village, as in ``Ned
Devine'' or Bill Forsyth's lovely ``Local Hero,'' becomes a
supporting character. Some standouts in the cast are Martin Clunes
as a doctor who does inhale, and Valerie Edmond as Matthew's
strong-willed, disapproving girlfriend. Phyllida Law and Linda Kerr
Scott as a couple of spinster shopkeepers deliver the movie's
funniest scene, unwittingly brewing up some ganja tea and melting
down in stoned hilarity.
</P>
<P>
   When the plot contrives to send Grace off to London to find a
dealer (Tcheky Karyo, a mix of sexy and sinister), it's mainly an
excuse to parade Blethyn around in an all-white suit, a
hausfrau-turned-Superfly. The movie loses some of its charm at the
very end, with a too-neat coda that seems tacked on. But for the
most part, ``Saving Grace'' can give you a mild contact high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Grace''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brenda Blethyn and Craig Ferguson. Rated R for drug
content and profanity. At AMC Phipps Plaza 14 and United Artists
North Point Market. 1 hour, 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A sweet little comedy in the Ealing spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
