<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4610 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-ORIGINAL-REVIEW-     08-17 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ORIGINAL-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE `KINGS' ARE CRUDE, NOT ORIGINAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
For some people, the title ``The Original Kings of Comedy''
doubtless evokes images of Charlie Chaplin or the Marx Brothers.
<P>
   With narrower definitions, you could probably get away with
calling such comedians as Lenny Bruce or Richard Pryor ``original
kings.'' They were all originals, though deciding who deserves the
article ``the'' before the title is a problem. What of the hairy
forebear who kept his clan in stitches, rolling with laughter on
the cold cave floor?
</P>
<P>
   Right away then, Spike Lee's new movie gets into trouble. One
wonders what went through Eddie Murphy's mind when he heard the
title. Why isn't he a comedy king? And surely he's as original as
the funny men featured here.
</P>
<P>
   The four comedians who make up the Kings of Comedy road show
from which this concert movie was extracted all hail from
television. They rose to fame on shows such as HBO's ``Def Comedy
Jam.''
</P>
<P>
   These programs target an audience often called urban but which
more accurately includes hip black teens, young blacks who want to
be hip and supposed hipsters who want to be black.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the favored subject matter, comedians who let on
that they read newspapers (or, heaven forbid, books) or who think
about anything other than sex and music are automatically
disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   A more accurate title would've been ``The Current Kings of
Vulgarity.'' Or maybe: ``Today's Boobs of Crude.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of the jokes can be printed here. The comics _ Steve Harvey,
D.L. Hughley, Bernie Mac and Cedric the Entertainer _ like to say
their profanity- and stereotype-filled bits draw on life as they
know it. Each comically exaggerates his own experience, they say,
and then offers it back to an appreciative audience that can relate
to it.
</P>
<P>
   Young black audiences seem to eat this stuff up. It's probably
safe to say, though, that for a large portion of the audience, much
like the mixed crowd who buy rap records, the shows provide their
primary window to African-American life.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey, Hughley, Lee and Cedric the Entertainer (what kind of
name is Cedric the Entertainer anyway?) appeared on the ABC talk
show ``Politically Incorrect'' the other night. Host Bill Maher
mentioned that their jokes repeatedly portray black people as
violent, sports-loving, sex-obsessed, dance-crazed alcoholics and
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a way to laugh at yourself without dehumanizing
yourself or degrading yourself,'' Lee volunteered in the comedians'
defense. ``There's a difference between laughing at somebody and
laughing with them.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not explain what that difference might be.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the humor on display in the movie is very funny, but
much of it is offensive and demeaning; it is of interest primarily
for its sociological value. It's instructive to know what young
people are laughing at these days. It's instructive to see what
type of minstrelsy black performers still think they must do to
attract and hold an audience.
</P>
<P>
   Of all of these comics, Harvey is the one most likely to be
remembered 10 years from now, the one most likely to earn the right
to be called a king of comedy for his keenly observant and socially
aware, sly humor.
</P>
<P>
   He'd do well to get himself away from the bulging-eyed shuckers
and jivers he appears with here. They can do nothing but bring him
down, the same way they drag the audience down into the gutter
during their acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Original Kings of Comedy''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley, Cedric the Entertainer,
Bernie Mac
</P>
<P>
   Director: Spike Lee
</P>
<P>
   Rating: R, for language and sex-related material.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 117 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
