<HEADER>
A4613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-SAVINGGRACE-REVI     08-17 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SAVINGGRACE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRENDA BLETHYN SPLENDID IN SAVING GRACE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
The first we see of the greenhouse that is a major setting in
``Saving Grace,'' the title character is inside, solemnly picking a
lily. A puff of what looks like smoke drifts into view. Because of
what we've already seen _ a gravedigger kicking back to enjoy
marijuana, a movie title that turns to smoke and blows away _ we
assume yet another local is having a furtive toke.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It turns out the cloud is from a humidifier. Not everyone in
this picturesque village is sky-high on grass, at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   We've already been sent several clues that this latest English
import takes place in environs not unlike the ones In ``Waking Ned
Divine'' and ``The Full Monty.'' This is an England filled with
eccentric characters and gentle humor, yet one not untouched by the
real world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Grace'' is particularly reminiscent of ``Waking Ned
Divine'' in that the village's good and charming denizens, while
unfailingly polite, harbor complete disregard for anything smacking
of authority or officialdom. There's nothing wrong with
circumventing the law, in their book, if some good might come of it
for the local folk.
</P>
<P>
   And in both movies, outsiders _ especially those wearing
neckties and the haughty air of a Londoner _ are to be dodged or
outsmarted; chances are they come carrying trouble.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of ``Saving Grace,'' there's even a skinny old codger
running around naked, just like in the earlier comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The wonderful Brenda Blethyn plays Grace, a recent widow (and
world-class gardener) who learns that her husband not only was
stepping out on her with another woman, but also that he's
squandered their money and left her deeply in debt. Everybody in
town seemed to know it before Grace did.
</P>
<P>
   Having sold her furniture to pay creditors, Grace now is on the
verge of losing her home. Her only salvation, she slowly realizes,
is to go into the marijuana business with her hired hand, who is
played by Craig Ferguson, who also is one of this movie's writers
and producers.
</P>
<P>
   Blethyn, who gave splendid performances as disheveled,
less-savory characters in ``Secrets &AMP; Lies'' in 1996 and ``Little
Voice'' in 1998, here plays someone who looks and behaves closer to
the way she does in real life _ an attractive if average
middle-aged woman. This is a less-showy performance than the ones
she gave in those other two movies, for which she was nominated for
Academy Awards, but it's just as impressive.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, Grace appears to be a rather proper lady in
mourning. As her troubles build, she moves up in notches to shock
and outrage and then to resignation before finally emerging a
survivor, a determined and resourceful woman willing to do almost
anything to stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   One of the movie's funniest scenes has her, dressed in a white
pantsuit, a scarf and jaunty feathered hat, standing on a crowded,
seedy London street corner, trying to peddle drugs to passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   Learning the ropes, she wrangles a meeting with a high-level
dealer. They hold their business meeting in the dank men's restroom
of a closed nightclub, beside the ever-sighing urinals. With the
sound of water dripping all around them, they seal their deal with
a toast.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, from time to time, succumbs to cutesiness, the
primary pitfall for these gentle British comedies that the best of
them manage to sidestep. You can't object too strenuously, though,
because one or two of the cuter scenes also happen to be among the
funniest. Nobody goes to movies like this looking for gritty
realism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Grace'' once and for all establishes that the ``just
say no'' era now is officially behind us. After largely
disappearing from the movies, marijuana has come back in a big way.
Central characters smoke and/or sell the stuff in ``American
Beauty,'' the upcoming ``Tao of Steve,'' Ice Cube's ``Friday''
movies and in other recent films. In none of those movies, though,
is it presented as so wholesome an endeavor as it is here.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the biggest pot smokers are portrayed as ditzy
dropouts from the high-pressured way of life _ not the sort of role
models today's young people would want to have. And the biggest
pothead of all in this movie is a doctor who's downright
incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Saving Grace,'' that will have to suffice as social
statement. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Saving Grace'' &QL; 
Starring: Brenda Blethyn, Craig Ferguson &QL; 
Director: Nigel Cole &QL; 
Screenwriters: Craig Ferguson, Mark Crowdy &QL; 
Rating: R, for language and sex-related material &QL; 
Running time: 94 minutes &QL; 
Grade: B &QL;
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
