<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4616 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-MARTINEZ-ARGENTINE-BL     08-17 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTINEZ-ARGENTINE-BLUES-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INEXORABLE HOPELESSNESS TAKES HOLD OF ARGENTINA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Wednesday, Aug. 16, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's MARTINEZ COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the MARTINEZ COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGHLAND PARK, N.J. _ Complaining seems to be an inherent part
of Argentine life, coupled with easy disappointment and fast
disenchantment. These laments haunt the words and music of the
tango and the busy offices of the nation's psychoanalysts.
</P>
<P>
   But I haven't seen Argentineans so depressed as when I passed
fleetingly through Buenos Aires and on my journey to Argentina's
northern provinces last month.
</P>
<P>
   While the government has just released discouraging unemployment
figures _ 15.4 percent _ a recent Gallup poll reveals that fully
one third of young Argentineans yearn to leave the country. Things,
though, appear to be no worse than in 1995, when those indexes were
higher, or in 1988, when the country was stuck in a relentless
recession. Argentineans today are simply tired of so many miseries
piling up, one after the other.
</P>
<P>
   In the local bars in Ceres, a small city in northern Santa Fe
Province, in the sleepy service stations on Route 34, or in the
small grocery shops in the seaport district of San Telmo, you can
hear the same chorus of complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Their criticism is not centered solely on President Fernando de
la Rua's government, but on the entire spectrum of political
leadership. Their desperation is extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for this, on first examination, seem to be more
subjective than objective, so it's rather difficult to rationalize.
What is obvious is the fact that the government has had only seven
months in power and its sluggish ``globalized'' economy offers few
means for performing miracles.
</P>
<P>
   But who can forget Carlos Menem's catastrophic first seven
months in office, complete with a runaway economy, rumors of
corruption in presidential circles and an imminent threat of
military coup.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a marked difference between the decade's
early years and now: the popularity of the former president, who
had once played on Argentina's national soccer team, and who
nightly could be seen dining with celebrities, was always very high
_ 70 percent to 80 percent. De la Rua's popularity, on the other
hand, has plummeted to less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Few people forget that Menem's government was characterized by a
general ongoing levity in the handling of public affairs, while the
honest determination of this administration is unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   So, where's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   A community's state of mind is better reflected in popular
expression than in opinion polls. During the 1990s everything was
spectacular. Now, reality has set it and it is terrifying: rising
prices, taxes hikes, so-called Budget tightening, shrinking
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, the sound of fear has been heard off and on in
Buenos Aires. Now it envelopes the whole country. The cold is
terrifying, the helplessness, too.
</P>
<P>
   When I crossed the wintry fields of Santiago de Estero in
mid-July, I was surprised to hear village folk sending each other
trifling messages over the radio. I wrote down two of them,
redolent with regional intonations and colloquialisms:
</P>
<P>
   ``Cachito: Go to Aunt Juana Rosa's house and tell her Mother is
waiting for her at the bus stop, and tell her not to be too long
because Mother's legs are hurting.'' And this other message:
``Anibal, I won't be able to be at your cousin's house at five
o'clock. I can get there by eight o'clock, but if you can't make
it, we'll see each other tomorrow. Please give me an answer through
this radio.''
</P>
<P>
   At the service station in Colonia Dora, in the heart of the
province, I asked how important these radio announcements were.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are very poor,'' the station manager told me.
``Nobody has a telephone. We `talk' by radio, when we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tucuman, the unemployment numbers are staggering. Twenty
percent of able-bodied workers do not have jobs and 50 percent have
no fixed occupation.
</P>
<P>
   The sidewalks of 25 de Mayo Street, the nerve center of the
provincial capital, teem with peddlers hawking their wares that
include everything imaginable, from fortune telling to Bolivian
spices.
</P>
<P>
   Legal money is almost nonexistent. Most of the transactions are
conducted with provincial bonds, bills of 1 to 20 pesos that look
like Monopoly money and have uncertain bank endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   In most of Argentina, the U.S. dollar is as common as the peso.
</P>
<P>
   But not in Tucuman.
</P>
<P>
   More than once I saw merchants suspicious of dollar bills, but
happily accepting the battered and crumpled ``monopoly'' bonds.
Money exchanges, you see, won't tolerate the least imperfection in
a U.S. dollar, and pay much less than they are worth if there's an
ink mark or the slightest stain.
</P>
<P>
   When I got back to Buenos Aires, I was struck by the
hopelessness of the young. Those who are in university feel there's
no point to finishing their studies, because at the end of the road
there are no jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, I watched on television a molecular-biology student who
was leaving for Italy knowing he would never return. ``What reason
would I have?'' he asked. ``Right now, I earn 930 pesos as a
research scientist, and with four more years of training my salary
will barely reach 980 pesos. If I come back, what would be the
purpose of all my efforts?''
</P>
<P>
   Science, education, health care and culture were never
priorities in Menem's government, but the sorry plight of Argentine
intellectuals has not improved much with the new government. Forced
to reduce public spending and to correct an oppressive legacy of
social inequalities, the government has to turn its attention
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The suicide of cardiologist Rene Favaloro _ the country's most
celebrated surgeon _ has weighed even further on the public mood.
In one of his last letters, Favaloro complained that even the
lowliest government health officers consistently declined to answer
his telephone calls. The surgeon's desolation parallels that felt
by poets Leopoldo Lugones and Alfonsina Stormi, who committed
suicide in 1938, overwhelmed by a somber time to which they could
see no end.
</P>
<P>
   It would be unfair to blame Fernando de la Rua's government for
these ills _ the emigration of so many young people, the increasing
level of poverty, an exceptional scientist's suicide _ but, taken
together, all these facts add up to a clear cry of alarm. If Menem
managed to maintain his popularity amidst a blizzard of disasters,
why then is De la Rua, whose honest efforts are undeniable, having
such a hard time?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the fact that the average Argentine doesn't know where
the country is heading, explains a lot. The wave of Menem's
privatizations and the great flow of foreign investment in the
1990s created the illusion of an economic boom that government
officials implied would never end.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nobody can be sure if tightening the economy and increasing
taxes will translate into a more stable economy and greater job
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   While the government downplays current hardships, it has yet to
present the nation with a coherent plan for the future that will
spark the Argentine spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Today's reality weighs too heavily, and there's no breath of
hope that will help it take flight.
</P>
<P>
   (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the author of ``The Peron Novel'' and
``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American studies
department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an editor
and journalist.)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
