<HEADLINE>
GORE PREPARES TO ACCEPT NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (This early version will be updated after 9 p.m. EDT with a version
written by R.W. Apple Jr. Complete text of the speech will be
available at the New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Twelve years after his first try for the
presidency ended in failure, and after eight years toiling in the
political shadow of President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore on
Thursday prepared to formally become the Democratic Party's
presidential nominee and his party's new leader.
</P>
<P>
   At about 10 p.m. EDT Thursday evening _ at the peak of the
television networks' prime-time viewing _ Albert Arnold Gore Jr.
will accept the nomination at the Staples Center in downtown Los
Angeles, where 4,339 delegates convened four days ago to work
toward that moment.
</P>
<P>
   Before delegates began the roll call vote on Wednesday night
that gave Gore the 2,170 votes needed for the nomination, his
running mate, Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut, introduced
himself to the nation in a speech that brought cheers and served as
a testimonial to the Democratic ticket leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``For his entire career, Al Gore's values have guided the way he
meets the challenges that lie ahead,'' Lieberman said. ``That's why
I hope you will conclude, you at home, as I have, that for his
honesty, for his strength, for his integrity and for his character,
Al Gore must become the next president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore told journalists who arrived in Los Angeles with him aboard
Air Force Two on Thursday morning that his own speech would rely
heavily on personal biography, details of his policy and his vision
for the future.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said he had composed the speech on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This speech I have written; I will deserve the credit or the
blame,'' Gore told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that those who watch and listen will feel afterward
that they have a clearer idea of exactly what I'm proposing to
do,'' Gore continued. ``They'll also know how the ideas and
proposals I'm making are rooted in experiences that I've had. I'll
give a few specific examples. I'll tell them why I feel as strongly
as I do about the choices we have to make.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was nominated as the Democratic Party's
presidential candidate Wednesday night by the actor Tommy Lee
Jones, who was Gore's roommate at Harvard. That nomination was
seconded by his eldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, among others.
</P>
<P>
   As Schiff finished a speech filled with family reminiscences,
Gore, unannounced, stepped on to the stage to embrace his daughter
and to wave, without speaking, to the wildly cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   That broke with tradition and so did the manner in which Gore
became the party's official nominee. Instead of the 68 delegates
from his home state of Tennessee casting the ballots that would put
him over the top, that honor went to the 144 delegates from
Florida. That was a clear indication that one of the battleground
states this fall will be Florida, where Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential nominee, is thought to have an advantage
because his brother, Jeb Bush, is the governor.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   All the convention days leading up to Gore's political ascension
Thursday night were scripted to ensure that the attention would
fall on him and that he would speak before a united and energized
party.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke on Monday night, symbolically handing over control
of the party to his No. 2 of the last eight years and then leaving
the convention so that the spotlight was Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the luminaries of the party's vital left _ including
Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, daughter of the late President John
F. Kennedy; Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts; the Rev. Jesse
Jackson Sr.; labor leaders; and former Sen. Bill Bradley, whom the
vice president vanquished nearly six months ago to win the party's
nomination _ have stepped forward to praise Gore.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After his speech Thursday night, Gore plans to return to the
campaign trail. He will fly from Los Angeles late Thursday evening
bound for La Crosse, Wis., to begin a four-day campaign swing down
the Mississippi River aboard a paddle-wheeled boat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
