<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4633 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TB-ENZYME-HNS &LR;      08-17 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TB-ENZYME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCIENTISTS REPORT POSSIBLE ADVANCES IN TREATING TB 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuberculosis is a clever bug that has learned how to live inside
the very cells that are supposed to protect the body from invaders.
</P>
<P>
   Now scientists say they may have unmasked a key player that
allows the TB bacteria to go dormant for years, waiting for an
opportunity to attack. It is a discovery that could lead to a whole
new approach in treating a disease that kills 2 million people
worldwide every year.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, reporting in Thursday's edition of the journal
Nature, say they have identified an enzyme called ICL that allows
the TB bug to change itself and survive the body's efforts to kill
it.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists also say they have found compounds that appear to
outsmart the bug by blocking this enzyme. It could lead to drugs
that dramatically shorten the length of time it now takes to treat
TB.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is that we may actually have new drugs to test in
animals as soon as this year, which is wonderful, considering we've
had no new TB drugs since the 1960s,'' said John McKinney, an
assistant professor at Rockefeller University in New York, the lead
author in the study.
</P>
<P>
   The study also involved researchers from Texas A&AMP;M University,
Washington University School of Medicine and the Albert Einstein
College of Medicine in New York.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of the world's population is infected with the TB
bacteria. Most of the cases are in developing nations. But TB
remains a persistent threat in Texas, particularly in the
Texas-Mexico border counties, where disease rates are two to three
times higher than the state average.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 million Texans carry the bacteria, and 200,000 of them
probably will develop the disease at some time in their lives, said
Jeff Taylor, an epidemiologist with the Texas Department of
Health's tuberculosis elimination program.
</P>
<P>
   TB treatment is lengthy, requiring people to take medications
for 6 months or longer. Many people drop out, which is giving rise
to drug-resistant strains of the bug.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have struggled for years to understand how TB
persists in the body.
</P>
<P>
   When the bacteria are actively causing disease, current drugs
can kill them. But these drugs are ineffective when the microbe
goes dormant in macrophages, cells that are part of the body's
defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has really known how these bacteria survive when they
are in the chronic phase,'' said James Sacchettini, a professor of
biochemistry at Texas A&AMP;M. ``All we know is that the drugs we
currently use don't work against the chronic stage.''
</P>
<P>
   In their current experiments with laboratory animals, scientists
discovered that the bacteria are able to chemically change
themselves once they take hold inside the macrophages. They begin
producing ICL, which then allows them to eat fatty acids, the most
abundant source of stored energy in their host cells.
</P>
<P>
   Using sophisticated techniques, Sacchettini's laboratory was
able to discern the three-dimensional structure of this enzyme, and
also identify compounds that potentially could interfere with it.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical giant Glaxo-Wellcome, which helped fund the
research, is now developing drugs with the researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most optimistic view of this is it would lead to drugs
that allow us to treat TB like any other bacterial infection, in
the course of two or three weeks,'' Sacchettini said. ``I think
this would change the perspective of TB around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Cindy Tumiel by e-mail at ctumiel(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
