<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN-DRESS (New York) _ ``Curios and Treasures,'' a modest,
yet serenely beautiful exhibition at the Costume Institute at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, displays 65 garments and accessories
that range through four or five centuries of European dress. By
Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-SEATTLE (Seattle) _ It is difficult to think of any city,
other than the urban behemoths like New York and Los Angeles, and
maybe Washington, that has shaped modern living in the United
States as much as this one. Nordstrom, Boeing, Microsoft,
Starbucks, Amazon: all innovators, all based here in the Pacific
Northwest, off in a remote corner of the nation, far from the main
centers of population. Yet they play a central part in daily life
across this continent and beyond. Seattle still has its funky side.
It revels in its mellow small-town atmosphere; a Seattle ad man
popularized the ``happy face.'' But it has become an unmistakably
rich, high-tech, high-rise, high-expectation metropolis. By R.W.
Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ALTERNATIVE-THEATER (New York) _ Scores of shows are now on
at the Fringe, the annual two-week downtown theater festival that
revels in all things dramatic and different. Every day, the Fringe
will present almost 80 performances, staged by some 2,000 artists
from 13 countries. The Fringe is only one of several theater
festivals currently running in the city. By Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-ARTISTS (New York) _ Institutional group exhibitions of
up-and-coming artists have long been an annual feature in the
city's art season. Three are on view now, at the Studio Museum in
Harlem, the Bronx Museum of the Arts and El Museo del Barrio. The
museums themselves are still seen as fringe venues, but they're
also integral players in the big picture of American art, and their
shows feed the larger pool of talent from which mainstream stars
emerge. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-COLUMN (Undated) _ When you are selling 800 vintage,
classic and antique sports cars in one place, you are bound to come
across a big party or two. There are nonstop festivities planned
around the car sales in Pebble Beach, Calif., this weekend, and the
auction houses and car dealers expect about 20,000 people. By Wendy
Moonan.
</P>
