<P>
   Higher interest rates slow the growth of the economy and
ultimately hurt the stock market. (Of course, some areas, like food
stocks, are considered havens during a slowing economy and should
do well.) As rates rise, risk-free Treasury bonds become more
attractive as investments.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks, on the other hand, become less desirable. With stocks,
you're taking on more risk than with Treasuries. To compensate for
that risk, stocks must produce ever-higher returns, which becomes
increasingly difficult if the economy is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   You might be asking: Then why is a healthy, growing economy bad?
</P>
<P>
   A blossoming, strong economy isn't bad. But an economy that's
growing too quickly can lead to inflation, which is a concern.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation means that prices for goods and services are rising.
And as prices rise, your dollar buys less and less. If inflation is
out of control, businesses cannot accurately price their goods and
services, which leads to economic instability.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Federal Reserve's broad mandates is to control
prices, which means controlling inflation. The Fed, led by the
always-popular Alan Greenspan, does that by raising or lowering
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed abhors accelerating inflation,'' says Mitchell Held,
economist at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates slow the economy and reduce the risk of
inflation, while lower interest rates spur the economy and entice
consumers and companies to borrow and spend. Lower rates are
traditionally good for the stock market. Higher rates are not.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Fed has raised short-term interest rates three
times in an effort to tame inflation and throw water on the hot
economy. Right now, the thinking is that the economy has
sufficiently cooled, inflation is in check and the Fed is done
raising rates _ at least for the time being. (The Fed's Federal
Open Market Committee meets again next week.)
</P>
<P>
   However _ and it's a big however _ one wild economic indicator
or two can sometimes change the whole picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``That view will change if it turns out that we're looking at
bigger gains in employment coupled with a great-enough increase by
wages and salaries to suggest that consumer spending is
rejuvenated,'' says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's
Investors Service. ``Market sentiment will shift from a neutral
view and investors should prepare themselves for additional Federal
Reserve rate hikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street monitors a host of different economic indicators in
every effort to predict the direction of the economy and the Fed.
Here's a primer on the most important ones.
</P>
<P>
   JOBS DATA
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, you want to pay attention to the employment
report that comes out on the first Friday of every month.
</P>
<P>
   This Labor Department report is usually the first major economic
announcement during any given month and is the single best measure
of the health of the economy. ``The first is always the easiest to
remember,'' jokes Held at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   This release, containing information about job and wage growth,
delivers a broad view of what is going on with the economy. This
report provides an overview of what happened to the economy during
the previous month and usually sets the tenor for the other
economic indicators that are released through the rest of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people use the employment stats to generate their own
economic forecasts,'' says Held.
</P>
<P>
   If job growth is rising, for example, you might conclude that
production of goods and services is likewise expanding, says
Lonski. If people are making more money, they are probably going to
be spending more money.
</P>
<P>
   And if all indicators point to an economy that's growing out of
control, the Fed could very well feel obligated to raise rates. And
rising rates are usually bad for most stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs report is key for another reason: Greenspan thinks it's
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any favored indicator of Alan Greenspan's is a favorite of
ours,'' says Held. ``He will run hot and cold on various indicators
but the employment report is a keeper.''
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER PRICE INDEX
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index is another closely watched indicator
that's released around the 15th of every month.
</P>
<P>
   This index measures the change in cost of a basket of goods and
services such as food, energy, housing, clothing, transportation,
medical care, entertainment and education. It's a direct gauge of
whether prices are rising or not. And rising prices can mean
inflation. And you know what the Fed likes to do to inflation.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also want to watch the core number, which excludes the
volatile food and energy sectors and gives a better indication of
inflationary trends.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER PRICE INDEX
</P>
<P>
   The Producer Price Index, or PPI, is an indicator of wholesale
prices in the country. This index measures the change in prices
received by domestic producers of commodities in all stages of
processing. The Labor Department releases both the CPI and the PPI,
which is released around the 13th of the month.
</P>
<P>
   This number can also give you an indication if spending is
growing and prices are on the rise. However, the CPI is arguably
the most direct measure of inflation. ``The CPI is a broader
measure,'' says Stuart Hoffman, chief economist at PNC Financial
Services Group. It includes not just goods but services like
medical care and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL SALES
</P>
<P>
   Once a month, the Commerce Department releases a measure of
sales at retail outlets. Although retail sales don't include
spending on services, it can tell you a lot about consumer
spending. Are folks buying more clothes or less?
</P>
<P>
   Anything that gives an indication that consumer spending is on
the rise and inflation is coming back can roil the market.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, any of these economic indicators can move the stock
market when they're announced, if they dramatically exceed what the
market is expecting.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that anyone knows from one measure or two if the Fed
will raise rates. It's the expectation of what the Fed might do.
</P>
<P>
   If the CPI number came in much higher than expected, it would be
an unpleasant surprise for the market and have a negative effect on
stocks and bonds. ``Inflation is the enemy of bond holders,'' says
Hoffman. With inflation, bonds will be worth less by the time they
mature because of rising prices. Any signs of inflation can hurt
the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   If the market thinks rates will continue to rise, investors
might sell financial stocks, which are typically hurt by rising
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Rising rates and a slowing economy can put downward pressure on
the stock market. In a slowing economy, businesses that make
expendable goods might get hurt. You may want to avoid buying the
stocks of companies that make cars or equipment used in home
construction _ sectors that will be dramatically affected in a
slowing economy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, investors will go for defensive stocks like utilities
or pharmaceuticals, companies that manufacture products that
consumers cannot do without. Think drugs, toilet paper and food.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are buying stocks to own for decades, you don't need
to be too fixated on these economic numbers. There are plenty of
people in the market who will do that for you.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Dagen McDowell is a senior writer for TheStreet.com. Send your
questions and comments to deardagen(at)thestreet.com, and please
include your full name. Dear Dagen aims to provide general fund
information. Under no circumstances does the information in this
column represent a recommendation to buy or sell funds or other
securities.)
</P>
