<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-SYRIA-TRAVEL-$ADV19-C     08-17 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-TRAVEL-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DAMASCUS UNVEILED: SYRIAN CAPITAL OFFERS HIGH POINTS OF ARAB
CULTURE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With if-you-go box attached at end of story.
 &HT;    With SYRIA-PALMYRA-$ADV19.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Aug. 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ Whether they know it or not, when Westerners
try to conjure an image of fine Arab culture, it's probably close
to the courtyards and covered market streets of Syria's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we go into the city,'' wrote travel writer Henry
Van Dyke, ``we step into a chapter of the 'Arabian Nights'
Entertainments.''
</P>
<P>
   That observation was made in 1908, but it still fits a city that
manages, amid its modernity, to stay alive with elegant detail.
</P>
<P>
   Cats slumber across finely carved tables with inlaid
mother-of-pearl oyster shell. Thick vines dangle over the walls of
the Old City. Diners smoke water pipes and sip tea in tile-lined
courtyards around quiet fountains. Swordmakers discuss their
ancient craft even as they consider advertising on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As Syria slowly opens to the west, a small but growing number of
Americans are getting to know the exotic city of about 3 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   Damascus prides itself as the oldest capital in the world _
going back at least 5,000 years _ and as a showcase of Arab
tradition. It shows itself off with sometimes grand, and sometimes
funky flourishes. For the former, there's the stately tomb of
Saladin (pronounced, ``sala-DEEN''), probably the most heroic,
non-religious, Muslim figure in all history.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the army museum, where the power might go out as
you wander between the run-down artillery, tanks, rifles and the
dusty exhibit on Syrian Hamad Feris, who joined Soviet cosmonauts
in space. One of the few English signs at the exit states, with no
apparent irony, ``Tanks(CQ) for your visit.''
</P>
<P>
   For travelers, Syria is largely crime free. Arabic is the common
language and many Syrians also speak French. There are few
proficient English speakers, but some taxi drivers or hotel staff
will know a few words.
</P>
<P>
   Americans need to get a Syrian visa before departing. Those can
be obtained in about a week from Syrian embassies or consulates.
Syria still does not recognize Israel and will not grant visas to
people with Israeli stamps in their passports.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian countryside is flush with archeological digs and
dozens of Crusader and Muslim castles. But the capital offers a
sampling of the great mix of cultures to come through this corner
of the Mediterranean. It's also a shopping wonder, offering rugs,
furniture and metal work from around the Middle East and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start is the walled Old City. It's a large,
working district where Syrians shop for everything from clothes to
dehydrated Newts. Sold in jars in the medi''). He was the Mamluke
ruler who, before his death in 1277, defeated the Mongols and
almost finished off the Crusaders who had hung on after Saladin. He
was violent and unforgiving, but his tomb is decorated with the
palaces and lush plants awaiting him in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the Old City is the Omayyad Mosque, a huge
courtyard bordered by a large prayer hall built around 708 A.D.
Inside and out are mosaics of glass beads from as far back as the
12th Century.
</P>
<P>
   The mingling between Islam and Christianity is apparent. The
mosque's minaret towers include the Jesus tower, where locals
believe he will return on judgment day. Inside the mosque is a
shrine to John the Baptist, revered and called Yahia by Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the mosque should remove their shoes, but keep their
arms and legs covered or borrow the robes offered at the ticket
office.
</P>
<P>
   The Old City also offers a Christian landmark. The underground
Chapel of Ananias is named after a disciple of Jesus who is
believed to have lived there. Ananias was ordered, according to the
New Testament, to go to ``the street which is called Straight'' to
heal a blind man. The Street Called Straight is still a main road
through the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   After sightseeing, tourists can join the genteel Arab elite in
Old City restaurants built around what used to be private palaces.
The Elizer and Arabesque restaurants are two fine examples where
you can dine on lamb kabobs and traditional yogurt stews.
</P>
<P>
   When you have enough of the living history in the Old City, you
can see Syria's ancient history in the National Museum. Most
explanations are in Arabic and French, but the museum is excellent.
Most interesting are the expressive, big-eyed statuettes carved by
the Canaanites, the pagan people who populated the region in 3000
B.C.
</P>
<P>
   There are also haunting relief statues from the Second Century
Roman period. Each depicts in personal detail men and women who had
been entombed behind them.
</P>
<P>
   The museum also contains a synagogue transported from Dura
Europus, near the Syrian-Iraqi border. Though nearly 1,800 years
old, the synagogue still holds colorful painted scenes from the
bible that brighten the small sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Museum visitors might want to stop and dash off some postcards
in the museum's tranquil archeological garden. Here, under trees
that quiet the city bustle outside the walls, you can stroll amid
detailed relief sculptures and statues that form the foundations of
today's Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be reached at LarryK(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.syriatourism.org/information.htm
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA: IF YOU GO . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  VISAS: U.S. citizens need a Syrian tourist visa, which costs
$61. Visas can usually be obtained in a few days from the Syrian
embassy in Washington at 202-232-6313, ext. 106; the consulate in
Los Angeles at 949-640-9888; or the consulate in Houston at
713-622-8860.
</P>
<P>
   Visas are not given to people with Israeli stamps in their
passport.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TRAVEL: Can be arranged for groups or individuals by
international travel agents. No U.S. carriers fly there. However
Swiss Air, Air France and others do. ``Jordan and Syria, a Lonely
Planet Travel Survival Kit'' is a common and helpful guidebook.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MONEY: The currency is the Syrian pound. Some hotels accept
American credit cards. Syria does not have automatic teller
machines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  LANGUAGES: Arabic is the language of Syria, though some
Syrians speak French or English.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHERE TO STAY: Hotels in Syria can be relatively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   In Damascus, top range lodgings include Le Meridien, The
Sheraton and the Semiramis. All starting around $200 a night. The
Al-Faradis Hotel offers mid-range rooms starting at about $70 a
night. There are many other lower-cost hotels.
</P>
<P>
   In Palmyra, the Cham Palace is at the top end for $150 a night.
Mid-range hotels include the Heliopolis and the Zenobia for about
$80 a night. The Al-Najil is for backpackers as low as $15 a night.
</P>
<P>
   For more information see:
</P>
<P>
   www.syriaonline.com
</P>
<P>
   www.cafe-syria.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
