<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: MON., AUG. 21, 2000 
 TV-TONIGHT COLUMN
</HEADLINE>
  
 $adv21  ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: Please check local listings for time and channel. All
times listed are EDT unless otherwise specified.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c. 2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two interesting specials tonight look at two different sides of
pop music and its effect on society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stand and Be Counted,'' on TLC at 9, finds David Crosby
hosting the first of a two-part documentary series on social
activism in rock 'n' roll, from the early days of the folk boom
through ``The Concert for Bangla Desh,'' right up to today's
benefits for the rain forests and a free Tibet. (Part two airs
Tuesday.)
</P>
<P>
   Crosby may be best known today as a test-tube daddy and liver
transplant recipient, but he was a stalwart rock activist even
before he wrote ``Almost Cut My Hair'' for Crosby, Stills and Nash.
The story he tells here and in a companion book begins with
nonviolent civil rights protests and moves through the tumult of
the 1960s to the all-star benefit cycle kicked off by Live Aid in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of rock-star interviews here (Bob Geldof,
Carlos Santana, Joan Baez, Peter Gabriel, Sting, Tracy Chapman and
Willie Nelson), as well as performance footage by Bruce
Springsteen, Woody Guthrie and CSN. Unfortunately, we'll also have
to sit through flashbacks to the ``We Are The World'' recording
session, which proved once and for all that an all-star performance
doesn't necessarily make for good art.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting companion piece airs on MTV at 7. ``When Lyrics
Attack'' looks at the controversies generated at the other end of
the musical spectrum over racist, violent, misogynist and
homophobic lyrics, especially from rappers like Eminem. Must
artists be role models? Do hateful lyrics influence young
listeners?
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Loder hosts, and we'll hear everyone from Eminem himself to
the Gay and Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation, plus the Beastie
Boys, who'll also be featured in the Crosby special. And at the end
of the 30-minute special, a round-table discussion will bring in
some young fans. But of course this topic could use two hours too,
or more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Football,'' ABC at 8: Preseason game finds Green
Bay at Miami. But most people are tuning in to hear color man
Dennis Miller's erudite wisecracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: Tonight, the cute little dog goes
into the red room and tearfully begs his former owners to remove
him from his reality-TV nightmare. (OK, not really, but it's more
interesting than whatever will really happen on the show.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Mysterious Ways,'' NBC at 8: Adrian Pasdar and Rae Dawn Chong
star in a series that might be called ``Touched By An X-File.''
Tonight they investigate a haunted railroad crossing.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of Queens,'' CBS at 8:30: A crossover episode finds Doug
and Carrie having an eventful dinner with Ray and Debra of
``Everybody Loves Raymond.'' Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' CBS at 9: Raymond's mother
browbeats him into hiring his loathsome cousin Gerard (Fred
Stoller). Then he finds out that everyone thinks they're a lot
alike. A funny rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order,'' NBC at 9: Is a young girl responsible for the
death of a boy found at a construction site? Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal,'' Fox at 9: In a first-season episode, Ally and
the gang get help from the lawyers over at ``The Practice'' when a
client goes Lizzie Borden on her husband. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Untamed Amazonia,'' Animal Planet at 8: Tapirs! Sloths!
Otters! Agouti! (What?)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``WWF Raw,'' USA at 9: Wrestling and vaudeville, followed at 10
by ``WWF War Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Resurrection Boulevard,'' Showtime at 10: On the eve of a big
fight, Alex gets involved with a powerful woman and may be losing
his focus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Wesley Snipes,
musical guest Dido and the latest ``Survivor'' castoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05: Green
Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader. He's got to get airtime
somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35 a.m.: John
Spencer of ``West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: TBA. &QL;
</P>
