<HEADER>
A4722 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     08-17 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO HANDLE BUSINESS CRISES COOLLY AND PROFESSIONALLY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CLAUDE CROWLEY 
 c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Crisis Counselor'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Step-by-Step Guide to Managing a Business Crisis &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Jeffrey R. Caponigro &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary Books, $16.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Crisis skulks around businesses like a hyena around a camp site
_ watching and waiting, and then dashing in, all teeth and claws,
shredding reputations, trashing earnings, leaving behind bloodied
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in his right mind would camp on a veldt swarming with
ravenous hyenas without taking protective measures. Yet businesses
and other organizations operate in an environment just as perilous,
metaphorically speaking, and most take no crisis precautions.
According to a survey taken in the early 1990s and quoted by author
Jeffrey Caponigro in his book ``The Crisis Counselor,'' only 5
percent to 10 percent of large organizations had a crisis
management plan.
</P>
<P>
   Caponigro says no business is too small or too large for crisis
planning. All businesses, regardless of size, face problems every
day. Many problems are handled quickly and dissolve, but others
erupt into crises. ``The Crisis Counselor'' is a practical guide
that defines crises, describes ways to prevent them and explains
how to manage them.
</P>
<P>
   The biggies _ oil spills, plane crashes, explosions, product
tampering _ spring to mind when ``business crisis'' is mentioned.
``The Crisis Counselor'' is unusual among crisis literature,
however, in that it doesn't focus on high-profile disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Caponigro takes aim at garden-variety events that are
more common and more likely to harm reputations or credibility. On
his list are employee layoffs, product recalls, lawsuits, irate
customers and the death of a senior executive.
</P>
<P>
   Most books and workshops on the subject are heavily slanted
toward ways to survive and contain damage. ``The Crisis Counselor''
focuses strongly on avoiding crises.
</P>
<P>
   Caponigro offers good basic advice, beginning with public
relations. He emphasizes its value as a tool to mitigate damage.
The best way to survive a corporate crisis, Caponigro says, is to
have a substantial store of good will from key ``publics'':
customers, employees, news media, suppliers, and civic and
community leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Also important in a corporate crisis-management program is an
assessment of vulnerabilities based on information gathered from
the organization's key publics. Having a realistic written list of
possible vulnerabilities allows the crisis-management team to take
preventive action, conduct practice sessions for employees, assign
the best-prepared people to respond, stockpile supplies and take
other steps to lessen damage.
</P>
<P>
   Caponigro also recommends that every business prepare a written
crisis-response plan, in which each person's duties are spelled
out. He warns, however, against thinking of the plan as the end
result. Sometimes people make a crisis-response plan, place it on
the shelf and say, ``That's that.'' Later, when a disaster strikes,
executives react intuitively, forgetting the plan. The plan,
Caponigro writes, is just one part of a crisis-management culture
that should include awareness and response training, even when no
crises threaten.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with most business books, this one is a refreshing
breeze. Each chapter starts with questions to help readers assess
their knowledge of the material to be covered. The text is
organized into comfortable paragraphs containing immediately useful
guidance, applicable to businesses and organizations from the
smallest to the largest. The author provides direction and
professional criticism on how everyday crises can be handled and
includes examples and case studies.
</P>
<P>
   If you are an executive or a manager in a business or
organization that hasn't faced up to crisis planning, this book may
be the best business investment you'll ever make. If you don't have
time to read it at work as part of your job, keep it on the night
stand and read a chapter each evening.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis hyenas are always circling. The professional way to
deal with them is to take precautions: appoint a crisis-management
team to seek vulnerabilities, establish preventive measures, review
and keep current a crisis response plan, periodically conduct
practice sessions and take the lead when a crisis strikes. This
book can help you do all that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Claude Crowley reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
