<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODZILLA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GODZILLA 2000': SIZE REALLY DOES MATTER AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only a diehard fan of the long-running Japanese ``Godzilla''
series could love ``Godzilla 2000,'' the 23rd screen appearance of
the indestructible fire-breathing monster that emerges from the sea
to wreak awesome destruction. This is not to say that there aren't
thousands (perhaps even millions) of cultists who won't adore it.
Watching this transcendentally tacky movie, which wants us to laugh
at it and with it at the same time, it is easy to see why the
series threatens to be as enduring as its namesake.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese version, as opposed to Roland Emmerich's
pretentious, clanking Hollywood update of a few years back, takes a
more philosophical view of Godzilla. Is the monster a super-clumsy
lumbering friend of mankind. Or is he our enemy? Or is he both?
Might his longevity owe itself to the fact that he is really
ourselves in a different form? Ah, who knows what evil lurks?
</P>
<P>
   The beast's latest resurrection, directed by Takao Okawara, has
been scaled back from 328 feet (his height from 1991 through 1995),
to 170 feet, which is close to his original size (from 1954 to
1975, the production notes, inform us, Godzilla was 164 feet). Such
things matter to cult audiences.
</P>
<P>
   What really hasn't changed radically in 46 years is the series'
1950s-style comic book pacing and dialogue. The movie wastes no
time cutting to the chase. In the first five minutes, Godzilla
destroys a submarine and a seaside restaurant. By the end of the
film, most of Tokyo lies smoking at his feet. Unlike the Hollywood
version, ``Godzilla 2000'' doesn't try too terribly hard for
realism. The structures that are toppled and snapped like match
sticks look like toys.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the fun is the awfulness of the dialogue that has
been hilariously (and badly) dubbed into English and is always
spoken in the semi-robotic gee-whiz tones of Saturday morning
cartoons. It reaches a peak of silliness when one startled
character actually exclaims, ``Great Caesar's ghost!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla 2000'' has enough story to fill three movies. The
fable basically pits the good guys (those who want to study
Godzilla and learn from him) against the baddies (those determined
to destroy Godzilla as quickly as possible and who are willing to
sacrifice human lives to get the dirty deed done).
</P>
<P>
   This time, the debate over Godzilla's fate is complicated by the
discovery of what at first seems to be a meteorite on the bottom of
the ocean. It metamorphoses into a flying rock and then a UFO with
designs on taking over the Earth. Ultimately, Godzilla goes
literally head to head (and in one scene head in mouth) with a
Godzilla-like monster the aliens have conjured up on the smoking
ruins of what used to be Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond being an obvious fable about nuclear power in the
computer age, none of this adds up unless you are determined to
force every square peg into every round hole and pretend they fit.
The most ardent fans, no doubt, will be able to piece together an
allegorical puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GODZILLA 2000'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Takao Okawara; written (in Japanese, dubbed into
English) by Wataru Mimura and Kaji Kashiwabara; music by Takayuki
Hattori; production designer, Takeshi Shimizu; special effects
director, Kenji Suzuki; produced by Shogo Tomiyama; released by
Toho Films/Tri-Star Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Takehiro Murato ( Shinoda, director), Shiro Sano
(Miyasaka, the scientist), Hiroshi Abe (Katagiri, the chief), Naomi
Nishida (Yuki), Mayu Suzuki (I-O) and Tsutomu Kitagawa (Godzilla).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes. This film is rated PG (parental
guidance suggested). It includes scenes of violence and destruction
that could upset young children.
</P>
</TEXT>
