<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLACE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PLACE VENDOME': IN A SETTING FIT FOR A STAR, DENEUVE FINDS THE
FACETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By DAVID KEHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Named after the Parisian square that is home to the Ritz Hotel,
several haute couture boutiques and some of the world's most
expensive jewelry shops, ``Place Vendome'' provides a perfect
setting for Catherine Deneuve, herself one of the French cinema's
most precious gems.
</P>
<P>
   Now 56, an age when most American actresses would have been
shuffled off to play eccentric grandmothers in television movies,
Deneuve remains a star of regal proportions. The face has filled
out a tiny bit, the figure a bit more, but the piercing eyes and
granite jaw remain as formidable as ever.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Place Vendome'' she is Marianne Malivert, the unhappy,
alcoholic wife of a prominent jeweler (Bernard Fresson, a veteran
who appeared with Deneuve back in 1967's ``Belle de Jour''). Busy
checking herself in and out of assorted clinics, Madame Malivert is
too far gone to notice that her husband is facing bankruptcy. One
night he brings home a pouch containing five exquisite diamonds,
which he places in his wife's care; the next day, he kills himself
by driving his car into a logging truck.
</P>
<P>
   The diamonds turn out to be stolen, and soon the befogged
Marianne finds herself besieged from all directions _ by
representatives of the De Beers cartel, who believe the stones to
have been taken from their stock; by her contemptuous
brother-in-law (Francois Berleand), who needs the gems to save the
family business; and by the mysterious Battistelli (Jacques
Dutronc), a shady operator with connections to the Russian mafia.
</P>
<P>
   All of which proves to be immensely therapeutic for Marianne,
who rises to the occasion by tossing out her bottles of Bordeaux
and rediscovering the canny businesswoman she was before her
marriage. Adding spice to the situation is the fact that in the
distant past she and Battistelli were lovers, until he abandoned
her to the police when one of his dubious deals went sour.
</P>
<P>
   It is not hard to imagine Lana Turner or Elizabeth Taylor
playing Marianne in a high camp Hollywood melodrama of the late
1950s, but ``Place Vendome'' takes a more restrained approach.
Though Deneuve is given plenty of opportunities to wear fabulous
gowns while drifting through fabulous locations, the film is so
darkly lit (by the cinematographer Laurent Dailland) that it's
often difficult to make out the details. The mood, nicely sustained
by the director, Nicole Garcia, is one of muffled despair,
world-weary resignation and faintly rekindled hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, herself a fine actress (in such films as Alain Resnais'
1980 ``Mon Oncle d'Amerique''), has now made three features as a
writer-director (including 1990s ``Every Other Weekend'' and 1994's
``Favorite Son''), and she certainly knows how to frame a
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The script of ``Place Vendome, `` which Garcia wrote with her
usual collaborator, Jacques Fieschi, is filled with superfluous
characters and strained coincidences _ Emmanuelle Seigner turns up
as Battistelli's current lover, a salesgirl at the Malivert
boutique, and Jean-Pierre Bacri is a disbarred lawyer with a
romantic interest in Marianne. But in spite of its many flaws, the
film never loses its focus on its fascinating central figure.
Grandly suffering, grandly triumphant or just plain grand, Deneuve
is a spectacle to behold.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES;
</P>
<P>
   `PLACE VENDOME'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Nicole Garcia; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Garcia and Jacques Fieschi; director of photography,
Laurent Dailland; edited by Luc Banner and Francoise Bonnot;
produced by Alain Sarde; released by Empire Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Catherine Deneuve (Marianne), Emmanuelle Seigner
(Nathalie), Jean-Pierre Bacri (Jean-Pierre), Jacques Dutronc
(Battistelli), Bernard Fresson (Vincent Malivert) and Francois
Berleand (Eric Malivert). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 105 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
