<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4731 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-THECELL-TEX     08-17 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THECELL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CELL' KEEPS YOU RIGHT WHERE IT WANTS YOU
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By TODD CAMP 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At its worst, music video/commercial director Tarsem Singh's
``The Cell'' is a gaudy exercise in style over substance with a
preconceived ``artiness'' that is likely to turn off fans of the
serial-killer subgenre.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, it's a horrifically gorgeous, masterful exploration
of the dark recesses of the human mind, a bold new direction for
the horror genre.
</P>
<P>
   Expect comparisons with Clive Barker and his directorial debut,
1987's ``Hellraiser,'' which was a stylish, terrifying new twist on
tried-and-true horror conventions. But in a genre slump dominated
by garden variety stalk-and-slash yarns (even this summer's
visually nifty ``Hollow Man'' turns into ``Friday the 13th)'' or
parodies thereof (the ``Scream'' films made fun of themselves
better than ``Scary Movie'' ever did), ``The Cell'' is a refreshing
new take on a familiar Hollywood premise.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as ``Silence of the Lambs'' on drugs. Same basic
story: Law enforcement authorities try to coerce a captured serial
killer into revealing the whereabouts of his last victim before
it's too late. Except what if, instead of Jodie Foster trying to
get into the mind of Hannibal Lector in a metaphorical sense, she
had done so in a literal sense?
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lopez is about to find out ``what if.'' Vicious killer
Carl Stargher (Vincent D'Onofrio) falls into the hands of the FBI
just as he falls into an irreversible coma, unable to reveal the
location of his latest abductee, who is trapped in a hidden,
water-tight cell awaiting a torturous death by drowning.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent Peter Novak (Vince Vaughn) is willing to try anything
to get the information, including turning to the practitioners of a
ground-breaking new transcendental therapy that enables one to
literally tap into _ and become a participant in _ a person's
unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   So child therapist Catherine Deane (Lopez) agrees to try to tap
into Stargher's nightmarish noggin. Trouble is, the arid, desolate
sand dunes of Deane's last patient's imagination are nothing
compared with the monstrously bizarre and terrifying imagery of
Stargher's demented mind. And if Catherine loses her ability to
distinguish reality from the killer's macabre mindscape, she runs
the risk of remaining trapped there.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Singh's past of directing music videos (including
REM's award-winning ``Losing My Religion''), it figures that ``The
Cell'' is visually stunning. The film is art-directed to the nth
degree (pay attention, Academy) _ borrowing from everything from
the haunted paintings of Hieronymus Bosch to the campy religious
imagery of Pierre &AMP; Gilles photography. The film also boasts
stunning costume creations by Eiko Ishioka (''Bram Stoker's
Dracula'') and an ominously pervasive score by Howard Shore.
</P>
<P>
   But Singh manages to avoid turning his players into parts of the
scenery, pulling solid albeit subdued performances from his leads
while actually providing thoughtful commentary on our culture's
view of the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the chilling and often grisly fantasy elements are
sure to turn off some, so moviegoers with more timid tastes are
cautioned to enter this nightmare at their own risk.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Cell''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 0-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Tarsem Singh
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jennifer Lopez, Vincent D'Onofrio, Vince Vaughn
</P>
<P>
   Length: 110 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ graphic violence, nudity, strong language, adult
subject matter and disturbing imagery
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
