u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     08-17 0171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDA: ``WILL YOU FIND ME'' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IDA: ``Will You Find Me'' (Tiger Style).
</P>
<P>
   Voices harmonize closely, somewhere between intimacy and
claustrophobia, in the quiet, unhurried songs on ``Will You Find
Me,'' the fifth album by Ida. Instruments are discreet, unwilling
to break a silence unnecessarily; if a lone guitar or piano is all
that's needed, Ida uses nothing else. Ida is a four-piece band
intent on sounding smaller and more private, the better to
contemplate questions like ``Am I still the one you wanted me to
be?'' That song, ``Maybelle,'' unfolds over nearly seven minutes of
billowing counterpoint, a minimalist bossa nova that never resolves
itself. Even when Ida, which plays the Knitting Factory in New York
on Aug. 27, allows itself to use a rock beat or guitar feedback,
its songs seem hushed. They're like the whispers of uncertain
lovers in a perpetual dance of vulnerability and assurance, parting
and reconciliation.
</P>
</TEXT>
