<P>
   &UR; `WALTER': FOND TALES OF A JOURNALISTIC CAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WALTER-THE-CAT-FISK-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ Walter was a street cat, a ``pusseini baladi'' as they
say in Beirut, brown and black with sharp ears and sharper teeth _
and the only creature of its kind to consume part of an Israeli
wire-guided air-to-ground missile. She could not escape journalism.
And journalism couldn't escape Walter....By Robert Fisk, The
Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Poignant Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (975 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN EMERALD CITY, WIZARD OF OZ ENDORSES THE TIN MAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON-CURSE-GORE-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There could be no more irresistible political
farewell. Like the flawed hero in his own Hollywood movie,
President Bill Clinton prepared to address the Democratic Party
faithful Monday night on a wave of high emotion and extravagant
praise for the man who would succeed him, Vice President Al Gore.
But the Gore camp has had to worry about being upstaged. Just by
opening his mouth and smiling his infectiously boyish smile,
Clinton risks putting his putative successor into the shade. In the
Emerald City, it will inescapably seem that the Wizard of Oz is
handing over to the Tin Man....By Andrew Gumbel, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
