   &UR; MOVED THURSDAY, 17 AUGUST: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; G-DAY: GORE'S THE CANDIDATE AT LAST. BUT IS HE A CONTENDER? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAN-GORE-WIN?-INDEPENDENT-825&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With Democrats looking for nothing less than an
epiphany to breathe new life into their struggling campaign for the
White House, all eyes turned Thursday night to the man who embodies
many of the party's misgivings but is the only one who can truly
rekindle its hopes _ its candidate, for better or worse, Al Gore.
As he prepared to formally accept the party's nomination at the
closing night of this week's convention, the vice president knew
that he had to give the speech of his life....By Andrew Gumbel, The
Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 175-word optional trim at 825; story uncut is 1,075) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AL GORE'S TEN-FOOT POLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GORE-CHARACTER-RESEND-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Thursday night, Vice President Al Gore must
walk on to the platform at the Staples Center in Los Angeles and
deliver the speech of his life. Having attained his party's
presidential nomination after two failed attempts, he must now show
that there is genuine substance beneath the exaggerated ardor or
anger he often displays in his public appearance. Success, as he
accepts the Democratic nomination for president, will keep him in
the presidential race with a sporting chance of winning. Failure
could spell the beginning of the end of his political career, at
only 52....By Mary Dejevsky, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...UPDATED, RESENT from 8-14) &QL;
