<P>
   &UR; `WHY HAS THE PRESIDENT BEEN SILENT?' ANGRY RUSSIANS ASK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN-FIRING-LINE-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ ``Why has the president been silent?'' demanded the
daily Komsomolskaya Pravda in two-inch high red letters on its
front page Thursday. The newspaper asks why vacationing Vladimir
Putin took five days to make his first brief comment on the sinking
of the Kursk nuclear submarine to the bottom of the Barents Sea,
while finding time to appoint new ambassadors to Jamaica and Chile.
Just before the presidential election in March Putin dressed up in
a military pilot's uniform to fly in a fighter-bomber. He even,
ironically, spent a night underwater in a nuclear submarine. It is
these images which are now coming back to haunt Putin....By Patrick
Cockburn, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KURSK: CITY HOLDS ITS BREATH AS TIME RUNS OUT FOR ITS SONS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KURSK-MOTHER-LIMBO-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ ``I can't sit around waiting here any longer. I must go
up there,'' cried Valentina Staroseltseva, whose 20-year-old son,
Dmitry, is among the 118 submariners trapped on the Kursk at the
bottom of the Barents Sea. The irony is that she had been pleased
to see Dmitry sent to the prestigious Northern Fleet instead of the
notorious ``stroibat'' (construction brigade), where bullying is
rife, or, worse, to what Russians call the ``meat grinder'' _
Chechnya. ``We thought the submarine was so safe,'' she said. ``We
called it our submarine. We were 100 percent confident in it. We
really believed in it.''...By Helen Womack, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN DESERVES RESPECT, BUT FRIENDSHIP TAKES LONGER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN-RESPECT-400&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ With every hour that passes, the chances of any of
the Kursk submarine crew surviving its sinking are dwindling. The
likely outcome will be a human tragedy and another blow to the
fragile, edgy pride of military Russia. The fate of the
nuclear-powered submarine _ the flagship of the Northern Fleet _
has strong symbolic significance for the Kremlin. Barring a miracle
rescue, it will be the first major disaster President Vladimir
Putin has had to deal with since coming to power, and a test of his
ability to comfort and sustain, as well as to rule....By Anne
McElvoy, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 325; total uncut is 1,225) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GERMANY SEEKS THE DE-NAZIFICATION OF YOUNG PEOPLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DE-NAZIFY-YOUTHS-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Reacting to the rentless drumbeat of daily atrocities,
the German government Wednesday announced the first of its sweeping
measures to combat the far right. The program _ the de-Nazification
of German youth _ is intended to be just the beginning of what
promises to be the most concerted attack on right-wing extremism
since the immediate aftermath of the Second World War....By Imre
Karacs, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
