<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT &LR;      08-17 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Singers To Swingers
</P>
<P>
   This week's DVD releases include ``Nashville,'' with a
commentary by Robert Altman, and ``Planet of the Apes: The
Evolution,'' Fox's umbrella title for the Charlton Heston epic and
its four sequels (``Beneath the ... '' ``Escape From ...''
``Conquest of ...' and ``Battle for ...'') on five discs, along
with a sixth disc with the documentary ``Behind the Planet of the
Apes,'' about the making of the series. And on Tuesday will come
``The Tigger Movie,'' with assorted games and songs about the Pooh
clan augmenting a sweet little film from Disney with muscle enough
to take in more than $40 million at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   But the DVD of the month will arrive a week later: James
Cameron's ``Terminator 2: Judgment Day'' (1991), to be released by
Artisan on Aug. 29. In the minds of many disc aficionados, ``T2,''
as it is known, is the ultimate. ``The general consensus was that
it was the greatest laser disk ever produced,'' said Douglas Pratt,
editor of the DVD Newsletter and author of The DVD Video Guide.
When DVD was new, ``T2,'' a sequel starring Arnold Schwarzenegger
as a machine man dispatched from the future to rescue a little boy
destined to save mankind, was issued at its original theater
length. Now, scenes have been added and many of the supplements
that were on the laser disc have been transferred to accompany new
ones on a special DVD edition.
</P>
<P>
   The list of extra features totals 40. ``For all the people who
haven't seen the laser disc, which is 99 percent of the population,
the DVD will be a revelation,'' said Van Ling, a DVD producer who
put together the supplements for laser in 1993 and helped create
the new DVD. That has to do primarily with the quality of picture
and sound. ``It is considered one of the standard demonstration
films for home theater,'' he said. And the effects, with machine
men rising from melting silvery puddles, play at their best on
large television screens.
</P>
<P>
   But in other respects this is a movie with a good reputation.
``From the standpoint of a film and disc buff, it's a virtual
catalog of cinematic technique,'' he said. Or as Janet Maslin put
it in The New York Times, ``Surprise. Cameron has made a swift,
exciting special-effects epic'' with ``better developed characters
(after all, the first Terminator was barely verbal), a livelier wit
and a more ambitious, if nuttier, message.''
</P>
<P>
   For the DVD, Ling said, he tried to present a film school class,
with much material on production and editing and other aspects of
big-budget moviemaking, from writing and editing to location
scouting and promotion. The new disc employs an interesting
approach to the director's commentary, also borrowed from the laser
disc. Instead of a film-length discourse by Cameron and
Schwarzenegger, which neither would do in the first place, the
commentary pieces together parts of interviews with 26 people who
made the movie. ``Sometimes,'' Ling said, ``directors get so
engrossed watching the movie they stop talking.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mifune
</P>
<P>
   Soren Kragh-Jacobsen's film violates at least one of the
principles of Dogma 95, the Danish school of stripped-down
filmmaking, by divulging the directorial credit. Otherwise, it's a
pretty good little movie about a Copenhagen businessman (Anders W.
Berthelsen) with a BMW and a trophy wife who returns to the rotting
farmhouse where he grew up to find his father stretched out dead on
top of the kitchen table and his mentally retarded brother (Jasper
Asholt) hiding underneath it. A prostitute on the run (Iben Hjejle)
and her brother (Emil Tarding), a raffish boarding-school student,
fill out an eccentric menage while, A.O. Scott wrote in The New
York Times, the ``brusque realism of Kragh-Jacobsen's style _ his
careful suppression of style _ allows a surprising sweetness to
emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37. 99 minutes. Danish with
English subtitles. R. Release date: Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes Brown
</P>
<P>
   The indefatigable, plucky, good-humored mother of seven adoring
children in 1967 Dublin, Agnes (Anjelica Huston) rarely loses her
temper despite being poor and newly widowed with mouths to feed.
That dazzles the French baker (Arno Chevrier) in her neighborhood,
though she prefers the strapping Welsh belter Tom Jones (who puts
in an appearance as an inflated 1999 version of his 1967 self). And
how does Agnes remain such an ideal gal? ``Only heaven and the
creators of upbeat radio serials and popular novels and the people
who turn them into treacly feel-good movies could tell you''
(Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. USA. $56.49; DVD, $24.95. 91 minutes. R. Release date:
Aug 22.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Rage
</P>
<P>
   A limping homage to Robert Altman, James D. Stern's film
intertwines the fates of nine characters (Gary Sinise, Anna Paquin,
Giovanni Ribisi, David Schwimmer, Andre Braugher, Robert Forster,
Joan Allen, Josh Brolin, Bokeem Woodbine), each of them either a
perpetrator or a victim of gun violence and sometimes both. But
satire turns into ``a ham-fisted, high-concept public service
announcement, directed with stagy deliberateness and tin-ear
vernacular speechiness'' (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36; DVD, $24.95. 103 minutes.
Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Here on Earth
</P>
<P>
   You know the drill. Suffering young lovers are kept apart by
class and tragedy. Sam (Leelee Sobieski), the winsome farm girl,
falls for Kelley (Chris Klein), a spoiled young god from the
wealthier side of the tracks. Only she is dying of cancer. And
underneath Kelley's blank look is actually a poor little rich boy
waiting to get out. With its shameless sob story on teen loss,
Elvis Mitchell wrote in The New York Times, here is ``the Best
Movie of 1961, lacking only the beautiful and vacant visages of
Troy Donahue and Suzanne Pleshette.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Fox. $104.16; DVD, $34.98. 96 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MY BEST FIEND. ``Every gray hair on my head I call Kinski,''
says Werner Herzog in his documentary about his stormy relationship
with the actor Klaus Kinski. The two made films together, including
``Aguirre: Wrath of God,'' ``Woyzeck'' and ``Fitzcarraldo,'' in the
Amazon jungle. ``Quite often it was very difficult to talk to him
because he answered back like Jesus,'' Herzog recalls. ``A splendid
job of chronicling the high drama and creative pinnacles of their
work together,'' Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times. 1999.
Anchor Bay. $14.98; DVD, $29.98. 100 minutes. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   CAUSE CELEBRE. John Gorrie's television film, adapted from
Terence Rattigan's play and broadcast on PBS' ``Mystery,'' recounts
the case of Alma Rattenbury (Helen Mirren), a 38-year-old former
singer who, with her 18-year-old lover, is charged with the murder
of her 61-year-old husband (Harry Andrews). Hardly proper and the
boy isn't even of the right social class, her lawyer (David Suchet)
tells Alma. Mirren, John J. O'Connor wrote in The New York Times,
gives ``a wonderfully complex depiction of a confused woman caught
in a situation that suddenly reveals her to herself.'' 1988. Lance
Entertainment. $19.95. 105 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   MURDER MUST ADVERTISE. Ian Carmichael is Lord Peter Wimsey in
the BBC production, based on the story by Dorothy L. Sayers. 1974.
Acorn. $59.95; four-volume boxed set. 200 minutes. Information:
(800) 474-2277.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
