r e BC-KINGS-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      08-17 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGS-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIKE LEE CAPTURES COMIC GENIUSES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SANDRA BARRERA 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Kings of Comedy'' can pack a stadium anywhere in America,
no problem. But try to get a movie made in Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   Few people in mainstream entertainment have ever heard of the
tour, let alone caught one of the dozens of sold-out shows, though
they are probably familiar with some of its African-American
headliners _ Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley, Cedric the Entertainer and
Bernie Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the ``Kings of Comedy'' raked in more money from
its tours last year than even the Backstreet Boys, or that it has
grossed $37 million since its inception two years ago. Being the
top grossing comedy tour in history had not meant diddley squat in
Hollywood until director Spike Lee came along.
</P>
<P>
   And that just amazes him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who ever heard of a tour where you're selling out 20,000 seats
(a show) in two years?'' Lee says. ``We're not talking about Janet
Jackson. We're talking about four comedians onstage with nothing
more than a microphone, who have the audience captivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee documents this underground phenomenon that's been sweeping
urban America in his latest movie, which opens today, ``The
Original Kings of Comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The film taps into the pulse of what is really a throwback to a
comic tradition started in the black community at the turn of the
20th century and includes such legendary comics as Jackie ``Moms''
Mabley right next to today's stars like Chris Tucker and the Kings
of Comedy.
</P>
<P>
   But the four comedians wanted to expand their audience and pick
up where such ground-breaking films as Richard Pryor's ``Live on
the Sunset Strip,'' Eddie Murphy's ``Raw'' and Martin Lawrence's
``You So Crazy'' left off.
</P>
<P>
   If only somebody in Hollywood would get a clue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is, they didn't know who the guys were,''
says Walter Latham, the mastermind behind the ``Kings of Comedy''
tour. ``And that was our selling point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's these guys you say you don't know, but when they go to
Washington D.C., they sell 55,000 tickets,'' Latham says. ``Chicago
_ they sell 48,000 tickets. Every year they sell more tickets. So
someone knows who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   So why haven't the Kings of Comedy caught on with mainstream
America yet?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we've got urban fans and have had them for a long
time without any media coverage. Well, the movie will expose (the
concert) to the general public, the masses of America,'' says
Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   And producer David M. Gale thinks the appeal of the ``Kings''
will be across the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that line, `Funny is funny,''' says Gale. ``Whether
you're black or white or you're young or you're older, it has that
effect. There were a couple of jokes I didn't get the first time
around, but what's really cool about this movie is you start to
understand the culture that maybe you didn't appreciate before.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee says he knew who the comedians were, even though he'd only
before worked with Mac, who was part of the ensemble cast for the
Spike Lee movie ``Get on the Bus.''
</P>
<P>
   The other comedians on the tour are mostly familiar to audiences
through television. Harvey stars in the WB's ``The Steve Harvey
Show'' and hosts the cable series ``Showtime at the Apollo.''
Hughley stars in the sitcom ``The Hughleys,'' formerly on ABC and
moving to UPN in the fall. Cedric the Entertainer co-stars with
Harvey on the ``Steve Harvey Show,'' and he also appeared in Martin
Lawrence's summer hit comedy, ``Big Momma's House.''
</P>
<P>
   The four did this while touring as the ``Kings of Comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee admits that before shooting the film he had never seen the
``Kings of Comedy'' show live because of his work schedule.
Although he had just finished shooting ``Bamboozled,'' a comedy
which stars Damon Wayans, Jada Pinkett-Smith, Tommy Davidson and
Savion Glover, he says he jumped at the chance after seeing a tape
of the concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw this great sense of community,'' Lee says about the
phenomenon of the tour. ``People (were) coming from all around the
country and putting on their Sunday best _ you know, it's a big
night to just have a good time and laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, laughter is therapuetic.''
</P>
<P>
   While making the film, Lee says he got a big dose of therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dyin' (of laughter),'' Lee says. ``And you surely
shouldn't do that because then you're neglecting what you're there
for. But I'll be honest, sometimes I was negligent in my job, I was
laughing so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Original Kings of Comedy'' is not Lee's first comedy
concert.
</P>
<P>
   He directed John Leguizamo in an HBO special that he says helped
prepare him for this one.
</P>
<P>
   Lee blanketed the Coliseum in Charlotte, N.C. _ where the film
was shot _ with cameras and a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   He says he filmed everything he could, from members of the
audience laughing so hard that they're standing up and clapping, to
the comedians doing their shtick on stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted people to see this and think they're actually in the
Charlotte Coliseum among this great mass of humanity laughing,''
Lee says.
</P>
<P>
   Lee also tried to show the comics when they weren't on, getting
footage of the guys just killing time playing cards or throwing
around a basketball, some of which was staged for the film's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cats are great athletes,'' says Hughley says about his
fellow comedians. ``I never was. I was so deep on the bench they
put me on a futon.''
</P>
<P>
   The cameras also tried to capture the relationship between the
comedians.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the thing we do most that didn't get captured on film
is trade cigars,'' says Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we don't trade cigars,'' Hughley chimes in. ``Steve takes
my damn cigars.''
</P>
<P>
   Mac says that despite what it might look like on film, the truth
is they really don't spend all that much time together off stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't got no business, a 42-year-old man, horning in on
everything they do, every place they go,'' he says. ``I don't like
that. Too much of everything leaves something to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody respects everybody's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Mac says that's probably why the tour has been so successful for
them: They're all equals. And that's probably why they got a movie
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good things come to those who wait,'' he says. ``And we've
been waiting a long time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1607EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0230 </DOCNO>
