</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-HOSTAGES-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELEASE OF WESTERN HOSTAGES DELAYED AS DEAL-MAKING CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ The entrepreneurs of the Sulu Sea are on
to their biggest deal yet, and like deal-making anywhere, the
last-minute bargaining appears to be intense.
</P>
<P>
   The business is kidnapping, and the deal involves nine Western
vacationers and four local workers who were seized by Muslim rebels
from an island diving resort nearly four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Westerners were to have been released Thursday in exchange
for a payment that could reach several million dollars, but
something has caused a delay. Officially, the reason is weather,
but local officials say the real snag seems to involve money.
</P>
<P>
   The release has been brokered by Libya, which has sent a plane
to fly the captives to Tripoli before they are sent home. Local
reports say the Libyans are prepared to give the hostage takers
millions of dollars in what is being described as development aid.
</P>
<P>
   But prospects for smooth negotiations cannot have been helped by
the comments on Thursday of Ricardo Puno, a spokesman for President
Joseph Estrada, who said: ``Once this matter is resolved, and it
will be resolved sooner or later, the government is going to take
certain actions against them. They're not going to have an easy
life after this.''
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting release are two Germans, two South Africans, two Finns,
two French citizens and a French-Lebanese woman as well as three
Malaysians and a Filipino from the diving resort. Three French
television journalists who trekked in to interview the hostages are
also being held, as well as a dozen evangelical Christians who said
they wanted to pray with them and may have remained voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny island of Jolo, in a remote area that for centuries has
been home to pirates and roaming bands of brigands, is already
awash in cash from a dozen earlier releases.
</P>
<P>
   The thatched villages and jungle-covered mountains have come
alive with gem dealers and gun runners. The 1,000-peso note _ worth
$22 and rarely seen outside the country's major cities _ has become
common currency.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippine military says as much as $5.5 million in ransom
has already been paid to the kidnappers, a Muslim rebel group
numbering only a few hundred.
</P>
<P>
   From among the original hostages a German woman, six Malaysian
resort workers and several other captives have been released after
separate deals were struck.
</P>
<P>
   With those payments, the group, calling itself Abu Sayyaf and
claiming to be fighting for a separate Muslim state, has entered
the big time in the area's kidnapping industry. The usual going
rate, local officials say, is $5,000 per hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine government policy bars the payment of ransoms, so the
payments for hostages are generally described as ``room and
board.'' But little of the money paid so far seems to have been
spent on accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   According to reporters who have visited them, they have been fed
a skimpy diet of rice and sardines and have slept on the ground,
hustled by their captors through the jungle whenever military
patrols approached. Through their visitors they have sent periodic
messages of anger and despair, sometimes threatening suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Since the original 21 people were seized on April 23 from the
Malaysian diving resort of Sipadan _ a short speedboat ride from
the islands of the southern Philippines _ a dozen news reporters
have been captured and released.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When 10 European journalists were seized in June, their editors
paid $25,000 for their freedom in what they described as a ``gift''
in return for their interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Others who managed to get out after interviewing the hostages
were stripped of their watches, tape recorders, cameras and
sometimes shoes. According to other journalists, a number of
reporters paid cash for their safe passage.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some officials here say that one reason for the current
delay involves negotiations for the freedom of the three French
television journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In his comments Thursday, Puno said, ``The government is
concerned about this kind of thing becoming a continuing
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   But there seemed to be little it could do to halt the
long-established kidnapping industry, in which gunmen disappear
into the local population once they have received payment.
</P>
<P>
   Jolo island is now a battleground filled with thousands of
frustrated Philippine soldiers who have been able to take little
action as long as the hostages are held.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear that in the last couple of years they have
stepped up their kidnapping activities basically as a fund-raising
exercise,'' Puno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intelligence groups are working double time to try to
determine what gunrunning syndicates are being contacted, where are
the possible sources going to be, and we're also trying to get
assistance from other countries,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with millions to spend, Abu Sayyaf could become a real
military force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1613EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
