<SLUG> BC-FILM-CECIL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKS GREAT, BUT `CELL' IS A VILE PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood's latest serial-killer thriller, ``The Cell,'' is a
visually impressive but exceedingly unpleasant little nail-biter
about a child psychologist (Jennifer Lopez) who uses some new
virtual-reality gizmo that allows her to enter the subconscious
mind of her patients.
</P>
<P>
   One day, a handsome FBI agent (Vince Vaughn) knocks on her door
with a problem only she can solve: It seems a brutal ladykiller
(Vincent D'Onofrio) has gone into a coma just as he was captured,
and his latest victim is imprisoned in some elaborate torture
chamber in some unknown remote location.
</P>
<P>
   Without too much hesitation, she jumps right into the monster's
brain, hoping to find his inner child, get its sympathy and
convince it to reveal the location of the titular prison cell
before it's too late. And believe you me, this guy's mind is not a
pretty place.
</P>
<P>
   If there's any good news about the result of this unlikely
quest, it's that Lopez proves once again she has no trouble
carrying a movie on her attractive shoulders. And first-time
feature filmmaker Tarsem Singh also establishes what must be a new
high in computer-generated surrealist imagery _ taking up more than
half the running time with Daliesque visuals.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there's so many dream sequences that they
soon lose their impact, and become rather boring. In fact, seeing
this movie is a bit like hearing a lengthy discourse on someone
else's nightmare: it may mean a lot to him, but it soon beccomes
extremely tiresome to you.
</P>
<P>
   And since most of what we see is happening in someone's
subconscious mind and not _ we're often reminded by the script _
``really happening,'' it gives the filmmakers license to load the
movie down with stomach-turning scenes of women being bound and
tortured, people being disemboweled and children being horrendously
abused.
</P>
<P>
   You may find a better way to spend an hour-and-a-half.
</P>
<P>
   THE CELL
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Tarsem Singh
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Mark Protosevich
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Jennifer Lopez, Vince Vaughn, Vincent D'Onofrio
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 108 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: R, for torture scenes and horror violence
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C
</P>
</TEXT>
