<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HIGH NOON': THE DAY GARY COOPER DIDN'T WALK DOWN MAIN STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (Broadcast notes at end of review. Time and station are for New
York area; see local listings.) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no need to get in a snit about remaking a movie, however
great. Every half-century or so, even a classic can use some
dusting off. But ``High Noon''? Even people who have never seen the
film probably have an image of Gary Cooper as the heroic marshal
striding down Main Street, alone, to face a killer. Few movies have
been so inseparable from the star, or so deeply embedded in the
popular imagination. (Harry Thomason, who produced Bill Clinton's
lone walk along a long corridor before his entrance at the
Democratic convention this week, said he was inspired by that
scene; for the record, Cooper was not shot from such a low angle
that his body looked as elongated as a space invader's.)
</P>
<P>
   The new TBS version is a faithful, pallid, thoroughly
wrongheaded echo of the 1952 original. The laughable phrase ``the
Tom Skerritt `High Noon''' merely hints at the many problems with
this movie, which doesn't begin to do what good remakes can:
reinvent a film for a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   What is ``High Noon'' divorced from Cooper's haunting presence?
Even without him, there could have been new life in the story of
Will Kane, the marshall who cleaned up Hadleyville. On the day he
marries, Kane is about to leave town with his Quaker bride when he
learns that Frank Miller, a killer he sent to prison, is arriving
on the noon train and gunning for him.
</P>
<P>
   The tale is fraught with moral issues. Should Kane stay and
defend himself, or listen to his pacifist wife and flee? That
question should carry even more resonance today, when the legacy of
the Vietnam War makes the wife's arguments more familiar than they
might have been in the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   And it is loaded with mythic Western figures in addition to the
noble marshal. There are the archetypal light and dark women: Amy
Kane, the virginal bride (Grace Kelly in the original), and Helen
Ramirez, the sensual Mexican who used to be the lover of both Kane
and Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Though the script makes few changes in Carl Foreman's original
screenplay, here the archetypes become caricatures. Every choice
backfires. The film maintains the idea of unfolding in real time,
running an hour and a quarter from the minute Kane hears that
Miller is coming until the train arrives. That stunt demands the
tautness that Fred Zinnemann brought to the original, but here Rod
Hardy's direction and pacing are slack. And how absurd is it to
shoot a film in real time, then break it up with commercials?
</P>
<P>
   The acting is timid. As Amy, who threatens to leave if her
husband stays to fight, Susanna Thompson is washed out and whiny.
(Grace Kelly's bride, shining with vitality, was no wimp.) Maria
Conchita Alonso seems equally worn down as Helen, who is supposed
to be fiercely in love with Kane.
</P>
<P>
   Skerritt doesn't even get points for having the gall to take on
the Cooper role because he does nothing to try to make it his own.
He mumbles through most of the movie. At one point he squints as a
reaction to bad news. As he lumbers from the church to the saloon
trying to deputize the townsmen, he looks pathetic rather than
brave. He might as well be an amateur impressionist doing Gary
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Diamond (Mike Kellerman on ``Homicide'') plays the callow,
selfish deputy, Harvey Pell, and Michael Madsen is the villainous
Miller. Reed looks conspicuously thin, while Madsen makes you
wonder how Miller ate so well in prison. The fact that such details
leap out is a sign of how uninvolving the movie is.
</P>
<P>
   And despite its slavish fidelity, this new version does not
include one original element that might have helped: the theme
song. (The producers were not able to get the rights.) ``Do Not
Forsake Me, Oh My Darling,'' runs through the original so
effectively it has become a Western anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Any remake deserves to be taken on its own terms, but the best
that can be said about the new ``High Noon'' is: Rent the old one
(or watch it on Turner Classic Movies on Sunday at 2 p.m.). It
holds up remarkably well and explains why Gary Cooper helped define
the Hollywood Western at its height.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HIGH NOON'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Sunday on TBS
</P>
<P>
   Teleplay by Carl Foreman and T.S. Cook, based on the screenplay
``High Noon'' by Foreman and the magazine article ``The Tin Star''
by John W. Cunningham. Rod Hardy, director; Karen Sharpe Kramer,
co-executive producer; Ted Bauman, producer; Robert McLachlan,
director of photography; Rick Roberts, production designer. Music
composed and conducted by Allyn Ferguson. Produced by Rosemont
Productions International Ltd. David A. Rosemont, executive
producer.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Tom Skerritt (Will Kane), Susanna Thompson (Amy Kane),
Reed Diamond (Harvey Pell), Maria Conchita Alonso (Helen Ramirez),
Dennis Weaver (Mart Howe), August Schellenberg (Antonio) and
Michael Madsen (Frank Miller).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
