<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STEAL-SPI </SLUG>
  
 `STEAL' POSITIVELY PORTRAYS NOTORIOUS '60s PROTESTER  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood movies of the '80s and '90s have tended to be very
hard on the student protesters of the '60s, invariably portraying
them as self-indulgent, dope-smoking cowards who spit on the flag
and didn't have the guts to fight in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Greenwald's ``Steal This Movie'' balances this ledger
somewhat with an unashamedly positive look at the rise of the '60s
counterculture in terms of a mostly admiring chronicle of the life
of one of its most notorious figures: Abbie Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   There's some irony here because Hoffman _ the self-appointed
leader of the handful of ``Yippie'' protesters at the 1968 Chicago
Democratic Convention _ has gone down in history as perhaps the
least admirable of the '60s radicals: a publicity-seeking clown who
represented little but his own ego.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenwald's movie _ and Vincent D'Onofrio's fearless (if
uneven) portrayal _ dig beneath this stereotype to find a character
of considerable humanity and much personal courage who paid a
tremendous personal price for the in-your-face audacity that so
enraged the Nixon administration and the '60s establishment.
</P>
<P>
   The story opens in 1977, from the point of view of a reluctant
magazine reporter summoned to a secret meeting with Hoffman, who
has been living on the run and undercover for too many years and is
now a paranoid wreck who desperately wants the reporter to tell the
``true story'' of his life.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the film takes a ``Citizen Kane'' approach, telling
Hoffman's story in flashbacks sparked by the reporter's interviews
with a succession of witnesses, most prominently his longtime
attorney Gerry Lefcourt (Kevin Pollack) and his long-suffering and
magnificently supportive wife, Anita (Janeane Garofalo).
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman is depicted as a nice New York Jewish kid whose path is
bent after being assaulted by a red-neck lawman while working for
the civil rights movement in the South. He finds a home in the
emerging '60s revolution and brief media glory as the most
uncooperative defendant in the famous trial of the ``Chicago
Seven.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter half of his life is much sadder, and the last third
of the movie is out to prove (as if any one would doubt it) that,
after Chicago, Hoffman was endlessly and illegally hounded by the
FBI and then personally set up by J. Edgar Hoover in a drug sting
that put him on the run for six years.
</P>
<P>
   The handsome, 6-foot-3 D'Onofrio looks nothing at all like the
short, homely Hoffman; his accent keeps shifting incongruously
between New England and the deep South. The movie has some clumsy
elements (a terrible Nixon vocal impersonation on the soundtrack,
for one), and it's noticeably fuzzy about Hoffman's motives in the
big-time drug deal that was his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenwald, who knew Hoffman in his later years, infuses the
film with authenticity (to the point of having co-defendant Tom
Hayden played by his real-life son) and does an excellent job of
evoking the '60s in not just the usual bold strokes and barrage of
classic rock music but in a string of delicate small touches that
could only come from a veteran of the era.
</P>
<P>
   D'Onofrio's brash, take-no-prisoners performance also captures
something elemental about the '60s and works well off Garofalo to
create a genuinely moving love story that is so strong it's somehow
not hindered a bit when the fugitive Hoffman takes on a lover
(Jeanne Tripplehorn), and his marriage turns into a rather awkward
menage-a-trois.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald (best known for the TV-movie ``The Burning Bed'') has
infused his movie with nostalgic appeal, but it's actually aimed
less at aging boomers than at their children: an intention that's
wonderfully crystallized in a teary-eyed speech in which the
now-50ish Hoffman praises the ``fire of youth'' and its absolute
necessity to endlessly question authority, challenge the system and
accept no compromise.
</P>
<P>
   STEAL THIS MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Robert Greenwald
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Bruce Graham
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Vincent D'Onofrio, Janeane Garofalo, Jeanne Tripplehorn,
Kevin Pollack
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 108 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: R, for language and drug scenes
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
