<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALVESTON-GREATSTORM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTURY AFTER THE STORM, GALVESTON CELEBRATES SPIRIT OF SURVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanied by GALVESTON-IF YOU GO)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems, perhaps, an odd event for a tourist destination to be
commemorating _ the 100th anniversary of the greatest natural
disaster in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   But with their weekend-long observance next month, the folks in
Galveston are not celebrating the great hurricane of 1900, which on
Sept. 8, 1900, virtually decimated the island, killing more than
6,000 people and destroying more than 3,000 buildings. They're
really honoring the city itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That storm was the defining moment in Galveston's history. It
wasn't just an ordinary storm; it has everything to do with the
spirit of the community and its survival,'' says Maureen Patton, a
Galveston native who now is director of the Grand 1894 Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Galveston could have packed up their tents and
left, but they didn't. The way they rebuilt this city really stands
as a great human accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The coastal city has been observing the storm's anniversary all
year with a series of lectures, exhibits and tours, culminating in
a full weekend of activities Sept. 8-10. There will be a
communitywide tribute, featuring CBS anchor Dan Rather; a
dedication ceremony for a public sculpture by a fourth-generation
Galveston artist; a series of open houses and parties; and arts
events including a modern dance performance and a play, both
centered on the storm and commissioned for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   And although the events will recognize the great losses suffered
by Galveston _ the weekend schedule includes the placement of a
wreath at the site of St. Mary's Orphanage, where 90 children and
at least 10 nuns perished _ the theme of the weekend is survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to share with people who are visiting, look at what
happened to this city, but look at what its citizens did to rebuild
it because they loved it so much,'' says Ruby Adams, operations
manager at the Strand Theatre, which on Sept. 8 will present the
regional premiere of ``Malhado,'' a fictionalized account of the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   The play, by New York playwright and director DeLora Whitney, a
Galveston native, is set in the two-week period before, during and
after the storm. Though fictionalized, it draws from the
experiences of real survivors.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the play re-creates, Galveston was one of the
richest cities and biggest ports in the United States. Its 37,000
residents enjoyed an atmosphere of sophistication and luxury _ they
were the first in Texas to enjoy electricity and telephones. And,
perhaps tellingly, because they had lived through storms in the
past, many ignored the signs that a great hurricane was
approaching.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is sometimes assumed that the entire island was
flattened by the 1900 storm, many buildings survived in some
fashion, and thanks to a massive rebuilding effort immediately
after the hurricane, many parts of the island look much as they did
a century ago. The island boasts about 1,500 buildings and four
districts on the National Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change precipitated by the storm, in fact, has
become Galveston's calling card _ the 17-foot-high, three-mile-long
seawall, built in the two years following the storm at a cost of
$1.5 million. (The wall was later extended to 11 miles long.) Also,
between 1904 and 1910, the elevation of the entire island was
lifted by several feet, with each existing structure lifted from
its foundation and filled underneath with sand.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston never fully recovered its stature as one of America's
richest cities, but it did return to prominence as a tourist
destination, a tradition that continues to this day. In fact, 7
million visitors are counted annually, according to figures from
the island's convention and visitors bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Many are still drawn by the beach, says Christine Hopkins,
spokeswoman for the Galveston Island Convention and Visitors
Bureau, but especially in the past five years, they've come to see
other attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The venerable Moody Gardens opened an acclaimed aquarium last
year, joining its IMAX theater, rain-forest exhibit and other
displays. The posh San Luis Resort and the historic Hotel Galvez
both recently completed multimillion-dollar renovations. Downtown
renovation has spread to the Postoffice Street Arts &AMP; Entertainment
District, home to several new restaurants, clubs and art galleries.
And Carnival Cruise Lines will begin short cruises to Mexico from
Galveston's newly renovated Texas Cruise Ship Terminal in
September; Royal Caribbean will also offer some Galveston-based
cruises next year.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, many of the storm-related events will be held in or
near buildings or areas that date to the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   The Strand Theatre, for instance, housed in a former sail
factory built in 1871, is a storm survivor. So is the Grand 1894
Opera House, where an original piece by the Parsons Dance Company
of New York will premiere Sept. 9; the opera hall was barely 5
years old when the hurricane ripped off its roof and destroyed
portions of the back wall, but the citizens had it restored and
operating within a year.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of spirit Maureen Patton and the opera house
board wanted to commemorate with its commissioned dance. And don't
think that spirit is not alive today.
</P>
<P>
   New York choreographer David Parsons was chosen to create the
dance, titled ``The Whip,'' because of his unique connection to the
city. The first time he performed in Galveston, some 15 years ago,
was on a day a hurricane was forecast to hit the coast. He and the
opera house managers talked it over. The show went on, and that
night, he and his dancers rode out the storm at a Galveston hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I laughingly said at the time, we need to commission a work
from you commemorating a hurricane, because you've been through
one,'' Patton says. ``So when this came up and we really started
thinking about doing it, it was really the perfect thing. Because
that's what this is all really about, celebrating how people's
spirit can be undaunted by whatever befalls them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
