<HEADLINE>
IF YOU GO TO GALVESTON ...
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanies GALVESTON-GREAT STORM)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you go:
</P>
<P>
   Now open: ``The Great Storm,'' a 27-minute documentary about the
1900 Galveston hurricane, is showing at the Pier 21 Theater, 21st
Street at Port Industrial Boulevard. Showings are every hour on the
hour, from 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Sunday-Thursday; 11 a.m. to 8 p.m.
Friday and Saturday. Adults, $3.50; children and seniors, $2.50;
children 6 and under, free. (409) 763-8808.
</P>
<P>
   In September:
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 8: 9:30 a.m., Placing of the Wreath ceremony, St. Mary's
Orphanage site, 69th and Seawall Boulevard, commemorating the 90
orphanage children and 10 nuns who died in the storm. A Mass will
follow in memory of all storm victims at Sacred Heart Catholic
Church, 11th Street and Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 8: 7:30 p.m., Centennial Tribute, Kermit Courville
Stadium, 27th Street and Avenue N. Keynote speaker Dan Rather will
be joined by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, other dignitaries, local
bands, bagpipers and a communitywide chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 8: 8 p.m., regional premiere of ``Malhado: The Storm of
the Century,'' by DeLora Whitney, at the Strand Theatre, 2317
Ship's Mechanic's Row. This performance is free. Additional
performances 8 p.m. Sept. 9; 2:30 p.m. Sept. 10; 8 p.m. Sept.
15-16; 2:30 p.m. Sept. 17; tickets are $15 each. (409) 763-4591.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 9: 11 a.m. Dedication of ``Place of Remembrance,'' a
bronze statue by Galveston artist David Moore. The 12-foot
sculpture will be placed at Seawall Boulevard and 48th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 9: 6-9 p.m., ArtWalk, Historic Strand and Postoffice
Street districts. Galveston Art Center, (409) 763-2403.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 9: 8 p.m., Parsons Dance Company, presenting a
commissioned piece, ``The Whip,'' at Galveston's Grand 1894 Opera
House, 2020 Postoffice St. Tickets, $16.50-$70. (800) 821-1894.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 10: Memorials and open houses throughout the city,
including events at the 1859 Ashton Villa, 1838 Michel Menard
House, and the 1839 Samuel May Williams House. Information:
Galveston Historical Foundation, (409) 765-7834.
</P>
<P>
   Information: For general information about Galveston, contact
the Galveston Island Visitors Center, (888) 425-4753;
www.galvestoncvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Rodriguez
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
