A4764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-FORD-NYT &LR;      08-17 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-FORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD HIGHLIGHT FILM STARTED EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Childhood memories are quirky, sometimes not so much
in what they leave in as what they leave out. I remember watching
the fourth game of the 1950 World Series on television _ it was an
October afternoon, a time on the calendar when kids across the
country suddenly developed mysterious illnesses and had to stay
home from school, and no one had even dreamed of playing a World
Series game at night.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember a single pitch thrown by Whitey Ford, a
21-year-old left-handed Yankee rookie, as he went into the ninth
inning that day having held the National League champs, the
Phillies, scoreless. What I remember was Casey Stengel, the old,
bowlegged Yankee manager, leaving the mound with Ford after having
taken him out of the game and actually apologizing to the sellout
crowd in Yankee Stadium for doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Vivid in my memory is Stengel's shrug, palms up at his sides,
gesturing in response to the mixture of cheers for Ford and boos
for his removal. It was a display of sympathy for the kid from
Astoria, Queens, who just a few years earlier was playing in street
stickball games, and now under a national spotlight and World
Series pressure had pitched so beautifully. The fans believed the
young man deserved to finish the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had the Phillies shut out by 5-0 when, with two out and two
on, Gene Woodling muffed a fly ball in left field. Two runs scored.
Mike Goliat followed with a single through the left side of the
infield. And that is when Stengel came out of the dugout and
motioned for a relief pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Allie Reynolds retired the last batter and Ford got his victory.
Ford would go on to win nine more games in World Series play, a
record, as well as break a Babe Ruth pitching mark with 33
consecutive scoreless innings in World Series games. In 16 major
league seasons, all with the Yankees, Ford won 236 games and lost
106, for the best winning percentage (.690) of any pitcher in the
20th century, and in 1974 he was elected to the Baseball Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   And on Sunday, in Yankee Stadium, the Yankees will hold Whitey
Ford Day, for 50 years of continuous service to the Yankees as a
player, a coach, a broadcaster, a consultant, and, finally, as
Chairman of the Board, the nickname he earned for being someone who
was regularly called upon in the clutch, and invariably came
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees called and asked if I'd be open to a day for me,''
Ford said Wednesday by phone from his home in Lake Success on Long
Island. ``Twenty minutes later I called back: `That'll be fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he's feeling fine _ ``a lot better than I was
a few months ago'' _ and that he was finished with the radiation
treatments he had been undergoing after removal of a cancerous
brain tumor from the left side of his head in November. Five years
ago, he went through a similar procedure after a cancerous tumor
had been discovered on the right side of his brain.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when a day for you is approaching, it is a time for
reminiscence. He remembers being in awe of Joe DiMaggio _ ``my hero
since I was 8 years old and just starting to follow baseball'' _
and seeing him and Lou Gehrig in 1938 from a bleacher seat. Ford
recalled meeting a very shy Yogi Berra on the day in 1947 when
Berra came up for the first time to the Yankees, from Newark, and
Ford was in the dugout after having just signed his first contract
with the Yankees, at age 17.
</P>
<P>
   And he laughed about his days as bon vivant on the road with
Billy Martin and Mickey Mantle, and being ``preached'' to by
Stengel about the dangers of ruining their careers by staying out
late. (At one point in the 1962 World Series against the Giants,
Stengel told them: ``If you're trying to outdrink San Francisco,
you're overmatched.'')
</P>
<P>
   One has to believe that whatever Ford was doing, he wasn't doing
it _ or no longer was doing it _ to harmful excess. When he
retired, partway in the 1967 season, it was because of problems
with his pitching elbow.
</P>
<P>
   While there were always rumors that he may have scuffed or
moistened a ball or two or more in his time, success for the
5-foot-10-inch, 180-pound Ford was due to great control, superb
breaking balls and an uncanny wit on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would be amazed,'' he once said, ``how many important outs
you can get by working the count down to where the hitter is sure
you're going to throw to his weakness and then throw to his power
instead.''
</P>
<P>
   What would he like to be remembered for? ``For being nice,
having a good family life, and I think I was liked by other
players,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And his greatest baseball memory? ``Not one single moment stands
out,'' he said. But literally a series of moments: pitching in 11
World Series in his first 13 seasons in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the rest of us, his first World Series, 50 years ago
this year, and that poignant moment when he was sent to the
showers, remains most compelling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
