<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4768 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      08-17 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 1960s Story, About Hoffman
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Robert Greenwald said the idea for making his new
film, ``Steal This Movie!,'' about the life of the 1960s
radical-prankster Abbie Hoffman, began when he was talking to his
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in their 20s, college-educated young women who had
great interest and excitement about the '60s,'' he said. ``You
know, the tie-dyed clothes, the music. They even heard rumors there
were drugs back then. But they didn't know much more about it than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A short while later, while at a Los Angeles bookstore, he came
across an old copy of ``Letters From the Underground,'' the book of
correspondence between Hoffman, who died in 1989, and his wife,
Anita, during the years the radical was living incognito, on the
run from the law. ``It was a wonderful love story,'' Greenwald
said. ``A bell went off. This would make a wonderful movie.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, he said, the sudden re-emergence of mass street
protests _ at the World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle last
year, at the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia and,
again this week, at the Democratic National Convention in Los
Angeles _ has only made the story of Hoffman's emergence at the
1968 Democratic convention in Chicago and his subsequent trial,
flight and descent into manic-depression more relevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, when we finished the movie and delivered it to
Lions Gate Films to be distributed, the thinking was that it would
appeal mostly to people who were there back then, to baby boomers
and others interested in the nostalgia factor,'' Greenwald said.
``Then, after the WTO demonstrations, it was like an alarm clock
went off. We started getting letters from youth groups all around
the country who wanted to screen the film. You know, there's a
scene in the film where the protesters are trying to get a permit,
and they keep getting the runaround, and it's the same sort of
thing that happened to the protesters in Philadelphia and Los
Angeles this year. It's eerie, like history repeating itself.''
</P>
<P>
   After he read the book, he said, he tracked down Anita Hoffman
in California and got to know her. ``We played volleyball together
in Venice, like all good radicals,'' he said. He told how he had
discussed the '60s with his daughters, how he found her book and
now wanted to make it into a movie. ``She said, `Absolutely not.
It's Hollywood and they'll just screw it up.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said he promised to make the movie independent of any studio
_ ``there wasn't any studio that was going to make a movie on this
subject, anyway'' _ and promised to show her every draft of the
screenplay. And he sent her some of the television movies he had
made in the past, like ``Forgotten Prisoners'' in 1990 (about a
crusading lawyer for Amnesty International) and ``The Burning Bed''
in 1984 (about spousal abuse), and finally Hoffman said he could go
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   That was three and a half years ago, Greenwald said. He
commissioned a screenplay, began to interview people about
Hoffman's life and started to think about casting and raising
production money. ``We got very lucky,'' he said. ``There was
something called a hedge fund. I'll never understand what it is,
but they had the money and wanted to invest it.'' In the end,
Vincent D'Onofrio was cast as Abbie and Janeane Garofalo as Anita,
who died in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Two pre-release screenings were set for this week in Los
Angeles, for some of the people who were in town to protest at the
convention. And the film's limited release begins Friday in New
York and a few other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Greenwald said, he hopes his daughters will have at least a
little better understanding of what the '60s were about.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movie is about that period of time,'' he said. ``And
Abbie is the tour guide.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramblin' Jack Revisited
</P>
<P>
   Aiyana Elliott said she ``did not intend to make a personal film
when I set out to make this movie; I wanted to make as objective a
film about my dad as I could.'' But in the making, ``The Ballad of
Ramblin' Jack,'' a documentary about her father, the folk singer
Jack Elliott, turned into a much more personal film than she had
ever anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was this interview I did with my mother,'' Elliott
said. ``She was just talking to me, her daughter, and talking about
what it had been like for me to grow up with my dad on the road all
the time. And when we brought the footage back to New York, our
editor looked at it and said that it was really interesting. It
changed the whole direction of the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Her film was screened at the Sundance Film Festival in January,
with her father in the audience, seeing it for the first time. He
had resisted making the film, she said, and was not at all
comfortable with some of the more personal material about their
family life. ``But I think it helped for him to see it with an
audience,'' she said, ``to hear them laugh and to applaud and to
see how people were reacting to his story.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott is a contemporary of such legendary folk artists as
Woody Guthrie and Pete Seeger, and in the critically acclaimed
film, which opened in New York on Wednesday, their stories
intertwine with his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out thinking it would be a more traditional verite
film, following my dad around with the camera, listening to his
stories,'' she said. ``It would be a natural. But then the movie
changed, and it was very difficult to tell such a personal story,
sometimes very painful. I often wondered if it wasn't just creating
more tension and problems for me and my dad, but in the end, I
think we have gotten closer because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Men of Summer
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dinner said he hadn't seen Clint Eastwood's ``Space
Cowboys'' yet, and it's just a coincidence that he, too, had a
summer movie coming out in which older actors played the central
roles. ``It's kind of nice to be able to see these actors in a
summer movie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner's film is ``The Crew,'' a comedy that opens August 25
about a foursome of aging gangsters in a Miami Beach hotel who
inadvertently find themselves in a dangerous duel with a South
American drug lord. Burt Reynolds, Richard Dreyfuss, Dan Hedaya and
Seymour Cassell play the old wise guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the audience is used to the big extravaganzas, and now
it's August and maybe it's time for some older actors and some
smaller movies that aren't all about special effects,'' Dinner
said. ``There's always the conventional wisdom that in the summer
the kids are out of school, so all the movies have to be geared to
kids. Maybe the success of a `Space Cowboys' can show that it
doesn't always have to be like that. Besides, I grew up watching
all of these actors. It's fun to see them working in a summer movie
again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
