<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4771 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-FASH-LADYLIKE-HNS &LR;      08-17 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASH-LADYLIKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTING FOR LADYLIKE LOOKS 
WITH PHOTOS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
(UNDATED) It had to happen: Almost the minute large companies
amended their dress codes to read ``casual every day,'' fashion
designers declared that dressing up is back in style.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I think this trend of ladylike dressing up will be one that is
accepted very readily,'' said LaVelle Olexa, senior vice president
of fashion merchandising for Lord &AMP; Taylor. And she views the trend
as positive for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw something recently about world power that said the
dressed have always ruled the undressed,'' Olexa said. ``Now I see
some men going to work looking like little boys going off to
camp.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Casual every day really started way back in the '60s, when
women didn't have to wear hats and gloves to work anymore,'' said
Jaqui Lividini, senior vice president of fashion merchandising and
communications for Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, she said, it was spoken of as ``the damnation of
America, but now dressing is all about options. There are days when
you really want a pulled-together look. However, I think a woman is
going to wear what's most comfortable and what's right for her.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there is no reason a woman cannot dress casually
one day and glamour-puss perfect the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dress down more when I go to work than I did a couple of
years ago,'' said Roz Pactor, vice president and fashion director
for Foley's, ``but I believe we went to extremes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every jacket was replaced with a twin set,'' Pactor said. ``We
went way too casual in women's wear, and now I think customers are
ready to put a jacket on again. They'll feel more complete.''
</P>
<P>
   The return of the '80s lady is certainly the biggest push for
fall, said Erin Carmack, director of fashion presentation for
Neiman Marcus, ``but it's a return to the '80s that's modern and
new _ an uptown lady. The designers borrowed a little bit from each
decade from the 1920s forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Several elements go into achieving this fall's new ladylike
look, and in the clothing department the return of the suit is key.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suits haven't been around in a lot of seasons,'' Lividini
said, ``so now they look right again.''
</P>
<P>
   Suits this year have peplums with nipped-in waists so that
jackets will need to be worn buttoned for best effect, perhaps even
with a narrow belt. The adventurous might make that a narrow
ostrich or even rhinestone belt.
</P>
<P>
   Skirts tend to be longer, often below the knee for slim designs,
but Lividini sees more volume returning in skirts with pleats and
kilts _ ``skirts with some movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladylike outerwear is going in the opposite direction, however.
Credit the '60s fitted coats and coat dresses, such as those worn
by Braniff flight attendants, for this trend to body-conscious fit.
Some coats also have belts across the back.
</P>
<P>
   The return of the blouse is another ladylike sign for fall, but
its style will surprise many.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the bow-tie blouse?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, no, you moan. Not the dreaded silk blouse with the floppy
bow tie!
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes. Shades of the feminist uniform. Dustin Hoffman in
``Tootsie'' and former Houston Mayor Kathy Whitmire at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   These blouses are already on store racks for fall, in matte silk
or shiny charmeuse, with attached or unattached ties.
</P>
<P>
   And _ would you believe? _ shoulder pads are back, said
Stephanie McKinley, owner of Pixie &AMP; Ivy, a Houston boutique.
</P>
<P>
   For young women who have never worn the look, it will be fun and
a feminine way to dress professionally.
</P>
<P>
   More mature women might want to choose from wrap blouses or ones
with soft ruffles at the neck. In fact, young women are snapping
these up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are more girly than a business blouse, more feminine''
said Tess Hall, manager of Arden B in Houston's Galleria.
</P>
<P>
   All this talk of suits and feminine blouses by no means heralds
the demise of pant dressing. Pactor said pants are changing,
however, from straight legs to cigarette-slim styles such as the
high-waisted ones Audrey Hepburn wore. Pactor refers to these as
``Hollywood pants.''
</P>
<P>
   More ladylike dressing includes the return of pumps _ high- or
midheeled shoes with closed toes and either closed heels or
slingback straps. Heels range from sharp stilettos to thick and
stacked to little princess styles.
</P>
<P>
   Any of these heel designs bode well for the return of the
covered leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost have to get reacquainted with the look,'' Lividini
said. ``A woman will have to put a little more thought into getting
dressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lividini said Saks allowed its sales associates to go without
stockings for the summer, not only for comfort but because the
company wanted its personnel to reflect the new business-casual
attitude of its customers.
</P>
<P>
   For fall, however, she sees them returning to stockings because
of fashion trends.
</P>
<P>
   Colored or patterned hosiery is the modern take on this legwear
trend, and it is closed heels or heel straps that will keep
stockinged feet from slipping out of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the new pumps a matching handbag and perhaps a belt or
gloves. Yes, matchy-matchy is back, and if gloves are returning,
hats cannot be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   For fall, the beret will probably be the hat of choice, one that
effectively integrates sportswear fabrics such as tweed and leather
and patterns such as plaid with ladylike looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But handbags are the most important accessory this fall,''
said Harriet Hart, owner of the Houston shop that bears her name.
``There is lots of embellishment, with beads, feathers and fur.
It's almost like having a piece of jewelry.''
</P>
<P>
   But not quite.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl, diamond and even rhinestone jewelry will abound this
fall, shown off at the ears and neck by sleek, pulled-back
hairstyles, such as chignons worn at the base of the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Griffin, owner of Scruples in Houston, said today's
self-assured woman will go for this '80s bejeweled look, but it
won't be contrived. ``It's not the grunge look or the big beehive
hairdos you're seeing in the magazines. Most women are
self-confident enough to know what's best for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest news in jewelry is not Barbara Bush pearls but the
return of gold or gold-tone jewelry, especially large hoop
earrings. Maybe Charlie's Angels were not precisely ladylike, but
they were the inspiration for this retro trend.
</P>
<P>
   In handbags, the top-handled purse with rigid framing, one that
has to be carried by hand or looped over the forearm, looks best
with the new ladylike styles. And Pactor reports that manufacturers
are quickly switching from silver and pewter to gold-tone hardware,
both shiny and matte.
</P>
<P>
   Lividini is among fashion-industry insiders who see the return
of the little black dress, which surely was out of style for only
15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The return of pearl necklaces, from one strand to several and
with larger pearls, makes this wardrobe standard almost a must,
said Pactor.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman's Carmack cautions women against ``junking up'' their
ladylike looks by going overboard with accessories.
</P>
<P>
   With minimalist dressing, she said, the rule was look in the
mirror and take off one accessory before going out. ``Now the new
rule will be put on two more,'' Carmack said, ``but don't overdo
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind this fall's large hoop earrings is not a return
to gypsy fashion but rather a slight casualizing of the ladylike
looks. The same idea follows with shoulder-dusting chandelier
earrings, Carmack said, earrings that look like Venetian glass.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that smacks of Coco Chanel's classic styles appears hot
for fall. Karl Lagerfeld is reintroducing the quilted,
chain-handled accordion bag, and another Chanel classic popular
this summer _ camel-colored shoes with black toe caps _ will
continue through fall and winter, replacing the basic black shoe.
</P>
<P>
   xxxEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
