<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S A PEPLUM? (WITH PHOTO OF LAURA BUSH) 
BY LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
Fashion's return to ladylike styles this fall heralds the return of
the peplum.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But what, you may ask, is a peplum?
</P>
<P>
   Strictly speaking, it is the extension of a fitted jacket that
flares over the hips. A peplum may be cut in one piece with the
bodice or joined to it by a seam.
</P>
<P>
   Popular in the 1860s, peplums looked new again in the 1930s and
'40s.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently the style appeared in the over-the-top dressing of
the 1980s, when it was often executed in elaborate brocade cocktail
suits and styles dubbed ``fit and flare.''
</P>
<P>
   The best examples in recent years have been seen on women in the
political arena, especially in Washington, D.C., in that genre of
fashion dubbed ``inside the Beltway.''
</P>
<P>
   While the peplum's return this year is considered a retro
fashion look, women in Washington have clung to the style since the
'80s. Only a year ago, high fashion standards would have labeled
peplums tame or even boring _ a sort of female political uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush prefers the style for many of the jackets made for
her by designer Michael Faircloth, who works exclusively at Lily
Dodson in Dallas. The white suit Bush wore on the final night of
the Republican National Convention was a Faircloth design.
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth said the peplum is particularly good for women who
have lower and longer hips because it bridges the space from a tiny
waistline to the fullest part of the hips.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't like a real flouncy peplum. It looks too girly,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
