<HEADER>
A4775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EUROPEAN-DRESS-ART-NY     08-17 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-DRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN REVIEW: AN EYE FOR ART TO DRESS A ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 2,3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could say that art critics are almost always, inescapably,
writing about installation art, or at least the art of
installation. This is because they are usually writing about
exhibitions, that is, groupings of artworks whose physical
arrangement, or installation, is basic to their impact.
</P>
<P>
   These arrangements require an unusual, probably unteachable
talent for placing objects in space and in relation to one another,
one reason a doctorate in art history does not necessarily a
curator make. Poorly done, installations can be an assault on art
and viewer alike. At their best they can cast spells, convert the
skeptic, provide transcendent moments of seeing, and make all kinds
of points about art and its display.
</P>
<P>
   This is the case with ``Curios and Treasures,'' a modest, yet
serenely beautiful exhibition at the Costume Institute at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. Its 65 garments and accessories travel
through four or five centuries of European dress, touching down
lightly here and there.
</P>
<P>
   Some may find it a stretch to call this assortment an
exhibition. Organized by Myra Walker, acting associate curator in
charge of the institute, it is really little more than a potpourri
of items whose primary common trait seems to be that they have
almost never been exhibited since joining the institute's
collection. But Walker has chosen her items well, juxtaposed them
tellingly and given them plenty of space (which is slightly unusual
for the Costume Institute). And she has had excellent backup from
the museum's design department, especially where lighting is
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The results are close to magical: an elegant, meditative
atmosphere in which the art of wearable clothes is unusually
palpable. The overall effect is so different from Walker's previous
effort, the raucous and overcrowded ``Rock Style,'' that it almost
seems an act of penance. Compared to rock 'n' roll, this is the
``Moonlight'' Sonata. Which is not to condone the only misstep: the
piping in of various bits of music, at rather high volume _ a
waltz, something Baroque, something modern _ to clue visitors into
the show's shifting focus. This is another example of the
inexplicable practice, on the rise in museums, of asking people
concentrating on still, silent objects to use their ears, too. If
the art itself isn't deliberately making noise, nothing else
should.
</P>
<P>
   It is always interesting to see what happens when the Costume
Institute falls back on its own collection without benefit of
outside loans or some big theme or epochal frame. This show
includes garments plain and fancy, representing the efforts of
people famous, forgotten or never known. There are 19th- and
20th-century evening dresses and tea gowns, including a suite of
dresses by the great Mariano Fortuny; three rare men's doublets;
and a group of men's and women's at-home wear from the 17th and
18th centuries. This last section is especially spare, with seven
examples of the short, close-fitting jackets and bodices that women
typically wore over loose dresses, seemingly suspended in midair.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a small vitrine contrasts accessories and social strata.
On the one hand are richly embroidered gloves, slippers and silk
purses, mostly from 16th- and 17th-century Spain and England, items
clearly reserved for the palace-born. On the other are two simple
knitted wool caps and four leather shoes, all English and dating
from as early as the late 14th century. On the whole they resemble
sows' ears, except a sharp-toed shoe called a poulaine. It's a
little like a face-off between the royal portraiture of Velazquez
and one of Breugel's roiling village scenes.
</P>
<P>
   But the true sovereign of this vitrine is an Austrian hat, an
early-17th-century ancestor of the Tyrolean. Made of buff leather
with a braid-trimmed rim, it has a full, slightly exaggerated crown
that is divided into sections and accented with sharp, short
diagonals, all embroidered in black. It suggests a hunter's hat
fused with a hunter's well-stuffed game pie, and beyond that it has
the slightly clumsy volupte of a Marsden Hartley still life.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly buff leather, this time in the form of a sturdy man's
doublet, presides over another vitrine. It contrasts strikingly
with a far fancier version in polychrome silk brocade bordered with
mauve silk braid, its front panels evoking the geometry of armor,
its sleeves slashed for decorative effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curios and Treasures'' presents several thin, wonderfully
transparent slices of aesthetic and social history, like random
frames excerpted from a film. These excerpts don't give us history,
but they convey a vivid sense of how history happens, of the
combination of invention, evolution and historical borrowing that
constitutes the life of any art form.
</P>
<P>
   All these tendencies meet in the Fortuny display, where more
than a dozen gowns and evening capes reflect unusual depth in the
institute's holdings. Fortuny (1871-1949) was born in Spain, where
he studied drawing and painting, spent time in France and Germany,
where he studied chemistry and dyes, before settling in Venice. His
clothing design (like his set designs for theater and opera) drew
on many cultural sources: Japanese kimonos; monks' habits; flowing,
trumpet-sleeved Renaissance gowns; diaphanous Greek chemieses.
</P>
<P>
   Fortuny was known for unusually rich, luminous colors, and he
also figured out how to stencil velvet with gold patterns
(variously Celtic, Islamic and Baroque in origin). Most important
he invented and patented a method for inflicting incredibly fine,
permanent pleats on silk, so it was both form-fitting and
expandable, like an early form of stretch fabric, and yet had some
body of its own.
</P>
<P>
   In a way Fortuny is the touchstone for the show. Nearby are
gowns by two little-known designers whom he influenced: Maria
Monaci Gallenga (Italian, 1880-1944) and Mme. Babani, a French
designer who opened a boutique on the Boulevard Haussmann in 1919.
</P>
<P>
   At another point the modernity and functionality of Fortuny's
pleating contrasts with a less progressive evocation of things
Greek: a yellow silk evening gown from the 1880s, attributed to
Liberty &AMP; Co., whose cascade of horizontally draped fabric is
actually carefully tacked down. It was inspired by Oscar Wilde's
pronouncements that women should dress according to ``Grecian
form,'' and its traditionalism is hinted at by a tiny row of box
pleats at the hem; all these also suggest the toothlike details
(called dentils) on the entablature of a Greek temple.
</P>
<P>
   Such mixed messages are not surprising, given that clothes often
reflect complicated knots of function, fantasy, art and desire.
Even more deeply divided is a French evening dress in blue silk
with a high bustle, a lace overdress and a skirt whose horizontal
draping is similar to the Wilde concoction. As if that weren't
enough, the skirt is completed by a deep border of box pleats and
gathered bands that resemble an inverted dust ruffle.
</P>
<P>
   A more harmonious alliance of old and new is to be found in an
ivory silk shantung dress, also French, from 1908. It updates a
relatively conventional hourglass silhouette with curling tendrils
of self-piping, whose bold spirals and undulations may have been
inspired by Art Nouveau but also presage Alexander Calder's
hammered silver-wire jewelry in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Another showstopper is a formidable worker's smock in
buff-colored linen from 19th-century rural England. In all
likelihood the handiwork of some farmer's wife, intended for Sunday
best, it has a broad densely embroidered collar and a square panel
of smocking that forms a kind of grillwork across the chest and
also appears in broad bands at the wrists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curios and Treasures'' is at the Costume Institute of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, Fifth Avenue at 82nd Street, (212)
879-5500, through Jan. 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
