<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSICIAN-PRACTICE-     08-17 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSICIAN-PRACTICE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING WAYS TO PRACTICE, AND NOT ANNOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For most musicians here, practicing without the
interruption of a broom handle banging on the ceiling is a
perennial problem. Practice rooms are expensive, and there are only
so many rooftops. So the solutions have become more and more
creative, from using high-tech gizmos to funnel an instrument's
sound into headphones to retreating to the privacy of a boat deck.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians tramping up and down the narrow stairway of
Smalls, a jazz club in a Greenwich Village basement, readily grouse
about the practice problem. ``People will almost never complain
about a TV,'' said John Mosca, a trombonist who leads the Vanguard
Jazz Orchestra and has been evicted from an Upper West Side
Manhattan apartment for soundproofing the floor. ``It's an
inalienable right. But about practicing, people will complain
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that is the case, Mitchell Borden, the proprietor of
Smalls, extends the come-one, come-all largess he offers customers
($10 for 10 hours of music, plus free soft drinks) to the jazz cats
who play there. The club, which used to be a restaurant, came with
a walk-in refrigerator, coincidentally soundproof, where Borden now
keeps a piano. Musicians practice there at all hours, even during
performances. Borden also keeps a large black book in which
musicians can sign up to use the club as a free rehearsal hall
during the day. He is, Mosca says, a saint.
</P>
<P>
   But such generosity is rare. Practice rooms, $25 an hour at a
minimum, are out of reach for many musicians who need a few hours a
day to do the kind of bleating musical calisthenics that build fine
motor skills but can induce migraines in involuntary listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Some musicians are lucky. Marco Katz hasn't rented a practice
room since 1988, when he moved into his 1969 Nautaline houseboat,
the Misty. Katz, 48, a freelance trombonist who often plays in
schools, said the boat is an ideal place to have jam sessions. But
not because he can motor the boat out of earshot _ it doesn't run.
Rather, he said, it's because the ``characters'' who surround him
at the 79th Street Boat Basin, where the Misty is docked, have a
live-and-let-live attitude.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor used to come over and bang on the door during
rehearsals, Katz recalled. ``He'd say, `I have a complaint about
the music. You guys aren't playing loud enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another time, Katz said, his jazz quartet was playing on the
marina's wave wall at sunset, when a sailboat full of tourists
disembarked. ``Just another service offered to you by the city of
New York,'' he told them. One guy laid a twenty on them.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Katz's, Johannes Pfannkuch, 39, has another kind of
retreat, thanks to a longstanding deal with the West End
Presbyterian Church on 105th Street and Amsterdam Avenue. In
exchange for playing at church services once in a while, Pfannkuch,
a classical trombonist, practices in the sanctuary or the choir
room almost every day, sometimes with his Meridian Brass Quintet.
``I can play loud, which is something you have to do once in a
while,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The church has a bonus feature: remarkable acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   Katz's boat reminded Rod Baltimore, an old-timer in the music
world who owns International Woodwinds and Brass on 48th Street, of
practicing hi-jinks that crossed the line to criminal trespassing.
Two musicians, a clarinetist and a saxophonist, once unmoored a
construction barge under the George Washington Bridge and went
floating down the Hudson, playing away, Baltimore said. ``Before
they got killed, the Coast Guard had to rescue them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another clarinetist, Baltimore remembered, took a rowboat to the
middle of the Central Park Reservoir to practice late one night.
Some weeks later, walking through the park, the man was chased by
the mounted police, who asked him if he had been the culprit. ``He
said, `No, I don't even swim. I'm afraid of rowboats.'''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore himself used to break into the basement pool of the
Paris Hotel on West 97th Street, which used to close at 10 p.m.
``Nobody ever came down there, and we never got caught,'' he said.
``Then we'd go swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most legendary example of resourceful practicing is
Sonny Rollins' tenor sax sessions on the Williamsburg Bridge, atop
a pedestrian walkway out of view of the cars. In 1959, at an early
peak in his fame, Rollins abruptly stopped playing public concerts
so he could ``get something under my fingers,'' Rollins, 69, said
by phone from Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   He played al fresco on the bridge, warmed by Cognac in cold
weather, because he did not want to disturb the neighbors in his
apartment building on Grand Street. And he liked the anonymity.
``People would walk right by and they didn't hardly look at me,''
he said. ``You know how sophisticated New Yorkers are. It was
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also inspiring. In 1962, Rollins released an album called
``The Bridge,'' and the romantic notion of a celebrated musician
practicing, unrecognized, became the stuff of articles, short
stories and documentary films.
</P>
<P>
   But some practice solutions are born of desperation, not
inspiration. For those without a church or a boat at their
disposal, standing with one's face buried in the coat closet can
become tiresome. Susan Stoderl, 48, said she and her husband, both
opera singers, had dealt with the problem for a combined 79 years,
hanging tapestries in their bathroom to muffle the sound or singing
in the car. But then they found their savior: a deaf landlady.
</P>
<P>
   ``A singer told me about the apartment,'' said Stoderl, who is
co-director of a small company called Opera Nova and who moved in
above the landlady in Astoria, Queens, nine years ago. ``I've had
full-scale opera rehearsals there.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When she does have her hearing aid in,'' Stoderl said of the
apartment's owner, ``she's just happy to have a good tenant.''
</P>
<P>
   Musicians who can afford it have chosen a more high-tech route.
Kamau Adilifu, a trumpeter who has played in ``The Wild Party,''
``Guys and Dolls'' and other Broadway hits, has outfitted his Upper
West Side high-rise apartment with a $3,000 soundproof glass booth
called the Whisper Room.
</P>
<P>
   Barely big enough for a chair and music stand, it looks like a
small radio station booth. When he's inside playing, it's
impossible to hear more than a faint melody.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was a priority for him not to bother his neighbors or
his wife. ``I've always been very self-conscious about playing the
trumpet,'' Adilifu said softly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of what I practice, it's not necessarily musical. It's
the physical aspects of playing trumpet.''
</P>
<P>
   Adilifu said he bought the Whisper Room because he liked to
practice at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when the muse struck me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Whisper Room, Adilifu has a newer gadget,
Silent Brass, that fits into the bell of his horn, silencing it and
channeling the sound into headphones. It can alter the music to
make it sound as if it's being played in a church or a concert
hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freedom that it gives me more than compensates for what it
lacks in realism,'' Adilifu said. But it doesn't work for every
kind of instrument; saxophones, for example, emit sounds through
the finger holes, not just the bell.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the stairwell at Smalls, as the musicians discussed
whether to have a drink or a jam session, a few pointed out that
someone who really wanted to practice would find a way.
</P>
<P>
   But most reminisced about the good old days, when downtown lofts
came without plumbing, but also without neighbors, and no one had
ever heard of a noise ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Borden seemed of the opinion that even the music, back then, was
better.
</P>
<P>
   His theory: ``There's gotta be a reason why there's such a big
rift between good music and music that's considered good now. Maybe
that's it. There's no place to practice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
