<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents exonerated in child's death
 &HT;    By Zack Barnett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ The parents of a two-day old baby who
died last month in Clifton trailer park will not face criminal
charges for relying on prayer instead of doctors to treat their
ailing son, Mesa County's chief prosecutor said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Billy and Barbara Reed ``clearly wanted to do the best for their
child,'' Mesa County District Attorney Frank Daniels wrote in a
statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Reeds' son, Billy Ray Reed Jr., died the evening of July 9
because a thumb tack-sized hole in his heart prevented him from
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's parents belong to the General Assembly and Church of
the Firstborn, a congregation that prefers faith healing to modern
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Church members Joshua and Mindy Glory were sentenced in February
to 16 years for probation for not seeking medical care while their
infant died of pneumonia that advanced to bacterial meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said last week they would not prosecute another
member of the church whose baby died during birth.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa County Coroner Dr. Rob Kurtzman said earlier this month
that Billy and Barbara Reed may not have known their son was dying
when they summoned church elders to pray for him. After reading
police reports and interviewing Barbara Reed, Kurtzman ruled Billy
Ray's manner of death was undetermined, rather than homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours before Billy Ray died, he started to turn blue and
have trouble breathing but his condition seemed to improve when the
church members prayed for him, Kurtzman said.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtzman said the baby's condition, which rarely results in
death, probably would have been recognized and treated by a
physician during a routine examination.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado law allows parents to practice faith healing and
requires them to seek a doctor's help only when their children are
in life-threatening situations or ones that will leave them with
serious disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtzman and Daniels said the Reeds may not have recognized the
urgency of their son's condition.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels called Colorado laws ``cumbersome'' and ``unwieldy''
before saying they were ``seriously flawed and should be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels said he is not lobbying to limit religious freedoms. He
said people should always have a right to pray for sick people.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the use of prayer to the absolute exclusion of medical
care is a remnant of the Dark Ages,'' Daniels wrote. ``This
practice endangers children.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
