<SLUG> BC-FASH-TWEED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWEED: THE SPORTY SIDE OF DRESSING UP (WITH PHOTOS)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
(UNDATED) Anyone who has ever puzzled over the weird and often
wacky world of fashion knows one of designers' most important
techniques lies in exploiting incongruities.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most creative combine the high with the low, softly feminine
elements with something roughshod, light with heavy, glitter with
matte or brassy with beguiling. For fall and winter 2000, designers
hit on perhaps the perfect odd coupling, that of ladylike,
glamorous styles with the lowly born fabric known as tweed.
</P>
<P>
   This rough and nubby fabric, named for the Tweed River in
Scotland, is usually made of a very coarse wool, dyed in its yarn
stage, so that two or more colors are woven together to create a
pebble effect.
</P>
<P>
   Television golf fans will recognize tweed plus fours, warm and
weather-resistant, as the traditional attire for men at St.
Andrews. But tweeds also became a standby for women.
</P>
<P>
   In the British Isles, a tweed skirt worn with a cashmere or
thick woolen sweater and sturdy shoes eventually became the
benchmark for upper-crust women's outdoor dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet tweed was not anointed by high-fashion women's wear
designers until the post-World War II 1940s, when it appeared in
shapely peplum suits with Paris labels. Now these suits have been
resurrected with some modern touches.
</P>
<P>
   Tweed, which can be woven in plaid, check or herringbone
patterns, also comes in varying weights, allowing a range of
garments from thick coats to pliable dresses. Today manufacturers
also combine other fibers with wool to achieve lighter-weight and
even stretch fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kors is among designers again raising tweed to
near-couture status, adding feather collars, tossing on pearl and
diamond accessories, fur flings and outfitting tweed-suited models
in high-heeled pumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``At market, we saw a lot of menswear-inspired tweed nipped in
at the waist and very slim,'' said Erin Carmack, director of
fashion presentation for Neiman Marcus. ``You can tailor it, and
it's a very crisp, polished and put-together look.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaqui Lividini, senior vice president of fashion merchandising
and communications for Saks Fifth Avenue, lists a fitted tweed suit
among fall must-haves for the fashion crowd. ``Now tweed looks
young and sexy and very sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   These are not at all the styles one would expect to see on the
back nine at St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   This season's tweeds are often updated with leather trims _
either piping or strip _ edging or bisecting jackets and skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Cari Kerns, buyer for Leonard Rutan, believes her clients will
go for tweeds because they are something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our customers have their basics, like the little black
dress. Now they want something else.''
</P>
<P>
   With a buttoned-up jacket, a tweed suit can be very elegant, but
a tweed skirt or pants worn simply with a silk blouse can go from
the office to dinner. And with this season's return of blouses,
expect to see that look a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a tweed skirt or pants to a wardrobe will also allow an
easy way to update last season's sweater sets.
</P>
<P>
   While many people think of tweed only in its rusty brown,
oatmeal, camel and black-and-white forms, today tweeds appear in
permutations from loden green to hot pink to baby blue.
</P>
<P>
   Accessories include quality leathers and skins, such as ostrich
or alligator, fur and feathers, and fabrics from velvet to
pleather.
</P>
<P>
   But one should not overlook the fun of wearing rhinestones, or
even diamonds, with tweed. Viva the incongruities!
</P>
<P>
   XXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
