<SLUG> BC-BALLOONFESTIVAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBUQUERQUE BALLOON FEST GIVES THE SPIRIT A LIFT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KATHRYN HOPPER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Traveling down Interstate 25 just before
dawn, we spotted what looked like giant lightning bugs hovering
over the New Mexico desert.
</P>
<P>
   I nudged my 3-year-old son, Henry, to look up from his Pop-Tart.
We drove closer to the glowing orbs, which were not errant UFOs up
from Roswell, but simply a few early-risers at the Kodak
Albuquerque International Balloon Fiesta, the annual nine-day
extravaganza billed as the world's largest balloon event.
</P>
<P>
   I was desperately trying to get to the Fiesta grounds for the
daily mass ascension at 7 a.m., when hundreds of balloons in all
shapes and sizes lift off at dawn. But even though we had left
Santa Fe at 4:30 a.m., we were cutting it close; traffic was backed
up the last mile going into the parking lot of Balloon Fiesta Park.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the million spectators who come to watch the hundreds of
balloons at this famous festival plan their trip months, even a
year, in advance. We were winging it.
</P>
<P>
   But with a little patience _ and luck _ we found that it's
possible to see Fiesta with only a minimum of planning. (This
year's Fiesta is barely six weeks away, scheduled for Oct. 7-15.)
The caveats: Be prepared to find hotels outside Albuquerque _ Santa
Fe, in our case _ and to spend extra time looking for flights and
rental cars, or to make the 10-hour drive from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, luck was with us when I found a cheap flight and a
not-so-cheap rental car at pretty much the last minute. And it was
with us again when a wind delay pushed that day's ascension back an
hour. We had plenty of time to park, grab a breakfast burrito and
stake out a viewing spot.
</P>
<P>
   I'd expected to watch the liftoff from a distance, but we were
soon standing in the midst of hundreds of uninflated balloon
envelopes, their gondolas and eager crews.
</P>
<P>
   Henry and other kids ran around, poking the balloons as fans
filled with them with air. Then hot burners heated the air,
breathing the balloons to life. As the balloons loomed larger, the
kids grew less bold, slinking away in awe. In only a few minutes,
the colorful balloons were fully inflated and sent into the sky,
row by row, by event officials.
</P>
<P>
   The balloons came in all shapes and sizes, and we had fun
picking out our favorites. Henry liked the one shaped like a cow. I
liked the alien face, with its big eyes and tiny mouth. There was
also a huge chile ristra, a frog, a grocery bag and a tequila
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   They slowly floated south, gradually gaining altitude. As they
rose, they hit another wind current, which drove them back north,
allowing the balloons to circle the grounds. The weather pattern,
created by the Sandia Mountains, is dubbed the ``Albuquerque Box''
and is responsible for making the area one of the best ballooning
sites in the world.
</P>
<P>
   As I clicked away with my camera, amazed by the spectacle, Henry
grew bored and started playing in the sand. We ambled over to the
special kids' area where Henry frolicked inside a half-filled
balloon and bounded around a bouncy house. By noon, we were ready
to head back to Santa Fe and an afternoon nap.
</P>
<P>
   When we'd first decided to travel to northern New Mexico about a
month before the early October event, I'd mistakenly figured it was
the off-season. The first tipoff I got that this wasn't the case
was when I tried to rent a car and found out Dodge Neons were going
for $60 a day.
</P>
<P>
   The rental agent told me I was lucky to get a car at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Balloon Fiesta,'' she said. ``Everything in town is
booked.''
</P>
<P>
   Grateful for the opportunity at the Neon, I went ahead with the
rest of my planning. By some weird quirk of airline scheduling, I
snared a $170 round-trip ticket on United through Denver.
</P>
<P>
   We stayed in Santa Fe, about an hour north of Albuquerque, where
we had little trouble booking at room at the Fort Marcy complex
just north of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   I had not intended to go to Balloon Fiesta, planning on sticking
to Santa Fe and Taos, but I got wrapped up in the round-the-clock
television coverage of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Local stations pre-empt network programming to cover events such
as the key ring grab, when balloonists compete to pick off a set of
keys hanging on a telephone pole. The winner gets to keep the keys
and a new Ford truck that goes with them. There are also ``balloon
glows,'' nighttime spectacles where balloonists synchronize their
burners in elaborate light shows set to music.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of watching it on television, I decided to see it
firsthand. Once there, I realized what a big deal the Fiesta really
is. The natives stage elaborate tailgate parties around the mass
ascensions and have lively debates about the best viewing sites.
(Tempting though it may be to pull over right on the side of
Interstate 25, which passes by the Fiesta grounds, don't do it;
signs are posted warning drivers not to do so.)
</P>
<P>
   This year's Fiesta, the 29th, promises to be bigger than ever,
with 1,000 hot-air and gas-filled balloons and crews from 27
countries participating. There's also a new event called the New
Mexico Challenge Long Distance Hot Air Balloon Race, which will
feature 40 balloon teams attempting to fly the farthest distance
from Fiesta Park.
</P>
<P>
   No matter whether you plan the trip a year in advance or just go
on the spur of the moment, going to Balloon Fiesta is a truly
uplifting experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a hard time explaining the event to people who have
never been here,'' says Susan Wilson, who handles public relations
for the Fiesta. ``Seeing so many balloons at close range lift off
at sunrise. It's surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   If you go:
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Kodak Albuquerque Balloon Fiesta is Oct. 7-15.
</P>
<P>
   General-admission tickets are $4, and are well worth it to get
the intimate vantage point. For an even closer look, spectators can
become participants by paying $175 and up to ride inside a balloon
during an ascension offered by Rainbow Ryders.
</P>
<P>
   For detailed schedules and more specific information, call (888)
422-7277 or visit the Web site www.balloonfiesta.com.
</P>
<P>
   For information on balloon rides, call Rainbow Ryders at (800)
725-2477.
</P>
<P>
   For information on accommodations, contact New Mexico Central
Reservations, (800) 466-7829.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
