<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GODZILLA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GODZILLA SAVES WORLD (AND FILM) WITH STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To most American viewers, the Japanese Toho Godzilla films will
never be more than exercises in camp. In this age of
computer-generated images, who's going to take a man in a rubber
suit stomping on toy trucks and miniature cities seriously?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's the only thing audiences will embrace in
``Godzilla 2000.'' The final third is a giant monster version of a
World Wrestling Federation match between the Big G (looking more
fierce and royal than ever) and an alien upstart (something between
a skyscraper-size ``Predator'' and Jabba the Hutt's dungeon ogre
from ``Return of the Jedi''), with the pug ugly alien mutating on
the move.
</P>
<P>
   The crunch of lovingly detailed buildings rendered to splinters
in a single step, the rubble and dust left in the wake of a
prehistoric body slam, the noble profile of the scaly gray one in
action. It's a juvenile thrill that a CGI can't touch.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of ``Godzilla 2000'' isn't going to change anyone's
mind about Japan's favorite atomic lizard. Godzilla is on the move
again (didn't he die last time out? oh, never mind) just as an
ancient UFO is dredged up from the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   In a fitting bit of turnabout, the script appropriates Roland
Emmerich's ``Independence Day,'' though on a significantly smaller
scale. This lone silver spaceship parks on a Shinjuku skyscraper,
drains the city of all computer information and turns himself into
a mutant monster.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an all-volunteer force of science nerds called the
Godzilla Prediction Network, run by peacenik professor Yuji
(Takehiro Murata) and his precocious adolescent daughter, clashes
with their arch rivals, the Crisis Control Institute, a government
strike force armed to destroy Godzilla run by Yuji's bloodthirsty
nemesis Katagiri (Hiroshi Abe, whose eyes bug out in glee every
time he launches a missile).
</P>
<P>
   Cartoonish English dubbing dumbs down an already painful script
and slipshod special effects run through the film. It had a preview
audience almost in stitches until the finale, a grand roar of old
time glories but hardly enough to justify sitting through a film
that seems destined for kiddie matinees.
</P>
<P>
   Its one saving grace is Godzilla himself, the James Bond of
giant monsters. Screaming his roar while stomping through modern
cities like some avenging force of nature, this isn't Emmerich's
post-``Jurassic Park'' garden variety dinosaur of the blandly
Americanized 1998 ``Godzilla,'' but a lizard king with dignity,
stature and personality. He deserves better than this overripe
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   GODZILLA 2000
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Takao Okawara
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS: Hiroshi Kashiwabara, Wataru Mimura
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Takehiro Murata, Naomi Nishida, Mayu Suzuki, Hiroshi Abe
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: PG for monster violence and mild language
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
