<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4804 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-SEATTLE-4TAKES     08-17 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-SEATTLE-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMILING THROUGH THE MIST AT LIFE'S DELIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's difficult to think of any city, other than the
urban behemoths like New York and Los Angeles, and maybe
Washington, that has shaped modern living in the United States as
much as this one.
</P>
<P>
   Nordstrom, Boeing, Microsoft, Starbucks, Amazon: all innovators,
all based here in the Pacific Northwest, off in a remote corner of
the nation, far from the main centers of population. Yet they play
a central part in daily life across this continent and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's man of the millennium, of course, is Bill Gates, who
created the corporate principality named Microsoft, making powerful
enemies in Washington, D.C., along the way. His company, housed in
40-odd X-shaped buildings on a 30-acre campus in suburban Redmond,
was for a time the most valuable in America, and Gates still
commands one of the greatest fortunes in history.
</P>
<P>
   The nerd-in-chief and his wife, Melinda, live in a $100 million
giga-mansion with a rather wistful quotation from ``The Great
Gatsby'' inscribed on the ceiling of the library: ``He had come a
long way to this blue lawn, and his dream must have seemed so close
that he could hardly fail to grasp it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle still has its funky side. It revels in its mellow
small-town atmosphere; a Seattle ad man popularized the ``happy
face.'' But it has become an unmistakably rich, high-tech,
high-rise, high-expectation metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Paul Schell, the mayor, what he's up to, and he will tell
you:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to manage the transition from regional center to
major international city without losing the core values of the
place in the process. We're eight and one-half hours from Tokyo and
eight and one-half hours from London; a basically conservative
city; a collection of small communities, now overlaid with 110
languages and living at the epicenter of technological change. It's
not an easy job.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle makes room for creators. It takes pride in its part in
the careers of Quincy Jones, Ray Charles, Kurt Cobain and Jimi
Hendrix and waxes nostalgic about Pearl Jam. August Wilson, the
playwright, lives close by at Enumclaw. Raymond Carver, the writer,
lived out the last years of his short, hard life at Port Angeles on
the Olympic Peninsula, just across Puget Sound, crafting terse,
claustrophobic short stories at the edge of the forest primeval.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Larson draws here, and the mystic Mark Tobey painted here.
So did the Harlem Renaissance master Jacob Lawrence, who died this
summer. Dale Chihuly, the flamboyant one-eyed glass sculptor,
produces his extravagantly vivid showpieces, which have been
displayed everywhere from Las Vegas to Venice to Jerusalem, in a
workshop on Lake Union where George Y. Pocock once built the
world's finest racing shells.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle always reminds me and my wife, Betsey, of San Francisco.
It belongs to the sea; around every corner there is a view of the
water. Its streets and its skyscrapers cling to hillsides. It has
more than a whiff of the Orient about it, and it is obsessed by
food, wine and restaurants. I know a Seattle native living in exile
in Washington, D.C., who has a whole Pacific salmon air-freighted
to him when he and his wife give a dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   But Seattle is different. It is less full of itself than its
rival down the coast. Less cynical, too. Young families and the
middle class here have resisted the stampede to the suburbs. People
worry that they'll be spoiled by success, yes. They worry that they
will have to wear neckties. But on balance they are optimistic,
even about the weather, smiling through the mist; it is all that
water, after all, that turns buddleias from butterfly bushes into
20-foot butterfly trees and brings out the flashing crimsons of the
fuchsias.
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, a culture of self-effacement prevails in
the city. There are techno-millionaires here, geeks worth 20 times
as much as New Yorkers with chauffeurs, who wear sandals and ride
the bus to work. Everyone is cheerful, pleasant, upbeat, from the
bank presidents to the bellhops. And everyone is pathologically
polite; people would rather die than honk, no matter how maniacal
the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets on your nerves,'' said Michael Kinsley, himself a
manifestly mannerly gent, who came west four years back to edit
Microsoft's online magazine, Slate. ``You keep wondering if you can
live up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wild and Urban
</P>
<P>
   Seattle took a hundred years and more to fully hit its stride,
but almost from the start it has been an unusual blend of wild and
urban.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1851 on a series of waterside hills then clad with
magnificent Douglas firs, it always had those noble vistas of the
Cascades and the Olympic Mountains, when weather permitted (as it
often didn't and doesn't, especially before the fog lifts at noon).
It always had Lake Washington and Lake Union, Elliott Bay and Puget
Sound, inhabited by salmon and giant octopuses with arms 15 feet
long, crossed these days by floating bridges, steel-arch spans and
ferries. By 1900 timber and trade with Asia as well as the
financial backwash from the Klondike gold rush of 1897-98 had put
big bucks in local pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Still, visitors from more cosmopolitan cities weren't much
impressed. Several decades ago Sir Thomas Beecham, the conductor,
who waggled his baton for a few seasons in these parts, called
Seattle ``an aesthetic dustbin.'' His countryman Alistair Cooke
called it ``a rain-soaked fishing village halfway between San
Francisco and Alaska.'' But that was before the World's Fair of
1962, with its monorail and its Space Needle (recently given a $20
million face-lift), and the 35-year population explosion that
followed it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pike Place Market, the zesty souk on the waterfront _ my
colleague Timothy Egan once described it as ``the Marrakesh of the
Northwest'' _ was saved from the wrecker's ball during the Vietnam
era. It has lived on as the heart and soul of the city, notable
alike for the goofy exuberance of its merchants and the quality of
its fare: Dungeness crab and Olympia oysters, pale pink stargazer
lilies and beaming yellow sunflowers, Rainier cherries and Walla
Walla onions. It is the outstanding public market in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   As the country rediscovered the outdoors, it discovered Seattle,
a city whose residents can sail among the orca whales in the San
Juan Islands, with bald eagles cruising overhead, and climb
snow-capped Mount Rainier in the same week. With its mild if
legendarily rainy climate, the place was made, positively made, for
skiing, cycling, running, rowing, sailing, hydroplane racing and a
dozen other sports.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the Eddie Bauer store here, originally an outfitter
for mountaineers, grew into a national sporting-goods powerhouse.
Seattle's Recreational Equipment flagship superstore, a co-op to
which almost one of three people in the region belong, has a
65-foot indoor artificial pinnacle where young studs practice rock
climbing.
</P>
<P>
   A Building Boom
</P>
<P>
   By 1975 Seattle was in fashion. The Seattle Opera produced
Wagner's ``Ring'' that summer _ the first time the cycle had ever
been produced within a week's time, as originally prescribed by the
Wagner family, anywhere in the United States aside from the
Metropolitan Opera in New York. New York took notice, as did London
and Bayreuth.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 15 years, a half-dozen books and magazines,
including Harper's and Money, rated Seattle as the nation's most
livable city. It got a snazzy new art museum, cunningly slotted
into the urban streetscape downtown by Robert Venturi in 1991, and
a heralded new home for the Seattle Symphony, Benaroya Hall, opened
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A new park for the Seattle Mariners, Safeco Field, was unveiled
last year to replace the unloved Kingdome, demolished in a mere
16.8 seconds on March 26, 1999, known locally as ``Dome's Day.''
The new ballpark, with a retractable roof, cost $517 million,
financed mostly by local taxes, making it the most costly sports
center in the country. The edge was taken off the celebration when
the team announced that it was trading its star, Ken Griffey Jr.,
arguably the best all-rounder in baseball, to Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   A $250 million rock 'n' roll museum, known as the Experience
Music Project, opened just this summer. Designed by Frank O. Gehry,
it houses 80,000 artifacts inside an aggressively billowing
aluminum and stainless-steel shell decked out in gold, silver, red,
powder blue and iridescent purple. The initial reviews have been
decidedly mixed. The tickets cost too much ($19.95 each), the
complicated electronic gadgets meant to guide the visitor around
too often don't work and as Susan Nielsen, a Seattle Times
columnist, wrote recently, ``The whole inside of the building is
like a guy trying so hard to be hip that the muscles stand out on
his neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the building boom rolls on, powered by the city's
cyber-riche. A new public library is planned, designed by no less
than Rem Koolhaas, the celebrated Dutch master; and Terry Farrell,
the British postmodernist, is working on a new aquarium. The Opera
House is soon to be rebuilt, in part with money from the McCaw
family, pioneers of the mobile telephone. Also on the way are an
elaborate new civic center and a grand new football stadium,
financed, like the rock museum, by Paul G. Allen, Gates' partner in
founding Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Old Guard Feels Ruffled
</P>
<P>
   All this activity unsettles the old guard, which is attached to
the city's comfy old Beaux-Arts look, typified by the terra-cotta
walrus heads that decorate the Arctic Building on Third Avenue. A
sleek new hotel, W, prompted the locals to ask, ``It's nice, but is
it really Seattle?'' People have the same doubts about the Venturi
and Gehry buildings. Phyllis Hayes, whose family has deep local
roots, summed up the attitude this way: ``Wonderful things are
happening, but they're happening too fast, and they cost so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Schell says it builds character. ``I want people's teeth to
chatter,'' he told me over a scotch and water. ``Change has no
constituency, or not a big one, but here of all places it would be
crazy to resist.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the things that are happening are not at all wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Employment is down at Boeing, the nation's largest manufacturer
and largest exporter. The e-business slump has the people over at
HomeGrocer.com and Drugstore.com worried, and Microsoft stock, the
foundation of thousands of local fortunes, has taken a dive in
response to the Clinton administration's successful antitrust suit.
With the population of the metropolitan area approaching 2.5
million, growth has slowed, at least for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   But angst is not at all Seattle's style. The city is still
thinking big; the least appealing suite in a new apartment complex
in Kirkland, not far from the Microsoft campus, is currently on the
market for $2.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle earned a reputation early on for radicalism. Anna Louise
Strong, a charismatic Marxist, sat on the school board, and the
Industrial Workers of the World, a pioneering hard-left union known
as the Wobblies, flourished here. The city was idled in 1919 by the
nation's only general strike. Communists led a maritime strike in
1934.
</P>
<P>
   That feisty spirit may be bubbling back to the surface as the
gap between have and have-not widens again. At least that is one
widespread interpretation of the protests last December at the
World Trade Organization's conference here.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Seattle has always been marked by a
certain emotional reticence, perhaps a legacy from its early
Scandinavian settlers. Walt Crowley, a historian who runs a
crackerjack local Web site (historylink.org), talks of this as ``a
city with a split personality, a yin side and a yang side.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of its most noted politicians, both Democrats, both
senators, exemplified the split. Henry M. Jackson, ``the senator
from Boeing,'' concentrated on national security issues;
personally, he was understated, a paragon of probity. Warren G.
Magnuson, a prime mover on civil rights, environmental law and
consumer protection, was much more rambunctious, a man who liked a
drink or two.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee, Coffee Everywhere
</P>
<P>
   The dark, rainy days of winter may have something to do with
Seattle's love of books. The city is notable for its bookstores,
from the encyclopedic Elliott Bay Book Co. to specialists like the
Peter Miller shop, which sells architecture books. The climate has
also contributed to the city's movie mania, satisfied at theaters
like the Harvard Exit and the Egyptian.
</P>
<P>
   I would wager that the same thing is true of Seattle's passion
for coffee, which added words like latte and dopio to the American
language through the unstoppable growth of Starbucks. The name, by
the way, comes from that of the java-loving mate in ``Moby-Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle must have a thousand cafes of one kind or another _
places to grab a quick cuppa, places like Le Pichet that serve
simple meals, breakfast cafes like Bacco that serve nine-grain
toast and juice bombs (an orange, pear and pineapple blend, for
example, called Pegasus). It has a pair of Thriftway supermarkets
that stage an annual Peach-O-Rama, featuring pallet-loads of
perfect fruit that has reached a prescribed, scientifically
measured level of sweetness. It has shops specializing in
espresso-machine repair.
</P>
<P>
   There are problems in this food paradise. Jon Rowley, who
introduced the ambrosial Copper River salmon from Alaska to the
lower 48, said that the black cod, which he calls ``one of the real
aristocrats of the ocean,'' has all but disappeared from local
waters. You can still see the elegant, silvery salmon swimming up
the fish ladder at Ballard Locks, bound with fixated stares in
their eyes for the fresh water where they spawn and die, but the
seasonal runs are smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the berries from the San Juan Islands remain the sweetest
I know. Sol Amon of the Pure Food Fish Market can still explain the
availability of razor clams, which depends on the tidal cycle. Sur
la Table has enough pots and pans and gadgets to cook a state
dinner. Jerry Traunfeld of the Herbfarm restaurant may know more
about cooking with herbs than anyone anywhere. And where else would
you find a hidden private dining room for four like the one at
Canlis, a treehouse for pampered grown-ups, just next to a towering
hillside pine?
</P>
<P>
   Fare for Inner Lives
</P>
<P>
   Seattle offers ample nourishment for the soul as well as the
body.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Art Museum, whose dramatic main staircase is a
late-20th-century version of the Louvre's, houses a few choice old
masters, including a Paolo Uccello illustrating episodes from the
``Aeneid,'' and rich holdings of African tribal art and Northwest
Coast Native American art. It has a fine Asian collection, housed
in a classic Art Deco building in Volunteer Park.
</P>
<P>
   One day it will have much more. More than $250 million was
reportedly spent on art by area collectors last year, and the
museum hopes to be given part of the splendid Barney A. Ebsworth
collection of modern American art that it has been showing lately.
That collection includes Edward Hopper's melancholy masterpiece
``Chop Suey'' (hung here near David Hockney's chillingly formal
double portrait of Henry Geldzahler and Christopher Scott).
Ebsworth is from St. Louis, his wife from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Symphony is shooting for the top echelon in its new
hall, which is adorned with a pair of arresting white clusters by
Chihuly and other works by Mark di Suvero and Robert Rauschenberg.
Under the accomplished and intense Gerard Schwarz, its music
director since 1985 (and the music director of New York's annual
Mostly Mozart Festival since 1982), it gave a performance last year
of Deems Taylor's neglected opera ``Peter Ibbetson.'' This year it
will play with such guest conductors as Claus Peter Flor and
Richard Hickox and such soloists as Radu Lupu, Maxim Vengerov and
Renee Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   Though somewhat less well known, the Pacific Northwest Ballet,
led by Francia Russell and Kent Stowell, former dancers with the
New York City Ballet, has won acclaim in recent years for its
staging of works by George Balanchine.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is awash in theater of every description. The Intiman
Theater staged ``The Kentucky Cycle'' by Robert Schenkkan in 1991;
the play won a Pulitzer Prize in 1992, before it opened in New
York. The Seattle Repertory Theater has a long-standing
relationship with Wendy Wasserstein dating from the days when it
was run by the director Dan Sullivan. And ACT _ the letters stand
for A Contemporary Theater _ is soon to present a new Philip Glass
opera, ``In the Penal Colony,'' based on a Kafka story, with sets
by John Conklin.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three has a budget exceeding $3 million a year, and
each has more than 10,000 subscribers _ remarkable numbers for a
city this size. Wagner, Environmentally
</P>
<P>
   But opera is easily the city's cultural long suit, thanks to
Glynn Ross, who brought Wagner to the region, and Speight Jenkins,
his successor at the Seattle Opera.
</P>
<P>
   A lean, fervent man, once a New York reporter and critic,
Jenkins has been at the helm here for 17 years. Next year, three
``Ring'' cycles will be presented in a new production directed by
Stephen Wadsworth, with more than a little kibbitzing from Jenkins.
Jane Eaglen, now established as the premier Wagnerian soprano of
her day, will sing Brunnhilde; she has been a Seattle darling since
making her American debut here in ``Norma'' in 1994. In 1998 she
teamed with Ben Heppner in a rapturously received ``Tristan und
Isolde.''
</P>
<P>
   The new $10 million ``Ring'' sold out more than a year in
advance to Wagnerians all over the world. Why Seattle? Earlier
Jenkins efforts were sometimes booed, even pelted with fruit, but
they came to be seen as classics. He pushed the company deep into
the red but lifted it back out again. ``We became the thing in
town,'' he said, ``and then people from elsewhere came here out of
curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, he promised a ``green `Ring,''' and the
``Rheingold,'' which made its bow this season, emphasized Wagner's
preoccupation with the natural world of forests, mountains and
rivers, inhabited by mythic gods and goddesses _ not inappropriate,
given the passionate environmentalism of the Puget Sound audience.
It was all totally unlike Bayreuth's new production, where Valhalla
is depicted as a high rise under construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will use technology to maximum effect,'' Jenkins vowed,
``but this will be a traditional `Ring,' and it will above all be
an acted `Ring' _ a theater piece. Everyone will act. No more of
this standing around singing.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IF YOU GO: PLEASURES OF THE MIND, SOUL AND PALATE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By R.W. APPLE Jr. &LR;  &QC;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of attractions, along with travel
information:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   ALEXIS, 1007 First Ave., (206) 624-4844. A graceful, century-old
109-room classic, this is a member of the boutique chain assembled
by the California hotelier Bill Kimpton. The public spaces are
filled with the work of regional artists (including several vibrant
Dale Chihuly glass sculptures), and the bright bedrooms are
decorated with cheerful, traditional fabrics. No view, but you
waken to the sound of sea gulls and foghorns. Terrific Aveda spa.
Double rooms from $230.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR SEASONS OLYMPIC, 411 University St., (206) 621-1700. Grand
with a capital G: a lobby straight from a Renaissance palace, a
blossom-filled garden court, a shopping arcade where you can buy a
ball gown or an antique candelabrum, and a windowed rooftop pool.
This is a dowager, built in the 1920s, but very well preserved.
Even the smaller rooms have duvets and luxurious bathrooms. Do you
need a notary public, a shoe shine or maybe a car wash? Just ask.
Double rooms from $230.
</P>
<P>
   INN AT THE MARKET, 86 Pine St., (206) 443-3600. Lean,
understated, enlivened with touches of Asia and Provence, this is a
discreetly distinguished little hotel _ especially if you can snag
a room like 514, a suite that looks down on the Pike Place Market
and beyond to Elliott Bay and the peaks of the Olympic Peninsula.
Fax machines, kitchenettes and even orchids in the bedrooms. Betsey
and I wish there were one of these in every city we visit. Double
rooms from $170.
</P>
<P>
   W, 1112 Fourth Ave., (206) 264-6000. Hard-edged, high-tech
decor, soft-edged service from a black-clad staff _ an apt
combination for Seattle. The lobby is small, crowded and noisy, but
the 428 guest rooms are quiet and comfortable, with 250-count
sheets and CD libraries. The restaurant, Earth &AMP; Ocean, is the
latest brainstorm of the mini-mogul Drew Nieporent. But the coveted
silver ``W'' yo-yo's are available only through the catalog. Double
rooms from $239.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAGNE, 86 Pine St., (206) 728-2800. Peter Lewis, a model of
warmth and charm, offers deeply satisfying French food, steering a
course north of bistro banality and south of nouvelle nonsense. One
night recently, my tart of crunchy, slightly sour chard made an
ideal introduction to a dish of unctuous braised pork cheeks.
Betsey's seafood boudin, though lighter, was no less tasty. The
wines, mostly French, are carefully chosen and gently priced.
</P>
<P>
   CANLIS, 2576 Aurora Ave., (206) 283-3313. Fifty years old this
year, a classic room in stone and redwood cantilevered over Lake
Union, Canlis has been revitalized by a new chef, Greg Atkinson. He
has nudged the menu toward seasonal and regional authenticity with
lime-seasoned raw Alaskan scallops and Frog Hollow Farm peaches,
while keeping the succulent steaks and chops that made the house's
name. The service is silky, the wine list the area's best.
</P>
<P>
   DAHLIA LOUNGE, 2001 Fourth Ave., (206) 682-4142. Tom Douglas is
Seattle's premier restaurateur, and this is his premier restaurant.
Japanese lanterns, red walls and music from the 1930s, '40s and
'50s cast a casual glow over the delicious Asian-accented food. Six
little fishy bites (for example, albacore with ponzu sauce) come
nestled in ice; a slab of grilled Alaska king salmon rests on a
chowder of tart sorrel leaves and sweet corn. Coconut cream pie
with fresh coconut for dessert. No wonder they shot a scene for
``Sleepless in Seattle'' here a few years back.
</P>
<P>
   HERBFARM, 195 Northeast Gilman Blvd., Issaquah, (206) 784-2222.
Dinner here is a major production _ nine courses, six wines, five
hours, $150 a head. But it's worth all that, and the half-hour
drive east of downtown, to experience the food of Jerry Traunfeld,
a culinary wizard who flavors duck with lavender and wild
blueberries, slow-roasts salmon in a giant zucchini blossom, and
pairs melon soup with tarragon ice. The results are absolutely
thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   RAY'S BOATHOUSE, 6049 Seaview Ave. N.W., (206) 789-3770. Ray's
seafood is never less than impeccably fresh and soundly cooked, and
on a fine summer's day what could be more enthralling than sitting
on the deck, watching boats cross the sound, with a breeze mussing
your hair? Manila clams steamed with beer, dill and butter, and
sesame-crusted halibut with sticky rice make a dandy lunch, and
there are 177 white wines to choose from. I counted.
</P>
<P>
   SAZERAC, 1101 Fourth Ave., (206) 624-7755. Sick of salmon? Had
it with halibut? Jan Birnbaum, the Louisiana-born owner of
Catahoula in the Napa Valley, has established a lively Seattle
beachhead for the cooking of the Southeast (pork barbecue),
Southwest (crab and rock shrimp enchiladas) and Cajun country
(crawfish beignets). His chicken and andouille gumbo is dense and
dark, full of okra, fire and file. Open all day, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   SHIRO, 2401 Second Ave., (206) 443-9844. This is the Plain Jane
among Seattle's top restaurants, a starkly simple little place with
plastic chairs and paper napkins. No matter; the sushi is superb.
We especially liked the shiro roll, made with mackerel, shiso and
ginger, and sea urchin roe (uni), so soft and creamy it barely
clung to the rice. Wasabi is hand ground here.
</P>
<P>
   WILD GINGER, 1401 Third Ave., (206) 623-4450. Another of
Seattle's favorites, Rick Yoder's pan-Asian brasserie moved this
summer into handsome new multimillion-dollar quarters across the
street from Benaroya Hall. It was jammed from the moment the doors
opened. Japanese screens, origami lampshades and rattan chairs set
just the right tone for a wide variety of satays, each served with
a different sauce, and for authentic Thai and Malay curries. The
baby boy choi is to die for.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   SPACE NEEDLE, 219 Fourth Ave. N., (206) 905-2100 or (800)
937-9582. Hours: Daily, 8 a.m. to midnight. Admission to
observation deck: $11; $9, the elderly; $5, ages 5 to 12; 4 and
under, free. There is also a revolving restaurant, SkyCity.
Accessible by the Monorail; information: (206) 448-3481.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE OPERA, Seattle Center Opera House, 321 Mercer St., (206)
389-7676. Tonight at 7: Final performance of ``Das Rheingold,''
with Phillip Joll and Stephanie Blythe; tickets: $62 to $125.
Saturday, Tuesday and Friday at 7 p.m.: ``Die Walkuere,'' with Jane
Eaglen: tickets: $40 to $125. Fall season begins Oct. 21 with
``Lucia di Lammermoor,'' with Harolyn Blackwell.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE SYMPHONY, Benaroya Hall, 200 University St., (206)
215-4747. On Sept. 6 and 7 at 7:30, Garrison Keillor performs with
the symphony, conducted by Philip Brunelle. On Sept. 16 the
symphony season opens with a gala and a concert conducted by Gerard
Schwarz and runs through July. Tickets: $25 to $62.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE MARINERS, Safeco Field, 1250 First Ave. S., at Atlantic
Street (exit on Interstate 5), (206) 346-4000. No game this
weekend. The Mariners play the Yankees on Aug. 28-30 at the
stadium. Tickets: $5 to $32; (206) 622-4487
</P>
<P>
   EXPERIENCE MUSIC PROJECT, at the base of the Space Neeedle, 325
Fifth Ave. NN., (206) 367-5483. Hours through Labor Day: Daily, 9
a.m. to 11 p.m. Admission: $19.95; $15.95 for the elderly and
students aged 13 to 17; $14.95 for children 6 and under.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE ART MUSEUM, 100 University St., (206) 654-3100.
``20th-Century American Art: The Ebsworth Collection,'' through
Nov. 1. Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.;
Thursdays, to 9 p.m. Admission: $7; $5 for students and those over
62; children under 12, free.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE ASIAN ART MUSEUM, 1400 E. Prospect St., Volunteer Park,
(206) 654-3100. Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.;
Thursdays, to 9 p.m. Admission: $3; children under 12, free.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFIC NORTHWEST BALLET, Seattle Center Opera House, 321 Mercer
St., (206) 441-2424. The season begins with ``Coppelia,'' Sept.
28-30 and Oct. 5-8. Tickets: $15 to $110.
</P>
<P>
   INTIMAN THEATER, Seattle Center, Second Avenue North and Mercer
Street, (206) 269-1900. ``The Chairs,'' by Eugene Ionesco: Friday
night at 8; Saturday at 2 and 8 p.m.; Sunday at 2 and 7 p.m.
Through Sept. 9. Tickets: $27.50 to $42. ``The Weir'' begins
previews Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE REPERTORY THEATER, Bagley Wright Theater and Leo K.
Theater, Seattle Center, 155 Mercer St., (206) 443-2222. The
nine-play season begins Sept. 6 with ``The Search for Signs of
Intelligent Life in the Universe,'' starring Lily Tomlin, in the
Wright. Tickets: $15 to $45. In the Leo K., ``Jar the Floor,'' by
Cheryl West, opens Sept. 18. Tickets: $15 to $42.
</P>
<P>
   ACT, Kreielsheimer Place, 700 Union St., (206) 292-7676. In the
Allen Theater, through Sunday, ``A Skull in Connemara'' by Martin
McDonagh. Friday night at 8; Saturday at 2 and 8 p.m.; Sunday at 2
and 7:30 p.m. Tickets: $27 to $42. In the Falls Theater, Aug. 26
through Oct. 1, the world premiere of ``In the Penal Colony,'' a
new opera theater work by Philip Glass; libretto by Rudolph
Wurlitzer, based on the story by Franz Kafka; directed by JoAnne
Akalaitis and conducted by Alan Johnson. Tickets: $19 to $42. In
the Bullitt Theater, through Sept. 10, ``St. Nicholas,'' by Conor
McPherson. Tonight and tomorrow night at 8; Sunday at 7:30 p.m.
Tickets: $15. In Busters, an open-ended run of ``Late Nite
Catechism,'' by the Seattle Theater Project and Cloud 9
Productions. Thursdays through Saturdays at 8 p.m.; Sundays at 2
p.m. Tickets: $24.50 and $29.50.
</P>
