888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Changes lede to say sales declined, sted profits.)  
 BOSTON SCI'S NEW CHIEF HAS A FREE HAND TO MAKE CHANGES  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 14 months since Jim Tobin became chief executive of
Boston Scientific, succeeding founder chairman Peter Nicholas, he
dismissed 1,900 people, closed manufacturing operations in three
states, and watched sales decline while the stock lost two-thirds
of its value.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas's reaction: ``I wished I hired him earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   His confidence in the 56-year-old Tobin stems from a deep trust
the two men have developed in each other as they attempt to turn
Boston Scientific around. For Tobin, that assurance _ and the free
hand he's been given by Nicholas _ is a stark change from the four
years he spent as president of Biogen under chairman Jim Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   Rising to CEO, Vincent called Tobin ``the ideal choice'' to lead
Biogen's management team. But Tobin reportedly had some differences
with Vincent, who is widely known for saving Biogen from near
bankruptcy and establishing it as an industry leader. Tobin,
sources said, felt he was being second-guessed by Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   In a December 1998 showdown, the Biogen board of directors sided
with Vincent, prompting Tobin to resign abruptly and go on an
extended skiing vacation.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent interview, Tobin calmly said he did not want to
talk about Vincent, but his demeanor changed quickly when he spoke
about Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with Pete is a joy,'' he said. ``Not that we always
agree on everything. We have a pretty productive collaboration. He
is better at some things than I will ever be.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 59-year-old Nicholas, turning over control of the
medical-device company he and John Abele founded in 1979 in
Watertown and grew through acquisitions to more than $2.8 billion
last year, with 13,500 employees, has been a deliberate process.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Nicholas told company directors that he wanted
to scale back his day-to-day involvement and urged them to begin
seeking his replacement. There were few candidates inside the
company. Abele left full-time company management in 1990 and
further reduced his workload this January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have the management depth,'' Nicholas said. He
focused his executive talent search on large medical products
companies with strong management talent, such as Abbott
Laboratories and Baxter International Inc. Tobin spent 22 years at
Baxter, the huge supplier of hospital products, rising from
financial analyst to chief operating officer before joining Biogen.
</P>
<P>
   So when Tobin bolted from Biogen for the western ski slopes,
Nicholas made his move, reaching him by phone in between downhill
runs for a first interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good discussion and it was clear to me that here was
the guy I was looking for,'' said Nicholas of Tobin. ``He fit my
view as an ideal successor. It was an easy decision to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas, who said he also received a strong recommendation
about Tobin from Vincent, believed that Boston Scientific's growth
through acquisition left it somewhat bloated and inefficient at
turning out products quickly.
</P>
<P>
   And while revenues were reaching record highs last year he was
worried about the company's future, following a four-year
acquistion spree in which Boston Scientific spent $6 billion on at
least a dozen deals.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas was particularly concerned about high manufacturing
costs and Boston Scientific's ability to keep pace with more nimble
competitors in emerging markets such as cardiovascular stents.
These are metal mesh devices used by cardiovascular surgeons in a
procedure known as angioplasty that keeps blood vessels open after
they are cleared of plaque to improve blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We underestimated the significance of the stent opportunity,''
conceded Nicholas, noting that while Boston Scientific anticipated
that stents would be used in 25 percent of patients with heart
disease, they are now used in upwards of 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For Tobin, who was hired in March 1999 but did not begin working
at Boston Scientific until that June, Boston Scientific's problems
fit perfectly with his Baxter skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Tobin has begun to do a lot of the things people thought
he would do,'' said Daniel T. Lemaitre, first vice president at
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., who has followed his career at Baxter since
1983. ``Tobin is very pragmatic and blunt-talking. He knows how to
drive manufacturing costs lower every year.''
</P>
<P>
   That directness also appealed to Nicholas. While Tobin was still
relatively new to biotech, Boston Scientific's challenges boiled
down to becoming more efficient in manufacturing, consolidating
some operations and figuring out how to stem the market-share loss
in cardiovascular stents, the fastest growing part of the stent
market that was the major cause of company's recent problems.
</P>
<P>
   Since his arrival at Boston Scientific's plush executive office
in Natick _ the former Prime Computer Corp. headquarters and once a
Carling beer brewing facility _ Tobin has moved quickly on two
major issues.
</P>
<P>
   The first is a corporate reorganization aimed at streamling the
company by eliminating overlapping manufacturing functions and
focusing stent production in Miami and Ireland. Last month the
company announced that 1,900 manufacturing jobs, including 850 in
Watertown _ the community where Nicholas and co-founder John Abele
launched Boston Scientific in 1979 _ would be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging the loss of jobs can be painful for
employees, Tobin didn't flinch from making the cuts. ``At Baxter, I
had 60,000 people and 131 plants and we closed 50 of them and built
five new ones,'' Tobin said. ``So closing three facilities (at
Boston Scientific) is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin says the restructuring will generate savings of $250
million annually by 2003 and boost research and development
spending. Boston Scientific also consolidated its Medi-Tech
division, which produces its vascular surgery and radiology
products division to Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The second and perhaps most intractable problem is Medinol Ltd.,
a company that Boston Scientific helped create in Tel Aviv five
years ago to produce state-of-the-art cardiovascular stents.
Disagreements over timely delivery of the top-selling stents led to
unusally high inventories which Boston Scientific had to be write
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rocky partnership for quite some time,'' said
Tobin. To solve the provlem, Boston Scientific announced last week
that it would acquire acquiring Medinol, its sole supplier of
cardiovascular stents.
</P>
<P>
   Owning Medinol would enable Boston Scientific to become more
competitive with rivals who make their own stents, generating
higher gross profit margins. Tobin maintains a closer working
relationship is needed between the two companies to avoid recent
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Boston Scientific, which does the final assembly
of the stent system by adding a balloon catheter, recalled
thousands of its top-of-the-line Nir stents because of suspected
pinhole problems after the company reported 22 leakages.
</P>
<P>
   Solving the problem and regaining US Food and Drug
Administration's approval took 17 months and set the company's new
product plans back by a year. It also puts Boston Scientific
further behind its leading rivals _ Guidant Corp. of Indianapolis
and Medtronics Incv. of Minneapolis _ and just ahead of Johnson &AMP;
Johnson of New Brunswick, N.J. _ in the $2 billion stent market.
J&AMP;J, the nation's largest medical device company is reportedly
gaining market share against Boston Scientific with its new
cardiovascular stent.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Boston Scientific suffered another setback,
when Medinol said it would have to delay its next generation stent
from early 2001 to year to the second half _ a move that chagrined
investors. Boston Scientific stock closed at a 52-week low of
$16.125 Tuesday, rising to $16.25 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a step slow right now,'' declared Tobin confidently.
``That is all that is boils down to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
