<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TIM-REID0818-COX     08-17 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIM-REID0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REID between the lines
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``Asunder'' isn't a typical black film,
producer-director Tim Reid acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   That's the point.
</P>
<P>
   Films aimed at black American audiences tend to be urban crime
dramas, broad comedies or light family dramas. ``Asunder,'' which
stars Blair Underwood, Debbi Morgan and Michael Beach, is a
suspense thriller with slasher-film elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different genre for us,'' Reid said. ``There
isn't really right now a film like it in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Asunder'' will premiere in Dayton to benefit the College
Fund/UNCF and Wilberforce University. Reid and his wife, executive
producer Daphne Maxwell Reid, will introduce the film and field
audience questions at its conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asunder ``concerns two married couples whose lives are torn
apart when one of the wives dies in a freak accident. Blaming best
friend Michael Hubbs (Beach) for his loss, widower Chance Williams
(Underwood) seduces Hubbs' wife Lauren (Morgan) to exact his
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a director, I attempted to wrap this sort of morality play
in the familiar context of the slasher-film genre as well as the
thriller-film genre,'' Reid said from Los Angeles, likening
``Asunder'' to such films as ``Scream `` and ``Fatal Attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   The title is taken from the biblical phrase from Matthew
commonly used in wedding vows, ``What God therefore has joined
together, let no man put asunder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This movie is about what happens when you disobey that rule,''
Reid said, chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asunder'' is the first film produced at Reid's Virginia-based
New Millennium Studios. The actor-turned-filmmaker _ best known for
his role as Venus Flytrap on the classic television series ``WKRP
in Cincinnati `` _ founded the studio in 1997 to produce motion
pictures for the under-served black audience, in an attempt to take
such films in new and different directions.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has proved reluctant to follow his vision. After
studio distributors passed on ``Asunder,'' saying they didn't see
an audience for the film, Reid earlier this year founded New
Millennium Releasing to distribute the $2 million feature himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood is in the big-movie game,'' Reid said, explaining
that a major releasing company would spend three times the cost of
his film to distribute it. ``The decisions that they make are
solely based on mass appeal _ the number of people that they think
they can get into the theater to see this movie. They don't think
about audiences so much, and especially, in particular, black
audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   The relatively few films Hollywood releases for black audiences
are typically aimed at teenagers, leaving middle-class black adults
with little to watch, Reid said. Rarely does the black middle-class
see itself on screen, and then it's only in proven genres such as
the family drama _ epitomized by such films as ``Eve's Bayou'' and
``Soul Food.''
</P>
<P>
   New Millennium Studios is Reid's attempt to produce niche-market
films for that audience. Situated on 60 acres near Richmond, the
full-service studio complex for motion picture, television,
commercial and music video production includes a 14,850-square-foot
soundstage, post-production facilities, music recording studios and
a 15-acre backlot.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was born in Norfolk, Va., and graduated in 1968 from
Norfolk State University with a bachelor's degree. in business and
marketing. He was awarded an honorary doctorate at his alma mater
in 1996 and is in the National Black College Alumni Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope, and it's still a dream at this point, is to be
prolific enough to turn out anywhere from four to six movies a
year,'' Reid said. ``We're building to that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Asunder'' will have played on 50 to 75 screens across the
United States before its November home-video release. New
Millennium Releasing has been targeting the film's audience with
limited runs in major cities such as Chicago, Atlanta and Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news about our audience for a young independent
distributor is that we can reach 50 to 60 percent of our audience
in 25 cities,'' Reid said. ``Because the concentration of people of
color in America is in primary markets.''
</P>
<P>
   In smaller markets such as Dayton, Reid often gets involved with
the community _ as with the benefit premiere _ to promote his film,
benefiting the cause and himself. ``I can't . . . spend $25,000 on
advertising in a small market,'' he said. ``I just can't afford to
do that at this stage. But I can go in and get involved with the
community, a fund-raiser, get people to come, start a word-of-mouth
campaign, leave the movie for a couple weeks and come away with a
decent earning opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid employed a similar grass-roots marketing strategy for his
1996 feature directorial debut, ``Once Upon a Time . . . When We
Were Colored.''
</P>
<P>
   As a television producer, Reid created the Showtime series
``Linc's,'' as well as the CBS situation comedy ``Frank's Place.''
He appeared as an actor in both series and was most recently seen
in the WB series ``Sister, Sister.'' Reid co-starred with his wife
in the 1989-'90 detective drama, ``Snoops.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his efforts behind the camera, Reid is still associated
with television roles such as ``WKRP''s'' smooth-talking nighttime
DJ Gordon Sims, aka Venus Flytrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, and I would be disappointed if I wasn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid recounts the story of shooting the tail end of a movie
several weeks ago in Ethiopia at a religious site in a remote area
near the country's north border, where the people live mostly in
huts, very few with electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm standing there shooting in this ancient site and a little
kid walked up to me and said, `Sister, Sister.' And it just blew me
away. I was dumbfounded. And I went, `How? Where?' And they said,
`Satellite.' I just started laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television, it has an incredible reach. Like I say, I'd be
kind of silly to go somewhere and not enjoy the experience of
people coming up to me and saying I like your (work). Especially
because of my success in terms of being blessed _ being in the
business for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The transition from actor to filmmaker has been extremely
difficult, he said. ``And yet, I love the process of filmmaking and
television shows. The frustration aspects are many indeed because
of the climate in Hollywood for people of color behind the cameras.
You're constantly in battle on the front lines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Linc's'' ran for two seasons to critical acclaim but was
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got canceled because I wasn't getting enough white
viewers,'' Reid said, laughing. ``You walk away from that
experience and you go, `What the hell am I doing?' I mean, I'm
doing critically acclaimed work like ``Frank's Place'' _ nine Emmy
nominations _ and I get canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Reid is forging an independent path with New
Millennium Studios and Releasing. His next production, ``Sold My
Soul to Keep,'' is a supernatural thriller starring Underwood, who
also directs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I don't think there's ever been a movie with people of
color quite like this,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
