<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0818-COX     08-17 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW EVIDENCE OF EXPLOSION ON SUB, BRITISH RESCUE TEAM HEADS TO
SITE
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As a British rescue team sailed to assist in the rescue
of a stricken Russian nuclear submarine Thursday new evidence
suggested that a huge explosion sent the vessel to the bottom in a
few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Navy officials are analyzing film taken of the Kursk
that shows massive damage reaching from the front to the conning
tower. The control room where most of the crew works is below the
tower, suggesting many sailors could not escape when the submarine
went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accident happened so quickly we can say it was like a
flash,'' said Russian Navy Capt. Igor Dygalo.
</P>
<P>
   Jane's Defense Weekly expert Paul Beaver told Reuters that a
NATO official had described to him what happened based on
information gathered with sophisticated reconnaissance equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first explosion sounded like a torpedo or other naval
weapon detonating,'' he said. ``The
</P>
<P>
   most likely location is the forward torpedo compartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Beaver said the NATO official told him that the first explosion
was followed almost immediately by a second much larger blast
``consistent with further warheads being triggered.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk can carry up to 28 torpedoes and anti-submarine
missiles, each with warheads
</P>
<P>
   weighing up to 1,000 pounds. An explosion involving even a few
torpedoes would have caused
</P>
<P>
   catastrophic damage.
</P>
<P>
   The damage apparently included the submarine's internal escape
capsule located in the
</P>
<P>
   conning tower, rendering it useless, Dygalo said.
</P>
<P>
   With hope dimming for the 118 crewmembers, Russia failed again
Thursday in its frenzied efforts to connect a diving capsule to the
Kursk. One of Russia's most modern subs, the Kursk is slowly
sinking into the sandy bed of the Barents Sea, making the rescue
attempts even more difficult. The weather remained treacherous with
high winds and crashing waves.
</P>
<P>
   The British team, which is equipped with a sophisticated rescue
mini-sub, is not expected to
</P>
<P>
   arrive until Saturday afternoon _ a week after the Kursk sank to
the Arctic seabed. The rescue
</P>
<P>
   mission set sail early Thursday morning from a Norwegian port
for the 900-mile voyage to the
</P>
<P>
   waters some 350 feet above the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the long odds of success, the British team, which had
been waiting for days to be asked by the Russians to assist,
expressed optimism. ``There's always a chance,'' said team
commander Alan Hoskins as the team set sail.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a second ship with Norwegian deep-sea divers that was
facing delays was expected to arrive early Sunday after Norwegian
officials scrambled to speed up its journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 24-hour delay would not be a good thing in a situation like
this,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Karsten Klepsvik said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Navy has given contradictory estimates of how long
the Kursk's oxygen could last, but some officers say air generators
may have been destroyed when the submarine slammed into the seabed.
Some officials have said oxygen would be depleted as soon as
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian Naval Vice Chief of Staff Alexander Pobozhy told
reporters in Brussels Thursday that the boat's oxygen could last
``as long as two to three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN reported that U.S. intelligence officials doubted Russian
claims that the crew survived the explosion. The officials
reportedly told CNN that they have detected no evidence of the
tapping reported by Russian officials or any other signs of life on
the Kursk since it went down Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Prime Minister Mikhail Kasyanov described the situation
as ``next to catastrophic'' and many Russian commentators said hope
for rescue had vanished.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin, who has been vacationing at a resort
near the Black Sea during the crisis, was criticized sharply
Thursday in the Russian press for delays in responding to the
tragic incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sailors on the Kursk fell silent yesterday,'' wrote the
popular tabloid Komsomolskaya
</P>
<P>
   Pravda in bold red type. ``Why has the president been silent?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why on earth did he think it was possible to keep mum five
days, when the entire nation has spent those days consumed by only
one thought _ will they be saved or won't they?''
</P>
<P>
   Izvestia, a widely read liberal daily, wrote: ``Together with
the K-141 (Kursk) has sunk people's faith that the state can
protect them from danger. It is the authorities themselves who have
hit the bottom, together with the K-141.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertrcoxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
