<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Aug. 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chilly air amassing over central and eastern Canada will spill
across the Northeast in a series of surges in the next few days. By
late in the weekend, scattered nighttime frost will be possible in
parts of the northern Appalachians and northern Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Cloudy, cool weather will cover most of the eastern Great Lakes
and interior Northeast Friday. Scattered light rain will fall north
of a low pressure area as it moves east along the Mason-Dixon line.
Farther south, strong thunderstorms will erupt in the warm, humid
air from Virginia to the eastern Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptional heat will persist from Texas to the Gulf states.
</P>
<P>
   A broken band of strong thunderstorms will accompany a cool
front as it moves south into the southern Plains and northern Gulf
states. North of the front, cooler and less humid air will cover
the Plains and Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: BLUE MOON
</P>
<P>
   A milky veil has been dimming the sun from Idaho to the northern
Great Lakes as smoke from wildfires has been drawn east by strong
high-level winds. On rare occasions, the appropriate distribution
of particle sizes in the smoke from fires can cause moonlight to
take on a bluish color. The airborne ash particles act like a
filter, selectively allowing blue light through the smokey pall
aloft. Huge forest fires in western Canada gave a bluish hue to the
sun and moon in the Northeast on Sept. 26, 1950.
</P>
</TEXT>
