NYT-08-17-00 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4829 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-17 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
y
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLUTCHING AT CLICHES
</P>
<P>
   c. Hearst Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   By MARIANNE MEANS
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The drive to the middle of the road by both the
Democratic and Republican conventions has produced such a traffic
jam in the center lane that the parties are robbing each other's
banalities and cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Sigh. Nothing new here to elevate the basic language of
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Is it asking too much to expect our partisan leaders to come up
with fresh ways of saying the same old thing? Both Vice President
Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush insist their campaigns are
about the future, but their talk is straight out of the past. Even
the jokes are stale.
</P>
<P>
   Politics was more fun when the candidates went directly at it,
verbal swords drawn, from the left and the right. This centrist
stuff forces them onto the same yellow line, with variations of
style and emphasis but very little room for inventive spark. In
politics, imitation is not the sincerest form of flattery. It is
running out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to them:
</P>
<P>
   Bush says ``I'm a different kind of Republican.'' Swell.
Different than whom? His father and President Reagan? Heaven
forbid. ``I don't think I'm reaching that far back in history,''
Bush says. Eight years is ``far back''? Then ``different'' in what
way? His policies sound like familiar GOP thinking, merely
expressed in a more polite manner than in the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   He's distancing himself from former House Speaker Newt Gingrich
and the harshly partisan Republican Congress that twice closed down
the federal government, tried to impeach President Clinton and
earned a reputation for not doing much. But he can't bring himself
to say so and undercut GOP congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also likes to describe himself as ``different.'' In his
case, we know what he's talking about. It's the Clinton, stupid.
But he can't come right out and say what he means, either, or he
will look disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are substantive differences between the two
candidates: otherwise why would we need an election? On national
policy, Gore and Bush disagree on important topics like taxes,
education, Social Security, health care and military preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans are papering over these disagreements to
make themselves look more like Democrats and the Democrats are
overdoing the moderate aspects of their programs to make themselves
look conservative, if not exactly Republican. The homogenized
result is like a blended fruit smoothie - you can't tell the
bananas from the cherries. This concoction may go down easy, but
you don't know exactly what you are swallowing.
</P>
<P>
   That's why we get the kind of silliness we saw shortly before
the conventions opened. In a rash moment, Gore promised that if he
were elected his administration would represent ``a fresh start'',
a modest attempt to avoid another repetition of the customary claim
to be making a brave ''new beginning.`` Bush professed to be
astonished that Gore would use a phrase that the Republicans had
already been using. ''Unbelievable, isn't it?`` Bush crowed,
holding up a GOP campaign policy statement that included the words
''a fresh start.`` How sad that this is what passes for significant
political dialogue..
</P>
<P>
   The Bush team, of course, practices its own word theft. The GOP
platform pledges to ``leave no child behind.'' in access to
education and economic security. First Lady Hillary Clinton, in her
speech introducing her husband, noted pointedly that for decades
the trademark of the Childrens' Defense Fund, a Democratic-inclined
organization promoting opportunities for disadvantaged children for
which she used to work, was ``leave no child behind.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, President Clinton, the master wordsmith, didn't
get the prize for originality in his valedictory address at the
Democratic convention's opening night either. Touting his
administration's record, Clinton added: ``As that LA detective Joe
Friday used to say, ''just the facts, ma'am.`` The remark drew
laughter from the crowd - just as it had in 1988, when then-Vice
President George Bush, the current GOP nominee's father, used the
same line in his speech accepting that year's GOP presidential
nomination. It clearly doesn't take much to amuse political
convention delegates. Joe Friday was a character played by Jack
Webb in the popular television series ''Dragnet`` which ran from
1952 to 1959 and was revived briefly from 1967 to 1970. It has been
off the air for thirty years.
</P>
<P>
   The basic campaign argument is about ``change'' , whatever that
may mean beyond the fact the current White House incumbent is no
longer on the ballot. Both sides claim that mantle but don't define
it the same way. Voters like the idea of forward motion and
progress but they fear any radical philosophical shift that might
disrupt rather than improve the status quo. So talking about it is
tricky, or as Gore might say, ``risky.'' . The vice president was
mocked by Bush for overusing that word and no ``risks'' were
uttered in the series of surrogate speeches at the Democratic
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Joe Lieberman didn't go
near ``risky'' , preferring to fall back on all-purpose
``differences.'' As he gracefully put it, the two parties see
issues ``through a different set of eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of the best pitches for a transition from a
Democratic administration to another Democrat rather than a
Republican was made by Bush's father as he sought to replace Ronald
Reagan in 1988. ``When you have to change horses in mid-stream
doesn't it make sense to switch to one who's going the same way?''
he asked rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing that the Democrats haven't yet stolen that line. $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
