<HEADER>
A4831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0818-COX     08-17 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Vice president gets ready to trim his title by
a word
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore takes the stage at the Democratic National Convention
tonight to urge Americans to reject Republicans who would take them
``back to the past,'' and to promise prosperity, progress and
positive change if he wins the White House. Gore said he has been
working on his speech for two months, ``rewriting and editing and
tweaking'' the words. ``He was literally the person at the
typewriter on this,'' Tad Devine, a Gore campaign strategist, said
today. He said Gore will both set his issues agenda and talk about
the key decisions that have shaped his life. Gore's campaign
chairman, William Daley, said the speech would be an opportunity
for Gore to address people who think ``that he's just a boring,
stiff, you know, unable-to-speak guy,'' and to come through as a
real person.
</P>
<P>
   WIN ONE FOR THE TIPPER
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Tipper Gore will step into the spotlight to introduce
her husband, and to help voters see the Al Gore she sees. Analysts
say that's just what the Democrats need: Pulling Tipper off the
sidelines and into a more prominent role may help in swaying the
millions of female voters who say they're inclined to back George
W. Bush. Said ex-Democratic chairman Robert Strauss: ``I'd put
Tipper on a campaign train through the South. She has the same kind
of warmth Lady Bird Johnson had. She doesn't offend anyone, she's
warm, and fighting for her husband is something women would find
appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER BATTLE FOR MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain is to begin treatment Saturday for a recurrence
of the most dangerous form of skin cancer. McCain underwent several
tests at the Mayo Clinic in Scottsdale, Ariz., this morning to
determine the course of treatment. Advisers said McCain didn't know
whether the cancer had spread and was planning a news conference
Friday to talk about his condition. McCain did not take questions
from reporters after the visit, but did say, ``I feel fine.''
</P>
<P>
   INTO ENEMY TURF
</P>
<P>
   One day after Al Gore officially accepts the presidential
nomination, rival George W. Bush will campaign in Gore's home state
of Tennessee. Bush and Dick Cheney will begin a three-state tour
with a ``Victory 2000'' rally in Bartlett, Tenn., Friday, noting
that the state is crucial in this election. ``Gov. Bush is leading
by 45 points in Texas. And Al Gore is leading by 54 points in his
home as well _ Washington D.C. But here in Tennessee, it's neck and
neck,'' said Tenn. GOP chair Chip Saltsman. Bush and Cheney will
then make their way to Dallas the next day.
</P>
<P>
   WINNING POINTS FOR PERSISTENCE
</P>
<P>
   Protesters returned to the streets today for the last day of the
convention, denouncing big business and promising to greet Al
Gore's acceptance speech with a chorus of shouts, chants and drum
beats outside the convention hall. The first rally began at
Pershing Square, a gathering place for protesters this week, where
about 100 activists criticized Citibank for funding projects that
they said were ruining the environment. The protest, called ``Spank
the Bank,'' moved about two blocks to Citibank Center downtown,
then returned to Pershing Square without incident. ``Boycott
Citigroup, the world's most destructive bank,'' read stickers that
protesters pasted on surfaces downtown.
</P>
<P>
   EVEN THE PROTESTS ARE CHOREOGRAPHED
</P>
<P>
   At the Los Angeles Police Department's Rampart station, an
earlier march had all the earmarks of a serious confrontation:
Hundreds of demonstrators vented at the police, and 38 were
arrested. But it was a carefully orchestrated arrangement, with
protest organizers and police scripting out just what kind of civil
disobedience would bring symbolic arrests without stirring the
crowd to violence. Said Capt. Michael Moore: ``They asked what it
would take to get arrested. We looked up the law and gave them some
ideas. They wanted to lie down in the street, but we told them they
wouldn't get arrested for that.'' Instead, the two sides settled on
a plan for the demonstrators to sit on a sidewalk, he said.
</P>
<P>
   LIEB'S LABOR LOST?
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman met privately with leaders of labor, women and
education organizations today as he renewed efforts to reassure
groups nervous about some of the positions he took before becoming
Al Gore's running mate. Aides said it was ``standard protocol'' for
the vice presidential nominee to reach out to core members of the
Democratic coalition with such meetings. But some blacks, teachers,
unions and others are looking for reassurance that his centrist
views are compatible with theirs. Teill take the podium to dispel
the image of the vice president as wooden.
</P>
<P>
   CHUG-CHUG, CHUG-A-LUG
</P>
<P>
   A four-day, 400-mile riverboat excursion down the Mississippi
River that was to take Al Gore and Joe Lieberman through some
Midwestern campaign stops following the convention has been
scrapped. Gore campaign officials said they are ditching the Mark
Twain riverboat in Moline, Ill., on Sunday and taking buses
instead. The boat couldn't go fast enough to fit all the stops;
it's speed is said to be 10-15 mph. ``The most important thing is
reaching communities and reaching people, and this was the most
effective way of doing that'' Gore spokesman Chris Moody said of
the change.
</P>
<P>
   NAGGING HEADACHE TURNING TO FULL-BLOWN MIGRAINE
</P>
<P>
   If the Republican convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago was
markedpers
</P>
