<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-ALTERNATIVE-THEATE     08-17 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ALTERNATIVE-THEATER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOG DAYS SIZZLE FOR THEATER'S OFF-OFFBEAT PUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Say what you will about the New York International
Fringe Festival, it is, without a doubt, the only place in the city
you can see a Hungarian adaptation of a Greek epic performed in
(what else?) German.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. For a limited time only, it's ``Die Ungarische
Medea,'' written by none other than Arpad Goncz, who recently
stepped down as president of Hungary. (The Fringe had nothing to do
with his resignation, festival officials say.)
</P>
<P>
   Goncz's play is just one of scores of shows now on the Fringe,
the annual two-week downtown theater festival that revels in all
things dramatic and different.
</P>
<P>
   How different? Well, a quick glance at this year's schedule
includes ``I Am Star Trek,'' a staged biography of Gene
Roddenberry, creator of that television series; ``Frankenclown,''
an evil-clown show promising ``several slayings and raucous
laughter''; and of course the Tiny Ninja Theater, which will
perform ``Macbeth'' using nothing but 100 tiny plastic ninjas,
several miniature aliens and a pair of and Smile dolls. (They play
the Macbeths.)
</P>
<P>
   All in all the Fringe festival, which began on Wednesday and
runs through Aug. 27, will present 180 shows in 20 theaters on the
Lower East Side, in the East Village and nearby. Every day the
Fringe will present almost 80 performances, staged by some 2,000
artists from 12 countries and overseen by a volunteer staff of 400.
</P>
<P>
   Even veterans of the Fringe, now in its fourth year, are a
little awestruck by the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I am absolutely certain there is no way it is
possibly going to happen,'' said John Clancy, the festival's
artistic director, who, as of Sunday, was already chain-smoking and
wearing a two-day-old beard. ``And yet somehow every day it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the scope of the Fringe's schedule, you might think
that every little-known actor, writer and director in the city was
booked. But the Fringe is only one of several theater festivals
running around the city.
</P>
<P>
   They include a newcomer, the Midtown International Theater
Festival, and a recent upstart, the Pure Pop Festival, as well as
two more established ones: the American Living Room, a seven-week
festival of theater, film and puppetry at the Here Theater in the
South Village, and the Blueprint Series at the Ontological Theater
in the East Village, which concentrates on the work of new
experimental playwrights and directors. Two other downtown
festivals, the Summer Camp series at Soho Rep and the Ice Factory
at the Ohio Theater, just finished their annual runs.
</P>
<P>
   With budgets less than the cast-party tabs for most Broadway
shows, these festivals make August the busiest month for the myriad
low-budget, bighearted theaters collectively known as
off-off-Broadway. The timing of course is hardly coincidental;
August is traditionally a slow time for Broadway and off-Broadway,
leaving smaller theaters a prime opportunity to fill the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``August has become festival season downtown, the one moment
when all the little theaters in town celebrate their vibrant little
community,'' said Aaron Beall, a longtime off-off producer who
founded the Pure Pop festival. ``We were able to find one of the
last slots available on the calendar, the one slot no one else
would touch, and we made it our own.''
</P>
<P>
   All the festivals share common characteristics. First and
foremost is their ticket prices, which are, in short, cheap. None
of the festivals have tickets more expensive than $12, and some
shows are free.
</P>
<P>
   Not that production values are completely threadbare. Despite
off-off-Broadway's ragtag image, many theaters involved in the
festivals are increasingly sophisticated, with air conditioning,
cushioned seats and elaborate technical setups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are emphasizing our location, our convenience and our
safety,'' said John Chatterton, the founder of the Midtown
festival. ``And our A.C.''
</P>
<P>
   And while all of the festivals' founders would claim their own
aesthetics, each festival has at least one show that falls into
this venerable category: the show with the outrageous title.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences of the avant-garde apparently love a goofy title,
which avant-garde artists are apparently plenty willing to provide.
Into this vast phylum fall entries like this year's ``Clowns in the
Vagina,'' another evil-clown show at the Fringe; ``The Hobo Got Too
High,'' a Pure Pop entry about a cocaine addict named Bug
Blowmonkey; and ``I Didn't Ask for Bare-Chested Men Singing
Doo-Wop,'' a Fringe show that is described as a farce and may well
be.
</P>
<P>
   The award for the oddest title, however, goes to the
Neo-Futurists, a Chicago-based comedy troupe playing the Fringe.
The show is ``The Complete Lost Works of Samuel Beckett as Found in
an Envelope (Partially Burned) in a Dustbin in Paris Labeled:
`Never to Be Performed. Never. Ever. Ever. Or I'll Sue. I'll Sue
From the Grave.''' True to form, it has been one of the Fringe's
hottest tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The newest of the bunch is the midtown festival, a monthlong
affair featuring 19 productions at four black-box theaters in the
West 40s.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which began on Aug. 9 and runs through Sept. 3,
was founded by Chatterton, an off-off-Broadway playwright who is
banking _ the festival's $30,000 budget comes mostly out of his
pocket _ on the idea that the theater lovers who go to midtown for
Broadway shows might take a chance on something a little less
polished.
</P>
<P>
   Chatterton, who also publishes a weekly newsletter called the
Off Off Broadway Review, said he started the festival after reading
several articles about the Fringe festival. ``To be honest,'' he
said, ``I thought I could do it better.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, he said, that's because his tastes differ from the
Fringe's. ``I am slightly more middle-of-the-road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the midtown festival has booked productions of
Shakespeare, Shaw and Beckett. But it also includes potential
modern epics like ``Stopless Go-Go Girls at the Troll Hole,'' the
heartwarming story of a group of topless dancers and their loyal,
leather-loving clientele. (``A could-be cult classic,'' reads its
news release. Time will tell.)
</P>
<P>
   And while Chatterton has been trumpeting his theaters' air
conditioning, at one of the festivals' theaters last week those
same units blew a fuse during a performance of Harold Pinter's
``Lover.'' After two false starts and several expletives from the
technical booth, the actors soldiered on under house lights. About
five minutes into the show, the stage lights came back on.
</P>
<P>
   Such experiences have made Chatterton somewhat more humble, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a far greater appreciation and respect,'' he said, with
a laugh, ``for what they've been doing at the Fringe.''
</P>
<P>
   Chatterton is hardly the first to challenge the Fringe. That
honor would belong to Beall, the proprietor of Todo Con Nada, a
basement theater on Ludlow Street on the Lower East Side. Beall
(pronounced bell) was also a Fringe co-founder, but he started the
Pure Pop Festival after he had a falling out with Clancy over the
Fringe festival's direction.
</P>
<P>
   So using the pseudonym Lestar Bang, he founded his own festival,
complete with visions of a 24-hour theater delicatessen, a yearlong
schedule of productions and a vast Internet network of support
services for off-off Broadway companies.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of that panned out, but this year Beall is back with
another ambitious slate of productions, some 20 shows including a
series of Chekhov shorts, a Richard Foreman play and several
stagings of the horrible horror films of the cult movie director Ed
Wood.
</P>
<P>
   On a shoestring budget, all of Pure Pop's shows are being
presented at either Nada or Beall's newest theater, Show World,
which he carved out of an unseemly corner of the former sex shop
with that name on Eighth Avenue near 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   And while other festivals delegate artistic responsibilities,
more than half the productions at Pure Pop are being directed by
Beall, a shadowy director named Frank Cwiklik (not another
pseudonym, Beall assures) and Ian W. Hill, Beall's protege, a man
so devoted to the theater that he long lived in a large, rat-proof
cage in the basement of Nada.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's rugged living situation notwithstanding, for sheer
perseverance, its still hard to beat the Fringe.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year it looked as if the festival might not happen.
The Present Co., the producer of the Fringe, had serious money
troubles that almost caused it to lose the Theatorium, its
5,000-square-foot home and the Fringe headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some very bad days,'' said Elena K. Holy, the
festival's producing director.
</P>
<P>
   Part of those problems came from the growth of the Fringe. In
1997, when it was founded, the budget was $74,000; this year, its
fourth, the figure is $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   This year's schedule, for example, includes a raft of
nontheatrical programming, including a literary reading series
(FringeInk), a visual art exhibition (FringeArt) and a children's
theater program (FringeJr.).
</P>
<P>
   The main emphasis, however, remains the shows, which as usual
run the gamut. A casual visitor to a theater at, say, 5 p.m. on a
Tuesday might encounter a puppet show (``Doctor Faustus''), a
comedy troupe (``The Chainsaw Boys'') or the obligatory paean to
Elvis (``Viva Los Alamos''). Come back an hour later, and the
theater might be home to an actual play (``Buddy Movie''), a new
musical (``To Sirloin With Love: A Meat Opera'') or even an
old-fashioned revival (George S. Kaufman and Edna Ferber's 1936
backstage comedy ``Stage Door'').
</P>
<P>
   Most of these shows are performed a few times, then disappear
without a trace. Some, however, have proved to have lives beyond
the Fringe, including last year's ``Never Swim Alone,'' currently
in a commercial run at the SoHo Playhouse, and the 1999 gag musical
``Urinetown,'' which is gearing up for its own off-Broadway run.
</P>
<P>
   The Fringe has also begun to pick up some higher-profile uptown
partners, including the Drama League and the Ensemble Studio
Theater, both of which are producing several short plays at the
festival. It also received technical support from off-Broadway
companies like the Joseph Papp Public Theater, the Vineyard Theater
and the American Place Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest change, however, is that for the first time
the New York International Fringe Festival is actually living up to
its name.
</P>
<P>
   ``International,'' Clancy explains, ``used to mean a couple of
guys from Toronto.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, there are 30 international shows _ ``coming
over actual seas,'' he said _ giving the schedule a multilingual
feel. International entries include ``Ha! Hamlet,'' a two-person
version from Switzerland; ``Girobira,'' a performance art troupe
from Bilbao, Spain; and something titled ``Synchronized Swimming:
The Dry Version,'' also from Switzerland, proving the outrageous
name theory transcends international borders.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say there is also another new element to this year's
festival: calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like senior year in high school,'' Clancy said. ``We
know how to do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking Risks
</P>
<P>
   Even as crews scurried around Fringe headquarters the other day,
Clancy and Holy seemed unconcerned about any potential logistic
land mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell if this is calm or exhaustion,'' Holy said. ``But
it feels OK''
</P>
<P>
   But what of the art? Many of the companies are performing
together for the first time. And more experienced troupes are
trying out new material. Are the organizers concerned that some
things may be, well, just plain bad?
</P>
<P>
   ``I view it as a place for established artists to take risks,''
Clancy said, ``and emerging artists to work in a professional
environment for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Holy thought for a moment, and added: ``And fun. The Fringe
should be fun.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
