<HEADLINE>
A SHEEP, YES, TAKES A COCKEYED VIEW OF THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Time, channel are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though the hero of ``Sheep in the Big City'' is a sheep named
Sheep, there is nothing generic about this sly, mordant new series,
which will have a preview on the Cartoon Network at 9 Friday night.
(It will begin for real in November.) The show's model is
unmistakably ``Rocky and Bullwinkle,'' with its hilariously
puffed-up storytelling voice, several cliff-hanging episodes in
each half-hour installment, puns and most of all a style of humor
that is silly enough to appeal to children and satiric enough for
adults.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Sheep in the Big City'' has its own look and feel. The
brightly colored characters have faces that are sometimes as askew
as those in a cubist portrait, a reflection of the show's cockeyed
yet astute view of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The first brief episode is not the most engaging. The mute yet
perfectly communicating Sheep is abducted from his home at Farmer
Brown's by an evil military group that needs him as ammunition for
its secret weapon. Things pick up instantly when Sheep escapes in
the city and has to evade the villainous General Specific and his
cohorts, General Dentistry and General Interest. Farmer Brown, a
man who has had way too much therapy, arrives and walks the city
street calling out in a singsong voice: ``Shee-eep! Where are you?
I need closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sheep is doing just fine, getting money from an ATM.
Don't ask how he earns it (innocently) or why Farmer Brown thinks
Sheep has become a cross-dresser; those are big-city surprises.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that Sheep will make it in the city and go on
to fresh adventures. The preview ends, after all, with him tossing
his fleece in the air, evoking the hat toss at the end of ``The
Mary Tyler Moore Show'' and signaling a happy future for this
series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
