<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHOSE-MESSAGE-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS DIVERSITY DEBATE IS CHANGING AMERICAN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, Aug. 17, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With three photos, of members of the Alabama
delegation at the GOP convention (NNS10), members of the same
state's Democratic delegation (NNS11) and members of the Democratic
New York delegation (NNS12) 
 By JONATHAN TILOVE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _'' And, in the category of most convincing
portrayal of a diverse and inclusive political party at a national
convention, the winner is ... Well, of course the winner is the
Democratic Party. They own this Convention in Philadelphia was,
``We're inclusive,'' the sledgehammer rejoinder at the Democratic
National Convention here was that when it comes to racial and
ethnic diversity, ``We're the real deal.'' But the contest that
counts, to be decided in November, is not a matter of whether the
Republicans can outdo the Democrats on diversity. They cannot.
Rather, it is whether the GOP can sufficiently burnish its image on
matters of race to keep pace with a changing America. It is an
America that is changing subtly in the warmer tones of tolerance
the electorate appears to desire, and unsubtly in the changing
complexion of a nation whose once-overwhelming whiteness diminishes
year by year. The Republican Party remains far whiter at its core
than the nation is, just as the Democratic Party is more
multiracial in its composition than America as a whole will be for
years to come. But the Republicans' anemic record in attracting
brown and black votes has its tactical advantage now. Why? Because
even a small improvement will look like victory and unnerve the
Democrats, who count so heavily on sweeping 90 percent of black
voters and big majorities of Latinos that they have nowhere to go
but down. Better yet for Republicans, if they succeed in upping the
ante on what Democrats need to do to keep black and Latino votes
from straying, they may force Democrats to make the kind of overt
policy commitments on issues of race and class that helped
Republicans win additional white votes in the past. However it
plays out, though, this summer's conventions may mark a signal
moment in American racial politics _ the point at the turn of a new
century when both major parties seemed determined to outdo each
other as celebrants of diversity. ``Demography is destiny,'' said
Frederick Lynch, a government professor at Claremont-McKenna
College. ``As far as being the white party,'' he said of the
Republicans, ``it's not going to get any better.'' ``They have
realized that they at least have to be perceived as inclusive, or
they are going to be irrelevant in the future,'' said Maria
Echaveste, the deputy White House chief of staff. ``The
demographics are telling.'' For decades, Republicans effectively
played off the image of Democrats as the ``minority'' party, the
hapless captive of constituent interest groups. President Clinton
moved his party away from that image. And at the same time,
America's Hispanic and Asian communities soared in size through
immigration and reduced the political burden of the Democrats'
reputation as the party of minorities. Republican strategists
decided they had to re-examine a strategy that depended almost
entirely on white voters. Among those setting the new GOP course is
Karl Rove, Texas Gov. George W. Bush's top strategist. In an
interview with The Washington Post in Philadelphia, Rove declared
that the ``Southern Strategy'' _ polarizing the electorate along
racial lines to win white votes _ was dead. The inclusionary tone
of this year's Republican convention was, in fact, first struck in
1996 in San Diego. But as former party chairman Haley Barbour noted
in Philadelphia, this time the message and messenger _ George W.
Bush _ are one. Still, as many news commentators in Philadelphia
noted, this year's convention _ which was chaired by a woman, a
Hispanic and a black _ sometimes verged perilously close to parody.
There were black preachers and church choirs and popular
entertainers. Abel Maldonado, a Hispanic Republican assemblyman
from California, delivered remarks entirely in Spanish. Laura Bush,
the governor's wife, delivered her speech to the convention in
front of a mock classroom set up on the stage and peopled by black
and brown children who, as one convention theme had it, would not
be ``left behind.'' Heavyweight figures like Gen. Colin Powell and
Bush's top national security adviser, Condoleezza Rice _ both of
whom are black _ spoke. But the bench is not deep. J.C. Watts, the
only black Republican member of Congress and one of the
convention's chairs, was on a relentless schedule of preaching,
singing and speaking. ``They had J.C. Watts so spread out you'd
think that he was mayonnaise,'' Detroit Mayor Dennis Archer,
himself one of the chairs of the Democratic convention, told a
breakfast of Louisiana Democrats in Los Angeles. Indeed, the
extraordinary colors of the Philadelphia convention were ridiculed
all week here as a masquerade, a minstrel show, a lie and an
insult. ``If I could just get my administration up here, it would
be as diverse as anything you saw on stage a couple of weeks ago,''
joked President Clinton in his opening-night address to the
convention. ``And it would be real, too _ it would be real,''
delegate Rosemary Brooks-Bitting called out from the New Jersey
delegation. The Republican convention, she said, represented ``an
excellent job of copycatting,'' but she considered it cynical and
insulting. To Elsie Y. Cross, a pioneer in the field of corporate
diversity management, it is all ``very cynical.'' The Republicans
are not changing their policies, their attitudes or their culture,
just their pitch, she said. ``I don't think it fooled very many
people,'' Cross said of the convention in her hometown of
Philadelphia. ``It's all about shrewd marketing,'' said professor
Michael Eric Dyson, a cultural critic and writer at DePaul
University in Chicago, of the Republican effort. ``It speaks to the
need to have multiculturalism in the new millennium.'' But Dyson,
an observer at the Democratic convention, said that while the
Democrats are more skilled at manipulating the symbols of
diversity, he, like Cross, believes they use black and brown faces
in nearly as superficial a fashion. James Pinkerton, a Newsday
columnist who was a White House adviser to Gov. Bush's father when
he was president, said that while the Democrats this week cried
``hypocrisy'' over the Republican embrace of multiracial images,
the Democrats are in his view the greater hypocrites for stifling
any debate on issues like trade, on which Democrats are deeply
divided. While the party line in Los Angeles was that most
Americans saw through the ``phony'' diversity in Philadelphia, not
everyone was discounting that it could have serious consequences.
``The danger is that it will be politically meaningful in an
undeserved way,'' said Christopher Edley Jr., a senior policy
adviser to Gore and Clinton's leading adviser on race. The
Democrats enjoy a profound advantage over the Republicans in having
so many surrogate campaigners with a stake in the election's
outcome. Blacks were 20 percent of the delegates in Los Angeles and
only 4 percent in Philadelphia. A third of all delegates were ``of
color'' here. According to the National Association of Latino
Elected and Appointed Officials, of the Latino elected officials
who identify themselves with a party, 1,577 are Democrats and 134
are Republicans. Of the 19 Hispanics in Congress, 15 are Democrats.
In Congress there are 38 black Democrats and J.C. Watts. In the
state legislatures there are 564 black Democrats and five
Republicans. Asians vote more independently, but most prominent
Asian elected officials are Democrats and the Asian vote is
trending in that direction. All the Asians in Congress are
Democrats. ``I think it's up to the Democrats not to take the
minority vote for granted,'' said Energy Secretary Bill Richardson,
who had aspired to become the first Hispanic on a national ticket
as Gore's runningmate. ``The Republicans are projecting an image of
inclusion,'' Richardson said. ``We have to have a clear message
that theirs is just show and ours is a reality. But in the age of
short attention spans and quick TV soundbites, I have to hand it to
them, they did a good job. They dented us a little bit. We have to
work extra hard.'' (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS) ``George W. Bush is for
photo opportunies, Al Gore is for real opportunities,'' Joseph
Andrew, the party's national chair, told the convention's Black
Caucus. Los Angeles was ``the most diverse political convention in
the history of the world,'' Andrew said. California Lt. Gov. Cruz
Bustamante told the Hispanic Caucus that Bush was making himself
out to be like Ricky Martin, but that anyone who thinks his
administration would be good for Latinos is ``living la vida
loca.'' Kathryn ``Cookie'' Manen'to, a black delegate from Chico,
Calif., and a former blues and gospel radio deejay, said she could
tell from watching the Philadelphia convention on TV that, while
the music on stage was OK, the rhythm on the convention floor was
not. ``They were trying to get their boogie down, but, come on
boys, that's not natural for you.'' In remarks before the Asian
Pacific Caucus, Commerce Secretary Norman Mineta, the first
Asian-American ever to serve in the Cabinet, said that while there
are distinguished Asian-American Republicans, they are less
connected to the grass roots. Many Republicans loved the line in
Condoleezza Rice's speech in which she said of the GOP, ``I found a
party that sees me as an individual and not as a member of group.''
But, as respected as Rice and Powell may be, when it comes to
helping persuade other blacks to vote Republican, they command no
troops. Instead, Bush and the Republicans must appeal over the
heads of most black and Hispanic leaders and directly to voters. It
is not a strategy that can win the Hispanic vote, said Raul
Yzaguirre, head of the National Council of La Raza, but it can peel
off enough to make a difference. But Lynch thinks it is a mistake
to underestimate how far a Republican embrace of the diversity
ideal can take the party. Lynch, who examined the diversity
industry in his book ``The Diversity Machine,'' said the Republican
Party, like many other like-motivated corporations that embarked on
diversity campaigns out of ``business necessity,'' may find they
have unleashed forces they ultimately will be unable to control.
``I don't think they realize,'' said Lynch, ``that inclusion means
their party is going to change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1751EDT &QL; 
