<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KINGS-FILM-REVIEW-2TA     08-17 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGS-FILM-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ORIGINAL KINGS OF COMEDY': IN THE FLAMBOYANT TRADITION OF
RICHARD PRYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The self-proclaimed Kings of Comedy in Spike Lee's concert film
``The Original Kings of Comedy'' couldn't be more resplendent in
the outfits they wear onstage. Filmed before a live audience on two
nights in February in Charlotte, N.C., Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley,
Cedric the Entertainer and Bernie Mac swagger across the stage,
urban legends in outfits that can best be described as Mack-tastic,
suits that qualify as Players' finery. If there's any real
competition among them, it's in their suits.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the ``Kings'' tour last winter escaped media
scrutiny _ there was the odd condescending magazine piece _ despite
being one of the most profitable stage shows in recent memory,
showing the power and hunger of the African-American audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Until a couple of years ago, the comedians' exposure was limited
mostly to cable television; all the Kings have spent time on HBO's
``Def Comedy Jam,'' or in Hughley's case, BET's ``Comic View'' _
``Def'' gone even more ghetto. Here, their comedy gives audiences
that have never seen anything like it a hilarious window on a new
world.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey, the star of ``The Steve Harvey Show'' on the WB network,
starts off the film as M.C. Harvey, who also patrols the perimeter
of the stage on ``It's Showtime at the Apollo,'' unleashing the
Sandman with his hook to snag minimally talented contestants
offstage. He wears a suit with a squared bottom and a single flap
across the bottom. (Later he changes into an off-white shadow
stripe number, as if preparing to star in an all-black version of
``Fantasy Island.'')
</P>
<P>
   With his flat-top fade haircut now trimmed so it's no longer
within range of air-traffic control, Harvey unleashes a shotgun
splatter of profanity. It may shock audiences who know him only
from ``The Steve Harvey Show,'' where he plays Steve Hightower,
rhythm-and-blues star turned teacher. (Perhaps it's because Harvey
and Hightower both dress as if they record for the rhythm-and-blues
label Philadelphia International.)
</P>
<P>
   Harvey is best at imagery. His upper lip curled so deep in
disgust that it cuts a dimple into his cheek, he begins by riffing
on ``Titanic,'' talking about how the band stayed on to play, a
notion he finds totally unbelievable. ``If Kool and the Gang had
been the band ...'' he says, then starts expertly wrapping the mike
cord around his arm, miming the packing up of stage equipment.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense that Harvey would play a former soul music pro on
his series. ``I'm a 1974 brother,'' he notes, referring to what he
considers the pinnacle of black music. In a recent performance with
the O-Jays at the Beacon Theater in New York City, where his love
of his fellow Ohioans and their classic soul lifted him, he almost
levitated as he reveled; when Harvey smiles, he goes into another
world.
</P>
<P>
   He swings into a definition of the differences between rap and
old-school funk, gracefully impersonating the Temptation Walk _
``five dudes and just one mike'' _ to the self-absorbed cacophony
of rap, where everyone has a mike and cannot be understood.
``Rappers make me sick!'' he says with a grimace, to a huge wave of
applause. (That remark has a special meaning for viewers of his
sitcom, where rappers turn up as guest stars.)
</P>
<P>
   Harvey is followed by D.L. Hughley, wearing a tan suit with
peaked lapels that could serve as ailerons. Again, those who know
Hughley from a sitcom _ ``The Hughleys'' in his case _ may blanch
at the banal profanity. They display their chops when they talk
about family, specifically African-American family with roots in
the South, which shows there's still something to the concept of
the monolithic black experience. (Harvey, who grew up in Cleveland,
and Mac, a Chicagoan, sound as if they came right out of the
South.) It's what gives these men a connection with the audience _
Hughley is on a high when talking about family behavior _ and shows
why their tour sold out on the order of the Steve Martin tours of
the 1970s. (A ``Queens of Comedy'' tour is tentatively scheduled
for next year.)
</P>
<P>
   The material on the cohesiveness of the black family is still
new to much of the country. But for those who have grown up living
what these comics talk about, this is a chance to see a part of
their lives exhibited in the mainstream and in the context of a
community of like-minded folks. (Given how quickly these extended
families are disappearing, it also suggests a sense of loss.) What
comes out of these comedians' hearts hits the most powerful chord,
and the audience wants more of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' debt to Richard Pryor's concert films is implicit; if
nothing else, it explains the downtown magnificence of their
apparel. Pryor found the true, idiosyncratic note and made it
universal. And despite what has been written about him as being a
scared, pathetic clown, in his performances the threat of physical
violence hung in the air; a friend once described him as the kind
who would take a gun to a prayer meeting. We may never see another
comedian comment so compellingly on his flamboyant
self-destructiveness, and so, in contrast, the Kings feel safe, not
challenging.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's an energy that comes from their rapport with their
crowd. (And their ease with one another is apparent in backstage
interviews included in the movie.) There is also the connection
that comes from their wardrobes; with more pleats than a Catholic
schoolgirl uniform store, they are an expensively customized
version of what their constituency wears. Lee catches members of
the audience posing for the cameras in their concert wear, grooving
to the '70s music. The show, which played in four cities before
opening in New York and throughout the nation, was recorded on
digital video and transferred to film; it looks fine, but
unremarkable.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The show includes too much of the ``white people do act this
way'' brand of comedy, an idea that was best dismissed on an old
``Simpsons'' episode when a black comedian, standing before a brick
``Night at the Improv''-type wall, did a groan-worthy routine about
the goofy way whites drive and Homer, laughing himself silly,
gasped: ``It's true. We're so lame.'' There is some great material
from this perspective: Hughley notes that black people don't ski or
do other dangerous physical activities because they experience
enough peril just trying to get through the average day. ``Bungee
jumping,'' he says. ``That's too much like hanging.'' And the
remarkably genial Cedric, a light-on-his-feet big man, embellishes
the differences between hope and wish: White people hope that
nothing goes wrong and blacks wish someone would start some
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric simply has more bounce to the ounce than the others, and
his joy at playing to a crowd makes it clear why he's called the
Entertainer. Especially when he does a routine about smoking (``You
can't smoke nowhere on earf,'' he says, marking himself as a
California resident) that concludes with a brilliant physical bit
on a street corner player who makes every smoker's gesture a piece
of ghetto theater. He flies across the stage, scoring with small
points.
</P>
<P>
   Mac, in a taupe suit and chocolate satin shirt and tie, is the
most autobiographical of the group. He turns his comedy on himself,
and with a dignified short Afro replacing his messy perm of the
'90s, he is more in command than ever. He uses short, punchy
attacks to make his point about his feigned lack of interest in sex
_ sometimes shooting a happy wink to the audience _ and he sounds
like a preacher on a roll, using a melodramatic shortness of breath
to punctuate his stand-up. He sums up with a piece on the ubiquity
of a certain swear word, which he describes as ``a noun, a person,
place or thing,'' and then proceeds to give the heft of an
adjective and even transforms it into a split infinitive.
</P>
<P>
   His routine is the best shaped, and in his hands the cussing
isn't tiresome. Using it to make a point, he comes off as King of
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE ORIGINAL KINGS OF COMEDY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Spike Lee; director of photography, Malik Sayeed;
edited by Barry Alexander Brown; production designer, Wynn P.
Thomas; produced by Lee, Walter Latham and David Gale; released by
Paramount Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley, Cedric the Entertainer and
Bernie Mac. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 117 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Original Kings of Comedy'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes enough
profanity to make Richard Pryor blush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
