<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4847 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ROTHKO0818-COX     08-17 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROTHKO0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chapel renovation brings Rothko's secrets to lightBy Jeanne
Claire van Ryzin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The windowless brick facade demands little attention.
Nestled in a tranquil, green oasis just a short distance from
traffic-choked thoroughfares, the Rothko Chapel offers an
unparalleled integration of modern art and architecture in the
service of spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by sturdy live oak trees and graced by a pool of
water in which Barnett Newman's rusted ``Broken Obelisk'' stands
sentinel, the small octagonal building is an oasis of meditative
stillness.
</P>
<P>
   Inside are 14 monumental paintings by the late abstract
expressionist artist Mark Rothko, which, along with the chapel,
were commissioned in 1964 by the visionary Houston art patrons John
and Dominique de Menil. The seven deep plum and seven ``black''
form paintings seem monochromatic, but their oblique rectangular
forms float against backgrounds of carefully modulated color. They
are at once puzzling and direct and reward those willing to lose
themselves in the infinite space they suggest. This ecumenical
sanctuary dedicated to human rights is a singular place apart _ a
place not to reflect but to clear the mind.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after an 18-month, $1.8 million renovation, the Rothko
Chapel is again open. And with the bustle of the opening
festivities now past, never has the synthesis of art and
architecture seemed more serene.
</P>
<P>
   The road to that repose, however, has hardly been easy.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the de Menils hired the venerable architect Philip
Johnson to design the building. But when Johnson's designs were
rejected by Rothko (the two had quite an acrimonious relationship),
Johnson bowed out. Houston architects Howard Barnstone and Eugene
Aubry completed the plans as the painter demanded. Although Rothko
completed the paintings in 1967, the chapel didn't open until 1971,
a year after his suicide.
</P>
<P>
   From the instant the doors opened, problems percolated. The
air-conditioning system never kept pace with the sweltering Gulf
Coast humidity. Rothko's plan for a skylight underestimated the
intensity of the Texas sun and, although a baffle was added to
diffuse the light, the interior remained murky and unevenly lit.
Then a crack appeared in the northwest wall, and it widened almost
enough to see through, the result of foundation problems that had
caused half the chapel to sink nearly 2 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The unstable interior environment led to the art aging
prematurely. Just a few years after the chapel opened, a mysterious
white film appeared on the black form paintings. Complicating
matters even more, the largest paintings were originally installed
via crane through the skylight and could not be removed for
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Carol Mancusi-Ungaro, the chief conservator of the
Menil Collection, began a quest to solve the riddle of the white
film. But she had few clues. ``No one was certain how Rothko had
created these paintings. There were maybe a few people privy to the
type of materials the artist used in his new work,'' she said.
After much searching, Mancusi-Ungaro tracked down Rothko's former
assistant Ray Kelly in New York. Kelly agreed to come to Houston to
demonstrate Rothko's painting process.
</P>
<P>
   To make his black form paintings, Rothko daily mixed a new batch
of whole egg, dry pigment, oil paint and dammar resins, which he
then applied in thin coats over rectangular forms sketched in
charcoal. In the Menil's conservation lab, Kelly created small
simulations of the black form paintings, which Mancusi-Ungaro then
subject to harsh conditions in order to prematurely age them. And
once again, the whiting occurred. At first, Mancusi-Ungaro thought
the film was caused by dammar resins. But when she sent a sample to
chemists at Shell Oil labs, they discovered that fatty acids from
the egg yolk had migrated to the surface of the painting, thanks to
Houston's stifling humidity. A solvent to treat the paintings was
developed, and in 1987 the paintings were restored.
</P>
<P>
   But by the mid-1990s, the whiting reappeared. (The solution has
since been reapplied.)
</P>
<P>
   Before her death in December 1997, Dominique de Menil had hired
Houston architect James McReynolds, along with the London
engineering firm Ove Arup &AMP; Associates, to resolve the building's
problems. In January 1999, the chapel closed for restoration. To
shore up the foundation, new concrete foundation piers were sunk to
55 feet _ twice the height of the building. A new climate-control
system was installed, and glass doors were fitted inside the
vestibule to stymie the flow of air from outside. Contractors put a
large door in one wall so the paintings can be easily removed. And
the interior walls were troweled with gray gypsum, which simulates
the raw concrete Rothko intended for the space. Perhaps most
importantly, a new skylight fitted with a smaller baffle diffuses
the sunlight in a softer, more even cast.
</P>
<P>
   Now literally seen in a new light with their surfaces restored,
Rothko's monumental paintings seem not to be the somber,
dispiriting images many understood them to be. Says Mancusi-Ungaro:
``These paintings are not depressing. They are not a prelude to
Rothko's suicide. Instead, they are the culmination of his career _
the ultimate distillation of his ideas. He was leading our
attention away from color and toward the surface of the
paintings.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the new materials and technique he used, Rothko
graduated beyond the brushy surfaces of his earlier work, creating
luminous flat surfaces that suggest infinite depth. And like never
before, that depth resonates with renewed spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
