<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4850 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TOYSMART-LIST-BOS &LR;      08-17 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-LIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RULING IN TOYSMART CUSTOMER LIST CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A bankruptcy judge declined Thursday to make a final
decision on the proposed sale of Toysmart.com's controversial
customer database.
</P>
<P>
   A Federal Trade Commission settlement would have allowed the
failed Waltham, Mass. Internet retailer to auction off the
information under certain restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Carol Kenner said there was no need to set guidelines
for a sale until Toysmart.com finds a buyer. Come back, she told a
group of attorneys, when there's an offer on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that deciding this in a vacuum _ without a
live, prospective buyer _ is unneccessary,'' Kenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com and the FTC had hoped to clear one roadblock to the
sale of the database. But now, ``we're back to where we started,''
said attorney Harry Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously disappointed that the court denied the
debtor's motion to accept the settlement,'' said Dana Rosenfeld,
assistant director of the FTC's Bureau of Consumer Protection.
``However we believe we will have the opportunity to bring before
the court the need for privacy protections for the consumer list
if, in fact, the creditors are able to find a buyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys general from 45 states who oppose the settlement
claimed a temporary victory. They said Kenner's ruling prevents
Toysmart.com from selling the database without another court
battle. Litigation and unfavorable publicity also have chilled the
market for the database.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now, the attorneys general have achieved their goal by
preserving the privacy rights of Toysmart's customers,'' said Tom
Reilly, attorney general for Massachusetts, which led the
objections of 43 states and the District of Columbia. New York and
Texas filed separately.
</P>
<P>
   On its Web site, Toysmart.com had gathered names, addresses, and
e-mail addresses from customers, as well as information about their
children and shopping preferences. As a reassurance, it promised
never to share that information.
</P>
<P>
   But the cash-burning Internet business collapsed in May after
majority owner Walt Disney Co. yanked its support. And soon,
Toysmart.com's database of about 250,000 customers went on the
auction block.
</P>
<P>
   After learning about the planned sale, the FTC sued
Toysmart.com. The two sides agreed to a settlement last month that
would allow Toysmart.com, which filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection in Boston, to sell the data under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys general and privacy advocates have rejected the
settlement, saying Toysmart.com customers should be notified and
given the opportunity to have their information destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Before Toysmart.com gained international notoriety, about five
companies, including Web stores, had stepped forward, said
Christopher Panos, an attorney for Toysmart.com's creditors. At
least one offered to pay more than $50,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there was interest before this hullabaloo,'' Panos
said. ``But they were frightened off.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand is now lackluster. A Disney subsidiary has said it would
pay $50,000 for the list and then have it destroyed, if no suitable
buyer emerges. But that offer received a cool reception.
</P>
<P>
   State authorities and consumer privacy advocates said a sale to
Disney still violates the Internet retailer's privacy policy. And
the bid was too low to please Toysmart.com and its creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Disney officials, who were apparently miffed that their offer
was cast aside, have not expressed interest in increasing their
offer, according to sources close to the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com isn't the only Internet retailer involved in the
online privacy debate. Following its collapse earlier this year,
British fashion e-tailer Boo.com sold information about 350,000
customers to Fashionmall.com. Lucy.com, Fusion.com, and Toys ``R''
Us have been accused of allowing market researchers access to
consumer data obtained from their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com's case has cast a dark cloud over the Internet
marketplace. Industry observers say investors and suppliers may
become increasingly reluctant to support Web-based businesses if
they believe they cannot recoup some of their losses in bankruptcy
court.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet shoppers say they have become choosier about where
to spend their dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
