<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ISRAEL-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL PRAISES CHINA'S EVEN STANCE ON MIDEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Shimon Peres lavishly praised China Thursday as he
finished a two-day visit intended to bolster Israel's ties with
this one-time foe and shore up global support for continued peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel China is a very friendly country with a very profound
understanding of events in the Middle East,'' Peres, a former prime
minister who is now Israel's minister for regional cooperation,
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great respect for President Jiang Zemin's call for
patience,'' he added, referring to remarks by the Chinese leader on
Monday, after a meeting with Yasser Arafat, and repeated to Peres
by officials during his visit.
</P>
<P>
   China's call for the Israelis and Palestinians to persist in a
search for peace despite the collapse of the Camp David talks last
month, diplomats here said, was intended to dissuade Arafat from
declaring a Palestinian state on Sept. 13, as he has said he would
do. Such an act would be likely to provoke a strong reaction from
Israel, hurting the chances for peace.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday in Jakarta, Indonesia, Arafat said he was
reconsidering the timing of declaring statehood after China and
then Indonesia joined a long list of nations urging him to back
off.
</P>
<P>
   Peres on Thursday praised Arafat for his apparent caution,
calling it ``a wise step.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel has been delighted with China's moderate diplomatic
stance, which in Israeli eyes validates the courting of a country
that until the late 1980s had championed Arab radicals.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Israeli officials said Peres' visit, part of a
quick Asian tour that also included Tokyo and Jakarta, was simply
intended to inform leaders about the status of Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   But for Israel, the visit also offered a vital chance to shore
up the budding friendship with China. Relations were jolted last
month when Israel reneged on a $250-million contract to sell
China's military an advanced airborne radar system after protests
by the Clinton administration and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   By all appearances, China has moved past the humiliation and
continues to seek friendly ties. Officials welcomed Peres' offer on
Wednesday to promote new Israeli investment and agricultural aid in
China's underdeveloped hinterlands.
</P>
<P>
   And most important, to the quiet satisfaction of Peres and his
colleagues, China took a temperate line on the peace talks in
successive meetings this week with Arafat and Peres, even as it
reaffirmed support for eventual Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Especially since 1992, when China gave Israel formal diplomatic
recognition, Israel has cultivated ties with China, secretly
selling weapons and offering agricultural and other technical aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis see enormous significance in their relations with
China,'' said Michael Yahuda, professor of international relations
at the London School of Economics.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he said, Israel sees friendly ties with this
largest developing country, with its permanent seat on the U.N.
Security Council, as blunting the often hostile stance of much of
the Third World.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the past, too, China has been known for selling arms to
archenemies of Israel's, like Iraq and Iran. China has halted most
such sales, but according to U.S. intelligence agencies, it has
continued to provide some missile technology to Iran and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Peres said he had raised the missile issue with China's foreign
minister and had been assured that China would abide by
international agreements to prevent transfers of long-range missile
technology and nuclear arms. China has provided similar ambiguous
assurances in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at his news conference Thursday, Peres went out of his
way to praise his hosts. ``Israel has much admiration for China,''
he said, calling theirs ``a very special relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
