<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4870 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-1STL     08-17 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE CAMPAIGN OF DUELING CLICHES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: This is a SUB for version that moved earlier)  
 &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The drive to the middle of the road by the
Democrats and Republicans has produced such a traffic jam in the
center lane that the parties are robbing each other's banalities
and cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Is it asking too much to expect our partisan leaders to elevate
the basic language of politics _ to come up with fresh ways of
saying the same old thing? Both Vice President Al Gore and Texas
Gov. George W. Bush insist their campaigns are about the future,
but their talk is straight out of the past. Even the jokes are
stale.
</P>
<P>
   Politics was more fun when the candidates went directly at it,
verbal swords drawn, from the left and the right. This centrist
stuff forces them onto the same yellow line, with variations of
style and emphasis but very little room for inventive spark.
</P>
<P>
   In politics, imitation is not the sincerest form of flattery.
Listen to them:
</P>
<P>
   Bush says ``I'm a different kind of Republican.'' Swell.
Different than whom? His father and President Ronald Reagan? Heaven
forbid. ``I don't think I'm reaching that far back in history,''
Bush says. Eight years is ``far back''? Then ``different'' in what
way? His policies sound like familiar GOP thinking, merely
expressed in a more polite manner than in the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   He's distancing himself from former House Speaker Newt Gingrich
and the harshly partisan Republican Congress that twice closed down
the federal government, tried to impeach President Clinton and
earned a reputation for not doing much. But he can't bring himself
to say so and undercut GOP congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also likes to describe himself as ``different.'' In his
case, we know what he's talking about. It's the Clinton, stupid.
But he can't come right out and say what he means, either, or he
will look disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are substantive differences between the two
candidates. On national policy, Gore and Bush disagree on important
topics like taxes, education, Social Security, health care and
military preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans are papering over these disagreements to
make themselves look more like Democrats. And the Democrats are
overdoing the moderate aspects of their programs to make themselves
look conservative, if not exactly Republican. The homogenized
result is like a blended fruit smoothie _ you can't tell the
bananas from the cherries. This concoction may go down easy, but
you don't know exactly what you are swallowing.
</P>
<P>
   That is why we get the kind of silliness we saw shortly before
the party conventions opened. In a rash moment, Gore promised that
if he were elected his administration would represent ``a fresh
start,'' a modest attempt to avoid another repetition of the
customary claim to be making a brave ''new beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush professed to be astonished that Gore would use a phrase
that the Republicans had already been using. ``Unbelievable, isn't
it?'' Bush crowed, holding up a GOP campaign policy statement that
included the words ''a fresh start.'' How sad that this is what
passes for significant political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush team practices its own word theft. The GOP platform
pledges to ``leave no child behind'' in access to education and
economic security. First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton noted
pointedly that for decades the trademark of the Children's' Defense
Fund _ a Democratic-leaning organization promoting opportunities
for disadvantaged children _ was ``leave no child behind.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, President Clinton, the master wordsmith, didn't
get the prize for originality in his valedictory address at the
Democratic National Convention's opening night. Touting his
administration's record, Clinton added: ``As that LA detective Joe
Friday used to say, `Just the facts, ma'am.''' The remark drew
laughter from the crowd _ just as it had in 1988, when then-Vice
President George Bush, George W.'s father, used the same line in
his speech accepting that year's GOP presidential nomination. It
clearly doesn't take much to amuse political convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The basic campaign argument is about ``change.'' Both sides
claim that mantle but don't define it the same way. Voters like the
idea of forward motion and progress but they fear any radical
philosophical shift that might disrupt rather than improve the
status quo. So talking about it is tricky, or as Gore might say,
``risky.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was mocked by Bush for overusing that word
and no ``risks'' were uttered in the series of surrogate speeches
at the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman, Gore's running mate, didn't
go near ``risky,'' preferring to fall back on all-purpose
``differences.'' As he gracefully put it, the two parties see
issues ``through a different set of eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of the best pitches for a transition from one
Democratic president to another was made by Bush's father as he
sought to replace Ronald Reagan in 1988. ``When you have to change
horses in mid-stream, doesn't it make sense to switch to one who's
going the same way?''
</P>
<P>
   Amazing that the Democrats haven't yet stolen that line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
