<HEADER>
A4871 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKSSPRINGSKANSAS-KA     08-17 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SWAGGER AND SWAY OF A GOOD PREQUEL:STEPHEN HUNTER'S FOURTH
NOVEL COVERS HARD-BOILED TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
 SPRINGS KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BILL NORTON  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hot Springs, by Stephen Hunter (475 pages; Simon &AMP; Schuster;
$25)
</P>
<P>
   After the Japanese surrender in World War II, Earl Swagger
returned to Arkansas, a Medal of Honor around his neck and
survivor's guilt squeezing his heart.
</P>
<P>
   All he wants, he thinks, is to curl up beside his pregnant wife,
blank out the past and make the transition to ``real life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Swagger's fame as a warrior appeals to Fred Becker, an
ambitious prosecutor in Hot Springs who wants to sweep out the
gangsters, the gamblers, the hookers, bootleggers and pushers who
thrive in a city where vice is protected. Once the vice is
squelched, Becker plans to ride the cleanup to a higher political
office.
</P>
<P>
   Swagger takes Becker's lure and joins an ex-FBI agent in
training a squad of aggressive young cops in the craft of staging
raiding parties and of handling a Thompson .45 submachine gun.
</P>
<P>
   The action that follows in Hot Springs is vintage Stephen
Hunter. Spare but precisely drawn. So vivid it plays large in the
theater of the mind. Of the four thrillers Hunter has written
involving members of the Swagger family, this one most resembles
the prose of the hard-boiled crime novelists of the 1930s and the
'40s, the era in which this book takes place.
</P>
<P>
   As Earl Swagger prowls the streets of lush Hot Springs, he is
drenched in memories of his father, a sheriff, a lawman in public
who in private battered and belittled his sons, causing one to
commit suicide. And once a month he drove into Hot Springs,
indulging in the pleasures of the brothels and casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled throughout this novel are real-life celebrities who've
come to play in Hot Springs: Mickey Rooney, Alan Ladd, Bugsy Siegel
(whose Las Vegas would one day supplant Hot Springs) and Siegel's
plaything, Virginia Hill. Hunter even pulls Siegel and Swagger
together in several scenes that add to the rapidly building tension
pacing the novel.
</P>
<P>
   For readers unfamiliar with Hunter, who was born in Kansas City,
they can find even more, and sometimes more tightly drawn, action
in earlier novels that feature Earl's son, Bob Lee Swagger: Point
of Impact, Black Light, Dirty White Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Much like ``The Phantom Menace,'' the ``Star Wars'' film that
came out last year, Hot Springs is a prequel; that is, this story
takes place before the first three novels. Even in this fourth
Swagger episode, Hunter has lost none of his touch.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Springs is an action novel that is almost as hot as the
142-degree water percolating from the Hot Springs mountain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1837EDT &QL; 
