<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4872 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKSHEMINGWAYBIOGRAP     08-17 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL REYNOLDS' WORK SPEAKS VOLUMES:LATE BIOGRAPHER WAS UP TO THE
TASK OF CAPTURING HEMINGWAY'S TEMPESTUOUS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
 HEMINGWAYBIOGRAPHER KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 STEVE PAUL  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   Editor's note: Ernest Hemingway
biographer Michael Reynolds died last weekend at 63. In July 1999,
Reynolds spoke at Unity Temple on the Plaza to celebrate the
centennial of Hemingway's birth and the release of Reynolds' fifth
and final volume of his biography. The event was co-sponsored by
The Kansas City Star. Senior writer and editor Steve Paul
introduced Reynolds at that event; the following is adapted from
that introduction.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If modern biography began with a book, Boswell's Johnson,
contemporary biography in England and America began with a bang _
the guns of the First World War blowing to pieces so many of the
men and the states and the attitudes and the values of the
Victorian world.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the words of Paul Murray Kendall, a professor who
wrote a wise little book called The Art of Biography. Kendall was
referring to Lytton Strachey, the British biographer who, to
Kendall, represented the ``triumph of the artist over the
accumulator.''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if it isn't more than coincidence that Michael
Reynolds' all-consuming biographical subject also was shaped as an
artist and a human being in that big bang of the First World War.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Hemingway towered over 20th-century American life and
literature. To re-create his life in a biography must be one of the
most daunting tasks a scholar could choose to bring upon himself.
</P>
<P>
   And to write a major biography of Ernest Hemingway in the shadow
of Carlos Baker's major biography of Ernest Hemingway would make
the challenge even greater.
</P>
<P>
   When I heard Reynolds speak at a Hemingway conference in early
1999 at the John F. Kennedy Library in Boston, I was struck by his
admission that now that he had come to the end of Hemingway's life
in a span of five books, he was tempted to go back to the beginning
_ if not to start over then to do some rewriting, because he knows
so much more now than he did back then.
</P>
<P>
   A journalist who dips in and out of subjects as whim or need
arises might find it humbling to consider what Reynolds has done.
He virtually lived with Ernest Hemingway for more than a quarter
century. And as we know _ as each of Hemingway's four wives came to
know _ that is a difficult thing to do. Dawn Powell once jotted in
her diary this impression of a brief visit with Hemingway: `` ...
exhausted by his immense gusto _ someone who gives out more in six
hours than most people do in a lifetime _ leaves you groggy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is one of Reynolds' achievements that he could capture the
energy of Hemingway's life and leave you not groggy but
exhilarated. Reynolds does not lecture or overanalyze. He lets the
life unfold dramatically. He provides context for understanding the
dynamics of Hemingway's life, but he doesn't speculate on motives.
It's perhaps a bit dangerous to say that he stays close to the
bull, but in fact if the bull is Hemingway and all his
complications, then that's exactly what Reynolds does.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' biography divides Hemingway's life into phases. Each
volume stands alone and tells its own story: The Young Hemingway,
The Paris Years, The Homecoming, The 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   The last book, The Final Years, covers the period of 1940 to
Hemingway's suicide in 1961. Reynolds details the years of World
War II, when Hemingway chased German U-boats in the waters off Cuba
and then chased some kind of glory on the beach and in the
countryside of France after D-Day. Hemingway thought at the time
that he would die, that his luck had run out. Yet the death spiral
lasted another 15 years, a period when Hemingway's stature as well
as his troubles grew. Most of Hemingway's best-known work was
behind him, yet Reynolds makes the case that these last 15 years
were as creative as any period in Hemingway's writing life.
</P>
<P>
   I was told a story by one of Reynolds' former grad students that
may be indicative of the good fortune he has had with his biography
of Hemingway. It has to do with the time Reynolds visited the
Library of Congress in search of photographs of Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   He spent most of the day coming up empty. Near the end of the
day, a librarian happened to drop by to offer help and when told
what he was looking for, she said he was in the wrong place. She
led him to a basement room where he found a great picture of
Hemingway in Oak Park, Ill., after his return from the war. He
turned to thank the woman, but she was gone. On his way out of the
library, when he stopped to ask about her, no one could identify
the woman. For Reynolds, she was the angel librarian. All great
biographers must hope to have one. For as one old master, Thomas
Carlyle, put it, ``A well-written life is almost as rare as a
well-spent one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1839EDT &QL; 
