<HEADER>
A4873 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKSNOTEWORTHYKANSAS     08-17 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- BOOKS NOTEWORTHY KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
Recent and noteworthy book releases FICTION
<TEXT>
<P>
   - Out of Nowhere, by Keith Botsford (296 pages; Toby Press;
$15.95). Botsford lives in Boston and shares editing duties of The
Republic of Letters with a fellow named Saul Bellow. In this
collection Botsford shares four strangely satisfying long stories
with readers who won't regret getting to know his seemingly easy,
graceful ways with words and characterization.
</P>
<P>
   - Iron Shoes, by Molly Giles (240 pages; Simon &AMP; Schuster; $22).
Molly Giles is a proven talent of the short story; her collection
Rough Translations was nominated for a Pulitzer Prize. Now she
tries her hand at the novel form with a story about a woman who
hits age 40 at the same time she crashes into disillusionment,
guilt, marital problems and more. Sounds like fun, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   - For the Love of Money, by Omar Tyree (413 pages; Simon &AMP;
Schuster; $24). Remember Tracy Ellison, better known as Flyy Girl?
Author Omar Tyree returns to the teen heroine, who of course is no
longer a teen, and follows her adventures and misadventures in a
fast-paced novel that is absolutely packed with dialogue.
NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   - Nymphomania: A History, by Carol Groneman (238 pages; W.W.
Norton; $24.95). Provocative title for a provocative subject.
Nymphomania has been classified at various times as a disease, a
psychological disorder, a sexual addiction or simply a construct of
patriarchal society bent on keeping the female libido in check.
Groneman looks at how women's sexuality has been defined, co-opted
or distorted, by men but also by women themselves.
</P>
<P>
   - Flophouse: Life on the Bowery, by David Isay and Stacy
Abramson with photographs by Harvey Wang (157 pages; Random House;
$24.95). This is the America that most Americans have forgotten _
or would like to forget. The authors and photographer make it
difficult to ignore the poverty and despair of New York City's the
Bowery. Changes in building codes mean that flophouses soon will be
a thing of the past _ but the poor will always be with us.
</P>
<P>
   - Along Route 66, by Quinta Scott (308 pages; University of
Oklahoma Press; $34.95). I did not travel Route 66 as a child, but
I am barely old enough to remember long trips between St. Louis and
Kansas City along the old U.S. 40, before Interstate 70 was
completed. It was a different world, one that existed before the
dominance of the gasoline and fast-food and motel franchises. The
tiny roadside inns, eateries, taverns and root-beer stands in this
book will be achingly familiar to anyone who ever traveled a
two-laner in those old roads' heyday. And of course Route 66 was to
many folks the greatest road of all, stretching from Chicago, down
through Illinois to St. Louis, on through Missouri to Joplin, into
a tiny corner of Kansas, and onward through Oklahoma, Texas, New
Mexico and Arizona, all the way out to Santa Monica, Calif. This is
no book, but rather a time machine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
