r e BC-FILMTARSEMKANSAS-KAN &LR;      08-17 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CELL' DIRECTOR MAKES DEBUT ON THE DARK SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
 TARSEM KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   When it comes to making music videos
like REM's ``Losing My Religion'' or award-winning TV commercials,
Tarsem is an acknowledged master.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feature films, though, are something else entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty steep learning curve,'' the India-born Tarsem
(his full name is Tarsem Singh) said in a recent telephone
conversation about his big-screen debut, the psychological thriller
``The Cell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Music videos and commercials are about cramming in as much
visual information as you can in a limited amount of time. But
there's no such thing as a perpetual climax. You try to do that for
an hour and a half, and the audience is throwing up after 20
minutes. You need to let a feature film develop on its own terms,
at its own speed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cell'' provided Tarsem with a directing crash course. The
tale of a psychologist (Jennifer Lopez) who is able to meld her
mind with that of a comatose serial killer offered plenty of
opportunities for Tarsem to fashion a surreal dreamscape. But the
rest of the film takes place in the real world, and he found
himself deliberately slowing the pace of those scenes.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he had to learn to handle actors. Not models or
musicians who serve as chess pieces that can be moved around at
will, but actors whose job is to develop believable characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, actors want their moment,'' Tarsem said. ``I got
complaints from the actors if I didn't give them room to perform.
They don't want to be puppets. They want to be people.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I wasn't prepared for that. The one thing I'll fight for
in the future is rehearsal time. That's what I really missed.
Basically we had to rehearse on the set. I finally got what I
wanted, but it was hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarsem said he views ``The Cell'' _ especially its eye-popping
fantasy sequences _ as a sort of grand opera. ``I adored Francis
Coppola's `Dracula' and made it my model. And of course there's no
such thing as a subtle opera.''
</P>
<P>
   But to make viewers accept the outrageous inner world of a
serial killer, in which the madman envisions himself as a sort of
dark emperor, Tarsem said he had to make the real-world scenes
gritty and believable. And he had to make Vincent D'Onofrio's
murderer about as ghastly a specimen as moviegoers had seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to make him terrible. Some of the things we did didn't
even get in the American cut. But I knew if I was going in for the
operatic look in the fantasy sequences, I had to make Vincent so
bad up front that when he shows up later in wild, exotic costumes,
people wouldn't laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his first taste of working with a big studio, Tarsem said
that overall it was ``brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not show business, it's business show,'' he said. ``If
you want to make an art-house film, do it with Dad's money. Or make
it low budget, not with $40 million. I pretty much knew what the
studio wanted and worked within their boundaries. They said, `Make
me a dark film.' I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my next film will probably be very small, very intimate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1842EDT &QL; 
