<TEXT>
<P>
   The following is a menu for New America News Service stories
that are for release Thu., Aug. 17, 2000, or anytime thereafter:
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN BRINGS SABBATH INTO FOCUS. Al Gore's selection of
Connecticut Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, as his
running mate has many non-Jewish Americans seriously learning about
Judaism for the first time. ``This is a healthy development for the
nation,'' writes columnist Bill Maxwell. In this commentary,
Maxwell contributes to the dialogue by explaining the importance of
the Sabbath, or ``Shabbat'' _ the day that observing Jews rest _
and the humorous way in which he learned about it. (slugged:
BC-LIEBERMAN-RELIGIOUS-BELIEFS-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS, FAMILY VALUES AND AN AMERICAN DREAM FOR GAYS.
Elizabeth Birch, executive director of the Human Rights Campaign,
the nation's largest gay-rights advocacy organization, made history
this week as the first leader of a gay group to address a national
political convention. In her speech, Birch appealed to the heart of
the nation. Poised and articulate, she spoke of real family values,
of ``healing the fractures _ soothing the wounds _ to making our
American family truly whole.'' ``Birch's speech was all about
breaking down the barriers of discrimination, dismantling the walls
of intolerance and opening closet doors,'' columnist Chuck Colbert
writes. (slugged: BC-GAYS-AND-DEM-CONVENTION-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING KOREAN CULTURE THROUGH FOOD. When Joe Norton and his
wife adopted two Korean children, they vowed to learn everything
they could about Korea. ``One topic that seemed to transcend
everything we were learning about was food,'' Norton writes. ``I
realized that in Korean tradition, food means much more than just
fulfilling your stomach's cravings.'' The Norton family took Korean
cooking lessons and visited local Korean restaurants and now
incorporate this health way of eating into their family diet.
Excerpted from KoreAm magazine. (slugged:
BC-LEARNING-KOREAN-CULTURE-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   REINVENTING THE WHEEL. NetFuerza, which specializes in selling
advertising on Hispanic Web sites, is seeing dramatic growth.
Online spending in Latin America topped $194 million last year,
with Brazil accounting for $121 million. Projections show that that
the figure may grow to about $8.3 billion by 2005. ``Ad networks
have a strong role to play here,'' analyst Jim Nail says. ``There
are hundreds of thousands of sites. An advertiser can't deal with
it. They need an intermediary to help make those buys easier.'' By
Jonathan J. Higuera. Excerpted from Hispanic Business magazine.
(slugged: BC-HISPANIC-ONLINE-ADVERTISING-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF)
</P>
