<HEADER>
A4894 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-HISPANIC-ONLINE-ADVER     08-17 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-ONLINE-ADVERTISING-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REINVENTING THE WHEEL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JONATHAN J. HIGUERA  
 &HT;    By Internet standards, Adsmart NetFuerza can be considered an
old-timer. In just a year and a half, the company has seen dramatic
change online and in terms of its own fortunes.
 &HT;    ``When we started, there were very few Latin sites,'' says Lisa
Weinstein, division director of NetFuerza, which specializes in
selling advertising on Hispanic Web sites domestically and abroad.
``We went into the game without much traffic to sell.''
 &HT;    In those early days, the network relied on portals like
ZonaFmanciera, El Nuevo Herald and Latino Link. NetFuerza initially
had just 10 million impressions a month from Latin America.
(Impressions are similar to pages in a newspaper.) Now the company
boasts 50 million impressions a month and is growing at a rate of
30 percent every 30 days.
 &HT;    ``There are many more interesting sites out there,'' Weinstein
says. ``In the last two months, we gained 10 sites. Six months ago
it was hard to target urban teens. Now we're seeing a number of
sites with that audience.''
 &HT;    Founded in September 1998 as a division of 2Can Media, NetFuerza
currently represents 67 clients with Web sites in 16 countries.
While more than half of its clients are U.S.-based, sites based in
Latin America are popping up every day. Televisa recently announced
it will launch a Spanish-language portal later this year. Jupiter
Communications, an Internet research firm, estimates that online
spending in Latin America topped $194 million last year, with
Brazil accounting for $121 million. Jupiter projects the figure
will grow to $8.3 billion by 2005.
 &HT;    ``Mexico and Argentina are advanced, but Brazil has even more
activity,'' notes Anjanette Lopez, a NetFueriza account executive
in charge of new business development. ``Brazil is a continent of
its own.''
 &HT;    Latin American Internet growth has prompted advertisers to take
notice. While online advertising in Latin America was relatively
soft last year, with about $51 million spent, according to
Forrester Research, another Internet research firm, it's expected
to grow to $1.6 billion by 2004. Worldwide, online ad spending will
grow to $22 billion by 2004, up from $2.8 billion last year.
 &HT;    ``Ad networks have a strong role to play here,'' says Forrester
analyst Jim Nail. ``The Internet is a very fragmented media space.
There are hundreds of thousands of sites. An advertiser can't deal
with it. They need an intermediary to help make those buys
easier.''
 &HT;    Other networks besides NetFuerza are stepping up to meet that
need. DoubleClick recently started a Latin America division, as did
247. But NetFuerza believes it has a head start.
 &HT;    ``We started with very small sites with hardly my impressions,''
Lopez says. ``Many of the people running the sites didn't know what
they were doing.''
 &HT;    While some still don't, the industry is getting more competitive
and savvy, she says. ``Some people know what the Internet user
looks for. They put out a great product and people go to it.''
 &HT;    Sports and finance sites have been popular with NetFuerza
clients, according to Weinstein. But other sites are beginning to
make headway, such as the recently created Todo Bebe.com, which
focuses on family planning and child-rearing. Although NetFuerza
has been bought twice _ last year by Adsmart and earlier this year
by Engage.com _ its client list has steadily grown. Web sites
ranging from Zona Financiera to TodoBebe.com to ElClick.com are all
NetFuerza clients.
 &HT;    ``It allows us to offer more options,'' Lopez says, who has been
with NetFuerza since April 1999. ``We're not eliminating any
products, just combining forces under one umbrella.''
 &HT;    To keep pace with the growth, NetFuerza has added five sales
representatives in U.S. cities and is looking to add more in Latin
America.
 &HT;    ``Finding representatives is difficult,'' Weinstein says. ``We
need bilingual folks who understand the Net.''
 &HT;    While Web site clients pay nothing, the advertisers pay
NetFuerza to handle their Internet campaigns.
 &HT;    ``We do auditing of impressions, provide reports and billing of
claims, turn it around, and send a check for the commission agreed
upon,'' Lopez says. ``It's a turnkey operation.''
 &HT;    Internet advertising costs depend on the type of campaign
launched. The more specific the intended audience, the higher the
price.
 &HT;    ``The Internet is not guaranteed. It moves very fast,'' Lopez.
``You need to be willing to take risks and see what happens.''
-----
 &HT;    (Jonathan J. Higuera is a free-lance writer.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Hispanic Business magazine 
