A4897 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-LEARNING-KOREAN-CULTU     08-17 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARNING-KOREAN-CULTURE-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING KOREAN CULTURE THROUGH FOOD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JOE NORTON  
 &HT;    I am the father of two Korean born children: Davis, 3, and
Cassandra, 1. My wife and I adopted these two beautiful children
from Korea when they were each 6 months old.
 &HT;    From the very beginning we hoped to learn everything we could
about Korea. Our goal was to become informed about Korea and its
culture so that we would be able to share this important piece of
our children's lives with them. Our investigation into the culture
also provided us with something to keep us busy as we anxiously
awaited news of our children.
 &HT;    We started our in a very fundamental way. Our first step was to
take our globe and see exactly where Korea is located. The next
steps included obtaining books from local booksellers on Korean
topics. We found travel guides helpful, even though we were not
planning to travel to Korea any time soon. (Our children were both
escorted to the United States and we met them for the first time at
the airport in Boston.) Travel books proved valuable as we learned
specific facts about the country. Aside from the important
geographical information, we also learned about key historical
figures and came to understand Korea's main imports and exports.
 &HT;    What intrigued me the most, as an American, reading about this
culture for the first time was how it seemed to me that everything
that the Korean person did was tied to some tradition. A person's
political opinions, religion, clothing, right on down to the food
he enjoys had a deeper meaning than at first view. Throughout our
reading, one topic that seemed to transcend everything we were
learning about was food. I realized that in Korean tradition, food
means much more than just fulfilling your stomach's cravings.
 &HT;    Each Korean American family and individual that I spoke with
keeps some type of Korean tradition in what they eat. I did not run
into many people preparing jars of cabbage to plant in the ground,
but most people are keeping traditions alive through the simple
basics of beef and chicken bulgogi, rice, bibimbap, soups and other
native foods. In Boston and surrounding towns, there are a number
of Asian markets and a handful of Korean markets that sell
ingredients for the delicious food. Also, Korean restaurants have
sprung up in downtown, in Chinatown and in communities such as
Newton and Burlington.
 &HT;    During our investigation into Korea, my wife and I visited
several of the area restaurants and were hooked on the food
instantly. In my own family, several of the foods mentioned above
are regulars and many extended family and friends look forward to
their visits with the anticipation of a feast for the senses _ the
taste, the aroma, the look _ and, to say the least, some mildly
spicy cuisine! The staples in the Korean person's diet have become
ours. We went from preparing boxed instant rice to purchasing a
rice cooker and buying our rice at an Asian market.
 &HT;    To take our interest in the food a step further, my wife pursued
an additional route. She was able to identify someone who could
teach Americans Korean cooking. Through a local church, she set up
several sessions of weekly cooking instruction from a group of
women who were all too willing to teach others about the food. I
attended a series myself and was struck instantly by the simplicity
of the food itself, while at the same time enjoying the different
spicy flavors. Our instructors spoke with great pride as they told
us of the reasons behind certain dishes. They taught us how to
appreciate the preparation and presentation of the food. This
cooking class remains to this day one of the most requested events
that my wife coordinates.
 &HT;    The added benefit, as any nutritionist will tell you, is that
this food is good for you. The typical meal of a bowl of rice, soup
and side dishes of meat or fish accompanied by vegetables is
certainly a healthy combination, and one that meets the
requirements of recommended daily dietary allowances.
 &HT;    The preparation that one goes through is equally as important as
the food itself. Shopping for the right ingredients is where it
begins. Carefully selecting the vegetables and meats that your
family and friends will enjoy is almost ritualistic, as is the
process of cutting, marinating and cooking.
 &HT;    When attending the cooking class, it becomes clear that while
measuring devices may be useful, they are not necessarily
essential. The Korean cook knows instinctively the amounts and
combinations necessary to bring a meal to life.
 &HT;    My family now makes an effort to use our mealtime to socialize.
We take turns at the table and discuss what we are about to do for
the day or what we have done for the just-concluded day. It has
brought a nice level of communication within our house and has
helped us understand the daily challenges and victories, however
small or large, that each of us has faced. We place particular
importance on listening. Each voice is heard from oldest to
youngest, and we have a lot of fun sharing our experiences and
helping one another all over food.
 &HT;    If you want a starting point for learning Korean culture or a
way to add to what you already know, look into food. There is a
great deal of history behind the food and how it is shared among
family, friends and community.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Joe Norton is a free-lance writer.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 KOREAM magazine 
