<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4899 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CAIRO-RENEWAL-ART-NYT     08-17 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAIRO-RENEWAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENIZENS OF OLD CAIRO WONDER HOW RENOVATION PROJECT WILL AFFECT
THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Nearly everyone agrees on one thing: The old
woman who sells live ducks and chickens from a makeshift stall does
not belong on Tentmakers Street. The squawking, to say nothing of
the dirty feathers that fly regularly from the alarmed birds,
upsets the tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Unsightly poultry is not the only problem when renovating a
1,000-year-old neighborhood packed with crumbling mosques, ancient
bazaars, illegal workshops, crowded apartments and world-famous
monuments in one of the most densely populated cities in the world.
</P>
<P>
   What is to be done, for example, with the poor family that for
generations has sold falafel from a stand they constructed smack
against a once-beautiful and historic city gate? Or the people who
long ago poured concrete over an ancient well to make a space to
sell souvenirs? Or the little boys dragging wagons full of fabric
for a dollar a day and madly dodging motorbikes carrying families
of four out for a shopping spree?
</P>
<P>
   These are burning questions for the people of Tentmakers Street,
a cramped and dim thoroughfare in the old heart of this old city
where a government preservation project is tearing up the
foundations of the buildings and, for many, a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, back in the old days it was beautiful here,'' said Saad
Ali, a 65-year-old tentmaker who was born a few streets away and
started working in the craft with his father and grandfather when
he was 10 years old. ``You could see the original stones and their
colors and the wooden doors. Now that whole image is destroyed. The
beauty is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali sat cross-legged and barefoot on a worn cushion in a tiny
alcove that has been his family's place of business for as long as
anyone can remember. His eyeglasses are as thick as his calloused
fingers, the cost of countless hours spent bent over his
needlework.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, a donkey cart piled high with cartons bumped its
way along the street just past his shoulder. The screeches of the
neighbor woman's chickens joined the honking of speeding
motorcycles and the whine of the machinery in the metalworking shop
a few doors down to produce an ear-splitting noise.
</P>
<P>
   Ali grimaced. ``In the old days, this street was peaceful and
you had the chance to buy and sell,'' he said. ``Now the tourists
have to dig their way in past all these inappropriate businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   For hundreds of years the people on Tentmakers Street made their
living sewing ornate patchwork tapestries _ red, yellow, black and
blue arabesque designs _ for the tents where Egyptians gather for
funerals, weddings and other ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The little street, like traditional Middle East bazaars, was
covered with a wooden canopy to protect the artisans from sun and
rain. Each alcove had a high ceiling with wood beams and an airy
workshop on the second floor. The archways over the entrances were
made of multicolored stones laid in a fan design.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors knew one another for generations, just as in the
stories of Naguib Mahfouz, the Nobel laureate who grew up in the
neighborhood and used it as the model for his trilogy ``Children of
the Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, years of grime give the stone the uniform color of
mud. The beamed ceilings have been obliterated with concrete, and
the workshops are rented out to families living 10 to a room.
</P>
<P>
   Most people now buy machine-printed fabrics instead of the
handmade tapestries, so the tentmakers sell their work as
pillowcases and wall hangings for tourists. And with the decline of
the old trade, small manufacturing operations and street vendors
encroached on the remaining artisans of Tentmakers Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian government, along with foreign donors, aims to
bring back the look of old Cairo to the crowded and frantically
busy neighborhood around Tentmakers Street, known as Islamic, or
Fatimid, Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   It has an ambitious renovation plan to sandblast away centuries
of dirt from the facades, modernize the leaky sewage system,
reinforce and repair the lofty minarets and mosques, clear the
entrances to the monuments, and group the artisans together by
craft as they were in the 18th- and 19th-century glory days of
Cairo's bazaar life.
</P>
<P>
   Originally the walled imperial capital of the Fatimid dynasty
that ruled Egypt in the early centuries of Islam, the 1
1/2-square-mile neighborhood contains many of the city's most
famous mosques, schools and markets. But most are dilapidated
hulks, threatened by rising underground water and littered with
garbage. And within the confines of Fatimid Cairo, still outlined
in a few places by the remnants of the ramparts and massive stone
gates, at least 365,000 people live, the Ministry of Culture
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration work on many monuments has begun. Parts of
Tentmakers Street have been gutted and some of the dirt cleaned
from the archways of the old shops. There are rumors _ welcomed by
many _ that the government will eventually ban cars and motorbikes
from the area. But many people who live and work in the
neighborhood wonder if they will be preserved along with the
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine, renovate the area,'' said Muhammad Tawfik, who sells
cheap shoes from a dingy stand in the shadow of Bab Zuweila, the
westernmost gate to the old Fatimid city. ``But what about the
people who make their living here?''
</P>
<P>
   Tawfik said he had been assured by government officials that his
store can remain, once the gate is refurbished and cleaned. But he
has his doubts. Just across from him, another shoe-seller was told
to clear out during renovations. Then workers uncovered a beautiful
ornate decoration on the gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll never be allowed back, now,'' Tawfik said.
</P>
<P>
   Ayman Abdel-Moneim, the Culture Ministry's archaeologist in
charge of the preservation project, said there are no plans to
relocate residents of the neighborhood, although he did want to
move incompatible businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program is to restore the monuments, the housing of the
people, the infrastructure and the ground itself,'' he said.
``People must believe us as the government. They are not going to
be moved out of historic Cairo.''
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime occupants said they want to believe the
restoration will improve their lot. But sometimes they, too, have
their doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come here and clean this up!'' shouted one tentmaker this
week, as workers renovating a building sent a cloud of plaster and
dust from their construction site onto the street in front of his
shop. When the workers studiously ignored his command, he pulled
out a broom from behind a sewing table and set about cleaning up
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ali would like to think that the neighborhood could once again
be a quiet, friendly place, as it is portrayed in the Naguib
Mahfouz books. Not that Ali has read them. ``I don't have to,'' he
said. ``I live them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he is reassured by the fact that the government is not
tearing down the old buildings in Tentmakers Street, but only
fixing them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they destroyed them, I'm sure it would only be a matter of
time before they'd move me out of here and tell me I had to go live
somewhere in a new part of Cairo,'' he said. ``If that happened,
they would be tearing me from my own heritage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
