<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-COX-CVN-MCNEELY-0818     08-17 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CVN-MCNEELY-0818 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATS STRESS GOP ABORTION STAND
 &HT;    By DAVE McNEELY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Peering out from a large ad in Monday's Washington
Post is Texan Liz Carpenter. In white print over the dark robe
Carpenter is wearing are the words, ``It's the Supreme Court,
Stupid!''
</P>
<P>
   That takeoff on James Carville's ``It's the economy, stupid!''
slogan during Bill Clinton's 1992 presidential campaign is an
underlying chant here at the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next president will likely nominate two or three Supreme
Court Justices,'' declared the ad, paid for by NARAL, the National
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League. ``Enough to
overturn Roe v. Wade and end legal abortion. George W. Bush says
his model justices are Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas. Are they
yours?''
</P>
<P>
   Scalia and Thomas have both voted to overturn the 1973 Roe v.
Wade decision that established a woman's right to choose whether to
have an abortion. Texas state law now tracks that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want equality,'' Carpenter said after a rousing speech to
the Texas delegation here. ``And we want the right to make our
choices about the privacy of our own bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, third-ranking Democrat in the U.S. House and
chair of the Texas delegation here, said the issue is very
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the issues where there's a clear distinction
between the two parties,'' Frost said. ``The Democratic party
clearly stands for a woman's right to choose on the issue of
abortion. The Republican party clearly does not _ in fact, has very
anti-choice language in their platform.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican platform states it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``The unborn child has a fundamental individual right to live
which cannot be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic platform says:
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that it is a fundamental constitutional liberty
that individual Americans, not government, can best take
responsibility for making the most difficult and intensely personal
decisions regarding reproduction.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure no one misses the difference, NARAL has been handing
out sacks of brochures to delegates here about the issue _
including one with an unflattering picture of Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, the Republican nominee for president.
</P>
<P>
   That brochure features a 1994 quote from Bush: ``I will do
everything in my power to restrict abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   As governor, the chief push Bush made on the abortion front was
requiring notification of a parent of a minor girl before an
abortion can be performed. That was passed by the Texas Legislature
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has disagreed with the Republican Party's stance _
like his father, he would allow abortions in cases of rape, incest,
or where the mother's life is in danger, rather than ban all
abortions _ the nominee said he thought the Republican platform
should not be altered.
</P>
<P>
   And during the primary season earlier this year, Bush said that
the Roe v. Wade decision ``was a reach (and) overstepped the
constitutional bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Aug. 17 acceptance speech at the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia, Bush said he would sign legislation
making late-term abortions illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will lead our nation toward a culture that values life, the
life of the elderly and the sick, the life of the young and the
life of the unborn,'' Bush said then.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, repeatedly voted during his
10-year congressional career for a constitutional amendment to
outlaw abortions.
</P>
<P>
   While the Democratic nominee, Vice President Al Gore, is now
completely pro-choice, Gore opposed federal spending for abortion
early in his career in Congress. He switched in the mid-1980s, when
he began gearing up to run for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's running mate, Joe Lieberman, has consistently been
pro-choice during his 12-year tenure as a U.S. senator from
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
