</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, third-ranking Democrat in the U.S. House and
chair of the Texas delegation here, said the issue is very
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the issues where there's a clear distinction
between the two parties,'' Frost said. ``The Democratic party
clearly stands for a woman's right to choose on the issue of
abortion. The Republican party clearly does not _ in fact, has very
anti-choice language in their platform.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican platform states it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``The unborn child has a fundamental individual right to live
which cannot be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic platform says:
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that it is a fundamental constitutional liberty
that individual Americans, not government, can best take
responsibility for making the most difficult and intensely personal
decisions regarding reproduction.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure no one misses the difference, NARAL has been handing
out sacks of brochures to delegates here about the issue _
including one with an unflattering picture of Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, the Republican nominee for president.
</P>
<P>
   That brochure features a 1994 quote from Bush: ``I will do
everything in my power to restrict abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   As governor, the chief push Bush made on the abortion front was
requiring notification of a parent of a minor girl before an
abortion can be performed. That was passed by the Texas Legislature
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has disagreed with the Republican Party's stance _
like his father, he would allow abortions in cases of rape, incest,
or where the mother's life is in danger, rather than ban all
abortions _ the nominee said he thought the Republican platform
should not be altered.
</P>
<P>
   And during the primary season earlier this year, Bush said that
the Roe v. Wade decision ``was a reach (and) t up in the euphoric
anticipation of a heralded class of freshman receivers. The
overwhelming potential of Roy Williams, B.J. Johnson, Sloan Thomas
and Tony Jeffery tends to overshadow the fact that Ellis arrived at
Texas with some pretty impressive credentials of his own.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he received honorable-mention All-USA recognition by
USA Today in 1998 by catching 59 passes for 963 yards and 12
touchdowns in his senior season at Westfield High School in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how he's viewed, Ellis is approaching his second year
at Texas with alacrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they've forgot me,'' said Ellis, who came out of
spring practice as the Longhorns' starting flanker. ``(Fans) know
we've lost a lot of key players and we need some help. The focus is
on those guys because they're young and new. I hope they work their
butts off and will be good. That's what I want. But I'm ready to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the combination of a redshirt year and the blue-chip
recruits' arrival might leave Ellis lost in a black hole of at
least some fans' consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a natural tendency because of the fact he
redshirted last year and these freshmen are new,'' Texas offensive
coordinator Greg Davis said. ``But he had a solid spring. He really
did some things that were exciting to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis demonstrated a high tolerance for pain by completing
spring training despite a stress fracture in his right shin. By
playing through the pain, he developed into a more reliable
receiver. Whereas he previously had a tendency to follow a
spectacular catch with a frustrating drop, he became consistently
sure-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not unusual,'' Davis said. ``So many things go through
your mind (as a freshman): Where am I in this formation? Do I go in
motion? What if we audible? The mind locks 'em down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the game slows down for them. As a freshman it moves so
fast. But (later) it's not moving as fast anymore. When that
happens their natural skills can be evaluated.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis' skills have been subject to evaluation by his harshest
critic long before he arrived at Texas. Early in his high school
career, the 6-foot, 4-inch Ellis was more interested in hoops, but
he changed directions after a blunt critique from someone with a
basketball background _ his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Patton was a basketball star at Houston Yates High School
and did not see the necessary skills for her son to flourish in the
gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked basketball more than football, but I told him, `I
think you're better in football,' '' Patton said. ``I told him
football can carry you a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis knows he's a long way from carrying the receiving load by
himself. Split end Montrell Flowers caught 34 passes last season,
while Brandon Healy and Jamel Thompson combined for 15 catches. The
four freshmen receivers also figure to get plenty of passes thrown
their way.
</P>
<P>
   But Ellis has an edge on the newcomers _ at least for now _
because he had a year as an understudy to Kwame Cavil and Ryan
Nunez, last year's top receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The freshmen) will learn how to go hard on every play,''
Ellis said. ``Then you go against the best DBs in the country _ I
think our defensive backs are the best in the nation _ in practice.
They will watch the experienced guys and learn a lot like I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it is I'll go in as a starter, but the other
guys can play my position. We'll all have a chance. We're pretty
much equal. It will be the guys who are consistent and run routes
so good that the DBs can't hold you that will play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis plans to be one of those guys. That will be the first step
toward making this a memorable season for him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
