<HEADLINE>
BONE CHIP DASHES MOCEANU'S PLAN TO RETURN TO OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hobbled by a tiny chip of bone jammed in her knee, what
her coach described as a ``wear-and-tear injury,'' Dominique
Moceanu announced Thursday that she has abandoned her dream to
return to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better here than a week from now,'' said Moceanu, America's
adolescent darling leading up to the 1996 Olympic Games. ``I have
to move on with life...life moves on...of course I am really sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, 18, officially called it quits less than 48 hours
before she was to compete in the first phase of the women's
gymnastics Olympic trials here Friday at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   According to her coach, Merry Lee Tracy, Moceanu injured the
knee Tuesday at the Fleet while practicing her floor routine. A
subusequent MRI and a call to the surgeon who operated on her knee
last summer delivered the diagnosis: a displaced bone chip lodged
in the knee. Moceanu, who will have surgery next week in
Cincinnati, has given up any idea of competing in Sydney (i.e. no
petition), and hopes to be back in about six weeks to join a post
Olympic tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to look at my life after this,'' said Moceanu, who
won't decide until January, after the tour, whether to continue
with competitive gymnastics. ``I have to try to get healthy and get
on with life.'' So goes another episode in Moceanu's life, another
chapter in what could be fodder for a Danielle Steele airport
novel. Following Atlanta, she ran away from home, eventually sued
her parents to gain her independence, and had a restraining order
issued against her father -- whom she accused of hoodwinking her
out of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling a lot better today than I was last night,'' said
Moceanu, who looked tired, as if she had been crying, during her
afternoon news conference on the third floor of the Fleet. ``I got
all the tears out and called my Mom, and the family and friends
that were going to come and watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu will remain here through Sunday night, she said, rooting
on her teammates. She'll meet with doctors Monday in Cincinatti and
undergo the operation as soon as it could be scheduled next week.
Doctors have been told to expect a three-week recovery process,
leaving her about another three weeks to get back into the gym and
shape up for the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've been dealt a big deck of cards,'' said Moceanu.
``I don't know why things do happen, but I know that they happen
for a reason. I've got to have faith and hope that everything will
work out for the best. And no matter how hard life gets sometimes,
you know, I've learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu was, at best, a long shot to return to Olympus.
Ultimately six women will be chosen for Sydney, and it will be a
surprise if more than two are '96 returnees. With the likes of
veterans Shannon Miller, Dominique Dawes and Amy Chow, seriously in
the hunt, Moceanu's name had barely surfaced earlier in the week
when Bela Karolyi, her former coach and now head of the women's
squad, handicapped the field.
</P>
<P>
   Come January Moceanu will have to decide whether to tune up for
a shot in the world championships, or make the hardest trip of her
life -- walk away from the sport that four years ago made her a
magazine cover girl.
</P>
<P>
   If it is time to go, Moceanu said she will pursue acting,
modeling and a career in sports broadcasting. She hopes to be in
Sydney next month, if only as a spectator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing event and, yeah, I'll be sad watching it,''
she said. ``But I'll be rooting for our team. I have to get used to
it, because from here on out, I will be watching most of these
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
