<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4907 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-DVD-PLAYBACK-BOS &LR;      08-17 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DVD-PLAYBACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE BARS DISTRIBUTION OF MOVIE-COPYING SOFTWARE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in New York has handed a major victory to the
motion picture industry, and a serious setback to computer hackers
and activists.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lewis Kaplan has ordered the popular hacker Web site
www.2600.com to stop offering copies of DeCSS, a program that can
be used to circumvent the anti-piracy features found on DVD movie
disks.
</P>
<P>
   Not only must 2600 stop offering the software directly, Kaplan
ordered 2600 to remove any hyperlinks to other sites that offer
DeCSS. This last command both angered and inspired an attorney for
2600, who says it increases the chances that her client will win on
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Gross of the Electronic Frontier Foundation, an Internet
civil liberties group, rejects the idea that DeCSS is an illegal
computer program. But she said the even if it is, 2600, has a
constitutional right to tell people how to get it. ``The judge has
essentially carved out a new exception to the First Amendment,''
Gross said. ``You can go on the Internet and find out where you can
buy drugs, and nobody can tell you can't do it.'' Gross said she'll
take this argument to the federal appeals court and the US Supreme
Court if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, said there's no constitutional protection for linking to
illegal materials. ``If you have criminally obscene material, you
can't link it,'' he said. Valenti, who represents the major
Hollywood studios that filed the suit, considers Kaplan's ruling
airtight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe for one second that the Supreme Court will
even look at this case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DeCSS was created last year by Norwegian programmers who claim
they were trying to invent a way to play DVD movies on computers
running the Linux operating system, because Linux-compatible DVD
software was not yet available for purchase. But the Motion Picture
Association of America regarded DeCSS as a transparent effort to
crack the encryption built into DVD disks, in order to prevent
illegal copying of movies.
</P>
<P>
   The 2600 site posted a copy of the DeCSS program. The MPAA
demanded that they remove it. 2600 did so, but encouraged
supporters throughout the Internet to post the software on their
own Web sites. Then 2600 published links to these other sites.
Technically, the software was no longer on 2600's own computer, but
in practical terms it was still available at the site.
</P>
<P>
   2600 argued that distribution of the software is an act of free
expression protected by the First Amendment, a view that Kaplan
dismissed in scornful terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer code is not purely expressive, any more than the
assassination of a political figure is purely a political
statement,'' Kaplan said. Both the software and the assassin carry
out particular functions, the judge said, and government has a
legitimate interest in regulating those functions. ``The
Constitution, after all, is a framework for building a just and
democratic society. It is not a suicide pact.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge said that DeCSS is banned under the Digital Millennium
Copyright Act. That federal law makes it a crme to circumvent
encryption features aimed at preventing piracy of software, music
or movies. The law allows for certain exceptions, but Kaplan ruled
that DeCSS is covered by none of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
