<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-KIDNAP-ART-2TAK     08-17 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-KIDNAP-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOVIE STAR AND HIS KIDNAPPER GIVE VOICE TO THE POOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Veerappan, the legendary bandit who has
humbled two Indian state governments with the kidnapping of a
matinee idol, is notorious as an elephant poacher, sandalwood
smuggler and ruthless killer who has eluded hundreds of police
officers devoted for years to nothing but his capture.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is reinventing himself as a romantic, gun-toting champion
of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Defying the expectations of the police, he has not demanded a
huge ransom or an amnesty for his crimes in exchange for the
release of the revered movie star, Rajkumar, 72, whom he has hidden
away in the jungle for the past 19 days.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Veerappan's roster of demands read like a political
manifesto for ethnic Tamils and the poor in the south Indian states
of Tamil Nadu and Karnataka, which have a combined population of
100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Let a statue to the Tamil-language poet Thiruvalluvar be erected
in Kannada-speaking Karnataka, he asserted. Let low-caste families
whose relatives have been murdered be compensated, he decreed. Let
51 of my compatriots and five Tamil militants _ detained for years
without trial under a draconian antiterrorism law _ be released.
All these wishes have been granted.
</P>
<P>
   An official emissary of the two states, a magazine editor, R. R.
Gopal, was venturing Thursday into the immense forest, alive with
elephants, tigers and cobras, that is the habitat of the hard-eyed
outlaw with the handlebar mustache. Gopal is bearing documents that
prove that the states have revoked the detention orders against the
56 people.
</P>
<P>
   As the kidnapping case has dragged on, its fascination for the
public has not flagged. Nor has its potential to terrify state
politicians who fear for their own political hides should any harm
come to Rajkumar, an elderly star with bad knees, who, like his
kidnapper, goes by one name.
</P>
<P>
   Rajkumar himself, in a taped message released in the first week
of his captivity, expressed great sympathy for Veerappan, who _ in
kidnapping him from his farmhouse on the fringes of the jungle on
July 30 _ respectfully called him ``sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever his desire, please fulfill it,'' the actor pleaded,
concluding with a paean to the outlaw: ``He is looking after us
with love and affection. He fully trusts us, and we have confidence
in him.''
</P>
<P>
   To a remarkable extent, the states have heeded the actor's
entreaties, but there has also been outrage at what The Indian
Express called ``the abject surrender'' to Veerappan.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning him by name, President K.R. Narayanan, in a
speech to the nation on Aug. 14, the eve of Indian Independence
Day, declared, ``It is time that civil society and the lawful
government asserted their authority and primacy over the daredevil
heroes of crime and banditry.''
</P>
<P>
   But the case is a delicate one. It presents perils that go
beyond the dire political consequences for the Congress Party,
which governs Karnataka, should harm befall Rajkumar. Officials
fear that Veerappan's demands could inflame old linguistic and
cultural antagonisms between the Tamil-speaking minority and the
Kannada-speaking majority in Karnataka, for whom the
Kannada-speaking actor, Rajkumar, is a mythic figure of regional
pride.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There is a history of anti-Tamil violence in Karnataka's
capital, Bangalore. In 1991, 17 Tamils were killed in riots and
hundreds of buildings destroyed after a court gave more irrigation
water from the Cauvery River to Tamil Nadu than Karnataka wanted to
share.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan has again raised these sensitive claims, demanding
that Tamil Nadu receive a larger share of the Cauvery water, that
the victims of the riots be compensated and that Tamil be given the
status of an official language in Karnataka.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan himself is an enigma. The police say he is a cunning,
inhuman criminal who strangled his infant daughter, murdered his
cousins because they were rival poachers and killed dozens of
policemen.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996 Veerappan told his version of the story to Gopal _
now the official emissary _ in nine hours of videotape whose
dialogue has been transcribed and published in Tamil. M.S.S.
Pandian, a fellow at the Madras Institute of Development Studies,
summarized it and translated portions into English in an essay in
the Economic and Political Weekly of Dec. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan describes in detail his kidnappings and killings, but
he depicts them as righteous efforts to avenge outrages committed
by the police as they pursued him.
</P>
<P>
   He says they raped, tortured and stole from the forest people
who protected him, and preyed on the desperately poor, extorting
money from those who depended on illegally hunting elephants and
cutting sandalwood for their survival.
</P>
<P>
   One high-ranking policeman who spent years chasing Veerappan,
who refused to allow his name to be used, acknowledged in an
interview that the police had committed terrible abuses over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In his narration, the outlaw described himself as having been
born to a peasant family that could not afford to educate him. He
went to work at a young age, he said, grazing cattle. He became a
hunter, too, and that led to life as an elephant poacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We target and shoot at the forehead of the elephant,'' he
said. ``It slumps to death without even knowing that life is
departing. Good death. To feed on its carcass birds come. 8.4
million living beings like birds and ants would eat it. Of all
charity, feeding is the greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The question now on the minds of the police and Rajkumar's fans
is what Veerappan will do with his captive. The risk of violence in
Bangalore, the capital of Karnataka, would be great if Rajkumar
were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   His kidnapping has already stirred his devout following to rage.
They took to the streets, throwing rocks, setting fires and
shutting down Bangalore _ one of Asia's most dynamic, modern
cities, with a population of about 5 million _ for two full days.
Schools and colleges were closed for two weeks and reopened only
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Gopal, the Tamil journalist who is the government emissary to
Veerappan, said in a diary of the case in Outlook magazine that he
agreed to take on the job after the chief minister of Tamil Nadu
told him that the safety of hundreds of thousands of Tamils in
Karnataka was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Gopal, who had negotiated the release of an earlier group of
Veerappan's hostages, described his first foray into the jungle,
from Aug. 7 to 9, as beginning in a tribal hut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late evening, as darkness envelops the forests, Veerappan's
men lead me and my team,'' he wrote. ``We begin walking. It seems
like an endless journey. Finally, we halt for the night. It is
uncomfortable. Insect bites make my skin itch perpetually. I can't
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   When he finally reached Veerappan the next day, he said, he
found him a changed man _ indeed the police describe a man worn out
from a life on the run, suffering from asthma and a bad stomach.
``Gone is his swagger and gay abandon,'' Gopal wrote. ``He is more
serious and stiff.'' This new man also speaks ``as if he is the
sole representative of the Tamils.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rajkumar, on his 10th day of captivity, seemed to the
magazine editor to have ``fallen in love with life in the jungle.''
He spoke in fluent Tamil of its lush natural beauty, of his long
chats with his abductors and of his close association with Tamils.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard about the Stockholm syndrome,'' Gopal wrote
dryly, referring to the development of a bond between hostages and
kidnappers. ``Probably this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   After two rounds of talks with the outlaw, Gopal headed back to
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   And now, as he heads back into the depths of jungle, India waits
for the next chapter of the saga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
