<HEADLINE>
METAL STRIP THAT DAMAGED TIRE WAS NOT PART OF CONCORDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story is not bylined) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The French minister of transportation said Thursday that
a metal strip that punctured a tire on the Concorde that crashed
north of Paris on July 25, killing 113 people, was apparently part
of another aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears it came from another plane,'' the minister,
Jean-Claude Gayssot, told the Europe One radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Gayssot's ministry and at the French Bureau of
Accident Investigations emphasized that the source of the 16-inch
strip of metal had not been definitely identified, but that it was
not part of the Concorde and appeared instead to have fallen onto
the runway from another aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe that chunks of rubber from the ruptured
tire tore through the Concorde's wing, producing a fuel leak and
fire that caused both engines on the left side of the plane to shut
down and the aircraft to crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
