<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4919 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-CVN-SANDERS-COLUMN-TE     08-17 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSLIMS BEGINNING TO MAKE THEIR PRESENCE FELT IN DEMOCRATIC PARTY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BOB RAY SANDERS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democrats had a right to boast about their natural
diversity at their 43rd convention here this week, and they did it
every chance they got.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker after speaker pointed out that the party has long been
made up of, and continues to welcome, all people, regardless of
color, gender, religion or sexual preference.
</P>
<P>
   But while all the talk about inclusion was being shouted from
the podium at the Staples Center, one minority group was quietly
making history simply by its unprecedented presence here.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 Muslim- and Arab-Americans were part of the convention
for the first time, leaders say, and this was just the beginning.
There were five Muslims in the Texas delegation, three delegates
and two alternates.
</P>
<P>
   At the Texas breakfast yesterday morning, Zafar Tahir of Houston
became the first Muslim to offer the opening prayer for the state
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Syed A. Ahsani, an alternate from Arlington, said many Muslims
identify with the Democratic Party because it does have a history
of inclusion and diversity.
</P>
<P>
   A former ambassador of Pakistan and chairman of the American
Muslim-Arab Political Coalition for the Southwest Region, Ahsani
said people of the Islamic faith are becoming better organized and
are beginning to participate more in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   About 6 million Muslims reside in the United States, he said,
and Islam is the fastest growing religion in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago (Michael) Dukakis said he didn't want our
backing _ the backing of Muslims,'' said delegate Selma Tameez of
Houston. ``The last 10 years we've come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Mustafa Iqbal Tameez, who is active in the Harris
County Democratic Party, said that, based on the number of
delegates at this convention and the growing number of Muslims in
the country, it won't be long before ``Muslims will have the swing
vote'' in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He points out that almost 80 percent of the Muslims are
concentrated in such key electoral states as New York, Texas,
California, Michigan, Illinois and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who understand that, and those who are truly visionary,
will begin to reach out and include Muslim-Americans,'' Mustafa
Tameez said.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of Al Gore's running mate being Jewish, all the
Muslim delegates I talked to said Sen. Joe Lieberman's faith wasn't
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no concerns about Lieberman,'' Ahsani said. ``We
appreciate his stand on moral issues because we share the same
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Mustafa Tameez said, ``The appointment of Joseph Lieberman in
one way opens the door to all religious minorities . . . We are
wanting to see if the administration will keep that door open.''
</P>
<P>
   If Muslims don't have a problem with Gore and Lierberman, they
do have concerns about something President Clinton said recently
when he announced that the administration was reviewing its
position on whether the U.S. Embassy in Israel should be moved from
Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   After the president's speech here Monday night the American
Muslim Council organized a letter-writing campaign among Muslim
delegates in which they reaffirmed their support for the
Gore-Lieberman ticket and for Hillary Clinton's New York campaign
for the U.S. Senate. But they urged the president ``to suspend the
review of moving our embassy into what is regarded under
international law as occupied territory.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gore still behind in the polls, Democrats can't afford to
make too many of their friends unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7775, or e-mail:
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
