<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-1STL     08-17 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPES OF SAVING SUBMARINE CREW DIM AS RESCUE EFFORTS CONTINUE TO
FAIL  
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS 5th graf to give full ID for the defense minister, Marshal
Igor Sergeyev. An expanded an updated version of this story will
move by 9 p.m. EDT.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In frantic efforts made against increasingly hopeless
odds to save the crew of the crippled nuclear-powered submarine
Kursk, Russian rescue teams failed again Thursday to lock onto a
rear escape hatch of the shattered vessel. As they worked, new
reports emerged of catastrophic damage to the hull, suggesting that
the ship went down in a torrent of fire and flooding that may have
killed or mortally wounded everyone on board.
</P>
<P>
   With no signs of life for two days from any of the 118 sailors
and officers, Russia's top navy commanders met with Deputy Prime
Minister Ilya Klebvanov at Severodmorsk, headquarters of the
Northern Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The officials were to discuss whether to continue the so-far
fruitless attempts to land a rescue vessel on the Kursk's rear deck
or whether to use other methods to raise and begin salvaging the
vessel, whose two nuclear reactors pose a threat to Arctic
fisheries. The submarine sank last weekend during naval maneuvers
in the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The grim damage assessments were made after viewing hours of
underwater video of the Kursk's shattered bow section, cracked deck
plates, shredded foredeck and battered conning tower. And stark
differences between Moscow and Washington were emerging over the
fundamental cause of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's defense minister, Marshal Igor Sergeyev, said he had
``irrefutable data'' pointing to a collision. But senior U.S.
defense and intelligence officials said the Kursk had suffered
powerful internal explosions. No scenario yet bridged the two
versions.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mikhail Kasyanov called the situation ``next to
catastrophic,'' as engineers and admirals studied whether giant
pontoons could be fitted to the rear of the Kursk to bring its rear
escape hatch nearer to the surface where divers might open it.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the past night, there were no changes for better or
worse,'' Kasyanov told a meeting of senior government officials in
Moscow. He added that ``we want to hope that there are chances''
remaining to rescue the crew.
</P>
<P>
   In Murmansk, where Russian naval officials mobilized the
hospital ship Svir to treat sailors who might be freed by rescuers,
a sense of gloom set in. Some families said they had all but lost
hope.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect that the whole crew may be lost, making the sinking
of the Kursk Russia's worst peacetime naval disaster, generated a
wave of recriminations through the Russian news media.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the criticism was aimed at the military, but also at the
Russian president, Vladimir V. Putin, who remained on vacation at
the Black Sea resort of Sochi and planned to meet with leaders of
former Soviet republics on Friday, the day when navy officials were
expected to acknowledge that the crew no longer had breathable air.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Russian media also questioned why the military and Putin had
failed to disclose to the nation that a tragedy had occurred on
Saturday, when the first reports of underwater explosions rattled
Western intelligence sensors in the region. The government
acknowledged the accident only on Monday, saying the mishap had
occurred on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sailors on the Kursk fell silent yesterday,'' the
newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda stated Thursday in large red type.
``Why has the president been silent? Why on earth did he think it
was possible to keep mum for five days, when the entire nation has
spent those days consumed with only one thought _ will they be
saved or won't they?''
</P>
<P>
   Izvestia said the catastrophe had ``sunk the people's faith'' in
government. ``It is the authorities themselves who have hit
bottom,'' the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   Underwater video taken over several days and analyzed at navy
headquarters Thursday confirmed massive structural damage to the
forward compartments of the ship, including the bridge section
under the conning tower where Capt. Gennadi Lyachin, 45, and a
number of senior officers of the Northern Fleet would have been
stationed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accident happened so quickly we can say it was like a
flash,'' said a navy spokesman, Igor Dygalo.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest mystery that remains is what triggered the
disaster as the 14,000-ton vessel steamed through the Barents Sea
at a depth that longtime Russian naval officers regarded as
dangerously shallow for the Kursk to operate in, given its length
of 490 feet and height of more than 100 feet from the bottom of the
keel to the top of its conning tower and periscope masts. A simple
failure of a torpedo tube or of the steering mechanism could pull
its nose down and send it crashing into the bottom, Western and
Russian naval experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev's remarks Thursday injected a new mystery into the sea
tragedy. U.S. defense and intelligence officials said Wednesday
that they detected the sound of two underwater explosions, one much
larger than the other, near the Kursk's location on Saturday
morning. The U.S. officials cast doubt on any speculation that the
submarine was involved in a collision.
</P>
<P>
   But Sergeyev, in remarks to the Interfax news agency, asserted
Thursday that ``The scenario in which the Kursk submarine suffered
from a collision with another object is now the main one _
irrefutable data are already available.'' He did not elaborate on
that evidence and whether it arose exclusively from an examination
of the hull or from interrogation of naval officers aboard other
Russian ships operating with the Kursk at the time of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Eduard Baltin, former commander of Russian submarine forces in
the Pacific, said Thursday that the Kursk was operating in a sea
lane frequently used by cargo vessels traveling between the ports
of Murmansk and Dikson, a remote port east of Murmansk on the Kara
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the only realistic version is the sub collided with a
cargo vessel,'' Baltin said, writing in Thursday's Komsomolskaya
Pravda, ``because it is in this area where there is a recommended
course for civil navigation between Murmansk and Dikson.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a similar collision, with less catastrophic results for
the submarine, occurred in the same area about 15 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
