<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOYSMART-BANKRUPTCY-N     08-17 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SETS ASIDE RESTRICTIONS ON SALE OF TOY RETAILER'S DATABASE  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A federal bankruptcy judge Thursday set aside a Federal
Trade Commission plan limiting the ability of an online toy
retailer to sell its customer database as part of its liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Toysmart.com, reached a settlement with the
commission last month meant to address concerns over the sale of
data that had been collected with the promise of confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge, Carol Kenner, said Thursday that in the absence
of a buyer, the commission's action was premature. ``I believe that
deciding this in a vacuum, without a real-live bidder here, is
unnecessary,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She took the action ``without prejudice,'' meaning that the
trade commission and others are welcome to renew their concerns and
objections once a bid and specific terms have been put forward for
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The function of any court is to resolve actual conflicts,''
the judge added, noting that complaints about potential abuse of
the information were based on hypothetical concerns rather than
specific details.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Rosenfeld, assistant director of the trade commission's
Bureau of Consumer Protection, said the company was disappointed by
the ruling, but noted that the judge had not rejected the basic
premise of the commission's position.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com had pledged not to sell its customer information to
third parties, but its bankruptcy prompted concerns that the data
would be sold as part of its assets. The trade commission voted 3-2
last month in favor of a settlement restricting the sale of the
database. Under those terms, the buyer would have to be in a
family-related commerce market, purchase the entire Web site and
agree not to resell the data without permission from the customers
who submitted it.
</P>
<P>
   Some commission members, state attorneys general and privacy
advocates opposed the settlement, saying it did not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Toysmart.com and its creditors withdrew the
company's Web site and customer list last month after rejecting two
offers, including one bid of $50,000 from a subsidiary of the Walt
Disney Co., the majority owner of Toysmart.com, which pledged to
destroy the list.
</P>
<P>
   The creditors contended in court Thursday that the commission's
terms unduly constrained efforts to find a potential buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the resolution will be crafted around the buyer,''
said Christopher Panos, a lawyer for the creditors, who urged the
judge not to approve the trade commission's plan. He said the
company ``cannot do anything with this asset without giving notice
to the FTC and the approval of Bankruptcy Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the company's other assets since its shutdown in May
have yielded more than $5 million, more than initially expected,
said Harry Murphy, a bankruptcy lawyer for Toysmart.com. He blamed
adverse publicity from the company's June attempt to market its
customer lists for the shortage of bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wanted to walk into a lawsuit,'' he said. ``Now we're
back where we started.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenner gave no deadline for Toysmart.com to find a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Other bankrupt dot-com companies have sold their customer data,
though Craftshop.com, a now-defunct arts and crafts retailer, also
withdrew its list from sale last month. The presence of information
about minors among the 250,000 customers in Toysmart's database
make its case unique, legal observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the buyer, Toysmart.com customers need to be
advised that details like children's names, ages and toy
preferences might be transferred, argued Pamela Kogut, a
Massachusetts assistant attorney general. Given Toysmart's specific
promise not to share that data with any third parties, customers
should be allowed to choose whether to remain on the list, she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
