<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE CONVENTIONS DON'T LIVE UP TO THE HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If any group was hoping for a ``bounce'' from the Democratic and
Republican conventions, it was the scores of political Web sites
that made their online debuts in Los Angeles and Philadelphia with
lots of gizmos and hype.
</P>
<P>
   But while some said the coming of the Internet to the
conventions would be as momentous as the advent of television 52
years ago, the reality has been somewhat less impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Technological problems have plagued many Web sites, causing them
to crash or to abandon many promised features. Some Internet sites
found expenses so high and visitors so low at the Republican
convention two weeks ago in Philadelphia that they drastically
scaled back operations at the Democratic convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Even traffic to political Web sites with brand names and long
track records was disappointingly low for the Republicans'
gathering, and some critics complained that the level of political
discourse in online chat rooms was lower than expected, too.
Detailed data on Web sites during the Democratic convention will
not be available until next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bridge hasn't yet been made between politics and the
Internet,'' said James Carey, a spokesman for PC Data OnLine, which
tracks Web use. ``There's not a lot of traffic to these sites. It
just isn't working yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Visits to political Web sites _ ranging from such mainstream
sites as MSNBC.com and CNN.com to more cutting-edge sites like
Pseudo.com or SpeakOut.com _ actually fell during the Republican
convention. MSNBC.com, for instance, saw a 27 percent drop in its
visitors to 2.4 million during the week of the convention, and
CNN.com saw an 18 percent drop to 1.9 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Newer Web sites like Speakout.com and Voter.com failed to even
pull more than 150,000 visitors during the Republican convention,
according to Media Metrix Inc., a company that tracks this data.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first online convention failed to live up to the hype that
preceded it,'' Michael Cornfield, director of the Democracy Online
Project at George Washington University, said about Philadelphia.
``This is not so surprising because the convention was not an
exciting news event.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for low traffic was the product: Despite
claims by many Internet Web sites that they could jazz up
convention coverage with offbeat stories, chat rooms and nifty
camera shots, the online coverage proved to be no more exciting
than that of regular television, which itself was often greeted
with yawns. Some of the promises _ streaming video, instantaneous
polling and ``behind-the-scenes'' footage _ failed to materialize,
or did so in fuzzy and unattractive formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of sites couldn't get their act together,'' said Marion
Just, a researcher at the Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press,
Politics and Public Policy at Harvard University. ``Many wanted to
have the fanciest gadgets and gimmicks, and some sites crashed and
burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo.com, which bought a sky box at both conventions, cut its
convention staff in half after the Republican convention, and did
not bring its 360-degree camera to Los Angeles after the camera
produced only small, grainy online pictures, in the opinion of some
viewers, and those came at high costs.
</P>
<P>
   The two political parties failed, as well, to live up to their
promises of plugged-in conventions. The Dems.2000 Web site promised
to have online chats with convention speakers immediately after
their presentations. That did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a live chat, anyone signing on with questions was
given an automated response thanking them for participating in the
``online event,'' saying the party was ``doing its best'' to answer
them and to continue participating in Democratic events online.
</P>
<P>
   And the Republican's highly touted dot-com delegate Web site,
which promised ``exclusive'' on-line access to top Republican
officials, also failed to deliver. A promised live chat room never
came about, information given to dot-com delegates was dated and
generic and online polls asked questions not related to the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the features lived up to the hype,'' said Chris
Hunter, an analyst with NetElection.Org. ``Chat rooms were vapid
and off-topic. It was all very disappointing. I think lots of the
dot.coms weren't there to promote democracy, but to get another
round of venture capital.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
