<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4927 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-NEXT18-COX     08-17 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-NEXT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ROAD OUT OF CONVENTION A STEEPER ONE FOR GORE
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After President Clinton accepted the Democratic
nomination in New York City in 1992, he and Vice President Al Gore
hopped on buses and blazed a trail west, hoping to generate
excitement about their insurgent campaign against President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Gore will wake up at dawn in La Crosse, Wis., and
begin a four-day riverboat cruise down the Mississippi River with
his running mate, Sen. Joe Lieberman of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   With bucolic images of the great Mississippi and small-town
America as their stage, Gore and Lieberman will be trying to
re-create the same excitement that catapulted Clinton to the White
House in 1992. But the political dynamics of the 2000 campaign are
far different for Gore and Lieberman than they were for Clinton and
Gore eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   No longer the outsiders seeking to scale the castle gates, Gore
and Lieberman are the incumbents seeking to persuade voters that
they offer a fresh start even though they have both belong to the
official Washington establishment.
</P>
<P>
   They also face the daunting task of linking themselves with
Clinton's record, but not his character, which Americans generally
hold in low esteem.
</P>
<P>
   The terrain Gore and Lieberman will encounter is also much
different than it was eight years ago. In 1992, the Midwest was
reeling from a three-year economic recession. Clinton's pledge to
restore the economy and put people back to work mined a rich vein
of voter resentment.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Midwest is once again the battleground for the
presidential election. But the region, like most of the rest of the
country, is enjoying record low unemployment, and Gore and
Lieberman will find it more difficult to generate enthusiasm among
voters who are more content than they were eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the states that Clinton and Gore narrowly carried last
time are at risk for the Democrats,'' said Emory University
political scientist Merle Black. Those states include Wisconsin,
Ohio, Pennsylvania, Illinois and Missouri _ all states in which
Gore will campaign heavily between now and Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will contest four states in the South _ North Carolina,
Georgia, Arkansas and Florida _ and also will have to maintain a
strong presence in his home state of Tennessee. Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush, who will campaign in
Tennessee today, intends to make a strong push for the state, which
has a Republican governor and two Republican U.S. senators.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond geography, Gore also will pursue a strategy that seeks to
offer voters a better sense of who he is as a person. So far, Gore
hasn't managed to connect with the voters in the same way that
Clinton did, particularly among suburban women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters have to see him as a reasonable and sympathetic human
being,'' said Black. ``Part of his problem is that voters don't see
him that way. He has this almost robotic approach.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's convention was heavily scripted by the Gore campaign
to overcome such perceptions. All three people who put Gore's name
into nomination stressed his character and integrity. And all three
are people who knew Gore intimately: actor Tommy Lee Jones, a
college friend; Lois Deberry, a Tenmessage has the potential to
draw votes away from Gore in Northwestern states that Clinton and
Gore carried in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nader takes away votes from Gore in those places, and forces
him to spend time and money in places that he should by rights
win,'' said Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   One big unknown as the campaign moves into the critical last few
months is how Gore will respond now that he, and not Clinton, is
the party's standard-bearer. Gore aides portray the vice president
as eager to have finally become the party's nominee and get on with
the final leg of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not worrying about expectations,'' said Carter Eskew, a
senior Gore aide. ``He's worrying about going out and laying out
his ideas, his story and where he wants to take the country. And I
think he'll let the chips fall where they do after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett's e-mail address is kfoskett(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
