<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4930 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-TEXAS18-COX     08-17 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-TEXAS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXASBy KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ By the time the final convention gavel fell, after
days of spreading their version of the ``truth'' about their
governor, Texas delegates had talked themselves into what seems
like the impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Lord's help and a lot of good effort we damned well
may win'' Texas for Democratic nominee Al Gore, former state
Democratic Chairman Bob Slagle told cheering delegates at their
Thursday meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate Slagle may be dreaming. And most Democrats here
acknowledged that beating George W. Bush in his back yard is out of
the question. Nevertheless, the Texas delegates headed home today
convinced they had met their goal of serving as eyewitnesses
spinning their view of the Bush record.
</P>
<P>
   State Chair Molly Beth Malcolm was up as early as 4:30 a.m. on
some days to begin making the rounds. Texas Democratic leaders were
popular guests at other delegations' breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's closing convention session, delegates honored
about 30 members of the ``Texas Truth Squad,'' Democrats who have
traveled around the nation to criticize Bush's record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``As proud Texans we are here to tell you briefly the truth
about things down in Texas,'' state Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos told
the convention, detailing the legislative record on teacher pay
hikes, children's health insurance and hate crime measures. ``We
know the truth because we were there.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those joining Barrientos on the podium were state Reps.
Dawnna Dukes and Glen Maxey, as well as Texas AFL-CIO President Joe
Gunn.
</P>
<P>
   With the convention over, the question now is whether the
message of Bush-as-abject-failure will take. Texas chic _ all the
rage in Philadelphia two weeks ago during the Republican National
Convention _ was decidedly out of style this week on the coast
where trends are born.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, all things Texan and Bush were cool, hinting at
the possibility that a Bush win might make Texas trendier than it
has been since Urban Cowboy days.
</P>
<P>
   Out here _ due in part to the Texans' efforts _ it was a
different story. Texas and Bush took it on the chin at the souvenir
stands, from the podium and when the states lined up to vote.
</P>
<P>
   In a shot at his home state, Rep. Martin Frost, chairman of the
state delegation, on Thursday said the GOP ticket _ heavy on Texans
_ typifies what's wrong with the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had an opportunity to demonstrate their diversity in the
ticket they chose,'' Frost said of the Republicans. ``They picked
two white guys from Texas for their ticket. We demonstrated
diversity in our ticket by picking the first Jewish-American to be
vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush running mate Dick Cheney is a former Wyoming congressman
who most recently lived and worked in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Austin, the Texas GOP summed up the Democratic National
Convention as ``Texas under siege'' featuring ``slash-and-burn,
Texas-bashing rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Texas Democrats are really proud to be Texans they will
join Republican leaders in defending the Lone Star State,'' said
Texas GOP Chair Susan Weddington.
</P>
<P>
   Austin delegate Liz Carpenter, about as Texan _ and Democratic_
as they come, joined in the verbal assault on Bush. In a Thursday
speech to the delegation, Carpenter, 79, poked fun at her long
years in politics by linking herself to another George W.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew George Washington. He was my friend. And you, Governor
Bush, are no George Washington,'' she said. ``After all, George
Washington never told a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of rhetoric found kindred spirits among those who make
a buck off political conventions. Button sellers offered wares with
messages such as ``Read my lips _ no new Texans,'' ``I refuse to
vote for a son of a Bush,'' ``My dog never met a Bush he didn't
like'' and ``W was born with a silver spoon up his nose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas delegates' attempts to denigrate their governor got a
boost from others during the roll-call vote that nominated the
Democratic ticket. Alaska's delegation chairwoman Cindy Spanyers
told the convention that her state ``is more than twice the size of
Texas, but with a Democratic governor 10 times as smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Chairman Tim Knaus noted that his state is the former
home of Neil Bush, ``George W's brother, who fled our state after
plundering the hard-earned savings of working families in the
savings and loan scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   For Texas, long synonymous with exaggeration, the highs and lows
will be taken in stride. The true state of the state is somewhere
between the polluted mess it sounded like out here and the miracle
portrayed in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Democratic convention moved to its logical and
anticipated conclusion, the Texas delegation declared itself
successful enough to dare to dream outside the lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to keep the Texas House and tak Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
