<P>
   DEM-RDP-NYT (Los Angeles) _ A roundup: Twelve years after his
first try for the presidency ended in failure and after eight years
toiling in the political shadow of Bill Clinton, Al Gore formally
becomes the Democratic Party's presidential nominee and his party's
new leader.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   (Early version by Jerry Gray has moved. We plan to move the
updated rewrite by 10 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top Center
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ In frantic efforts against
increasingly hopeless odds to save the crew of the sunken nuclear
submarine Kursk, Russian rescue teams tried and failed through
another stormy night and throughout Thursday to lock onto a rear
escape hatch of the shattered vessel. New reports emerged of
catastrophic damage to the hull, suggesting the ship went down in a
torrent of fire and flooding that may have killed or mortally
wounded everyone aboard. The growing prospect that the crew may be
beyond rescue, making the sinking of the Kursk Russia's worst
peacetime naval disaster, generated a wave of recriminations
through the Russian news media. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   (Early version has moved. Updated rewrite scheduled to move by
8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-Lead
</P>
<P>
   LEE-TRIAL (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ A ruling is expected in the
contentious bail hearing for Wen Ho Lee, a former nuclear weapons
scientist at the Los Alamos National Laboratory, accused of
illegally moving secret data to an unsecure computer and portable
computer tapes, some of which are missing, with the intent to harm
the United States. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
