<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SKIN-CELLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS BELIEVE THEY HAVE FOUND ORIGIN OF SKIN CELLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ill., N.J.)   (Previously skedded as SCI-SKIN-CANCER)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's not like discovering a new bone in the human body.
But researchers now believe they have found the source of the new
skin cells that replace those shed in every day's wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   Those source, or stem, cells turn out to be hiding in the roots
of the hair.
</P>
<P>
   The finding, if confirmed, could lead to a better understanding
of how the skin heals as well as to insights into basal cell
carcinoma, a common skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Hair follicles, small pockets in the skin from which the hair
shaft sprouts, occur in varying density throughout the human skin,
except in the palms, soles, foreskin and labia. Even in bald
scalps, hair follicles are present and healthy but just arrested in
midcycle.
</P>
<P>
   A small bulge on the side of the follicle, just below the skin
surface, houses stem cells that migrate down to the follicle root
and repopulate the hair-making cells. Researchers report in
Friday's issue of Cell the surprising finding that the bulge is
also home to the stem cells for the skin.
</P>
<P>
   These epidermal stem cells migrate upward from the bulge and
into the surrounding skin, the researchers say. Given the general
spacing of hair follicles in human skin, a stem cell need only
migrate 3 millimeters, or one tenth of an inch, to cover half the
distance to the neighboring follicle.
</P>
<P>
   The senior authors of the study are Dr. Tung-Tien Sun of the New
York University School of Medicine and Dr. Robert M. Lavker of the
University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine. The two
dermatologists have been working together in search of the skin's
and other stem cells for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Their experiment tracking the exodus of the stem cells from the
follicle bulge was done in mice, but human follicles also have a
bulge and it seems likely this is also a source of skin cells in
people too, said Dr. Elaine Fuchs, a skin biologist at the
University of Chicago. But there might be other sources of stem
cells in human skin, she said, particularly in the regions that
have no hair follicles.
</P>
<P>
   She described the work as a ``very important finding'' because
it nailed down the localization of the skin's stem cell compartment
and also showed the stem cells in the bulge are pluripotent,
meaning they can develop either into hair cells or skin cells.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the body's cells have assumed their final, mature form,
and if they divide at all will produce two identical daughter
cells. Stem cells, when they divide, produce daughter cells which
can either remain as stem cells or develop into mature cells of the
relevant type. This means the population of stem cells is
continually replenished, acting as permanent reservoir for
replacing damaged tissue cells.
</P>
<P>
   Recent discoveries about the stem cells in other tissues are
suggesting the cells are remarkably versatile and that, with the
right signals, one kind of stem cell can be converted to another.
If stem cells should become an important way of helping to repair
the body's tissues, as many biologists are hoping, the bulge of a
patient's hair follicles will be a particularly convenient source.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kurt S. Stenn, director of the skin biology research
laboratory of Johnson &AMP; Johnson in Skillman, N.J., said the new
study was convincing and would advance any application of stem
cells for healing the skin since the source of the cells was now
known.
</P>
<P>
   Lavker said that he and Sun have not yet formally proved that a
single cell can make either hair or skin, but he believes that if
the cells in the bulge receive a signal to generate skin cells they
will migrate up and into the skin; if the cue is to generate hair,
they will migrate down into the base of the follicle. The relevant
cues have not yet been identified.
</P>
<P>
   The new finding suggests that any form of hair removal that
damages the hair follicles could impair the long-term health of the
skin by depriving the area of its stem cells. Stenn said that
electrolysis, for example, destroys the follicles. But he and other
dermatologists did not know why the skin generally seems to escape
damage in these circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Lavker believes his work may help explain basal cell carcinoma,
a skin cancer caused by ultra-violet light. The light cannot reach
the stem cells in their deep-set bulge but it can derange the stem
cell's descendants as they migrate closer to the surface. It is
these light-damaged cells, that have considerable proliferative
capacity, that initiate the cancer, Lavker believes.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists do not yet understand the widely varying qualities
and distribution of human hair. There is an evolutionary advantage
in having no follicles on the palms or soles, Stenn suggested,
because grip is improved by having no hair there. But how nature
arranges for this outcome is not yet known. Lavker believes that
the copious sweat glands found in the palms and soles are probably
the site of these region's stem cells.
</P>
</TEXT>
