<HEADLINE>
VERIZON, UNION SAY PROGRESS MADE IN TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Verizon Communications and one of its two striking unions
reported making substantial progress Thursday, saying they would
likely continue to negotiate until an agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, officials from the Communications Workers of
America, the larger of two unions that struck the company Aug. 6,
said members of its bargaining committee would leave the talks if a
tentative agreement was not reached by midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   However, CWA spokeswoman Candice Johnson said Thursday the two
sides had not reached an impasse and would now likely continue the
talks. But labor leaders from the CWA's north bargaining committee,
which represents former NYNEX Co. employees, maintained they would
abide by the pledge to quit talking if no agreement were reached by
the midnight deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made some progress over the last 24 hours and talks
are continuing,'' said Johnson. ``We are going to keep at it. We
want to reach a settlement. Officials will keep talking and they
will try to resolve the issue,'' she added. ``There will not be a
complete walkout. Top officials will continue to talk. But the
bargaining committee members are frustrated and have said that if
there is no substantial movement they will go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to move the talks toward a resolution, the 13,000-member
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers submitted a new
proposal outlining new job security language. Details concerning
the proposal were not available.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two sides have worked out some of their differences
some issues remain, including the unions' demand for more job
protection and security. Labor leaders said they are concerned that
work in the Eastern region will be moved to call centers in other
states.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Rabe, vice president of communications at Verizon, said the
company would find new jobs for workers who do not wish to
relocate. ``We do not force people to move across the country,'' he
said. ``The ability to move work refers to being able to shift
calls from centers where there is less demand to those that have
greater demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabe seemed hopeful the negotiators were nearing a resolution.
``Sometimes it is helpful to have a deadline,'' he said. ``It gets
people focused.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, the company services about 25 million residential
clients and businesses from Maine to Virginia, some of whom have
experienced disruptions in service. The number of repair requests
increased to 100,000 this week, up from 80,000 last week, and
people in need of new phone lines have been asked to wait until the
strike ends.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether one union could reach an agreement before the
other, Rabe said he was not sure whether one labor group was
further ahead and would agree to a settlement this week.
</P>
<P>
   Although the unions had reported progress in reaching an
agreement on the unions' request for permission to organize
wireless workers through a card check neutrality plan, one segment
of the IBEW has said it has not yet resolved the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Spillane, a spokesman for the IBEW, told the wire services
Thursday the union is concerned that some wireless workers in New
Jersey would not be covered by the card check neutrality agreement.
Card check allows unions to avoid time-consuming elections that can
be challenged by employers.
</P>
<P>
   While talks continued Thursday, managers from Verizon
Communications testified before a panel of judges at Suffolk
Superior Court in Boston that they had been harassed by strikers
while on their way to work.
</P>
<P>
   The managers said strikers had called them names, hurled sexual
slurs, and threatened to kill them. The company is seeking an
injunction to bar strikers from blocking company doors and exits
and prevent harassment.
</P>
</TEXT>
