<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-TRACKING0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS is criticized for tracking charge for Web inquiries
 &HT;    By Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This may be the Information Age, but United Parcel
Service Corp. has found a way to limit access to Internet data that
can cost it money.
</P>
<P>
   The company began guaranteeing delivery times for its ground
shipments in 1998 and promises full refunds for packages that
arrive late. UPS even invites customers to track their shipments on
the company's Web site for free.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a catch in the fine print of UPS shipping contracts.
</P>
<P>
   UPS reserves the right to charge $3 for each Web inquiry if
customers or their agents track too many packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS makes promises and then tries as hard as possible not to
keep them,'' said Mark Taylor, founder a ShippingRefunds.com, a
Michigan firm that audits freight bills. ``The right thing for UPS
to do would be to honor its commitments. Instead, it throws every
conceivable roadblock at anyone who tries to make them keep their
word.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said UPS uses the threat of charges for Web inquiries to
keep customers from obtaining the refunds.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS bullies shippers and tries to intimidate them,'' he said.
``UPS regards people like me as 'value extractors.' But if UPS
wants to put me out of business, all it has to do is honor its
guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS, the world's largest transportation firm, handles 13.2
million shipments a day, and the vast majority of them get to their
destinations on time. Still, Taylor estimates about 5 percent of
all guaranteed shipments arrive late, and about $2 billion a year
in refunds go unclaimed throughout the package delivery industry.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Black, a UPS spokesman, said customers can track as many
packages as they want free of charge, but professional auditors
like Taylor can't. UPS has spent billions of dollars in recent
years expanding its information technology infrastructure to
provide package tracking and other services.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors like Taylor would bombard UPS computers with
information requests, and real UPS customers would get stuck with
the bill, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These computer networks are expensive, and it takes time,
talent and money to build and operate them,'' Black said. ``We
aren't in the business of bearing those kinds of expenses to
accommodate non-customers. It would be totally unfair to saddle our
customers with huge additional expenses for computer capacity that
they don't need.''
</P>
<P>
   Black said UPS customers are notified of delivery problems, and
UPS works hard to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We build a level of trust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   UPS's 1998 rate book notified customers that the company could
assess the shipper ``a $3 charge per package-tracking request
initiated by or at the request of the shipper.'' The company said
it would not charge customers for their first 200 tracking requests
each month or up to 20 percent of their shipments.
</P>
<P>
   UPS would not say if it has ever imposed the $3 charge for Web
tracking.
</P>
<P>
   UPS rival FedEx Corp., which also offers online package
tracking, said it has never charged for Web inquiries and doesn't
intend to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability of our customers to track their packages is an
integral part of the service we offer,'' said Sally Davenport, a
FedEx spokeswoman at the company's Memphis headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine FedEx ever charging a separate fee for package
tracking. It's never even been contemplated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
