<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-YOUNG-ARTISTS-2TAKES-     08-17 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-ARTISTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: PICKING OUT DISTINCTIVE VOICES IN A PLURALISTIC
CHORUS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOLLAND COTTER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The one-off showcase titled ``Greater New York: New
Art in New York Now'' at PS 1 last spring received a lot of
attention. But the fact is, similar institutional group exhibitions
of up-and-coming artists have long been an annual feature in the
city's art season.
</P>
<P>
   Three are on view now, at the Studio Museum in Harlem, the Bronx
Museum of the Arts and El Museo del Barrio. The museums themselves
are still seen as fringe venues, but that's not their whole story.
Yes, they're alternative spaces, and two of them are ethnically
specific, so you'll find things there you might not find elsewhere.
But they're also integral players in the big picture of American
art, and their shows feed the larger pool of talent from which
mainstream stars emerge.
</P>
<P>
   That pool is growing wider all the time. Art isn't just
pluralistic these days; it's pulverized. There seems to be one of
everything, even when a lot of things feel sort of alike. Old
distinctions between art, craft, design and architecture have
dissolved. Obsessive hand-crafting and digital technology are
equally ubiquitous. Shape-shifting of the most casual kind is the
rule.
</P>
<P>
   The identity consciousness that drove art in the 1990s has
soaked in; its tincture comes through no matter what else is going
on. Personal roles on which artists once had to be firm _
ethnicity, gender _ they can now play with, layering them,
customizing them, taking them off, putting them back on. As for
styles, there's room for whatever, from the confrontational to the
seriously inconsequential, and all of it is out there, as the
summer shows demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   Studio Museum in Harlem
</P>
<P>
   ``From the Studio: Artists in Residence'' is the smallest of the
annuals, with just three participants. Now in its 32nd year, it is
also the oldest, and its family tree includes distinguished alumni
like David Hammons, Kerry James Marshall, Alison Saar and Nari
Ward. The residents are given studio space for a year on the
premises, in a large scuffed-up room divided into thirds by
partition walls. In the past, the summer residency show was
installed in roughly the same tripartite format. But the curator of
the 2000 edition, Thelma Golden, has mixed things together, letting
the work interact the way the artists themselves presumably did
while they shared quarters.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good idea. Individual voices are distinct, but they
amplify common themes. Nicole Awai, from Trinidad, is a figurative
painter with an unprettified technique and a metaphorical bent.
Colonialism and how it shaped the West Indies is her subject, built
up through overlaid images of tropical birds, wallpaper patterns,
antique prints and illustrations from the British-published
schoolbooks with which she grew up. Background and foreground in
her paintings keep shifting, which is a good way to think about
history.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Boddie, from Nevis in the eastern Caribbean, takes the
notion of cultural influence along other routes, back to Africa via
his childhood home. In a hushed blend of photography, paint, ink
and collage, he joins portraits of his family, pressed tropical
leaves, and near-abstract views of moving water to simulate psychic
time travel, with images alternately fading out and coming into
focus.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Biggers tackles cultural convergence with a wry, urban
energy, stirring art, politics and world religions together with
hip-hop culture. The Black Panthers, Dr. Dre and strange science
join forces in his sculpture titled ``The Chronicle,'' a giant Afro
pick with a raised fist for a handle and slides of ethnological
objects projected onto its surface. ``Mandala of the B-Bodhisattva
I'' is a Carl Andre-style floor piece assembled from brightly
colored institutional linoleum tiles silkscreened with
break-dancing versions of the Hindu god Shiva, Lord of the Dance.
</P>
<P>
   This mandala got some use as a dance floor during the ``Battle
of the Boroughs,'' a break-dance competition held in the Bronx this
summer. And a larger example appears in a collaboration between
Biggers and the artist David Ellis, who has used Duchampian
roto-relief patterns as break-dance pads. It includes a pocket-size
video of dancers in action, their acrobatic moves echoing the
circular designs on the tile floor. The video is framed by black
and white tiles with speckled patterns that evoke a night sky
filled with stars. At this point, Biggers, who received a master's
degree from the Art Institute of Chicago last year, is trying out
many ideas and formats, which is fine. He clearly has strength in
reserve, and the times are on his side. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bronx Museum of the Arts
</P>
<P>
   The Artist in the Marketplace program, now in its 20th year at
the Bronx Museum, is also a residency, but a short one (12 weeks)
for 36 participants. It is based on a seminar-style curriculum,
with dealers, critics, and museum curators advising on the ins and
outs of building a career. As a departing gift, the artists are
given a group show, organized this year by Lydia Yee and Edwin
Ramoran.
</P>
<P>
   Three dozen artists are about two dozen too many for the
allotted basement gallery. (All the upstairs spaces are occupied by
a historical survey of past graduates of the program.) With room
for only one or two entries a person, everyone gets the benefit of
the doubt, critically speaking, though some work does manage to
stand out.
</P>
<P>
   Figurative paintings and drawings can be self-contained enough
to survive such circumstances, and Amy Cutler's dream scenarios and
Reet Das' crisp black ink silhouettes of Hindu divinities hold the
wall. So do Richard Pasquarelli's abstract ``self-portraits'' made
of jigsaw puzzle shapes painted over photographs of the suburban
house where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Thyzel's ``Corporate Sculptures,'' made of office
construction materials and self-illuminated with light bulbs, have
potential, but they need to be punched up a bit, twisted somehow.
``Daemons,'' by Bruce Brosnan, on the other hand, looks witty as
is, with its lump-shaped cutout forms standing out from the wall
and repeated as painted ``shadows.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Jacobs' peephole installation about vermin and
pesticides is ingenious. And a Web site about race, class and
consumption by Tana Hargest, still under construction, looks
promising, with its promotion of a derma-patch drug called
Privitrol, which allows a user ``to discover the benefits of
privilege-free living.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's a trend to be isolated, it might be a light-touch
brand of text-based conceptualism involving charts, diagrams and
lists, often with personal meanings. Contributions by Marcus
Bjernerup, Sara Eichner, Daniel Seiple and Anton Sinkewich all
fall, in different ways, into this category, with Beth Campbell
being exemplary.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Campell is represented here, as she was in ``Greater New York,''
by an elaborate hand-annotated graphite flowchart titled ``My
Potential Future Based on Present Circumstances.'' In it she
details all the possible outcomes of certain personal and
professional choices, real and fictional, plotting them out as a
kind of wildly branching nervous system of hopes, fears, and
self-recriminations. Although Campbell was producing such drawings
before her Bronx residency, their fever-chart records of modest
triumphs and high anxieties are tailor-made for an
artist-in-the-marketplace occasion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   El Museo del Barrio
</P>
<P>
   ``The S-Files/The Selected Files'' is the baby among the summer
annuals; this is its second year. No residency is involved, but the
museum has always had a policy of reviewing slides sent in by
Latino artists born in the United States and Latin American artists
based in New York City. From recent submissions, the curators,
Deborah Cullen and Yasmin Ramirez, have culled work by 27 artists _
several of them past participants in the Bronx and Studio Museum
residencies _ and made a lively show.
</P>
<P>
   It has no overriding theme, and certain political and religious
images automatically tagged as Latino are absent, or at least
played down. The result isn't exactly a post-identity gathering,
but on the whole it does take an oblique, submerged approach to
social issues, exploring them by way of forms and materials.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, it's true, a Latino connection is right up front.
Domingo Nuno's elegant computer-manipulated ink-jet prints combine
watery patterns with racy love scenes from Spanish-language
fotonovelas, and Miguel Trelles' serigraphs have a skeletal Taino
shaman eying Jennifer Lopez and an Ingres odalisque.
</P>
<P>
   One might trace a Latin American baroque sensibility in Paul
Henry Ramirez's decorative abstractions, or in Fernanda Brunet's
draftsmanly clouds of volcanic smoke, but other readings are
equally valid. And while the show's many fabric-based pieces may
have distant roots in a tradition of textile industry labor, work
by H.A. Rodriguez-Mora, Juana Valdes, and Alejandro Diaz (whose
``Breakfast Tacos at Tiffany's'' is a standout) is interesting for
its intelligent and expressive riffs on Minimalism and Pop.
</P>
<P>
   In general, as Cullen and Ramirez argue in the show's slender
catalog, there is evidence that the hard ideological lines of the
1990's are growing more supple and elastic and weaving together in
new ways to refresh abiding concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Hand-altered photographs of Manuel Acevedo, a former Studio
Museum artist in residence and a participant in ``Greater New
York,'' are at once poetic conceptual fantasies and realizable
proposals for revivifying desolate urban landscapes. And a mural
drawing in the show by the artist who goes by the name
Vargas-Suarez Universal similarly unites divergent impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching across a wall, it resembles a statistical graph or an
EKG readout. But its contours, drawn in a solution of alcohol and
blood (the artist's), trace the outlines of two pieces in El
Museo's permanent collection by the influential Conceptualist
Rafael Montanez-Ortiz, who was among the museum's founders 30 years
ago and its first director.
</P>
<P>
   The mural is a complex homage by a young artist with a complex
story. Born in 1972 in Mexico City, Vargas-Suarez Universal majored
in astronomy and art history at the University of Texas. Last year
he was in the Bronx Museum's Art in the Marketplace program; this
year he was enrolled in a medical course at Mount Sinai hospital,
studying, among other things, blood analysis. His installations
incorporate architectural references, collaborative sound pieces,
scientific data pulled from the Internet and site-specific wall
drawings in various media, including ballpoint pen.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his colleagues, he is operating both deep inside
and way outside familiar, clearly marked categories. And the same
may be said of the ``alternative'' museums that, by giving artists
like him a platform, play such a seminal role in New York art.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the Studio: Artists in Residence 2000'' is at the Studio
Museum in Harlem, 144 W. 125th St., (212) 864-4500, through Sept.
17. ``Artist in the Marketplace: 20th Annual Exhibition'' is at the
Bronx Museum of the Arts, 1040 Grand Concourse, at 165th Street,
Morrisania, (718) 681-6000, through Oct. 15. ``The S-Files/The
Selected Files'' is at El Museo del Barrio, 1230 Fifth Ave., at
104th Street, Manhattan, (212) 831-7272, through Sept. 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
