<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DOT seeks data on airline delays
 &HT;    By Nancy Fonti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With hopes of easing the massive airline delays and
cancellations that have plagued travelers this summer,
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater is summoning the industry's
top executives and labor leaders to Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms, air traffic control delays and labor disruptions
at Chicago-based United Airlines, the nation's largest airline,
have caused the number of delays and cancellations to surge this
summer, as planes teem with more travelers than ever before.
Singling out United as the industry's worst culprit, Slater made
his remarks Wednesday at the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines Chairman and Chief Executive Leo Mullin will
attend the meeting with Slater on Monday, a spokesman for
Atlanta-based Delta said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're pleased that the DOT is looking at the issues, and we're
hoping for a productive meeting,'' said spokesman John Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines will handle more than 670 million passengers this year,
and the number will jump to 1 billion over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   While the DOT is limited in what it can do to improve service,
Slater hopes to get the industry talking about cancellations and
delays before the issue spins out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're straining the system right now with 650 million, 670
million, what do you do to ensure that the system can handle 1
billion?,'' Slater said.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT calls the airlines together from time to time to discuss
industry issues, but this is the first meeting this year to discuss
on- time performance and cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   United is in the middle of contract talks with its mechanics and
pilots unions. Some members of the pilots union have refused to
work overtime, disrupting schedules. In May only 56.6 percent of
the airline's flights arrived within 15 minutes of the scheduled
time, according to DOT statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has fared well in service rankings this year, reporting
comparatively good baggage and consumer complaint statistics to the
DOT. For the first six months of the year, Delta reported 4.34
mishandled baggage reports per 1,000 passengers, second-best in the
industry. It also had the second-lowest rate of consumer complaints
to the DOT.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT has not released flight delay statistics for June or the
first six months of the year because it is changing the computer
host that produces the data. Slightly more than 80 percent of
Delta's flights arrived on time in May, the best rate among major
carriers for that month.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
