<HEADER>
A4963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ADULT-STUDENTS-0820-C     08-17 1827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADULT-STUDENTS-0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLLEGES CHANGING TO MEET NEEDS OF OLDER STUDENTS
 &HT;    For Sunday, Aug. 20
 &HT;    Eds: 900&AMP; adds, with ADULT-SINCLAIR, ADULT-TYPICAL and
ADULT-STUDENTS-DATA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyle categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Millions of older college students are changing
higher education, even as it changes them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say 'college student' and most people think of an 18- or
19-year-old. That's because we have a cultural tradition in which
that marks the transition time from adolescence to adulthood,''
said Ken Foster of the University of Utah, who has written four
books on adult learners.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the average age of college students now is over 26, and
they take just over seven years to complete their education.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall, 42 percent of the students in the nation's colleges
and universities will be 25 or older, according to the Education
Department. That's up from 28 percent in 1980, before so many
working women began to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges compete vigorously to attract those 6.4 million older
college students, who are in the vanguard of more than 70 million
adults their age who will take some sort of job-related or personal
development class, seminar or workshop in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the deepest reason they enroll is a hunger for
learning,'' said Janice Gordon-Kelter of Houston, dean of special
programs at the University of St. Thomas, which offers a well-known
degree completion program for adults who have earned at least two
years of credits elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other big reason is, they've been laid off or seen others
promoted ahead of them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earning a degree at any age can pay off monetarily. Among adults
25 or older, a woman with a bachelor degree typically earns $12,141
more annually than a woman with a high school diploma. Among men,
the increase is $15,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they come in, they're often less secure because they've
been out of school for awhile,'' said Susan Robinson of Washington,
D.C., who heads the center for adult learning at the American
Council on Education. ``But they are actually more likely to become
stellar students.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they bring with them is a wealth of on-the-job, family
and community experience, maturity, perhaps the financial support
of their employer, and certainly an appreciation of the value of an
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Hamby(cq), who directs a degree completion program at
Abilene Christian University for 170 adults up to 72 years old,
said, ``We waste education on 18-year-olds, which I know because I
was once 18 myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He said older students ``absorb new information and theories
like sponges, but they'll challenge the socks off you if you don't
bring the theory down to a practical application at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Younger students often like the way the older ones bring life
experiences into class discussions,'' said Gabe DeGabriele of Grand
Junction, Colo., president of the Association for Non-Traditional
Students in Higher Education. Still, he said, some complain that
adults ``ruin the curve'' by acing tests or ``ask too many
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition for older students has forced many institutions
to re-evaluate traditions, including the five-course semester, dorm
rooms, long registration lines, ostentatious partying, and
all-night cramming for tests that require regurgitation of lecture
notes.
</P>
<P>
   To attract adults, some emphasize credit for life experiences
and flexible credit transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Others offer ``stop-out'' policies that retain potential
dropouts by letting a student whose course is interrupted by a
family emergency resume the course when it is offered again.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Denver's Women's College helps find cheap,
clean, safe hotel rooms for women from rural Colorado who take
weekend courses on its campus in Denver. It also offers them math
brush-up clinics, computer labs, a writing facility and a drop-in
center where they can chat with each other and the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Most colleges have decided that it would be too costly to
sponsor a day care center. But many offer parents a list of
respected providers or sponsor special children's events. In
Brunswick, Ga., for example, student activity fees at Coastal
Georgia Community College help pay for free family movies and for a
Saturday cookout at which a magician or other entertainer keeps
children occupied on campus while their parents use the library.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet helps some adults tuck lessons into niches in their
hectic days of balancing family, work and study. Pat Kapper, a vice
president at the profitable Career Education Corporation, which
offers degrees in 15 states, said, ``Older students also happen to
be disciplined learners (with) self-motivation, which makes them
perfect candidates for on-line or other distance-education
courses.''
</P>
<P>
   Even computer-phobic adults can schedule courses to suit
themselves, now that the University of Maryland offers some courses
by voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Non-traditional students tend to view things more from a
consumer standpoint, and their biggest concern is the impact on
their family in finances and time,'' DeGabriele said at Mesa State
College, where he counsels transfer students. ``The idea that a
professor would try to have his only office hours at an
inconvenient time, or that a bookstore or finance office wouldn't
be open on evenings or weekends can bug them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADDS FOLLOW)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Students re-entering college didn't always act like consumers,
according to Barbara Denison, associate dean for graduate and
continuing education at Lebanon Valley College in Annville, Pa.
Many used to see themselves as dropouts who ``waited to be assured
that they were still capable students who had now matured and could
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, she said, many act more like someone who is deciding
whether to hire the college to educate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, potential adult learners 'shop' their work experiences,
prior credits earned and anything else around to several schools,
trying to negotiate for the maximum allowable in transfer credits
and in experiential credits,'' Denison said. ``We are expected to
respond to requests for schedules tailor-made to one individual
student's needs (and) to eliminate any instructor whom students
don't feel is teaching what they want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   As director of the office of adult learning services in the New
York headquarters of the nonprofit College Board, Carol
Aslanian(cq) advises colleges to adjust to the reality that adult
students ``are savvy consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They shop around for exactly the course they want, they look
for a nearby classroom with easy in-and-out parking, and they are
relentless and persistent once they start to take a course,''
Aslanian said. ``Most want to learn stuff, not just pile up
credits, and they want to apply what they learn as fast as they
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Their impatience is understandable, said DeGabriele. They are
paying their own way and have ``a shorter remaining work-life''
than a 25-year-old in which to repay loans and earn more income
from their investment in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, convenience and lower cost are prime reasons why about
55 percent of adult students go to community colleges, which today
have campuses within less than an hour's drive of the vast majority
of U.S. homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adults are the most diverse students in higher education,''
said George Boggs, president of Palomar College, who will leave the
nine-campus California institution this fall to become president of
the American Association of Community Colleges in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an economic development and workforce training
mission, which benefits adults who want to change career
directions, recover from a downsizing or get a promotion,'' Boggs
said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he explained, ``We also have students who take a course at
a community college while attending a university, or come to us
during their university's summer break. Some others already have
earned their degree, but come back to learn the latest computer
software application or learn a foreign language in preparation for
a trip.''
</P>
<P>
   To meet the needs of those students, Palomar supplements its
traditional fall and spring semesters with ``fast-track eight-week
sessions, late-start and self-paced courses, on-line courses, TV
college, weekend college, and four-, six-, and eight-week summer
sessions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add, which can stand alone as a
sidebar, follows)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At National University, the third largest private university in
California, a one-course-a-month format is a major draw for its
all-adult student body. About 31 percent are minorities and 59
percent are women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students go to our facilities in the evening from 5:30 to 10
two nights a week for one month, concentrating on one course at a
time,'' said Thomas McCalla, vice president for student affairs at
National's main campus in San Diego. Each evening consists of four
hours of classes and a half-hour break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether they work in a supermarket or a law office, this is a
way to get fast results, especially for those who are working
full-time,'' McCalla said. Technology consultants and musicians
with occasional out-of-town jobs are among those who like the idea
of taking a course or two between jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Monique La Chappa, 35, who graduated from National in July, said
she worked full-time when she started 42 months ago. But she
switched to a half-time job after she fell asleep on a freeway and
ran into a roadside reflector on the 60-mile drive from San Diego
to her home on the reservation of the Campo Band of Kumeyaay(cq)
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 27 and taking four courses at a time at a community
college, I ended up dropping out, partly because I was overwhelmed
by all the homework, driving to and from the rez, day care hassles,
and no money,'' she said. ``But when I was taking just one course
at a time at National, a course was over before I was sick of it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her degree in business administration with a double
minor in human resources and finance ``has made my life better and
it's going to make my people's life better.'' But, she added, ``In
fairness, you'd better warn anyone who is thinking of doing this
that I also put 118,000 miles on my Toyota Tercel, and I'm $35,000
in debt.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Association for Non-Traditional Students in Higher Education:
www.antshe.org
</P>
<P>
   University Continuing Education Association: www.nucea.edu
</P>
<P>
   Association for Continuing Higher Education:
www.charleston.net/org/ache/
</P>
<P>
   American Association for Adult and Continuing Education:
www.cdlr.tamu.edu/tcall/aaace/
</P>
<P>
   Learning Resources Network: www.lern.org
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
