<SLUG> BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A convention reporter's notebook:
</P>
<P>
   Who says there's no place for religion in politics? Speaking to
the
</P>
<P>
   non-partisan American Jewish Committee, Rep. Rush Holt, a
freshman Democratic from New Jersey, said: ``without being too
partisan here, let me just say vote for the ticket that has the
Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Picking Joe Lieberman as the Democratic vice-presidential
</P>
<P>
   candidate is a healthy sign, according to Zafar Tahir, one of
three
</P>
<P>
   Muslim delegates to the Democratic National Convention from
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Tahir, a native of Pakistan who now lives in Houston, prayed at
the Texas delegation breakfast Thursday ``that this party of true
diversity can move together.''
</P>
<P>
   While some may think Muslims would not favor a Jew as vice
president because of tensions between the two religions in the
Middle East, Tahir said picking someone from a minority religion in
the United States is positive for Muslims because they also are in
the minority.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio state Sen. Rhine McLin, provided an unusual description of
</P>
<P>
   herself when she spoke to the Ohio delegation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a quadruple minority,'' said McLin: female, Democrat,
woman of color and mortician.''
</P>
<P>
   McLin, one person in the audience shouted, is ``the last to let
you down.''
</P>
<P>
   No podium, no TelePrompTer, no problem. At least that's the way
Sen. Max Cleland of Georgia described it Thursday after his speech
the night before honoring veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland, a triple amputee after a grenade blast in Vietnam,
wheeled onto the state with Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, a fellow
Vietnam vet, only to see that the podium and the teleprompters had
disappeared to make way for a filmed tribute.
</P>
<P>
   The setup ``left the city in a dangerous position _ me and Bob
Kerrey unleashed,'' Cleland joked. ``It was left to me to ad-lib
for only 40 million people.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a TelePrompTer 60 feet away under the media riser
flickered to life after the film clip, prompting Cleland to give
thanks that his staff picked ``the largest type font in the
universe'' for his speech.
</P>
<P>
   The gift shop at the downtown Marriott Hotel received a shipment
of new Beanie Babies this week, including the star-spangled ``Lefty
2000'' the donkey and ``Righty 2000'' the elephant. Lefty sold out
almost immediately. Righty lasted well into the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
