<SLUG> BC-UAL-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAL DOWNGRADES PROFIT FORECAST, CITING FLIGHT CANCELLATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UAL Corp., the parent of United Airlines, lowered its
third-quarter earnings estimate Thursday, citing the thousands of
canceled flights that have come amid a dispute with its pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also announced several initiatives to placate its
disgruntled passengers, including frequent-flier bonuses and
elimination of certain service fees.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Goodwin, UAL's chairman and chief executive, said in a
statement that the company expected third-quarter earnings to be
lower than the range of $2.60 to $3.20 a share announced on July
19, when it reported its second-quarter results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although booking patterns remained strong through early August
despite poor operating performance, booking levels have since
fallen on the adverse publicity surrounding the cancellations that
occurred in early August,'' Goodwin said. ``While our operating
performance has improved somewhat, the reduced booking levels
continue, and as a result, revenues are not as strong as we had
previously anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Harris, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, reduced his
third-quarter earnings estimate to $2.10 from $2.95, and his
fourth-quarter estimate to $1 from $1.35.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Buttrick, an analyst with PaineWebber, expects that United's
labor and operational problems will have a $250 million impact on
its third-quarter pretax profit. He lowered his third-quarter
estimate to $1.90 from $2.60, and his fourth-quarter estimate to 95
cents from $1.10.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the recent publicity, everyone who flies knows United
isn't a good choice,'' he said. ``Although operations have improved
in recent days, as a practical matter, the damage has been done.''
</P>
<P>
   But Buttrick said he did not expect that the airline's current
labor problems would permanently alienate passengers. ```The
airline business is fundamentally a network business,'' he said. ``
People choose United for its network, and that's not changed.''
</P>
<P>
   United's management and its pilots' union have been negotiating
a new contract since December 1998. With few signs of progress
seen, the pilots have been declining to work overtime.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of a shortage of pilots, as well as weather and air
traffic control problems, United said it completed only 90 percent
of its scheduled flights during the first two weeks of this month.
</P>
<P>
   United management and its pilots continued their discussions
this week after talks were recessed last Friday. Kathie White, a
spokeswoman for the union, said that although agreement had been
reached in some areas, ``the major issues remaining are big.'' She
said these included wages, benefits, working conditions and job
security.
</P>
<P>
   United declined to comment on the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The bonus frequent-flier mileage will be given to United's top
travelers. Frequent-flier program participants who fly between
25,000 and 50,000 miles a year will receive an additional 25
percent bonus for flights taken between May 1 and Dec. 31, while
those who fly more than that will receive an additional 100 percent
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   United also is waiving its regular $75 service fee for
passengers who change plans if their outbound flight is affected by
a delay or cancellation; passengers must travel before Sept. 30 and
return within seven days of their original return flight.
Passengers flying before Sept. 30 who choose to postpone their
travel may also do so without penalty; new travel must be completed
by March 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   AMR's American Airlines, United's archrival, said it was
evaluating United's bonus mileage offer, which was reported
Thursday in The Wall Street Journal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
