<SLUG> BC-BIOGEN-ELAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOGEN TO DISTRIBUTE IRISH FIRM'S DRUG FOR MS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biogen Inc., looking to strengthen its franchise of drugs to
treat multiple sclerosis as well as expand into new disease areas,
said Thursday it has licensed Antegren from Elan Corp. of Dublin,
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the agreement were not disclosed although
James C. Mullen, Biogen's chief executive told the Wall Street
Journal that the drug could generate at least $1 billion in annual
sales for multiple sclerosis. Biogen's current multiple sclerosis
drug is Avonex, an injectable medication that last year had
revenues of $619 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen said Antegren may be marketed to multiple sclerosis
patients who have not had satisfactory results with currently
available drugs, including Avonex. He said Antegren also has
``blockbuster potential in a variety of diseases,'' and could be
used in combination with Avonex to help a broader range of multiple
sclerosis patients.
</P>
<P>
   Elan is nearing the completion of a Phase II clinical trials of
Antegren in multiple sclerosis patients and has conducted separate
trials for Crohn's disease, the chronic inflammation of the
intestinal disease and a third illnesss, ulcerative colitis. For
Biogen, gaining a promising drug like Antegrin in later-stage
testing may ease Wall Street's concern that the company was too
dependent on Avonex with few signs of another major drug reaching
the market soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street knew Biogen was looking to get a late-stage drug,
but they wanted to something that could reach the market in the
next 18 months to two years, but Antegrin won't hit the market
until 2004,'' said Anthony C. Butler, biotechnology analyst for
Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Biogen hastily withdrew a Antova, a drug it hoped
would be used to treat hemophilia, lupus, kidney transplant
rejection and three other maladies, after some patients taking the
experimental medication developed blood clots.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company's next big hope after Avonex is Amevive, a
psoriasis treatment, which has shown impressive clinical trial
results in about two years Mullen said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, investor initial reaction was muted as the stock
closed at $70.25, up 25 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
