<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOL-(2T     08-17 1727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOL-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FAILURES AT ALBANY CHARTER SCHOOL, A CAUTIONARY TALE EMERGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Gov. George E. Pataki of New York visited the newly opened
New Covenant charter school in Albany last September, he lavished
it with praise, proclaiming it a model of the kind of educational
change he intended when he pushed a charter school bill through the
state Legislature nine months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In the months after Pataki's visit, however, New Covenant
descended into apparent chaos. Its fourth-graders scored among the
lowest in the state on standardized English tests; the
profit-making company overseeing the school's academic program
resigned; two principals came and went, as did one-fourth of the
school's 500 students.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Dare, founder of the school and president of the local
Urban League chapter, whom Pataki hailed during his visit as ``a
visionary,'' quit the New Covenant board after two state inquiries
accused him and the school of multiple violations of state
education law, including misappropriation of tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with three weeks to go before the start of the new school
year, state regulators have theatened to revoke the school's
charter, and it is uncertain if New Covenant will open again.
</P>
<P>
   How things went so wrong so quickly at New Covenant is a
cautionary tale for entrepreneurs and education reformers who are
tempted by the promise of charter schools, which have been hailed
around the country as one of the most promising solutions to the
problems plaguing public education, particularly in poor, minority
school districts in the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's 2,069 charter schools operate with public money but
are free of the control of local school districts. They are often
championed by conservatives and liberals alike, who see them as a
competitive alternative to troubled public schools because of their
ability to experiment with teaching methods and to hire nonunion
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   That such a spectacular failure could occur practically in
Pataki's back yard, at a school in which he took a close interest,
speaks of the difficulties _ in oversight, administration and
academic achievement _ that face even the most trailblazing schools
and educators.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics contend, however, that New Covenant's failures were
not simply a result of bad luck but rather a direct result of an
unnecessary rush last year by Pataki, a vocal champion of charter
schools, and his political appointees to open schools without time
for adequate planning and training. New Covenant received its
initial approval a mere three months before it opened.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, 79 charter schools, or about 4 percent of
the charter schools started in the last nine years, have already
shut their doors, though many others seem to have established a
successful foothold, including two New York City charter schools
that opened at the same time as New Covenant: the Sisulu Children's
Academy and the John A. Reisenbach school, both in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Morris, a spokeswoman for Pataki, said the state's
review process for new charter schools, including New Covenant, was
very thorough. And while no one expected things to go as wrong as
they did at New Covenant, she said, ``the governor does not believe
this particular situation is a reflection on the future of charter
schools,'' which he believes is ``quite positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dare could not be reached for comment. But Ward DeWitt,
co-chairman of New Covenant's board, said he was confident that New
Covenant would open in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the board asked state authorities to allow Edison
Schools of Manhattan, the country's largest profit-making operator
of public schools, to replace Advantage Schools, a Boston-based
education company, as manager of New Covenant's academic programs
in the coming year. Edison has hired Eleanor Bartlett, a member of
the state's Board of Regents, as principal of the school, and
Bartlett resigned from the Regents post to take the job.
</P>
<P>
   But before the school can open, charter school regulators at the
State University of New York, the state Education Department and
the Board of Regents must once again hastily review Edison's
proposed academic program, in even less time than last year.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Edison and the newly reconstituted school
board will be able to correct the faults detailed by two regulatory
panels, which issued their independent reports within a week of
each other in late July and early August. A team of observers from
the Education Department, which visited New Covenant near the end
of the school year, found ``serious violations of law and of the
school's charter,'' its report said, including inadequate academic
programs, building code violations and missing and unaccounted for
students. The report said the school's facilities ``appeared to be
very run-down'' and overcrowded, with some classes being conducted
in hallways, where carpets were mended with duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   A separate review by the State University of New York, which
granted the school its charter, found many of the same problems, as
well as a lack of financial controls and conflicts of interest
among school board members, many of whom were also affiliated with
the Urban League and some of whom were relatives of Dare's. One
board member was his aunt and another was his stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   Even Pataki, speaking last week on an Albany radio program, said
he had ``reservations'' about the school's ability to reopen next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest victims of New Covenant's problems are the 360
children who made it through the school's first year. Most have
said they intend to re-enroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``This school really was the result of a grass-roots effort that
was pushed by the community,'' DeWitt said. ``People here were
looking for a bona fide choice to move their children's education
along. With that kind of momentum, it would have been hard to tell
them to wait for a more deliberate process.''
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, there were signs that the approval process
was being rushed and that problems were on the horizon. In June
1999, shortly after the SUNY trustees approved a September opening
for New Covenant and the two charter schools in New York City,
questions were raised about whether the trustees had given adequate
legal notice and a chance for public comments by the Albany City
School District. Because charter schools draw their funding from
local school districts, those districts are entitled by law to have
a voice in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The SUNY trustees voted again in July 1999 to approve the
school, but the next month the Board of Regents raised objections,
questioning whether the school's temporary facilities in a group of
trailers were adequate and expressing concern that the school would
draw too much money out of the Albany public schools. Because of
political compromises that forged the charter school law, the
Regents cannot prevent a SUNY-approved school from opening, but
they have do have advisory powers.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Wilson, the chief executive of Advantage Schools, said
inadequate facilities were among the primary problems with the
school. ``We knew our program couldn't successfully operate in that
building,'' Wilson said. In its application, the school's sponsors,
including Dare, said a permanent site would be ready in
mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   By then, however, the Urban League was having financial
difficulties that were beginning to weigh on New Covenant's
operations. The school leased its temporary space from a
profit-making subsidiary of the Urban League known as the Commons,
and last year, the Commons also was in financial trouble. It had
made a $2 million unsecured loan to a financial company for which
it was constructing an office building, but in December, that
company collapsed. At the same time, an Albany construction company
that had performed work on the trailers being used by the school
was demanding payment.
</P>
<P>
   According to an inquiry conducted for the SUNY trustees by
Richard J. Bartlett, a lawyer in Glens Falls, N.Y., in December
Dare forwarded state education dollars that were supposed to be
paid to Advantage to the construction company on behalf of the
Commons, an act that Bartlett said violated Dare's fiduciary duty
to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett wrote in his report that while Dare's actions did not
``rise to the level of criminal conduct,'' Dare should either
resign from the school's board or be removed. Early this month,
Dare resigned, although he told the Times Union of Albany that the
move was not related to Bartlett's report.
</P>
<P>
   Following Dare's resignation, several other directors also
resigned, and the school's board has been substantially
reconstituted.
</P>
<P>
   Willard Washburn, co-chairman of the board, said Pataki's office
expressed interest in New Covenant and Advantage throughout the
last school year. Top Advantage officials and Dare had first talked
about establishing the charter school after being introduced by
Lisa O'Brien, an Advantage executive who previously worked as a
midlevel aide in the Pataki administration. In an interview,
O'Brien said her work for the Pataki administration was
coincidental to Advantage's selection as the operator of the
school.
</P>
<P>
   If the SUNY trustees act on New Covenant's charter amendment in
the next three weeks, the Board of Regents can perhaps clear the
way for the school to open late next month.
</P>
<P>
   Edison has pledged more than $3 million toward the construction
of a $10 million building for the school.
</P>
<P>
   Others have expressed less certainty about whether the school
can open in the fall. Among the Education Department's concerns was
the performance of the school's fourth-graders on the standardized
English test. Only 9 percent of New Covenant students met or
exceeded the state standard, among the worst performance by any
school in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Sanders, a Democrat who is chairman of the Assembly
Education Committee, said he believed that New Covenant's failures
can be traced back to the accelerated approval process.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Covenant is a case study of how not to do a charter
school,'' Sanders said. ``The failure, in my judgment, was in SUNY
and the governor trying to accelerate the approval process when it
really needed more time. The results speak for themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
