<HEADLINE>
VINTAGE CARS OFFER MILEAGE AT AUCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.) (Eds: ``Historics'' in graf 4 is cq; ``saloon'' in grafs 8 and 14
is cq.) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you are selling 800 vintage, classic and antique sports
cars in one place, you are bound to come across a big party or two.
</P>
<P>
   Nonstop festivities are planned around the car sales in Pebble
Beach, Calif., this weekend, and auction houses, car manufacturers,
restoration shops and car clubs expect at least 20,000 people from
all over the world. The gathering will be as glamorous as (or more
glamorous than) the one at the Democratic National Convention, with
entertainment stars, dot-com billionaires and business tycoons in
attendance. As Bing Crosby once said of his own golf tournament at
Pebble Beach, ``It's going to be a great clambake.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend concludes the Monterey Historics Week, with car
rallies, auctions, the Concours d'Elegance (a display, on the golf
course, of vintage cars, which are judged according to body design,
restoration work and originality), and various races at a track at
nearby Laguna Seca.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Morris, the head of Christie's car department in New York,
said, ``Winning Pebble Beach is undoubtedly the most prestigious
competition in car judging in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Car collecting may be changing. Once many people bought elegant
vintage cars simply to admire them in their garages. They formed
clubs like the Horseless Carriage Club, organized by Los Angeles
car enthusiasts in 1937, to swap gossip and restoration tips about
cars made before 1916. (The club's Web site address is
horseless.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, famous car collectors like Jerry Seinfeld, Jay Leno, Ralph
Lauren, Nicolas Cage and the cellular communications billionaire
Bruce McCaw buy racing cars to drive. ``The vast majority use their
cars on the road on a regular basis,'' said Robert Brooks, the
founder of the England-based Brooks Auctioneers. On Saturday,
Brooks is to conduct his third annual California sale _ 73 vintage,
classic and antique autos _ at the Quail Lodge Resort and Golf Club
in Carmel, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are seriously important cars,'' he said. The sale
includes Mary Pickford's 1962 Rolls-Royce Silver Cloud II saloon,
Pope Pius XII's 1936 Cadillac V16 Series 90 Ceremonial Town Car by
Fleetwood, and a classic prewar racing car, a 1936 Alfa Romeo 8C
2900A short-chassis Botticella Grand Prix winner, which is being
sold to raise money to preserve the Brazilian rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Botticella is the be-all and end-all of pre-World War II
sporting cars,'' said Paul Clark, managing director of Brooks USA.
Only four short-chassis models were made, all built to race.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's International Motor Cars is conducting its 11th
annual ``Exceptional Motor Cars'' sale on Sunday at the Pebble
Beach Equestrian Center. This sale, which begins at 6 p.m. Pacific
time, will have a live Webcast (www.christies.com), so interested
collectors around the world can participate.
</P>
<P>
   The sale includes the car collection of the late Denver lumber
magnate Robert D. Sutherland, which features several prewar
American and European racing cars and has a sales estimate of $5
million, and 50 classic cars from the collection of Matt and
Barbara Browning of the Browning firearms family.
</P>
<P>
   For the 15th year, the Monterey Sports Car Auction will hold its
sales in Monterey, Calif., at the Doubletree Hotel Friday night and
Saturday. This sale has 135 vintage cars, reasonably priced.
</P>
<P>
   The only great car missing in California is one that will be
sold on Sept. 27 in New York in the William Doyle sale of property
from the estate of James Cagney. The Doyle sale is not a car sale,
but it does include Cagney's elegant 1961 green Bentley S2
four-door saloon.
</P>
<P>
   Cagney, who won an Academy Award for his role in ``Yankee Doodle
Dandy'' in 1942, played a race car driver in the 1932 film ``The
Crowd Roars.'' His Oscar is displayed in the Brooks tent with an
announcement about the September sale.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is making a push to penetrate the antique-car market in
America. He founded Brooks Auctioneers in England in 1989 after
working for 14 years at Christie's in London. The son of a
legendary London auctioneer, Brooks took over Christie's motor car
department in 1977. In 1989, after organizing a Christie's car sale
in Monte Carlo that brought in $33.4 million, he asked to be put on
Christie's international board.
</P>
<P>
   His request was denied, and he left Christie's to start Brooks.
``We are the biggest specialist auctioneers of motor cars in the
world,'' he said. ``Last year we did 33 auctions in nine
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks conducts sales of what he calls ``mechanical
antiquities'' _ that is, motor cars, motorcycles, automobilia,
aeronautica, mechanical toys and watches. Last year he reported car
sales of $46 million. ``We sell 800 to 1,000 cars per year,'' he
said. ``We have 40 percent of the U.K. market. But the U.S. is the
home of motorcar collecting. In America the competition is fierce.
It's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks neither buys nor restores cars. ``At the end of the day,
the owner is selling the car,'' Brooks said. ``We might polish it,
but we don't fix it. And we don't do third-party auctions. We only
act as an agent for people who want to sell their cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's normally doesn't buy cars, either, but in Carmel it
will sell at least one it owns: a 1908 Rolls-Royce Silver Ghost
Landaulette made for Lord Dundas of Dundas Castle in Scotland. It
was built to be especially quiet; hence the name Silver Ghost. (And
it was made by C.S. Rolls, Henry Royce and Claude Johnson, a
founder of the Royal Automobile Club.) ``It's one of the earliest
Silver Ghosts ever built, and it's one of the most important of the
early ones,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   Car auctions are not like sales of impressionist paintings.
``This is a market that, to a degree, is event- or club-driven,''
Brooks said. ``Many sales are set at racing sites. In Carmel,
everyone shows up for the Monterey Historic Automobile Races, one
of the top races in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a great believer in the importance of sale venues,'' he
added. ``With motorcars, it's London, Gstaad, Geneva, Monte Carlo
and Carmel.'' Brooks' December sale, which is held at the Palace
Hotel in Gstaad, Switzerland, consists entirely of Ferraris. ``The
sale is part of the social season. People are attracted to the
location.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 20,000 expected at the Concours d'Elegance, 2,000 will
attend the sales. Clark said 700 to 1,000 people register to bid in
Brooks' California sale. Of these, at least 150 will bid.
Information: (831) 620-1950.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone can appreciate a car, no matter what sector of
society you come from,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks remarked, ``The beauty of motor cars is the third
dimension, the movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, who still races his own cars, observed, ``Cars appeal to
the little child in all of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
