<HEADLINE>
IF AT FIRST YOU DON'T SUCCEED, CELEBRATE! 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 20) 
 By ABBY ELLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a concept for a reality TV show that is sure to knock
'em dead: ``Who Wants to Be a Failure?''
</P>
<P>
   It would work like this: Put a dozen young entrepreneurs on a
perilous island _ say, Manhattan _ and equip them only with
millions of dollars in venture capital. Set up Webcams to watch
their offices around the clock and tell them to start dot-com
companies. Over two years, America gets to witness their trials and
tribulations: The caffeine-fueled all-night brainstorming sessions,
the aching trauma of wooing investors, the bare-knuckled struggle
to make sure each employee gets his own nap area.
</P>
<P>
   The contestant who tanks his company first wins, yes, $1
million, plus a zippy new motorized scooter and a copy of the
play-at-home game.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, failure has come to mean triumph. These days, it seems, the
way to prove that you're a real pioneer is to sink somebody else's
$125 million into a half-baked online venture, attract huge
attention and only then discover that, oops, you're in a little
over your head. Cratering is a sign that you're in the core of the
culture, that you're clicking on the brass mouse.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always so, of course. Failure used to connote repo
men and leaving town in the dead of night to escape the
disapproving stares of neighbors. Today, it's a rite of passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure is the price of being on the bleeding edge, on the
forefront of something you take pride in,'' said Gretchen Rubin,
author of ``Power, Money, Fame, Sex'' (Pocket Books). ``In the
past, you would have never wanted to be branded a failure, but now
it shows you're creative, a risk taker. Entrepreneurship is the
greatest virtue these days _ it's what everybody praises.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, it is much easier to rebound from failure in these
boom times than it would be during a recession. Jobtrak.com, which
monitors job postings at colleges, reported that the number of
openings for new college graduates rose by 40.8 percent this year.
So who cares if your job evaporates? Another is always just around
the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Failure chic has spawned a cottage industry of failurenalia.
Academics are writing books about failing. The VH-1 and E!
Entertainment cable channels have shown programs about it. An
Internet marketing firm called Thehiredguns.com sponsors pink-slip
parties where casualties can get together and ``dot-commiserate.''
</P>
<P>
   How better to capitalize on the trend than with a Web site? A
flock of pages have appeared, from failuremag.com and
dotcomfailures.com (motto: ``Kick 'em when they're down!'') to a
few with unprintable names.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purpose is to take the stigma away from failing,'' said
Nicholas Hall, 30, the chief executive of Startupfailures.com, a
three-month-old online community for people in the throes of
dot-com angst.
</P>
<P>
   Hall ought to know. He ran no fewer than three companies into
the ground before starting his latest site. Rather than sit around
lamenting, he published an inspirational book for peers in need of
a pick-me-up and hit the lecture circuit to share his insights on
going bust. ``What people call failure,'' he said, ``I choose to
call an experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Sewell, chief executive of Despair Inc., which runs
despair.com and sells ``demotivational'' products like ``Failure!''
T-shirts, says young people, especially, are no longer ashamed of
failing. ``It has been properly recognized as a natural and
understandable consequence of taking risks _ in business, in
research, in relationships,'' he said. ``The biggest risks most
often end in the biggest failures. But I think our culture admires
a risk taker who fails more than a coward who never succeeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Or better still, a risk taker who fails and then succeeds _ like
Sewell, who followed a ``frustrating and demoralizing'' experience
at an Internet service provider by starting his current venture,
which he said will gross $1 million in online sales this year.
</P>
<P>
   Here, then, are some failure do's and don'ts. First, be sure to
fail big. ``It makes you more important in the world,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   But do not remain a failure for long. You must work and rework
your magic to show the world that your last setback was simply the
fault of bad timing, bad forecasts or bad luck, not any flaw in
you.
</P>
<P>
   Above all else, never, ever disappear. Invisibility is a fate
worse than failure _ which is precisely what I won't do once my TV
show does. After the Letterman appearances dwindle and the
magazines stop hailing me as a visionary, I'll pen a motivational
book full of my insights and experiences. I'll call it ``You'll
Never Eat Lunch Online Again.'' I'm sure it will sell in the
millions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
