<HEADER>
A4977 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WEEKEND-TV18-COX     08-17 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEEKEND-TV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weekend TV preview
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``History's Lost &AMP; Found'' (8 p.m. on the History Channel) _
Featured: Elvis Presley's letter to President Nixon, offering his
help in the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Chris Rock Show'' (Midnight on HBO) _ Rock, who's hotter
these days than a cheap portable hair dryer, is back with his
series that combines stand-up and chat. Tonight's guest: comedian
Bernie Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Cindy Margolis Show'' (10 p.m. on WHOT) _ Blonde
bombshell, model, Howard Stern guest and occasional actress,
Margolis allegedly is ``Queen of the Internet'' for her high
download status. Now she launches her own syndicated series, a sort
of talk/gawk show, taped in Miami's South Beach. It will have
music, dancing, games, stand-up comedy, D-list celebrities and a
``Webkini'' contest, where girls come onstage in bikinis and
viewers vote on the Web for their favorite at www.cindymargolis
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Last One Standing: Nebraska.'' (8 p.m. on USA,) _ Twelve
people in a farming community try to win a tractor by standing and
keeping one hand on it until everyone else has dropped out. Kind of
a mini-``Survivor.'' Very mini.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Secret World of Fame and Fortune'' (10 p.m. on the
Learning Channel, 874020) _ Madonna's personal party-planner is
interviewed. This was going to air on cable network E! but was
turned down for being too lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Bud Greenspan's Favorite Stories of Olympic Glory'' (10 p.m.
on Showtime, 447204) _ Greenspan is the Ken Burns of the Olympics,
which means he deserves great credit for what he's done as an
exhaustive documentarian, and if you've seen very much of his work,
you sometimes find yourself wishing that someone with a new
approach would come along.
</P>
<P>
   For this run-up to the Sydney Games, Greenspan looks back
instead of forward and retells the stories of gymnast Nadia
Comaneci, decathlete Dan O'Brien, swimmer Duncan Armstrong,
marathoner Abebe Bikila and Greco-
</P>
<P>
   Roman wrestler Alexander Karelin.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Deal
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``High Noon'' (8 p.m. Sunday on TBS)
</P>
<P>
   On the off chance you're unaware, there was another film called
``High Noon,'' a 1952 release with Gary Cooper and Grace Kelly that
won four Oscars. Because it's so easy to slam remakes of classics,
I pretended I've never seen the original, which is harder than it
sounds. (The old ``Don't think of a green elephant'' bit.)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Skerritt stars as Will Kane, sheriff of a small town in the
Old West who's marrying a Quaker (Susanna Thompson) and promising
to give up his dangerous job. On Kane's wedding day, old nemesis
Frank Miller (Michael Madsen) comes to town on the noon train to
kill Kane. Torn between his vow to his new wife and his code of
honor, Kane decides to stay and fight, but can't get anyone in town
to back him up.
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple story, almost too short for two hours, so there
are subplots that don't work as well as the main narrative. The
clock keeps ticking (and I kept looking at my watch) until Madsen
arrives toward the end, and oh, is he bad. He just gets off the
train and squints, and that's all he has to do, 'cause he's Michael
Madsen (Mr. Blonde in ``Reservoir Dogs'').
</P>
<P>
   While Skerritt here is of the Kris Kristofferson jaw-clinching
school of acting, Thompson, who plays ex-wife Karen Sammler on
ABC's ``Once and Again,'' is memorably intense. If only this movie
were.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
