<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday Aug. 18 and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CONVENTION (Los Angeles) _ Stepping into a moment that
could make or break his presidential ambitions, Al Gore took his
case directly to a skeptical America in a speech that was laden
with policy details, partisan jabs and personal asides. Gore's
goal, in what is universally viewed as the most important speech of
his life, is to imprint himself on voters and declare his
independence from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Pope. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ANALYSIS (Los Angeles) _ Over the past half-century,
America's fall presidential campaigns have resembled less a
come-from-behind horse race, and more a hydroplane race in which
one boat stays ahead from starting line to checkered flag. Not
since 1960, when Richard Nixon had a wafer-thin lead over John F.
Kennedy, has a candidate ahead in the polls on Labor Day lost the
November election. Vice President Al Gore has run behind Texas Gov.
George W. Bush in opinion surveys for most of the year. Gore faces
a narrow post-convention window of attention in which to
reintroduce himself before public attention gets diverted to the
Olympics and World Series.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING (Seattle) _ The Boeing Co. met with the Internationl
Aeromachinists Union and outlined its plan to close two small
plants and shift about 1,000 workers in the Puget Sound region.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PGA (Louisville, Ky.) _ A dog-bites-man story: Tiger Woods
leads (tied, actually) after the first round of the PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ What's going wrong with the Mariners,
who head out on the road with a five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   By John Hickey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-THIEL-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Column on the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CELL (Undated) _ Hollywood's latest serial-killer thriller,
``The Cell,'' is a visually impressive but exceedingly unpleasant
little nail-biter about a child psychologist who uses some new
virtual-reality gizmo that allows her to enter the subconscious
mind of her patients. You may find a better way to spend an
hour-and-a-half.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GODZILLA (Undated) _ To most American viewers, the Japanese
Toho Godzilla films will never be more than exercises in camp. In
this age of computer-generated images, who's going to take a man in
a rubber suit stomping on toy trucks and miniature cities
seriously? Perhaps that's the only thing audiences will embrace in
``Godzilla 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   By Sean Axmaker. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CECIL (Undated) _ A spoof of independent filmmaking at its
most absurdly radical (and contradictory) fringe, ``Cecil B.
Demented'' affectionately lampoons both Hollywood and guerrilla
cinema in a bizarre revision of the Patty Hearst story.
</P>
<P>
   By Sean Axmaker. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STEAL (Undated) _ Hollywood movies of the '80s and '90s
have tended to be very hard on the student protesters of the '60s,
invariably portraying them as self-indulgent, dope-smoking cowards
who spit on the flag and didn't have the guts to fight in Vietnam.
Robert Greenwald's ``Steal This Movie'' balances this ledger
somewhat with an unashamedly positive look at the rise of the '60s
counterculture in terms of a mostly admiring chronicle of the life
of one of its most notorious figures: Abbie Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
