<HEADER>
A4980 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BEAR-PROBLEMS0818-COX     08-17 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAR-PROBLEMS0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As bear sightings increase, so do problems
 &HT;    By Marija Vader and Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ It's fitting that a baby bear would make
its debut in town on the same day as Rifle High School's
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The Rifle High School mascot is the bears.
</P>
<P>
   A hungry baby bear stopped traffic along the bridge leading into
Rifle, as well as along Highway 6 &AMP; 24 Thursday afternoon. The
animal was one of a growing group of bears that is pouring down
into Western Colorado valleys from the high country, were a
late-spring frost and summer drought have killed most of the bear's
normal food supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Junction office of the Colorado Division of Wildlife
has received, on average, seven reports of bear sightings per day
for the past several weeks, said district wildlife manager Joe
Gumber. So far this summer his office has tranquilized and
relocated 14 bears. In the Roaring Fork Valley, wildlife officers
have tranquilized and relocated five bears this summer, including a
sow and her two cubs, said Pat Tucker, Glenwood Springs area
wildlife manager for the Colorado Division of Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   In Rifle Thursday, the baby bear swam into the muddy Colorado
River from the north bank, nabbed a fish and headed back to shore
for lunch while about a hundred people lined the highway to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's being boneheads,'' said Rifle Police Chief Daryl
Meisner, trying to shoo people from the scene. ``If they'd quit
being boneheads, the bear would be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   To Meisner's view, the bear was trapped on two sides by adoring
humans and on a third side by the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already stressed from a lack of food in the high
country,'' Meisner said. ``If it's pressed, it will be more
stressed. This isn't a zoo bear. This isn't a zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the main problems right now, Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole situation is turning into a real sight-seeing,
people issue,'' Tucker said. ``Obviously it's intriguing, it's
neat, it's an animal you don't get to see all the time, but people
are starting to become the problem with their actions. People
prevent bears from trying to get out of an area.''
</P>
<P>
   He said in the past week there was an incident of a bear up a
tree in Aspen with people underneath it throwing rocks at it, and
of a little girl trying to pet a bear cub at the Grizzly Creek rest
area.
</P>
<P>
   The bears, too, are becoming bolder, wandering into busy Grand
Junction neighborhoods and downtown Glenwood Springs. Thursday
morning residents of IHS Mantey Heights nursing home saw a bear
walking by their windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing at the nursing station when people came running
up and said I had to look outside,'' said Valerie Tabor, a dietary
manager at Mantey Heights. ``I went up the the window and saw a
bear casually walking along, going up to the canal. Yesterday
morning it was in the grassy part right in front of the parking lot
upstairs, looking in the dining room.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said he is concerned that bears will keep coming into the
valleys, and in larger numbers, going into fall because bears start
coming from greater distances to historic fall feeding areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are heavy oak brush acorn areas and we're worried that
those areas may have gotten a freeze earlier this summer or that
the dry weather has prevented the acorns from maturing,'' he said.
``If bears move into historic fall feeding areas and they don't
find anything to eat, they know they've got to find something to
eat because winter time's coming on. That's going to take them into
wider and wider areas, lower and lower into the valleys where
theoretically there's more food, and more people.''
</P>
<P>
   Tranquilizing and relocating bears that come into populated
areas and become a nuisance is a last resort, Tucker said. The
Colorado Division of Wildlife currently is focusing on educating
residents of areas where bears are coming into, asking them to seal
up trash, pet food, bird feeders, barbecue grills and other items
whose smell attracts bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our time is far better spent getting the problem solved once
and for all by getting people to make an area less attractive to
bears,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   If a bear is caught and relocated, it gets an ear tag and lip
tattoo so wildlife officers will recognize it if it comes back into
populated areas and becomes a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   Bears get two strikes, so wildlife officers recently have had to
kill several bears on their second strike. Tuesday wildlife
officers destroyed a bear that originally was caught Saturday in
Palisade and on Tuesday came into Silt and became a nuisance,
Gumber said. Wildlife officers from Glenwood Springs have had to
destroy two bears so far this summer, one that was captured near
Vail and relocated above Ruedi Reservoir and one that was trapped
in Aspen, taken south of New Castle and went into New Castle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just inundated with bear issues this summer,'' Tucker
said, ``and we're worried that the problems are going to continue
and even intensify.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
