<SLUG> BC-RETIRE-401-PLANS-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
  
 READY OR NOT, WELCOME TO THE 401(k) PLAN  
(For release Sunday, Aug. 20) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EVE TAHMINCIOGLU    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Margaret Fuller, manager of profit sharing at 7-Eleven Inc., is
proud that three-quarters of the company's nearly 15,000 eligible
employees now participate in its 401(k) retirement savings plan.
Three years ago, only half had signed up.
</P>
<P>
   The big increase wasn't caused by a surge in the company's
matching contribution or a change in the plan's investment
offerings. All it took was a bow to human nature.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of leaving it up to employees to complete enrollment
forms and return them _ and having many of them procrastinate or
shy away _ 7-Eleven started enrolling employees automatically on
the first anniversary of their hiring; only those who want to opt
out of participation needed to lift a finger.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Dallas, is one of about 50 large
corporations that have begun automatic enrollment in recent years,
as many other employers waited for the federal government to take a
stand on the practice. Last month, however, regulators in two
federal departments gave it a solid go-ahead, and the Internal
Revenue Service announced several rulings clarifying the
automatic-enrollment ground rules for businesses, nonprofit
organizations and school systems.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, Labor Secretary Alexis Herman and Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers said they saw automatic enrollment as a
``promising method of encouraging participation by those who
disproportionately have been missing the benefits of a regular,
disciplined approach to retirement saving,'' meaning the many
younger and lower-paid workers who put off saving for retirement
because they feel they cannot spare any of their pay.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, experts say, most people cannot afford not to
contribute to the plans. Even if the current Social Security system
is maintained indefinitely, the dwindling of traditional,
defined-benefit pension plans means that few workers can count on a
financially secure retirement without putting aside money of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt Associates, a benefits research firm in Lincolnshire,
Ill., estimates that three-fourths of eligible American workers are
enrolled in 401(k) plans. But that still leaves millions of
Americans without any retirement savings program.
</P>
<P>
   David Wray, president of the Profit Sharing/401(k) Council of
America in Chicago, said he expected the number of companies using
automatic enrollment to double annually for the next five years,
and that more than half of all plans would use the method by 2005.
In addition, the new IRS rulings make it possible to automatically
enroll all workers, not just new hires, in 401(k) plans and their
close cousins, 403(b)'s (for public schools and charities) and
457(b)'s (for state and local government workers).
</P>
<P>
   In automatic enrollment, the initial percentage of pay to be set
aside is left to the employer's discretion. (7-Eleven's plan sets
aside 3 percent of gross pay, a typical rate, and the company
matches employee contributions at 36 cents on the dollar.)
</P>
<P>
   Employers also decide how the money will initially be invested.
According to Mark Iwry, the benefits tax counsel for the Treasury
Department, employers are encouraged to put savings of automatic
enrollees into a balanced fund, rather than a more risky stock fund
or a low-return money market fund. ``The plans are typically very
careful in the investments they select for employees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once enrolled, employees are generally free to select different
rates and investment vehicles according to plan rules.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of 7-Eleven shows that automatic sign-up can go a
long way toward closing the enrollment gap for lower-paid employees
_ an important issue for all participants, because federal rules
sharply restrict benefits for top earners if too few of their
lower-paid co-workers take part.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some critics wonder whether herding uninterested workers
into the plans accomplishes much in the long run. ``The government
is leading the horse to water, but they haven't focused on teaching
them to want to drink,'' said Ric Edelman, an author and financial
planner in Fairfax, Va. He cited Hewitt statistics showing that
fewer than one-third of people who leave jobs with 401(k)'s roll
over the money into individual retirement accounts; the remainder
simply pocket _ and pay taxes on _ the cash payout from the plans.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts worry that automatic enrollees will be too
passive as savers. In a study of one company's workers, the
National Bureau of Economic Research in Cambridge, Mass., found
that most left their starting contribution rates unchanged and
never moved out of the low-yielding money market fund in which the
company put them.
</P>
<P>
   But Leslie Kramerich, an acting assistant labor secretary, said
it was most important that the workers become savers in the first
place. ``Once they get started, then we can tackle whether they're
too conservative or too cautious,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting more workers involved in 401(k)'s makes the plans more
effective as morale builders, employers say. Ben Goldstein,
director of strategic human resource planning for Primex
Technologies, an aerospace company in St. Petersburg, Fla., said
that when his company's workers receive their quarterly 401(k)
statements and see the 50 percent matching contribution from the
company, they are more motivated to stay on. ``It's like free
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, before Primex started using automatic enrollment,
about 35 percent of workers took part in the plan; now four-fifths
do, Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some workers who are automatically enrolled in 401(k)
plans ought to opt out, because even plans with generous matching
rates are not the best choice for everyone, experts say. Lower-paid
people in their 20s and 30s may be better off putting their limited
resources toward a down payment on a first home or paying off debts
like college loans, said Robert Clark, professor of business and
economics at North Carolina State University. And union officials
say that however advantageous the plans might be, some of their
members genuinely cannot spare the money.
</P>
<P>
   If workers decide to leave automatic-enrollment plans after the
deductions have already begun from their paychecks, they face the
same early-withdrawal penalties that other 401(k) members do: 10
percent of the balance, plus income tax. But Fuller of 7-Eleven
said few workers had complained about being unwittingly swept into
the company's plan. ``When they get the statement at the end of the
quarter,'' she said, ``they're usually very happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
