<HEADLINE>
SURFER DUDES IN MALIBU SAY GORE'S THEIR MAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ One hour's drive physically and several light
years mentally from the barricaded fortress of the Democratic
National Convention, choppy waves six feet high were pounding the
beach yesterday at the Malibu Lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome!'' said the convention's official surf instructor,
Israel ``Izzy'' Paskowitz.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't talking about the surf.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about the Democratic Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the beaches, where the only controversy usually involves
the proper strength of sunscreen, Southern California is enthralled
with environmental guru Al Gore and his sidekick, Joe Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Paskowitz pasted a bumper sticker on his surfboard: ``Gore
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a little crud over it,'' said Paskowitz, one of
nine siblings who run the San Clemente, Calif.-based Paskowitz Surf
School. ``Some surfers want us all to be non-partisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's time for surfers to do the right thing. It's time to
elect somebody who will do the job well.''
</P>
<P>
   Half American Jew, half Latino _ his mother is from Durango,
Mexico _ Paskowitz is among those Democrats who instantly gained
interest when they heard Lieberman's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not put him in there?'' Paskowitz asked. ``Let's do things
differently from the last 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he is so ``stoked'' about the convention that he taught
a surf school for reporters Saturday at Santa Monica Beach. Twelve
showed up, including reporters from MTV, CNN and a German woman who
he said had ``no balance whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Another German reporter is taking home a surfboard. Paskowitz
quoted him: ``I want to surf now and forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The surf crowd only reflects California's love for the
Democrats, but even the beach has a few dissenters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People try to put surfers in a bloc,'' said Mark Cox, 19, a
confessed Republican voter working at the beach RV park. ``That's
wrong. Some don't care. But a lot of us are very involved in
government.''
</P>
<P>
   His greatest disdain is not directed at the dominant Democrats,
but at the young protesters marching and blocking streets outside
the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so embarrassing. They just look for something to yip
about. I'm glad they're not getting much attention.''
</P>
<P>
   One Malibu resident couldn't stop talking about a Democrat who
isn't even a candidate. Laureen Sills, 40, and her children were
thrilled Sunday when President Clinton stopped his limousine to
meet them on his way to a big-money brunch at the home of James
Brolin and Barbra Streisand.
</P>
<P>
   The Sills family was watching his motorcade from their front
curb on Zumirez Drive. G.T. Sills, 9, and his sister Hallie, 8, and
brother, Danny, 4, held a hastily painted sign: ``Please Shake Our
Hands, Mr. Prez.''
</P>
<P>
   The motorcade suddenly halted. A Secret Service agent ordered
them, ``Don't move.''
</P>
<P>
   They froze. Then the agent said, ``The president wants to meet
the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton shook their hands, thanked them and autographed the
sign. ``We've always been big fans of his, despite his moral
slips,'' Laureen Sills said. ``We think he's been wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Al Gore should only follow the wake, she said,
using a Malibu analogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a great feeling when you just get on that wave and
ride it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore needs to just get on the wave. He should get on
Clinton's surfboard and ride it.''
</P>
<P>
   That sea will be even rougher than the Malibu Lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
