<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-FINE0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis fined for hurting NFL's image
 &HT;    By Ken Sugiura
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last month, NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said
Baltimore Ravens linebacker Ray Lewis ``had suffered a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   It was why the league did not suspend the player for pleading
guilty to obstruction of justice in the Atlanta murder
investigation after Super Bowl XXXIV in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a substitute for the courts,'' Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, the league dealt Lewis a fine of $250,000. It
is thought to be the largest fine the NFL has levied against a
player in a case not involving substance abuse. The league also
will fine Lewis an additional $250,000 if he violates his 12-month
probation in Fulton County.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said Lewis caused harm to the league and its players
by not cooperating fully with police, which ``fueled a public
perception that he had something to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Ravens statement, Lewis said he was disappointed and will
appeal the decision to the league.
</P>
<P>
   He originally was accused of the crime before pleading guilty to
obstructing justice and testifying against his two co-defendants,
who later were acquitted. ``Such admitted misconduct,'' Tagliabue
said, ``clearly contributes to the negative stereotyping of NFL
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
