<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MCCAIN-CANCER-NYT &LR;      08-17 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELANOMA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 McCAIN UNDERGOES MORE TESTS AND MAY HAVE SURGERY TO TREAT By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Doctors at the Mayo Clinic in Scottsdale examined Sen.
John McCain on Thursday and recommended that he begin treatment
immediately for the recurrence of a serious form of skin cancer, a
McCain spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman, Nancy Ives, said the results of tests that he
underwent for three hours were expected to be known on Friday,
after which doctors would consult with McCain and determine a
course of action that would likely include surgery. After leaving
the clinic with his wife, Cindy, McCain told reporters, ``I feel
fine, thanks.'' He took no questions.
</P>
<P>
   Ives said McCain could undergo surgery, if that is required, as
soon as Saturday. She also said doctors at Mayo planned to release
a detailed report on Friday outlining McCain's condition, after
which McCain would probably hold a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The urgency for treatment arose after a routine examination of
McCain at the Bethesda Naval Medical Center outside Washington on
Aug. 2, when doctors found two spots _ one on his left temple, the
other on his left arm _ that were confirmed through a biopsy to be
malignant melanomas. It is the deadliest and most aggressive form
of skin cancer and the least common, but if caught early, it is
highly curable.
</P>
<P>
   Because it was unclear whether the melanomas had spread, the
doctors recommended additional tests, and Thursday, McCain, 63, was
given blood work, a chest X-ray, an electrocardiogram, an
echocardiogram, an MRI and a CT scan. The seriousness of skin
cancer is determined by how deep the cancer has grown and whether
it has spread to other organs.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who gave up his campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination in March, has a history of skin problems and in 1993 had
a melanoma removed from his shoulder. Medical records released by
his campaign said he had routinely had skin lesions or moles
removed, but they were usually the most common and least
threatening type of skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   While he was speaking at the Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia this month, blotches were evident at his temple. In
the closing moments of his speech, he left an eerie and suggestive
echo. He said: ``I will not see what is over America's horizon. The
years that remain are too few, I trust, but the immortality that
was the inspiration of my youth has, like all the treasures of
youth, quietly slipped away.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ives said the speech, written by Mark Salter, who was a
co-author of McCain's memoir, ``Faith of My Fathers,'' was not
intended to portend ``anything dark about the senator's health,''
only the broad notion that the country's best times are always
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, she said, the speech preceded the examination at
the Naval Medical Center, ``so the timing is all wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   After the biopsy was taken, McCain returned to Philadelphia for
the final night of the convention, wearing a bandage to protect the
area.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's examination came on the final day of the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles, from which both Vice President
Al Gore and his running mate, Joseph Lieberman, wished him well.
Their sentiments echoed many others that aides to McCain said he
had received over the last two days, including those from Gov.
George W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, as well as
scores of friends and other leading Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, McCain had toured Western states with Bush
and he had planned to resume campaigning next week. But his
schedule is now uncertain, pending the treatment of his skin
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Ives said it was uncertain whether McCain's skin cancer had, in
any way, been caused by the five years he spent in a prison camp
during the Vietnam War. For much of the time, the fair-skinned
McCain was kept outdoors, exposed to many hours of sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, fair-skinned people and those who have been sunburned
at young ages are at greater risk to skin cancer, the American
Cancer Society says.
</P>
<P>
   Because he qualifies under both risk groups, McCain, aides said,
has undergone checkups every three months, a vigilance that could
mean his latest problems are treatable.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Dr. Charles McDonald,
past president of the American Cancer Society, said: ``He probably
just has another melanoma. Anybody who's had one, you have to keep
very close eye on them. Nine times out of 10, they're going to
develop another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
