<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-GIANTS-PACBELL081     08-17 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-PACBELL0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You'll leave your heart in Pac Bell Park
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the Braves play their first game tonight at
Pacific Bell Park against the San Francisco Giants, they'll be
hitting on the dock of the bay.
</P>
<P>
   They'll find a stadium where tape-measure home runs called
``Splash Hits'' land in the water just beyond right field. The
homers land in an inlet named Willie McCovey Cove for the former
first baseman, not far from Lefty O'Doul Bridge, named for another
San Francisco baseball institution.
</P>
<P>
   They'll find a scene where Portuguese water dogs, in the name of
charity, race a flotilla of nautical spectators for the floating
souvenirs. The idea was the brainchild of Don Novello, the Bay-area
comedian better known as Father Guido Sarducci on ``Saturday Night
Live.''
</P>
<P>
   THE PLACE TO BE
</P>
<P>
   They'll find a hangout atmosphere where fans on the street are
invited to watch _ for free _ through screened portals in right
field. Every three innings, Giants employees rotate crowds, which
they call ``the knothole gang,'' an old-time reference to kids
sneaking a peek through the fence.
</P>
<P>
   What the Braves won't find at Pac Bell are the elements that
made visits to the old Candlestick Park such a novel hardship _
canyons of empty seats, pockets of hardy fans dressed like Sherpas,
wind conditions out of ``The Perfect Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   In its inaugural season, Pac Bell Park has turned funky,
activist, radical old San Francisco into something completely
unexpected: a baseball town. The Giants have become as tough a
ticket as the opera.
</P>
<P>
   The team sold 29,800 season tickets this year _ 20,000 more than
last year. With the exception of 500 bleacher seats put on sale
every game day, the season is sold out. Season attendance this year
will surpass 3.3 million, a significant jump from last year when
the franchise drew 2 million for only the third time in its
history. ``We've found that this can be a great baseball town with
the right facility,'' Giants CEO Larry Baer says. Pac Bell has
endowed major-league baseball in San Francisco with social status.
It is located within walking distance of downtown, technically in
China Basin, but part of trendy South of Market (SOMA), a reviving
neighborhood of upstart dot-coms, world-class museums and flashy
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   A HINT OF TURNER FIELD
</P>
<P>
   ``The park has turned the town on,'' says Ronn Owens, morning
talk-show host on KGO-AM. ``There's a lot more of the
quiche-and-wine crowd. Everybody seems to be in a good mood. At the
Stick, you could always see fights in the stands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody will tell you that the games have become social
events, and it's true,'' says William Nolan, 48, a fan from
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   In California style, fans will find an international food court
offering sushi, calamari and burritos along with the pricey basics:
cheeseburger and fries, $9.50.
</P>
<P>
   If not for its bayside setting and glorious views of the marina,
the Bay Bridge and Treasure Island, Pac Bell might remind fans of
Turner Field. It has the same updated amenities inside, the Main
Street feel, the brickwork, the industrial-girder look.
</P>
<P>
   Braves fans also will relate to the 9-foot-tall bronze statue of
a legendary home-run hitter on the main plaza _ not Hank Aaron, but
Willie Mays. The giant Coke bottle above left field should feel
familiar, too. It is a tilted 80-foot framework for four giant
slides inside, part of a family entertainment area, Coca-Cola Fan
Lot, which also sports a miniature replica of Pac Bell where kids
can run the bases and watch themselves on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   As with all the new baseball stadiums, Pac Bell's amusement-park
features were designed to turn baseball field into entertainment
destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognized going in that if we built a park only for the
people who memorize batting averages and ERAs, we'd draw a million
people per season,'' Baer says. ``But because we're privately
funded, we have to draw 3 million. To do that we had to create an
experience in fans' minds.''
</P>
<P>
   `THE BIG PHONE?'
</P>
<P>
   Probably the best news for Giants fans is that their team is a
contender. The newly involved hometown crowds seem more rabid, too;
they have been cultivating the throw-back-the-homer tradition of
Cubs fans. ``It's awesome playing in front of a full house,''
Giants manager Dusty Baker says. ``This ballpark has meant a lot to
the game in San Francisco and a lot to the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker's pick for best Pac Bell feature?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the weather,'' he says. ``The wind's a factor; it's
just not the factor it was at Candlestick. It doesn't swirl like it
did there.'' The only thing Giants fans haven't hit upon is one of
those nicknames _ like ``The Ted'' for Turner Field, or ``The
Jake'' for Jacobs Field in Cleveland. The closest thing offered so
far has come from a local writer, in reference to the stadium's
naming-rights owner: ``The Big Phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the most accurate description of the park may be
``the best.'' As the Houston Chronicle recently put it, ``The Great
Ballpark Building Battle is over. San Francisco won.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
