<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rivalry nonexistent for Graziani, Kanell
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tony Graziani might be playing the best football of
his life, but these days are not his favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani is trying to beat out Danny Kanell for the right to
back up quarterback Chris Chandler for the Falcons (3-0). Coach Dan
Reeves has suggested that the loser in this competition will be
cut.
</P>
<P>
   But the Graziani-Kanell relationship is not the rivalry fans
might picture when thinking about two men competing for the same
job in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani and Kanell eat together, joke together, play golf
together.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, two days after Kanell supplanted him as the backup
only to suffer a knee injury in a start at Tennessee, the two were
at the mall. Kanell was on crutches, and Graziani was helping him
around.
</P>
<P>
   But tonight, Graziani, 26, will try to move ahead of his friend,
who is a month older. Graziani is expected to play the second half
against the 2-0 Chargers. He has a passer rating of 135.1; Kanell's
rating is 106.4.
</P>
<P>
   It is tough to say which one aches more inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just try not to think about it, at least on the field,''
said Graziani, a seventh-round draft choice of the Falcons in 1997.
``Obviously, off the field, you think about it a little because you
have to make plans and so forth. It's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziani's first three NFL seasons went from Titanic to train
wreck to fender bender. His passer ratings were 3.7, 42.4 and 64.2.
A rating of about 70 is average.
</P>
<P>
   But he became a world traveler, played with Barcelona in NFL
Europe in the spring, logged a lot of time and threw more passes
than in three seasons in the NFL. He grew as a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to take what the defense gives me,'' he said. ``I
was always confident. Now, I'm more prepared for what I'm going to
see. It's not that I was shocked before, but now I'm more
prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks coach Jerry Rhome knows that Reeves favors keeping
strong-armed rookie free-agent Doug Johnson as a developmental
project for the No. 3 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to be able to keep all four. That's coach Reeves'
decision,'' Rhome said. ``You just got to look at them, and look
into the future, if they're even. They're both intelligent. Tony's
a little more mobile, but Danny's more experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziani appreciates the kind words. What he would really
appreciate is a job, but not at Kanell's expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, and I think it's going to make us better
players,'' he said. `'Like Danny said last week, maybe we'll force
them to keep all four of us. If not, I'll be sad to see one of us
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
