<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5006 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOREA-SPIES-BOS &LR;      08-17 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-SPIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREAN SPIES MAINTAIN LOYALTY YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ Wizened but unbowed, Shin In Young and his seven elderly
housemates, all former North Korean secret agents, have emerged
blinking into the sunlight of a world that has changed dramatically
since they were imprisoned decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   They were among thousands of agents who infiltrated South Korea
on missions from the North's communist government in the 1950s and
'60s. Captured and jailed for fomenting revolution by the south's
former rightist dictatorships, they endured water torture, being
hung from the rafters, and beatings.
</P>
<P>
   Many died in prison or changed sides to win their freedom. But
about 100 survived and clung to their allegiance to the North,
remaining in prison until Kim Dae Jung, himself a former political
prisoner, was inaugurated president of South Korea in 1998 and
began granting amnesties.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, these men have lived humbly in church-supported
group homes in Seoul, working as garbagemen to supplement the
charity they receive, offering free acupuncture to the poor, a
skill they learned in prison when they had to secretly treat
themselves, and pining for home.
</P>
<P>
   They have awkwardly acclimated to smog and computers, to
dyed-hair youth culture and MTV. But one thing they cannot accept
is the political system that they vowed to overturn years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When they were first released they found themselves free men
trapped in South Korea, barred from returning home across the
world's last Cold War battle front. Now, thanks to the least
publicized and perhaps most delicate provision of the unprecedented
June summit between the leaders of South Korea and North Korea, the
``unconverted long-term prisoners'' will be allowed to go home next
month, and two-thirds say they are going.
</P>
<P>
   Televised images of this week's 200 tearful and agonizingly
short cross-border family reunions have tantalized the men in this
sunny two-story house in a working-class neighborhood. The
fleeting, desperate embraces between mothers and long-lost
children, between wives and missing husbands, will be by Saturday a
heartbreaking memory. But in a few short weeks, these men will be
permanently reunited with their surviving loved ones and with the
world's last unreconstructed Stalinist state, the fiercely
``self-reliant'' North Korea for which they sacrificed their
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   As young nationalists who had just cast off the yoke of Japanese
colonialism, they joined the North to fight for a united Korea,
free from domination by the post-war superpowers. ``All the
progressive people went up North to help the government reunify,''
said Shin, 71. ``All the conservative people stayed here and blamed
communism for their failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoon Yong Gi, 74, jailed 39 years for his activities, resents
the label ``spy.'' He calls himself a patriot.
</P>
<P>
   ``A spy is someone hired by other governments for money. I came
from the North to liberate my country and help it unify itself,''
he declared. ``I was working for my own people. . . And my ideology
hasn't changed a bit. I still believe the South Korean government
is dependent on the U.S. and others.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, these tough old men refuse to discuss their
``missions,'' revealing only that they were sent to ``create
rebellion among university students and the public,'' glean
information from southern officials, and promote reunification.
</P>
<P>
   These days, they have little opportunity for such activities.
They spend their time preparing herbal medicines, treating
patients, collecting trash, and reading North Korean papers on the
Internet. But if their involvement in promoting unification has
diminished, their commitment to that ideal has not.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the South's obvious prosperity, nor news of the North's
backwards economy, clouds their idealism. Capitalism violates human
rights, they say, since some people are rich and others poor. The
North's economic troubles would disappear, these men believe, if
the U.S. lifted its longstanding economic blockade.
</P>
<P>
   Shin's small room is decorated with things he may not have
access to in the North _ a late-model TV, a computer, a variety of
books and newspapers, and some choice kitsch, including a fake
bronze rococo bust of a kissing couple. But these, he says, are
unneccesary trappings that he won't mind leaving behind.
</P>
<P>
   For all the warm treatment from human rights groups and Catholic
Church volunteers, and the simple comfort of their lives, these men
are outsiders in this society, contrarians whose politics
stigmatized their relatives in the South when they were caught.
</P>
<P>
   These men believe that in the North they will find dignity, a
hero's welcome, and a community of like-minded souls. They are for
ideology first, family second.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I need is my own country, which I have been dreaming to go
back to all these years,'' Shin said. He is dying of bone marrow
cancer, and he believes his medical care in the North will be
better than the free treatment he has received in Seoul. ``I
believe they will take care of my health there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the long dreamed-for return and reunion with the wife and
three children he hasn't seen in 33 years will come at a bitter
price. His 92-year-old mother, five sisters, and brother live in
the South, and going home means bidding them goodbye forever. Shin
is lobbying the Seoul government to let him take his mother to the
North so she fulfill ``her last wish'' to meet her daughter-in-law
and three grandchilden.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea announced Wednesday it would welcome the
ex-prisoners' southern relatives to come live with them, but the
South has not said whether it will allow such an unprecedented
cross-over.
</P>
<P>
   Even the decision to let the prisoners go back has raised
hackles here; many say President Kim should have insisted on a
trade for the estimated 400 southern POWs believed to be laboring
in camps since the 1950s, plus any political prisoners or spies
from the South. The Pyongyang government denies there are any.
</P>
<P>
   Shin believes that his wife is alive and passed the years ``with
dignity,'' knowing that her husband did ``something for the whole
nation, not just for our small family. I told her when I left that
this division of Korea happened in our generation, so our
generation must sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   But three men living in the house have decided not to return
next month, either because they married since their release or
never had families in the North. But they insist that they will
still be fighting quietly for the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came all the way down here to work for reunification, and it
hasn't happened yet, so how can I go back?'' said an indignant Ahn
Hak Seop, 70. ``My relatives here treat me like a bloody communist.
My nephew came to me when I got out of prison and said, `You look
just like my father, but you're a bloody Red.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'd have a better life in North Korea, and that people
would welcome me there. But I need to stay here to prove that I
have stood by my ideals all these years,'' said Ahn, who rises
daily at 4 a.m. to collect trash for $200 a month. He spends
afternoons making herbal medicine for patients and studying
Northern leader Kim Jong Il's reunification theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show these brainwashed South Korean people that
we're the same people, that we're even more diligent, more honest.
I want to show people here a moral way to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
