<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-WEEK19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DULL CONVENTION? NOT IF YOU KNOW WHERE TO LOOK
 &HT;    By JILL VEJNOSKA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ TV talk is all the rage here, just as it was in
Philadelphia a few weeks ago. All anyone wants to know is why the
major broadcast networks aren't providing more convention coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Not interesting enough, say the TV types.
</P>
<P>
   That's not true. You just have to know where to look. Here are a
few scenes from the Week That Was at the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   A motorcade pulled up to the Staples Center shortly before noon
on Thursday, escorted by a plethora of California Highway Patrol
officers riding motorcycles and displaying none of the friendliness
of Ponch and John on ``Chips.'' The reason became apparent when one
of the officers in the rear guard spilled the name of their
celebrity passenger:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tipper.''
</P>
<P>
   That was it. Not ``Mrs. Gore,'' not ``the vice president's
wife.'' Just ``Tipper,'' who's married to ``Al.'' As in ``Al and
Joe,'' which is all it says on the best-selling button at Jim
Bayne's table outside the convention (Better even than the ``Please
don't shoot me, I'm not a protester'' button).
</P>
<P>
   Forget becoming the First Family. The Gores are rapidly becoming
the nation's First Name Family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've watched their family grow up,'' explained California
delegate Arlie Ricasa, watching inside the Staples Center as Tip--,
er, Mrs. Gore, ran through a sound check on the podium for her
Thursday night speech. ``It's very hard to call them by their last
names.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind Mrs. Gore, electronic signs in the arena where the Lakers
play read ``Tipper Rocks!''; in front of her, some 30 photographers
_ professional and otherwise _ stood on chairs in the Tennessee
delegation's section and snapped photos. A longtime professional
photographer, Mrs. Gore pulled out her camera and began snapping
right back.
</P>
<P>
   Then she moved toward the back of the podium, where she spent
some 10 minutes being interviewed by NBC's Maria Shriver. Watching
from the press gallery of seats above the podium was 11-year-old
Chaille Stovall, who's making a film about the political
conventions and filing short reports for the cable channel HBO
Family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Gore!'' Chaille screamed and across several rows, his
equally pint-sized camera man and sound man scrambling along behind
him. ``Mrs. Gore! Will you do an interview?!''
</P>
<P>
   As an aide pulled the waving second lady off the podium, Shriver
headed towards Chaille. Would she do instead, Shriver wondered?
</P>
<P>
   Chaille scrambled through a notebook for questions he'd prepared
for just such a moment. Shriver, a mother of four, soothingly asked
him questions about himself, and, seeing how he'd spelled her name
in his notebook _ ``Schreiber'' _ gently set him straight.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Chaille began questioning her about the role of young
people in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 5, I passed out bumper stickers for my uncle who
was running for president. His name was John Kennedy,'' Shriver
told him, just before reaching over unobtrusively and straightening
up his microphone.
</P>
<P>
   After several minutes, Chaille finally asked a seemingly
unscripted question. Did Shriver bring her children to the
convention?
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter came to the Republican convention and my two kids
came here the other night,'' Shriver said, before expressing common
lament of nearly everyone here, Kennedys or otherwise. ``None are
coming tonight. I don't have any passes.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, an event sponsored by four Jewish organizations that
was to feature speeches by President Clinton and first lady and New
York Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton began running long.
The president apparently was running behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   To fill some of the time, two groups that had been providing
separate musical entertainment merged their repertoires. The result
of mixing mariachi with Eastern European ``Klezmer'' music was a
not unpleasant feeling of being at a bar mitzvah in Mexican
restaurant. They called it the ``Klezmer Mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing they didn't call on one of three cabinet officers in
attendance, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson. Two nights later, at
a party at the home of Shriver and her husband, actor Arnold
Schwarzenegger, Richardson joined Shriver's uncle, Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy of Massachusetts,er ``Roll Call.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of discordant notes, the police and the
aforementioned protesters have been in an increasing state of
standoff all week. Many of the protesters refuse to give their
names _ ``I can't, I'm an anarchist,'' one young man with a
bandanna covering half his face explained Wednesday evening _ and
often claim, as one also did Wednesday, that their concerns are
``too complicated'' to be articulated.
</P>
<P>
   But you didn't have to be a young anarchist to find yourself
caught up in protests this week _ or to experience conflicted
emotions over how both sides have handled themselves.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Aaron Cogan and Kelly Calvey left nearby Laguna
Hills to attend a rally for vice president Al Gore at the Burbank
Airport. Next they headed downtown to sight-see at the Staples
Center; around 6 p.m., they stood near the heart of the protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm staying to make sure it stays peaceful,'' said Cogan, 36,
who felt it was his duty as a citizen. ``If nothing else, you've
got to have the space to speak your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   As police tried to clear the area, some protesters heckled
Calvey, who wore a Gore T-shirt. She defended their first amendment
right to protest anything _ including her choice of presidential
candidate. But as more and more of the protesters departed, Calvey
was somewhat downcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed that they didn't stand their ground
longer,'' said Calvey, 35, who works in employment recruiting.
Then, as police announced anyone who didn't move along would be
subject to arrest, she and Cogan fretted over whether to stay and
risk arrest themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the decision was taken out of their hands. With most of
the protesters gone, the duo moved out along with police.
</P>
<P>
   The police have had other things to do here, of course. Around
11 p.m. on Monday, a suspected carjacker led to police on a
prolonged high-speed chase near the Los Angeles Airport. The chase
was broadcast live on the local Fox affiliate, whose anchorman at
one point somberly informed viewers there was ``no connection''
between the chase and the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the convention got a mention on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska's e-mail address is jvejnoska(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
