<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLOUDY `NOON'
</HEADLINE>
  Remake can't stand up to sentimental original 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Sun., Aug. 20.) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ted Turner must imagine himself similar to Will Kane, the
protagonist of ``High Noon'' _ a lone, decent man battling on
despite the indifference of his countrymen: contemporary audiences
with blase attitudes toward Westerns.
</P>
<P>
   Turner alone seems to be producing for his cable stations TNT
and TBS what they called, back in the day, ``oaters.'' The results
are obvious labors of love _ in this remake for TBS of Fred
Zinnemann's beloved 1952 Gary Cooper-Grace Kelly melodrama,
cinematographer Robert McLachlan polishes Rick Roberts' handsome
production design, not to mention some spectacular vistas, to a
gorgeous sheen.
</P>
<P>
   But here the genre's cliches show their aching joints
pronouncedly (some considered the original even upon its release to
be a bit on the sentimental side), which works decidedly against
its overall effectiveness. In his book ``The Hollywood Western,''
historian William K. Everson declared Henry King's less celebrated
but far grittier 1950 effort ``The Gunslinger,'' which operated on
many similar levels to Zinneman's more popular work, to be the
superior of the two films.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Noon'' 2K stars stolid Tom Skerritt as Kane, who
discovers, seconds after marrying Quaker pacifist Amy (``Once and
Again's'' Susanna Thompson), that a killer who has sworn revenge
against him has been dubiously released from prison and is lusting
for blood on the next train to Kane's sleepy town of Hadleyville.
</P>
<P>
   Amy, naturally, thinks Kane should get while the getting is good
_ ``I don't see anything but death and destruction coming out of
this,'' she opines. The townspeople agree: The town judge (Matthew
Walker) grimly tells Will, ``You could be on your way to your
wedding bed instead of your grave.'' Will, of course, is too
willful a manly man to drop his guns and badge.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, his efforts to form a posse to battle his foe are
singularly disastrous _ as much as everyone has valued his
contribution to the community, no one wants to muss his hair or
endanger risk his life to fight for right. In 1952, this commented
archly on the encroaching American values of apathy and passing the
buck; today, it simply seems depressingly de rigueur.
</P>
<P>
   A key scene _ Kane confronting the town gentry in the church,
only to be rebuffed in a genteel and gutless fashion _ should be
the film's highlight, but instead, no thanks to nonsupple scripting
and the supporting cast's oblivious obviousness, it feels flat and
schematic.
</P>
<P>
   Skerritt plays his role with a stoicism that borders on dull
fatalism, as if he's collapsed Elisabeth Kubler-Ross's five stages
of death down to the final signpost _ acceptance. Despite the fact
that director Rod Hardy apes Zinnemann's conceit of letting the
action play out in real time, Skerritt's turn understates the
menace too much _ he's obviously working off the knowledge of too
many crass hero-against-the-odds movies. If he's channeling the
sublime cool of Clint Eastwood (who also cribbed from ``High
Noon,'' to greater effect, in ``The Outlaw Josie Wales''), he's
also draining the film of its urgency.
</P>
<P>
   The final showdown is nonetheless effective, though Michael
Madsen, playing too handily off his icily homicidal cinematic
persona, is still woefully underused as Kane's would-be killer.
Thompson, too, could have been given a better stage _ her
performance seems to end as soon as she's done burning her gaze
into Will at their wedding _ as could Maria Conchita Alonso, who
plays Kane's embittered former lover. TBS's ``High Noon'' may seek
to reinvent the cliches of the Western, but ultimately, it only
rehashes them. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``High Noon.'' &QL; 
What: Remake of the 1952 Western. &QL; 
The stars: Tom Skerritt, Susanna Thompson, Maria Conchita Alonso,
Michael Madsen. &QL; 
Where: TBS. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight; also Aug. 26 and Sept. 2. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
