<HEADER>
A5012 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-OIL-PROFITS-MOSB     08-17 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-OIL-PROFITS-MOSBACHER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL PROFITS ARE FINALLY WHERE THEY OUGHT TO BE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Friday, Aug. 18, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By ROBERT A. MOSBACHER    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Too many people are accusing the oil and gas industry
of greed, blaming oil companies for both the runup in the price of
gasoline, which has moderated since last spring, and for more
recent rises in home heating and energy prices.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is the American oil industry is not the instigator of
higher prices. In the case of oil, producing nations including
those of the Middle East decided last spring to cut production to
force prices up, since some were having trouble meeting their
debts. Natural gas prices rose because of reduced supply as
American and Canadian companies, hurt by previously low prices, cut
back on drilling. As for gasoline prices, they had been depressed
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with American oil companies finally making a
profit? A year ago, pitting oil against the rest of American
industry in a contest of earnings was like putting a weekend duffer
against Tiger Woods. Indeed, for two decades, it has been a rarity
for analysts to recommend oil stocks as a top pick for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Now oil prices have increased by 100 percent since last year. In
the first quarter of 1999, crude oil was $11.50 a barrel; now oil
producers receive $30 a barrel. Virtually all of this additional
price per barrel can go to the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   If the cost of producing the oil is between $7 and $12 per
barrel, which it is for the majority of oil companies, any amount
they receive above that figure is potential profit. When they get
$30 a barrel, close to $20 of this might become pretax operating
income. But this does not mean that in the long term, oil
companies' bottom lines are being fattened inordinately.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of 1999, most oil companies had only a small
net income. Many, with high costs or debt, had net losses. From
1977 through 1999, net income in the oil industry was equal to only
9.7 percent of net investment, as opposed to 11.5 percent for all
of American industry.
</P>
<P>
   Take a more recent snapshot. From 1994 through 1998, oil company
profits averaged 7.2 percent, or about half of the 14.2 percent
average for all the companies on the Standard &AMP; Poor's list of 500
industrial stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern was little better in the first quarter of this year,
when oil companies' profit margin was 5.9 percent, compared with
7.3 percent for all industries. And in some lucky businesses _
banks, publishing, broadcasting and electronics _ profits were 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter of 2000, however, as the rising price of
crude oil had its effect, most oil companies had large profit
increases over the same months a year earlier. Exxon Mobil, Chevron
and BP Amoco all reported profit increases of well over 100
percent. But these and all oil companies had a long way to come
from what was, for them, starvation a year ago. And rises like this
won't continue.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts of the oil industry expect that over the next couple of
years, profits should level out on a plateau compatible with
earnings for the rest of the companies in the S&AMP;P 500. But it will
be the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries that will
really determine what happens, because OPEC has considerable power
over the price of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   And in the future, as current sources of oil run dry, energy
companies will have to spend increasing amounts drilling and
developing in deeper and more hazardous regions. They will also
have to commit huge sums to develop synthetics and find new sources
of natural gas. Of course, all of this will make it more difficult
for oil companies to maintain a healthy bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the future bodes well for oil and gas companies,
compared with their dismal recent past. And it is high time for
them to enjoy good returns along with most other American
industries.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Mosbacher, chairman of the Mosbacher Energy Co., was
commerce secretary under President George Bush.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
