<SLUG> BC-R-JEWS-RURAL-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH COMMUNITIES TAKING ROOT IN RURAL AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add photo advisory.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: This story was previously skedded on some budgets as
WOODSTOCK-SYNAGOGUE.) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK, Vt. _ Route 4, a rural highway that twists across
Vermont's midsection, passes the sort of roadside signs one would
expect in northern New England. Maple syrup, they advertise.
Cheddar cheese. Bed and breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   And then outside a 150-year-old farmhouse is the sign adorned
with a Star of David, announcing the presence of Congregation Shir
Shalom.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected? Perhaps, but also very much a sign of the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Jews haven't realized the extent to which Jews have moved
to the country,'' said Stuart M. Matlins, founder of the synagogue
along with his wife, Antoinette.
</P>
<P>
   Matlins, a New York native, management consultant and, more
recently, a publisher, said that every-other-Friday services this
summer had been drawing 50 to 60 people. On the High Holy Days last
year, he added, 200 came to services.
</P>
<P>
   America's Jewish population, about 6 million, has changed little
in total number in recent years, but it is not immune from the
restless impulses that make the United States a transient society.
</P>
<P>
   In disparate places, Jewish communities are growing _ and as
they do, new synagogues are appearing in towns from Woodstock in
the Green Mountains to Ketchum, Idaho, and Park City, Utah, in the
Rockies, where such institutions have been rare, if they existed at
all.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening, said Samuel C. Heilman, professor of Jewish
studies and sociology at City University of New York, is part of a
trend, ``a radiating Jewish community,'' he calls it, whose members
have been moving from once-solidly Jewish neighborhoods to the
suburbs and, for some, to rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have here is Jews who are so much a part of America
now,'' Heilman said, ``they no longer feel constrained to live
among Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 edition of the American Jewish Yearbook, published by
the American Jewish Committee, shows that Jewish populations have
been growing in such widely scattered locales as Portland, Ore.;
Tampa, Fla.; Charleston, S.C.; and Portsmouth, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish population is also increasing in Vermont. By the
yearbook's count, about 5,700 Jews live there _ only 1 percent of
the state's population but double the number of Jews there two
decades ago. Congregation Shir Shalom, also known as the Woodstock
Area Jewish Community, belongs to Judaism's liberal Reform
movement. The newer, small-town synagogues tend to be non-Orthodox,
partly because the challenges of living an Orthodox lifestyle _
requiring kosher food and walking to services _ are difficult in
places where Jewish resources are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodstock synagogue began a dozen years ago with services in
Matlins' office, at the company he founded, Jewish Lights
Publishing. The company publishes books on Jewish spirituality and
life, and, through a sister imprint, on topics related to religious
experience more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, the congregation grew, with new residents
(mainly young families and retirees), along with people who had
weekend homes in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to live in a rural area and have a Jewish life,''
said Matlins, 60, who serves on the board of Hebrew Union College,
which trains men and women as Reform rabbis, cantors and educators.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, the group reached a sufficiently critical mass to
buy the farmhouse, both for its services and its Hebrew school.
Local Protestant, Roman Catholic and Unitarian-Universalist clergy
attended the dedication. The congregation also affiliated with the
Union of American Hebrew Congregations, the Reform movement's
synagogue organization.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, another small-town temple, in Great
Barrington, Mass., joined the union. Lately, officials say, such
additions to the ranks are not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're emerging in very interesting areas,'' said Rabbi
Daniel Freelander, the union's director of program, citing
synagogues in places like Bainbridge Island, Wash.; Hickory, N.C.;
and Keene, N.H.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many, like the one in Woodstock, are too small to afford a
full-time rabbi and rely on student rabbis who come once or twice a
month. They also depend on volunteers to keep them running.
</P>
<P>
   In Woodstock, that category includes Bob and Muriel Steinberg,
who retired from their jobs in West Hartford, Conn., four years
ago. After they began attending the synagogue as full-time Vermont
residents, Steinberg said, ``It just hit me, there was something to
be done.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, he said, ``has the people skills, I have the
organizational skills.'' They now serve as its co-presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The synagogue's roadside sign helps attract people, Steinberg
said. One day last summer, her husband was standing outside when
two young women pulled up and asked about services. He invited them
to attend that evening, which they did. ``As it turned out,''
Steinberg said, ``one was from Brazil, one was from Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the sanctuary exudes a feeling of intimacy, befitting a
space that once served as a living room. Three Shaker-style
benches, arranged on a wooden floor, face an ark whose hand-carved
cover depicts the tree of life. ``We can get 50 to 60 people in
here,'' Matlins said. Upstairs, what had been bedrooms have been
turned into classrooms and meeting rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby stands an old barn, built of rough-hewn logs. The
congregation is mulling whether to convert it to a new sanctuary to
accommodate more people.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the sanctuary, with Mount Tom as his backdrop, Matlins
was moved to reflect on Judaism's traditions in light of the
faith's earliest history. In such a place as Woodstock, he said, an
event like the festival of Tabernacles _ in which Jews set up
sukkahs, or booths, as reminders of the Israelites' sojourn in the
wilderness _ has a resonance lacking in more urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judaism,'' he said, ``was a religion of people who did not
live in cities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
