entertainment/arts and travel articles this week for release
Sunday, August 20. Sunday business artcles began moving Thursday
evening. The remainder will move Friday. If you have questions
about stories, call 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES/FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MANCHEVSKI-FILM (Stavica, Macedonia) _ Hemmed in by Kosovo to
the north, Greece to the south, Albania to the west and Bulgaria to
the east, and lacking any outlet to the sea, Macedonia swelters in
the sun. It is late July, a few miles from the Greek border;
nothing moves; tobacco crops wilt in the fields. Behind a Byzantine
church, men, their shirts caked in blood, are draped on the bald
mountainside. Shots ring out. Milcho Manchevski, the Macedonian
director of the acclaimed, Oscar-nominated film, ``Before the
Rain,'' is at it again, putting the tortured history of his
homeland on the screen in his second film. By Joan Dupont.
</P>
<P>
   ABBIE-HOFFMAN-FILM (Undated) _ ``The whole world is watching!''
was chanted during the Republican Convention this month. Many of
those chanting had not yet been born in 1968, when that cry first
sounded on the streets of Chicago, as the police clubbed protesters
in town for the tumultuous Democratic convention. The scene was yet
another tribute to the enduring power of the '60s in the national
imagination. So is ``Steal This Movie,'' which opens Aug. 18,
Robert Greenwald's biographical movie about Abbie Hoffman,
charismatic exemplar of '60s cultural radicalism, a defendant in
the conspiracy trial of the Chicago Seven, the leaders of the
Chicago protest, and the author of ``Steal This Book,'' among other
provocations. By Ellen Willis.
</P>
<P>
   JANSSEN-FILM (Undated) _ Famke Janssen, like a rollercoaster,
tall and steeply curved, is having herself a thrill ride of a
summer. As Jean Grey, the telepathic, telekinetic protege of
Professor X, Janssen was part of the team that not only arrested
the vengeful Magneto's quest for world domination in ``X-Men'' but
has also raked in a superheroic $144 million at the box office in
five weeks of release. Now, opening on August 25, comes Valerie
Breiman's romantic comedy ``Love and Sex,'' a crowd pleaser at the
last winter's Sundance Festival. By Jamie Malanowski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-BERKSHIRES (Lenox, Mass.) _ In ``Henry V,''
Shakespeare asked the patrons to use their imaginations and
``Suppose within the girdle of these walls/Are now confin'd two
mighty monarchies.'' Tina Packer, the ebullient director of
Shakespeare &AMP; Company, is making an equally audacious request of
her audiences here in Western Massachusetts: to envision an exact
replica of an Elizabethan playhouse nestled among the rolling
Berkshire hills at the company's new home. Soon, after its wrangles
over use of the nearby Edith Wharton estate _ Shakespeare &AMP; Company
will be ensconced on 63 acres in Lenox, near Tanglewood. Given
Packer's drive and the plans already in motion, a replica of the
Rose Theater, which once stood in London in Shakespeare's time, is
likely to be the core of what Packer hopes will be a major center
for Shakespearean performance, teaching and scholarship in this
country. By Iris Fanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLDER-DANCERS (Undated) _ In recent years, Americans have become
more accepting of older dancers. Whether this attitude is a result
of aging baby-boomers or has been imposed by political correctness,
it is expanding the concept of dancing. The United States now has
several organizations that present performances by older dancers,
Dancers Over 40 _ the traditional retirement age _ and the 40Up
Project among them, or mingle the generations onstage, as does Liz
Lerman's Dance Exchange. By Harris Green.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUMS-ON-WHEELS (Undated) _ Since it began 29 years ago,
Artrain USA, one of the oldest of an increasing number of museums
on wheels, has brought original artworks by Picasso and Warhol,
Calder and O'Keeffe, Norman Rockwell and Robert Rauschenberg, to
more than 600 towns and cities in 44 states. It has gone to big
cities like Baltimore, Detroit, Pittsburgh and Washington, but more
often its destination isn't even a whistle stop anymore _ places
like Zeeland, Mich.; Plant City, Fla., and Parkers Prairie, Minn.
By Jonathan Mandell.
</P>
<P>
   OKAMOTO-ART-MUSEUM (Tokyo) _ On the Japanese art scene, the
baburu (economic bubble) burst long ago. Today, the friends and
contacts a Western visitor encounters here are sure to recollect,
with incredulity and undisguised embarrassment, the heady days of
the 1980s, when Japanese corporations spent tens of millions of
dollars on Impressionist paintings at overseas auctions, and when
new museums seemed to pop up every month. Nevertheless, against a
backdrop of lingering art-world doldrums, the Taro Okamoto Museum
opened late last year in Kawasaki, not far to the southwest of
central Tokyo. And with some 100,000 visitors already to its
credit, it has quickly become something of a hit. By Edward M.
Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MORAL-MUSIC (Undated) _ What's an election year without a moral
panic? Popular music, and pop culture in general, are set up to be
prime targets this year, stuck in the crossfire of a battle for the
righteous high ground. Republicans and Democrats are both
positioning themselves as guardians of what George W. Bush, in his
speech accepting the Republican nomination, called ``essential
values.'' When the moral-panic soundbites start to fly, artistic
subtlety is the first casualty. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   MESSIAEN-MUSIC (Undated) _ This is very much Messiaen's year _
as most years now tend to be. Barely was there time to draw breath
after the Brooklyn Philharmonic's presentation of three scenes from
``St. Francois d'Assise'' than the Lincoln Center Festival offered
four big pieces in quick succession. And now comes a thoroughly
spectacular recording of his greatest solo piano work, the ``Vingt
Regards sur l'Enfant-Jesus,'' played by Pierre-Laurent Aimard
(Teldec 26868-2). By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOGRAPHY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COFFER-PHOTOGRAPHY (Dundee, N.Y.) _ For the wet-plate and
tintype photographer John Coffer, it is as if the 19th century were
today and his contemporaries were not Cindy Sherman and Thomas
Struth but Mathew Brady, Timothy O'Sullivan and a host of itinerant
portrait makers who plied their trade until the dawn of the modern
era. Coffer has for more than 20 years been practicing one of the
earliest methods of photography and living the life that went with
it. He has crisscrossed the country by horse-drawn wagon in an
11,000-mile odyssey, making pictures. By Lyle Rexer.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS, PAPERBACKS and BESTSELLERS-CHILDREN have all moved.
</P>
