<HEADLINE>
HORNADAY TO STAY WITH EARNHARDT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; NASCAR Busch Grand National Division driver Ron Hornaday Jr. is
close to signing a two-year contract extension with Dale Earnhardt,
Inc., in a deal that would keep him on the Busch circuit until
2002, according to a team source.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday, a former Saugus Speedway, Winston West and Craftsman
Truck Series champ, has won two of the last three Busch Series
races and has been a contender for rookie-of-the-year honors. He
trails Kevin Harvick of Bakersfield in the rookie points race.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday is coming off a 15th-place showing in the NASCAR
Winston Cup Global Crossing at the Glen on Sunday. Hornaday was
subbing in for the injured Terry Labonte in the No. 5 Kellogg's
Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old Hornaday returns to the Busch Series for his
NAPA Auto Parts team this weekend in Saturday's NAPAONLINE.com 250
at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday won the Kroger 200 at Indianapolis Raceway Park on Aug.
4 and the NAPA Autocare 250 at Pike's Peak International Raceway in
Colorado on July 22.
</P>
<P>
   The DEI team source said Hornaday is expected to sign the
extension mext week.
</P>
<P>
   __ Godde eyes SCORE Off-Road title: After finishing second in
his class in the SCORE Primm 300 on July 29, Ty Godde of Lancaster
has a chance to win the SCORE Lites season title.
</P>
<P>
   With one race to go, Godde is in a dead heat with Jerry Penhall
of Costa Mesa, the two-time reigning champion in the SCORE Lites
class, an unlimited buggy division. A SCORE official said that
updated standings would not be available until Monday but that
Godde and Penhall are most likely tied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made up a lot of points,'' said Godde, a graduate of
Paraclete High. ``And considering (Penhall) has been the champ the
last two years, it makes it even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Godde, 30, and his driving partner, Jim Greenway of Ojai,
finished two seconds behind the race winner, Tom Ridings of Long
Beach, in the Primm 300 and he considers themselves lucky to have
been that close in the race.
</P>
<P>
   During lap two, Godde's buggy had a flat front tire. After
fixing the flat, Godde ended up flipping the buggy out of a
150-foot ditch during the third lap and rolling before landing
upright and continuing in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from almost wrecking to landing on all four wheels and
finishing the race,'' Godde said.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth and final race on the SCORE series is the Baja 2,000
in October.
</P>
<P>
   __ Kanke, Purlsey so close: M.K. Kanke of Frazier Park and Greg
Pursley of Newhall combined to lead for 114 laps of the NASCAR
Featherlite Southwest Series Sandia 125, but it was Auggie Vidovich
of Lakeside who led for the last 11 to win race in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 laps to go in the race, Kanke, who was leading, got
tangled with Matt Crafton of Tulare down the main stretch on the
0.4-mile oval. Kanke spun and lost his lead. Vidovich took over and
held on for his second win of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of expected it,'' Vidovich said of the Kanke-Crafton
incident. ``All I did was go high. I thought I was going to get
collected.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanke, a Kennedy High graduate, won the Gatorade Frontrunner
Award for leading the most laps, 73. Pursley led the first 40.
</P>
<P>
   Kanke ended up third, Pursley fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Kanke is now sixth in the Southwest Series standings. Pursley is
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Woodside of Saugus, who is fourth in points, finished 19th
in the Sandia 125. He left in lap 94 with engine trouble. Frank
Maronski Jr. of Quartz Hill, ninth in points, finished eighth.
Keith Spangler of Chatsworth was ninth and Bob Lyon of Agua Dulce
finished 21st.
</P>
<P>
   The next race on the Southwest Series is Saturday at Colorado
National Speedway in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   __ Winston West returns to Irwindale: The NASCAR Winston West
Series makes its second stop of the season at Irwindale Speedway on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first race on June 24, Bobby Dotter of Charlotte, N.C.,
held off series points leader Brendan Gaughan of Las Vegas for his
second win of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Former Winston West champ Bill Sedgwick of Acton, who is chasing
his first win of the 2000 season, is expected to drive in the
Irwindale Speedway race.
</P>
</TEXT>
