<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: BORDER CZAR
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Vicente Fox said that after he takes office in
December, he will appoint a ``czar'' to help resolve border issues
that have long strained relations between the United States and
Mexico. A chief duty, he said, would be to promote greater
cooperation between local governments on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: BOLSTERING THE RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The new right-wing party, the Canadian Alliance, won another
defection from its shrinking rival, the Progressive Conservative
Party, as Brian Pallister, a former Manitoba Cabinet minister, left
the ranks of the old party, known as the Tories. Pallister, a
former national Tory leadership candidate, said he would run for
Parliament from Manitoba in elections expected next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: GANDHI TOUR
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party president, Sonia Gandhi, the Italian-born
inheritor of the Nehru-Gandhi dynasty, will make her first trip
abroad as leader of the opposition for a conference of presiding
officers of parliaments in New York that begins on Aug. 31. The
delegation will also include the Bharatiya Janata Party's Pramod
Mahajan, the Samajwadi Party's Mulayam Singh Yadav and the
Nationalist Congress Party chief, Sharad Pawar.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: ANTI-CHRISTIAN SUSPECT
</P>
<P>
   Police in the southern state of Karnataka said they had arrested
a junior air force officer, Syed Hasan Ur Zama, as a suspect in the
bombings of Christian churches this summer. They said Zama, a
member of a Muslim organization called Deendar Anjuman, admitted to
passing information about the location of railway bridges and
defense posts to Pakistan. Most attacks on Christians have been
blamed on Hindu groups.
</P>
