<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-HN     08-17 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
GORE VOWS FIGHT AGAINST COMPLACENCY, SAYS HE'S `NOT SATISFIED' &HT;    (For use by clients of New York Times News Service)
 &HT;    By STEWART M. POWELL and
 &HT;    CHARLES J. LEWIS+
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES Al Gore, capping a 24-year career in politics with
the Democratic presidential nomination, tried to steal Republican
George W. Bush's campaign thunder Thursday night by insisting that
the Democratic successors to President Clinton are ``not
satisfied'' with mere prosperity and will now lead the nation ``on
a new journey to the best America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, 52, seeking to stake out a political persona apart from
Clinton, delighted cheering Democratic delegates with his firm
declaration that after almost eight years as Clinton's loyal vice
president, ``I stand here tonight as my own man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic nominee for president used his acceptance speech
to lay out policy proposals and relate personal anecdotes about his
life _ and deliver the campaign message that the nation's wealth
must be expanded to reach all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he was eager to build upon the nation's prosperity _
symbolized by expanding federal budget surpluses, the lowest
inflation rate in a generation and 22 million new jobs since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, let's make sure that our prosperity enriches not
just the few, but all working families,'' Gore said. ``And for all
our good times, I am not satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, hoping to draw a contrast with Bush's generalizations,
insisted that voters ``deserve to know specifically what a
candidate proposes to do.'' Gore called for tax cuts for working
families, health insurance for all children by 2004, expanded
child-care opportunities, reductions in the estate tax and ending
the so-called ``marriage penalty'' that requires married couples to
pay more federal taxes than they would if they filed separate
returns as single taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Gore said, he would be ``fighting for all the
people not just the people of one state or one district; not just
the wealthy or powerful all the people,'' according to excerpts of
his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke as Clinton's legal travails again leaped into the
spotlight, with the disclosure in Washington that special
prosecutor Robert Ray is weighing whether to indict Clinton for
obstruction of justice and perjury in connection with the cover-up
of his sexual dalliance with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Ray impaneled a federal grand jury on July 11 to hear evidence
in the episode that led to Clinton's impeachment by the House and
acquittal by the Senate, legal sources told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, trying to stand apart from Clinton, said he wanted America
to ``know me for who I truly am.'' He recounted his biography and
his practice of meeting ordinary people on a regular basis back in
Tennessee when he was in the House and Senate. He vowed to continue
the practice if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was nominated on Wednesday night by his eldest
daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, 27, emphasized that he has ``strong
values the love of my family, my faith, my love for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also tried to co-opt Bush's campaign theme of national
renewal and a restoration of morality, telling his audience that
America ``must challenge a culture with too much meanness and not
enough meaning.'' Just a few miles from the heart of America's
multibillion-dollar entertainment industry in Hollywood, Gore also
promised to ``give more power back to parents'' to protect children
from entertainment that ``glorifies violence and indecency.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president paid homage to Los Angeles, the city where
the American westward migration ended and where John F. Kennedy
declared the New Frontier in his 1960 convention address. ``Let us
set out a new journey to the best America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Harvard-educated son of a U.S. senator, repeatedly
allied himself with ``working families,'' vowing to stand by their
side against ``powerful forces and powerful interests (that) stand
in your way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore added: ``I want you to know this: I've taken on the
powerful forces. And as president, I'll stand up to them, and I'll
stand up for you.''
</P>
<P>
   National polls show Gore trailing Bush by as much as 10
percentage points. But a Harris poll released Wednesday showed Gore
getting a ``bounce'' as the Democratic convention began, enabling
him to edge ahead of Bush for the first time since the GOP
convention two weeks ago. The survey showed Gore leading Bush, 43
percent to 42 percent, with 6 percent favoring Green party
candidate Ralph Nader and 5 percent favoring disputed Reform party
candidate Pat Buchanan. The survey had a margin of error of 3
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers at the final night of the four-day Democratic National
Convention traced Gore's life from his roots in Carthage, Tenn., as
the son of a U.S. senator to his education at Harvard, his
volunteer Army service in Vietnam and his early career in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore, the 51-year-old wife of the nominee and an
experienced amateur photographer, introduced her husband for his
acceptance speech with a series of photos she has taken over the
years. ``Faith and family are at the center of Al's life,'' Mrs.
Gore said, adding: ``Al has always been there for our family and he
will always be there for yours.''.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Gore spent nearly two months crafting his address,
the most important political address of his 24 years in national
politics as a member of the House, the Senate and the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was literally the person at the typewriter on this,''
explained Tad Devine, a senior Gore adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and vice presidential candidate Joseph Lieberman, the
58-year-old senator from Connecticut, planned a four-day 400-mile
boat trip down the Mississippi River starting Friday. The journey
aboard the Mark Twain river boat would take them past the
battleground states of Wisconsin, Iowa, Illinois, Kentucky and
Missouri. Bush plans a post-convention raid on Gore's native
Tennessee on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Gore's address, the Bush campaign announced in
Austin, Texas, that the second-term Texas governor and GOP running
mate Dick Cheney would seek to negotiate a total of five campaign
debates this fall with Gore and Lieberman. Bush spokeswoman Karen
Hughes said Bush hoped to stage three debates with Gore and Cheney
hoped to reach agreement on two debates with Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's agreement to take part in three debates appeared designed
in part to underscore the Texan's confidence that he has the policy
detail and temperament to match Gore's mastery of the campaign
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane responded to the announcement by
saying Gore ``has been ready to debate for months. Their new-found
readiness to debate shows this campaign is tightening.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Washington, Ray's office neither confirmed nor denied that
the legal deliberations could lead to an indictment of Clinton
after he leaves office on Jan. 20. Ray emphasized in an ABC News'
interview in March when he succeeded special prosecutor Kenneth
Starr that he would determine ``whether crimes have been committed
and whether ... it is appropriate to bring charges'' against the
president after he leaves office in January.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert condemned the inopportune
revelation, saying: ``The timing of this leak reeks to high
heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of potential federal legal action against a high
ranking official at a sensitive moment in the election year
recalled the indictment of former Defense Secretary Casper
Weinberger by special prosecutor Lawrence E. Walsh four days before
the 1992 election. Aides to then-President George Bush blamed the
indictment for contributing to the Republican's loss to Clinton
that November.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, a federal judge threw out the one-count
indictment against Weinberger in connection with a six-year inquiry
into Reagan administration arms sales to Iran and the secret
diversion of some of the profits from the sales to provide arms to
anti-Marxist guerrillas battling the regime in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign criticized the disclosure Thursday, with the
Bush spokeswoman saying: ``We think the timing is wrong,'' adding:
``It's not appropriate for this type of announcement to be made on
the day that the vice president is going to accept the Democratic
nomination. This election is not about the past, it's about the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart M. Powell and Charles J. Lewis can be reached at
202-298-6920)
</P>
