<HEADER>
A5028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SCHOOL-SNACKS0818-COX     08-17 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SNACKS0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kids must avoid `triangle' of TV, fridge, computer
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Potato chips, popcorn, pudding cups,
chocolate cereals: There are cartloads of snack foods aimed at kids
out there, but it's a heavy load, nutritionists say.
</P>
<P>
   Fat- and sugar-laden snack and fast foods crowd the grocery
aisles. They tempt kids and time-stressed parents alike.
</P>
<P>
   Penelope Morgan says her two teenage boys are fairly typical of
today's kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``They snack on popcorn, fruit roll-ups and a bowl of cereal,''
she said. ``They do like fresh berries, but with sugar or whipped
cream on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick snacks often put convenience above nutrition. A fruit cup
with a peel-off lid is a lot simpler than washing, peeling and
cutting up fresh fruits. Opening a bag of cookies is easier than
baking a batch of low-fat muffins.
</P>
<P>
   But the unhealthful foods are contributing to what a recent
Newsweek story labels Generation XXL _ kids who tip the scales and
are off the weight charts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet weren't there always chips, and peanut butter and cookies in
the house after school? And haven't kids always snacked?
</P>
<P>
   What's happened, then, to make the normal ``kid food'' a dietary
pitfall?
</P>
<P>
   Foods are only part of a bigger problem, the experts say. TV,
computers and crime are partly to blame, according to doctors who
are watching the next generation develop health problems related to
weight at frighteningly early ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the kids are much less active than before. They get no
exercise; they have TVs and computers and sit inside with them
rather than going outside to play. Crime plays a role, too, making
parents afraid to let their kids go outdoors,'' said Dr. Renato
Dubois, a West Palm Beach pediatric cardiologist. Dubois is seeing
a jump in health problems related to weight gain. Hypertension and
diabetes are typical adult diseases that now affect numerous
children.
</P>
<P>
   Diet and exercise are the focus of those trying to help young
patients.
</P>
<P>
   A Louisiana doctor involved in a 12-year study on overweight
youngsters has developed a weight management program designed
specifically for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stewart Gordon, of Pennington Biomedical Research in Baton
Rouge, works on teaching families food choices and behaviors that
make for a lifetime of health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't just hand them a diet and tell them to do this, that
and that. We have them work with a dietitian, and work one-on-one
with them to modify their eating and lifestyle behaviors,'' he
said. ``Sometimes there's an exercise program involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, chief of pediatrics at LSU Health Sciences Center, said
kids are bombarded with candy, pizza, sodas and fries at every
party and outdoors event.
</P>
<P>
   Certain behaviors, including the after-school home ``triangle''
_ the path between the TV, the fridge and the computer _ are traps
that catch kids up in eating mindlessly, he said. ``They sit in
front of the computer or TV, eating _ not even realizing they're
eating, in some cases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He cites a study that showed that when kids were given
incentives not to watch TV _ even with no change in diets or
mention of weight loss _ kids lost weight automatically.
</P>
<P>
   But giving up TV is tough. Support from parents or peers is
crucial for success. ``We give them goals, and praise them when
they're met,'' Gordon said. Those in the program are taught how to
say no to pizza at a friend's slumber party, or how to make a more
healthful choice when given options. ``For these kids, turning down
a teacher's reward of a candy bar or doing some exercise instead of
watching TV is a big step.
</P>
<P>
   Weight gain in any person is difficult to manage, Gordon said,
but in children, it's tricky on several levels.
</P>
<P>
   Parents especially need to understand the fragile self-esteem of
an overweight child. When parents criticize their weight, Gordon
said, it's easy for kids to feel they don't measure up. ``They feel
unloved,'' he said. ``They can't separate their weight from the
rest of the package.''
</P>
<P>
   Too much focus on weight can lead adolescents, especially girls,
to develop eating disorders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Younger children, even if slightly overweight, don't need to
worry as much as older children, whose adult weight will be
determined by their weight in preteen and early teen years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see patients from 5 to 19 years old,'' Gordon said. ``It's
the adolescent age where we really focus. If a child is obese at 10
to 13 years old, the chances are 70 to 80 percent they will carry
the obesity over to adulthood.''
</P>
<P>
   The elementary school age is the prevention age, he said, but
parents should be aware that putting youngsters on a diet is
dangerous because they're still developing. Younger children always
should be under a doctor's care for weight problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can, however, buy foods that have more nutrition,
avoiding snack foods that tempt too much.
</P>
<P>
   They also can limit the number of hours spent indoors in front
of the TV or computer, and encourage outdoor activity _ maybe even
getting involved themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win situation,'' Gordon said. ``Parents feel
better, too, and are better role models for the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
