<HEADER>
A5031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SNACKS-TIPS0818-COX     08-17 0239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNACKS-TIPS0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Food tips for weight conscious kids
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   Tips for feeding kids with weight concerns:
</P>
<P>
   _ Learn about and choose healthful foods for your child. Involve
kids in reading labels as soon as they can read.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eat dinner as a family as often as possible, in a room away
from the TV.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make the family the focus of the meal _ not the food.
</P>
<P>
   _ Involve your child in food shopping, meal making and lunch-box
packing. They will eat what they prepare.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never criticize your child about his weight nor punish her for
weight gain. Be supportive, show concern about your child's health,
but show that your love isn't based on their appearance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Set realistic goals for weight loss or control, and reward the
positive steps toward that goal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never use food as a punishment or reward. For good deeds, buy
a new book, rent a favorite movie or dismiss a chore instead.
</P>
<P>
   _ The appeal of many unhealthful snacks is their convenience.
Make good food easy to eat: cube low-fat cheeses, keep whole-grain
crackers in easy-open tins and cut up fresh fruits to keep in the
fridge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unplug the TV and computer often. Make physical activity part
of the routine. Make time for walks and bike rides; the whole
family will benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
