<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5033 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-LIEBERMAN18-COX     08-17 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-LIEBERMAN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIEBERMAN SPOTLIGHTS HIS JEWISH ROOTS
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's one major difference between the
post-convention campaign tour that the newly minted Democratic
ticket will start Friday and the famous bus trip that Al Gore took
with Bill Clinton eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Before sundown on Friday, Gore's running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman of Connecticut, will leave the campaign behind him to
attend to sabbath services at a synagogue in Moline, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, an observant Jew, will not resume his campaign
activities until after sundown Saturday, a practice he intends to
follow for the duration of the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While in Los Angeles, Lieberman lost few opportunities to
highlight his Jewish heritage, often noting that he is the first
member of his faith to seek national office on a major party
ticket. In appearances before successive sets of minority groups,
Lieberman invariably said his selection was important because
``once barriers fall for one group, the doors of opportunity open
wider for all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go through my daily life I don't think about my
story,'' Lieberman said Thursday. He reflected on what has happened
to him in the 10 days since he joined the ticket in a brief
interview in his downtown hotel suite.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Lieberman added, ``when you come to a moment like this,
you look back and you want to tell your story. And I must say when
I do it at this stage of my life it makes me even more fervently
grateful to America and more fervently patriotic.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator noted, as he had the night before in his prime-time
speech to the delegates, that both his parents were born poor and
did not attend college.
</P>
<P>
   ``They encouraged me to work hard and get a good education,'' he
said. ``I got it at Yale and that opened doors for me.'' At the
elite university, Lieberman became chairman of the Yale Daily News,
a highly coveted post.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time several decades earlier when very few Jews were
admitted to Yale, and none of them would even think of aspiring to
become editors of the campus newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman likes to stress that all that has now changed, and
that it is still changing for the better. If he and Gore prevail in
November, the opportunities for minority groups to move up the
economic and social ladder will be even greater still, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand when you rise this level that questions get
asked,'' he said, referring to his religious beliefs and how they
might impact public policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I haven't been offended at all. ... There have been a few
statements that I think have been uninformed and that have shown
some bias. But from all the delegates here the questions have been
quite reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very confident that I haven't changed anything about
myself in the last 10 days. Sometimes there's been misinformation
out there. But it's been my nature to be open to new ideas. It's
also my nature to share my thought processes in public as I make up
my mind about issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I shouldn't do this,'' Lieberman mused.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
