<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GERMANY-TELECOM-ART-1     08-17 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-TELECOM-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIDS NEAR $50 BILLION FOR WIRELESS COMMUNICATIONS LICENSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS grafs 5 and 6 to clarify ) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAINZ, Germany _ The most expensive auction in history ended
Thursday, when six companies bid nearly $50 billion for licenses to
offer a new generation of wireless communications in Germany, the
biggest country in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The bids exceeded almost all expectations, and far exceeded the
$35.5 billion paid by many of the same companies for similar
``third-generation'' wireless licenses in Britain in April.
</P>
<P>
   The results have already sent a chill through financial markets,
as stock and bond investors fret not only about the billions the
bidders spent on licenses but the additional billions required for
building the new networks in a brutally competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   The results are something of a defeat for Europe's two biggest
wireless players _ Deutsche Telekom AG, the former German telephone
monopoly; and Vodafone Airtouch PLC, which owns Mannesmann
Mobilfunk and is a neck-and-neck rival with Telekom in the German
wireless market.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies had been intent on capturing enough licenses to
limit the number of new rivals. But despite pushing up the bids by
about $15 billion since Monday morning, they failed to knock out
smaller players.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Thursday's successful bidders will pay $15 billion
more than they would have paid if the bidding had stopped last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For consumers, the result promises the most intense
competition,'' said Klaus-Dieter Scheurle, head of Germany's
telecommunications regulatory agency and the auction's architect.
``This was the most favorable solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The results Thursday, just four months after the British
auction, are only part of a much larger project. All countries
throughout the European Union, and eventually in Central Europe,
are awarding new licenses. Analysts predict the total cost of
licenses across Europe could reach $150 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, which has 82 million people and is by far the biggest
country in Europe, is crucial for all rivals with pan-European
goals. Besides its size, the country is one of the most affluent in
the world, and its residents still use mobile phones less than
those of many neighboring countries. That gives it potentially more
room for growth.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the costs of controlling a continental chessboard are huge.
Beyond the cost of wireless licenses, the big players are spending
enormous sums acquiring existing carriers. Just Thursday, for
example, BT of Britain announced an agreement to pay 6.6 billion
euros for a controlling stake in Viag Interkom, Germany's
fourth-largest wireless company.
</P>
<P>
   That deal comes in the wake of France Telecom's recent purchase
of Orange PLC, which owns Britain's second-largest wireless
network, and Deutsche Telekom's bid to acquire a young U.S.
wireless carrier, Voicestream Communications, for $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Most of Thursday's winning bidders are intent on owning
pan-European and even global wireless networks. Besides Deutsche
Telekom and Vodafone, they include Mobilcom AG, a fast-growing
German telephone carrier that is backed by France Telecom; Viag
Interkom, now to be owned by BT; a consortium called Group 3G,
backed by Telefonica SA of Spain and Sonera Oy, the Finnish
telephone company; and E-Plus Hutchison, a consortium led by KPN
Mobile of the Netherlands, NTT DoCoMo of Japan and Hutchison
Whampoa of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, these new wireless networks will provide the capacity
and technology to offer far faster and more sophisticated data
services than those now available. Supporters of third-generation
networks talk of high-speed mobile Internet access, scores of
``mobile commerce'' applications and even the ability to receive
streams of video over a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, nobody is yet sure which services will prove
practical and what consumers will be willing to pay for them. But
most analysts say ordinary mobile telephone service will become
steadily cheaper and will no longer provide the booming revenue
that wireless operators have enjoyed during the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   The big bet is that as mobile telephones become almost
ubiquitous but far less profitable, exotic new data services will
more than make up for the difference.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``If you don't believe that the average revenue per month will
double over the next 10 years, then there really isn't any point in
participating in the auctions,'' said Holger Grawe, a
telecommunications analyst at WestLB Panmeure in Duesseldorf.
</P>
<P>
   He, along with many others, is convinced the bet will ultimately
pay off.
</P>
<P>
   But in the short term, investors are increasingly nervous.
Deutsche Telekom's stock has plunged by almost half this year,
mostly in the wake of the British auctions that generated
unexpected high prices. Duncan Warwick-Champion, a
telecommunications analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's in London, said all
the companies in Thursday's auction are poised for possible
downgrades in their credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly vulnerable, Warwick-Champion said, is the Dutch
telephone carrier KPN, which has already teamed with BellSouth
Corp. to acquire control of the E-Plus wireless network in Germany.
But Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom and BT will also be evaluated
for possible downgrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these sorts of auctions are short-sighted and
counterproductive,'' said Eden Zoller, a senior consultant at Ovum,
a telecommunications research firm in London. ``They would all be
much better spending their money on developing new services.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the mammoth cost of wireless licenses in Europe,
investors are also digesting the impact of acquisitions like France
Telecom's purchase of Orange and Deutsche Telekom's plan to acquire
Voicestream. Deutsche Telekom's bid may be blocked by U.S.
regulators, adding to the uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Bernd Eylert, an executive at Deutsche Telekom who is also
chairman of an industry group called the UMTS Forum, said the
enormous license fees could put pressure on operators to build
their networks as fast as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But other executives were clearly frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have had it for 30 billion marks less,'' said Peik
von Bestenbostel, a spokesman for Viag Interkom, which had
announced several days ago that it would seek only two rather than
three licenses allowed under the bidding rules.
</P>
<P>
   Another executive, speaking privately, called it ``the worst
possible scenario'' _ high license prices and the maximum number of
competitors at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Under the German government's scheme, 12 licenses were up for
auction but a company had to win two licenses to establish a
service. Theoretically, it was possible for four companies to
emerge with all the licenses, but most experts had predicted that
five companies would prevail _ two with three licenses apiece and
three smaller players with two apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extraordinarily high prices, von Bestenbostel said
his company was ready to plow ahead. ``We think it is an
extraordinary opportunity, and we are ready for a market with six
players,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
