u f BC-FURNITURE-OUTLOOK-NYT     08-17 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURNITURE-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKRUPTCIES DEFY GROWTH IN FURNITURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two recent failures by furniture sellers show that the furniture
business is joining the retail clothing business in a much more
competitive arena where poor execution is increasingly fatal.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Heilig-Meyers Co., the largest furniture
retailer in the country, with $2.3 billion in annual sales,
announced that it was filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection
and that it would close 302 stores, most in rural areas in the
Southeast and California.
</P>
<P>
   The news came the same day that Living.com, an Internet retailer
with losses but glamorous partners like Starbucks and Amazon.com,
said that it had filed for bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those announcements, the furniture industry is not
moribund. Thanks to a strong economy that is driving home sales and
a Martha Stewart-like national obsession with renovations, sales
have been growing at more than 5 percent a year since 1992 and now
stand at $61 billion.
</P>
<P>
   With consumer spending starting to ease, growth in furniture
sales is expected to slow to 2 percent to 3 percent this year. But
analysts contend the bankruptcies speak more to heightened
competition than to overall weakness in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened at Heilig-Meyers is extremely unfortunate,
because it didn't have to be,'' said Jerry Epperson, a furniture
industry analyst and a managing director of Mann, Armistad and
Epperson, an investment banking firm in Richmond, Va. ``The
industry is having the best of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Living.com was the less significant of the two bankruptcy
filings because selling furniture over the Internet is still an
experiment that many feel will not pan out soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need for the consumer to touch and feel and sit and judge
comfort cannot be addressed over the Web,'' said Jeff Butler, a
principal at the retail consulting firm of Kurt Salmon Associates.
</P>
<P>
   While Heilig-Meyers faced numerous problems, including a lack of
cash flow caused by an unwieldy string of acquisitions, the
merchant was struggling because it still hewed to the old school of
furniture retailing. Traditionally, furniture stores were more
banks than merchants. That is, they made money not so much by
selling sofas and chairs but by offering credit to low-income
people to buy merchandise and then making a profit on the terms of
the loan. This focus on financing as opposed to product explains
why many older furniture chains were grim places with ugly stock
and dim lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Such operations have been hit hard by credit card companies that
lowered income requirements, allowing even relatively poor
customers to shop wherever they liked, and by a huge increase in
competition.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there has been an explosion of rent-to-buy
retailers. Such retailers offer higher prices, but if customers
fail to make a payment for a large-screen TV or recliner, it does
not hurt their credit record _ the companies simply come and
repossess the rental item.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the low- to mid-price category is also undergoing
startling change. Rooms to Go, a chain of furniture stores founded
in 1990 that offers discounts to buyers willing to pay for a
package of merchandise for one room, is already the third-largest
furniture seller in the country, with $720 million in annual sales.
In addition, nonfurniture retailers like Costco, Sam's Club, and
Lowe's sell some furniture, much of it at competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
   The competition in the mid- and upper-price range has also
increased with chain stores like Pottery Barn and Crate and Barrel,
which sell lifestyle and ambience with their leather club chairs
and pewter picture frames.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customer wants to buy in a place that makes them feel good
and comfortable,'' said Gerald Birnbach, chairman of the Rowe Cos.,
which supplies to those chains and others like J.C. Penney and
Jordan's in Massachusetts. ``They are talking about value, but not
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry is retarded when it comes to change,'' he added.
``That is why the young aggressive ones are catching the upswing.
The ones doing it the same old way are going dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 2101EDT &QL; 
