<HEADER>
A5038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DVD-DECODE-610(2TAKES     08-17 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DVD-DECODE-610(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE HALTS PROGRAM TO CRACK DVD FILM CODES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Norway)  By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge in Manhattan ruled Thursday that a
Web site operator cannot distribute a computer program used to
crack codes that prevent the piracy of movies.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, a victory for the motion picture industry, applies
only to the Web site operator, Eric Corley, and his company, 2600
Enterprises. But experts on both sides of the issue agreed that the
decision could have far greater reach as the courts hammer out
legal guidelines that will govern the rules of commerce and free
speech in the digital world.
</P>
<P>
   Like recent decisions concerning the unauthorized transmission
of music over the Internet, the battle over the distribution of
code-breaking programs used to copy digital versatile discs, or
DVDs, has been closely watched by the entertainment industry and
Internet groups.
</P>
<P>
   Motion picture companies argued that they had invested
tremendous amounts of money on the assurance, through
long-recognized copyright laws, that they would have the exclusive
right to sell their movies to the public. Their opponents argued
that new federal laws designed to protect those copyrights were
overly restrictive, both by unreasonably blocking the legitimate
use of digital movies and by illegally infringing on their right to
free speech under the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In a detailed analysis, Judge Lewis A. Kaplan tried to weigh
both positions and to measure Congress' 1998 guidelines for
Internet copyright, known as the Digital Millennium Copyright Act.
Kaplan found that Congress had clearly intended to prohibit the
distribution of software used to circumvent copyright protections,
something he said the defendant's Web site did by posting the
code-breaking program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each side is entitled to its views,'' Kaplan wrote. ``In our
society, however, clashes of competing interests like this are
resolved by Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan found that the Digital Millennium Copyright Act, which
prohibits the distribution of software designed to circumvent
copyright protections, did not violate Corley's First Amendment
right to free speech, and he prohibited Corley from posting the
program in the future or from establishing Internet links with
other sites that provided copies of the code.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, defense lawyers asserted that Kaplan's
analysis was incorrect and said they would appeal. Martin Garbus,
Corley's lawyer, said the decision would have made its way to
higher courts no matter what the outcome because ``this is an issue
that has to be decided by the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Kaplan sits on the district court, which is the trial
court of the federal system, his decision is not binding on other
federal courts and is subject to review by the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals. But the judge's decision has considerable
persuasive force for other courts both because it is the first time
the law has been tested and because the Manhattan court is among
the more prestigious district courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very important case dealing with how intellectual
material is going to be transmitted over the Web,'' Garbus said
Thursday. ``The Internet, as a free exchange of information, is
crippled by this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the motion picture industry said the case was not
about free speech, but about efforts to circumvent copyright
protections that were established by Congress. ``What we sued the
defendants for was circumventing our protective device,'' said Leon
P. Gold, the lawyer for the movie companies. Gold likened the
code-breaking programs to a key that could be used to break into a
bank vault.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot steal any other person's property, even if it is
copyrighted property,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The decoding program at issue in the case is called DeCSS,
because it counters the encryption system known as CSS, for content
scrambling system. It was devised by a Norwegian teen-ager and made
available, among other places, on Corley's New York-based Web site,
2600.com. The movie industry filed suit in January and won a
temporary injunction against Corley. Separate cases are pending in
California and Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Although Thursday's decision is among the first to balance free
speech and copyright protection on the Internet, the courts have
been measuring the tension between the two concepts for well over
100 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment protects speech, and the copyright statute
restricts the uses of speech,'' said William W. Fisher, a professor
at Harvard Law School. ``There is a tension between these two.''
</P>
<P>
   A traditional exception to copyright law has been the concept of
``fair use,'' which usually means the excerpting of material for
scholarly, journalistic or artistic purposes. A book review that
quotes from a novel is typically not a violation of copyright law
because it is considered fair use.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress severely restricted the fair-use concept in the
Digital Millennium Copyright Act, in part as a recognition that it
is much easier to copy and distribute copyrighted material over the
Internet than by photocopying or videotaping. The defendants tried
to use the fair use concept to defend their distribution of the
code-breaking program, arguing that it could be used by scholars
and others to make legitimate excerpts of movies. But Kaplan denied
that claim, saying that Congress considered this possibility when
it wrote the law and ``clearly faced up to and dealt with this
question.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Congress listened to arguments about the need to protect
copyrighted works and the counterarguments that the protection
would inhibit people with legitimate needs to excerpt those works,
``and it struck a balance among the competing interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendants also argued that computer code, including the
code-breaking programs, is a form of speech and that Congress
cannot lawfully restrict their ability to transmit the code under
the First Amendment. But Kaplan rejected that argument as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer code is not purely expressive,'' he said, ``any more
than the assassination of a political figure is purely a political
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan found that because the restriction of the code-breaking
program was not based on the idea it conveyed, Congress had greater
latitude to establish restrictions. He ruled that the law was
``content neutral'' and ``in furtherance of important governmental
interests that does not unduly restrict expressive activities.''
</P>
<P>
   In a more limited section of his opinion, the judge also forbade
Corley from establishing Internet links with other Web sites that
made the code-breaking program available. But Kaplan made it clear
that the links to the sites would be unlawful only if someone could
prove that the person that established the links did so with the
express purpose of transmitting the code-breaking program.
</P>
<P>
   He said the person establishing the link would have to know the
program was on the site, know that the program was illegal, and
establish the link ``for the purpose of disseminating that
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An essential ingredient, as explained above, is a desire to
bring about the dissemination,'' he wrote. ``Hence a strong
requirement of that forbidden purpose is an essential prerequisite
to any liability for linking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
