<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SNACKS-RECIPES0818-CO     08-17 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNACKS-RECIPES0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enjoy (low-fat) sweets, in moderation
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Nutritionists say there's nothing wrong
with sweeteners and that everyone needs a certain amount of fat.
It's when these ingredients make up most of the calories in a whole
diet that they become detrimental.
</P>
<P>
   Here are recipes featuring foods that are low in sugars and fats
that you can use for healthful snack alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   FROZEN BANANA PIE
</P>
<P>
   6 very ripe bananas, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup natural or light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 pre-baked pie crust (graham cracker is good)
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 cups fresh berries, or other fruit for a garnish
</P>
<P>
   Put all the ingredients except pie crust and berries into a
blender or food processor. Blend or process until smooth. Pour into
baked pie shell and freeze until solid.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: You can freeze in custard cups if desired and eliminate
the pie shell.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the freezer 15 minutes before serving; garnish with
fresh berries or other fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   This pie is a snap to make and can be a frozen banana custard if
you don't want to put it into a pie shell.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   PUMPKIN MUFFINS
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pumpkin puree
</P>
<P>
   3/4 to 1 cup maple syrup (depending on sweetness of pumpkin)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons light olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whole-wheat pastry flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup walnuts, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350(degrees).
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the pumpkin puree, maple syrup and olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together flour, baking soda, salt and spices; add walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Blend dry ingredients into the wet ones just until mixed; do not
beat.
</P>
<P>
   Divide batter equally into 18 or 24 greased mini-muffin cups.
(If using paper liners, spray with vegetable spray to prevent
sticking).
</P>
<P>
   Bake 25-30 minutes or until muffins spring back at the touch.
</P>
<P>
   Cool slightly before removing muffins.
</P>
<P>
   Make these muffins in mini-muffin tins; they can be portioned
out in smaller amounts.
</P>
<P>
   The ``secret'' healthy ingredient in these cookies is tofu.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell, and no one will know.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are volatile oils in the sesame seeds and almonds,
it's a good idea to keep these cookies in the refrigerator for best
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   SESAME ALMOND COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup whole-wheat pastry flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup unbleached white flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sesame seeds, toasted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raw almonds, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces silken tofu, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup light olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup light brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350(degrees).
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, sift together the flours, baking powder and salt. Mix
in sesame seeds and chopped almonds.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, mash the tofu and combine with the olive oil,
brown sugar and almond extract.
</P>
<P>
   Using a rubber spatula, fold wet ingredients into the dry ones.
Roll the mixture into 1-inch balls, flatten between your palms, and
place them on ungreased baking sheets. Bake cookies about 10
minutes or until edges begin to brown.
</P>
<P>
   Lift from sheets with spatula to wire racks for cooling.
</P>
<P>
   Store in airtight tins kept in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   (Above recipes from ``Eating Well for Optimum Health,'' by
Andrew Weil, M.D., Knopf, 2000.)
</P>
<P>
   BANANA FRENCH TOAST
</P>
<P>
   1 banana
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup nonfat milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 egg white
</P>
<P>
   4 slices whole-wheat bread
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients except bread into a blender and puree.
</P>
<P>
   Pour mixture into a shallow soup bowl. Dip each slice of bread
on both sides and place on a nonstick cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 15 minutes at 350(degrees), or grill on a nonstick
grill.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately with fruit syrup, sliced fruit or honey.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GRANOLA DATE BARS
</P>
<P>
   1 cup rolled oats
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Grape-Nuts
</P>
<P>
   1 cup crisped rice cereal
</P>
<P>
   1 cup oat-bran flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dates, pitted and chopped (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 110-ounce jar no-sugar apricot preserves
</P>
<P>
   3 egg whites, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   Note: To chop dates, sprinkle them with a little flour first;
alternately, use vegetable spray on the cutting knife to prevent
sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Place dry ingredients in a bowl with the dates. Add egg whites
and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Line a 15 1/2-by-10 1/2-inch cookie tray with parchment paper.
Press mixture into tray.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 15 minutes at 350(degrees); bars will be partially
baked. Remove from oven.
</P>
<P>
   Lift the parchment paper with the partially baked bars on it
from the tray and set aside. Reline the tray with another piece of
parchment paper. Invert the bars onto the new paper. Remove the old
paper and discard.
</P>
<P>
   Return the bars to the oven, and continue baking for another 15
minutes or until a light golden brown. remove from the oven. Cut
into 1 1/2-by-2-inch bars while still warm.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 50 bars.
</P>
<P>
   FRESH APPLE SODA
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup apple juice concentrate
</P>
<P>
   2 cup sparkling mineral water or sodium-free seltzer ice
</P>
<P>
   apple slices for garnish
</P>
<P>
   cinnamon sticks for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Combine apple juice concentrate and mineral water or seltzer and
mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Pour over ice and garnish with apple slices and cinnamon sticks
if desired.
</P>
<P>
   (Above recipes from ``The New Pritikin Program'' by Robert
Pritikin, Pocket Paperback, 1991.)
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT BUTTER COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup plus 1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup natural peanut butter (no sugar added)
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups unbleached or all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375(degrees).
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine 2/3 cup of the sugar, the butter or
margarine, and buttermilk.. With a mixer, beat on medium speed
until creamy.
</P>
<P>
   Add peanut butter, egg and vanilla. Beat on low speed to mix
well. In a medium bowl, combine flour, baking powder, baking soda
and salt. Stir into the peanut butter mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Drop the dough by teaspoonfuls onto an ungreased baking sheet.
Flatten the dough with a fork dipped in the remaining tablespoon of
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 10 to 12 minutes or until lightly browned. Cool cookies
on a rack for 10 minutes before removing them from the pan. Allow
to cool completely on a rack before storing them in a tin.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 40 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from ``Jeanne Jones's Homestyle Cooking Made Healthy,''
by Jeanne Jones, Rodale, 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
