u a BC-LEE-TRIAL-565&AMP;ADD-NYT     08-17 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-TRIAL-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI AGENT ADMITS HIS TESTIMONY AGAINST NUCLEAR SCIENTIST WAS
MISLEADING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ An FBI agent admitted in federal court here
Thursday that he had provided misleading testimony last December
that made a Los Alamos scientist accused of mishandling nuclear
weapons secrets appear deceptive when he had not been.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is critical because the government has successfully
argued since last December that the scientist, Dr. Wen Ho Lee, be
held without bail in part because his deceptions, along with the
vast amount of nuclear secrets that remain unaccounted for,
suggested he was a major threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to incarcerate Lee after his indictment in December,
the judge, James A. Parker, had cited Lee's alleged deceptions
among the reasons for denying bail. Lee is in the middle of his
third attempt to be released on bail, and the government is now
acknowledging what amounts to a pattern of misleading testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is the first person ever to be accused under the specific
atomic energy statute cited in his 59-count indictment, and a
growing number of Asian-Americans and civil rights proponents have
rallied to his side saying that he was singled out for prosecution
at least in part because of his Chinese ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Messemer, an FBI supervisory special agent, had said
under oath last December that when Lee improperly downloaded a
trove of weapons secrets six years ago onto portable computer
tapes, he had lied to a colleague in order to gain access to the
colleague's computer. Messemer had testified that Lee told the
other scientist that he was just going to download a resume, which
was not true.
</P>
<P>
   But since December, Lee's defense lawyers have gained access to
that other scientist's previous grand jury testimony, and it does
not mention that Lee spoke of a resume.
</P>
<P>
   Messemer acknowledged that fact on the stand Thursday, but said
his misleading testimony represented ``an honest mistake,'' and
that it was not intentional. Messemer insisted nevertheless that,
in other areas, Lee had been deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   There were, however, several other instances in which the
defense appeared to show that the government had misled the judge
in describing Lee's supposed deceptions. Messemer had testified at
the December bail hearing that Lee had not disclosed certain
contacts with Chinese scientists during officially sanctioned,
professional visits to Beijing during the 1980s. But the defense
attorneys have since obtained a report Lee filed after a 1986 trip
in which he listed seven Chinese scientists with whom he spoke
during his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Messemer also acknowledged that, though Lee clearly disclosed
the contacts, he was never subsequently questioned about them.
Messemer also disclosed that he never consulted Lee's trip report
before testifying in December. He still maintained that Lee had
been deceptive because he had not been open about ``the full nature
and scope'' of his contacts.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends that until Lee faced questioning a year
ago, he failed to report a highly suspicious meeting he had with a
Chinese scientist in his hotel room during a 1988 visit. The
government also insists that Lee's downloading of the huge library
of weapons secrets was itself a deliberate act of deception that
took more than 40 hours of computer time and knowingly violated
rules on the handling of sensitive data.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   None of the statements in court here Thursday or Wednesday
appeared decisive. The government presented weapons experts who
insisted Lee's downloading was unprecedented and a grave threat to
national security, since the data, in hostile hands, could alter
the global balance of power. The defense offered its own experts
who insisted that most of the information was already public and
that its use to another country was extremely limited.
</P>
<P>
   In one tense exchange, Paul Robinson, the president of the
Sandia National Laboratories, said that one of the defense experts,
Harold M. Agnew, a former director of the Los Alamos National
Laboratory, had simply not understood the information Lee
downloaded or had not understood the threat posed by Lee's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Agnew fired off an affidavit Thursday in response to that
testimony, saying, ``What Paul said is a bunch of bull,'' and then
refuted parts of Robinson's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In two other areas Thursday, defense lawyers tried to show that
that government witnesses had provided misleading evidence in
December. Messemer had said Lee had failed to disclose
correspondence he conducted with some Chinese scientists, saying
that he had only exchanged Christmas cards. On Thursday, one of
Lee's lawyers, Mark Holscher, produced a transcript of an interview
with Lee and the FBI on March 5, 1999, in which Lee did discuss
correspondence with the Chines scientists.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Messemer had said in December that during the
search of Lee's home, the FBI had discovered letters that Lee had
sent to a number of foreign scientific institutes seeking a job.
The prosecution has said in previous filings that they believe the
principal reason Lee improperly downloaded the nuclear secrets was
to enhance his job prospects with the foreign institutes.
</P>
<P>
   But under questioning, Messemer acknowledged Thursday that the
FBI found some letters but had no evidence they were either mailed
or received by the foreign institutions, which were in countries
like Australia, France, Singapore and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The bail hearing will resume on Friday. Parker has allowed the
examinations and cross-examinations of the witnesses, much of it in
closed sessions because it involved classified information, to
stretch on far longer than is usual at bail hearings.
</P>
</TEXT>
