<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHIPPER-CONTRACT0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones gets chance to `finish it' in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In nine months Chipper Jones has gone from winning the
NL MVP award to living it as he and the Braves sealed their $120
million deal on Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 28, had agreed to a contract extension worth $90 million
over six years, with two option years worth $15 million apiece. It
is both the richest and the longest contract in Braves' history.
The first overall pick of the 1990 draft was 18 when he first
signed with the Braves for a bonus of $275,000. He could be 36 _
and making that kind of money every three games _ before he has any
more big decisions to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the ultimate as far as a baseball player goes,
especially for me, having been born in this organization and grown
up in this organization,'' said Jones, whose options will
automatically kick in if he makes either 450 plate appearances or
the All-Star team the previous season. ``Hearing from so many
different players around the league, how lucky I am to be here and
have this opportunity to stay in one place for such a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tremendous feeling for me because I would certainly
love nothing more than to start my career here and finish it
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a career .302 hitter who has scored 100 runs, driven in
100 and homered at least 20 times in four of his five major league
seasons, helped convince the Braves to invest with both his
consistency and his ability to fight back from and play through
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a young man here who has established himself as one of
the real cornerstone players of this franchise,'' Braves general
manager John Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones received $8 million of his new contract in a signing
bonus, which means he can go ahead with his childhood plans of
running a ranch with his father. He's got his eye on some land in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of money is really unheard of and it's almost
embarrassing to talk about,'' Jones said. ``It's not where I came
from. I came from middle class. We had to work hard for what we
got. To have this given to me is a little overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his teammates were a little wide-eyed Thursday too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch out for Sammy Sosa, Alex Rodriguez and Andruw Jones when
he comes up,'' Brian Jordan said. ``The price tag has just gone
sky-high.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
