<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-LAWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL-TOWN LAWYER TAKES ON BIG TIRE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By JANE TANNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCALA, Fla. _ When Bruce R. Kaster started suing tire
manufacturers more than a decade ago, he worked alone facing
legions of lawyers hired by corporate conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Most often he went up against Michelin. Many cases were settled
out of court, but of those that went to trial, Kaster lost more
than he won. By his account, the companies' lawyers heckled him
about the losses in front of his clients and stonewalled requests
for information. He said they expected to wear him down until he
folded and went away.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaster did not go away. Instead, he pursued case after case.
Win or lose, he held onto case documents and stacks of depositions
and trial testimony. Before long, he had crammed hundreds of
thousands of pages into his offices in Ocala, a rural horse farm
community in central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he set about schooling himself in tire manufacturing,
watching videos, being tutored by experts and assiduously studying
processes like how rubber adheres to metal. The more often
corporate lawyers erected roadblocks, the more passionately Kaster
tried to knock them down.
</P>
<P>
   To win that war, he collaborated with other trial lawyers,
usually sharing his archives for no fee. This stockpile of data has
helped win cases for him and others. ``These are multinational
corporations,'' Kaster said. ``They thought, `What do I have to
worry about a small-town lawyer?' ''
</P>
<P>
   He does not mind being called a small-town lawyer, but Kaster,
54, prefers the term ``cowboy'' or ``Florida cracker.'' On most
days he works in jeans and cowboy boots. He likes to spend his free
time hunting hogs or tending cattle on a small ranch he owns. Once,
Kaster said, he rode a horse into a bar, had a drink without
dismounting and rode back out.
</P>
<P>
   He needs the recreation to relax between courtroom battles. He
is often on the road, backing up other lawyers rather than arguing
cases himself. Because there is no commercial airline service in
Ocala, he routinely drives an hour and 15 minutes to Orlando to fly
to cities throughout the United States. (He drives a Ford Explorer,
but replaced the Firestone tires with Pirellis and replaced the
factory-installed shock absorbers with a heavy-duty alternative.)
</P>
<P>
   Kaster works as a consultant, preparing expert witnesses for
trial or sitting as co-counsel. He and others in the tightly knit
group of lawyers who go after tire makers exchange information.
``When we need something, we call him,'' says Randy James, a Kansas
City, Kan., lawyer with 18 years of experience with defective-tire
cases.
</P>
<P>
   A defense lawyer who has gone up against Kaster says his
warehouse of documents and in-depth knowledge of tires makes Kaster
a threat to manufacturers, not his courtroom finesse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are worried he's got something that will hurt them,''
said the lawyer, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``He's a
great librarian, not necessarily a field marshal in the tactics and
strategy of the courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Even his critics concede that Kaster is tenacious and often
successful in his efforts to uncover details about tire defects.
Over six months in 1998, he made repeated trips to Decatur, Ill.,
seeking evidence about the Bridgestone Corp. factory there. He
knocked on doors and spent hours at a Bob Evans restaurant sipping
coffee with former employees to tease out information about
suspected quality-control problems.
</P>
<P>
   The workers were willing to open up, Kaster said, in part
because he had been a member of the Communications Workers of
America union when he installed telephones while attending Virginia
Tech. The Decatur Bridgestone workers had recently been embroiled
in a labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bulldog in discovery,'' said David Steelman, executive
director of the Attorneys Information Exchange Group, a lawyers'
cooperative on automobile and defective-product cases based in
Birmingham, Ala. ``He stays with an issue until he gets the
answers. He starts from ground zero and is relentless until he
finds out what happened to cause the defect.''
</P>
<P>
   Steelman said Kaster had contributed the largest share of
information to the group.
</P>
<P>
   Kaster, who earned a law degree from the University of Florida
after serving as a paratrooper in Vietnam, moved to Ocala in 1975
to work with Buddy McKay. McKay went on to serve as Florida's
lieutenant governor under Lawton Chiles, then lost a bid for
governor against Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Kaster defended companies and insurers against
lawsuits. He switched to plaintiffs' work in the mid-1980s when a
client at a factory he was defending asked him to help out
relatives whose father had been killed in a car accident. Although
he represented major insurers, Kaster took the case because the
Canadian trucking company involved was covered by Lloyd's of
London, which did not present a conflict. The company settled.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Kaster took on his first tire case, suing the
Uniroyal Goodrich Tire Co. on behalf of a teen-age boy who had been
rendered a paraplegic in an auto accident. Kaster battled with
opposing lawyers over how many similar cases had been filed, and
the company settled during jury deliberations for $2 million. He
has had a few other big successes, including a $5 million verdict
in a Connecticut case, but he says he spends much of his time
providing information without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kaster, in tandem with other lawyers, has four cases on
the dockets, with a fifth set to be filed. All are against
Bridgestone/Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got angry about misleading and false information by the tire
industry,'' Kaster said. ``I've stayed angry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
