u s BC-FBC-VPI-PREVIEW0818-C     08-17 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VPI-PREVIEW0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trust transforms Beamer's Hokies
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKSBURG, Va. _ From his office, Frank Beamer can show you
just how far he, and Virginia Tech football, have come. A flick of
a switch and the floor-to-ceiling slatted blinds swivel, then slide
open on tracks to reveal a panoramic view of Lane Stadium. Gazing
out the window, Beamer's no longer the 1999 national coach of the
year but a frightened college freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played in the first game here,'' he said. ``Well, not play.
I stood on the sideline.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1965, Beamer was an 18-year-old defensive back
the day the Virginia Tech and Maryland freshmen teams christened
Lane Stadium. Beamer remembers little of the game, not even the
result, much less the final score. The feeling, though, lingers
still. Always will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so down after that game,'' he said. ``I didn't play.
I'll never forget how I felt.''
</P>
<P>
   How all the typical freshman fears flashed through his mind:
Would he ever play here? Had he picked the wrong school? Fast
forward 35 years, to a bright summer's day in southwest Virginia,
and it's clear Beamer made the right decision. So did his alma
mater when it hired him in 1987 and stood by him in the dark days
of '92.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I've really been proud of,'' said Beamer, ``is
there's not many jobs you can go into and change the image of that
job.''
</P>
<P>
   This job's one of them. From the depths of that disastrous 1992
season, when Beamer's sixth Tech team went 2-8-1 and many Hokie
fans screamed for his ouster, Beamer has built one of the premier
programs in the country. Last fall, the Hokies climbed to No. 2 in
the polls after completing the first 11-0 regular season in school
history and setting for a date with top-ranked Florida State in the
Sugar Bowl for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 28-7 in New Orleans, Tech rallied behind
its incomparable freshman quarterback, Michael Vick, to take a
29-28 lead. While FSU won 46-29, Virginia Tech still finished No. 2
in the AP poll and became one of just eight schools to play in
bowls in each of the past seven seasons. The others: FSU, Florida,
Nebraska, Tennessee, Penn State, Michigan and Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   And now, guess who's coming back to Blacksburg? ``ESPN College
GameDay,'' the cable network's pregame show, which will air here
Aug. 27. Despite losing 11 starters (eight from the nation's
stingiest defense, including All-American end and Lombardi and
Nagurski awards winner Corey Moore), Virginia Tech was picked to
host Georgia Tech in the BCA Bowl a week from Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that. College football will kick off the 2000 season
here, 40 miles west of Roanoke, in this charming little town whose
full-time 11,000 population is less than half of Tech's
25,000-student body. Here, in Lane Stadium, now enlarged from its
original 40,000 capacity to 55,075, with next year's 12,000-seat
expansion due to push capacity near 70,000.
</P>
<P>
   All because Vick _ the most profane four-letter word to college
defenses everywhere and likely to become the first sophomore to win
the Heisman Trophy _ is back. And because Beamer stayed, rejecting
several coaching overtures after transforming Tech into a national
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wanted both ways,'' Beamer said, grinning. ``Wanted
to get the heck out of town, and wanted to keep me around town.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what's amazing?'' he asked. ```GameDay' is back here
for the third time in eight games (ESPN televised last year's
Syracuse and Miami games). They say they never come back twice in a
season. That kind of makes a statement. Things have certainly
changed around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Changed for the better-than-anyone-in-the-Big East Hokies,
who've won two outright league titles and one co-championship in
the past five years. Last season, Tech sold out every home game for
the first time. This year, it had more than 35,000 season ticket
applications, nearly double 1998's total. The university has been
richly rewarded for its faith in Beamer in the face of severe
criticism after '92's disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not many coaches who would've hung around, if you go
2-8-1 in your fifth or sixth year,'' Beamer said. ``But the
(administration) here could really see we had (laid) the foundation
OK. We just had to hang around and play enough games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies went 9-3 in 1993, won the Independence Bowl and never
looked back. Beamer's compiled a 64-20 record the past seven
seasons, doing it with swift, attacking defenses, remarkable
special teams and a potent offense. In '99, Tech led the nation in
scoring (averaging 41.4 points) behind Vick. Vick passed for 1,840
yards, ran for 585, accounted for 20 touchdowns, led the nation in
passing efficiency (a 180.37 rating) and was third in the Heisman
Trophy voting, matching the highest finish by a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Now Vick has seven other returning offensive starters and Tech
still is ranked from 10th to 12th in most preseason polls. And
Beamer almost has the Hokies where he wants them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal,'' he said, ``would be that in 10 years, if you said
name me the top 10 teams in the country, everybody would say
Virginia Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
