<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEWIS-FINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS OF RAVENS FINED $250,000 FOR LYING TO POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Football League fined Baltimore Ravens linebacker
Ray Lewis $250,000 Thursday for lying to the police about his
involvement in an incident that resulted in the stabbing deaths of
two men outside an Atlanta nightclub after the Super Bowl last
January.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue also said Lewis would be fined
another $250,000 if he violated the terms of his 12-month probation
in Fulton County, Ga. It was there on June 5 that Lewis pleaded
guilty to a misdemeanor count of obstruction of law enforcement
officers and interference with a law enforcement investigation in
connection with the death of the two men the night of January 31.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Lewis' lawyers and the NFL Players Association,
made public by the NFL Thursday, Tagliabue addressed criticism from
the news media and others that Lewis should have been suspended.
Tagliabue said that since Lewis was wrongly charged with murder, he
had already suffered significant harm to his reputation as well as
financial damage. Therefore, a suspension was not warranted,
Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   A fine, however, was warranted, Tagliabue said, because no NFL
player should lie to the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Lewis was not entirely truthful and candid with the police
in his initial interview, and he counseled others that night to say
nothing about what had happened,'' Tagliabue said in the letter.
``This misconduct no doubt fueled a public perception that he had
something to hide. In doing so, he put his own livelihood and
reputation needlessly at risk, and he caused great harm to other
NFL players and to the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unlawful obstruction related to a very serious occurrence
_ a double homicide,'' Tagliabue wrote. ``The homicides resulted
from an altercation at which Lewis was clearly present, aspects of
which he observed, and which involved associates or friends whom he
had brought to and from the scene of the incident. In short, the
obstruction here impaired or impeded an investigation of serious
criminal conduct in circumstances that plainly led a wide segment
of the public to view Lewis' conduct very negatively. That negative
perception, in turn, negatively affected other NFL players and the
league itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount is the largest nonsuspension fine levied against a
player by the league office. A person close to Lewis said that
although the Pro Bowl linebacker thought the amount was excessive,
he was uncertain whether to appeal the fine. However, the person
said, the players association may convince Lewis that the fine is
too large and that he needs to appeal it.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens officials privately are furious at the amount. They say
Tagliabue made the number so high because he wanted to appease the
public, mainly the news media. They say Lewis has suffered enough
financially, paying more than $1.5 million in legal fees and court
costs.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Lewis and two friends went on trial in Atlanta, charged
with malice murder, felony murder and aggravated assault with a
deadly weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution's case crumbled, however, and murder charges
against Lewis were dropped in exchange for his plea to obstruction
of justice for lying to the police. As part of the deal, Lewis
testified against the two co-defendants, Reginald Oakley and Joseph
Sweeting, who were later found not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis met with Tagliabue earlier this summer, and in the weeks
following the commissioner spoke to a number of people involved
with the case. Tagliabue determined that Lewis should be hit with a
hefty fine.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons was Tagliabue's determination to make it
clear to other players, and especially fans, that NFL players
should be held accountable for their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an NFL player engages in and admits to misconduct of the
type to which Lewis had pled here,'' Tagliabue wrote, ``the biggest
losers are thousands of other NFL players, present, past and
future. Such admitted misconduct clearly contributes to the
negative stereotyping of NFL players.''
</P>
<P>
   Both league and Ravens officials maintain that Lewis has been a
model citizen since the trial. He spoke to the league's rookies
this off-season and in a passionate speech took responsibility for
deceiving the police, but denied any participation in the murders.
Lewis, as part of a personal conduct policy, has been meeting
regularly with a counselor.
</P>
<P>
   The fine for Lewis comes only months after the NFL refined and
expanded its personal conduct policy. The changes were made in
light of the Lewis case, as well as the case involving Carolina
receiver Rae Carruth, who has been accused of masterminding the
murder last year of his pregnant girlfriend.
</P>
</TEXT>
