u p BC-CVN-CAMPAIGN-BEGINS-$     08-17 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CAMPAIGN-BEGINS-$ADV20-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
(For release Sunday, Aug. 20)
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN SEASON IS LAUNCHED, WITH THE EDGE TO BUSH
</P>
<P>
   By DAN FREEDMAN and MARK HELM
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Hearst Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With 79 days before election day, Vice President
Al Gore and Sen. Joseph Lieberman confront an electoral map that is
leaning in favor of their Republican opponents, Texas Gov. George
W. Bush and former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   A wide swath of 18 states in the South, West and Midwest are
solidly in the Bush corner, giving him a claim on 167 electoral
votes out of 270 needed to win, according to political analyst
Charles Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other states are leaning to Bush, including Ohio, which
would bring his total to 250 _ 20 short of victory.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore has a solid lead in seven states _ including
New York _ for a total of 77 electoral votes. Four other states _
California, Illinois, Tennessee and Minnesota _ are leaning to
Gore. If Gore wins those states, he brings that total up to 174,
according to the Cook analysis.
</P>
<P>
   That means the race is likely to be decided in such traditional
toss-up states as Illinois, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Michigan,
Wisconsin and Washington, with a total of 78 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say they are not worried _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our position,'' Sen. Christopher Dodd, former chair of
the Democratic National Committee, told reporters late last week.
``We have a very good chance of winning, but the perception is that
we're the underdog, and as everyone knows, America loves an
underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   While national voter polls show Democrats enjoy advantages on
major issues such as education and Social Security, Gore still
suffers the perception of being linked to questionable campaign
finance practices in the 1996 election and President Clinton's
involvement in the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   And while he battles to capture the critical center, Gore is
fighting a brush-fire war on his left flank against the Green Party
candidate Ralph Nader. The veteran consumer activist could draw
enough votes in critical states such as Wisconsin, Oregon,
Minnesota and California to guarantee a Bush victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Nader costs Gore California, the race is over,'' said
George C. Edwards III, director of the Center for Presidential
Studies at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's strategists claim that the Nader threat will fade once
liberal voters _ a traditional Democratic bloc _ realize that a
vote for Nader is tantamount to electing Bush. And they are
convinced that in addition to volunteering for duty in Vietnam,
Gore's long record of public service in Congress and the White
House will prove compelling to a public just beginning to focus on
the elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a story many voters have not heard,''' said Tad Devine,
Gore's senior strategist. ``The vice president's life is almost
like a revelation. Many people don't know where he comes from.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd insisted that voters don't necessarily have to like Gore to
vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to convince the American public that this election is
not about whether you want to have a beer with the candidate ...
it's about who can run the country best,'' he said. ``When you
choose a doctor to operate on your wife, you don't worry about
whether you'd want to have a drink with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore shouldn't try to compete with President Clinton or Bush on
affability, Dodd said, but should instead talk specifically about
issues such the environment, health care and education.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, many Republicans are amused at the Democratic
angst over Gore's image.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great Democratic myths is that people don't know Al
Gore,'' said Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster based in Atlanta.
``I disagree with that. People have known him eight years as vice
president and they've concluded they don't like him very much ...
He would need a personality transplant to become more likeable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's challenge in the campaign ahead is the mirror image of
Gore's, according to Donald Kettl, political science professor at
the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore has to ratchet up his personal appeal, Bush needs to
better articulate his proposals and overcome the fuzzy menu of
ideas rooted in ``compassionate conservatism,'' Kettl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question for Bush is how to calibrate his compassionate
side with his conservative side,'' Kettl said, noting the first
helps Bush with moderates and independents while the second draws
in the GOP's true believers. ``It will be a challenge for Bush to
put out enough detail to satisfy the critics and the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, the best Gore can hope for is that the public
is willing to put aside a year's worth of Jay Leno and David
Letterman jokes and look at the vice president anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harder Gore tries, the more artificial he looks,'' Kettl
said. ``Whether he can create a softer, more likeable personality
is a big `if.'''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman and Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
