</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS, WITH NO SIGN OF WEAKNESS, SHARES LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The excellence of Tiger Woods has become
expected, particularly at major championships. Was anyone surprised
that Woods opened the PGA Championship with a six-under-par 66? You
could almost hear some of his competitors saying to themselves,
``There he goes again.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget the thought of Woods getting off to a slow start. If
Woods is to be denied his third consecutive major championship,
someone at Valhalla Golf Club will have to play superb golf to beat
him. Thursday, on a sultry Kentucky afternoon, Scott Dunlap, who
has never won a PGA Tour event, shot 66 to tie Woods for first
place. Darren Clarke, who defeated Woods this year in the Andersen
Consulting Match Play Championship, was tied for third place at 68,
along with Davis Love III, the 1997 PGA champion.
</P>
<P>
   Play was suspended at 8:27 p.m. with 18 players still on the
course.
</P>
<P>
   The tightly bunched leader board, which featured many players
under par, gave credence to the theory that it may be harder for
Woods to run away with this major. Many players have the ability to
shoot low scores this weekend. But the big question remained the
same. Will anyone shoot lower than Woods?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger has won the last two majors by 23 shots combined,''
noted Dunlap after his round, which included five birdies, one
bogey and a chip-in eagle at No. 2 that jump-started his day. ``His
presence is nothing but discouraging to everyone else in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's going to do it, he's going to do it. There is no
stopping him. All I can do is come out tomorrow, play another good
round and take it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods intends to take another championship and become the first
player to win three consecutive majors since Ben Hogan in 1953.
Woods took advantage of his 9:13 a.m. tee time, playing most of his
round before the afternoon temperature reached 91 degrees, with a
heat index of 100. It was telling that Woods, Dunlap, Clarke and
Love teed off before 10:30 a.m. Those who played in the afternoon
felt as if they were in a sauna with the temperature gauge stuck on
high. Some of the afternoon rounds were painfully slow.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the pre-tournament favorites struggled, including Hal
Sutton (74), Sergio Garcia (74), Vijay Singh (77) and Tom Lehman
(82). But despite the hoopla surrounding Woods as he entered this
tournament, he remained unflappable. Woods was paired with Jack
Nicklaus and Singh, marking the first time that Nicklaus and Woods
had ever been paired together in a competitive round. As expected,
their gallery was the biggest and the most boisterous, yet Woods
played with machinelike efficiency, making seven birdies and just
one bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Want more bad news for the competition? Woods putted well. And
when Woods putts well at majors, he usually wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you shoot 66 in a major championship, you are going
to be happy,'' said Woods, who said he enjoyed playing with
Nicklaus, who shot a 77. But Woods never lost sight of his goal.
``It was an honor to play with Jack. To be honest, though, when I
am on that first tee, I could care less who I am playing with. I am
trying to put myself in position to win a major championship.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what Woods did, and from the moment Woods' name
appeared on the leader board, his opponents knew it meant trouble.
Woods can bunch birdies together at any time, on any golf course,
and you can never tell when a torrid stretch might begin.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, it started at the par-5 7th. Sitting on even par
through six holes, Woods birdied No. 7, No. 8., No. 9 and No. 10 to
reach four under par. At the 597-yard 7th, Woods reached the green
in two shots with a driver and a 7-iron, then two-putted from 30
feet. At No. 8, he made a 12-foot putt. At No. 9, he made another
12-footer. And at the par-5 10th, after missing the green with his
second shot, Woods hit a beautiful chip from behind the green that
stopped 3 feet from the cup, setting up an easy birdie putt. Woods
added another 12-foot birdie putt at No. 12, and he birdied the &QC; 
par-5 finishing hole, hitting his second shot into the green-side
bunker, then blasting out to 3 feet to set up the birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   While Woods is accustomed to leading majors, Dunlap, who turned
37 Wednesday, continued his celebration with a superb round. Dunlap
entered the tournament unsure of how he would perform, having not
played since last month's British Open, and still feeling somewhat
drained after fighting a bad cold last week. His best finish this
year is a tie for third at The Players Championship, so Dunlap
realized he was a long shot to keep pace with Woods for three more
days. That didn't mean Dunlap wouldn't try.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know I have not won on the PGA Tour yet,'' Dunlap said.
``But you never know when your first one is going to be. Jeff
Sluman's first one was the PGA, so why not mine?''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, however, had different ideas. And as he went to bed with
a share of the lead, it was an unsettling thought for the rest of
the field, thinking about a player who shows no mercy in majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be you could slip up a couple of times, have three
very good rounds and one OK round, and still win the
championship,'' said Curtis Strange, who shot a 72. ``Not
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
