<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Webvan: Delivery or bust
 &HT;    By Brad Schrade
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Webvan may say no tipping required for home delivery,
but it occasionally does some tipping of its own.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, local Webvan officials tipped police to a
suspected credit card scam, and made the home delivery: a police
officer dressed as a Webvan worker.
</P>
<P>
   The sting bagged Tonya N. Walker, 27, who was expecting $357 in
groceries, including a dozen fine steaks. She was arrested
Wednesday night on charges of using a stolen credit card number to
order through the online service.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was surprised,'' said Detective Gary Lowe. ``Suddenly she
wasn't getting a crate of food anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Webvan opened its metro Atlanta operation in May and has
encountered a few customers trying to use stolen credit cards. In
this case, Webvan became suspicious when the addresses didn't
match. The card belonged to a Newnan, Ga. couple who said they had
never heard of Webvan.
</P>
<P>
   When investigators searched Walker's apartment, they found a
computer she had purchased fraudulently, police said. She also was
charged with forgery, computer forgery and financial card fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Four other Webvan customers have been arrested on similar
charges, including one who complained the delivery was late.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be the only customers dissatisfied with our
service,'' said company spokesman Mark San Fratello.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
