<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GILRUTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA SPACE PIONEER ROBERT R. GILRUTH IS DEAD AT 86 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert R. Gilruth, a pivotal figure in America's Cold War-era
race to the moon and the first director of NASA's Johnson Space
Center in Houston, died Thursday in Charlottesville, Va., after a
lengthy illness.
</P>
<P>
   He was 86 and had Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   The family planned a private memorial. His ashes were to be
scattered in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Gilruth was a true pioneer in every sense of the word
and the father of human spaceflight,'' said George W.S. Abbey, the
current Johnson Space Center director. ``His vision, energy and
dedication helped define the American space program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His courage to explore the unknown, his insistence of
following strict scientific procedures, and his technical expertise
directly contributed to the ultimate success of the American space
program and the landing of a man on the moon,'' NASA administrator
Dan Goldin said from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   An innovative aeronautical engineer, Gilruth proved an
inspirational though soft spoken leader when in 1958 he was
selected to lead the space task group, a team of 35 experts
assembled by the newly created National Aeronautics and Space
Administration to place an American in space.
</P>
<P>
   By Nov. 1, 1961, Gilruth had resettled the task group, comprised
initially of engineers and other experts from the old Langley
Aeronautical Laboratory of the government's National Advisory
Committee for Aeronautics, in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The campus-like spaceflight research facility that was carved
from cattle grazing land in Houston's Clear Lake area was known as
NASA's Manned Spacecraft Center until it was renamed the Lyndon B.
Johnson Space Center in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   As director of the task group and the Manned Spacecraft Center,
Gilruth oversaw the nation's first 25 human spaceflights. They
spanned the May 5, 1961, Mercury flight of the late Alan Shepard,
through the Apollo 15 lunar mission of August 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Gilruth's tenure was dominated by America's come-from-behind
victory in a race to the moon with the former Soviet Union. The
Soviet's launch of the first artificial satellite, Sputnik, in
1957, spurred the creation of NASA.
</P>
<P>
   Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin became the first human launched
into space, beating Shepard by less than a month. But the triumph
fueled American fears that the country was falling behind its
Communist rival.
</P>
<P>
   Gilruth transitioned from NASA's Mercury program to the director
of its Gemini project. Within less than two years, Gemini broke new
ground in orbital maneuvering and the rendezvous of multiple
spacecraft, concepts essential to NASA's strategy for reaching the
moon ahead of the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   Gilruth's steady demeanor helped to steer NASA back from a
tragic launch pad fire that killed three astronauts in early 1967,
shortly before they were to make the first Earth orbital test
flight of the Apollo capsule.
</P>
<P>
   By Christmas 1968, an Apollo crew was orbiting the moon. On July
20, 1969, Apollo 11 astronauts Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin
stepped onto the lunar surface in triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo 11's flight satisfied the mandate from President Kennedy,
issued within days of Shepard's 15-minute Mercury flight, that
American astronauts reach the moon and return safely to Earth by
1970.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a decade at the Manned Spacecraft Center's helm,
Gilruth stepped down on Jan. 17, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Moving on to the agency's Washington headquarters, he served as
NASA's director of personnel development until his retirement in
December 1973.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Gilruth spent four decades with NASA and its
predecessor, NACA. Among his many accomplishments, he was a member
of the National Academy of Engineering and the National Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Nashwauk, Minn., on Oct. 8, 1913, he earned bachelor's
and master's degrees in aeronautical engineering from the
University of Minnesota. Shortly after graduation in 1936, he began
his career in flight research at Langley.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Gilruth was drawn to research in high speed flight.
Limitations in the sophistication of wind tunnels, then an
essential tool in evaluating the flight characteristics of new
aircraft design, forced Gilruth and his colleagues to innovate.
</P>
<P>
   They did so, first by dropping their models from high altitude
aircraft to achieve supersonic velocities and then by fastening
their prototypes to small rockets.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950's, Gilruth was in charge of Langley's pilotless
aircraft research division, which supported the research of a range
of military and civilian piloted rocket research projects,
including the X-15 and Dyna-Soar. All contributed to the eventual
development of the space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, he inspired those he worked with,
colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gilruth's management style developed the best minds in the
space program into the finest organization of its time,'' said
Chris Kraft of Houston, who served as Gilruth's deputy and
Johnson's director of flight operations. Now retired, Kraft
succeeded Gilruth, serving as Johnson's director for nearly 11
years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
