<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5054 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     08-17 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET EXPLOITATION CONTINUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, there's plenty of crying in baseball. Just watch any of the
Little League World Series games on ESPN, ESPN2 and ABC leading up
to, and including, the championship next week.
</P>
<P>
   But cry as they might, this is just the beginning of a
relationship not so quietly bordering on _ dare we say it _
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next season, there'll be 16 teams in the Little League
World Series instead of eight. There'll be a U.S. Championship game
on Saturday, followed by the World Championship on Sunday. And the
U.S. Regional Championship telecasts, which numbered four on ESPN2
this week, will increase to eight in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   They're adding another field in tiny Williamsport, Pa., to
accommodate this gold rush. And the dough that Little League
suddenly has in its budget to make all this happen? It came, of
course, from the kid-friendly family of Disney sports networks,
which recently extended its contract through 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Little League World Series title game was once a
special event on ABC's ``Wide World of Sports,'' it's become a
televis property hotter than an aluminum-bench seat on a Saturday
afternoon in July.
</P>
<P>
   Innocence left this game years ago. Greed has taken over. Using
11- and 12-year-olds, forced to grow up so much quicker these days
whether they're emotionally ready or not, doesn't seem to matter.
</P>
<P>
   And it's so much so that ESPN made other strategic changes in
its summer programming for fun and profit.
</P>
<P>
   You might not notice it, but the X Games are in August for the
first time (the first five were held in June). And a closer
examination of the schedule shows all six of ESPN2's X Games
telecasts and two of ESPN's X Games shows will follow Little League
World Series telecasts. ABC's final day of X Games coverage a week
from Saturday will precede its coverage of the Little League title
game.
</P>
<P>
   Congrats all around to Disney for finding a way to reach its
much-sought kids TV demographic. Cartoons aren't enough,
apparently.
</P>
<P>
   Run all the ads for Disneyland, Disney movies and Disney toys
you can cram into a Little League telecast, too. At this rate, the
Little League World Series will look like the NCAA men's basketball
tournament, sponsored by some dot-com video-game maker and moved to
Orlando, Fla., by the time this year's players finish high school.
</P>
<P>
   __ Local radio buzz: The lineup for the new Fox Sports Radio
Network, scheduled for launch out of the Premiere Radio Network's
new Sherman Oaks studios a week from Monday, includes several Fox
TV personalities, with one promiment exception.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Olbermann's contractual obligations to the WinStar
syndicators, where he does weekday commentaries, prevents him from
doing anything for his primary employer's latest venture.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Jeanne Zelasko, Kevin Frazier, Chris Myers and Steve
Lyons will be co-hosting mid-day shows, with Tony Bruno providing
the morning fare from 5 to 9 a.m. The station won't have
programming from 9 a.m. to noon to continue giving Premiere's
premier man, Jim Rome, his window of smackdom.
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel-owned stations KXTA-AM (1150) and XTRA-AM (690)
will use programming from that Fox lineup, but don't expect
anything other than overnights or weekends (where Tom Murray has a
7-to-9 a.m. show on Saturdays). Rumors continue that Clear
Channel-owned KRLA-AM (570), which already runs Angels and Lakers
games, will eventually become the 24-hour all-sports affiliate for
the network.
</P>
<P>
   __ Forward lateral: In Tuesday's edition of The Chicago
Sun-Times, columnist Jay Mariotti wrote of Dennis Miller's second
``Monday Night Football'' exhibition performance:
</P>
<P>
   ``(It) was such a hoot Monday night that I can't wait for the
next Monday night. . . . (Miller) was looking to find a balance
between comedic timing and passable football knowledge. He thrived
in both arenas, firing off an impressive flurry of nuggets and
observations while turning an unwatchable exhibition blowout into a
must-hear howltrack from the start to signoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Miller, who claims to have stopped reading the
newspaper sports section or listening to sports-talk-show critiques
of his work, made a special appearance on Mariotti's One-on-One
Sports show the day that review came out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just staying out of the way,'' Miller said on the show
heard locally on KMPC-AM 1540. ``I'll let America judge. Everyone
has an opinion. . . . It's too pressurized a job to hear people
abuse you on a regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, cha-cha, it's only been two weeks, all right? Just
decompress, babe. It's not time for you and Teddy Koppel to start
blow-dryin' your hair.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the sooner Al Michaels figures out that he doesn't have
to match you quip for quip, the faster the chemistry project will
progress.
</P>
<P>
   __ Showing his stripes: Probably not a great precedent allowing
Matt Millen, the broadcaster, to pretend to be Matt Millen, the NFL
official, when he not only wears the Foot Locker costume Sunday for
Fox's coverage of the Tampa Bay-New England exhibition but the
camera cap that now goes with the job.
</P>
<P>
   Millen will act as the game's umpire for the entire third
quarter, preparing for this promotional task by spending the last
two months at the NFL's officials' clinic as well as working at
several team's training camps. All in the hope that he captures
some excellent video for the game's broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he remembers that he's not allowed to tackle anyone out
there,'' Fox's John Madden said.
</P>
<P>
   We hope he doesn't. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
