<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-HNS &LR;      08-17 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GRAND JURY INVESTIGATING CLINTON-LEWINSKY SCANDAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL HEDGES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent counsel Robert Ray has impaneled a
federal grand jury to review President Clinton's efforts to conceal
his affair with Monica Lewinsky, raising howls from Democrats about
a political sneak attack on the day Al Gore accepted the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury was sworn in more than a month ago, according to
sources outside the independent counsel's office. The panel is
positioned to help Ray fulfill a promise to announce once Clinton
leaves office whether he can be indicted on charges of perjury or
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who replaced Clinton nemesis Kenneth Starr last October,
has quietly continued the investigation into Clinton's affair with
Lewinsky, which was at the center of the president's impeachment by
the House and subsequent acquittal by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert on Thursday issued a
statement saying, ``The timing of the leak of this information
reeks to high heaven. But given their (the independent counsel's
office) track record on this, it is hardly surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   As Vice President Gore was preparing to give perhaps the most
important speech of his political career Thursday evening, his
staff reacted angrily to the reports of the resurrection of
scandals plaguing the administration in which he is top deputy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is highly suspect,'' said Doug Hattaway, a Gore
spokesman. ``People are sick and tired of the judicial system being
manipulated for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Hattaway added, Gore was not concerned the reports might
mar his acceptance speech. ``We believe the voters are focused on
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Gore's November opponent, George W. Bush's campaign
spokesman Ray Sullivan said, ``Americans are sick and tired of
investigations and scandals. The best way to change the tone in
Washington is to change the administration in the White House. That
is what Governor Bush intends to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray's office refused to confirm that a grand jury had been
impaneled, but at the same time denied any link to reports that a
grand jury was meeting, and especially to a leak on the night of
Gore's address.
</P>
<P>
   ``The source of these reports is not within the office of the
independent counsel,'' said Lynda Flippin, spokeswoman for the
independent counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   Flippin added that Ray ``has publicly said this is an open
investigation. He has said he will determine at a later date if the
matters investigated by Mr. Starr are prosecutable.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as this spring Ray said in televised interviews that
he had not ruled out indicting Clinton nor had he decided to issue
an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Ray took over the ongoing Lewinsky probe on Oct. 18, after
Kenneth Starr left the office.
</P>
<P>
   Legal bombshells dropping near important political events are
not new in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Iran-Contra independent counsel Lawrence Walsh
issued an amended indictment of Caspar Weinberger, President Bush's
defense secretary, on the weekend before the 1992 election. It was
the first indictment in the scandal to make specific references to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's political advisers pounced on that and within hours of
the Walsh filing issued a statement headlined: ``New Iran-Contra
Evidence Released By Prosecutor Shows Bush Flatly Lied.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Bush loyalists claimed the court filing halted his momentum
before the 1992 vote.
</P>
<P>
   But some Clinton advisers and friends think Thursday's leak
could actually end up helping Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is no doubt this leak is designed to deprive Al
Gore of his moment tonight, but you know what, I think it will
boomerang,'' said Lanny Davis, a former Clinton administration
official who has remained a friend of the president. Davis said he
believed the leak would be seen as ``a corruption of the legal
process.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past six months, Ray's office has issued statements
noting the hiring of about eight new attorneys and assistants in
his office, indicating that at least some aspects of the Clinton
case had not been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Ray has been in Nova Scotia on vacation for several days and was
heading for his home in New Jersey during the critical hours when
the story of the new grand jury broke. He was out of touch even
with his own staff, according to close associates.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a panel of federal judges overseeing the ongoing
independent counsel investigations re-authorized Ray's
investigation for another year. That panel said in a brief
statement that it was ``not currently appropriate'' to end the
investigation begun in 1994 into Clinton's Arkansas business
dealings known as Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   Ray had argued to keep the investigation going, citing progress
on a number of lingering issues left over from Starr's far flung
probes.
</P>
<P>
   Starr told Congress in September 1998, when he filed his
impeachment referral with the House, that he believed there was
``substantial and credible'' evidence that the president had
committed perjury, first during a sworn deposition during the Paula
Jones sexual harassment case, and then when he testified via close
circuit television to Starr's original grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was Clinton's claim to Jones' lawyers that he had not
had sexual relations with Lewinsky when he was asked that as part
of Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also alleged Clinton had obstructed justice in his efforts
to cover up the affair with the young White House intern that he
eventually admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's lawyer, Plato Cacheris, was not immediately available
to comment on the new grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was impeached by the House of Representatives, but was
not convicted of the charges following a Senate trial. Removal from
office would have required approval by two-thirds of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright, who oversaw
the Jones case, ordered Clinton to pay about $90,000 to the Jones
legal team, finding the president in contempt of court for giving
false testimony about his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a former low-level Arkansas state employee, had charged
Clinton with sexual harassment in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   While keeping the Clinton-Lewinsky matter open, Ray has ended
two Clinton administration scandal cases in recent months. Ray said
he would bring no charges in either the leak of classified FBI
files to the White House _ the so-called Filegate _ or in the
firing of White House travel office employees, known as Travelgate.
</P>
<P>
   That brought a sigh of relief and claims of vindication from
supporters of the president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Simply empaneling a new grand jury doesn't necessarily point to
further charges in the case, legal experts said. Grand juries
expire, and in order to keep options open, a prosecutor will
request that a new panel be sworn and made familiar with any
evidence already gathered in the case.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the Lewinsky investigation said there had been
no recent signs of new evidence-gathering in the case. One option
open to Ray, sources close to the investigation have said, is to
seek a grand jury indictment on virtually the same case Starr gave
to Congress. But any such decision is likely months away, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   A new grand jury probe hanging over him could darken Clinton's
final months in office. But Davis said the president likely
anticipated the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say he is immune from being surprised at the coarse
political moves of the independent counsel,'' said Davis. ``He will
probably simply say to close friends, `I told you so.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
