<HEADLINE>
ROSTER EXPANSION SHOULD BRING BACK RAMON MARTINEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM KALEC  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jimy Williams will have the luxury of expanding his
25-man roster to 40 Sept. 1, ending a dilemma similar to the one he
addressed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, on the 15-day disabled list retroactive to Aug.
1, is eligible to return. Although he still wore a brace on his
right knee, Martinez said Thursday he was healthy enough to return
to the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem: Williams doesn't have a spot for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are you going to take off of here?'' said Williams as he
scanned the Red Sox roster. ``So the best thing, if you can't put
(Martinez) on right now, is keep pitching. (Bret) Saberhagen,
Ramon, (Pete) Schourek, whoever it is. If you don't have a spot for
them right now, then the best thing to do is to keep your arm
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are not pitching, then it doesn't help them or us.
Mainly it doesn't help them.''
</P>
<P>
   So with that in mind, Martinez will join Saberhagen on a
rehabilitation assignment this weekend in Pawtucket against
Scranton/Wilkes-Barre. Saberhagen will pitch Saturday, Martinez
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the decision but I have to accept (it) because it
is a manager's decision, so I have to go with that,'' Martinez
said. ``But I don't agree with the decision, you know. So I am
ready to pitch, ready to help the team and that is about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez started two games for Pawtucket last season while
rehabbing his right shoulder. He gave up nine earned runs in nine
innings with the PawSox. Martinez was called up when the rosters
were expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Before suffering a right knee contusion on the Sox' West Coast
road trip in early August, Martinez had averaged just under five
innings per start. Tomo Ohka took Martinez's spot in the rotation
and has given Williams no reason to send him back to Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's picthed pretty darn good,'' Williams said of Ohka.
``Hopefully, he'll keep pitching good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of you who follow us understand all the games we have
coming up, so we are going to need starters.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps more importantly, Williams needs healthy starters to
pitch extended innings in the final month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had three innings of simulation the other day so that's 50
pitches, 45-50 pitches,'' Williams said. ``(Ramon) was fine coming
off that out here, so I don't know what exactly is set up for
pitches or innings (in Pawtucket). He'll probably throw 60, 65,
hopefully four or five innings. But you got to play the game, that
dictates everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
