<HEADER>
A5066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-FUTURE-NYT &LR;      08-17 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINKING AHEAD TO 2004, DEMOCRATS PREEN BEFORE DELEGATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The five dozen delegates from Iowa had just
finished breakfast Thursday when the senator from North Carolina,
dressed in a blue suit and black cowboy boots, strode confidently
into their meeting room.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, John Edwards, had come to praise Vice President Al
Gore, but he managed to squeeze in a few words about himself, too.
How the ``struggling farmers'' of Iowa reminded him of the
struggling farmers of North Carolina, for instance. And how, as a
trial lawyer, he once fought an insurance company on behalf of a
boy who had been denied coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates hooted and cheered for the brief but fiery speech.
And as Edwards turned to the door, the Iowa Democratic chairman,
Rob Tully, pulled him aside, saying, ``I think we'll see a lot of
you.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a not-so-subtle reminder that the presidential primary
season kicks off in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Election Day 2000 is not yet here, but the beauty pageant for
2004 and beyond is already under way, judging from the parade of
prospects who have visited the Iowa delegation this week.
</P>
<P>
   Few people at the Democratic National Convention here will say
that they expect Gore to lose this year _ but plenty are preparing
for the day he departs the national scene. So this year, as in any
other convention year, the party's would-be rising stars are
strutting their wares, meeting the Democratic cognoscenti, raising
some money and laying the groundwork for future campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's politics,'' Tully observed. ``In case the world comes
to an end, and Al Gore and Joe Lieberman aren't elected, there will
be people already working to fill the void.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, 47, a first-term senator who gained national attention
when Gore put him on his short list of potential running mates,
logged a schedule this week of someone with plans to make plans for
a national campaign. He gave speeches to the delegations from
Massachusetts, New York and California; made a prime-time
appearance on the convention stage and several appearances on
national talk shows; and gave scores of news media interviews.
</P>
<P>
   He was far from alone. Sens. John Kerry of Massachusetts, Paul
Wellstone of Minnesota and Evan Bayh of Indiana, Govs. Gray Davis
of California and Tom Vilsack of Iowa, and Rep. Dick Gephardt of
Missouri, the House minority leader, all had busy, high-profile
weeks here. And all are considered potential presidential
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The jockeying among the party's noisy factions to promote their
favorites has already begun. Labor leaders talk up Gephardt. Former
Sen. Bill Bradley's supporters want him to give it another go.
Moderates promote Bayh. And liberals say they would love to see
Wellstone, Gephardt or Hillary Rodham Clinton _ who is still
seeking her first elected office, senator from New York _ run for
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this ticket goes down, I think progressives are going to be
pretty determined to have a horse in the field next time around,''
said Robert Borosage, co-director of Campaign for America's Future,
a nonprofit group that promotes liberal ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats have complained that their roster seems rather
thin. By comparison, the Republicans had a deep pool of well-known,
highly experienced governors who could have been the running mate
for their nominee, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. (That said, Bush
chose a former congressman and defense secretary, Dick Cheney.)
</P>
<P>
   But other Democrats note that in 1996, when the Republican Party
seemed in desperate need of new blood, Bush was just midway through
his first term and barely registering on most people's political
radar screens.
</P>
<P>
   Among Democrats from Iowa, there are widespread hopes that
Vilsack will emerge, Bushlike, from the pack. An obscure state
senator when he was elected governor in 1998, Vilsack offers what
many Midwestern Democrats think their party needs more of: a
folksy, earnest style coupled with a populist agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Vilsack, 49, put some of those assets on view Thursday when he
spoke before members of the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees. After getting bumped down the speakers'
list by more prominent Democrats, including Sen. Edward M. Kennedy
of Massachusetts, Vilsack muttered, ``I'm batting eighth in an
all-star lineup here.''
</P>
<P>
   But he brought the crowd to its feet with a story about how a
union member had given him a $100 campaign contribution out of her
tiny savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man with a great future, mark my words,'' Larry
Scanlon, the union's political director, told the crowd as Vilsack
departed.
</P>
<P>
   In separate interviews, Edwards and Vilsack brushed aside
suggestions that they are thinking ahead to national campaigns. But
they did not exactly close the door to the idea, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting to watch all these people maneuvering and
thinking about the future,'' Vilsack said. I'm just going to work
hard, which is what I've always done. I'm a fighter. And if it
works out, something comes up in the future, then we'll go after
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
