u s BC-BOX-IBF-ACQUITTAL-NYT     08-17 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-IBF-ACQUITTAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE SENIOR OF IBF IS ACQUITTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By RONALD SMOTHERS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ In a mixed and complicated verdict Thursday, a
federal jury acquitted the founder of the International Boxing
Federation of major bribery and racketeering charges, but convicted
him on counts of money laundering, tax evasion and interstate
travel to aid in racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Lee Sr., 66, also the former president of the IBF, sat
motionless at the defense table as the verdict in the
four-month-long trial slowly unfolded with the reading by U.S.
District Judge John Bissell of a 12-page verdict sheet detailing
the charges in the original 34-count indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was found not guilty on the racketeering charges that were
the heart of the government's case. But he was found guilty on six
counts and could face a sentence of three years in jail, according
to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also acquitted Robert W. Lee Jr., 38, the son of the
IBF founder, of all nine counts that he faced.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Lee responded to the verdict in a hallway outside the
courtroom. ``My head is bloodied, but it's unbowed,'' he said. Lee
contended, as his lawyer had during the trial, that the prosecution
was racially motivated and aimed at him as an African-American who
headed one of boxing's major rating groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been a Caucasian this would never have happened,''
Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Lee called the verdict bittersweet, in that his
father was not also acquitted on all counts. The two men were
accused of demanding and accepting $338,000 in bribes from nearly
two dozen boxers, promoters and managers in exchange for inflated
rankings that qualified fighters for lucrative title bouts.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of seven men and five women had deliberated for 15 days
over a period of more than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, jurors said that their verdict had pivoted
largely on their understanding of significant legal points in the
judge's instructions to the jury. They also said they had been wary
of the credibility of the government's key witness, Colin Douglas
Beavers, who was for many years the IBF's ratings chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The racketeering charges at the heart of the prosecution case
involved a series of alleged violations of the New Jersey
commercial bribery law over the 14 years covered by the case.
Federal racketeering laws permit federal prosecutors to bring
together alleged violations of state and federal laws to try to
show a pattern of illegal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But jurors said that in many instances they could find no
evidence that bribes allegedly paid to Lee, Beavers and other IBF
officials had been negotiated or paid in New Jersey, as required
under the judge's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Without such proof, said one of the jurors, Aileen Smith,
``there was no pattern, and without a pattern there was no
racketeering.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Brand, the jury foreman, said jurors had been reluctant
to accept uncorroborated testimony from Beavers.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers testified that he had received many of the bribes that
the Lees were said to have demanded, and he also said he had shared
those bribes with both Lees and other IBF officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we couldn't trust Beavers alone,'' said Brand,
recalling the defense suggestion that in the absence of audiotapes
and videotapes in which Lee asked for and received bribes directly,
there was the possibility that the scheme had involved Beavers
alone.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said that jurors also thought the elder Lee was not
totally innocent. Asked if she thought he had committed crimes, she
responded, ``Well, we convicted him of something, didn't we?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the history of the IBF figured prominently in
the trial. The organization was created by Lee in 1984 to counter
the influence in boxing of white promoters and of the sport's two
other major sanctioning groups, the World Boxing Association and
the World Boxing Council.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors invoked the IBF's history to contend that Lee had
corrupted boxing under the guise of trying to reform the sport and
achieve racial justice.
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyers depicted the IBF as an embattled,
black-controlled group that was resented by ``multimillionaire
white promoters'' as well as by broadcast and cable operators who
wanted to control the rankings. The defense argued that the Lees
were targets of selective prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Krovatin, the lawyer for Robert Lee Sr., accused the
prosecutors of being ``unwittingly allied with these promoters who
concocted allegations of bribery.''
</P>
<P>
   Beavers, the former IBF ratings chairman, was the only witness
who directly linked Lee to the acceptance of payoffs; Lee appeared
not to have personally solicited or collected the alleged bribes
from promoters or fighters. Beavers testified that he had acted on
Lee's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also produced 83 audiotapes and videotapes of
conversations among Beavers, Lee and others. In one videotape, shot
surreptitiously in a Virginia motel room, Beavers is seen removing
a packet of bills that are strapped to his ankle and handing it to
Lee, while the IBF president in turn slides an envelope across a
table to Beavers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
