<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5076 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-BOS &LR;      08-17 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE DELIVERS POPULIST APPEAL FOR SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH AND SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Declaring that ``I am not satisfied,'' Al Gore
sought Thursday night to step out of the shadow of President
Clinton as he accepted the Democratic presidential nomination,
proclaiming himself a populist fighter for the working class who
will create a ``better, fairer, more prosperous America.''
</P>
<P>
   Seizing what may be his best chance to transform and energize
his candidacy, Gore reminded a nationwide television audience that
he and Clinton have overseen a booming economy. But Gore said that
is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   It was a speech that at times mirrored Republican nominee George
W. Bush's vow to create ``prosperity with a purpose'' and ``leave
no child behind.'' Gore said he wanted to make sure ``our
prosperity enriches not just the few, but all working families''
and that the powerless ``are never left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a two-term vice president who also served eight years each
in the US House and Senate, also used the speech to re-introduce
himself to the public. With aides anxious for Gore to overcome his
image as a stiff and plodding speaker, the speech was preceded by a
documentary video that portrayed the vice president as a friendly,
folksy father and family man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're entering a new time,'' Gore, 52, said, according to
remarks prepared for delivery. ``We're electing a new President.
And I stand here tonight as my own man, and I want you to know me
for who I truly am,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 25 years, I've been fighting for people,'' Gore said. ``So
this is not an election between my opponent and me. It's about our
people, our families and our future _ and whether forces standing
in your way will keep you from having a better life.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as Gore sought to create a separate identity, he was
once again buffeted by the aftershocks of President Clinton's
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. Just hours
before Gore spoke, word leaked that Independent Counsel Robert Ray
had empanelled a grand jury to hear evidence in the Lewinsky
matter. While Clinton was found not guilty of ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' in his impeachment trial, the possibility remains
that he could be indicted on criminal charges that could be brought
after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare display of unity, both the Gore and Bush campaigns
said that leaks about the grand jury were ill-timed, but the story
had more potential to be hurtful to Gore, especially with so much
television coverage focusing on the Lewinsky story on a day when
Gore had hoped to dominate the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   After a winter of primaries, a spring of anticipation and a
summer of message molding, the dueling dialogue between Gore and
Bush over how to spread prosperity now shifts to an 83-day sprint
along the campaign trail. The Bush campaign said it would agree to
three presidential debates, the number proposed by an independent
commission, but the timing of them has not been solidified. The
commission has proposed the first meeting, and possibly most
important, be held in Boston. Bush did not agree to the commission
format, or to any particular debate venue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the son of the late US Senator Albert Gore Sr., and Bush,
the son of former President Bush, face off during a period of
prosperity but with no single issue dominating the race. The
campaign may be affected by two other candidates: Green Party
nominee Ralph Nader, who is attracting some liberals and others in
key states and may hurt Gore; and the Reform Party candidate,
either Patrick Buchanan or John Hagelin.
</P>
<P>
   With both Gore and Bush seeking to appeal to the broad middle of
the American electorate _ where the election likely will be decided
_ the two conventions have focused on similar themes. Both men have
said that the boom times have left too many people behind, that the
federal government must do more to help improve schools, and that
Social Security should be overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   But the two disagree on many details, most notably on the size
of a tax cut, and Gore seized on that difference to portray himself
as a populist while asserting that Bush is beholden to the rich and
powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say it plainly,'' Gore said. ``I will not go along with
a huge tax cut for the wealthy at the expense of everyone else and
wreck our good economy in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So often, powerful forces and powerful interests stand in your
way, and the odds seemed stacked against you -- even as you do
what's right for you and your family,'' Gore said. ``How and what
we do for all of you _ the people who pay the taxes, bear the
burdens, and live the American dream _ that is the standard by
which we should be judged.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for all of our good times, I am not satisfied,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight night, the convention veered between a
nomination and a humanization of Gore. On Wednesday, Karenna Gore
Schiff introduced her father by describing how he helped her when
she was little to butter her toast and with her science project, a
dinosaur diorama. Thursday night, Gore's wife, Tipper, an
accomplished photographer, said she wanted to introduce her husband
through pictures she has taken of their 30 years together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, I know, some of you are saying, please, not the family
photo album,'' Tipper Gore said. ``But, come along for just a
little while and see the man I love in a way you may not have seen
him before.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech was preceded by a series of tributes from his
friends, including his brother-in-law, Frank Hunger;
Pulitzer-prize-winning journalist David Halberstam, who worked with
Gore at the Nashville Tennessean; and Jim Frush, who guided Gore up
Mount Rainier last year.
</P>
<P>
   With the introductions complete, Gore then delivered what was
widely described as the most important speech of his career, with
the Battleground/Voter.com poll showing him about nine points
behind Bush. Even many Democrats are skeptical about Gore's
prospects. A CNN/Gallup poll taken earlier this month showed that
50 percent of Democrats think that Bush will win, while 44 percent
thought Gore would be victorious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes couldn't be higher for him,'' said Mark Baldassare,
survey director of the Public Policy Institute of California, a
non-partisan think tank. ``A lot will be determined right after
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldassare and others cautioned that not until early next week
will the polls provide an accurate read on Gore's performance, as
well as on the success of the convention in shaping public opinion
about Gore's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to wait a few days for all the news to filter through
television and newspapers and through people's own personal
conversations after they see the speech tonight and read about it
and talk about it with others,'' said Baldassare.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School of
Communication, said one reason Gore's speech is so important is
because the media has declared it to be, given persistent polling
that shows Gore lagging in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the polling data are totally unreliable,'' said
Jamieson. ``But the press says, he's behind, what does he have to
do?''
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson suspects that the overall message of the convention has
been muddled, with too many ideas being transmitted each day by too
many speakers. That put even more importance on Gore's performance
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems this convention is having is that it has a
lot of themes that has not yet been knit together into one sense of
the Democratic agenda,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has argued for months that the vice president
would pull ahead in the horse race polls once he has selected his
running mate and basked in attention to his convention, much the
way then Vice President George Bush pulled ahead of Massachusetts
Governor Michael S. Dukakis in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't come out of the convention ahead and stay ahead
for awhile, then they've lost another one of their arguments,''
said one Bush adviser.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone viewed Gore's performance as do or die.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end it's an important speech and that's all it is,''
said Ron Kaufman, the former White House political director to
President Bush. ``The election will not be won or lost (tonight)''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Jill Zuckman of the Globe staff contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
