<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKAKEL TO BE TRIED IN MOXLEY MURDER, JUDGE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a quarter-century of innuendo and speculation about
culpability and cover-up, the Martha Moxley murder case is headed
for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday a juvenile court judge ruled in Stamford, Conn., that
sufficient evidence exists to try Michael Skakel, a nephew of Ethel
Kennedy, for the 1975 killing of his teenage neighbor in exclusive
Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   However, Judge Maureen Dennis said the decision on whether to
try Skakel, 39, as a juvenile or an adult will await an
investigation by a juvenile probation officer. Skakel was 15 when
Moxley was discovered bludgeoned and stabbed to death on her
family's estate.
</P>
<P>
   State Inspector Frank Garr, the lead investigator in the case,
said Thursday that prosecutors are pleased. ``I think we presented
enough evidence to warrant this decision,'' Garr said. ``There's
certainly evidence to show that probable cause exists, that this
crime was committed by this person.''
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's attorney, Michael ``Mickey'' Sherman, said he is
confident that his client will be exonerated in either juvenile or
adult court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's neither shocking nor terribly disturbing,'' Sherman said.
``I've always said and will continue to say we will get a fair
trial and an acquittal, whether it be from a juvenile court judge
or a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   If Skakel is tried as an adult, he could be sentenced to life in
prison. But if he is tried as a juvenile, legal observers have
said, he might be convicted but face no prison time.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation ordered by Dennis, Garr said, probably will
look at whether the state's juvenile facilities are adequate to
hold Skakel. The review also will examine Skakel's family life,
schooling, and mental and physical health.
</P>
<P>
   State's Attorney Jonathan C. Benedict said he views the
investigation as a formality. ``We are confident that she will be
transferring the case to the adult court, and that we will
eventually be presenting the matter to a jury of Mr. Skakel's
peers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict, the chief prosecutor in Fairfield County, has said
that no Connecticut juvenile institution ``has the ability to deal
in any way with a 39- or 40-year-old man.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Connecticut law in 1975, juveniles convicted of murder
were held in a juvenile facility and then freed when they became
adults. Today, juveniles can be tried for murder in adult court.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to try Skakel followed a three-day probable-cause
hearing in June, when two ex-classmates said he confessed in the
late 1970s to Moxley's slaying. At the hearing, Benedict also
presented evidence that placed Skakel at the crime scene on the
night of Moxley's death.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sherman produced witnesses from the Elan School in
Poland Spring, Maine, a facility for troubled adolescents, who
testified that Skakel never confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Moxley is believed to have been killed shortly after visiting
the Skakel home on the night of Oct. 30, 1975, and spending time
with Michael, his 17-year-old brother, Thomas, and other teenage
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Police long focused their attention on Thomas Skakel, whose
family stopped cooperating with authorities within weeks of the
killing. Greenwich police never filed charges, even though a broken
golf club used in the slaying was traced to the Skakel home.
</P>
<P>
   The Skakel family, however, has been dogged by speculation for
25 years. The alleged association was fueled by a fictional account
of the murder by novelist Dominick Dunne and a true-crime analysis
by Mark Fuhrman that named Michael Skakel as the likely culprit.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Fuhrman's book was published, a single-judge grand
jury was convened in 1998 to reexamine the case. Skakel, of Hobe
Sound, Fla., was indicted in January and surrendered to police.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict said Dennis's finding of reasonable cause Thursday is
more compelling than the grand jury's earlier finding that probable
cause existed to arrest Skakel.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis ``ruled after an evidentiary hearing after defense
counsel had the opportunity to confront some of the state's
witnesses,'' Benedict said. ``We didn't show all our evidence. . .
. She was satisfied that there was cause to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material from the Associated Press was used in this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
