<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMPTON'S INJURY MARS A PERFECT DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAFAEL HERMOSO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robin Ventura detected the grimace when Mike Hampton
hit a grounder in the third inning. The next indication was
Hampton's trot to first base.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura approached Hampton during his warmup pitches the next
inning. ``I know you want two more innings but if you keep pitching
and really hurt yourself, the next two months aren't going to be
too good,'' Ventura told him.
</P>
<P>
   Things are going too well for the Mets to let an ill-timed
injury interrupt their streak. When a recurrence of pain from an
old football injury knocked out Hampton, Turk Wendell provided four
strong innings in relief. Four homers completed a 13-2 victory over
the Rockies as the Mets finished a 6-2 home stand. They moved two
and one-half games behind the idle first-place Braves in the
National League East and four and one-half games ahead of Arizona
in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Precautionary X-rays revealed a pre-existing stress fracture in
Hampton's right ribs, an injury he believes he suffered as a senior
in 1989 playing football for Crystal River High School in
Homosassa, Fla. Hampton, who took a helmet to the ribs while
carrying the ball, had the ribs wrapped at halftime and started the
second half. He left after one play, but proudly recalled playing
the next week.
</P>
<P>
   Such optimism was missing Thursday, when Hampton admitted
feeling worried and was not sure if he could make his next start on
Tuesday. Manager Bobby Valentine said Hampton was questionable but
did not think he would need to go on the disabled list. Pat
Mahomes, who started the first game in Tuesday's doubleheader,
would most likely be the substitute.
</P>
<P>
   The rib had not bothered Hampton since high school until he
began feeling discomfort in his previous four or five starts. The
pain resurfaced on the groundout. He lasted six pitches into the
fourth inning before Ventura approached him. Soon, the trainer Fred
Hina and the pitching coach Dave Wallace followed, and then
Valentine came out. With a 5-0 lead, Hampton's competitive side
battled his logical one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could get through it,'' Hampton said. ``I was kind
of stubborn. I just wanted to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The training staff said Hampton could not aggravate the injury
by playing through it, meaning his status hinges on his pain
tolerance. Hampton, who has a 2.44 earned run average in his last
19 starts, can feel the pain taking a deep breath and throwing a
four-seam fastball. He said it hurts the most when he swings a bat,
and the proud hitter, who is batting .293, vowed to be a cautious
swinger. He said the injury would need eight weeks to completely
heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have that kind of time,'' he said. ``The team needs
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendell had just arrived in the bullpen when he was stunned to
learn he would pitch. Hampton was not the only one recalling his
teens. In his longest outing in three years, Wendell felt like a
starting pitcher in high school. He was unusually prepared. John
Franco joked that he was on vacation because he had not pitched
since Monday. Wendell, third in the major leagues in appearances
with 62, had thrown only six and one-third innings since reliever
Rick White's arrival July 29.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell (5-4) allowed two runs, one earned, and struck out a
career-high six. He was as reckless as ever, even with a thin
bullpen behind him. Mahomes, who is usually the long man, was still
unavailable after throwing six and two-thirds innings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell doesn't consider such trivialities during games. He
didn't when he dove past second base to avoid a tag in the fifth
inning, trying to take an extra base after a misplay on his first
hit since 1996. He was out, but blamed himself for not hustling out
of the batter's box. At least Wendell's monstrous 37{-inch,
35-ounce bat finally produced his first hit as a Met.
</P>
<P>
   And Wendell did not think twice when he dove after a loose ball
in foul territory in the seventh, flipping over to make an errant
throw off the baserunner at third that allowed a run to score for
the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't live life or do things because I'm afraid to get
hurt,'' said Wendell, who added that he has never been approached
by a Mets coach about his aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell held the early lead and the Mets piled on Masato Yoshii,
a former teammate who was jettisoned to Colorado in January to dump
salary. The thin air has not been kind to Yoshii and neither have
the Mets. Yoshii pounded a water cooler with two fists after
allowing six runs in three and two-thirds against them in April.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton applied a forearm shiver to a cooler in the same series
after an equally ineffective outing.
</P>
<P>
   When Yoshii (5-13) constantly fell behind in the count Thursday,
hitters laid off his trademark forkball, rendering him helpless. He
allowed nine runs in five innings. Todd Zeile hit his 200th career
home run in the fifth inning and Benny Agbayani followed with his
10th homer of the season, giving the Mets seven players with
double-digit homers for the first time in 10 years. Robin Ventura
and Mike Bordick later hit home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell's outing only continued the bullpen's recent dominance.
The offense added a new wrinkle. The 13 runs were the most since
the Mets scored 14 against the Rockies in Denver in April, and it
was the most runs scored at sea level since they scored 15 at home
against the Cubs on April 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing good baseball,'' Valentine said. ``We've
had to play good baseball to win games and we have been winning.
But a team has to know it can win many different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
