<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AGREES TO 3 DEBATES, BUT HITCHES ARE POSSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Advisers to Gov. George W. Bush said Thursday
that he would participate in three presidential debates, an
announcement clearly intended to blunt a drumbeat of criticism from
the campaign of his opponent, Vice President Al Gore, that Bush was
trying to avoid such face-to-face contests.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's advisers left open the question of whether those
debates would be the ones suggested by the Commission on
Presidential Debates, which sponsored all of the post-primaries
presidential debates since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, Bush and his advisers were obviously trying to
retain either some bargaining power over the length, format and
other aspects of the commission's debates or the option of looking
to other sponsors for debates that better suited the campaign's
desires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush wants a thoughtful debate,'' said Karen P.
Hughes, a senior adviser for the Bush campaign, ``and we feel that
as the nominee, he should have some input into the structure and
format of the debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes pitched the announcement that Bush would participate in
three debates and that his running mate, Dick Cheney, would
participate in two vice presidential debates as ``a modern-day
record,'' saying that five combined presidential and vice
presidential debates would be the most in more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But several Republican strategists said the Bush campaign was
clearly concerned about making sure that the Texas governor ended
up in the kind of debate formats that flattered him the most.
</P>
<P>
   They said this reflected both an awareness among Bush's advisers
that debates were not necessarily his best showcases and the fact
that the front runner, which polls show the governor to be,
typically has more to lose than gain from debates. In 1996, for
example, President Clinton agreed to only two debates while former
Sen. Bob Dole, the Republican nominee, was amenable to three.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a Gore campaign spokesman, noted that Gore had
long ago publicly agreed to all three debates suggested by the
commission, and dozens of other debates. ``The more, the merrier,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the chairman of the Gore campaign, William M. Daley,
released a statement late Thursday saying that the campaign had
told the debates commission it was ready ``to meet with them
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   With the post-conventions phase of the campaign nearly upon
them, both the Bush and Gore campaigns were demonstrating an
awareness of how large the matter of debates loomed, and were
maneuvering to put their candidates in the optimal positions.
</P>
<P>
   With Thursday's announcement, Bush's advisers were clearly
trying to quell any sense that Bush was frightened of a somewhat
extemporaneous contest of wits. But they and Bush have also gone
out of their way to talk about what an impressive debater Gore is,
a tactic designed to diminish expectations for the Texas governor
and make sure he exceeds them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the presidential candidates agreed to three debates.
There was only one vice presidential debate, sponsored by the
commission, in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission on Presidential Debates, a bipartisan group, has
proposed presidential debates on Oct. 3 in Boston, Oct. 11 in
Winston-Salem, N.C., and Oct. 17 in St. Louis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
