<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5087 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-SPEECH-460&AMP;ADD-N     08-17 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPEECH-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S SPEECHWRITING APPROACH: OVERWHELMING LENGTH, THEN EDITED
DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Al Gore sat down at his laptop to write _ no
pressure, but everyone said it had better be the speech of his life
_ he began by raiding some of his favorite speeches past, culling
some material that had been written for him and some of his own
stuff, like the eulogy he wrote for his father's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   He threw in everything he might even conceivably want to mention
_ 12,000 words in all. Then he let his speechwriters edit and
polish, tinker and tweak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in the speech reflects what he wanted in the
speech, if you know what I mean,'' said his top consultant, Carter
Eskew, one of three aides who helped edit Gore's acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   The top-down approach is not only the perfect reflection of the
way Gore operates, but the mirror image of the way his Republican
opponent, Gov. George W. Bush, worked on his recent acceptance
speech. Bush, as is far more typical, left the writing to the
professionals and then fiddled with the text, asking for certain
changes and adding some personal touches.
</P>
<P>
   That Gore would make the highly unusual decision to write his
own words surprised no one who knows him well. After all, he wrote
his own book, ``Earth in the Balance,'' and before running for
office worked as a reporter for the Nashville Tennesseean, where
his former editors fondly recall having to tear copy out of his
hands as he kept right on reporting past deadline, never satisfied
that he had all the information.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday afternoon, he was still asking his staff for
various documents he might want to draw from.
</P>
<P>
   For such an important speech, Bush put his writers through 17
drafts.
</P>
<P>
   But a few hours before Gore was to deliver the address, his aide
Laura Quinn joked, ``It's in draft 625'' _ and not necessarily in
final form even then.
</P>
<P>
   Of this much, though, Quinn was positive: ``It won't be short,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gore's original first draft ran 12,000 words, he never
intended to deliver a speech of that length, Eskew said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process was to gather a lot more material than he knew he
could use,'' he said. ``He enjoys the editing process, and that's
how he likes to work. That helps him decide what's essential.''
</P>
<P>
   What was essential? He wanted to explain why he is running, what
he's learned from listening to voters. He wanted to introduce
himself with some good biographical stories. Yet he also wanted to
get into policy details he thought Americans ought to hear before
deciding how to vote.
</P>
<P>
   And another thing: What he most wanted to do, he told his staff,
was look to the future. ``He was adamant that it not be a
recitation of past accomplishments,'' Eskew said. ``He wanted a
direct statement that says this is not an award for past
performance; It's about the future.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After taking his initial, 12,000-word crack at the speech, he
handed a computer disc with that first draft on it to consultant
Robert Shrum and speechwriter Eli Attie, who whittled the speech
down to 7,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   Gore took that version with him on his recent vacation in North
Carolina and worked on it throughout the week of the Republican
convention.
</P>
<P>
   He kept putting various chunks that his aides had taken out back
in _ again in contrast to Bush's impulse to pare down his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to include a foreign policy section,'' for example,
Eskew said. ``Some of us felt that might be a place to cut, but he
said it's an important part of the job and I want to talk about it
and explain how the threats facing our country have changed over
the last 20 years. That's very much him.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked, recently, whether he regretted anything he had
written in ``Earth in the Balance,'' a book that proposed phasing
out the internal combustion engine, and has been widely parodied,
he answered not as a candidate, but as a writer, saying he's still
mulling and very much regrets some sections that were edited out.
</P>
<P>
   As a senator, he not only wrote his own op-ed pieces, but in the
early '80s once turned up at the office New York Times, announced,
``I pulled an all-nighter on this one!'' and hung over an editor's
shoulder as his piece on arms control was being edited.
</P>
<P>
   Where he did make cuts in his acceptance speech, though, they
were in some rhetoric that speechwriters had come up with that did
not feel comfortable for him. His aides, for example, had come up
with the line, ``We're for the people; they're for the powerful,''
_ a line his team wanted him to repeat about a half-dozen times,
throughout the address.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't feel right to him, he told them. Eskew said:
``He said, `Well, that's true, but I only need to say it once.' He
was very much for stripping down the rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Kristin, who works as a comedy writer, contributed
a joke at the last minute, not a side-splitter but a play on words
on why he opposes a Republican-size tax cut: ``You would get 63
cents in change, but that's not the change I'm seeking in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   It was his daughter Sarah, though, who will be a senior at
Harvard in the fall, who of all his family worked most closely with
him on the speech, and spent much of the family vacation helping
him edit and rewrite.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did practice his speech the last couple of days before he
was to deliver it, trying parts of it out on his family, the three
aides who had helped him write it and a couple of members of the
staff of his wife, Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday afternoon, Eskew said the speech _ now down to
5,700 words, about 1,800 more than Bush's _ was finally more or
less finished, except for ``a few little word things. He might
still have to take some things out for time, but he's not making
substantive changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew insisted that Gore did not feel pressured by expectations
and the perception among some pundits that he had to hit a homerun
to stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking forward to it,'' he said, shortly before show
time. ``It's a speech he's been waiting to give for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
