<HEADER>
A5088 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CARSMART-LEXUS-ART-$A     08-17 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARSMART-LEXUS-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FACSIMILE OF GERMANY'S SOLID-GOLD SPORTS SEDAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 20) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DAN NEIL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1996, the Bureau of Engraving began redesigning paper
currency to incorporate anticounterfeiting measures like
color-shifting ink, microprinting and a security thread woven into
the paper. These days it's nearly impossible to make high-quality
money at home.
</P>
<P>
   It is likewise difficult to reproduce the exact mechanical
alchemy that gives certain cars their living spirit. Lexus, for
example, put BMW's 328i on its color copier and came up with the IS
300, a car that is nearly identical to the BMW sport sedan in all
the crucial dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   In height, width and length the Lexus is within an inch of the
BMW. Both cars' profiles are what horse trainers call
short-coupled, with compact, athletic dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Both are motivated by in-line six-cylinder engines with highly
efficient variable valve timing. Both wear outsized, antilock disk
brakes behind lightweight alloy wheels and low-profile tires. Both
interiors are richly appointed with leather and brightwork, both
dashboards are jammed with avionics-style displays.
</P>
<P>
   But the 3-Series' legendary quality is its high-performance
handling, the surreal quality of being almost an anatomical adjunct
to the driver. Once in the Bimmer's deeply bolstered driver's seat,
the contoured leather wheel in your hands, it seems your nerve
endings stretch out to each wheel; control becomes less a matter of
speculation than a matter of limbic certainty. It's not that the
3-Series has such incomparable limits _ it is, after all, a luxury
car on street tires _ but that those limits are so palpable.
</P>
<P>
   How, exactly, BMW designers achieve such a lyric quality is
something even they might find difficult to explain, but if they
could bottle it, other companies would buy it. In vigorous
cornering, the Bimmer's rear tires slide in a controlled and
progressive way, allowing the car to change directions like a skier
schussing his way through a slalom. The ability of a car to behave
this way, called oversteer, is designed in. Oversteer makes a car
more lively and more fun to drive near the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Most cars are designed with a lot of the opposite quality,
understeer, built in _ meaning that in a hard corner the front
tires scrub and scuff like a novice skier plowing down the bunny
slope. Understeer is inherently safer because it requires less
driving skill.
</P>
<P>
   The IS 300, while it has the mechanical credentials to challenge
the 3-Series (in fact, with 215 horsepower and slightly lower curb
weight, the Lexus has a better power-to-weight ratio than the
193-horse BMW) ultimately fails to clone the soul of the German
car. In aggressive driving the Lexus tends to plow _ ``push,'' as
they say in Nascar _ through tight corners and hairpins, scrubbing
the shoulders of its 17-inch Goodyear Eagle GS-D's. It is possible
to get the tail to pitch around by chopping the throttle, but when
tossed around, the IS 300 never seems as comfortable and
controllable as the BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexus' speed-sensitive steering felt a little leaden,
accurate but immoderately heavy, particularly at slow speeds. The
3-Series, with its joystick quickness, remains the gold standard of
vehicle dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say the Lexus is a slug _ not by a long shot.
Even with the automatic transmission, which would dampen the flame
of any performance car, the IS 300 is gloriously quick. The
charcoal-metallic test model had gone more than 3,000 miles and
seemed, by benefit of that break-in period, quicker than the cars
tested by enthusiast magazines. Motor Trend paced the IS 300 to 60
mph at 7.4 seconds; I saw 7.1 seconds on my handheld stopwatch.
</P>
<P>
   Deactivate the traction control and the Lexus will smoke the
tires nicely. The brakes are fabulous, stout and fade-free, the
calipers seizing the ventilated discs with a longshoreman's grip
long after the pads begin to stink from the effort. Sitting on a
well-damped and sprung suspension, the IS 300 exhibits excellent
control of body roll, and the ride is first rate, cloudlike and
supple in the hovercraft way that Lexus has perfected. At its most
harried the IS 300 hums like a transformer.
</P>
<P>
   About 25,000 Americans are expected to pick up their copies of
this Lexus, and they can console themselves with the IS 300's high
design quotient. The signature piece of the IS 300 is its
instrument panel styled like a Breitling chronograph. Combined with
the many climate and audio buttons, the drilled-out aluminum foot
pedals and a hefty globe of polished aluminum serving as a shift
knob, the IS 300 gives you plenty to look at. Ultimately, however,
it seems to lack the BMW's maturity and seriousness, a quality that
political pundits might call gravitas.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lexus yields to the BMW in driving pleasure, it
surrenders nothing in value. The test car, with leather, moonroof,
heated seats and more, came in at $34,635 _ roughly $3,000 less
than a comparably equipped 3-series. And even with the siren call
of the BMW's delightful handling, 3 grand is to most buyers a lot
of money. Unless they print their own.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
