<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miller, 23, relies on experienceBy Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At Bela Karolyi's training camps earlier this year,
Shannon Miller didn't feel like she was so old that she creaked
around the other gymnasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were in the gym, it's like we're the same age,'' said
Miller, 23, who is trying for her third Olympic team. ``In a lot of
ways, I'm still a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Once outside the gym, however, Miller acted her age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to play GameBoy during breaks,'' she said. ``I
want to read a book or call my husband. I gotta pay the bills when
I get home.''
</P>
<P>
   The most decorated gymnast in U.S. Olympic history with five
medals _ two gold _ Miller is one of the final three holdouts from
Atlanta's Magnificent Seven at the Olympic trials. She and
Dominique Dawes, also 23, and Amy Chow, 22, hope their seasoning
will match up well against the younger gymnasts' skills.
</P>
<P>
   A committee headed by Karolyi, who has praised Miller's effort,
will select the team after Sunday's final all-around competition.
</P>
<P>
   Miller decided to return in December while she was getting into
shape for the post-Olympic tour. She took a year off from Oklahoma,
where she is a junior majoring in finance _ ``I just love numbers,
I always have'' _ to train.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Miller has been asked point-blank if she has put her
reputation on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Steve (Nunno, her coach) asked me that: `Do you really
want to tarnish your image? What if you go all the way and don't
make the team? Why not finish on a high note?' I look at it, `Why
would you quit knowing you can succeed, instead of trying and maybe
fall a little short?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Miller doesn't plan on falling short. This time, she has
even invited her husband to watch. Chris Phillips, an
ophthalmologist who is doing his residency in Houston, has never
seen his wife compete in person.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips didn't come to St. Louis for the national championships
because Miller wasn't sure if she would perform. Because of a
hairline stress fracture in her right leg, she wound up doing only
one routine, tying for second on the uneven bars.
</P>
<P>
   The injury, Miller said, ``is really not even in the equation
right now. It's just whether I have done enough numbers of routines
to be able to hit it when I need to hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Olympic trials were held here in 1996, Miller didn't
need to hit anything. Because of a wrist injury, she sat out the
trials. Her scores carried over from nationals, and she placed
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upstairs in the suites,'' Miller said. ``I'm happy to be
down on the floor this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was also on the sidelines as the athlete rep when a young
U.S. team finished sixth at the 1999 World Championships in China.
She wants to help her country return to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love doing this sport,'' she said. ``To be able to hold an
Olympic medal in your hand is something I've felt before, and it'd
sure be nice to feel it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
