u p BC-CHENEY-RETIRE-NYT &LR;      08-17 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN CHENEY'S RETIREMENT PACKAGE, SOME UNCHARTED
TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The retirement package awarded by the Halliburton Co. to Dick
Cheney, the Republican nominee for vice president, is nowhere near
the largest ever given to a chief executive, but it is trailblazing
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Cheney's estimated $20 million package consists of a
stock option grant. And although options are an increasingly
popular form of executive compensation, they would be in totally
uncharted territory in the hands of a vice president, whose role in
the White House has the potential to affect the company's fortunes
and so place him in a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   When Cheney resigned from Halliburton on Wednesday, he received
an unspecified bonus, was free to sell 140,000 formerly restricted
shares of company stock and was allowed to keep options on 1.16
million shares. The current value of Cheney's stock and options,
which give him the right to buy Halliburton shares at a specified
price, is approximately $39 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has said that if the Republican ticket wins the election,
he will sell his Halliburton shares before he takes office,
removing one potential conflict of interest that he would have in
the future of Halliburton, the oil services giant.
</P>
<P>
   But the way Halliburton has structured part of Cheney's option
grant would keep him squarely in a conflict: 233,000 of his options
_ worth around $3.8 million, if they could be exercised today _ can
be turned into shares of Halliburton only in December 2001 and
December 2002. Because he cannot sell or transfer the options
before then, he would continue to have a stake in the company while
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Vande Beek, a spokesman for Cheney, former secretary of
defense, said Thursday, ``Secretary Cheney will do whatever he
needs to do to avoid any conflict of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   But exactly what, as a practical matter, he would need to do is
not cut and dried. Neither the president nor the vice president is
subject to the criminal conflict-of-interest laws that govern all
other employees in the executive branch. Both must complete
financial disclosure statements, and politics demands that they
work to avoid creating a conflict with their personal interests;
the assumption is that voters can judge for themselves whether
these elected officials are living up to the nation's standards.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of time-tested practices that a high official
can follow to avoid conflicts. Cheney, for example, could recuse
himself on matters involving the oil industry, though that might
limit his usefulness as a presidential adviser. Like President
Clinton or former Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin, an official
can also set up a blind trust for his holdings. But such a trust
would not solve any conflict issues posed by Cheney's options,
because the trust is meant to be invested in assets whose identity
is unknown to the beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts said Cheney's best approach would be to divest
himself of every Halliburton share and option. ``The cleanest route
would be to eliminate self-interest altogether and forfeit and
cancel the options,'' said Patrick McGurn, vice president of
Institutional Shareholder Services, an investment advisory firm in
Rockville, Md. ``But is anybody going to do that? Given the paper
value, that's putting a pretty hefty price tag on altruism.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is by no means the only politician whose public life has
been complicated by his or his family's investments. Vice President
Al Gore has become the object of environmentalists' wrath for his
mother's stake in the Occidental Petroleum Corp. _ a holding worth
$250,000 to $500,000, according to government filings. And the
income earned by Gore on land he leases for zinc mining has raised
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is Cheney's retirement package that shines the
spotlight on practices in executive compensation that critics
describe as over the top, from enormous grants of stock options to
pay that has nothing to do with performance. Carl Schmitt, vice
president at WestWard Pay Strategies, an executive compensation
consulting firm in San Francisco, said he believed that Cheney's
deal would bring more public scrutiny to executive pay in general
and to retirement packages in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be the continuing issue of the smell test,''
Schmitt said. ``It's very common for boards of directors to give
sweetheart deals to executives who are retiring. But that may not
pass the smell test in the political arena, and that may be a new
issue for people to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   The immense wealth created by rising stock prices in recent
years has made the intersection of Wall Street and Washington an
increasingly busy place. Politicians, like most Americans, have
flocked to the stock market in search of portfolio gains.
Meanwhile, public service holds appeal to many in the corporate
sector who have made their fortunes and are looking for a way to
give something back to the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the nature of the beast today that you don't see that
many lifetime politicians anymore _ they tend to jump in and out of
public life,'' McGurn said. ``So every time one of these
transitions occur, the boards of the companies on which they serve
have to deal with these issues. It's another one of those issues
that is going to come up in the stockholder or stock option society
that we've moved into.''
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat surprising that Cheney's relatively modest exit
deal should create such a stir. Retirement packages among corporate
titans have become so outsized today that some of them can make
Cheney's look like chump change.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Doug Ivester retired last year after a
two-year, largely unsuccessful stint as chairman of the Coca-Cola
Co., he received a total package worth $120 million, according to
Graef Crystal, an executive compensation specialist who writes a
column for Bloomberg News. And Jill E. Barad left as chief
executive of Mattel Inc. with a $50 million package even though the
company and its stock had performed woefully under her leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney's deal was unusually favorable in one way, according
to experts in executive compensation: Halliburton's board did not
demand that he quickly exercise all his options. When executives
and even lower-level employees retire from a company, they are
typically forced to exercise their options within one year of their
exit. The longer an option lasts, the greater the potential for
large gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a minority of companies that provide the full term of an
option, post-retirement,'' said Ed Archer, vice president at Pearl
Meyer &AMP; Partners, an executive-compensation consulting firm in New
York. ``Most don't do it.'' Indeed, he said, the general
requirement that options be exercised quickly means they are very
often unlikely to pose conflicts for ``28-year-old dot-commers''
running for office.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Hall, a spokeswoman for Halliburton, said Cheney had
received no special treatment. ``All of this is part of our
standard retirement policy,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
