u p BC-DEM-CUOMO-NYT &LR;      08-17 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-CUOMO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LOS ANGELES, NEW YORK HOPEFULS MAKE THE ROUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Andrew Cuomo, the federal housing secretary who
wants to be governor of New York, had just finished speaking to the
Native American Caucus and was heading for the African-American
Caucus when he was stopped by a delegate who had heard him speak to
the California delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to put you on the spot,'' Cuomo declared, leaning
in close to the Californian, as passers-by snapped photographs of
the son of a New York celebrity. ``Who gave a better speech this
morning, me or Ted Kennedy?''
</P>
<P>
   The delegate did not even stop for a breath: ``Ted Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo froze, shook the man's hand and moved on down the hall of
the Westin Bonaventure Hotel, whispering over his shoulder to a
reporter who had observed the encounter, ``California is Kennedy
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, at times this week, California seemed to be more like
New York country, or rather, New York political country. No sooner
had Hillary Rodham Clinton taken her campaign for senator from New
York back to New York than Cuomo _ and the other New York Democrat
who wants to run for governor in 2002, Carl McCall, the state
comptroller _ plunged into their own political rounds, talking to
state delegates and any delegation who would hear them, and of
course, to reporters. Both men even got a chance to address the
convention here, McCall on Wednesday and Cuomo tonight, though both
speeches were given south of prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo insisted Thursday that his top concern here was not
tending to any hope he might have to become the second New York
governor named Cuomo, but rather in advancing the campaign of Vice
President Al Gore, whom Cuomo refers to as ``Al.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Democratic convention,'' Cuomo said, on a drive over
to the convention center here. ``As a cabinet member, my job here
is to communicate the record and mobilize the Democrats to go
forward. That's job No. 1. Everything else is a distant second _ it
being two years away.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo has received pointed reminders this week of both McCall's
enduring popularity among Democratic leaders in New York, as well
the lingering animosity some Democrats hold toward Cuomo's father,
Mario. And Andrew Cuomo is still viewed in some quarters here as a
bit of a political whippersnapper.
</P>
<P>
   So Cuomo's schedule of events is 23 pages long for the week,
taking him Thursday to the empty convention floor for an interview
with Gabe Pressman of WNBC-TV, Channel 4 in New York, and to
private meetings with New York delegates. There he argued that the
success of Gov. George W. Bush to date was proof that Cuomo would
not be weighed down by his own father, who was defeated for a third
term in 1994, should he run for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've learned in this election is the American people
don't condemn a son for the acts of the father,'' Cuomo said. And
then, referring to his own case, Cuomo said: ``If that were the
case, this election would be over _ even if you thought Mario
Cuomo's a negative in the state, which I don't believe it is.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall has also been methodically tending to his own political
future, meeting with New York Democrats and lining up future
financial contributors in a state where, he said Thursday, he has
already raised $400,000 toward the 2002 race. McCall was loudly
applauded when he appeared before the New York delegation, where he
was repeatedly referred to as ``the next governor of the state of
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay a lot of time paying attention to what Andrew
Cuomo or anyone else is doing,'' McCall said Thursday. ``Let met
just tell you what I'm doing. I've just solidifying what I have.
I've been relating to these folks for quite a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo suggested he was less than impressed with that. ``It's
what I would have to believe,'' he said. ``I've been in Washington.
His is the highest patronage office. It has to be that way. It
can't be any other way. What does the Democratic Party
establishment do for you? It's not a field operation. It's not your
money-raising operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, Cuomo was a bit more splashy in his
activities here, traveling around with a contingent that includes
his wife, Kerry Kennedy Cuomo, and a California-based public
relations consultant who alerted reporters back in New York to
Cuomo's comings and goings.
</P>
<P>
   For Cuomo, the high point Thursday was his speech to the
convention, an event that inevitably recalled the keynote speech
that Mario Cuomo delivered in 1984 to the Democratic National
Convention in San Francisco, one of the most memorable of recent
conventions. (It seemed that the four words Cuomo heard most often
Thursday were, ``I loved your father''). But the younger Cuomo
blanched at the suggestion that his own speech invited comparisons
to his father, quickly noting that his mission was limited to
talking up Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have only five minutes,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
