<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5095 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-PGA-LEDE0818-COX     08-17 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PGA-LEDE0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods fires a 66 to assume share of 1st-round lead
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Stop me if you've heard this one. . . .
</P>
<P>
   It's a major championship and Tiger Woods is in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Pass the remote, Mildred. Is there anything else to watch?
</P>
<P>
   If golf fans have been following during the previous two majors,
there might be only one question remaining: Will Woods rout a major
championship field for the third consecutive time or just eke one
out to spare everyone from a humiliation hat trick?
</P>
<P>
   For those clinging to high-drama hope in the 82nd PGA
Championship at Valhalla Golf Club, Woods, 24, at least for one
night had to hit the sack as merely a co-leader, having been
matched at 66 by Scott Dunlap, the well-traveled Duluth, Ga.,
resident.
</P>
<P>
   What happens from here on in could be all too predictable. If
mind-boggling trends from Pebble Beach and St. Andrews, where Woods
has won a U.S. Open by 15 shots and a British Open by eight, are to
continue, we could be in for an historical, but familiar rerun.
Players with afternoon tee times who glanced at the leaderboard
Thursday, seeing Woods at 66 before they even began, could not help
but feel they knew what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a player of that caliber gets that much confidence and
sees and feels the other players saying, `Oh, there he goes again,'
it gives him another shot of confidence,'' said Greg Norman, who
struggled to a 75. ``You have to get over that hump and know you're
good enough to beat whoever is leading. If you feel like you're not
good enough to do that, don't even be out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Dunlap, who has no intention of leaving but trails Woods in
PGA Tour victories 21-0, had to admit, ``He's won the last two
majors by 23 shots. I'd be lying to suggest that his presence is
anything but discouraging to everyone else involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the rest of the field, which contains 91 of
the world's top 100? If Dunlap can keep pace with Tiger for a day,
so can others. The bad news? Woods could have just as easily shot
Nicklaus' age.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to equal Ben Hogan's 1953 record of three major titles in
one year, Woods birdied all of the par-5's and the par-4 9th,
bogeying only the 5th hole after blasting long from a bunker and
missing a 20-footer. He made a 10-footer for par on the 17th, then
needed only a 3-footer at the par-5 18th after blasting from the
greenside bunker. He hit driver, 7-iron to the 597-yard 7th, taking
the short cut after the island fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're playing with a man who is shooting a 66 and looks like
he's shooting a 60,'' said Nicklaus, who for the first time was
grouped with Woods, joining Vijay Singh, in a major championship.
``He is unlucky to shoot 66. You're out there struggling for 75. It
makes you feel like you're shooting 95.''
</P>
<P>
   While thrilled with the opportunity, Nicklaus, who had a 77, was
distracted somewhat after the death of his 90-year-old mother
Wednesday. Playing in what could be his final PGA Championship,
Nicklaus remained in the tournament according to his mother's
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what she wanted me to do,'' Nicklaus said. ``I had no
desire to be here, I promise you. But I felt like that is what she
would have wanted me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sea Island's Davis Love III, the 1997 PGA champion, and Northern
Ireland's Darren Clarke are tied for third at 68, which could be a
wash as competition for Woods. Love carved a negative image by
showing he was intimidated by Woods at Bay Hill. Clarke beat Woods
in the World Golf Championship Match Play in February.
</P>
<P>
   With the course drying out and firming up with temperatures in
the 90's, Woods has a great advantage hitting shorter irons into
the par-4's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger can spin it so much,'' said Fred Funk, who had a 69,
``he can hit a 7 or 8-iron 170-180 yards, spin the heck out of it
and stop it. He's amazing. He's in a different world right now and
I don't know who is going to be able to challenge that kind of
shotmaking he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
