<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5096 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-17 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK AND TIGER: MIRROR IMAGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Tiger Woods' name traveled up the giant
scoreboard beside the 17th green at Valhalla Golf Club Thursday
like an elevator called to the penthouse. A fan stood off to the
side, mesmerized by the red numbers rising next to Woods's name.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods hit 5-under par, the fan blinked, turned back to his
friend and, pointing to the scoreboard, said, ``I can see Tiger
going into Saturday 10 strokes ahead of everyone else. Good God.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Good Woods to you, Scott Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   You, too, Darren Clarke, Davis Love III, Edward Fryatt, et al.
</P>
<P>
   Woods spent most of the morning chasing Dunlap, who clipped six
strokes off par to grab the lead at the PGA Championship. He caught
the journeyman on the 18th hole, matching Dunlap's 66 with a 3-foot
birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   With Woods ensconced alongside Dunlap at the top of the
leaderboard after one round of golf's fourth and final major of the
season, we feel quite comfortable saying ``60 Minutes'' curmudgeon
Andy Rooney can start affixing his smirk; this CBS weekend sports
production is in the can.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to surpass Woods _ Clarke? Sure, the Irishman shot
an opening 68. But he also stated earlier this week that Woods
clearly is the one to beat in the majors for the foreseeable future
and ``the fact that Tiger is going to play so well gives less
opportunity for the rest of us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   You like Love's chances, you say? Yes, he fired a 68, too. But
you should know he is the same guy who earlier this year said of
Woods, ``He plays his best more than we do. You start thinking,
`Can I beat him?' and he thrives on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap might be every duffer's choice, but he has zero victories
in 87 PGA tournament starts. Fryatt, who fired a 69? His goose is
cooked.
</P>
<P>
   We like Woods' chances of becoming the first golfer since Ben
Hogan in 1953 to win three consecutive majors because he has led
after the first round three times in the past two years and won two
of those events. Moreover, since his victory in the 1999 PGA
Championship, the 24-year-old has been within two strokes of the
lead after the first round nine times and emerged victorious in
eight of those tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   No way would we advise betting against Woods to win the fifth
major of his career and his seventh tournament of the year right
here. Not after the Man inside the ropes with Woods on Thursday
spoke as emphatically of him as the fan we heard around the 17th
green.
</P>
<P>
   For Jack Nicklaus, his round with Woods _ the first-ever pairing
of the two in a tournament _ unfolded like a compact mirror. He
caught a reflection of his much younger self in the former Stanford
star out of Anaheim's Western High.
</P>
<P>
   The steely focus, the prodigious length off the tee, the
masterly course management that Nicklaus used to win 18 major
professional tournaments were all there, albeit in a decidedly
distinct package.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus he has, the shots he hits, the absolute control of
what he'strying to do is fantastic,'' Nicklaus said. ``He shot the
easiest 66 today. He missed a half-dozen putts that were burning
the hole. It was a privilege to watch him.''
</P>
<P>
   The honor was mutual. From the time Woods was a wee one,
Nicklaus has been the yardstick by which he has measured the growth
of his game. He has patterned his golf so closely after Nicklaus'
that Nicklaus knew exactly what magic trick Woods had pulled out of
his bag on the 166-yard, par-3 eighth hole when he waved his
9-iron. The ball landed 12 feet below the pin and he made the
birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of funny,'' Woods said, ``because he asked me,
`You are trying to play short of the swell?' I said, `Yeah . . .
but I got away with it and hit it at the flag.' Most people would
be thinking (he was) trying to hit the ball up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me a couple of times what I was trying to do. Most
people don't do that. I thought that was kind of interesting
because I feel like I have an understanding of how he plays. I kind
of play the same way he used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus was understandably not himself Thursday. His
90-year-old mother had passed away the previous day after a long
illness, and thoughts of her punctured his concentration. ``I had
no desire to be here, I promise you,'' Nicklaus said after posting
a 77 (the same as Vijay Singh, who rounded out the day's must-see
threesome). ``But I felt like playing is what she would have wanted
me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The small city that followed the threesome around on another
sweltering day let Nicklaus know it appreciated his presence. He
received the warmest, loudest, longest applause at every tee and
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was yelling `Jack, Jack, Jack, look over here,
Jack.' No one saw me,'' Woods said, breaking into a wide smile.
``It was kind of nice. Shot 66.''
</P>
<P>
   And 149 golfers' hearts stopped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
