<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MCGARITY0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGarity tries to make last cut at camp
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ As Wane McGarity will attest, not every
promising football story has a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   This comes from a young man who knows plenty about adversity.
Knee injuries. A separated shoulder. A broken finger.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is another hurdle to clear before the regular season
begins in 16 days. There is no guarantee that the Dallas Cowboys,
heavily stocked with capable wide receivers, will keep the comeback
kid from the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do anything to help this football club,'' McGarity said
after Thursday morning's camp workout. ``This is where I need to
be. This is where I feel I'm at my best.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest decisions the coaching staff faces will be
final cuts. The Cowboys are expected to keep six receivers _ maybe
five _ and a few talented players will not make the grade.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: Joey Galloway, Rocket Ismail and James
McKnight will make the cut. McGarity and Jason Tucker likely will
make it, too. Then again, Chris Brazzell, Darran Hall and Jeff
Ogden also have impressive credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, the players who aren't on top of the depth chart
are fighting for playing time _ and for jobs,'' Coach Dave Campo
said.
</P>
<P>
   If you read between the lines, though, McGarity's job status
appears safe. Before he missed 11 games last season with various
injuries, McGarity impressed the Cowboys with his toughness and
positive attitude. When pressed on McGarity's status this week,
Campo and offensive coordinator Jack Reilly gave him a vote of
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Campo: ``Wane showed me enough last year to make me think he
will have playing time this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly: ``I don't feel he's in that (bubble) category. He's done
a very good job. You never know what could happen in the next
couple of games.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been McGarity's year of redemption. The screws that
were inserted into his right ring finger during last fall's surgery
have been removed. By squeezing putty daily during rehabilitation,
his hand once again is strong enough to handle Troy Aikman's
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Mention injuries and McGarity smiles. Mention his comeback from
injuries, he smiles again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big relief,'' McGarity said. ``All I have to worry
about now is the soreness. I've been injury-free in camp, and I
take good care of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Final cuts are hard to determine because other players have been
slowed by camp injuries. Ismail, Knight, Tucker and Ogden have
missed part or all of camp because of injuries. How the injury
status affects roster decisions, no one knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can do is control my position,'' McGarity
said. ``I try to make my statement every day. It's going to be a
tough decision, though. (The receivers) are out here working hard
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity has had a fair share of camp mistakes. He has dropped
passes in games and practices. He has lined up wrong on a few
occasions. Yet he has made up for it with enough good plays to keep
him around.
</P>
<P>
   There was another sign this week that McGarity's job is safe. He
is learning how to be a holder for field goals, and it makes little
sense to cut a player who has been asked to handle such an
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's practice, McGarity joined Galloway on the
first-team offense while Ismail (thumb injury) and McKnight (knee)
took time off.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway and Ismail will start at wide receiver during the
season, and McGarity is expected to be an inside (slot) receiver on
passing downs. Tucker likely will make the team over Brazzell and
Ogden because he played well last season. A starter in four games,
Tucker finished with 22 catches, 439 yards and two touchdowns. It
makes no difference that he has missed most of summer camp with a
groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel Tucker did enough last year to solidify the fact that
he can be an improving player as it goes,'' Campo said. ``I have a
real good feel for what he did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo said the receivers at the back of the pack still have time
to make a good impression. The two remaining preseason games could
make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it's going to work out for everybody,''
McGarity said. ``I'm going to keep on working and let it all come
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
