u s BC-GLF-PGA-BOS &LR;      08-17 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER WOODS OFF TO EARLY LEAD IN PGA CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ They were gasping for air at the 82d PGA
Championship Thursday at Valhalla Golf Club, to no avail. The heat
index of 105 degrees was bad enough; then Tiger Woods sucked the
life out of the festivities with another clinic that dropped a
bucket of despair on the other 149 players in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Don't buy it? Listen to Scott Dunlap: ``He's won the last two
majors by 23 shots. His presence is nothing more than discouraging
for the rest of the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider that those words belong to a man who had just hit 14
greens, taken only 26 putts, and birdied the par-5 18th to shoot a
6-under 66, and you get a real sense of why this major championship
was tucked snugly into a blanket of frustration just five hours
after it started. That's because Woods, threatening to join Ben
Hogan as the only players to win three major championships in a
season, continued his incomparable play with a 66 to grab a share
of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Clarke, whose match-play triumph over Woods in February
is often used as a rallying point for those competitors who feel
hopeless, shot 68, as did Davis Love. The group at 69 consists of
Edward Fryatt, Fred Funk, Stephen Ames, and J.P. Hayes, while those
at 70 include Phil Mickelson, Brian Henninger, Miguel Angel
Jimenez, and Jean Van de Velde.
</P>
<P>
   Formidable players, but on a rainless day that was interminable
_ 18 were still on the course when darkness halted play at 8:27
p.m. _ the overpowering stature of Woods dominated. Again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you can shoot 66 in a major championship, you are
going to be pretty happy,'' said Woods, who seemingly didn't break
a sweat in his near-perfect trip around a course on which he had
barely practiced on. It was a performance that led his playing
partner, Jack Nicklaus, to utter an expression that was once spoken
by the legendary Bobby Jones:
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays a game with which I am not familiar,'' said Nicklaus,
who prompted that Jones quote back in the early 1960s, when the
Golden Bear was mauling Augusta National and starting his stockpile
of green jackets. He is the Olden Bear now, more an ambassador than
a competitor, and recently he acknowledged that other PGA Tour
players have waved the white flag to Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Paired with Woods for the first time in competition, Nicklaus
(77) now knows why. That's because the guy who this summer has
posted 12- and 8-shot wins at the US Open and British Open,
respectively, was at it again over a course designed by Nicklaus.
Woods hit 11 of 14 fairways, 16 greens, and ``shoots a 66 that
looks like 60,'' said Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   A nice compliment, said Woods, but not quite accurate. ``I don't
know if I left that many (shots on the course), but I definitely
left a few. Then again, I also made some good putts for par, so
it's give-and-take.''
</P>
<P>
   More like take-and-keep-taking because the roll Woods is on is
unprecedented. Including the final two rounds of this year's
Masters _ when an opening 75 led to a fifth-place finish _ Woods is
now a mind-boggling 44-under par in the last 11 rounds at major
championships. He opened with a 65 at the US Open, a 67 at the
British, so you may see some sort of trend here.
</P>
<P>
   His competitors sure do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a player of that caliber gets that much confidence and
when he sees and feels the other players saying, `Oh, there he goes
again,' it gives him another shot of confidence,'' said Greg
Norman, who shot 75 and is one of the many marquee names who can
say goodbye to this chance for a major victory.
</P>
<P>
   That list includes Ernie Els and Colin Montgomerie, both of who
drew an afternoon tee time that set them in motion on a six-hour
torcher chamber in sweltering heat, accompanied by the knowledge
that Woods had already shot 66.
</P>
<P>
   What they may not know are the details, which again featured a
trademark Woods birdie-burst. Even par through six holes, he
birdied the 597-yard par-5 seventh with a driver, 7-iron and two
putts from 30 feet, then ran off birdies at the next three holes to
get to 4-under. After a 3-wood, 6-iron combination set up a 12-foot
birdie putt at the 467-yard par-4 12th, Woods strung together five
pars, highlighted by one nightmarish hole. Or what passes as a
nightmare for him these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 17th wasn't very good,'' said Woods, who drove it into the
rough, left his second shot well short of the green, and stubbed a
chip shot. Ah, but when you putt the way your playing partner
(Nicklaus) used to 30 years ago, there are no worries. Woods
drained the 15-foot par save, then birdied the par-5 18th after
nearly holing his sand shot for eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The putt at 17 enabled me to keep the momentum going,'' said
Woods, who stole virtually all of the thunder from the unheralded
Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   That should come as no surprise, since Dunlap's resume such
victories at the Manitoba Open, Litoral Open, Peru Open, and
Argentine Open. He has one top 10 finish in eight major
championships and though he eagled the par-5 second and recorded
five birdies against a lone bogey at the par-3 third, there is a
1-2 punch dwelling on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is come out (Friday) and hopefully do a whole lot
better than I did Friday at the British Open,'' he said, referring
to his 68 start that got wiped out with a 78.
</P>
<P>
   And Woods?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is going to do it, he is going to do it. There is no
stopping him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap wouldn't find many who'd argue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
