<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5108 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-RDP-ART-2NDTAKE-N     08-17 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-RDP-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: their kids.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The economy is in many ways Gore's greatest asset on the stump.
Given its strength, he should be doing much better, by normal
standards. Candidates of parties that hold the White House usually
fare well when the economy is strong and the country is involved in
no foreign war.
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president has been unable to generate the kind of
electricity that follows Clinton everywhere. And Clinton's speech
on Monday night did nothing to light a fire for his protege. ``All
he did was, he made a good case for Clinton,'' said Gerald
Rafshoon, Jimmy Carter's imagemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Some weeks ago, Sam Popkin, a professor at the University of
California at San Diego who is working in the Gore campaign,
defined the goals of the two candidates at their respective
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, he said, needed to show some gravitas, while Gore needed
to show some levitas. In other words, one needed to show he was not
a lightweight, the other to lighten up.
</P>
<P>
   By common consent, the Republican made at least a start at the
Philadelphia convention towards establishing himself as a serious
political figure, capable of handling large issues. It was much
less clear that the Democrat had improved on his image as a
plodding, overearnest orator and campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   At least in its written form, Gore's speech seemed pedestrian,
without notable rhetorical flourishes or unexpected new policy
departures.
</P>
<P>
   Some in his camp still hope for a modest post-convention
``bounce'' in opinion polls about Gore's candidacy, but their
ultimate goal is to turn the race around in the debates with Bush.
The Texas governor agreed Thursday to three debates with the vice
president, starting in early October, as well as two between the
vice presidential nominees. But the Bush campaign made no agreement
as to the debates' length or format.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, an experienced and accomplished debater, said earlier in
the campaign that he would like to debate twice weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was preceded to the podium by a parade of speakers,
including Kweisi Mfume, a former congressman who is now president
of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People,
and Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamente of California, the first statewide
Hispanic officeholder in this state this century.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the modern, made-for-television style, a parade of
friends of the nominee extolled his virtues. Among the speakers
were David Halberstam, the journalist and author, a family friend,
and Robert Delabar of Seattle, who met Gore while both were
stationed at Fort Rucker, Ala., in their service in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Gore served in Vietnam while Bush did not, and the Democrats
have made a point of that difference all during their convention.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Tipper Gore, the vice president's wife, came on to
introduce him. An amateur photographer, she described her husband
as ``a decisive leader with strong values, deeply held convictions
and an unwavering commitment to making the American dream a reality
for all our people,'' and showed samples from what she described as
``the family photo album.''
</P>
<P>
   There was an echo of Tipper Gore's past attacks on popular music
that features explicit sexual content in Gore's speech, much of
which he wrote himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we must challenge a culture with too much meanness
and not enough meaning,'' he said. ``And as president I will stand
with you for a goal that I know we share: To give more power back
to the parents, so that you can choose what your own children are
exposed to, and pass on the basic lessons of responsibility and
decency.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Gore's other themes was an openness to voters' views.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm elected president,'' he said, ``I'm going to keep on
having open meetings all over this country. I'm going to go out to
you, the people, because I want to stay in touch with your hopes,
with the quiet, everyday heroism of hard-working Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing John F. Kennedy, who announced the start of a journey to
a New Frontier when nominated here in Los Angeles 40 years ago,
Gore urged listeners to ``set out on a new journey to the best
America.''
</P>
<P>
   He called it, in some of the most poetic language he used, a
journey ``on which we advance not by the turning of wheels, but by
the turning of our minds, the reach of our vision and the daring
grace of the human spirit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
