<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DONATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS' CONVENTION, LIKE THAT OF GOP, UNDERWRITTEN BY
CORPORATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., S.D., N.J., Calif., Va.)   By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Barely an hour after Vice President Al Gore issued
a call for reforming the ways political campaigns are paid for, he
headed back to the fund-raising circuit for a concert that raised
$5.2 million for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In the prepared drafts of his acceptance speech Thursday night,
aides said, Gore once again called for an end to the large,
unrestricted political contributions known as soft money and
promised to make legislation banning soft money the first bill he
would send to Congress as president.
</P>
<P>
   But the four-day Democratic convention here was a soft-money
extravaganza, underwritten by scores of corporations that have
already contributed millions of dollars to Democratic committees
and from which the party hopes to reap millions more. Most notable
among the convention's sponsors were telecommunications companies,
which have reaped large profits from the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials were quick to note that the sold-out
fund-raising concert at the Shrine Auditorium Thursday night
featuring Barbra Streisand continued a tradition of celebrating the
party's nominee at an event after the convention ends.
</P>
<P>
   And they noted that the concert Thursday night, also starring
Whoopi Goldberg and Enrique Iglesias, raised only ``hard'' dollars,
money collected in amounts from $150 to $20,000 that the party can
use directly on Gore's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic National Committee has always held a gala at
the end of the convention to raise money and excitement for the
ticket,'' said Jennifer Backus, a spokeswoman for the party. She
said that the event was consistent with the party's support for
campaign finance reform because it collected only hard money. The
$5.2 million raised Thursday night was the largest hard-money event
in Democratic Party history, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sen. Russell Feingold of Wisconsin, a Democratic
co-sponsor of a measure to ban soft money in politics, was critical
of the concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would prefer there be no such events at our convention,''
Feingold said. ``It doesn't add to our message to have these events
going on in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   The concert was the only fund-raiser that the Democratic
National Committee held this week. But Democratic candidates and
congressional fund-raising committees courted contributors
ceaselessly all week.
</P>
<P>
   At a luncheon at the home of children's entertainment executive
Haim Saban, the most generous donors to the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee sipped lemonade and picked at a luncheon of
chicken salad with the Senate minority leader, Thomas Daschle of
South Dakota; Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, the committee's
chairman; Dianne Feinstein of California; Charles Robb of Virginia,
and a bevy of other Democratic senators.
</P>
<P>
   After playing a prominent role at the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago, telecommunications
companies were big underwriters of events for the Democrats.
Corporate giants like AT&AMP;T, BellSouth, Verizon, SBC Communications,
Sprint Telecommunications and Teligent sponsored more than a dozen
costly receptions for top lawmakers this week.
</P>
<P>
   They entertained members of the House and Senate commerce
committees, their legislative overseers, at Dodger Stadium Tuesday
evening. Among the sponsors of Dodger Day 2000 was the U.S. Telecom
Association, a trade group whose president, Roy Neel, is a former
chief of staff for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   They also helped underwrite a ``Mardi Gras'' party for Sen. John
Breaux of Louisiana, and a nightclub show featuring the singer
Sheryl Crow.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Knight, another former chief of staff for Gore and now
deputy chairman of the Democratic National Committee, has lobbied
on behalf of two telecommunications companies, Bell Atlantic and
Leap Wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Communications companies rented out Spago restaurant in Beverly
Hills for Torricelli on Tuesday and for House Democratic leader
Dick Gephardt on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, which donated $250,000 to both Republican and
Democratic conventions, also paid for a dinner to honor Daschle on
Wednesday. The company seeks federal approval to lay a
telecommunitions cable across the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, which has the most prominent presence here of any
telecommunications company, gave $1 million in goods and services
to each party for their conventions. The long-distance giant is the
largest contributor to the Republican Party, having given $1.4
million since January 1999, and the fourth-largest to the
Democrats, who received $993,000 over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``These firms are the driving engine of the new economy and are
in the process of becoming the driving force in political
finance,'' said Fred Wertheimer, a longtime advocate of campaign
finance reform. ``They have a huge stake in government decisions,
more so than almost any other sector of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications companies rely on Congress and the executive
branch for approvals of mergers, for access to the airwaves, for
permission to offer local or long-distance telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of telecommunications technology has made these
companies enormously wealthy and they are spreading that wealth
around elected officials without regard to party affiliation,
Wertheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Taylor, the chief lobbyist for the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, said that communications companies support members of
both parties because issues that concern them, including visas for
foreign workers and privacy protection on the Internet, are
generally not ideological and require bipartisan majorities for
passage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
