<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   The following photos have been sent as part of tonight's New
York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 08/17/00.
</P>
<P>
   We will be sending a separate budget slugged,
BC-DEM-PHOTO-BUDGET-NYT, listing the photos moved from the
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Photo clients will automatically receive our photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   ELIMINATION NOTICE:
</P>
<P>
   Please note that we have sent out an elimination advisory for
NYT3 sent Sunday, Aug. 13, 2000, with the story slugged:
TOMCLANCY-MEDIA. The photo is of Robert Gottlieb, editor of New
Yorker Magazine, and is not the Robert Gottlieb mentioned in the
story. Please delete this photo from your files and archives.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 2000 -- TOMCLANCY-MEDIA -- On August
3, Robert Gottlieb, one of the most powerful agents in the book
business and the head of the William Morris agency's New York
literary group, received a letter from Tom Clancy, his old friend
and biggest client. His message: He was ending their 15 years of
business together. From now on, his book deals would be handled by
Michael Ovitz. Gottlieb during a tribute to the late writer Joseph
Heller in New York last June. (Carol Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. -- August 17, 2000 --
BEAR-PROBLEMS-COX-3 -- A growing number of bears have been pouring
down into the Western Colorado valleys because a late-spring frost
and summer drought have killed most of the bear's normal food
supplies. The Colorado Division of Wildlife has received several
reports of bear sightings and have advised residents to seal up
trash and other items whose smell attracts bears. The bears are
becoming bolder, wandering into busy neighborhoods. One particular
bear was caught and put in a cage. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- BATTLE-OF-BROOKLYN --
Trying to recreate the Battle of Brooklyn, the bloodiest but one of
the least-known episodes of the American Revolution, with a
star-unstudded cast of one, plus a handful of nonspeaking bit
players. Directed by Joe McCarthy, a 15-year resident of Cobble
Hill and lifelong American history buff, ``The Battle of Brooklyn''
was recreated on a very low budget and help from a lot of friends.
Actor Graeme Malcolm on location as an American general.(Nancy
Siesel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) SUNNYVALE, Calif. -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- TOOTH-TECH-2 --
The business of straightening teeth has always been a small-scale,
fairly low-tech affair -- a one-on-one interaction between
orthodontist and patient, usually an adolescent. Until now. Unlike
braces advertised as invisible but held in place by a wire, Align
Technology's product is transparent. Instead of visiting the
orthodontist to have braces adjusted, patients would simply switch
to the next retainer in the series every two weeks. (Thor Swift/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SUNNYVALE, Calif. -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- TOOTH-TECH-1 --
Kelsey Wirth, left, and Zia Chishti, right, the co-founders of
Align Technology based in Sunnyvale, Calif., had no experience in
dentistry when they designed a new treatment option, which uses a
series of plastic braces aimed at appearance-conscious adults.
Unlike braces advertised as invisible but held in place by a wire,
Align's product is transparent. Instead of visiting the
orthodontist to have braces adjusted, patients would simply switch
to the next retainer in the series every two weeks. (Thor Swift/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WOODSTOCK, Vt. -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- JEWS-RURRAL -- Stuart
M. Matlins, along with his wife, Antoinette, founded the synagogue
in Woodstock, Vt. It is one of many rural locations places across
the country where Jewish communities have been established in
recent years. (Paul O. Boisvert/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BOSTON -- Aug 17, 2000 -- OLY-USGYMRAY-BOS -- The name
to know among the new kids in women's gymnastics is Elise Ray, an
18-year-old from Columbia, Md., who last month won the title in St.
Louis, stealing the crown with a vault that she never tested in
competition. The final goal, of course, is Sydney. Ray has a full
scholarship awaiting at the University of Michigan, where she'll go
in hopes of being a veterinarian. For now, she closes her eyes and
thinks of what it would be like to stand in Sydney with a medal
draped around her neck and the necks of her Yankee sisters.
(Jonathan Wiggs/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BOSTON -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- OLY-USGYM-WILSON-BOS -- U.S.
gymnast Blaine Wilson, 26, has more than earned a spot on this
year's olympic team based solely on his resume, with a record five
straight national titles and a fourth-place finish at last year's
World Championships. Still, Wilson is no charity case and does not
believe in petitions. ``If by some chance I screw up and don't make
this team, I'm not going,'' he says. ``If you didn't earn a spot on
this team, you shouldn't be there.'' Wilson warming up for the
Olympic Gymnastics Trials at the FleetCenter in Boston, Thursday.
(Jonathan Wiggs/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MABLETON, Ga. -- August 17, 2000 -- BRAIN-COX-2 --
``Brain-based learning'' is the latest controversial idea being
implemented in schools across the country. The idea is based on the
premise that scents, sugar, sounds, colors, lighting, water and
other inputs produce various responses in young brains, and can be
orchestrated to make them more receptive to learning. At Avondale
Elementary in DeKalb, Ga., 6-year-olds Karymar Villanueva, left,
Edrick Aall, center, and Matthew Kennedy, try to coordinate their
hands, arms and legs in their brain-based first grade class. (Jean
Shifrin/The Atlanta Journal Constitution) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MABLETON, Ga. -- August 17, 2000 -- BRAIN-COX-1--
``Brain-based learning'' is the latest controversial idea being
implemented in schools across the country. The idea is based on the
premise that scents, sugar, sounds, colors, lighting, water and
other inputs produce various responses in young brains, and can be
orchestrated to make them more receptive to learning. Kyunghae
Shin, a teacher at Avondale Elementary in DeKalb, Ga. leads her
third grade class in a brain-based learning exercise that involves
students following the teacher's lead in hand and body
coordination. (Jean Shifrin/The Atlanta Journal Constitution) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PHILADELPHIA, Aug. 17, 2000 -- FASH-LADYLIKE-HNS --
Laura Bush, wife of presidential candidate Gov. George W. Bush,
wore a modified peplum suit by designer Michael Faircloth when she
joined her husband following his address to the Republican National
Convention. Several elements are going into achieving this fall's
new ladylike look, and in the clothing department the return of the
suit is key. (Andrew Innerarity/The Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) GROVELAND, Mass -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS --
Chris Mattrick, of the New England Wild Flower Society always wears
hospital gloves inside elbow-length pesticide gloves, eye
protection, and a dust mask when spraying. He also wears long pants
and shirts with long sleeves, which are washed separately from
family laundry. He also carries an eye wash. Mattrick removes an
invasive Glossy Buckthorn he just dug up. (Frank O'Brien/The Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. -- August 17, 2000 --
BEAR-PROBLEMS-COX-2 -- A growing number of bears have been pouring
down into the Western Colorado valleys because a late-spring frost
and summer drought have killed most of the bear's normal food
supplies. The Colorado Division of Wildlife has received several
reports of bear sightings and have advised residents to seal up
trash and other items whose smell attracts bears. These bears are
hoping for a better view. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MESA COUNTY, Colo. -- August 17, 2000 --
BEAR-PROBLEMS-COX-1 -- A growing number of bears have been pouring
down into the Western Colorado valleys because a late-spring frost
and summer drought have killed most of the bear's normal food
supplies. The Colorado Division of Wildlife has received several
reports of bear sightings and have advised residents to seal up
trash and other items whose smell attracts bears. Hungry black
bears coming out of the hills into the orchards in Mesa County,
Colo. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- HOME-ROADSHOW-BOS --
``Antiques Roadshow'' is produced by WGBH-TV and underwritten by
the Chubb Group, insurers of collectibles and fine arts. It is
PBS's highest-ranked prime-time show, with 14 million viewers each
week. Daniel Elias, the new host of PBS TV'S Antiques Roadshow,
siting at an early 19th century America library table with 1950's
Cuban chairs. The artwork on the wall is 'Acquario (NU)1' by
Valerio Bevilacqua. (Frank O'Brien/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- SHEER-FUN -- Ella
Cattabiani, 10, walks through panels of sheer, lightweight fabric
as she plays amidst an art installation called ``Invisible City,''
by Raquel Rabinovich on display on the plaza at Lincoln Center,
Thursday. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WELLFLEET, Mass. -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- LEAPFROG-PRESS-BOS
-- From the start, Marge Piercy, and her husband and fellow author,
Ira Wood's aim at Leapfrog Press was simple: to create an outlet
for writers whose books have all but died amid the
multi-million-dollar deals of New York's major publishing houses in
the last 15 years. Piercy and Wood working together in the offices
of Leapfrog Press in Wellfleet, Mass. Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- CLINTON-GRAND-JURY --
Independent Counsel Robert Ray has empaneled a new grand jury to
hear evidence against President Clinton in the Monica Lewinsky
scandal, accroding to news reports. Ray in a March file photo.
(Justin Lane/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- BOSTONSCI-TOBIN-BOS -- In the
14 months since Jim Tobin became chief executive of Boston
Scientific, succeeding founder chairman Peter Nicholas, he
dismissed 1,900 people, closed manufacturing operations in three
states, and watched profits decline while the stock lost two-thirds
of its value. Tobin says ``restructuring will generate savings of
$250 million annually by 2003 and boost research and development
spending.'' (Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HARTFORD, Ct. -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- INVEST-DIBELLA-AETNA --
The fund manager Thomaas J. DiBella runs the $239.5 million Aetna
Small Company fund, says his experience as an accountant has helped
him in analyzing companies' finances. (George Ruhe/The New York
Times) Story moved 08-11-00
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SURDA, West Bank -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- -- Hisham Abdullah,
left, is consoled by a relative, Thursday. Abdullah's father,
Mahmud Abdullah, was shot Wednesday by Israeli forces while
searching the village for a man suspected of terrorism. Israeli
forces said they opened fire when Abdullah allegedly opened fire.
Relatives claim the man believed the Israeli forces were burglars.
(Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- EUROPEAN-DRESS-2 -- ``Curios
and Treasures,'' a modest, yet serenely beautiful exhibition at the
Costume Institute at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, displays 65
garments and accessories that range through four or five centuries
of European dress. From top: Doublet, 1620-25, French (Luchesse
silk); Purse, English, 1580-1600. Linen embroidered with polychrome
silk floss, metallic thread, and metallic purl, lined with pink
silk; Poulaine, English, 146h-15th century. Brown leather.
(Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- EUROPEAN-DRESS -- ``Curios
and Treasures,'' a modest, yet serenely beautiful exhibition at the
Costume Institute at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, displays 65
garments and accessories that range through four or five centuries
of European dress. From left: Caraco, 2nd half of the 18th Century,
Dutch; Evening Coat, circa 1920's, by Mariano Fortuny; Evening
Dress, circa 1925, by Madame Babani. (Metropolitan Museum of
Art/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 17, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 20 --
JANSSEN-FILM -- Famke Janssen is having a thrill ride of a summer.
As Jean Grey, the telepathic, telekinetic protege of Professor X,
Janssen was part of the team that not only arrested the vengeful
Magneto's quest for world domination in ``X-Men'' but has also
raked in a superheroic $144 million at the box office in five weeks
of release. Now, opening on August 25, comes Valerie Breiman's
romantic comedy ``Love and Sex,'' a crowd pleaser at the last
winter's Sundance Festival. Janssen in theoffices of Lion's Gate,
an independent movie company. (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
