<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5118 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-TIPPER-GORE-2DLD-     08-17 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-TIPPER-GORE-2DLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TIPPER GORE INTRODUCES HER HUSBAND AND SHOWS THE FAMILY PHOTOS.
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDs: UPDATES lede and inserts 5th graf to describe Mrs. Gore's
dancing on the stage, edits in first 4 grafs.)
</P>
<P>
   By JUDY HOLLAND and SUSANNA McBEE
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tipper Gore, a dedicated advocate for her husband
of 30 years, introduced Al Gore as the Democratic presidential
nominee at the party's national convention Thursday night after
dancing her way to the podium and saying that he ``has always been
there for our family and he will always be there for yours.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that, ``many of you know that faith and family are at
the center of Al's life,'' thus underscoring a key campaign theme
that both Democrats and Republicans are pushing this year. ``Many
of you know Al to be a decisive leader with strong values, deeply
held convictions, and an unwavering commitment to making the
American dream a reality for all people.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Mrs. Gore, who was a photographer for five years in the
1970s at the Nashville Tennessean when her husband was an
investigative reporter there, sought to give the nation a more
intimate look of their life together by showing family photographs
to convention delegates and the TV audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, some of you are saying, please, not the family photo
album,'' she said. ``But for those of you running for the door,
stay for just a while and see the man I love in a way you may not
have seen him before.''
</P>
<P>
   Known as an unconventional, humorous woman, she danced around
the stage to rock music before her speech, doing high-fives with
with several people nearby and bringing the delegates to their
feet. She let out a big whoop when the entire audience held up
round signs saying ``Tipper Rocks.'' The delegates laughed, roared
their approval and danced themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore, who celebrates her 52d birthday Saturday, has been at
her husband's side since they dated in high school and has given
speeches and campaigned for him throughout his career. An aide said
Thursday that she will continue to stump for him this fall,
traveling separately to reach as wide an audience as she can.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic image makers say her relaxed and confident demeanor
is a big asset on the hustings. They also say her dedication to her
family and her wholesome All-American looks give her a personal
appeal that can win votes and soften the stiffer image her husband
has projected.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Strauss, a former Democratic Party chairman and an
adviser to presidents of both parties, said earlier this week that
if Gore wants to boost his standing with certain blocs of voters _
southerners generally and women in particular _ he should send his
wife on a campaign train through the South.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss recalled that Lady Bird Johnson, wife of President
Lyndon Johnson, made such a trip in the fall of 1964, stopping in
47 places in four days. Her ``Lady Bird Special'' whistle-stop tour
was credited with helping her husband retain much of the South in
his election battle against Barry Goldwater that year.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that Mrs. Gore is ``a very appealing campaigner,' Strauss
added that she also could help Democrats running for Congress in
certain areas of the South.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore has said if she becomes first lady, she will continue
her efforts to improve mental health care.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton administration she has sought to remove the
stigma from mental illness. Last year she publicly discussed her
own battle with depression, which she said was triggered when her
son Albert, then six, nearly died after being struck by a car 11
years ago. She also served as President Clinton's top adviser on
mental health and presided over a White House conference on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago Mrs. Gore became an object of scorn among some
elements of the music industry and some civil libertarians when she
crusaded against obscene, sexually explicit rock and rap lyrics. In
pursuing that effort, she joined with Susan Baker, wife of
President Ronald Reagan's chief of staff, James Baker, in founding
the Parents' Music Resource Center.
</P>
<P>
   Their effort led to five months of Senate hearings, and the
entertainment industry, to stave off federal legislation, agreed to
police itself and put labels on tapes and albums warning of graphic
material.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore also was attacked as a prissy censor on a moral
mission when she wrote a book, ``Raising PG Kids in an X-Rated
Society'' in 1997.'
</P>
<P>
   The reaction from Hollywood and many civil libertarians came as
a shock to Tipper Gore, a longtime follower of the Grateful Dead
and a drummer in her high school rock band. She was dismayed to
find that she had become, in the minds of some, the worst enemy of
the pop music industry. She acknowledged in her1996 book, ``Picture
This: A Visual Diary,'' that her campaign ''landed me in hot
water.``
</P>
<P>
   But so far Hollywood has been a rich source of campaign
contributions for Democrats. The entertainment industry has given $
5.9 million to Democrats since January 1999, according to the
Center for Responsive Politics, not including events at the Los
Angeles convention, making it the fourth largest donor to the
Democratic Party. Hollywood has doled out$3.7 million to
Republicans during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore has also been an advocate for women's issues and for
helping poor people, particularly the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of her husband before her speech Thursday night, she
told CNN that ``even though he's had a very busy public life and
career... whenever any of us have needed him, he's been there for
us,'' That, she said, shows he will ``be there for the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she hoped to be a mother of a politician as well
as the wife of one, she said she wants her children to find out who
they are, what their gifts are ``and to go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Convention has been a family affair for the
Gores.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores' eldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, 27, is a close
adviser to her father. She seconded his nomination Wednesday night,
praising him for balancing his family life with his career and for
once helping her with a dinosaur diorama after a day of hearings on
Capitol Hill. The Gores' other children are Kristin, 23; Sarah, 21,
and Albert III, who is now 17. The Gores also have a one-year-old
grandson, Wyatt Gore Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore, born Mary Elizabeth Aitcheson, was called Tipper by
her mother, an accountant who suffered from depression. Her parents
had a difficult marriage and were divorced when she was four. She
has a bachelor's degree and a master's degree in psychology and has
considered the idea of becoming a family therapist _ even if she
becomes first lady.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
