<HEADER>
A5121 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-DEMS-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      08-17 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PEOPLE'S AL GORE   STEPS TO THE PODIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For eight years the vice president has had a
prominent place on the national stage, for four days the Democrats
have spoken of the Al Gore hardly anyone knows, and for one hour
Thursday night he appeared before the American people, shorn of
advisers, free of props, apart from the president who has
overshadowed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand here tonight as my own man,'' he said, ``and I want
you to know me for whom I truly am.''
</P>
<P>
   The Al Gore whom Al Gore wanted the nation to see is a populist,
with an antagonism to entrenched interests; a fighter, with a taste
for the battle; and a reformer, with an impatience for the way
things are.
</P>
<P>
   All that plus a thinker, with no fear of specifics. Gore set out
to add depth and perspective to the sketch Americans have of him,
and his strategy clearly was to show that he is a man of depth and
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   And though the campaign has struggled to reconcile two notions _
that Gore wanted to continue the Clinton-era prosperity even as he
wanted to separate himself from Clinton-era scandals _ the
Democrats' new presidential nominee made clear that he would be no
mere steward of what preceded him.
</P>
<P>
   He envisions a style of leadership that would sow the notion of
personal responsibility, not simply speak of it; a society that
would make parents' jobs easier, not harder; an economic culture
that gives the striving and middle classes, and not just the
educated and the elite, a larger chunk of the product of the
American prosperity engine.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that is the New Democratic agenda that Clinton never
accomplished, or that Clinton's own comportment made it impossible
to achieve. Moreover, Gore's view of the presidency is rooted more
in his own experience as a congressman and senator and as a
presidential candidate than in what he witnessed as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   His presidency would be, in a word freighted with meaning in the
information age, interactive.
</P>
<P>
   As a lawmaker, Gore held a continual series of town meetings
each weekend, listening to ordinary people, staying in touch. As a
presidential candidate he vowed to answer every last question,
sometimes remaining at an event site even as the maintenance crew
was completing its last rounds of a near-empty hall. And as
president, he vowed Thursday night, he'd keep the lines open,
meeting with people continually ``because I want to stay in touch
with your hopes; with the quiet, every-day heroism of hard-working
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks were full of graceful turns of phrase and gentle
asides, and when the vice president spoke of ``the daring grace of
the human spirit,'' he invoked as well the spirit of John F.
Kennedy's 1960 acceptance speech, when the Massachusetts senator
first set forth the idea of the New Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Few shimmering phrases emerged from Gore's remarks, but the
speech included much of the tone _ especially the sense of
challenge _ of the Kennedy speech. ``In our democracy, the future
is not something that just happens to us; it is something we make
for ourselves _ together,'' he said. ``So to the young people
watching tonight, I say: this is your time to make new the life of
our world. We need your help to rekindle the spirit of America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-MAIN18-COX     08-17 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MAIN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE VOWS TO FIGHT FOR 'EVERYDAY HEROES'
 &HT;    Eds: Will be updated.
 &HT;    700&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore promised to support the
``quiet, everyday heroism of hard-working Americans'' as he
accepted the Democratic Party's presidential nomination Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that focused on the possibilities of the future
rather than the accomplishments of the Clinton administration, Gore
declared himself ``my own man'' as he re-introduced himself to the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than try to match the charm of his Republican rival,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the notoriously formal Gore used his
acceptance speech to draw distinctions on issues he believes will
help him overcome Bush's steady lead in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to use the federal government's record budget
surplus to expand health care coverage, improve education, shore up
safety net programs and extend tax cuts to help ``every
hard-working family'' to ``open the door to their dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   He also recalled how he had fought ``against the powerful
interests'' over the course of his career, pushing for welfare
reform and an improved environment.
</P>
<P>
   And despite his own abuses of the campaign finance system, Gore
vowed that a reform bill will be the first one he sends to Congress
as president. ``Let others try to restore the old guard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also took direct aim at a sweeping tax cut proposal at the
heart of Bush's campaign. ``Let me say it plainly: I will not go
along with a huge tax cut for the wealthy at the expense of
everyone else and wreck our good economy in the process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gore's emphasis on issues in a speech he largely crafted
himself, the convention's final day was mostly devoted to showing
the American public parts of the 52-year-old Gore's life that have
been obscured by his eight years as President Clinton's vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime friends of Gore played roles in an evening talk-show
style segment that featured anecdotes about Gore's relationship
with his father, a fiddle-playing populist senator from the hill
country of Tennessee; his decision to join the Army during the
Vietnam War; and his career in journalism before entering politics.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore, an accomplished photographer, used photographs from
their three decades of marriage and his 24 years in politics to
present her husband as a family man. ``Al has always been there for
our family and he will always be there for yours,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore family photo album was shared not only with the more
than 4,368 delegates in the Staples Center, the site of the
convention, but also with the prime-time national television
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's biography has a central part of nearly every night of the
convention since Clinton's curtain call and departure Monday night,
a reflection of the concern among Gore advisers that voters
continue to view the vice president through the lens of Clinton's
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns were not diminished by the disclosure earlier
Thursday that a new grand jury has been empaneled to continue the
investigation of Clinton in connection with his extramarital affair
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Not only Democrats, but also Republicans expressed dismay over
the disclosure just hours before Gore was to accept his party's
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not appropriate for this type of announcement to be made
on the day that the vice president is going to accept the
Democratic nomination,'' said senior Bush strategist Karen Hughes.
``This election is not about the past; it's about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his acceptance speech, paid a brief single tribute to
Clinton. ``Millions of Americans will live better lives for a long
time to come because of the job that's been done to President
Clinton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we turn the page and write a new chapter,'' he said.
``We're entering a new time. We're electing a new president. And I
stand here tonight as my own man, and I want you to know who I
truly am.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I have strong values, the love of my family, my
faith, my love for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention delegates erupted with cheers as Gore entered the
convention hall after Tipper's introduction. He walked down an
aisle past the Tennessee delegation on his way to the speaker's
podium.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Promising to champion ordinary folks and their children, Gore
said, ``Tonight, I ask for your support on the basis of the better,
fairer, more prosperous America we can build together.''
</P>
<P>
   He reminded the audience of the administration's economic
accomplishments: 22 million new jobs, the lowest inflation in a
generation, the highest home ownership ever, the lowest
unemployment in a quarter century and the biggest budget surpluses
ever.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``for all of our good times, I am not satisfied,'' he
added. ``Together, let's make sure that our prosperity enriches not
just the few, but all working families.''
</P>
<P>
   As president, Gore said he would continue the open meetings that
were a part of his presidential campaign and his 16 years in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go out to you, the people, because I want to stay
in touch with your hopes, with the quiet, every-day heroism of
hard-working Americans,'' he said. ``So this is not just an
election between my opponent and me. It's about our people, our
families, and our future _ and whether forces standing in your way
will keep you from having a better life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not dwell exclusively on economic issues, however. He
also vowed to use the presidency to ``challenge a culture'' that
has ``too much meanness, and not enough meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut,
planned to leave Los Angeles shortly after the climactic event of
the convention to begin a four-day trip down the Mississippi River,
through Midwestern battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
