<SLUG> BC-EXP-CHENEY-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN CHENEY'S RETIREMENT PACKAGE, SOME UNCHARTED
TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The retirement package awarded by the Halliburton Co. to Dick
Cheney, the Republican nominee for vice president, is nowhere near
the largest ever given to a chief executive, but it is trailblazing
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Cheney's estimated $20 million package consists of a
stock option grant. And although options are an increasingly
popular form of executive compensation, they would be in totally
uncharted territory in the hands of a vice president, whose role in
the White House has the potential to affect the company's fortunes
and so place him in a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   When Cheney resigned from Halliburton on Wednesday, he received
an unspecified bonus, was free to sell 140,000 formerly restricted
shares of company stock and was allowed to keep options on 1.16
million shares. The current value of Cheney's stock and options,
which give him the right to buy Halliburton shares at a specified
price, is approximately $39 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has said that if the Republican ticket wins the election,
he will sell his Halliburton shares before he takes office,
removing one potential conflict of interest that he would have in
the future of Halliburton, the oil services giant.
</P>
<P>
   But the way Halliburton has structured part of Cheney's option
grant would keep him squarely in a conflict: 233,000 of his options
_ worth around $3.8 million, if they could be exercised today _ can
be turned into shares of Halliburton only in December 2001 and
December 2002. Because he cannot sell or transfer the options
before then, he would continue to have a stake in the company while
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what he would need to do to avoid a conflict is not cut
and dried. Neither the president nor the vice president is subject
to the criminal conflict-of-interest laws that govern all other
employees in the executive branch. The assumption is that voters
can judge for themselves whether these elected officials are living
up to the nation's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts said Cheney's best approach would be to divest
himself of every Halliburton share and option. ``The cleanest route
would be to eliminate self-interest altogether and forfeit and
cancel the options,'' said Patrick McGurn, vice president of
Institutional Shareholder Services, an investment advisory firm in
Rockville, Md. ``But is anybody going to do that? Given the paper
value, that's putting a pretty hefty price tag on altruism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
