<DOCNO> NYT20000817.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-LABOR-NYT &LR;      08-17 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS TRY TO SHORE UP THE CRUMBLING LABOR PILLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Organized labor has always been one of the
strongest pillars supporting the Democratic Party. Or, as John J.
Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, enthused on Sunday while
addressing a cheering throng of union members here for the
Democratic National Convention:
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at you _ 1,500 strong, 30 percent of the delegates to
this convention and 100 percent of the soul of the Democratic
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   But cracks are showing in the labor pillar as this convention
draws to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the union officials and union members who showed up here
are still deeply upset about the trade deal the Clinton
administration negotiated with China. They remain convinced that
the agreement, which organized labor bitterly fought, threatens
American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Other union officials and members here say their party has
become too centrist on social matters and less firmly committed to
goals like maintaining affirmative-action programs and opposing
school voucher plans.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders are concerned about such talk, especially because
members of a group that makes up another pillar, black Democrats,
have also expressed concern here about the party's ideological
direction. The party bigwigs have spent much of the week scurrying
from delegation to delegation trying to reassure disgruntled union
members, lest union support flag for the Gore-Lieberman ticket,
with grievous consequences on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut met
for the second time with Bob Chase, president of the National
Education Association, to reassure members of the powerful teachers
union that while he had supported experimental voucher programs in
the past, he would now go along with Vice President Al Gore in
opposing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good, productive meeting,'' Chase said in a statement
issued by his office.
</P>
<P>
   This is the calculus the party leaders cannot escape: In the
last presidential election, when Bill Clinton won a second term, 23
percent of all voters came from union households, and they voted
Democratic 63 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Will they do it again?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, say delegates from one of the country's most heavily
unionized states, Michigan, where one of every two households has a
union member. But sometimes their doubt is unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm with Al Gore and Joe Lieberman all the way, every step,''
said Clarice Squillace, a retired autoworker from Eastpointe,
Mich.. ``I'm not happy with the China trade thing but I'm resigned
to it because it's a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we get our people to turn out on Election Day? I don't
know. I'll do everything I can to build the excitement. We've got
to convince people there really are big differences between the two
tickets. That's the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Flynn, a National Education Association member from
Sterling Heights, Mich., struck a similar note as he discussed how
to turn out a big vote for the Gore-Lieberman ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about this,'' Flynn said. ``It's the issues that
will do the job, the differences between the two tickets. If you
can make them clear, I believe we can drum up the kind of
excitement we've seen here on the floor of the convention. I just
wish I could bottle this excitement and take it back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he concerned that the Democratic Party was becoming too
centrist, edging too close to things like school vouchers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you think on a particular issue or issues, the center
is where you win,'' he said. ``I'm comfortable with Al Gore and Joe
Lieberman. Why not? Ted Kennedy and Jesse Jackson got up there on
the podium the other night and praised them to the skies. If it's
OK with a pair like Ted and Jesse, it's sure as heck OK with me.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lana Boldi, a United Auto Workers official from Grand
Rapids, Mich., the China trade deal was a stinging blow. ``But as
much as I disagree with that,'' she said, ``I disagree with George
W. Bush even more on just about everything he stands for. You weigh
it all out, and you go with Al Gore easily, whatever serious
differences you may have with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't any other real choice. You can't throw in with
somebody like Ralph Nader just because he says the right things on
something like China trade. That's just throwing a vote away.''
Nader is running on the Green Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Until just before the convention opened here, the UAW's
enthusiasm for Gore was considerably less than overwhelming. The
union held back on endorsing him _ its president, Stephen P.
Yokich, is a Michigan delegate _ until just about the last moment.
And in an auto state like Michigan, which also happens to be one of
the important Midwestern swing states in Election 2000, that hurt _
and still hurts. The latest Michigan poll has Gore trailing Bush by
eight points.
</P>
<P>
   Gore won the endorsement of the AFL-CIO leadership earlier on,
though again, there was much concern about his support for the
China trade agreement. Another powerful union, the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters, has still not committed to a candidate.
Its president, James B. Hoffa, is being heavily courted by both the
Gore and Bush camps, as well as by Nader, who is drawing 5 percent
to 10 percent of the vote in some big labor states, mainly at
Gore's expense.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa was welcomed as an onlooker at the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia. And here in Los Angeles, he is listed
as a ``superdelegate'' in the Michigan delegation. But he says the
Teamsters will not make a decision on whom to back until after
Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House minority leader, said here at
midweek that organized labor's vote would be crucial not only in
the presidential race but also in many congressional races and,
ultimately, the control of the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that in 1994, when the Democrats lost 52 seats in the
House and, with that, control of the House, turnout by union
members was only 13 percent. But turnout was 23 percent, he said,
in 1996, when the party regained nine seats, and in 1998, when it
regained five more seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or base has not come home yet,'' Gephardt said. ``We will have
to work on that. The Republican base has accepted George Bush much
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   His view of the base?
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talk about the base,'' he said, ``we are talking about
yellow-dog Democrats _ like union members _ who are mostly white
males, and who we have not done particularly well with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
