<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5129 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-SPEECH-ANALYSIS-H     08-17 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-SPEECH-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SPEECH STRONG ON PROPOSALS, LACKING IN SOARING RHETORIC,
MEMORABLE QUOTES &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  Editors: This story is an analysis of the Gore speech 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Al Gore camp is fond of tossing around the
Texas saying ``all hat and no cattle'' to describe Republican rival
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   As the Democratic contender finally got his chance to address a
national audience Thursday night he clearly sought to show there
was more beef in his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to focus groups of undecided voters who say they are
tired of vague political speeches, Gore said he was there to talk
seriously about his proposals on Social Security, Medicare, middle
class tax cuts, and prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   And he offered some specifics such as his commitment to ``an
iron clad lockbox '' to protect federal retirement program
surpluses from being raided for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   He effectively pointed to real people he has met along the
campaign trail to illustrate his commitment to such measures as HMO
reform and school building program.
</P>
<P>
   But the challenge facing Gore was far greater than just
demonstrating that he has dutifully done his homework.
</P>
<P>
   The cautious politician who carefully modulates his every
response had to show sizzle and somehow connect with voters who
find him remote and patronizing.
</P>
<P>
   While the delegates lustily cheered his address it was unclear
whether he would be able to puncture his old image with the voters
outside the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The speech, written by Gore on his laptop computer, seemed
lacking in soaring rhetoric or memorable quotes. And unlike his
boss President Clinton, Gore is not adept at breathing life into
mundane lines.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidate also seemed more relaxed and natural than he
often does on the campaign trail, punching out some sharp lines.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not in Clinton's league when it comes to rousing
speechmaking. But the Texas governor entered his Philadelphia
convention in far better shape than Gore, with the Republican base
electrified and independent voters more comfortable with his
amiable demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   The address also provided an opportunity for Gore to more firmly
cut the umbilical cord to Clinton _ to demonstrate to voters that
after playing understudy for almost eight years he could take over
the leading role.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're entering a new time,'' he said. ``We're electing a new
president. And I stand here tonight as my own man, and I want you
to know me for who I truly am.''
</P>
<P>
   But even on a day when the spotlight was supposed to shine
solely on him, Gore could not escape from Clinton's shadow as the
news was leaked that a grand jury had been convened a month ago to
probe the Monica Lewinsky matter that has dogged Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to President Clinton's philandering, Gore made a
point of noting that he was still in love with the woman he met the
night of his senior prom.
</P>
<P>
   He also fleshed out his life story in an effort to demonstrate
that he had a compelling autobiography and had made tough choices
such as his decision to enroll in Vietnam _ another departure from
Clinton who avoided the draft.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore didn't want to completely distance himself from the
Clinton years, which has generated the economic prosperity the
Democratic candidate hopes will propel him to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   So far polls show that Americans do not seem to be giving Gore
credit for the good times. Gore used his address to hammer home the
point that the current period of prosperity can only continue if
Democrats stay put at 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore flung back at Republicans a word they freely used against
the current administration at their convention. In Philadelphia,
Bush accused Clinton and Gore of squandering their two terms in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Gore seized on the same language when he warned of the dangers
of making the wrong choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could squander this moment, but our country would be the
poorer for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the convention the Gore camp has been intent on
portraying the candidate as someone who is not just a stiff policy
wonk but a warm and funny family man with roots outside of
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   They continued that theme on the final night when his wife
Tipper introduced him by opening up her family photo album to show
folksy an irreverent photos she had taken of her husband over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   The coming weeks will tell whether voters replace their mental
snapshots of the Democratic candidates with the warmer images
presented in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
