<HEADLINE>
BEANO COOK CALLS DECISION `IDIOTIC'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC might be excited about the opportunity to
play Penn State in the Kickoff Classic, but its decision to open
the season against the Nittany Lions is ``idiotic,'' according to
ESPN college football analyst Beano Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a dumb move on USC's part. It's ridiculous.
They're nuts,'' Cook said by phone from his home in Pittsburgh.
``It's a home game for Penn State. I don't understand it. USC plays
a tough enough nonconference schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give USC some credit for playing the game. It's not the
dumbest move since Hitler went to war on two fronts, but it's
close. I said the same thing about Arizona last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn State routed Arizona 41-7 last year in the season opener
for both teams, although that game was played in State College,
Pa., and not the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Cook predicts the Nittany Lions will defeat the Trojans 28-14
but added, ``tell (USC coach) Paul Hackett I hope I'm wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Trojans, they remain unfazed by Cook's words.
</P>
<P>
   ``USC has not been getting the respect it deserves and this
year, that's what it is all about,'' linebacker Zeke Moreno said.
``That's just another challenge. We're not out to prove it to him,
we're out to prove it to ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Waiting for decision: Although David Newbury has basically
won the kicking job, Hackett said he will wait until Monday to
officially make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Bell has been disappointing, but he needs to get his act
together and I want to give him a little longer to bounce back,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell will probably handle kickoffs again. Freshman John Wall of
Birmingham High is expected to redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   __ Defensive breakdown? The defense's weakness against the run
in Wednesday's scrimmage was a prime topic addressed during
Thursday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked awful on defense,'' defensive coordinator Bill Young
said. ``That's the first time we looked that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said players were often not in their proper positions on
the field, which accounted for so many big running plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a tremendous concern,'' he said. ``It can be
corrected just like that. We also had some defenses that we hadn't
run a lot as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said the defense settled down in the second half, when the
Trojans went back to their base defense.
</P>
<P>
   __ Kelly improving: Wide receiver Kareem Kelly, who had two
catches for 76 yards and a touchdown in the scrimmage, said his
strained knee feels about ``95 percent'' recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Malaefou MacKenzie, who cut his hand Wednesday and
required stitches, practiced Thursday, but did not do anything that
required the use of his injured hand. He is expected to return
full-time perhaps as soon as today.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Petros Papadakis (sore foot) is expected to return
today after missing two days.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he expects tight end Antoine Harris (sore
hamstring) to start the Penn State game but isn't sure how long he
will last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
