<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge Halts Program to Crack DVD Film Codes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled Thursday that a Web site operator cannot
distribute a computer program used to crack codes that prevent the
piracy of movies. The ruling, a victory for the motion picture
industry, applies only to the Web site operator, Eric C. Corley,
and his company, 2600 Enterprises. But experts on both sides of the
issue agreed that the decision could have far greater reach as the
courts hammer out legal guidelines that will govern the rules of
commerce and free speech in the digital world.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon's Unions Agree to Draw Up Unified Plan
</P>
<P>
   With a midnight deadline looming in which representatives for
nearly two-thirds of 86,000 striking workers planned to end formal
talks with Verizon Communications, negotiators sought to resolve
issues including job security and mandatory overtime. The unions'
three main bargaining units, which were divided on Wednesday,
agreed to draw up a unified proposal Thursday night, a person close
to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   UAL Lowers Earnings Estimates
</P>
<P>
   UAL, parent of United Airlines, lowered its third-quarter
earnings estimates, citing the thousands of canceled flights that
have come amid a dispute with its pilots. The airline also
announced several initiatives to placate its disgruntled
passengers, including frequent-flier bonuses and elimination of
certain service fees.
</P>
<P>
   For Firestone, a Jubilee That Wasn't
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be a jubilee year for Firestone. One
hundred years ago, on Aug. 3, 1900, to be exact, Harvey Firestone
established Firestone Tire &AMP; Rubber Co., and the company was
planning to celebrate that fact, in a big way. Then it all came
crashing down. Firestone tires have been implicated in 62 deaths
and countless injuries. Now Firestone's ad campaign is revolving
around notices in 41 newspapers, detailing the mechanics of a huge
tire recall.
</P>
<P>
   Stock Options Take Center Stage
</P>
<P>
   The retirement package awarded to Dick Cheney, the Republican
nominee for vice president, is neither the largest nor the most
generous ever given a chief executive officer. But the estimated
$20 million package from Halliburton is remarkable in other ways.
It has brought executive compensation back from the dead as a
campaign issue and has elevated stock option wealth _ and the
potential conflicts it may pose to politicians who have amassed it
_ to center stage. '
</P>
<P>
   Chip Makers Lead Shares Higher
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose, led by semiconductor makers, as investors bet that
technology shares would weather a slowing economy. The Nasdaq
composite index ended up 79.67 points, or 2.06 percent, to
3,940.87, while the Dow Jones industrial average gained 47.25
points, or 0.43 percent, to 11,055.64. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index gained 16.22 points, or 1.10 percent, to 1,496.07.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart Database Plan Set Aside
</P>
<P>
   A federal bankruptcy judge set aside a Federal Trade Commission
plan limiting the ability of the retailer Toysmart.com to sell its
customer database as part of its liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless Auction Nets $50 Billion
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive auction in history ended today, when six
companies bid nearly $50 billion for licenses to offer a new
generation of wireless communications in Germany, the largest
economy in Europe. ``For consumers, the result promises the most
intense competition,'' said Klaus-Dieter Scheurle, head of
Germany's telecommunications regulatory agency and the auction's
architect. ``This was the most favorable solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Molecule Used in Electronic Circuit
</P>
<P>
   Chemists at the University of California at Los Angeles are
reporting a further advance in the effort to produce electronic
circuitry on a molecular scale.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico Rejects Sugar Trade Plan
</P>
<P>
   A protracted dispute over sugar trade between Mexico and the
United States escalated when the Mexicans rejected a U.S. proposal
and requested a special arbitration hearing under a provision of
the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
