<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE AL GORE BIOGRAPHY QUIZ
 &HT;    By FRANK CERABINO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Let's say, for argument's sake, that you actually
listened to all the speeches this week. I know. Nobody's that
crazy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, nobody here at the convention actually listened to the
speeches. The protesters outside the hall were too busy condemning
the convention to listen. The reporters were too busy analyzing to
actually listen. And the delegates are too busy checking out each
other's goofy hats and buying $3 McDonald's quarter-pounders on the
concourse level.
</P>
<P>
   The speeches on the convention floor went on for nearly seven
hours every day, a kind of rhetorical Muzak that most people here
tuned out by the first afternoon. There were always seats available
in the media section, even during the big speeches, and the network
anchors _ as if to punctuate their lack of enthusiasm for the
proceedings _ sat in glass enclosures with their backs facing the
convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   I'm concerned that America has missed some of the incredibly
important information that has come from the podium during this
week.
</P>
<P>
   So as a public service, I offer you the Al Gore Biography Quiz.
If you paid excruciating detail to the podium speakers this week,
here's what you could have learned about Al Gore, the man. I hope
this makes you a better-informed voter. (The correct answers are
listed on the bottom of the column.)
</P>
<P>
   1. The breakfast Al Gore made his young children was ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) eggs with bacon
</P>
<P>
   (b) toast with lots of butter
</P>
<P>
   (c) grits with sausage
</P>
<P>
   2. President Bill Clinton said Al Gore ``was born in a summer
storm to a young widow in a small Southern town.''
</P>
<P>
   (a) True.
</P>
<P>
   (b) False, Clinton said that about himself.
</P>
<P>
   (c) Isn't that a Bruce Springsteen lyric?
</P>
<P>
   3. When Al Gore should have been studying for exams in college,
he and roommate Tommy Lee Jones would sometimes ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) volunteer at a soup kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   (b) be stagehands at a local community theater.
</P>
<P>
   (c) shoot pool and watch Star Trek.
</P>
<P>
   4. Al Gore built his daughters a backyard ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) swing set
</P>
<P>
   (b) play house.
</P>
<P>
   (c) igloo.
</P>
<P>
   5. Al Gore once took former House Speaker Tip O'Neill to task
for scheduling a vote during ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) trick-or-treating time on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   (b) a Jewish holiday.
</P>
<P>
   (c) a Tennessee Volunteers football game.
</P>
<P>
   6. Al, the journalist, and Tipper, the photographer, worked on
stories together at a Tennessee newspaper, including the story
about ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) big environmental polluters.
</P>
<P>
   (b) corruption in county government.
</P>
<P>
   (c) an 86-year-old man who hunted groundhogs for food.
</P>
<P>
   7. When Joe Lieberman's young daughter first met Al Gore, she
said, ``He must be a ...''
</P>
<P>
   (a) daddy
</P>
<P>
   (b) nice man
</P>
<P>
   (c) mannequin
</P>
<P>
   8. Al Gore wanted to give his friend, Bob, a good send-off to
Vietnam, so he spent two hours ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) driving to an all-night diner to bring Bob his favorite
dessert.
</P>
<P>
   (b) writing Bob an inspirational poem
</P>
<P>
   (c) wandering a highway median until he found a four-leaf clover
to give to Bob.
</P>
<P>
   9. Al and Tipper's first home together was ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) a second-floor apartment in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   (b) a trailer home in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   (c) the family farm in Carthage, Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   10. When Al Gore climbed Mount Rainier last year, he kept
climbing even though ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) the temperature had dropped to 20 degrees, and the wind
picked up to 30 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   (b) he lost his cell phone in a snowbank..
</P>
<P>
   (c) he had to miss an appearance at a foreign funeral the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   11. Caroline Kennedy said she has a special kinship with Al Gore
because ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) his father gave her father that New Frontier idea.
</P>
<P>
   (b) his parents played matchmaker for her parents.
</P>
<P>
   (c) they both were born into wealthy political families.
</P>
<P>
   12. When returning to Tennessee during college breaks, Al Gore
...
</P>
<P>
   (a) chased loose women
</P>
<P>
   (b) chased loose cows
</P>
<P>
   (c) chased fly balls for the Carthage Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   13. Al Gore proposed getting married to Tipper ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) on a river bank
</P>
<P>
   (b) via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   (b) on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   14. Al Gore's only grandchild, Wyatt, was born on ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) Lincoln's Birthday.
</P>
<P>
   (b) The Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   (c) President's Day.
</P>
<P>
   15. A 10-year-old Al Gore didn't want to go on a campaign
appearance with his father, a U.S. Senator, because young Al wanted
to ...
</P>
<P>
   (a) Watch the Beverly Hillbillies on TV.
</P>
<P>
   (b) play chess
</P>
<P>
   (c) play on the farm
</P>
<P>
   Answers: 1(b), 2(b); 3(c); 4(c); 5(a); 6(c); 7(a); 8(c); 9(b);
10(a); 11(b); 12(b); 13(a); 14(b); 15(c).
</P>
