<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT &LR;      08-17 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO EXPRESSES OPTIMISM ON UPSTATE ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENDICOTT, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick Lazio, the Republican Senate
candidate, toured two high-tech businesses Thursday to underscore
what he said were bright spots in the upstate economy and to
counter what he said were Hillary Rodham Clinton's portrayals of
the region as an ``economic wasteland.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, on the second day of a bus tour across the state, watched
machinery spool cable wire at a plant in Cortland and then donned a
white protective coat and blue ducks as he inspected components for
motion sensors at a company in Ithaca.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he called the companies examples of an economic
rebound and models of the future in a region that he said had got a
negative reputation. Although upstate has lagged in job growth, it
is now catching up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think we are in an economic wasteland, like the other
side likes us to believe,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep things moving, Lazio said, he would work for tax relief
for businesses, including cutting the capital gains tax rate from
20 percent to 15 percent, and encourage technology businesses to
move upstate, perhaps linking with local colleges and universities,
as the Kionix Technology Co. in Ithaca did with Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   The state's chief economist, Stephen Kagann, reported last month
that private-sector employment increased and unemployment rates
fell over the last year, both downstate and upstate. Private
employment in June rose 2.3 percent over June 1999, with a 2.5
percent increase in New York City and its suburbs and 1.8 percent
upstate. The national growth rate was 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Independent analysts, however, have said that much of the growth
occurred in low-paying retail jobs. The statewide unemployment rate
fell to 4.5 percent in June from 5.3 percent a year earlier but
still remained higher than the national average of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates view the upstate region as a pivotal trough of
votes and have mounted remarkably similar swings through the area.
Just last month, Clinton, too, visited electronics and technology
companies, advocating those sectors as potential areas of growth
and promising tax breaks and other incentives. Her aides said she
has never called the region a wasteland but, like Lazio, has talked
of young people leaving the area for higher-paying jobs and the
need to explore other areas like technology to stimulate growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, Hillary is the only candidate in this race who
knows upstate needs more jobs and has a plan to create them,' said
Cathie Levine, a spokeswoman for Clinton, referring to a plan the
first lady unveiled in February.
</P>
<P>
   While Lazio sought to keep his day focused on the economy, he
was distracted by the tactics of Clinton's campaign, which has a
young worker following the congressman with a videocamera for
prospective advertising footage, and the Democratic Party, which
has sent a young man dressed as Uncle Sam to pursue Lazio and
demand he release his income tax returns. Lazio, for the third
consecutive day, said he would release the returns sometime this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides, after nearly three months of tolerating the young
man's videotaping, turned angry Thursday and began holding signs in
front of the man's camera. One aide stuck his face right up against
the lens, with a hard stare.
</P>
<P>
   At a stop in Owego, Lazio ended his remarks to a gathering of
party loyalists by introducing the young man who was taping him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So let's all say hello to Hillary Clinton and the whole
Clinton camp,'' Lazio said. ``We don't have to resort to that
stuff, do we?'' A chorus of no's then rose up from the four dozen
people.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had arrived in Owego somewhat self-consciously since his
staff had misspelled it in a news advisory as Oswego _ which is on
the shores of Lake Ontario about 300 miles away. The gaffe was
noted by local newspapers Thursday. The campaigns have seized on
each other's upstate geographical blunders as evidence of a lack of
familiarity with the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
