<HEADLINE>
MILT ROSEN, 77, A MASTER OF ZINGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Milt Rosen, a versatile writer whose work included television
scripts, comedy one-liners and books, died Aug. 11 at his home in
Los Angeles. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said a friend and author, Austin Kalisch.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's more than a dozen books include ``The Second Book of
Insults'' (1985), containing lines like: ``She's not very
photogenic, especially in person,'' ``He stays longer in an hour
than most people do in a week,'' and ``She's not the girl she used
to be, and she never was.''
</P>
<P>
   He also edited the book ``More of the Best of Milton Berle's
Private Joke File'' (1994, Avon). Berle and Arnold Schwarzenegger
were among the celebrities he wrote one-liners for.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen edited the book ``A Treasury of Sports Quotes and Wisdom''
(1999) Rosen and Robert Foster were nominated for an Edgar Award of
the Mystery Writers of America in 1976 for an episode ``Murder
Comes in Little Pills'' for the CBS series ``Kate McShane.'' Among
the other television series Rosen wrote for were `CHiPs,'' ``Lewis
&AMP; Clark,'' ``Mr. Novak'' and ``Tales of the Gold Monkey.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also a co-author of the screenplay for the film ``Do Not
Disturb'' (1965) with Doris Day.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Poland, Rosen came to New York City with his family as a
toddler and went on to graduate from City College. During World War
II he became chief navigator of his squadron in the 8th Air Force
in the European Theater of Operations. He won the Air Medal five
times, Kalisch said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen taught in New York City public schools and moved to
California in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving are his wife, Judy; a son, Joshua; two daughters,
Stephanie Rimbach and Rachel Rosen, all of Los Angeles; and four
grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
