<HEADER>
A5143 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-GORE-ANALYSIS-SPI &LR;      08-17 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ANALYSIS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE FACES UPHILL BATTLE IN COUNTDOWN WEEKS TO ELECTION DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Over the past half-century, America's fall
presidential campaigns have resembled less a come-from-behind horse
race, and more a hydroplane race in which one boat stays ahead from
starting line to checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1960, when Richard Nixon had a wafer-thin lead over
John F. Kennedy, has a candidate ahead in the polls on Labor Day
lost the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has run behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush
in opinion surveys throughout the year, even as the national
economy has continued to surge ahead.
</P>
<P>
   As he took the podium Thursday night, Gore was still waiting for
the convention ``bounce'' that would narrow the gap with Bush and
show that the vice president is emerging from the shadow that Bill
Clinton has cast over American politics for the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Cast in a subordinate role, vice presidents have a traditional
problem getting respect. But the malady has been painfully acute
with the current No. 2 man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think Al Gore was born in the summer of 1992,''
said James Carville, the consultant who helped put Clinton in the
White House that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is very talented and very smart but he doesn't understand
political communication. ... The public is bored by him,'' said
Frank Luntz, a top Republican opinion expert who has been
assembling focus groups of undecided voters for MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Gore faces a narrow post-convention window of attention to make
American voters see him, in Gore's words Thursday night, as ``my
own man'' and an agenda-driven potential president different in
character from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., a Gore intimate, reflected on the
difficult, multi-dimensional task facing the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to establish Gore as a real leader,'' Dicks said. ``We
have to show him as a real human being. And we have to energize the
Democratic base. Republicans are already unified. Democrats have to
get off their duffs and show the same intensity and desire we're
seeing with the Republicans. They want the White House back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is appearing increasingly robust, recently
taking the GOP nominee to Democratic-leaning West Coast states and
agreeing to hold a record five debates during the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush managers said Thursday that they are ready for three
Bush-Gore faceoffs and a pair of encounters between vice
presidential nominees Dick Cheney and Joe Lieberman. Just last
month, Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, forecast only two
debates and said: ``Our debate strategy can be summed up in one
word: Survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has built his lead in the polls, in large
part, coming across as an affable, unthreatening and at-ease guy,
focused on a few big-picture goals.
</P>
<P>
   Using an array of surrogates, including Jim Frush, the
Seattle-area attorney who guided Gore to the top of Mount Rainier
last summer, Gore's campaign has spent the week seeking to humanize
its candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Key Democrats concede, however, the likeability battle may
already be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's at stake is not whether you want to have lunch with
him, or a beer with him, but whether you want him running the
country,'' said Sen. Chris Dodd of Connecticut, a former Democratic
National Chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The main hope for a Gore victory is summed up in five words by
Dicks: ``Issues are on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats believe they hold the high ground on an array of
popular proposals: prescription drug coverage for seniors under
Medicare; a patient's bill of rights in dealing with health
insurers; a higher minumum wage; guarantees of privacy in the
information age; and protection of America's environment.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Greenberg, President Clinton's pollster, did a nationwide
survey of 1,007 voters last week. It found that Gore trailed Bush
by nine points, but that Democrats have an advantage in public
confidence on such issues as health care, Medicare and managing the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush wins this race by nine points, boom! The (Democratic)
party is wiped out,'' Carville said. ``It would be like the
dinosaurs.'' The ``Ragin Cajun'' political strategist is convinced,
however, that Republicans have reached ``their high-water mark.''
</P>
<P>
   As the presidential race unfolds, key developments to watch
include:
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATIC TENT: As he spoke Thursday night, polls showed
Gore supported by only 75 percent of Democrats, while Bush enjoys
90-plus percent support among Republican-leaning voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has to win back Democrats inclined to vote for Bush,
including one-quarter of union voters, according to Greenberg's
poll. He also needs to ``deal with Nader,'' in Dicks' words.
</P>
<P>
   By draining support from Gore, Green Party candidate Ralph Nader
has helped turn states that Democrats need to win into tossups.
Washington, Oregon and Michigan are three examples.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEBATES: Having bested such foes as Jack Kemp, Ross Perot
and Bill Bradley in the past, Gore will confront huge expectations
when he takes the stage with Bush this fall.
</P>
<P>
   As to Bush, ``He simply has to survive and not make mistakes,''
said independent pollster John Zogby. ``Voters are telling us they
like George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   SEPTEMBER'S SHOWDOWN: President Clinton has gone eye-to-eye with
Congress' Republican leadership in recent fall budget battles, and
it is the GOP that has blinked.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can use the upcoming budget showdown to focus attention
on such topics as patients' rights and prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's (congressional leaders') worst nightmare,'' Dodd said.
``It is an opportunity to break through into public consciousness
with our agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   THE STRETCH RUN: Dramatic come-from-behind victories haven't
happened since Harry Truman's whistle stop campaign of 1948, but
stretch runs do happen.
</P>
<P>
   After falling far behind after early fall debates, Nixon came
within 110,000 votes of catching Kennedy. Hubert Humphrey,
massively outspent and with Democrats divided over Vietnam, wiped
out a 15-point deficit in the polls and barely lost to Nixon in
1968. Gerald Ford trailed Jimmy Carter by as much as 30 points in
1976 polls, but lost 50-48 in a photo-finish election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice Presidents are good closers,'' said Carville. ``Gore is a
good closer.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of this year, a largely contented America has tuned out
the televised babble of political junkies, and switched channels
when the Republican and Democratic national conventions came on.
Opinion experts are encountering a public that has refused to pay
much attention to picking a new president.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Brazile, Gore's campaign manager, summed it up on CNN on
Thursday night: ``People are really taking their time to figure out
where they are and where they want to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-00 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
