<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-ASSESS-1STLD-WRI     08-17 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TO EMPHASIZE DRY TIMBER OF ISSUES OVER FLASH AND DAZZLE OF
PERSONALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Updates with quotes from speech and comments from Gore aides on
future of campaign) 
   By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Al Gore tried to accomplish a political feat so
daunting Thursday night that even, say, President Clinton himself
might have had trouble pulling it off.
</P>
<P>
   Gore presented himself as his own man and skated over his
service as vice president as he sought to persuade the nation that
he is more than the dutiful lieutenant. But he also tried to take
credit for helping to bring about ``the biggest surpluses ever'' _
the grandest achievement of the Clinton era.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to shake the impressions of Americans who, in the words
of his campaign chairman, think he is ``boring, stiff'' and
``unable to speak.'' But he also asserted that he would build a
campaign based on the dry timber of issues rather than on the flash
and dazzle of personality.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to embolden and excite liberals whose turnout are
essential to his victory. But he also tried to embolden and excite
moderate voters who are crucial to a victory in November _ and have
shown an interest in Gov. George W. Bush of Texas that has alarmed
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's elaborate _ and often conflicting _ objectives Thursday
night, and throughout this convention week, reflect the trying
challenges he and the Democrats confront as they emerge from this
convention. Forget all the confetti and mirthful talk of harmony
from the rostrum this week. For the Democrats, happy days are
certainly not here again. They may not be panicked, but they are
jittery about their standard bearer. And they are jittery about
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a difficult campaign,'' said James Patrick Leahy, a
delegate from Ohio, even after four days of enforced partisan
cheerleading. ``Gore has one of those personalities you have to
develop a relationship with.''
</P>
<P>
   The polls showing Gore behind, Leahy said, have dampened his
enthusiasm. ``The polling has a psychological effect,'' he said.
``It's like when you go to the race track and look at the racing
form and see your horse isn't supposed to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no such worries when the Republicans concluded their
political production in Philadelphia two weeks ago. At that
convention, Dick Cheney, the vice presidential nominee, did not
have to scurry from constituent group to constituent group with
words of appeasement _ as Sen. Joseph Lieberman did Thursday, and
the two days before.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years on the outside, even Republican delegates who
were not pleased with the inclusive tone of the program were so
desperate to return to power that it took little, if any, prodding
to corral them behind Bush. Eight years ago, Democrats were also
willing to put aside their differences in the name of the greater
goal of helping Bill Clinton bring them back to power. Now, they
are less accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   So the party tried to fire up the rank and file by jamming the
stage this week with liberal icons like Sen. Edward Kennedy and the
Rev. Jesse Jackson, and leaders of labor, abortion rights and gay
rights groups. Even Senator Lieberman, in his acceptance speech,
retreated from his usual condemnation of the collapsed culture of
Hollywood and instead played the partisan.
</P>
<P>
   More than one Democratic official complained that the campaign
this week seemed more focused on winning over the liberals who
might back Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate, than the biggest
threat, Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that, unlike the Republicans, the Democrats had
less success in presenting a convention that appeared to be broader
than the party itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans played to the country _ the Democrats played
to the hall,'' said Frank Luntz, a Republican pollster. ``Voters
saw through the big tent Republican convention. They know it was
staged. But they were thankful that somebody cared.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is Al Gore. Whether it is his link to the
scandals of Clinton, the unfavorable comparisons to the more
politically adroit president _ or simply his personality _
Democrats here are are just not as enamored of their new nominee.
On this day four years ago, even the bombshell that Clinton's top
strategist was having an affair with a call girl did nothing to
disrupt _ and maybe added a little spice _ to the week of lock-step
partisan harmony behind the president.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before his boss was to deliver the most consequential
speech of his political career, one of Gore's top aides confessed
that he was worried because the campaign was still roiled by
squabbling factions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Daley has not gotten the warlords under control yet,''
this campaign official said, referring to William Daley, Gore's
campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident, certainly, that Gore spewed out lots of
policy Thursday night. He was trying to make the case that ``people
deserve to know specifically what a candidate proposes to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of polls showing that the public gives Democrats higher
marks than Republicans on a range of issues, Gore's aides said they
hope the campaign can be fought on that terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Before he can do that, Gore wants to neutralize Bush's biggest
advantage _ his appealing personality. That explains that footage
in a film Thursday night lauding Gore for his Frankenstein disguise
during a Halloween party. That is why all week Democrats, and the
candidate himself, offered testaments to the fuzzy and decidedly
un-vice-presidential Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that Bush has the edge on charm, Gore said, ``The
presidency is not a popularity contest. It's a day-to-day fight for
people. Sometimes, you have to chose to do what's difficult or
unpopular. Sometimes you have to be willing to spend your
popularity in order to pick the hard right over the easy wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then-Vice President George Bush, in his acceptance speech
in Dallas in 1988, did not face the difficulties of Gore. He, too,
had the unfortunate fate of having to stand on his own after eight
years in the shadow of a far more dexterous political performer.
But Bush never had such trouble untangling himself from Ronald
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The symbolic transfer of political power was far smoother in
1988 when Reagan put forth a dignified and full-throated pitch for
his No. 2. This week, Clinton was criticized for not making more of
an energetic case for Gore in his speech here on Monday _ or in
their joint appearance in Michigan the next day. The rub is that
had he been more generous in his praise, Clinton might have been
accused of injecting himself too much into the role of star
performer giving an assist to his understudy. In his speech
Thursday night, Gore seemed to borrow a bit from the playbook of
the man whose son is standing in his way to the White House. He
directly addressed what the personality questions, saying, ``If you
entrust me with the presidency, I know I won't always be the most
exciting politician.'' But, he pledged, ``I will work for you every
day and I will never let you down.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Bush said in 1988: ``I may not be the most eloquent,
but I learned that eloquence won't draw oil from the ground. I may
sometimes be a little awkward, but there's nothing self-conscious
in my love of country.''And, as Bush did 12 years ago, Gore sought
to fasten himself to the economic successes of his administration
</P>
<P>
   . ``Instead of losing jobs,'' Gore said, ``we have 22 million
new jobs. Above all, our success comes from you, the people who
have worked hard for your families.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush put it this way in 1988, ``We've created 17 million new
jobs in the past five years,'' more than twice as many as in Europe
and Japan combined.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that the appeal will work and that people will
entrust Gore to continue bringing the nation down the path of
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But in a telling acknowledgment that the campaign ahead will not
be easy, Gore's aides were already playing down the import of
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important moment, a crescendo,'' said Tad Devine,
one of Gore's top strategists. ``It's the first time Al Gore is on
the stage by himself. But there will be other big moments in this
campaign, including the presidential debates.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
