<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5282 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-DEMS-LEWINSKY-HNS &LR;      08-17 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-LEWINSKY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
LEWINSKY GRAND JURY TIMING `REEKS' TO DEMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
By CLAY ROBISON &QL; 
C.2000 Houston Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democrats meeting in Monica Lewinsky's hometown
were outraged Thursday to learn that a new grand jury had been
impaneled to hear evidence against President Clinton in the scandal
involving the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   They were convinced that the timing of the news, which rippled
through the Democratic National Convention only hours before Al
Gore accepted his party's presidential nomination, was designed to
derail his race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But they predicted it would not affect the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has taken pains throughout his campaign to distance himself
from the scandal, which led to Clinton's impeachment by the House
and acquittal in a Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing reeks to high heaven,'' said Eric Hartman, a
convention delegate from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's part of a consistent pattern to get people to
concentrate on extraneous matters'' and ignore more substantive
differences between Gore and Republican nominee George W. Bush,
Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman blamed the news leak about a grand jury that was
impaneled more than a month ago on Republicans who want to continue
to ``hound Clinton'' and hurt Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' moaned Sue Schechter, chairwoman of the Harris
County (Texas) Democratic Party. ``I'm sure it's to take away from
Gore's (acceptance) speech. They never know when to stop playing
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Ismael Ahmed, a delegate from Detroit, predicted the Republican
ploy _ if that's what it was _ wouldn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an Arab-American. But in Southern terms, that dog won't
hunt,'' he said. ``The American people have had their time to look
at this for what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Guthrie, an auto parts worker from Three Rivers, Mich.,
blamed the news media for keeping the Lewinsky story alive by
giving the independent counsel a forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pure trash. If the press can't find anything else to go
for, they ought to pack their bags and move out of the country,''
he said. ``I'm tired of the press trashing our country. It's your
country, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally Rizzo, a delegate from Newton, Mass., also lashed out at
the news media. ``I think it's a ridiculous waste of time and a
ridiculous waste of ink for newspapers,'' she said. ``People don't
want to hear about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo said that people would rather hear about other issues,
such as health care.
</P>
<P>
   Emmett Sheppard, secretary-treasurer of the Texas AFL-CIO and a
delegate from Austin, said the timing of the news ``probably
stinks.'' The aim, he said, was to help Bush by turning off
Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're just trying to drive voter participation
down,'' Sheppard said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Krausz, of Swarthmore, Pa., predicted the new grand jury
probe will be a negative for Bush in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given all this rhetoric about running a positive campaign, all
these behind the scenes attacks by others have a chance of
backfiring on him,'' Krausz said. ``The American public is smart
enough to see things don't happen by coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Bebitch Jeffe of Claremount Graduate University agreed
that the investigation could hurt Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good for Gore, but there could be a backlash,'' she
said. ``They (voters) are sick and tired of Clinton, but they're
also sick and tired of the scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffe said the development also could put Gore's running mate,
Joseph Lieberman, on the spot. Lieberman was an early Democratic
critic of Clinton's behavior during the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he (Lieberman) fall in line or does he continue to speak
out?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
