u p BC-CVN-GORE-HNS &LR;      08-17 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ACCEPTS DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL NOMINATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vowing to extend prosperity to the working
families that he's made central to his campaign, Democrat Al Gore
on Thursday accepted his party's presidential nomination,
declaring, ``Our whole future is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The future should belong to everyone in this land,'' Gore said
in remarks prepared for delivery at the Democratic National
Convention. ``We could squander this moment, but our country would
be poorer for it. Instead, let's lift our eyes and see how wide the
American horizon has become.''
</P>
<P>
   Delivering the most important speech of his life on the
convention's closing night, the 52-year-old vice president marked a
pivotal moment between more than a year of non-stop campaigning and
the final sprint to Election Day Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sought to project a passion that would overcome low
expectations, lagging polls numbers and the reputation for a stiff
personality that has been the subject of Republican derision, late
night television one-liners and even his own self-deprecation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know this,'' Gore said in accepting the
Democratic nomination and calling on voters to support him and his
running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken on the powerful forces. And as president, I'll
stand up to them, and I'll stand up for you.''
</P>
<P>
   He specifically mentioned the pharmaceutical industry, invoking
a key campaign theme _ health care reforms including Medicare
coverage for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll fight for it and the other side will not,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan crowd responded often with applause and cheers of
``Go, Al, Go.''
</P>
<P>
   With his campaign for president trailing Republican Gov. George
W. Bush for months heading into the Democratic National Convention,
Gore strove in a speech he wrote himself to knit his name and
message to the nation's bounding economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that the stock market has boomed and so many
businesses and new enterprises have done well,'' he said. ``This
country is richer and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my focus is on working families _ people trying to make
house payments and car payments, working overtime to save for
college and do right by their kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to those who did not support him and his more centrist
campaign for president, Gore acknowledged Bill Bradley, the former
U.S. senator from New Jersey the vice president vanquished in the
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Lighting on a question raised frequently about his difficulty in
emerging from the shadow of President Clinton, Gore said, ``We're
electing a new president. And I stand here tonight as my own man,
and I want you to know me for who I truly am.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the week leading up to Gore's climactic speech,
Democratic supporters and family members have urgently worked to
convey an enhanced, multifaceted image of Gore, whom many voters
say they find stolid and inscrutable.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore, his wife of 30 years and an avid amateur
photographer, introduced her husband at the convention through a
montage of her own pictures and others showing the family man
behind the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of you know that faith and family are at the center of
Al's life,'' she said. ``Many of you know Al to be a decisive
leader with strong values, deeply held convictions and an
unwavering commitment to making the American dream a reality for
all our people.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also want you to know that as a husband, father and
grandfather, Al has always been there for our family and he will
always be there for yours,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Texan Robert Strauss, former ambassador to the Soviet Union and
lifelong friend and adviser to presidents of both parties, said
earlier this week that in order to connect with voters, Gore would
have to deliver an issue-laden convention address that also was
``appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   The biographical journey that preceded Gore's speech traced his
life from Carthage, Tenn., to Harvard College, Vietnam, years spent
working as a journalist, 16 years in Congress and eight as vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   In adding family flourishes, such as remarks by his wife and
daughters Karenna and Kristin, to Gore's delivery on the
convention's national stage, his handlers hope to benefit from a
post-convention ``bounce'' in the polls, such as the one that Bush
enjoyed after the Republican National Convention two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Gore laid out a list of accomplishments and an
agenda for the country's future aimed at closing the gap between
the Democratic and Republican campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   He said the federal budget surplus makes possible ``a full range
of targeted tax cuts to working families. Not just to help them
save for college, but to pay for health insurance or child care, to
reform the estate tax ... and to end the marriage penalty _ the
right way, the fair way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he wants to build upon the nation's prosperity, as
symbolized by expanding federal budget surpluses, the lowest
inflation rate in a generation and 22 million new jobs since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, let's make sure that our prosperity enriches not
just the few, but all working families,'' Gore said. ``And for all
our good times, I am not satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   In a swipe at Bush and what Gore has deemed the ``do-nothing
Republican Congress,'' Gore said: ``Let me say plainly. I will not
go along with a huge tax cut for the wealthy at the expense of
everyone else and wreck our good economy in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, try as he might to define his own persona separate from
Clinton, the president's ongoing legal troubles invariably inserted
themselves during what was to be Gore's unspoiled moment in the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepared to address the convention, the disclosure came
from Washington that a new federal grand jury was impaneled July 11
to hear evidence in Clinton's affair with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a decision by special prosecutor Robert Ray on
whether to indict Clinton for obstruction of justice and perjury.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert condemned the inopportune
revelation, saying: ``The timing of this leak reeks to high
heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign was similarly critical of the news, as was
Karen Hughes, spokeswoman for the Bush campaign, who said, ``We
think the timing is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Also before Gore's address, the Bush campaign announced from
Austin that Bush and running mate Dick Cheney would negotiate a
total of five debates this fall with Gore and his running mate,
Sen. Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   With the conclusion of the convention, Gore and Lieberman plan a
four-day 400-mile boat trip down the Mississippi River starting
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The journey aboard the Mark Twain river boat would take them
past the key of Wisconsin, Iowa, Illinois, Kentucky and Missouri,
battlegrounds in the race for electoral college votes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
