<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5285 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-BAXTER18-COX     08-17 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BAXTER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DOES AL GORE'S VISION OF AMERICA REFLECT REALITY?
 &HT;    By TOM BAXTER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the past week, the focus of speculation about
Al Gore has been whether the American people really know him, as he
said in his speech Thursday night, for who he truly is.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's acceptance speech at the Democratic National
Convention suggested another question that could be even more
important to the outcome of the November election: How well does
Gore know the American people?
</P>
<P>
   The hard-working families Gore spoke of, struggling to make the
monthly house payment and educate their children, have been stock
characters in Democratic speeches since the party began turning
toward the center and distancing itself from its special interest
groups. That strategy proved so effective the Republicans this year
have gone all-out to adopt it.
</P>
<P>
   These days those working families come in many more
configurations than they used to, which ought to work to the
advantage of what has traditionally been the party of outsiders and
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   But this year there is keen competition for families of all
sorts, and it was for this reason that the vice president pointed
out several specific Americans and their families in his speech,
attempting to personalize a larger American family that is becoming
more and more extended.
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged several debts in this speech, outright or
implicitly.
</P>
<P>
   First and most obviously, he thanked Bill Clinton, on whose
watch grew the economy on which the Democrats' appeal this year is
centered.
</P>
<P>
   Gore pledged to continue having open meetings in the places
where Americans live and work, something he said he has been doing
for 25 years. Perhaps so, but in this campaign year it was
Republican John McCain and Democrat Bill Bradley who made the first
inroads with their freewheeling town meetings. Gore, the good
student, shifted to this format early on, giving him the vital
boost that insured his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Through the efforts of his wife Tipper, Gore has been identified
with those who decry the coarsening of the American culture. But in
decrying a culture with ``too much meanness and not enough
meaning,'' he was clearly leaning more in the direction of his
running mate, Joe Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there are deep concerns about the violence and license
in much of popular culture. But that's a slippery slope in
presidential politics, as the Republicans have learned. It wasn't
coincidence that Gore's words were preceded by Tipper bobbing out
on stage to ``Turn the Beat Around'' and showing America her looser
side.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's entrance across a convention floor, which was much more
crowded and boisterous than the one at the GOP convention in
Philadelphia, was a risky but perhaps necessary move.
</P>
<P>
   Gore not only needed to negate the image of stiffness which has
dogged him, but even more he needed to electrify this Democratic
crowd and demonstrate to the American television audience that this
party will pursue the presidency with as much enthusiasm as the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   It was a risk to deliver this long a speech and write it
himself, but the Gore campaign did have the foresight to bring the
candidate on stage a few minutes ahead of prime time, and to put
some of his most important lines in the opening paragraphs.
</P>
<P>
   It was, indeed, a different Gore than most Americans think they
know. The question now is how closely those Americans he singled
out Thursday night resemble the electorate that will show up to
vote in November.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter's e-mail is tbaxter(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
