<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5280 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DNC-UNITED-LADN     08-17 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-UNITED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURMOIL AT UNITED MAY FORCE DELEGATES TO FLEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY and ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thousands of delegates in Los Angeles for the
Democratic National Convention are being urged to leave Friday
instead of Sunday to avoid delays caused by a labor dispute at
United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But the early departure could cost the city and region millions
of dollars in lost tourist revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking to people in Beverly Hills and businesses
there have definitely felt a positive impact from the convention,''
said Jack Kyser, chief economist with the Los Angeles Economic
Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of money was being dropped on Rodeo Drive,'' he said.
``The economic impact is estimated to be $4million spent on retail.
If they are told to get out of town, you are taking away a few good
business days.''
</P>
<P>
   UAL Corp., the parent of United Airlines, has delayed or
canceled thousands of flights this summer, primarily due to a
dispute with its 10,500 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute comes as United, the official airline for the
Democratic convention, scrambles to shuttle thousands of delegates,
lobbyists and journalists home from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   United has four information stands set up at the Democratic
National Convention _ two inside Staples Center and two inside the
Convention Center _ where a steady stream of delegates and media
members checked on flights Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Curley, a public relations specialist from Washington,
D.C., wanted to make sure she has a seat on her 6:30 a.m. flight
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous,'' she said after being reassured by a United
employee. ``I wanted to make sure my flight was still going and it
wasn't delayed or canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   Illinois delegates, who will fly back to United's Chicago hub
today, were warned by delegation leaders to go early to the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Kaplan, a delegate from Chicago, was supposed to fly
United but changed her flight. ``I'm flying American back because I
flew United a week ago for a vacation and was delayed eight hours
going from Maine to Chicago,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline says its pilots have refused to work overtime and
increasingly have been calling in sick to protest prolonged
contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Line Pilots Association, which represents United pilots,
denies there is any organized job action.
</P>
<P>
   Still, thousands of flights have been delayed or canceled this
summer, some due to bad weather but most because of the labor
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking steps to protect the high number of passengers
leaving Los Angeles and flying back to their homes,'' said Matt
Triaca, an airline spokesman. ``We plan to allocate enough spare
planes to key hubs.''
</P>
<P>
   At Los Angeles International Airport, United is fully staffed
and has extra planes and crews standing by just in case they are
needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also bulked up to get delegates to the convention,
but their efforts were lost on Ed Hasevawa, a delegate from
Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were delayed three hours coming out here. I hope I'm not
delayed three days going back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline issued an apology to its passengers Thursday and
handed out bonus miles to its most loyal customers in a face-saving
move that came on the same day as an embarrassing earnings
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in a month, UAL Corp. announced Thursday
that it expects third-quarter earnings per share to be lower than
the $2.60-to-$3.20 range it previously announced.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say the revised earnings estimates are because
travelers worried about flight cancellations at its United unit are
switching to other air carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser said savvy travelers shouldn't wait until a cancellation
to make the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though United Airlines is the largest airline at LAX, it
is not the dominant carrier,'' he said. ``You have American, Delta
and Southwest among others. If you were in Chicago it's American
and United. You are not being held hostage at LAX.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of cancellations and delays by United and other air
carriers, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater has called for a
summit with the airlines' chief executives in Washington on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting will also include airport and labor officials in an
attempt to address the recent impact of weather, scheduling and
other problems put on the traveling public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
