<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING, UNION MEET OVER EMERGING OPERATIONS PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The largest union at The Boeing Co. said Thursday the
company had notified it of an emerging plan to shut down some
operations, move others and uproot but retain roughly 1,000 union
members.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the potential moves created anxiety among some
affected workers in the Puget Sound area who worried about the
possibility of longer commutes and new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two years Boeing would close its Harbour Pointe
facility near Mukilteo, transferring at least 300 workers to other
company jobs in the region, according to the International
Association of Machinists District Lodge 751. The union said it
expected Boeing to unveil the proposal Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, outlined for the first time in Thursday's
Post-Intelligencer, would also call for Boeing to build new tools
in Wichita, Kan., tapping 2,000 Puget Sound tooling workers for
support programs and retraining an additional 350 members, the
union said.
</P>
<P>
   The union posted an outline of the plan on its website Thursday,
and said an announcement was coming Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials Thursday said the company had nothing to
announce. Company spokesmen declined to comment on the union's
statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not announcing anything at this point. But, if
something does come to pass we would be endeavoring to communicate
directly with our employees,'' Peter Conte, a Boeing spokesman,
told the P-I.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are scared,'' said one worker at Harbour Pointe, who
requested anonymity. ``It's like we are being sold down the river.
We don't know at which port we are going to land.''
</P>
<P>
   The steps, if taken, would represent the latest in Boeing's
broader campaign to shed underutilized assets and boost efficiency.
If the Seattle-based company does announce a consolidation plan
Friday, that may not be the only step it takes in the region to
trim operations.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction from Boeing workers to reports of the emerging plan was
mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees said the potential steps could help the company
eliminate unnecessary costs, while also allowing union members to
retain their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of new airplane orders at Boeing also is making some
employees feel a bit more comfortable, according to Steve Vergala,
who works on parts control in the wire shop of Boeing's massive
Everett, Wash., facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more orders they see the better off people feel,'' Vergala
said.
</P>
<P>
   Others worried that the potential consolidation is only the
beginning of deeper cuts, according to John Scofield, who works in
final assembly on the 777 airplane line in Everett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people in our area think this is just the
beginning of the end over the next five to 10 years,'' Scofield
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other steps, announced by the union but not confirmed by the
company, the company would take include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Close a machine shop in Kent, which employs more than 300
people.
</P>
<P>
   _ Move an emergency support team, known as Blue Streak, to
Boeing's EMF building in Auburn. The plan would also eventually
shift a similar team in Everett to the Auburn facility.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consolidate Boeing Auburn facility's Process Assembly.
Affected union members would be retrained and receive lateral
positions in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
