<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5287 &Cx1f; tad-z
b p BC-CVN-MAIN18-1STLD-COX     08-17 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MAIN18-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE VOWS TO FIGHT FOR 'EVERYDAY HEROES'
 &HT;    950&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore promised to support the
``quiet, everyday heroism of hard-working Americans'' as he
accepted the Democratic Party's presidential nomination Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that focused on the possibilities of the future
rather than the accomplishments of the Clinton administration, Gore
declared himself ``my own man'' as he re-introduced himself to the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than try to match the charm of his Republican rival,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the notoriously formal Gore used his
acceptance speech to draw distinctions on issues he believes will
help him overcome Bush's steady lead in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my own imperfections,'' he said. ``I know that
sometimes people say I'm too serious, that I talk too much
substance and policy. Maybe I've done that tonight. But the
presidency is more than a popularity contest. It's a day-to-day
fight for people.''
</P>
<P>
   And with news of a new investigation of President Clinton
casting yet another shadow on his candidacy, Gore added, ``If you
entrust me with the presidency, I know that I won't always be the
most exciting politician. But I pledge to you tonight: I will work
for you every day and I will never let you down.''
</P>
<P>
   The party's new presidential standard-bearer promised to use the
federal government's record budget surplus to expand health care
coverage, improve education, shore up safety net programs and
extend tax cuts to help ``every hard-working family'' to ``open the
door to their dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   He also pledged his support for affirmative action, new gun
controls, federal hate crime legislation, an increase in the
federal minimum wage, a patients bill of rights, funding for more
police and teachers and cracking down on the marketing of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Although frequently interrupted by the pennant waving delegates
and chants of ``Go, Al, Go,'' Gore drew the most sustained applause
when he reiterated his support for abortion rights, a direct
counterpoint to Bush's opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let there be no doubt: I will protect and defend a woman's
right to choose,'' he said. ``The last thing this country needs is
a Supreme Court that overturns Roe v. Wade.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also recalled how he had fought ``against the powerful
interests'' over the course of his career, pushing for welfare
reform and an improved environment.
</P>
<P>
   And despite his own abuses of the campaign finance system, Gore
vowed that a reform bill will be the first one he sends to Congress
as president. ``Let others try to restore the old guard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also took direct aim at a sweeping tax cut proposal at the
heart of Bush's campaign. ``Let me say it pla Those concerns were
not diminished by the disclosure earlier Thursday that a new grand
jury has been empaneled to continue the investigation of Clinton in
connection with his extramarital affair with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Not only Democrats, but also Republicans expressed dismay over
the disclosure just hours before Gore was to accept his party's
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not appropriate for this type of announcement to be made
on the day that the vice president is going to accept the
Democratic nomination,'' said senior Bush strategist Karen Hughes.
``This election is not about the past; it's about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his acceptance speech, paid a glowing but brief tribute
to Clinton. ``Millions of Americans will live better lives for a
long time to come because of the job that's been done to President
Clinton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we turn the page and write a new chapter,'' he said.
``We're entering a new time. We're electing a new president. And I
stand here tonight as my own man, and I want you to know who I
truly am.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I have strong values, the love of my family, my
faith, my love for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention delegates erupted with cheers as Gore entered the
convention hall after Tipper's introduction. Wearing the more
traditional blue suit rather than the earth tones that were
ridiculed during the presidential primaries, Gore took the unusual
route to the speaker's podium, charging down an aisle on the
convention floor past the Tennessee delegation.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Promising to champion ordinary folks and their children, Gore
said, ``Tonight, I ask for your support on the basis of the better,
fairer, more prosperous America we can build together.''
</P>
<P>
   He reminded the audience of the administration's economic
accomplishments: 22 million new jobs, the lowest inflation in a
generation, the highest home ownership ever, the lowest
unemployment in a quarter century and the biggest budget surpluses
ever.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``for all of our good times, I am not satisfied,'' he
added. ``Together, let's make sure that our prosperity enriches not
just the few, but all working families.''
</P>
<P>
   As president, Gore said he would continue the open meetings that
were a part of his presidential campaign and his 16 years in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go out to you, the people, because I want to stay
in touch with your hopes, with the quiet, every-day heroism of
hard-working Americans,'' he said. ``So this is not just an
election between my opponent and me. It's about our people, our
families, and our future _ and whether forces standing in your way
will keep you from having a better life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not dwell exclusively on economic issues, however. He
also vowed to use the presidency to ``challenge a culture'' that
has ``too much meanness, and not enough meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   The party's 43rd convention, much more traditional than the
TV-driven GOP gathering two weeks ago, ended with a picturesque sea
of red, white and blue balloons and confetti dropped from the
Staples Center as family, friends and political joined Gore on the
podium.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut,
planned to leave Los Angeles shortly after the climactic event of
the convention to begin a four-day trip down the Mississippi River,
through Midwestern battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   Their trip follows word from the Bush campaign that the
Republican nominee and his running mate, former congressman Dick
Cheney, would like five debates this fall: three involving the
presidential candidates, two with the vice presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush initiative calls into question the three debates
scheduled by the Commission on Presidential Debates, which usually
organizes and runs the debates. The Bush campaign is seeking other
organizations to sponsor the debates.
</P>
<P>
   William Daley, the Gore campaign chairman, suggested that the
five debates sought by Bush should be in addition to the three
already scheduled by the debate commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of our campaign will be simple: to set up the
greatest number of debates in forums accessible to the greatest
number of voters, starting at the soonest possible time,'' Daley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
