A5293 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-GRAND-JURY-1S     08-17 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GRAND-JURY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GRAND JURY TO HEAR EVIDENCE IN LEWINSKY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS with inserts, revisions thruout)  
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent counsel investigating President
Clinton's relationship with a White House intern has empaneled a
new grand jury to hear evidence in the case, government officials
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel, Robert W. Ray, convened the panel last
month as part of his publicly announced intention to consider
whether Clinton should be charged with criminal wrongdoing in the
case, once he leaves office, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
there was no indication that the decision to empanel the grand jury
was based on any fresh evidence in the case. Nor did it indicate
that prosecutors were preparing to seek an indictment anytime soon,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House reacted angrily to the grand jury disclosure,
coming as it did just hours before Vice President Al Gore was to
accept the Democratic Party's nomination for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing of this leak reeks to high heaven,'' said Jake
Siewert, a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the new grand jury was empaneled on July 11. But
its existence became known only Thursday, a day after a panel of
three federal judges decided to allow the special prosecutor to
continue his investigation for another year. It was unclear if the
judges' decision had anything to do with the timing of Thursday's
leak to The Associated Press, which first reported the existence of
the new grand jury, attributing the information to ``legal
sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Ray's office were said Thursday to be fearful that
the disclosure would undercut their credibility and force an
investigation into whether anyone in the office had provided the
information.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel's office issued a statement that said:
``News organizations are reporting that a new grand jury has been
empaneled to hear evidence with respect to the investigation
involving allegations of perjury and obstruction of justice by
President Clinton. This office has no comment with respect to these
reports and will neither confirm nor deny them. These reports
indicate, and we confirm, the source of these reports is not within
the Office of the Independent Counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, mindful that the 1998 impeachment of Clinton
had probably contributed to their loss of seats in the House,
expressed reluctance to see any re-emergence of the Clinton scandal
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the timing is terrible,'' said Rep. Nancy Johnson, a
Republican moderate from Connecticut. ``I wish he hadn't done this
in a political season. It needs to be done when it can be
considered on its own merits and doesn't color other matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahm Emanuel, the fiercely partisan former senior adviser to
Clinton, said the news from Ray's office was ``brazenly political''
and predicted that it would cause a backlash against Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take my hat off to their gall,'' said Emanuel, now an
investment banker in Chicago. ``But my gut tells me the American
people, in their great wisdom, will once again recognize the
political nature of this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential
nominee, declined to speculate on the political impact of Ray's
action. But a spokesman for the governor said the development would
be viewed by the public as a reminder of the caustic climate in
Washington during the Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are sick and tired of investigation and
scandal,'' said Ray Sullivan, the Bush spokesman. ``The best way to
change that and change the tone in Washington is to change
administrations in the White House. George W. Bush and Dick Cheney
aim to do just that.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest grand jury's work begins more than 2 1/2 years after
Ray's predecessor, Kenneth Starr, first initiated his inquiry into
Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, then a White House
intern, and more than a year-and-a-half after the president was
impeached by the House and acquitted by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Starr began his inquiry examining the Whitewater real estate
development in Arkansas, and over the years expanded that
investigation to include a number of other matters, including the
intern issue.
</P>
<P>
   Although the independent counsel statute expired in June 1999,
Ray remains in office because the investigation began before the
law lapsed, assailed by both political parties as an unwieldy
investigative bludgeon that failed in its intended purpose to
remove politics from corruption cases against high-level
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews earlier this year, Ray, who took over from Starr
last October, said that he had completed the investigation into
whether presidential aides engaged in wrongdoing in connection with
the firing of employees at the White House travel office and with
another matter, the collecting of hundreds FBI personnel files by
White House employees. Ray decided against bringing charges in
either case.
</P>
<P>
   But Ray said that two matters remained open in an investigation
that had already spent $47 million when he took over. One was
whether the White House improperly kept e-mail messages from
congressional and Justice Department investigators looking into a
variety of accusations involving presidential aides.
</P>
<P>
   But the other far more incendiary issue was whether Clinton
could be charged with perjury or obstruction of justice when he
denied having a relationship with Lewinsky when he was deposed in
the Paula Jones sex harassment civil case against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the Jones case has already found that Clinton
testified falsely and fined him for civil contempt of court. The
disciplinary committee of the Arkansas Supreme Court has also moved
to revoke Clinton's law license.
</P>
<P>
   In empaneling the grand jury, Ray will seek to determine whether
Clinton's testimony in the Jones case was sufficiently misleading
to warrant bringing criminal charges against the president once he
leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's office would not comment on the decision to convene the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court panel that re-authorized Ray to continue his
work for another year, decided that termination was ``not currently
appropriate.'' Under the law, the panel must decide annually
whether to discontinue investigations of independent counsels like
Ray, who were named before the law expired.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, one of the three judges, Richard D. Cudahy, a
Democratic appointee to the bench, said the ``endless
investigation'' should be shut down when Starr stepped down. The
two other judges, appointed under Republican administrations, Peter
T. Fay and David B. Sentelle, ruled the office should continue. On
Wednesday, the decision to keep the inquiry open was unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Ausbrook, senior counsel to Ray, said Thursday that the
judges' decision suggested that the prosecutor was making progress
to conclude the inquiry. ``It reflects substantial progress in
completing our work,'' Ausbrook said. ``It also reflects that there
are open matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
