<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-TAXES-560&AMP;AD     08-17 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-TAXES-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUNT KEEPS A FOCUS ON LAZIO'S TAX RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, the Republican U.S. Senate nominee in New York,
has attracted an unbidden guest at some of his campaign events this
week: a Democratic lackey in an impressively garish Uncle Sam
costume who taunts Lazio over his failure to release copies of his
income tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Call it sophomoric or tacky (Lazio partisans call it much
worse). Still, the jeers have helped draw attention to a question
that has hung over Lazio: Why has he not yet disclosed his tax
returns, particularly given the long history of politicians in New
York stumbling over this issue?
</P>
<P>
   Almost since the day Lazio entered the race in May, his campaign
has pledged to make the information public. And with each passing
week, his assistants say they need more time, explaining that they
want to ensure that the returns are thoroughly researched so that
when they are released, the campaign will not be blind-sided by
anything in them. By the end of summer, the assistants promise. By
Labor Day? The autumnal equinox on Sept. 22? They won't say.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have been sowing conspiracy theories of the
what-is-Lazio-hiding variety, not to mention dispatching Uncle Sam
to keep the issue in reporters' faces. On Wednesday, Howard
Wolfson, the chief spokesman for Lazio's opponent, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, even showed up at a Lazio event in Harlem to fan the
flames.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that Lazio is hiding anything, and no law
requires candidates to release their tax returns. But it has become
customary in high-profile contests for candidates to do so; many
elected officials always do. President and Mrs. Clinton have
released their returns since he took office in 1993, and before
that, when he was governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio thus cannot easily brush aside the matter, leaving him
fending off the same accusations of obfuscation hurled at the
Clintons at times. And that diverts him from his strategy of trying
to keep the spotlight on whether Mrs. Clinton is suitable for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton campaign very badly needs to get him into the
race,'' said Lee M. Miringoff, director of the Marist Institute for
Public Opinion in Poughkeepsie, N.Y. ``Lazio would happily rent a
rowboat up in the Adirondacks and just paddle around until November
and let it stay all about Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, reporters repeatedly asked Lazio about the returns as
he campaigned in central New York. ``People are going to find this
is a pretty boring subject,'' he said, declaring that he was not a
wealthy man and vowing that the public and the media would have
plenty of time to examine the returns. He seemed to suggest that
they might be released by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also attacked the Clinton campaign and the State
Democratic Committee, which is paying for the Uncle Sam character.
``It's beneath what the public expects, I think, in a good,
civilized dialogue about the issues and about government,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is residency and whether you actually ever paid
New York state income taxes,'' he said. ``How can you possibly
represent the people of the state of New York if you've never paid
a dime of New York state income taxes?''
</P>
<P>
   To which Wolfson responded, ``He should stop making excuse after
excuse, come clean with New Yorkers, and release eight years of tax
returns for the eight years he has been in Congress.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since he went to Washington in 1993, Lazio has been required to
file financial disclosure statements with the House, which are
available to the public and provide limited details about his
investments and other aspects of his finances. Lazio, whose
congressional salary in 1999 was $136,700, disclosed several
securities trades on the forms but the profits were not specified;
they were listed under a range that goes from zero to $15,000 each.
Information in those documents about Lazio's trading in the
securities of a brokerage firm, Quick &AMP; Reilly, led to an ongoing
inquiry by regulators into whether he profited from inside
information.
</P>
<P>
   The returns would supply far more data, including how much, for
example, his wife, Patricia, earned; how much the couple donated to
charity; and other deductions they took.
</P>
<P>
   The wrangling over the returns could have few repercussions if
Lazio releases them soon and they are unremarkable. Yet the delay
has already left its mark, in that the returns seem likely to be
scrutinized far more closely now than if they had been distributed
in June.
</P>
<P>
   That is a lesson that more than a few politicians in New York
have learned over the years, most notably former Rep. Geraldine
Ferraro. In her last three runs for office _ for vice president in
1984 and for the U.S. Senate in the Democratic primaries of 1992
and 1998 _ Ferraro had to confront criticism that she was not
releasing her tax returns or was hindering access to them. She lost
all three races.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, her delay in releasing her and her husband's returns
dominated the news after Democratic presidential nominee Walter
Mondale selected her as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to have a stroke, only because the media frenzy
was so bad,'' Ferraro, now a consultant, said this week. ``The
media was killing me. What happens is that when you don't stop that
kind of stuff, and it gets out of control, you discuss nothing
else. You discuss no issues, you discuss no campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years later, in her final run for office, she imposed
restrictions on access to her returns, allowing reporters only
three hours to view them and declining to provide copies.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, fights over disclosure of tax returns have
roiled other New York campaigns. After Gov. Hugh Carey, a Democrat,
won a difficult re-election in 1978, assistants of his Republican
opponent, Perry Duryea, a former Assembly speaker, conceded that
Duryea's refusal to release several years of returns had played a
crucial role in his defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Such history did not impress Michael Long, chairman of the
Conservative Party and a Lazio adviser. Long said he did not think
Lazio had to release anything because the disclosure forms he filed
with the House provided plenty of information about Lazio's
finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the average New Yorker understands that here we
have a person who has never worked in New York, never paid income
taxes in New York, now asking for someone else's tax returns,''
Long said. ``It's clearly harassment, it's clearly a diversion to
create a distraction. Just because Mrs. Clinton wants to see his
tax returns, the congressman should jump through a hoop and do
everything she demands?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any purpose for it,'' Long said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
