<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHIELDS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIELDS SPURNS LSU FOR PROS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOLLY EDWARDS  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SANTA CLARITA, Calif. _ Reluctantly rejecting a full athletic
scholarship, 18-year-old Hart High graduate Jamie Shields has
instead opted to sign a three-year contract with baseball's Tampa
Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough choice, but I just have to follow my dreams
now,'' Shields said of his decision to play with the Devil Rays
rather than Louisiana State University. ``To get the opportunity to
play pro ball is pretty exciting and I feel like I can do a good
job right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Impressed by Shields' 93-mph fastball, the Devil Rays drafted
the pitcher in the 16th round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the natural tools of his velocity, we liked his
athleticism and his competitiveness,'' said Fred Repke, the Devil
Rays scout who has been working with Shields. ``We were also
impressed by his work ethic, and he comes from a solid family.''
</P>
<P>
   Shields said his parents, Jack and Cindy Shields, allowed him to
make his own choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're happy with whatever makes me happy,'' he said.
``They're just there to support me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shields will report for an eight-week camp in St. Petersburg,
Fla., on Sept. 17, then will return to Santa Clarita until spring
training begins in March.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting a brand new Cadillac SUV, Shields declined to reveal
the amount of his signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money really wasn't an issue to me,'' he said. ``I just had to
decide whether or not I really wanted to play right now.''
</P>
<P>
   A back injury forced Shields to sit out most of last year's
season. After months of intensive therapy, however, he said his
back is in ``awesome'' shape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
