</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-TELECOM-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIDS NEAR $50 BILLION FOR WIRELESS COMMUNICATIONS LICENSES
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for rewriting, updating thruout)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAINZ, Germany _ The most expensive auction in history ended
here Thursday, when six companies bid nearly $50 billion for
licenses to offer a new generation of wireless communications in
Germany, the largest economy in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The bids exceeded almost all expectations, and far exceeded the
$35.5 billion paid by many of the same companies for similar
third-generation wireless licenses in Britain in April.
</P>
<P>
   Stock and bond investors seemed concerned both about the
billions the bidders spent on licenses and the billions more
required for building the new networks in a brutally competitive
market.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the results represented something of a defeat for
Europe's two biggest wireless competitors: Deutsche Telekom, a
former monopoly, and Vodafone AirTouch of Britain, which owns
Mannesmann Mobilfunk and is a neck-and-neck rival with Deutsche
Telekom in this country's wireless market. Each had been intent on
capturing enough licenses to limit the number of new rivals.
Despite pushing up the bids by nearly $15 billion since Monday
morning, they failed to knock out smaller companies and must now
face more competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Thursday's buyers are intent on owning pan-European and
even global wireless networks. Besides Deutsche Telekom and
Vodafone, they include MobilCom, a fast-growing German phone
carrier that is backed by France Telecom; Viag Interkom, in which a
controlling stake has just been bought by British
Telecommunications; Group 3G, led by Telefonica of Spain and Sonera
of Finland; and another consortium led by KPN Mobile of the
Netherlands and NTT DoCoMo of Japan.A third partner, the Hong Kong
conglomerate Hutchison Whampoa, withdrew a few hours after the
group won a $7.7 billion license, Bloomberg News reported from Hong
Kong on Friday, quoting Canning Fok, Hutchison's group managing
director.)
</P>
<P>
   Klaus-Dieter Scheurle, head of Germany's telecommunications
regulatory agency and the auction's architect, said that ``for
consumers, the result promises the most intense competition.'' He
added, ``This was the most favorable solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's license sales, coming four months after Britain's
third-generation wireless auction, are part of a much larger
project. European Union nations, and eventually those in Eastern
Europe, are all awarding new licenses. Analysts predict that the
total cost of licenses across Europe could reach $150 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, with 82 million people, is crucial for companies with
pan-European ambitions. In addition, the affluent Germans use
mobile phones less than people in many countries nearby, so there
is room for growth.
</P>
<P>
   But the costs of controlling a Continental chessboard are huge.
Beyond the cost of wireless licenses, the big companies are
spending enormous amounts of money acquiring existing carriers.
Just Thursday, British Telecom announced an agreement to pay as
much as 7.35 billion euros, or $6.7 billion, for 45 percent more of
Viag Interkom, Germany's fourth-largest wireless company.
</P>
<P>
   That deal comes in the wake of France Telecom's recent purchase
of Orange PLC, with Britain's second-largest wireless network, and
Deutsche Telekom's bid to acquire VoiceStream Wireless of the
United States for $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the new third-generation wireless networks will
provide the capacity and technology to offer far faster and more
advanced data services than those now available. Supporters of the
third-generation networks talk of high-speed mobile Internet
access, scores of mobile commerce applications, and even the
ability to receive streams of video over a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, no one is yet sure what services will prove
practical and what consumers might be willing to pay for them. But
most analysts say that ordinary mobile phone service will become
steadily cheaper and will no longer provide the steep revenue
growth that wireless operators have enjoyed in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   The big bet is that as mobile telephones become even more widely
used but far less profitable, exotic new data services will more
than make up for the difference.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't believe that the average revenue per month will
double over the next 10 years, then there really isn't any point in
participating in the auctions,'' said Holger Grawe, a
telecommunications analyst at WestLB Panmeure in Duesseldorf.
Grawe, along with many others, is convinced that the bet will
ultimately pay off.
</P>
<P>
   But in the short term, investors are increasingly nervous.
Deutsche Telekom's stock has fallen by almost half this year,
mostly in the wake of the British auctions that generated
unexpected high prices.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan Warwick-Champion, telecommunications analyst at Standard
&AMP; Poor's in London, said that all the companies in Thursday's
auction were poised for possible downgrading of their credit
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly vulnerable, Warwick-Champion said, is Royal KPN of
the Netherlands, which has teamed up with BellSouth of the United
States to acquire control of the E-Plus wireless network in
Germany. But Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom and British Telecom
will be put on a credit watch list for possible downgrading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these sorts of auctions are shortsighted and
counterproductive,'' said Eden Zoller, a senior consultant at Ovum,
a telecommunications research firm in London. ``They would all be
much better spending their money on developing new services.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the huge cost of wireless licenses in Europe, investors
are also digesting the impact of deals like France Telecom's
purchase of Orange and Deutsche Telekom's agreement to acquire
VoiceStream. And Deutsche Telekom's bid may be blocked by U.S.
regulators, adding to the uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Bernd Eylert, a Deutsche Telekom executive who is also chairman
of a mobile phone industry group called the UMTS Forum, said the
huge cost of licenses could put pressure on operators to build
their networks as fast as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Other executives expressed frustration. ``We could have had it
for 30 billion marks less,'' said Peik von Bestenbostel, a
spokesman for Viag Interkom, which announced several days ago that
it would seek only two rather than three licenses allowed under the
bidding rules.
</P>
<P>
   Another executive called it ``the worst possible scenario'' _
high license prices and the maximum number of competitors at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   Under the German government's rules, 12 licenses were up for
auction but a company had to win two licenses to establish a
service. Theoretically, it was possible for four companies to
emerge with all the licenses, but most experts had predicted that
five companies would prevail _ two with three licenses each and
three smaller competitors with two each.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extraordinarily high prices, von Bestenbostel said
Viag was ready to plow ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is an extraordinary opportunity, and we are ready
for a market with six players,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
