<HEADER>
A5305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ACCIDENT-NYT &LR;      08-17 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ACCIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKAWAY CABLE SPOOL SERIOUSLY HURTS 2 AT SUBWAY WORK SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHAILA K. DEWAN and RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 7,500-pound spool of electrical cable being lowered
into a Manhattan subway station Thursday suddenly broke loose and
barreled down the stairs of the station, gravely injuring two
women, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened at about 11:45 a.m. at the 14th Street and
Eighth Avenue station. Workers for Sheldon Electric, a
subcontractor for the Metropolitan Transit Authority, had left half
of the stairway open, allowing passengers to use it as workers
lowered the spool on the other side, which had been taped off, said
Bob Slovak, a transit authority spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The one-inch thick nylon rope that held the spool snapped, he
said, and the spool, which had reached only the third step, went
rolling down the stairs with enough force to destroy the metal
bannisters, bouncing off a wall and then hitting the women, Slovak
said.
</P>
<P>
   The women, identified by the police as Andresa Kippins, 73, of
Brooklyn and Valca Valentine, 41, whose address was not known, were
badly injured, with multiple broken bones, said the police and
hospital officials.
</P>
<P>
   Kippins' son David said she and Valentine, who did not know each
other, had stopped at the foot of the stairs when they saw the
spool, about 5 feet in diameter, being lowered. But they were
assured by workers that they could proceed, David Kippins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy waved to them and said it was OK to pass,'' he said.
``And the next thing they knew, it broke and this thing came at
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kippins suffered several broken bones, including the fibula and
the tibia of one leg, three ribs, her collarbone and her pelvis,
her son said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine broke her left leg and clavicle, according to a
spokeswoman for St. Vincents Hospital, where the women were taken.
</P>
<P>
   David Kippins said he was astonished at the lack of safety
precautions. ``How could they just have men holding a rope? Why
didn't they have a crane lowering something like that? It was 7,500
pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Electric, which is based in Queens, had not notified the
transit authority of its plan to use a ``muscle operation'' to
lower the spool, Slovak said. ``If they had, we would have had them
close off this staircase completely when the cable was being
lowered,'' he said. ``We would have directed people away from the
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Electric was working for CAB Associates, the main
contractor for the $15 million renovation of the subway station,
which is served by the A, C, E and L trains. The renovation began
in 1994, but Sheldon has been working for the transit system for at
least a decade, a city official said. Sheldon is owned by a company
called Railworks.
</P>
<P>
   The company has faced questions about safety issues before, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have had other safety issues in which they at least had
to be talked to about the problems,'' the official said. ``I don't
know if there were any penalties involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cahn, the chief executive of Sheldon, said he did not
know whether the company had notified the MTA that it was going to
lower the spool manually. He did not provide more details about the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of it is such that my attorney would probably tell
me not to say anything about this, and that's easy because I really
do not know what happened,'' Cahn said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kippins was to have surgery Thursday night, her son said.
</P>
<P>
   A retired first-grade teacher, she had been on her way to a
class with other retired teachers in which she was learning to play
the recorder, a flutelike instrument, her son said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very active lady,'' said Dorothy Kippins, the wife of
Mr. Kippins. The family of the other victim could not be reached.
She was reported in stable condition by a hospital spokeswoman
Thursday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
