<HEADLINE>
EPA EXAMINES WHY IT FAILED TO PROTECT MONTANA TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIBBY, Mont. _ Five federal inspectors came to this tiny town
this week, looking not for asbestos but for something even harder
to grasp _ why the Environmental Protection Agency failed for
decades to protect miners and their families from the deadly
fibers.
</P>
<P>
   The visit is extraordinary. Although every federal agency has an
inspector general's office to review its actions, those
investigations are normally bloodless _ conducted by phone or by
reviewing mountains of paper.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors in Libby are sitting face to face with real people
_ victims of the actions of W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. and the inaction of
their own agency, which admits it knew about the deadly hazard of
asbestos-tainted ore at Grace's vermiculite mine and did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors are in living rooms, motels, coffee shops,
schoolrooms _ anywhere they can get people to tell them stories.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, 22 of the men and women who came to give information
to the inspectors had parents, other relatives or friends who died
from asbestos-related disease.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one of the people sitting in the red chairs of the
brightly-colored school auditorium were themselves dying because of
exposure to the lethal fibers.
</P>
<P>
   Once-strong men sat next to their women _ wives and mothers
sickened by the asbestos the men brought home on their work
clothes. All of them made it clear that they were more concerned
about what the EPA is doing about the problem today than about what
happened 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were glad that the EPA auditors came to hear
their stories, but they were not shy about asking why
representatives of the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration and the Mine Safety and Health Administration _
agencies responsible for the well-being of workers _ were not there
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole government screwed up by not telling anyone about
the dangers they'd found, but the only one here is the EPA. Where
is OSHA? Where is MSHA?'' asked Les Skramstad in a whisper. Years
of working in the mine have decimated his lungs. His wife, Norita,
also has asbestosis, as do two of their five children. He fears for
the health of the other three.
</P>
<P>
   ``OSHA and MSHA weren't here when we needed them to tell the
workers the truth and they aren't here today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Tafer, the leader of the EPA inspection team, told the
group of Libby residents that the inspectors' mission was to
determine who in the EPA knew about the hazards, when they knew it
and why nothing was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like putting together a huge puzzle and you may have some
of the pieces we need,'' Tafer said. ``Send us an anonymous box of
documents, call our free hot line, invite us to your home. We need
the right pieces to put this puzzle together so we can ensure it
doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s and '80s, EPA health experts were among a parade of
federal investigators who dropped by this bucolic corner of
northwest Montana to visit the world's largest vermiculite mine.
They reported the dangers, and the inspector general's staff is
trying to pin down why nothing was done about those reports.
</P>
<P>
   Those sporadic visits by EPA researchers were far outnumbered by
mandatory inspections by other state and federal agencies.
Inspectors from OSHA, MSHA and the National Institute of
Occupational Safety and Health toured the mine on a regular basis
and repeatedly reported that the miners were at great risk.Yet in
the end those agencies, too, did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the EPA team tried to keep the focus on EPA's actions,
the miners and their families kept questioning the failure of other
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand we've got all these dead bodies, our relatives and
friends. On the other, we've got all these covered-up government
documents. What are the real answers to why the government let the
people of Libby die?'' Bob Dedrick asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't trust anyone any more. Not doctors, lawyers or the
government. We've just been hit, betrayed, too many times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported in November that
hundreds of the miners and their family members have died or
contracted fatal disease from asbestos in the mine.
</P>
<P>
   The thousands of documents the P-I collected while investigating
the Libby situation included government reports and Grace's
internal papers discussing those reports.
</P>
<P>
   EPA made at least four reports, in 1980, 1982 and 1985 and 1991.
The reports presented the risk the miners faced and the hazards to
the townsfolk six miles downwind from the stacks at the mine, which
spewed 5,000 pounds of tremolite asbestos into the air every
working day.
</P>
<P>
   Of wider national significance, the EPA investigators also
projected the risks to the millions of consumers using insulation,
garden products and other materials containing vermiculite from the
mine, and to the tens of thousands of workers using the tainted
material in construction and a hundred other professions.
</P>
<P>
   None of the recommendations in any of the reports was followed
or passed on to other agencies. EPA pulled the funding halfway
through the most comprehensive of the studies. Ironically, next
Tuesday, 15 years later, EPA is releasing a new report on the
asbestos risk faced by consumers and workers using vermiculite for
gardening and other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the four EPA reports, the P-I found dozens of
other reports and extensive correspondence about Libby from the
U.S. Bureau of Mines, OSHA and NIOSH.
</P>
<P>
   Files were full of letters to and from Grace discussing the high
levels of asbestos exposure to miners, found by the agencies'
investigators year after year. There is no indication in the
worker-safety agencies' files that the miners or their unions were
ever told about the risk. In fact, some Bureau of Mines reports
were stamped ``confidential,'' for management eyes only.
</P>
<P>
   Several miners complained to the EPA team about federal mine
inspectors giving Grace three or four days notice before they
showed up to examine safety conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as management got the word the inspectors were coming,
we stopped everything and spent the next few days shoveling and
hosing the vermiculite dust out of sight so the inspectors wouldn't
see how bad the problems were,'' said Butch Hurlbert. Tall and
handsome, the former steelworker and rodeo roper is still a poster
image of a cowboy, but his three years working at the vermiculite
mine were enough to damage his lungs and his life, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Dedrick and his wife, Carrie, both have asbestosis. He told the
inspectors that he was disappointed in his government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fighting some very, very rich people with very powerful
friends. All we have is us and the truth,'' Dedrick said, gesturing
to the handful of people sitting around him, ``and a handful of EPA
workers who care a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's team took copious notes and shook their
heads occasionally at the comments they were hearing, even though
they knew that most of complaints were well beyond the scope of
their inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the authority or the ability to unravel
everything that happened here,'' team member Eileen McMahon told
the group. ``We will give you our full efforts but even though we
report to Congress, we can't force any other agency to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors didn't come to Libby to answer questions, but
even if they had, the questions being asked by the locals were too
hot to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to happen after the election, if Bush and Cheney
win?'' asked Gayla Benefield, whose mother and father both died of
asbestosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the new administration pull out the EPA people that have
been trying to help us for months? Will the Republicans stop
everyone from investigating asbestos? How will we know if they stop
you from doing your report?''
</P>
<P>
   Tafer looked uncomfortable and said she couldn't comment on most
of the questions, but added, ``If we don't finish the report,
you'll know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Judge, the head of Montana's AFL-CIO, suggested that if the
inspectors really wanted to find out why EPA's asbestos efforts
were thwarted in the '80s, they might be in the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're back in Washington, check out what impact the
Grace Commission had on all the agencies' effort to regulate
asbestos,'' Judge said. ``The 28,000-page Grace Report on getting
government off industry's back was taken to heart by the Reagan
White House. And Reagan's EPA administrators were way too cozy with
industry. Check it out. You may find your answers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grace Commission was headed by the late J. Peter Grace,
former head of W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. and a close friend of President
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   For white-collar, bureaucratic types, the auditors have
impressed many of the Libby victims with their efforts. Since they
arrived, they've been working dawn to dark, and the sun sets late
in Libby. They shed their pin-striped suits and grown-up clothes
for durable pants, sneakers and boots as they toured some of the
asbestos-contaminated sites where Grace processed and shipped the
ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it's all about. This is vermiculite,'' Jim Stout
said, holding up a piece of ore for the inspector general's team to
see and photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Stout works for URS Corp., which is managing the cleanup project
for Grace at the old expansion plant near the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   He showed no reluctance in telling the auditors that he and EPA
don't come close to agreeing on how much the site has to be
cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only find a trace of asbestos and EPA says we have to
remove it. Hell, it's only a trace. Why go to all that effort for a
trace? Kids go to school all day in buildings that have traces of
asbestos and that's no big deal,'' Stout said.
</P>
<P>
   They walked past the large, open-sided building that Grace used
to store huge piles of Zonolite waiting to be bagged and shipped.
It was where most of the kids in town climbed and played in piles
of the ore. It's also where many apparently sucked in the tremolite
asbestos fibers that are killing them today.
</P>
<P>
   When an auditor asked about the tremolite, Stout answered, ``We
don't deal with tremolite in the United States. The only place you
find it is here. We're really only worried about three kinds of
asbestos _ chrysotile, crocidolite and amosite. The rest don't
matter much.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the auditors who had studied the federal regulations
looked puzzled. A couple of supervisors from the cleanup company
were suddenly examining the clouds, and Duc Nguyen, the EPA guide
for the tour, quietly shook his head and said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   All government agencies list six types of asbestos as
cancer-causing and thus regulated. They include the three that
Stout mentioned, but also anthophyllite, tremolite and actinolite.
</P>
<P>
   The latter two contaminate the Libby vermiculite and other ore
mined around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tremolite and actinolite are not really a big deal. They're
not used much, and I never really heard about that anthophyllite,''
Grace's project manager added as the auditors returned to their
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Skramstad accompanied the auditors on their tour of the
contaminated buildings where he was exposed to asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked away from the crowd, Stout said he was sorry
Skramstad was sick, but added, ``He's a hell of a troublemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, another group of residents told their stories at the
school auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   In the front row sat Alice Priest and Edna Oikle. Some of the
inspectors kept glancing at the small oxygen tanks the women held
in their laps. Edna's husband, Gerald, patted her hand
reassuringly.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the comments went well beyond EPA's past actions.
</P>
<P>
   Don Wilkins told the auditors of a case in Idaho where the owner
of small waste-processing plant knowingly sent his employees into
situations where chemicals could harm them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was given 30 years in prison and none of his people died.
Why can't Grace officials be charged with homicide? They knew they
were killing their people and concealed it. Hundreds here have
died. Why can't criminal charges be brought against Grace?''
Wilkins asked.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Maynard, whose father and grandfather worked at the mine
and died from asbestos, got in the last word of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in Libby in the last century can still happen
elsewhere in America today and it shouldn't be allowed to occur,''
Maynard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if industry can thwart government's responsibility to the
workers, then we are not any safer than workers in a third-world
country. Will what you people from the inspector general are trying
to do make any difference? Can you get the other agencies to
protect the workers and their families or will thousands more die
because government doesn't care?''
</P>
<P>
   The auditors said they would do what they were permitted,
gathered the new documents they were handed and returned to their
motel.
</P>
<P>
   They knew the sun rises early in Libby.
</P>
</TEXT>
