 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DELEGATES SAY HOPE IS BUOYED BY CONVENTION
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Editors: tightens, updates &QL; 
 &QL; 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE &QL; 
C.2000 Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Delegates had arrived at the Democratic National
Convention anxious about their presidential nominee trailing in the
polls, but they said Thursday they are leaving more confident and
excited about a tough battle ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very big feeling that there is a fight ahead of
us,'' said Daniel Krausz, 20, a college student from Swarthmore,
Pa. ``I don't think anyone had given up hope, but after the last
three nights there's more hope than there was going in.''
</P>
<P>
   A speech by vice-presidential candidate Joseph Lieberman
appeared to have given many of the delegates a renewed confidence
that Vice President Al Gore can win the presidency in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But many admitted Gore's poor position in the the polls was
troubling, and they were counting on a good nomination acceptance
speech to get him back into the game with Republican George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have everything riding on it, like some people are
making out, but it sure will help,'' said Joe Gunn, president of
the Texas AFL-CIO. ``He doesn't have to hit a grand slam home run.
A two bagger will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions about delegate unease began surfacing Wednesday as
U.S. Sen. Joe Biden of Delaware told a group of delegates ``there's
a lot of anxiety hanging over this convention'' because of Bush's
lead in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Republican observers of the convention were fast to fan the
flames of doubt and division.
</P>
<P>
   ``What struck me was how factionalized this party is at its
base,'' said Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, R-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said that questions Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Los Angeles,
raised about Lieberman and his commitment to minority issues showed
a rift among Democrats, ignoring a public display of solidarity
that Waters and Lieberman engaged in on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Gilmore, R-Va., said the Democratic convention stands
in stark contrast to the unified Republican gathering two weeks ago
in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us have observed how nervous and dispirited this
convention is,'' Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a bigger task than reinventing themselves. They
almost need to reinvent party unity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the convention may have been firing up delegates, it had
failed in its first days to light a fire under voters. A
Voter.com-Battleground 2000 poll showed Bush had held onto a 10
percentage point lead over Gore through Wednesday night _ 50
percent to 40 percent in a two-way contest that does not include
third-party candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the polls say, but except for us political
junkies, everyone's out buying school clothes for their kids. No
one's paying attention,'' said Linda Howe, 58, a probation officer
from Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Howe said Ohio Democrats will leave the convention energized to
work at carrying their critical swing state. They will be selling
Gore on the issues, such as the conservative voting record of
Republican vice-presidential nominee Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law enforcement officers are going to be upset when they look
at Dick Cheney's vote against banning cop killer bullets,'' Howe
said, as she drew a sign that said ``Hi Mom!'' with a purple
marker.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Campbell, 38, an office manager from Uhrichsville, Ohio,
who wore a ``2000'' crown on her head, said she got a new
confidence after hearing Lieberman speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had any doubts at all, I have laid them aside,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Guthrie, 53, an auto parts worker from Three Rivers, Mich.,
sported a button on his vest that said, ``Read my lips, no more
Texans.'' He said the tide will turn once groups that have just
recently endorsed Gore, like the United Auto Workers, start
organizing.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie said he also is counting on the American people finding
out what he believes is the truth about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fake, misleading people with total distortions,''
Guthrie said.
</P>
<P>
   Pame Moore-Morrow, 50, from Columbia, Tenn., worked for Gore in
past campaigns. She said the American public needs to get to know
Gore like she does.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the stiff person people try to make him out to be,''
Moore-Morrow said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
