<HEADLINE>
STRATEGIES: THE WHOLE OF VOLATILITY IS LESS THAN ITS PARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 20) 
 By MARK HULBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be difficult to imagine that any decade in American stock
market history saw the magnitude or number of violent swings
witnessed in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, however, the market volatility of the last 10
years was no higher than the average of the last seven decades. In
fact, there was less volatility in the 1990s than in either of the
two previous decades _ 21 percent less than the 1970s and 31
percent less than the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Those are among the more startling conclusions of a new stock
volatility study by Professor John Campbell of the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology; Martin Lettau, senior economist at the New
York Federal Reserve Bank; Prof. Burton Malkiel of Princeton; and
Prof. Yexiao Xu of the University of Texas at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, do the recent gyrations seem so severe? One possible
explanation is in another of the researchers' findings: that even
though the overall market may be no more volatile than in the past,
the average stock is much more so. In fact, the volatility of the
typical stock in the 1990s was about twice as high as in the early
1960s. That is because the correlation between individual stocks'
gyrations has fallen _ in other words, more stocks are rising
sharply at the same time that other stocks plunge.
</P>
<P>
   So on a day when an Internet retailer misses earnings
expectations and immediately sheds a third of its market value, the
stock of another company is skyrocketing because it has just
reported unexpectedly good news. The extent of the volatility for
any given company is indeed a modern phenomenon. But across the
entire stock market of more than 7,000 companies, these gyrations
largely cancel one another out, leaving the overall market no more
volatile than it was in previous decades.
</P>
<P>
   This combination of higher volatility and reduced correlation
has profound implications for how many stocks an investor needs in
a portfolio in order to achieve adequate diversification. For
years, statisticians have argued that a portfolio of about 20
stocks, in a variety of industries, is large enough to diversify
away 90 percent of the volatility associated with owning a single
stock. According to the new study, however, given that the average
stock's volatility is twice as high as it was during the 1960s and
1970s, the number of stocks needed to achieve such diversification
is now closer to 50.
</P>
<P>
   If your portfolio does not have that many stocks, chances are
that you will have more sleepless nights and yet no greater returns
to show for it, than you would with a larger portfolio. Your
greater suffering will be in vain.
</P>
<P>
   That melancholy conclusion comes from the market's structure. In
a stock market as efficient as ours, investors are for the most
part rewarded only for taking unavoidable risks. But the volatility
and risk associated with smaller portfolios are entirely avoidable
_ and thus you shouldn't expect higher returns for incurring them.
</P>
<P>
   What accounts for the average stock's much-increased volatility?
Answering with any certainty will require additional research, but
the authors of the new study point to two contributing factors. The
first is the trend over the last decade away from conglomerates and
toward companies whose businesses are more focused. In a
conglomerate, poor earnings from a single division have a
relatively small impact on the price of the company's stock. If
that division is spun off and becomes publicly traded on its own, a
similarly poor earnings report will have a much greater impact.
</P>
<P>
   A related factor is that a greater number of younger and smaller
companies are publicly traded today. Because investors feel far
less certain about the long-term prospects of these companies,
their stock prices are much more sensitive to good or bad news than
are those of larger, more established concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the reasons, the wider gyrations of individual
stocks teach a broad lesson: Diversification, which has always been
an important way to gain immunity from volatility, is now more
crucial than ever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
