<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS POWER ANGELS, 6-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are your parents' Yankees, a team reliant on
power, Bronx bombers. Only now the slugger whose best position is
in the batter's box is not Johnny Blanchard, but Glenallen Hill.
The left-handed hitter with a swing suited perfectly for Yankee
Stadium is David Justice, not Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in Jose Canseco, who came here with 440 career home runs,
and suddenly the Yankees' lineup is transformed. Less defense, less
speed. Far more explosive. The Yankees hit 100 home runs in 83
games before the All-Star Game break, but already have 53 in 34
games since the break, including homers from Hill, Justice and Luis
Sojo Thursday night in a 6-1 thumping of Anaheim at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle gave up nine hits in six and two-thirds scoreless
innings and snapped his three-game losing streak, helped by three
exceptional defensive plays from third baseman Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, Justice and Canseco are all best suited as designated
hitters, and they all were in the starting lineup Thursday night _
Hill in left field, Justice in right field and Canseco as the
designated hitter. They have combined for 20 home runs since
joining the Yankees, in only 202 at-bats, or about one for every 10
at-bats. Manager Joe Torre does not exactly know how it will work
out, trying to find playing time for all of them; the only thing he
does know is that so far, it has worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco and Justice struck out against Anaheim's Kent Mercker to
open the second inning, but when Mercker tried to whip a fastball
past Hill, he turned on the ball. His drive soared, on the line,
just to the right of straightaway center, and the ball bounded into
the black-painted seats _ only the 19th home run hit there in the
remodeled Yankee Stadium. It was his 38th at-bat with the Yankees,
and his seventh home run, and it gave the Yankees a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees added another run in the third, on a sacrifice fly
by Bernie Williams (his 107th RBI). The Angels would threaten in
almost every inning, but twice sabotaged rallies with base-running
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco walked leading off the sixth inning. He seems to have
been liberated in the Yankees' lineup, feeling free to take bases
on balls, rather than swing at bad pitches in an effort to create
offense, as he did for Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Justice followed.
</P>
<P>
   Justice has always been a pull hitter, but scouts who have
followed the Yankees over the last month believe that the short
right-field stands present a particularly attractive target for
him, and think that in certain situations, he will try to turn on
pitches and lash them to right.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander Juan Alvarez pitched to Justice in the sixth
inning, and threw a ball inside. Justice lifted and flicked his
right foot, turned his hips, swung, and the only thing that
prevented the ball from landing in the upper deck was the screen
attached to the right-field foul pole. Justice has 11 homers with
the Yankees, nine in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
