<HEADER>
A5318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-NYT     08-17 0297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH BRONX LITTLE LEAGUERS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Conn. _ A team from the South Bronx that was bidding to
earn a trip to Williamsport, Pa., and trying to become the first
Little League World Series champion from New York City in 36 years,
stumbled in the Eastern Regional final Thursday night at the A.
Bartlett Giamatti sports complex.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a team from Goffstown, N.H., will make the trip after
it got a run in the seventh inning and won, 1-0, behind the two-hit
pitching of Bud Collins, who scored the game's only run.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Almonte of the Rolando Paulino Little League team, which
represented New York State, matched Collins in a wondrous pitching
duel through the regulation six innings, striking out 10 New
Hampshire batters and not yielding a hit until two were out in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   But in the seventh inning, a walk to Collins, a sliced single to
right by Jarek Ostrowski and an errant throw from right field gave
the team from a suburb of Manchester, N.H., the green light to
Williamsport, where the eight-team tournament begins a weeklong run
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It also ended a superb run for the team from the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Only three teams from New York City have reached the Little
League World Series, and all three were from Staten Island. Mid
Island won the championship in 1964. Teams from South Shore
qualified in 1985 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 family members and friends of the Bronx players,
almost all of them wearing the team's cardinal red colors and some
of them with their faces painted red, sat behind the team's dugout
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love these kids,'' said Rolando Torres, whose son Victor is
on the team. ``Most of us have been here for every game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
